<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TORNADOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BIG RUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 5:
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes like the ones that devastated parts of Oklahoma and
Kansas Monday afternoon, killing more than 40 people and
obliterating whole neighborhoods, begin and end in strangeness.
Before they form, the horizon seems to approach, to acquire a
preternatural clarity against the deep black front of the storm.
Houses and trees seem almost to leap into the foreground. And when
the tornado has finally passed, it leaves behind a track that
insists upon its unpredictability, forcing us to consider the knife
edge that divides what was totally destroyed from what was barely
touched.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes are utterly localized, and on a night of many
tornadoes, the fear that strikes comes from knowing that you are
out of the worst until you are in it, with no way to know when that
will be. ``Basically, it was a very large black wall that just
moved here,'' was the way one resident of Moore, just south of
Oklahoma City, described Monday's terrible storm. Another elderly
survivor cited the ``big rumble'' she heard as the tornado passed
her home in South Oklahoma City. The twisters were exceptional both
for their size and the time they spent in contact with the ground,
their impact multiplied by hitting in populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   The overpowering sounds of tornadoes cannot be reproduced in any
meaningful way, but the sight of them has been. These latest storm
cells were tracked from high and low by the National Weather
Service, and the funnel clouds were photographed probably hundreds
if not thousands of times. There was a sense that the storm was
occurring right in front of a nationwide audience, and it
undermined once again the persistent naive feeling, which is always
being undermined, that what we can watch so closely we can somehow
control.
</P>
<P>
   Those on the scene know better. They know in fact that the only
way to control your fate when a tornado strikes is to break off
watching and head for the storm cellar. From ``The Wizard of Oz''
to Monday afternoon, we have perpetuated the myth of a kind of
visual coexistence with twisters. But to watch your own tornado is
a little like watching your own funeral. The wonder about Monday's
storm, given its path, is not that so many died but that so many
did not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 0001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
