<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-REDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS STRUGGLE ON BASES IN LOSS TO REDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Even though several players said it feels like they
left Phoenix more than a month ago, the Diamondbacks refuse to
offer up this exhaustive and seasonlong 13-game road trip as the
reason for their recent losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The facts, however, may point in a different direction. By
virtue of their 6-4 loss to Cincinnati Tuesday night, the
Diamondbacks have now lost three in a row, their longest such
streak since opening the season with four losses.
</P>
<P>
   The club's 14-14 record marks the first time since April 19 they
have been at the .500 level.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks left eight runners on base, six of them in
scoring position. They had 12 different at-bats with runners in
scoring position and came through three times.
</P>
<P>
   All the scoring possibilities aside, the Diamondbacks were
caught on the base paths twice Tuesday night. Feats that were
somewhat surprising mostly because base-running mistakes have
become so rare this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are guys who know how to play the game,'' reliever Gregg
Olson said. ``They're pros in every sense of the word. Last year we
made mental mistakes. That's why when you see something like what
happened here, you're kind of shocked. But you know it's because
they were being aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Tony Womack was picked off at first base in the third
inning when the Diamondbacks had runners at first and third with no
outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My foot slipped getting back,'' Womack said. ``It's not that
he got me. I'm not going to give him that much credit. If my foot
didn't give, I'm in there. As it was, I thought I was safe. But I
wasn't going to argue it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, in the fifth inning and the score tied at 4, Luis Gonzalez
was thrown out on a bizarre play between third and home.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks actually had runners at second and third with
no outs after Matt Williams, one of the hottest players in the
league, doubled into the left-center field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Williams saw third base coach Brian Butterfield waving Gonzalez,
put his head down and thought he could make third base easily. But
Butterfield had applied the brakes to Gonzalez and Williams drew a
throw at second base from catcher Brian Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The ball trickled away from Reds second baseman Pokey Reese and
Gonzalez took off for home plate. But Reese recovered the ball and
chased Gonzalez down for the out. Williams wound up being stranded
at second and the Reds took the lead the next inning when Barry
Larkin slammed a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decoyed me pretty good,'' Gonzalez said of Reese. ``I think
he thought the ball was farther away from him, too. By the time I
realized he had the ball, I was in no man's land. I was trying to
be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield, who sometimes forgets what a veteran group of
players the club has compared to last year, wa amazed at the
response's he received from Gonzalez and Williams after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gonzo came up to me in the dining room and said, ``My bad,' ''
Butterfield said. ``Then a few minutes later, Matty peeks in and
said, `I'm sorry.' I told each they had nothing to apologize for.
We've lost some games in a row now and haven't scored as much as we
would like and guys are just trying to make something happen. Some
of the mistakes that have been made, I have applauded because
they're aggressive and the way to take it to the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Omar Daal lost for the third consecutive start
and saw his record dip to 2-3, while his ERA rose to a very
uncharacteristic 3.99. Daal has experienced a slight pain in his
elbow in the days leading up to each of his starts during the past
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But tonight, it was the best it's felt in a long time,'' he
said. ``The days I have pitched it hasn't felt bad. It's sometimes
the next few days. But that's not why I have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the eventual game-winning home run Daal served to
Larkin, his worst offense of the night was a two-run, two-out
single to Reese in the fourth. After a pair of singles to start the
inning, Daal labored hard to strikeout Aaron Boone and Brian
Johnson and had two strikes on Reese before he hit a soft line
drive up the middle off the end of his bat for the two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one that hurt the most because I was so close to
getting out of the inning,'' Daal said. ``The hit went to where
there was no one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
