<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRESERVING MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 5:
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic is using the war in Kosovo to try to sabotage
his most formidable political rival, Milo Djukanovic, the president
of Montenegro. Djukanovic has brought economic reform and ethnic
tolerance to his part of Yugoslavia, and calls the ethnic cleansing
in Kosovo ``insane.'' The West should do everything possible to
help him.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Djukanovic's popularity has discouraged Milosevic from
using his Second Army, stationed in Montenegro, to attempt a coup.
Instead he is trying to undermine Djukanovic by creating ethnic
instability and worsening the economic crisis brought on by the
war. Belgrade has driven 70,000 Kosovars into Montenegro, where
they are resented by the Slavic population. It has made Montenegro
into a NATO target by shooting at alliance planes from there.
Although NATO has responded with restraint, each bomb undermines
public support for Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has also tried to use the army to take over
Montenegro's border posts, television transmitters and its main
port _ Yugoslavia's only outlet to the sea. He has replaced
commanders with his loyalists, and brought in troops from Serbia.
So far Djukanovic's police have kept control.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has made the crucial pledge that ships carrying oil
bound for Montenegro will be exempt from the planned embargo on
Serbia. It has also sent Montenegro $10 million, which will help
pay pensions and salaries this month. Congress should approve an
additional $20 million requested by the White House, but more is
urgently needed.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro also needs more aid to help the Kosovars it has taken
in. It has treated them well, but some have now been killed by the
Second Army. If these measures fail to keep up support for
Djukanovic and the army does attempt a coup, NATO ought to
retaliate from the air. NATO should do whatever it can to protect
this democratic enclave from Milosevic.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
