<HEADLINE>
NUNEZ'S PERFORMANCE FORCING PERSONNEL DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Reliever  &UR; Vladimir Nunez was called up as insurance
on April 14, one day after the Diamondbacks exhausted their
relievers in a 16-inning marathon victory over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, the club has been pleasantly surprised with
Nunez's effort. The right-hander has an 0.96 ERA in 9 innings and
may actually find himself squeezing fellow reliever  &UR; Amaury
Telemaco off the club's roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working hard trying to stay here,'' Nunez said. ``I know
the other teams study you once you reach this level. My thinking is
I have to learn something new everyday now that I'm here. I have a
better idea of how tough it is to stay at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks must decide by Saturday what to do with
Telemaco. The options are to bring him to the big-league roster,
trade him or place him on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco's 30-day injury rehabilitation assignment ends Friday
night. Because Telemaco is out of options, the club must make one
of the above-mentioned moves.
</P>
<P>
   Because Nunez and  &UR; Brian Anderson are the only two candidates
with options remaining, one or the other could wind up being sent
down if Arizona opts to keep Telemaco. The chances of that being
Anderson seem remote given his nearly four years of big-league
service time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Vladimir's got a pretty good thing going,'' Manager
 &UR; Buck Showalter said. ``I think he realizes the fleetingness of
being here, how you have to prove yourself. We're real proud of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   From none to second &QL; 
 &UR; Tony Womack, who has been converted to an outfielder, made his
first start at second base. Womack was inserted at second base, his
position the past two seasons with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter wanted to give his normal double-play combination a
day off. Womack started at second and  &UR; Andy Fox got the start at
shortstop in place of  &UR; Tony Batista. &QL; 
Womack played four innings at second base in the 16-inning game on
April 13. &QL; 
New experience &QL; 
 &UR; Randy Johnson, who is scheduled to start tonight's game, has never
started a game in Cincinnati. Johnson's only experience in
Cincinnati was on April 25, 1989, in a relief role with the
Montreal Expos, one of nine career relief appearances in 302 career
games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
