<HEADER>
A4636 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-INGLEWOOD-LADN     05-05 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-INGLEWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ERA ENDS IN INGLEWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Byron Scott was no different than most kids
growing up in the shadow of the Fabulous Forum in the 1970s. He was
enchanted by his neighbors at Manchester and Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   On game nights, he staked out the arena's service entrance on
90th Street, waiting for glimpses of the great Jerry West. He'd
wave pens and slips of paper at the opposing team's bus, hoping to
coax an autograph from personal idol Bob McAdoo of the Buffalo
Braves. And, occasionally, he'd sneak into the building through
side doors known only to arena personnel and neighborhood kids
devoted to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Scott would realize a dream and don the
purple-and-gold himself _ a direct result of the passion instilled
in him during those many nights hanging out at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that changed my life and showed me what I
wanted to do. I never wanted anything more after going to a couple
games but to be an NBA basketball player,'' says Scott, who
graduated from Morningside High and later won three championship
rings as a member of the ``Showtime''-era Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing how good they were, how the fans loved them and the
clothes they wore, how stylish they looked... it just made me want
it that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   That lifelong bond with the Lakers makes it that much more
painful for Scott to see his former team bid farewell to the Forum
and to his humble hometown of Inglewood, the self-described ``City
of Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight the Lakers play their final regular-season home game at
the Forum, with an undetermined number of playoff games to follow.
Then they will join the NHL's Kings, who have already played their
final game, in moving to the luxurious new Staples Center in
downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. gains the teams that have borne the city's name for more
than three decades. But Inglewood _ an incorporated city of 118,000
whose name never appeared on jerseys, only in newspaper datelines _
loses its two most renowned residents. And with the Lakers and
Kings go hundreds of thousands of dollars in revenue, an
incalculable measure of civic pride and many, many memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was a lot of sadness, because I grew up with
this team, and to me it was like the `Inglewood Lakers,''' says
Scott, now an assistant coach for the Sacramento Kings. ``It was
the only major sport we could call our own when I grew up in
Inglewood. It was right down the street, and I could walk to the
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be a big blow to the city, because they have pretty
much adopted the team as their own _ `City of Champions.'... When
they play that last game, it's going to be a big disappointment to
the city of Inglewood and it's going to be a sad day for not only
kids but adults also.'' &QL; 
Inglewood loses out
</P>
<P>
   And, it will be a sad day for those who have made a living off
the Lakers' and Kings' residence. The manager of the Sizzler on
Manchester Boulevard anticipates possible layoffs. The Lakers
T-shirt vendor down Prairie, on the ``Avenue of Champions,'' won't
have the same captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   The city's general fund of $59 million could take a hit of about
$1 million, according to the city's finance department, though the
losses could be offset by new events booked at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   After a 32-year relationship between the city and the teams,
it's no wonder that among Inglewood business people and political
activists there are bitter feelings of abandonment. The issue is so
volatile that city staff members tap dance around it, and Lakers
and Kings officials would rather not discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the politically charged divorce from
Inglewood, the Lakers are not commemorating tonight's final
regular-season game at the Forum. In fact, the public relations
staff has been instructed not to mention the significance of the
evening in any game-night events.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers will stage a fan appreciation night in
October, when the Lakers play a relatively meaningless exhibition
game at the Forum before next season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city is bracing for potentially severe financial
losses. For every sold-out Lakers game, city hall takes in about
$13,000 from sources such as admissions and parking taxes, plus
increased sales tax revenue from the thousands of fans who descend
on the city.
</P>
<P>
   The city is already anticipating a tight budget year, and such a
hit could potentially throw the city general fund into a deficit in
fiscal year 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant to us,'' finance director Nick Rives said of
the sports-related revenue.
</P>
<P>
   What effect the loss will have is undetermined, but a worst-case
scenario could mean budget cutbacks, even layoffs, though city
officials avoid such dire predictions.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the city might not need as many civilian and sworn
officers if there's no longer a need for additional security in the
Forum neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is of course concerned,'' Inglewood city manager
Joseph Rouzan says. ``It's going to be hard for us to judge exactly
what impact (the loss of the Kings and Lakers) is going to have.'' &QL; 
Forum will live on
</P>
<P>
   Jeanie Buss is trying to diminish that impact. Buss, president
of the Forum and daughter of Lakers owner Jerry Buss, said the
arena will continue to be a thriving entertainment center for years
to come, even without its long-time tenants.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Forum has hosted 185 to 200-plus events per
year. That number will drop to probably 120 to 150 events, and
``it's hard to say'' whether the arena will reach previous activity
levels again, Buss said.
</P>
<P>
   But she's optimistic. Buss recently secured a minor-league
hockey team from the West Coast Hockey League. Announcement of an
L.A. franchise should come in the next 60 days, and the team will
be playing here by fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the WNBA's Sparks are committed to the arena
through 2000, Forum boxing will continue, the number of concert
dates will increase to 30 or 40 per year and other dates will be
filled by family-oriented entertainment such as the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Gone will be Shaq and Kobe. In their place will be Barnum &AMP;
Bailey, 'N' Sync and Marilyn Manson.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum also will be part of L.A.'s bid for the 2012 Summer
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building has been left in a very good status,'' Jeanie
Buss said. ``It is debt-free and so we feel very positive it will
be successful in its own right, even without NBA and NHL tenants. I
see a very, very, very promising future for the Forum.'' &QL; 
Downtown too attractive
</P>
<P>
   For many in Inglewood, nothing can replace the Lakers and Kings,
who have played a combined 2,800 games here since the Forum opened
in December 1967. And there are many civic leaders who are angry
with both city hall, for failing to fight harder to keep the teams,
and with Kings owners Philip Anschutz and Ed Roski, for choosing
downtown L.A. instead of Inglewood for the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely owe the city something,'' said Charles Harkey,
business activist and owner of Inglewood Tickets. ``I think there
should have been some kind of compensation for the Lakers (and
Kings) leaving.... You're here, you made the money, you have taken
resources out of the community and certainly when you're given a
magnificent deal downtown where you're leaving because you're
making money, that shouldn't be a hard thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings say moving downtown was less a financial decision
_ they estimate it would have been $50 million to $100 million
cheaper to build in Inglewood _ than a philosophical one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was a difficult choice, because we were
comfortable with Inglewood,'' said Kings president Tim Leiweke.
``But when you looked at the impact the arena would create for Los
Angeles by being in downtown Los Angeles, it was too big an
opportunity, too big a challenge and too big a potential to pass
up.... We saw a great opportunity to spark the rejuvenation of
downtown Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Staples Center has helped L.A. attract next year's
Democratic Convention, secure the Grammy Awards and the 2002 U.S.
Figure Skating Championships, Leiweke said.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers owner Jerry Buss lobbied the Kings to build in Inglewood,
but once the site was chosen, Buss made a simple business decision
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Buss, who also owns the Forum, said his team needed a
state-of-the-art arena, and the lure of the Kings-financed, $365
million Staples Center was too great to turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Inglewood,'' Buss said. ``If I had made the
decision myself, the answer is yes, I would have stayed in
Inglewood _ in a state of the art facility.''
</P>
<P>
   As for compensating Inglewood, as some have suggested, the
Kings' ownership is considering building a soccer stadium there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life will go on. We were not their sole existence or center of
their day-to-day lives,'' Leiweke said. ``I think Inglewood will
find other business opportunities that they will rally behind.'' &QL; 
The next chapter
</P>
<P>
   The ``City of Champions'' is already refocusing its image.
</P>
<P>
   The street-pole banners bearing the likenesses of Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant are slowly being phased out; in their place
are images of thoroughbreds and a jazz trumpeter (Hollywood Park
and casino), doctors attending to a patient (Centinela Hospital),
and graphic representations of highway interchanges and L.A.
International Airport _ symbols of the city's growth and its
connection to the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
   But what's the ``City of Champions'' without its (begin
ital)champions?(end ital) Actually, the motto predates the Kings
and Lakers _ the phrase coined after the city hosted the marathon
for the 1932 Olympics, and three Inglewood natives won Olympic
events.
</P>
<P>
   And the motto will live on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we still have champions,'' insists former assistant
city manager Norm Cravens. ``We have championship race horses and
we have championship jockeys and we have championship medical
people. Hockey players and NBA players aren't the only kind of
champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Rouzan said with a wistful laugh, ``I guess we need
another marathon or something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
