<HEADLINE>
APACHE HELICOPTER IN ALBANIA CRASHES ON TRAINING MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Army Apache helicopter on a training mission
crashed about 45 miles northeast of the Tirana-Rinas airport in
Albania on Tuesday night, the Pentagon reported. There was no
immediate word on the fate of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no initial indications of hostile fire,'' said a
Pentagon spokesman, Jim Kout, adding that a rescue helicopter was
sent to the crash scene. The Apache was part of the helicopter
force supporting the overall NATO mission in Yugoslavia. Kout said
the helicopter crashed at about 1:30 a.m. local time, or 7:30 p.m.
Eastern daylight time.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was the second involving the Apache, the Army's
vaunted antitank weapon, during the Balkans deployment. On April
26, an Apache crashed within a few miles of the site of of Tuesday
evening's crash. Both pilots survived that crash.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of two Apaches could add to the unease some military
authorities have expressed about sending the helicopter, which
normally operates at low altitudes, into Kosovo over rugged terrain
that may be occupied by hostile troops armed with surface-to-air
missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
