<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DULL IN DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Dodgers' flight home takes more than five hours.
They leave after tonight's game at Montreal and arrive home early
Thursday morning to conclude one of their most difficult road trips
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers left home playing horribly and below .500 and will
return in second place, and anything other than a win will bring a
disappointing finish to the nine-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   After being shut down by Montreal's Carl Pavano in a 2-1 loss
Tuesday at Olympic Stadium, tonight's conclusion of the three-game
series is the difference between a good road trip and a stellar
road trip, especially given the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos (8-17) won for the fourth time in 18 home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the East Coast swing, with the start in the Midwest and
this type of road trip travel-wise, it'll be great to win,'' said
catcher Todd Hundley, who accounted for the Dodgers' lone run with
a seventh-inning homer. ``It's definitely one that will make the
plane ride much better. The (begin ital)long(end ital) plane
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (15-12) aren't beating up on the National League
powerhouses _ Milwaukee, Philadelphia and Montreal are a combined
33-44 _ but given the way they played on their last homestand, a
sweep in Milwaukee and winning two of three in Philadelphia was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   And after winning the opener in Montreal handily to go 6-1 on
the trip, the Dodgers were in position for their first eight-win
road trip since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer possible, but when the Dodgers lost four of six
on their last homestand to fall to 9-10 they hardly looked like a
contender in the NL West. They were 3{ games behind San Francisco.
And it's possible they could be just a half-game behind the Giants
when they touch down at LAX.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a good road trip,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``Win two of three here is what we need to do. We need to win
the series. We need to put it together and make the trip back
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the Dodgers must put forth a better offensive effort
than the one against the right-hander Pavano, whose best outing to
date was a three-run, five-inning stint against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Pavano's talent finally manifested itself or fatigue
wore on the Dodgers _ Johnson gave both thoughts credence _ didn't
really matter. The Dodgers tied a season low with four hits and
didn't have two runners on base in any inning.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano (1-4) entered with four losses and a 7.83 ERA and left
with his first win and his ERA down to 6.23. He struck out six,
didn't walk a batter and tied his career-high by pitching 71/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got everyone out of balance,'' Dodgers second baseman Jose
Vizcaino said. ``He was changing his pitches, using his fastball.
He had a good changeup. He was sharp. He was throwing the ball
right where the catcher wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavano was slightly better than Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes
(3-1), who lost for the first time. The Expos had a base runner in
every inning but the ninth, but could only muster a pair of runs in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero gave the Expos (8-17) a 1-0 lead with his
fifth homer of the season. Later in the inning, Orlando Cabrera
doubled home Chris Widger to put Montreal ahead 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he took Valdes out after the sixth inning because
the recurring blister he's had surfaced again. Valdes yielded seven
hits, waked three and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him a little sharper, he made a few mistakes out
there,'' Johnson said. ``Pavano was just outstanding. A lot of
first-pitch strikes, made some good pitches with his curveball. It
didn't look like he was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you just give up a couple of runs, you're supposed to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
