<HEADLINE>
STORMS MISS TRIPLE-A GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Southwestern Bell Bricktown Ballpark, home of
the Rangers' Triple-A affiliate in the Pacific Coast League,
suffered no damage after Monday's fierce tornadoes cut a path of
destruction through Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Officials suspended Monday's game between the Oklahoma RedHawks
and Memphis Redbirds after the third inning and postponed last
night's game. The RedHawks' ballpark, though, provided a haven for
its spectators while tornadoes hit the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people stayed there because it was a safe place,''
said John Blake, the Rangers' vice president for public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's postponement, though, means that Rangers
right-hander John Burkett (bursitis, right shoulder) did not make
the second start of his medical rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers instead plan for Burkett to fly to Jackson, Miss.,
and pitch tonight for Double-A Tulsa. Burkett will rejoin the
Rangers if all goes well and start Sunday against the Blue Jays in
Toronto, manager Johnny Oates said. FREQUENT STROLLERS Left fielder
Rusty Greer and designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro are the Rangers'
only qualifying players (81 or more plate appearances) with more
walks than strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Greer enters tonight's game at Fenway Park with 15 walks and
only seven strikeouts, while Palmeiro has drawn 14 walks to 11
strikeouts.
</P>
