<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENAFRO FINDS UNEXPECTED SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Thursday's fifth-inning at-bat by Yankees
right fielder Paul O'Neill resulted in a double-play ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   His eighth-inning at-bat produced another routine ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill emerged from the third-base dugout puzzled after the
fourth of four 1-2-3 innings thrown by Rangers left-hander Mike
Venafro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did you get this guy from?'' O'Neill asked Rangers
third-base coach Jerry Narron while trotting to the outfield. ``The
upper deck?''
</P>
<P>
   Such praise from one of the American League's toughest outs _
not to mention a streak of 16 consecutive batters retired _
illustrates why Venafro's stint with the Rangers could be
unexpectedly prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect right-hander John Burkett to be reinstated
from the 15-day disabled list and to rejoin the rotation for a
start Sunday against the Blue Jays in Toronto. That will require a
roster move.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro, whom the Rangers recalled April 24 from Triple-A
Oklahoma for Burkett, once appeared destined to return to the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro replaced the injured Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, a healthy Burkett replaces Venafro.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds logical, but the unexpected happened.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro has allowed one hit since that promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously want to be a part of this,'' said Venafro, whose
62/3 scoreless innings leave right-hander Danny Patterson in
jeopardy of losing his roster spot. ``I plan on doing everything I
can to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates declined to address his decision. ``No one
knows what's going to happen between now and then,'' he said,
hinting that Venafro could be around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making my decision easier,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Having three left-handed relievers in the bullpen is intriguing
to Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me three moves, especially with the way Venafro is
throwing the ball,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager used left-handers Dennis Cook, Mike Stanton and Ed
Vosberg effectively during the Rangers' 1996 AL West championship
season. Those three allowed Oates to orchestrate favorable
late-inning, situational matchups more frequently than any
major-league manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' 1996 relievers received a favorable matchup _
left-handed pitcher vs. left-handed batter or right-handed pitcher
vs. right-handed batter _ a major league-high 67.2 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Oates' 1996 relievers made 44 one-batter
appearances. That ranked fourth in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the Rangers' rotation creates the need for more
late-inning, situational matchups. The rotation will begin the game
against the Boston Red Sox tonight averaging 5.08 innings per
start.
</P>
<P>
   Having a third left-handed reliever would allow Oates to use a
lefty-righty-lefty combination of relievers to quell a threat
during an important inning ``and still have a left-hander sitting
out there'' in the bullpen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That could leave others asking about Venafro, as O'Neill did
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Venafro said, ``he'll remember me now.''
 &LR; tagtop:Johnny Paul, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:jpaul &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
