<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTED AND READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ With eight days to prepare for their second-round
playoff series that is scheduled to begin tomorrow night, what did
the Stars do yesterday?
</P>
<P>
   They took the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. You talk about the downside of things and the
upside of things, well we've found a way to turn what we thought
was a downside into a big upside,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``The breaks we had in October and November and February, we hated
them at the time. But now they're helping us. We've learned that
this is not a very good team when it practices three days in a row.
We've learned that we don't have to be on the ice all the time to
get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have eased through their eight-day break since ousting
Edmonton from the playoffs a week ago _ taking days off, scheduling
longer practices and following those with another day off.
</P>
<P>
   This is old hat. The Stars had two breaks of five games apiece
in October and November _ a lifetime by NHL standards _ and didn't
handle them well, Hitchcock said. Then, in February, they played
one game in 10 days and realized that too much practice wasn't good
for a veteran team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We \Roriginally\S felt we could use practices as game
preparation, like scrimmages, and mentally our team got burned
out,'' Hitchcock said. ``That little break \Rof one day\S seems to
give us a lot of energy. And I think your ability to win in the
playoffs has a lot to do with energy and freshness.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars begin the second round tomorrow, they will have
had time to rest, to heal and to plan for a multitude of different
attacks. And they will face an opponent that is likely to be
battered from a physical, seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take advantage of that by being really good in the
first couple of games here,'' Hitchcock said. ``If we kind of wade
into this series and use \Rour\S not playing as a disadvantage,
they'll get out of this thing and they'll get better as they go on.
We have to jump hard and now and often and quick.''
</P>
<P>
   When the second round begins, Hitchcock will have several
decisions to make. He has seen a lineup that was missing six
players in Game 4 against the Edmonton Oilers get healthy to the
point where he's now missing only one injured player _ center Guy
Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   With Pat Verbeek expected to play his first game after being
sidelined three weeks with a knee injury, Hitchcock will have some
tough choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel Verbeek will be a good player for us,'' Hitchcock said.
``I just don't know where I'm going to play him.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek is a gritty right winger with goal-scoring skill (17)
and strength on the power play. He has played on the third and
fourth line for much of this season and would be a likely
replacement for rookie Blake Sloan. But Hitchcock said he doesn't
want to take Sloan out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With Grant Marshall (groin) and Tony Hrkac (concussion) healthy,
Hitchcock will likely have to make a decision to sit at least two
of the following: Sloan, Verbeek, Hrkac, Brian Skrudland, Derek
Plante or Dave Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see us playing a group of 12\R(forwards\S, but to be honest
with you, I don't see four lines staying together,'' Hitchcock said
of the roll-four-lines policy he has used for much of the season.
``I see there's some big changes happening throughout the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe \RBrett\S Hull, \SMike\S Modano and \RJere\S Lehtinen
might start out as a definitive threesome. But depending on the
checking roles for the other team were playing, maybe Verbeek might
have to be a player with Modano, or \RJamie\S Langenbrunner might
have to be a player with Modano.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, players said the options are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've worked for,'' Carbonneau said. ``We want to
have these options. It's a lot better than not having them.''
 &LR; tagtop:Mike Heika, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
