<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DREAM OF OLYMPICS IS IRRESITIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ So tell me. What are you doing in the summer
of 2012?
</P>
<P>
   Can they count on you to retrieve a few javelins? Bail out some
over-zealous kayaks? Maybe drive a herd of Uzbekistanis to dinner?
</P>
<P>
   If so, follow that torch.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow night at Fair Park, the Dallas 2012 bid committee will
be looking for volunteers who want to buy into its Olympic dream.
</P>
<P>
   The dream lives, I feel obligated to report. Once just the
starry-eyed fantasy of Arlington trash entrepreneur Grady Hicks,
and once dubbed a ``silly idea'' by a columnist whose name (oops)
sounds remarkably similar to mine, the notion of bringing the 2012
Summer Olympics to North Texas continues to grow like wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know whether to mow them down or take a picture with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Luce, chairman of Dallas 2012, is banking on the latter.
Beginning at 6 p.m. in front of Fair Park's Hall of State, there
will be interactive demonstrations of Olympic sports, lasers,
fireworks, Olympians, a theme song and the inevitable lighting of
the torch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started out as a news conference,'' said Dallas 2012
spokesman Kevin Sullivan. ``We wanted to launch our drive to
recruit volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the whole thing just kind of snowballed.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the snowball is being called the Dallas 2012 Opening
Ceremonies and Sports Festival. There will be a videotaped message
from Olympic champion runner Michael Johnson. Mayors Kenneth Barr
of Fort Worth, Elzie Odom of Arlington and Ron Kirk of Dallas will
render brief remarks. And a choir of 1,200 students, accompanied by
the University of North Texas orchestra, will debut ``Our Time to
Shine,'' a song written by Jim Kirk that will serve as the theme
for the 2012 bid.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance is futile.
</P>
<P>
   In the rain last Sunday, the committee held an orientation for
the 120 volunteers who will assist at tomorrow's event.
</P>
<P>
   Among the orienteers was swimmer Ryan Berube of SMU, who told
the saga of marching in with the U.S. team at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics. He talked about the thrills and the chills and showed the
group the Olympic gold medal that he earned in the 4x200-meter
relay.
</P>
<P>
   As Berube spoke, some of the volunteers got misty eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, futile.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the notion did seem preposterous. We don't
reside in anything I'd consider a cradle of Olympic sports. Our
boundaries are large and unwieldy. And we don't always get along
ourselves, whether it's arguing about an airport or a ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But things happen on Planet Olympus. Citizens in Seattle,
considered by many to be the leading candidate for the U.S. bid,
voted to disband any effort to attract the Olympics. The
Baltimore-Washington bid still hasn't mustered any forward
momentum. A Los Angeles push has drawn been-there-done-that yawns.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, even the Olympic scandal in Salt Lake City has
helped the Dallas 2012 bid. The scrutiny in Salt Lake has
underlined the importance of a future bid city being a trusted host
to corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Luce says he has had only one potential corporate contributor
mention the Utah scandal. By 2002, Luce said, ``the process will be
cleaned up, we will have clear rules, and there will be a level
playing field for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas 2012 committee has already formulated a policy of
publicly disclosing every expense and contribution. Board meetings
will be open to the public and the media. An independent ethics
advisory panel has been formed, to be chaired by former SMU law
school dean Paul Roger.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty hurdles, of course, still exist. Somebody _ Dallas?
Arlington? Jerry Jones? _ is going to have to build a new
$350-million stadium to house the track and field events and the
opening and closing ceremonies. Someone also needs to piece
together a $150-million Olympic Village.
</P>
<P>
   But Luce and his people have done their homework. Tomorrow
night's event could be Fair Park's debut as Dallas' Olympic park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great asset to sell to the Olympic Committee,
and it's already assembled,'' Luce said. ``A lot of municipalities
would love to have a 275-acre park with controlled perimeters.''
</P>
<P>
   No artist sketches have been drawn, but the Dallas 2012 dream
includes constructing a pedestrian promenade from Fair Park to
downtown Dallas _ a Texas version of Barcelona's Las Ramblas, if
you will.
</P>
<P>
   The dream lives. The line for Olympic volunteers begins forming
in earnest tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Bring your own tissues.  &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lebreton &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
