<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-BRIDGECREEK-2ndLdWritethru-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUERS HAPPY TO FIND SURVIVORS IN VAST CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Note further update in 7th graf on grandmother found) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ A 6-year-old boy walked aimlessly along a
road amid twisted mobile homes, crumpled cars and appliances
scattered randomly amid the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   When a massive tornado slammed into the Southern Hills
subdivision Monday evening, he and his mother were on the run,
heading to what they believed would be the safety of a nearby
creek, the boy told officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he saw the wind pick her up and take her off,'' said
Bob Paul, a deputy with the Grady County Sheriff's Department.
``When they found him, he was wandering the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, law enforcement officers and the National
Guard continued searching for her in this farming community of
6,000 about 30 miles southwest of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   While the National Guard scoured the south side of Bridge Creek,
the 30-member volunteer firefighter department led the search teams
in northern Bridge Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that the mother was found alive
Tuesday afternoon under debris near her house, but last night a
Grady County sheriff's dispatcher said the boy's grandmother, not
mother, had been rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the Bridge Creek community was the hardest hit in
the series of deadly tornadoes that ravaged Oklahoma and Kansas.
Officials said 11 people were killed, most of them in Southern
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Lindsey was among the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   As the mile-wide tornado headed toward her mobile home, she had
four screaming children at her side. The pickup in her back
driveway wouldn't run. Lindsey, who was celebrating her 31st
birthday, grabbed bedding and sofa cushions and ushered her family
into the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, the walls were gone. Only a kitchen island
and a few pieces of furniture remained. Lindsey and her four
children, ages 11 months to 9 years, crouched in the rubble,
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we lived through it,'' an almost cheerful Lindsey said
Tuesday as she and her husband, James, picked through the debris
that had once been their home. ``What better birthday than that?
Happy birthday to me. Best present I ever got.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady County sheriff's officials tailing the huge tornado
arrived in Southern Hills to find bodies mingled with twisted
debris scattered across the hilly landscape. Among the dead were an
elderly woman and a 2-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Palmore, a volunteer firefighter, said his first discovery
was a family huddled together, the grandmother dying and a
3-week-old baby missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found (the baby's) body about 300 feet away in the trees,''
Palmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar wrenching scenes would be repeated throughout the night,
he said, but the memories to which he clung were of finding people
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to take ambulances into the rural area, rescuers used
pickups to load the injured, and later the dead. The Bridge Creek
school's gymnasium was transformed into a triage area; the school
cafeteria was a temporary morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that were alive, they were just covered with mud.
You just had to look and then suddenly you'd see a pink tongue or
white eyes,'' Palmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of the Lord in my heart,'' he added. ``The Lord
was around here (Monday) night. I think he saved my family and a
bunch of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady County Sheriff's Deputy Al Hooper said he believed that
meteorologists' warnings saved many lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have that certain amount of people that say, `Oh,
it's not going to get me. It's not going to hit,' '' Hooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it did.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
