<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ First, Mike Hampton frustrated the New York Mets with
his arm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next, he did it with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton allowed a meager two hits over seven innings Tuesday
night and ignited a five-run outburst over the final three innings
with a two-out triple as the Astros snapped the Mets' six-game
winning streak 6-1 at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's triple was his second in 236 career at-bats. His first
came in 1997 against Cleveland's Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians played him to the right side, and Hampton hit the
ball to left-center field. On Tuesday, the Mets played Hampton
shallow. He drove it over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just another case of me getting lucky,'' said Hampton,
who on the mound allowed only a sixth-inning run. ``I knew where
they were playing I had a chance to get it over their heads. (But)
that's where teams play every pitcher, except maybe Dwight Gooden
and Fernando Valenzuela. Those guys are probably just as good
position players as they are pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton had some help as four Astros had at least two of the
team's 13 hits.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 1 in the top of the seventh, Hampton, who
hit a two-run double in his previous start April 29 against
Arizona, drilled a 1-0 pitch off Al Leiter (1-3) over the head of
Mets center fielder Brian McRae.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be the lift the Astros needed, as Craig Biggio
followed with an RBI double and Derek Bell hit a two-run homer to
left field to push the lead to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hampton) is like another hitter in our lineup,'' said Astros
shortstop Tim Bogar, who had an RBI double in a two-run eighth.
``He's not going to go out there and get punched out real easy.
That's the thing some teams forget; he is that kind of an athlete.
He's not an easy out like 90 percent of the rest of the pitchers in
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's two-bagger was the 344th of his career, surpassing the
previous team doubles record held by Cesar Cedeo, an Astro from
1970-81.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's homer, a 387-foot foot shot, was his fifth of the season
and part of a 3-for-5 night. The Astros just missed hitting for the
cycle in four consecutive at-bats in the seventh when Jeff Bagwell
grounded out to third.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (3-1) was a good enough athlete to receive scholarship
offers from Notre Dame and Florida State out of high school _ as a
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what he gets paid for is to pitch,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The normally potent Mets found out the hard way. In winning his
third straight decision, Hampton struck out five and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   After issuing a walk to the first batter he faced, Hampton
retired nine straight batters. And before Mike Piazza's RBI single
in the sixth, he had allowed only an infield hit _ charitably
scored at that, considering a poor throw from third baseman Ken
Caminiti _ to Edgardo Alfonzo in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elarton allowed one hit in two scoreless innings of relief
as the Astros won for the eighth time in 11 games and improved to
4-1 on their six-game road trip. Dating to last Aug. 10, they are
12-4 in Hampton's last 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The top five spots in the New York batting order came into the
game hitting a career .361 (26-for-72) against Hampton with 10
RBIs. They went a combined 3-for-14 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Mets) are a pretty hot team. They throw some pretty good
bats at you, and you have to concentrate on every pitch,'' Hampton
said. ``The big thing is I didn't make too many mistakes over the
middle of the plate. I was able to keep the ball down, work in and
out, and change speeds. With a team like this, you have to minimize
your mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got on the scoreboard first in the fourth when
Bagwell and Caminiti hit consecutive singles and Richard Hidalgo
followed with an RBI double into the left-field corner. They did,
however, leave the bases loaded for the third time in the past four
games.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter would finally cave, allowing six runs and a
season-high 11 hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I want to pitch a shutout every time out there,''
Leiter said. ``I felt pretty good tonight until the seventh
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio, who is 6-for-13 in his last three games, knocked
Leiter out with an RBI single in the eighth, and Bogar followed two
batters later with a run-scoring double off reliever Josias
Manzanillo to cap the scoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
