<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTICS SELECT HOLDSCLAW AS NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chamique Holdsclaw stood on the podium holding her
new jersey in front of her. The most notable thing about
Holdsclaw's appearance _ aside from the professional hairstyling
and makeup obviously preparing her for an endorsement bonanza _ was
that it was not a New York Liberty uniform the best player in the
game held, despite conspiracy theories that had dominated
discussion about the Women's National Basketball Association
draft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, the four-time all-American from Tennessee, was taken
by the Washington Mystics as the first pick of the WNBA draft on
Tuesday, and she is staying put. No trade, no manipulation by the
league, nothing is bringing Holdsclaw back to New York, where she
grew up and starred at Christ the King High School. ``A lot of
people wanted me to play in New York,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I'm kind
of glad I didn't. I don't know if I could have handled the pressure
and the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of playing in New York with Tennessee, she added: ``I
learned a lesson when I played in Madison Square Garden. Your
friends want tickets, they want to be with you, and I don't need
that right now. I'm trying to establish my own life. It's just like
Marbury. He wanted to be in New York, but he settled for New
Jersey. If I came here, I would get no rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's general manager, Carol Blazejowski, said the team
tried to negotiate with Washington before the draft to establish
the possibility of a trade. But the Mystics rebuffed everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, a 6-foot-2-inch guard-forward who took Tennessee to
three straight national championships and averaged 21.3 points a
game last season, was undoubtedly the star of an extraordinarily
deep draft, stocked full of experienced players from the defunct
American Basketball League. Because of the wealth of talent, just
12 collegians were among the 50 picks in the four-round draft.
Holdsclaw was the only one in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The new collective bargaining agreement allowed each of the 10
existing teams to take three ABL players and the two expansion
teams to take five apiece. Thirty-five AB. players were picked,
including Jennifer Azzi (Detroit, 5th pick over all), Yolanda
Griffith (Sacramento, 2d pick), Kate Starbird (Sacramento, 26th)
and Jennifer Rizzotti (Houston, 48th). The only ABL player who did
not sign a contract with the WNBA, and so was not eligible for the
draft, was Teresa Edwards. It was not known why she hadn't signed.
</P>
<P>
   When it became obvious to the Liberty that nothing was going to
swing Holdsclaw its way _ and that the league would not step in to
help a deal putting the top player in the league's biggest media
market, something that the league's president, Valerie B. Ackerman,
said was never even considered _ New York tried to fill its
multiple needs, particularly for perimeter scoring and youth.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, which was 18-12 and missed the playoffs last year,
averaged just 68.6 points a game, eighth of the 10 teams in the
league. Center Kym Hampton is 36, point guard Teresa Weatherspoon
is 33, and the shooting guard Sophia Witherspoon is 29. For that
reason, Coach Richie Adubato anticipates a highly charged training
camp, with almost every starting position up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   In taking Crystal Robinson, 25, with the sixth pick of the first
round, the Liberty gets a 5-11 forward who, with the Colorado
Xplosion of the ABL, averaged 14.9 points a game and who shot 52
percent from the floor and 46.6 percent from 3-point range. She can
play shooting guard and small forward. ``Her perimeter shooting is
as good as anyone we've seen,'' Adubato said. ``Her overall
shooting is excellent, not only from 3-point, but also midrange.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said: ``I have a gift for scoring. New York has a great
core group, but they need something they can go to in the clutch,
someone who can score every night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
