<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERFRAUD-AZR &LR;      05-05 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERFRAUD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA COALITION TARGETS FRAUD AIMED AT SENIORS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Arizona coalition announced Tuesday the largest joint
educational campaign against telemarketing in the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough of making it open season on seniors in Arizona,'' said
Attorney General Janet Napolitano during the public launch of Opera
tion Intercept, a two-month elder fraud prevention campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While no money was targeted toward it, organizers say they their
agencies will donate their time. And they will be calling heavily
on volunteers to help make it a success.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the campaign is to educate Arizona elders and their
children about telemarketing fraud so fewer of the state's
grandparents will fall prey to financial scams.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was created by the Elder Fraud Prevention Team
whose members also include other law officials, the U.S. Postal
Inspection Service, AARP and the Arizona Cardinals football team.
Members of the Cardinals will be donating their time for television
or radio spots.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, Arizona victims have lost more than $100
million since 1994. Nationwide, over $40 billion a year is lost to
telemarketing fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona continues to be a high target area for illegal
telemarketers due to the state's significant number of elderly
residents,'' said FBI supervisory Special Agent Jim Whalen.
</P>
<P>
   The average person loses $20,000 to $100,000, said Whalen,
though in one recent case a Valley man lost $1.8 million. He was
called by a Canadian company and told he had won the lottery but he
had to send $4,200 in fees, which he did continually. Though he had
been a successful businessman, he was suffering from dementia and
didn't realize he was doing it time and again, Whalen said.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a family didn't find out until their father
died that he had squandered $2 million of his $8 million in assets
on fraudulent investment scams.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Telemarketing Task Force formed five years ago but
most of its efforts have been directed at prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting people in jail, but many of their victims still
lose their nest egg and their dignity,'' said Daniel Drake,
executive assist ant U.S. Attorney. The last three cases his agency
prosecuted in volved scams of $17 million. Only 5 percent was
recovered for victims.
</P>
<P>
   Since February of 1994 there have been 152 arrests for telemar
keting scams in Arizona with 154 indictments and 112 convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano agreed that such pros ecutions aren't the only
solution. ``Prevention and education is what this program is all
about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was delighted with the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a good step but it doesn't go far enough, said
Joe Soltis of Scottsdale, whose father has fallen victim to some
question able solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed the Legisla ture doesn't have the courage to
enact laws that would clamp down on scams of the elderly, and on
products that offer no value to them,'' he said. ``Some are coerced
into buying products they don't need.''
</P>
<P>
   AARP volunteer Ann Weber, however, sees Operation Intercept as a
great beginning. ``We have to keep trying. Friends, neighbors have
to be on a lookout. Person-to-person is how change is going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Morton, also an AARP volunteer, agreed. Tuesday morning
she had received three unsolicited calls from people wanting her to
purchase something over the phone. One man said he was going to be
in her area that week and would stop by with a product. When she
quizzed him further and asked him to name the area she lived in, he
was stumped.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, the Elder Fraud Prevention Team, which
formed last fall, will hold commu nity fraud forums in Phoenix on
May 13, in Sierra Vista on May 27 and in Kingman on June 23.
Earlier this year there were similar forums were held in Mesa,
Phoenix, Pres cott and Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Cardinals football play ers, including wide receiver
Frank Sanders, will tape public service announcements asking
younger rela tives and neighbors of elders to be on the lookout for
scams. Sanders is doing this partly because his own grandmother
helped raise him. ``I don't want anyone taking advantage of me, my
grandmother or any elders in the state of Arizona,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A series of live call-in shows will air on KAET (Channel 8) at 7
p.m. June 28, June 29 and July 1.
</P>
<P>
   While the fraud prevention efforts will continue throughout the
year, Operation Intercept will conclude with a reverse boiler room
in Phoenix on July 13. The phone bank of volunteers will make warn
ing calls to Arizona elders whose names were found on lists used by
convicted scam artists.
</P>
<P>
   Fraudulent telemarketers are de veloping new scams and frauds
constantly, often based on the day's news. Appealing to the elder
gener ation's spirit of community, fake charities are likely to
spring up in the wake of any national tragedy, including the
Midwest tornadoes or Colorado shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Or appealing to the desire or need for money, fraud merchants
offer phony prizes, illegal sweepstakes or sham investments.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen of the FBI says that the two biggest schemes now in Ari
zona involve lottery and investment frauds.
</P>
<P>
   Recent investigations by the FBI indicate that 80 percent of
calls were deliberately targeted at older people.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, re search sponsored by AARP shows
that the older people victimized by fraudulent telemarketers are
not lonely, vulnerable or isolated. The typical telemarketing fraud
victims are relatively affluent, well-educated people, socially
active in their community and just as suspicious of dishonest
telemarketers as non-vic tims.
</P>
<P>
   Not all sweepstakes and contests are scams. Or telemarketers
crooks. But the FBI estimates that there are more than 1,400 scam
operations making calls each day in America. Most of them, it
seems, at dinner time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
