<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLICKI STOPS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Dave Mlicki wasn't good enough to crack the Dodgers'
starting rotation, but Angels hitters might find that difficult to
believe.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki, traded to the Detroit Tigers by the Dodgers on April 16,
held the Angels to one run in seven innings in the Tigers' 3-1
victory Tuesday night before 13,411 at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki, however, did not get the win because the Tigers did not
take the lead until the eighth inning on Dean Palmer's two-run
homer off Mark Petkovsek. It spoiled another impressive performance
by Angels starter Ken Hill, who allowed just one run and seven hits
in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Brocail (1-0) earned the victory over Mike Holtz (1-1).
Todd Jones pitched the ninth and got his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mlicki's fourth start with the Tigers since the trade,
and in three of them, he has allowed one earned run or fewer. He
also lowered his ERA to 2.01 after yielding five hits, including a
solo homer by Matt Walbeck that accounted for all of the Angels
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was behind a lot of good pitchers in L.A.,'' Mlicki said.
``And I was in the bullpen. I didn't like that too much. It was
hard knowing that I can start, but I had to look at it like we had
some good arms over there and I couldn't take it personally. Who
are you going to take out of the rotation?''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mlicki whom the Dodgers removed from the rotation, and
Tuesday he made the Angels pay. The Angels, however, made a
relative unknown like John Snyder of the White Sox look good Monday
when Snyder threw a complete-game four-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Without Tim Salmon in the lineup (sprained left wrist), the
Angels looked feeble at the plate Tuesday. When batting with
runners in scoring position, they were 0 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to start finding holes in big situations,'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``You win games with two-out hits with
guys in scoring position. We're just not swinging very good right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Salmon out of the lineup, Troy Glaus batted cleanup. In the
first inning, he came to the plate with runners on second and third
and one out. He struck out and the Angels didn't score in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take responsibility for that,'' Collins said. ``I slapped
him in the 4-spot. That's a lot of responsibility for a young guy.
I'm sure his grip on the bat was tighter than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hill, it was another hard-luck outing. Tuesday's game marked
the fourth in a row that he's gone at least seven innings. He
hasn't allowed more than three runs in any of them, but has only
one win to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying, man,'' Hill said. ``I'm just trying to get some
consistency. The thing is timely hitting. They got timely hitting
and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   After walking eight batters in his previous start, Hill walked
only three Tuesday. However, he also hit three batters, including
two in one inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Tigers loaded the bases with no outs on a
single and two hit batters. But Hill got Damion Easley to hit into
a 1-2-3 double play. The Tigers still managed to score on a wild
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, he pitched a great game,'' Walbeck said. ``He threw
strikes, got ahead of hitters and had a great fastball. He kept us
in the game. As lethargic as our bats are, he did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck did all he could for Hill, hitting the homer, throwing
out two would-be base stealers and tagging out a runner at the
plate on an attempted double steal. But it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the tough ones,'' Collins said. ``When you have
opportunities ... Dave pitched a great game, but we had some shots
tonight. We had chances where a base hit can put the game away. But
that's what's been happening to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
