<HEADER>
A4657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT &LR;      05-05 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS TOP METS, 6-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If he could have just one pitch back from the seventh
inning on Tuesday night, Al Leiter said, it would not be the
two-run homer he surrendered to Derek Bell, or even the run-scoring
double from Craig Biggio that broke a 1-1 tie. It was a seemingly
harmless two-out pitch to the opposing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   That pitch, which Mike Hampton hammered for a triple, opened the
way to the New York Mets' first defeat in seven games, a 6-1 loss
to the Houston Astros before an announced crowd of 27,192 on
another chilly night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely the pitch to Hampton,'' Leiter said, shaking
his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch was a fastball on a 1-0 count that Leiter left up in
the strike zone. Hampton blasted the ball over the head of the
Mets' center fielder, Brian McRae, and raced his way to third base,
standing up.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (3-1) is a good hitter for a pitcher, one who batted
.262 last season. And considering that he was recruited to play
defensive back by Alabama and Notre Dame, Hampton _ according to
scouting reports _ might also be among the fastest-running pitchers
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the triple was just the second of Hampton's career in 236
major league at-bats (the first was off Orel Hershiser, who now
pitches for the Mets). His hit not only led the Astros to a
three-run outburst, all with two outs, but it also helped drop
Leiter to 1-3 on the year.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch after Hampton's triple, Leiter threw Biggio a
tough slider in on his hands, but Biggio was able to line it over
the glove of a leaping Robin Ventura, scoring Hampton. Bell
followed with his fifth homer of the season on a 3-1 fastball up.
The Astros had a 4-1 lead, and the Mets' season-best winning streak
was nearing its end at six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Hampton hit that triple, Al might have lost his
concentration a little bit,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the other side, too,'' said Hampton, whose .273
average this year is nearly double Bobby Bonilla's .140. ``You
expect to get the pitcher out every time he comes to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for expectations. This is not the sort of beginning to
the season that Leiter _ who wound up being charged with 6 runs and
11 hits in 7-plus innings _ had hoped for after winning a
career-best 17 games last season before re-signing with the Mets
for $32 million over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the most earned runs Leiter allowed in any of his 28
starts was four. This season, he has allowed four earned runs once
and, after Tuesday night, six earned runs twice.
</P>
<P>
   In 40 innings covering six starts, Leiter has allowed 21 earned
runs. His earned run average is a bloated 4.73. Last season, it was
2.47, tied for third lowest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   And, to think, Leiter could have escaped the seventh inning of a
1-1 game if he could have just made one good pitch to Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, meanwhile, made seven innings full of them, allowing
the Mets just two hits. The first was an infield single to Edgardo
Alfonzo leading off the fourth. The second was a run-scoring single
off the end of Mike Piazza's bat with two out in the sixth that
briefly erased the Astros' 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonilla _ who was booed again all night in his first game
since April 24 _ left runners on first and third when Hampton
struck him out to end the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I'm upset at myself because I got two quick
outs,'' Leiter said. ``I'm thinking, `Great. I'm going to have a
1-2-3 inning and keep Biggio, Bell and Bagwell for the eighth.' And
then Hampton gets a triple.''
</P>
<P>
   And ruined Leiter's night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
