<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLVES-ROCKETS-HN     05-05 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLVES-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
With the lead slipping and the last hopes of home-court advantage
hanging in the balance, the Rockets took motivation seriously.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They began shooting the players.
</P>
<P>
   Never have the Rockets seemed so determined to hold on to a
lead. Less clear was why they waited so long to resort to such
extreme measures. That and how a Rockets point guard could be
involved in a freak accident and it not be Brent Price.
</P>
<P>
   But after Cuttino Mobley was shot by the team mascot in a
T-shirt giveaway, the Rockets brought out their own offensive
firepower to rebuild their lead and keep it growing in the second
half until taking a 100-83 win Tuesday night over the Minnesota
Timberwolves at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   The win allowed the Rockets to keep pace with the Los Angeles
Lakers in their down-to-the-wire race for the home-court advantage
in the first round of the playoffs. The Lakers (30-19), hosting
Portland tonight, hold the tiebreaker on the Rockets (also 30-19),
who are at Denver tonight in the last game ever in McNichols Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to do their thing; we're going to do ours,''
Rockets forward Charles Barkley said of the race with the Lakers.
``When we play well, we can win anywhere. If we don't get it (the
home court), we can't whine and complain about it. We blew it
ourselves. We'll go to LA and play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets seemed capable of winning on any court Tuesday night
when they got just the sort of momentum-building game they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley not only survived a T-shirt shot upside his face, after
leaving the court for repairs he returned late in the first half.
(The Rockets Power Cannon/accident waiting to happen did not
reappear.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocked me, but I knew what hit me,'' Mobley said. ``I was
mad. He shoots it, but he doesn't know how to control it. It stung,
but it didn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Once back in the game, Mobley, who had 18 points, and fellow
rookie Michael Dickerson, who finished with a season-high 31, took
over the shooting for the night. Dickerson's 31 were the most for a
Rockets rookie since Hakeem Olajuwon in the 1984-85 season. He made
six of eight 3s, one shy of his Rockets rookie record, and had five
assists, also one from his personal best.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence is booming right now,'' Dickerson said. ``Last
night, I shot some extra shots, Sam Mack and I. He helped me with
my 3-point shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than merely catching a good night and taking
advantage of the usual double teams inside, Dickerson, Mobley and
Mack got open looks on the breaks and off drives inside and passes
back out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets matched their season high with 32 assists. And
though they scored just 14 fast-break points, they again credited
their newfound taste for life in the fast lane for igniting their
offense, and especially Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games are what I had in mind,'' Barkley said of
the emphasis on playing with greater pace and energy. ``The kid
(Dickerson) is too good a player to shoot 3s all night and not get
touches. He's capable of scoring 15 to 20 points a night on shots,
fast breaks and making 3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Running more) brings energy to the table. We need the young
guys to play with a lot of energy. The young guys got it going.
They played with emotion. It makes it easier for everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   In a thorough role reversal, they even made it easier for the
big men inside. Though each shooter was handed plenty of open looks
while circling the double teams inside, they also worked to find
and create their own shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were moving the ball around,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``A lot of times, there wasn't even a double team
(involved). It makes it easy when you shoot the ball so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, especially, lit up the third quarter. He scored with
a three-point play, cutting to take a pass inside from Mobley, then
began to heat up. He scored on a break on a pass from Barkley, then
fired a 3 for a 61-50 Rockets lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Mobley nailed a trey, Dickerson added two, for 29 points
before the end of the quarter and a 10-point Rockets lead.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders, who called
off the double teams inside and paid for it. Barkley scored eight
of his 12 points in the first 4:09 of the fourth quarter. Olajuwon
hit a jumper and a pair of free throws, and with the Rockets up
86-70, Saunders went back to the double teams.
</P>
<P>
   That worked no better than it had in the third quarter. Mobley
immediately nailed a 3, then flipped a behind-the-back pass to
Scottie Pippen on the break. When Dickerson hit a short jumper in
the lane, he had 31 points, the Rockets led 93-71 and Saunders
called time out to allow both teams to begin clearing the benches
with 6:04 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're knocking down their shots, they're a difficult
team to beat,'' Saunders said. ``They weren't shooting the ball
well lately, and that's why they were having troubles. When they're
playing well, they're usually shooting the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   And should they slide again, they have a cartoonish bear with an
air cannon who is not afraid to use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
