<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-05 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING RITE TAKEN FROM SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Early in the game last week at KeyArena, Utah coach
Jerry Sloan pulled Greg Ostertag from the floor after the Jazz
center fluffed a layup that should have been a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   As Ostertag took a seat on the bench, player and coach bickered
for a couple of moments. Then Sloan ended the discussion with the
finality of a 50-mph mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just dunk the (deleted) ball,'' he shouted, staring directly
into Ostertag's eyes, ``and shut the (deleted) up.''
</P>
<P>
   What a powerful moment. What a perfect vignette for Sloan and a
superb metaphor for the continuing success of the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   What a great thing to repeat to the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, let the whole league hear it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of fat players, soft players, achy players, guys who
don't play hard all the time, guys who can't make free throws,
coaches who rationalize and cover up, and executives helpless to
manage the mess.
</P>
<P>
   I'm especially tired of the scene in a year when owners locked
out the ego monsters they created, then unlocked the monsters to
stumble over themselves while charging the public full price.
</P>
<P>
   Am I little cranky?
</P>
<P>
   Yup. Been cranky all season. Watching the Sonics, the league's
most disappointing team _ remember, the Chicago Bulls planned to be
horrific _ cranked up the crankiness.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who or what is saddled with blame for the
butchery, the worst thing about it from a fan perspective was the
Sonics cashiered the one steady highlight of the local sports
calendar _ the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the last nine seasons, Seattle's oldest and most
tradition-rich pro franchise provided a steady spring stream of
entertainment by inviting Michael Jordan, Charles Barkley, Karl
Malone, John Stockton, Clyde Drexler, Hakeem Olajuwon, Kevin
Garnett, Jason Kidd and Dikembe Mutombo, among many others, to an
irresistibly unpredictable hoops party.
</P>
<P>
   Freakish as was Dennis Rodman, his play and his circus in June
1996, will never be forgotten by all who bore witness.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Shawn Kemp grow from shaky fawn against Portland's Buck
Williams in 1991 to virtual co-MVP with Jordan in the '96 Finals
was a rich treat for the long-term Sonic investor.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Gary Payton carry a flagging team past a desperately
eager Minnesota unit last spring was a rare demonstration of pure
force of will.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Game 4 of the first-round series in 1997 in Phoenix,
when Rex Chapman threw in an off-balance, running 28-footer to tie
the game, only to see the Sonics win in overtime? I'm not sure if
that result was more confounding than one on the same America West
Arena floor four years earlier, the seventh game of the Western
Conference finals, which the Suns won 123-110 because of a huge
disparity in free throws that assured a made-for-TV Barkley-Jordan
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   How about the 3-2 first-round win over a favored Golden State
team in '92 that ushered in the Sonics as an NBA power? Or the 4-0
second-round sweep of defending champion Houston in '96 that made
the Sonics look limitless?
</P>
<P>
   Even the astonishing defeats, such as 1994's first-round loss to
the eighth-seeded Nuggets, were epic sports spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   Spoiled? Sure. That's a big virtue of big-time spectator sports.
Expectations can be indulged without fear of consequence to
anything truly meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly all of this decade, the Sonics engaged their
following in a tumultuous run through spring whitewater that
annually threw the fans overboard with the always-overboard George
Karl _ only to see all pull themselves back and ask to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't write me about the cyclical nature of sports.
Every moron knows that. That all sports franchises screw up doesn't
eliminate the annoying reality that the Sonics have broken with
their tradition right now.
</P>
<P>
   The void is something of a screamer, particularly given the
other local voids.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that saw the Seahawks go 8-8, the Husky footballers go
6-6, the Husky men's basketballers go 17-14 and the Mariners flail
around .500 in the worst division in sports, the Sonics were
expected to be the go-to guys for big-time sports fun beyond the
vast ooze of Seattle mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, the Sonics had the sixth-longest active streak in
the NBA for consecutive playoff appearances. While it can be argued
that only championships count, their steady presence in the
playoffs was not just a point of pride about consistency, but was a
growing sports tradition in a relatively tradition-free part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for reasons already well-chronicled that will be
relentlessly rehashed in the coming days as fingers get pointed
(and raised), the party will go on in Portland, San Antonio and 14
other cities while the Sonics share draft-lottery intrigue with the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Cranky? Spoiled? You betcha, Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   As my man Sloan was saying, just dunk the stinkin' ball, and
shut the hell up.
</P>
<P>
   But in the absence of an opportunity to dunk ...
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
