<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-SUIT-LADN     05-05 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TRIAL TESTIMONY GETS NASTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Walt Disney Co. Chairman Michael Eisner testified
he may have aimed the statement ``I hate the little midget'' at
former studio chief Jeffrey Katzenberg and vowed not to pay him
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   In the extraordinary showdown Tuesday between two of Hollywood's
most powerful men, Eisner also said he didn't recall seeing most of
the documents that Katzenberg says proves Disney owes him more than
$250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with notes taken by his biographer, Eisner conceded
he might have made the ``midget'' comment about Katzenberg, who is
shorter than Eisner. The notes indicate his response to
Katzenberg's dispute over the contract was: ``I don't care what he
thinks, (I'm not) going to pay him any of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements, read by Katzenberg lawyer Bert Fields, never
made it into Eisner's autobiography, ``Work in Progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner responded to Fields' tactic with a stern warning,
suggesting the line of questioning was ``ill-advised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To characterize me as hating him is absurd, and is going down
a direction that I think is not in your client's best interest or
mine, but particularly your client's,'' Eisner told Fields. ``But
that's up to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner sought to downplay the feud with Katzenberg. He said he
only recalled two face-to-face arguments with Katzenberg _ both
toward the end of the studio chief's tenure at Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's like a dentist,'' Eisner said. ``You forget
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Disney's lawyer, Eisner testified that
Katzenberg had a ``dark side,'' but stressed that the comments he
made to book collaborator Tony Schwartz were meant to stay private.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, who worked at Disney from 1984 to 1994, claims he
brought the studio ``from worst to first'' during his tenure, but
was never paid a multimillion-dollar bonus based on his division's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Disney claims Katzenberg lost that bonus when he left the
company two years before his contract was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lawsuit was settled last year, but both sides agreed
to let a retired judge decide a few final issues, including
Katzenberg's fraud claim and a dispute over merchandising profits.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's fiery testimony came at the end of what had been a
relatively uneventful day in the week-old trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Disney lawyer Louis Meisinger, Eisner
said he became angry with Katzenberg because he believed him to be
playing ``media games.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said he once received a fax from Katzenberg that was
intended for Fields, thanking the lawyer for his help in dealing
with the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just one of the dark sides of an otherwise
exceptional executive,'' Eisner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
