<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4688 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      05-05 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAME DUCK SONICS WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There were no lineup changes to question. The injuries
were inconsequential, and for the first time so was the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of play was important. But making sharp defensive reads
or crunch-time baskets were nowhere near vital.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics finally played a plain and simple game _ one they won
110-100 Tuesday night against the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is how a season winds down when you have
been eliminated from the playoffs. The Sonics missed the postseason
for the first time since the 1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   The unfamiliar situation compelled Sonics coach Paul Westphal to
give the team's younger players heavy minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He already had begun to take a hard look at what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fairest criticism is that we didn't find a way to overcome
adversity,'' Westphal said. ``Somehow, some way we didn't get the
job done. Whether it was losing in Vancouver or making a defensive
breakdown. ... The fairest criticism is we did it to ourselves. We
didn't overcome adversity well enough to get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics conclude their regular season Wednesday night in
Los Angeles against the Clippers, they will play for a respectable
record. They can finish the year 25-25, and avoid a below-.500
record. The last time the Sonics turned in a losing season was
1986-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to finish strong,'' guard Hersey Hawkins said.
``Everybody did a great job tonight of trying to be aggressive and
playing hard. Everybody knew the circumstances we were under, so I
was happy about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics controlled the game from start to finish. They led
38-27 after the first quarter, and were never seriously threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the team's predicament is a bitter pill for Westphal to
swallow. He certainly could never have fathomed missing the
playoffs in his return to NBA coaching.
</P>
<P>
   He has been asked the question, ``What happened?'' a thousand
times and the barrage will continue until next season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal points to the 50-game schedule and, most of all, to
injuries as the reasons the Sonics were derailed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he can't help but think of a couple of games. Like when
the Sonics could have beaten the Los Angeles Lakers at the Forum
March 5. The Sonics lost that game 103-100 because they allowed the
Lakers to cherry-pick and score easy layups down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there are the missed free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics shot 68 percent from the line this season. That has
nothing to do with being out of shape or playing five games in five
nights.
</P>
<P>
   Just think what could have happened if the team had scored 100
more points from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fair,'' Westphal said. ``To me the only thing that's
unfair is when people don't get their facts right and then build a
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from winning their final regular-season home game, the
Sonics gave younger teammembers playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Vladimir Stepania started at center with Vin Baker, Don
MacLean, Gary Payton and Hersey Hawkins. Rookie forward Jelani
McCoy played significant minutes off the bench as did third-string
point guard Drew Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania showed just how much he has improved since the
beginning of the season. He scored 17 points and grabbed 10
rebounds. More impressive was that Stepania played 34 minutes.
Earlier this season he would have fouled out before logging that
much time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I as nervous,'' Stepania said. ``But as the game went on I
felt OK. This season has been a big experience for me. I think I'll
be OK next season.''
</P>
<P>
   The team will activate rookie Rashard Lewis, who could be
inserted into the starting lineup Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some good performances from the young guys, which is
something to build on,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's time to forget this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
