<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-05 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SCORE 25,000-plus NBA points and have a spiffy banner bearing your
name raised to the rafters, and you, too, can enjoy what Hakeem
Olajuwon enjoyed Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Comp time.
</P>
<P>
   He did what he needed to do, then let the kids handle the rest.
He rebounded like the champion he is. He threw in 17 points. He
blocked and altered a few shots.
</P>
<P>
   He got up the floor for some honest-to-goodness hard work,
banging with all the young studs from Minnesota who really thought
they had a chance. They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the stuff of Dream in more ways than one. This was
how it was supposed to work all year long.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets won, the Rockets ran, the rookies shot lights-out,
and Olajuwon turned in a mere 32 minutes, laughing away the final
few ticks of this 100-83 laugher from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   This was the stuff that makes the Rockets dream about all sorts
of possibilities for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the young guys get going and get emotional, it makes it
easier on all the older guys,'' Charles Barkley said. ``This was a
game when we were at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Olajuwon rebounding defensively and turning and
throwing the ball up the floor and rookies Michael Dickerson and
Cuttino Mobley finishing so many fast breaks with authority.
</P>
<P>
   This was Barkley backing it in, backing it in, forcing the poor
Timberwolves to double-team him, then laughing through his
mouthpiece while finding Dickerson outside the arc for a wide-open
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles told us we need to start getting the ball up and down
the floor,'' Dickerson said. ``We're trying. I love it. We play
better when we're going up and down the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson sank 10 of 18 shots for a career-high 31 points, the
most by a Rockets rookie since 1984-1985, Olajuwon's first season.
Mobley hit six of 10 shots en route to 18 points _ this despite
being wounded in action when Clutch, the furry mascot with a death
wish, accidentally shot a T-shirt from a cannon at Mobley's jaw in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The trio of Olajuwon, Barkley and Scottie Pippen
combined for one more shot but made one fewer field goal than
Dickerson and Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone was in agreement afterward that this was a good
thing. This was the stuff of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``All night, I was getting the ball and wasn't hesitating,''
Dickerson said. ``I got kind of hot, and they started looking for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Dickerson admitted he rarely had the
confidence to demand the ball and take the big shots. Olajuwon,
Barkley and Pippen were, after all, players whom Dickerson idolized
as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know me, and I didn't know them,'' Dickerson said.
``I had to earn their confidence. Tonight, to be honest, Hakeem was
the one that got me going. I didn't take one shot (early), and he
started telling me, `Take that shot. You have to take that shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   After so many ups and downs in 1999, so many plodding efforts on
both ends, it was the second consecutive game in which the Rockets
seemed to find a nice balance. There they were, shuffling back and
forth between the post-up game that makes Olajuwon and Barkley
happy and the running, shooting, passing effort that might be the
answer for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we move the ball around,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said, ``it makes it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked it. As huge as Olajuwon was on his night, it all
seemed effortless. As nice a game as Barkley had (12 points, eight
rebounds), his most impressive statistic clearly was his six
assists. In fact, going into the fourth quarter, the Rockets as a
team had hit 28 field goals _ 26 of them coming off an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to win (in the playoffs) like this team did
five years ago,'' Barkley said. ``We can't win that way anymore. We
can't play that game. We have to get out running with the guys we
have. Scottie can run, Cuttino can run, and Dickerson is real
athletic and can shoot. When we run, Dickerson can help us a lot
more than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what happened Tuesday, and it couldn't have come at a
better time. The Dream got to enjoy the final few minutes of his
night from the bench. Dickerson had a career night. Everyone
pitched in _ inside, outside, up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone could dream. The playoffs are just around the corner,
and the Rockets might finally be turning the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three times this year, I've felt like I felt tonight,''
Dickerson said. ``I've felt like I could shoot and hit everything,
but the shots weren't always there. Tonight, it came to me.
Hopefully, we'll keep playing like we did tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
