<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Making a mess of poke salad
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A fellow I know had brought me a mess of poke
salad. Maybe you're familiar with poke salad. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   If not, let me quote Tony Joe White, an authority on the
subject. He had the 1960s hit song ``Poke Salad Annie,'' which
begins with this intro:
</P>
<P>
   ``If some of y'all never been down south too much, I'm gonna
tell you a little about this so that you'll understand what I'm
talkin' about ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Down there we have a plant that grows out in the woods, and in
the field ... looks somethin' like a turnip green, and everybody
calls it poke salad ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Used to know a girl lived down there and she'd go out in the
evenings and pick her a mess of it, carry it home and cook it for
supper, cause that's about all they had to eat, but they did all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The refrain is the part I like best:
</P>
<P>
   Poke Salad Annie,
</P>
<P>
   The gators got your granny,
</P>
<P>
   Everybody said it was a shame,
</P>
<P>
   Cause her Mama was workin on the chain gang,
</P>
<P>
   A wretched, spiteful, straight-razor totin' woman,
</P>
<P>
   Lord have mercy, pick me a mess of it.
</P>
<P>
   The thing about poke salad, lest we forget, is that it's
poisonous, right down to the roots. You want to pick the leaves
early in the spring when they're young and tender, then be sure to
parboil them good and proper.
</P>
<P>
   Bring them to a roiling /
</P>
<P>
   When I happened to come across it, the stuff looked still fresh
enough. So it was I decided to cook a pot full.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, picking away at the stems and washing the leaves,
when, hard to believe, two ugly spiders bigger than a quarter came
crawling out from under a sprig of poke salad, each alive and
kicking on all eight legs despite their stint of forced
hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes more than a couple of spiders to deter me from
dinner. I loosed them outside _ after what they'd been through,
they deserved to go free _ and then finished washing the poke salad
and put it in a pot to boil.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the second egg pouch surfaced, bright white as a
new golf ball and almost as big as a bird's egg, that I decided to
take the whole mess out back and dump it.
</P>
<P>
   All together now ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said it was a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. I can tell you probably why she carried a straight razor.
It was to fight off spiders while she was cleaning the poke salad
... wretched, spiteful spiders, especially after two weeks in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
