 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 430 - May 5, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY
-- No. 430 -- May 5, 1999 We are offering the following articles
for sale. Please contact us for availability your country. Best
regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SLIM CHANCE : CALISTA FLOCKHART SEES OPPORTUNITIES
</P>
<P>
   ON THE BIG SCREEN The star of the popular TV series ``Ally
McBeal'' has paid a price for her sudden fame that includes
speculation that she suffers from an eating disorder and a recent,
widely publicized rumour that she was having an affair with
``Ally'' creator David E. Kelley, who is married to Michelle
Pfeiffer, Flockhart's co-star in her next film. Fans may be
astounded to see ``Ally'' spout Shakespeare as the hopelessly
love-struck Helena in ``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' but Flockhart was actually a stage veteran long before she
hit the small screen. ``What's so amazing,'' she says, is that
Shakespeare wrote the play centuries ago and yet the Helena he
created is not unlike Ally in 1999. They are both young women who
are ambitious, driven and passionate ...'' By Jeanne Wolf and Shep
Morgan. 1,300 words + photo. (N/A England.) 2. HOLLYWOOD GOOD GUY
Australian actor Guy Pearce admits he's a sensitive man. So when he
agreed to star in the grisly cannibalism movie ``Ravenous,'' the
decision was largely based on the reputation of its director,
Milcho Manchevski. And then two weeks into filming, 20th Century
Fox abruptly fired Manchevski. ``They obviously wanted to make a
movie that was funny and fun. Milcho didn't.'' So Pearce rebelled,
as did his co-star Robert Carlyle (of ``Trainspotting'' and ``The
Full Monty.'') By Louise Farr. From W magazine. 1,000 words +
photos. 3. MERLE HAGGARD STILL CALLS THE TUNE When Merle Haggard
released ``Okie from Muskogee'' 30 years ago, the song made him a
right-wing hero. Issued at the height of the Vietnam War protests,
it won him praise from conservatives for the line ``We don't smoke
marijuana in Muskogee/We don't take our trips on LSD.'' Haggard
always said the fuss was overplayed, claiming he intended the song
as a kind of joke. And today this country legend and rugged
individualist says that conservatives - especially the
anti-marijuana forces - have gone too far. By Steve Morse. From The
Boston Globe. 1,200 words + photo. 4. BOSNIAN-BORN DIRECTOR'S
APOLITICAL COMEDY DERAILED BY WAR It seems like dij` vu all over
again for Emir Kusturica. October Films has announced it is pushing
back the U.S. release of the Bosnian-born director's latest comedy
``Black Cat, White Cat'' from May until the autumn because of the
conflict in Kosovo. After the release of Kusturica's last film,
``Underground,'' in 1994, the French press declared that the
director's three-hour-long satirical comment on 50 years of war and
upheaval in the Balkans was pro-Serbian. Kusturica was
understandably furious and shortly after winning the Palme d'Or for
best film at the 1995 Cannes Film Festival, he announced he was
quitting the movie business. By Andrea R. Vaucher. From The
Hollywood Reporter. 1,000 words + photo. 5. NEW 'SEASONS' DAWN IN
VIETNAM Vietnamese-American director Tony Bui's first feature film,
``Three Seasons'' won both the Grand Jury Prize and the Audience
Award at this year's Sundance Film Festival. It is a moving,
remarkably mature depiction of life in modern Saigon. Bui, 26,
portrays a city scarred by decades of war, but trying to look to
the future. Harvey Keitel, the only non-Vietnamese actor in the
film, plays an American soldier who returns to Saigon after more
than 20 years to find the half-Vietnamese daughter he left behind.
By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo. 6. PUTTING THE FORCE IN
'THE PHANTOM MENACE' ... FOR LESS Filmed on three continents and
loaded with special effects, sceptics contend that the budget of
``only'' $115 million for the new Star Wars film ``Phantom Menace''
defies conventional logic. But there was nothing conventional about
the way it was made, says its producer Rick McCallum, who has
worked in the trenches with George Lucas to engineer a new type of
filmmaking. By Paula Parisi. From The Hollywood Reporter. 3,000
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
REGINA CARTER'S HIP 'HEART' STRINGS If music were a self-ordained
life force that could change form and chemistry at whim, crackling
like lightning then sobbing like a child, it might evince the same
metaphysical vigour as the supple jazz violin of Regina Carter. By
Timothy White. From Billboard. 1,200 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
AIDAN QUINN'S FAMILY AFFAIR Aidan Quinn's new movie ``This Is My
Father'' is based on a story that his mother used to tell her young
sons around the fire on cold winter nights, a story about two
lovers separated by class and religion in 1930s Ireland. It is a
true story. ``My grandfather actually carried the coffin of the
young suitor in the movie,'' says Quinn, ``so he was known to our
family. And, like any good Irish story, it got passed down until it
became lore.'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
