A4886 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-VACCINE06-COX     05-05 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-VACCINE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Test vaccines for cancer to begin
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Franciscan Medical Center will develop and test
the first cancer vaccine of its kind on up to 40 local patients in
the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Finley and his staff will combine immune-system cells
from a patient's blood with irradiated and coated cells from the
patient's tumor to produce the two-part vaccine in a new lab at
Franciscan.
</P>
<P>
   Participants must have cancers for which there is no effective
conventional treatment, such as chemotherapy, and usually must
enroll before surgery to remove the tumor. Melanoma, the deadliest
skin cancer, has been the most susceptible to cancer vaccines, but
the trial will include a variety of other cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer vaccines enhance the immune system not to prevent a
disease, as do most vaccines, but to attack a tumor that already
exists. While the immune system is designed to destroy any cells
that don't belong in the body, it does not recognize cancer cells
as interlopers, which enables tumors to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because each patient's malignancy is genetically unique, it is
our hope that this cancer vaccine will teach the body's immune
system to attack the cancer cells,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   Each part of his vaccine has been used with some success
independently. Finley and other scientists suspect the combination
will be more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Melanoma and colon cancer cells have been destroyed by using
vaccines with inactive cells from the same tumor, coated with a
substance the immune system can recognize, called a hapten. That
process helps the immune system identify the tumor as foreign to
the body.
</P>
<P>
   Dendritic white blood cells, which Finley called the body's best
cells for activating the immune system, have been used in treating
kidney and prostate cancer cells, as well as melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``By pre-exposing those cells to the tumor cells, the hope is it
will develop a more robust reaction to the cancer,'' said Dr.
Stuart Merl, Franciscan's medical director for oncology.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for community hospitals to conduct Phase I cancer
trials, designed to establish the safety and effectiveness of a
treatment before it is compared with existing therapies. But Finley
began working on cancer vaccines in 1995 with scientists at Hipple
Cancer Research Center and conducted a small trial of five terminal
melanoma patients, two of whom survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went right back to work at my own real estate business and I
play golf twice a week,'' said Wally Sweetwater, now 73, who
completed the vaccine protocol in November 1995. ``We carry our own
bags and walk 18 holes at Miami Valley. I would not be here today
without Dr. Finley.''
</P>
<P>
   CANCER VACCINE TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   What: Clinical trial of two-part cancer vaccine using cells from
the patient's own tumor and blood.
</P>
<P>
   Who: Cancer patients with advanced breast, colo-rectal, gastric,
hepato cellular, nero-endocrine, non-small-cell lung, ovarian,
pancreatic, head and neck carcinomas as well as melanoma and
sarcoma skin cancers, may be eligible to be treated on this
protocol. Participants must have cancers that have not responded to
conventional treatment, such as radiation or chemotherapy, or
cancers for which no standard treatment exists beyond surgery.
</P>
<P>
   How: To be screened for possible enrollment in the research
protocol, patients must be referred by their physicians to Nancy
Hines, Dr. Robert Finley's registered nurse, (937) 228-5130.
</P>
<P>
   When: Enrollment must precede surgery to remove the cancer in
most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: Free to participants. The Surgical Oncology Fund,
available through the Franciscan Foundation at the medical center,
has been established to cover costs of the research project,
including charges for treatments not covered by insurance because
they are experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
