<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commandments a bit too rigid to become law
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I'm not surprised that the Ten
Commandments died in the Florida Legislature last week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 52, which would have permitted the posting of The
Ten Commandments in public schools, courtrooms and government
buildings, didn't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   That's because it wasn't handled right.
</P>
<P>
   Good legislation must be flexible to manipulation by the
competing lobbies. There's got to be a little something in it for
everybody. But there was nothing in the Ten Commandments the way it
was presented. Just a lot of don't do this, don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   Florida legislators needed more of a reason to embrace the Ten
Commandments. They needed some Ten Commandments pork.
</P>
<P>
   I've begun compiling a workable Ten Commandments for the state
to adopt in future legislative sessions. Sure, it's not perfect.
But no viable piece of legislation shaped by amendments ever is.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the name needs to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``commandments'' is a red flag to the American Civil
Liberties Union. It just an invitation to a lawsuit. The ACLU is
currently talking trash to Palm Beach County's government over a
move to make strippers carry ID cards (a visually challenging
concept.)
</P>
<P>
   Why give the ACLU something else to gripe about?
</P>
<P>
   So before we even get started, let's just deal with the name.
Delete word ``Commandments.'' Replace with ``Voluntary
Suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Voluntary Suggestion: I am the Lord thy God, Thou
shalt have no other gods before me.
</P>
<P>
   Way too churchy. The atheists will never buy it. Suggested
amendment: Delete the word, ``God.'' Insert the word, ``Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   The Second Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not make unto thee
any graven image, or any likeness of any thing. . .
</P>
<P>
   OK, we can throw a bone to the Religious Right on this one. And
to avoid confusion, we'll tack on, ``This should not be construed
to prohibit the state from marketing a `Choose God' vanity license
plate at a future date.''
</P>
<P>
   The Third Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not take the name of
the Lord thy God in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Amended: ``. . . without the express prior written consent of
Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Voluntary Suggestion: Remember the sabbath day, to
keep it holy. . .
</P>
<P>
   Gambling industry amendment: ``. . . and remember, kids get into
the greyhound track for only 50 cents on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Voluntary Suggestion: Honor thy mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   AARP amendment: ``. . . with senior citizen discounts for all
shopping mall purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not kill.
</P>
<P>
   NRA amendment: Delete the word ``not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seventh Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not commit
adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton amendment: Replace the word, ``commit'' with the word,
``prosecute.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eighth Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not steal.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal defense lawyer amendment: ``. . . but if thou do, thou
shalt hire a lawyer and avoid making incriminating statements after
getting arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ninth Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not lie.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism amendment: ``. . . but thou may make exaggerated claims
if it helps fill hotel rooms during the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tenth Voluntary Suggestion: Thou shalt not covet thy
neighbor's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Nudist amendment: Replace the word ``covet'' with the word,
``cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
