<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN06-COX     05-05 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pity the poor politician
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You've got to feel sorry for a candidate who
finishes behind a homeless person with a beeper. How do you explain
that on your resume?
</P>
<P>
   My heart goes out to Ray Vrudhula, a retired IBM engineer who
faces the ignominy of coming in dead last among all 17 candidates
in Saturday's three Austin City Council races.
</P>
<P>
   If this had been a NASCAR race, Vrudhula, who owns a small
software company called TekUSA, would have been lapped and run
over. Vrudhula even finished behind Jennifer Gale, a pager-packing
transient of questionable gender who got 691 votes (2.1 percent of
the vote) in the City Council Place 4 race for Beverly Griffith's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vrudhula staggered to the finish line like a
three-legged mule with a paltry 478 votes, or 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the votes I got were in my neighborhood,'' Vrudhula
said. Vrudhula needs to move to a bigger neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Vrudhula figures he finished behind Gale because it was ``just a
random happening.'' So was the Titanic running into that large
iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Vrudhula figures he would have done better if he'd raised more
money. The quixotic Vrudhula began the race with the notion that it
was ``really obscene `` to raise buckets of money for a local
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, one of the things is I refused to raise money like the
other people,'' Vrudhula said. ``I just had one fundraiser, and a
few people came and gave me money.''
</P>
<P>
   If Vrudhula's intent was to avoid contributions, he did one
heckuva job. As of April 21, the latest figures available show he
had raised $2,276, or $82,743.29 less than Griffith. So naturally
Griffith won, because as we all know in politics, money talks and
you know what walks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those same figures show Gale had raised just $69.75. And
it was probably raised a dime at a time on the corner.
</P>
<P>
   I think the reason Gale whupped Vrudhula like a rug on a
clothesline is that her message was sexier than Vrudhula's. ``One
of the things I wanted to bring out was to make Austin truly the
Software Capital of the World,'' Vrudhula said. His platform called
for training software engineers here instead of importing them.
</P>
<P>
   That message is dishwater compared to Gale's exciting call for
more Austin roads that lead ``right out into the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a candidate forum published in this newspaper, Gale said she
would like to build the Austin ``avenues, roads, streets and
boulevards'' that allow folks to travel ``right out into the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, most roads around here already end up out in the country,
if you follow them long enough. But I find Gale's ``Suddenly
Manor'' campaign more interesting than Vrudhula's call for more
locally-trained modem monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Vrudhula says he put out 75 yard signs . ``By the way, a lot of
those signs were stolen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why. They weren't particularly creative. They said,
simply, ``Vote for Ray Vrudhula Austin City Council Place 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Vrudhula would have turned more heads if his yard signs had
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Be a Fool-A
</P>
<P>
   Vote for Vrudhula''
</P>
<P>
   Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
