<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN06-COX     05-05 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Son learns lesson of friendship, letting go
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When you call home and there are loud sobs on the
other end of the line, it's never a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   These were not the wails of a spouse at-the-end-of-his-rope, but
chest-heaving, end-of-the-world-sobs. The way the world can only
end when you're 7.
</P>
<P>
   And the world had indeed ended, for one very small member of our
household _ Stripe, a salamander my son adopted as a pet.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, Stripe had not died a natural death. Alec had covered
Stripe's bucket with a dingy-white shawl that protected him from
the light, but not, unfortunately, from 3-year-olds. While
``playing'' with Stripe, Veronica yanked the tail off her brother's
pet.
</P>
<P>
   The salamurderess refused to exhibit remorse or accept
responsibility for the crime. She was concerned about Stripe, it's
true, but purely from a territorial standpoint: ``What happened to
my salamander? Who hurt my salamander?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alec shouldered all the weight of first loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe it,'' he said. ``I saw him this morning,
and now he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the only time in his life he would experience that
pain, that bereftness _ loss through death or desertion _ but this
was the first. I wish I could make it all better, kiss the hurt
away, but I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   I should have seen this coming, from the minute Alec captured
Stripe in the back yard and started in on his ``Can I keep him can
I keep him Mom please?'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   For a week, all was bliss. Alec shared his knowledge of
salamander habits and lore. He cupped Stripe in his palm and
chatted with him. He checked in on Stripe last thing before he went
to bed at night and first thing when he woke in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   And then, tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Served me right for breaking my cardinal rule, forged in the
crucible of childhood grief: ``Never let them become emotionally
attached to anything smaller than a cat.''
</P>
<P>
   I too, after all, had lost a pet at the hands (or, more
specifically, the feet) of a sibling. I flashed back to 1968, to my
pet mouse, Frodo _ my best friend the desolate summer after sixth
grade, after my ``group'' disowned me on the not unreasonable
grounds that they didn't care for my personality.
</P>
<P>
   Since my company was in little demand elsewhere, Frodo and I
spent countless hours together. I even let him sun himself on the
front porch, hovering protectively over him.
</P>
<P>
   A horn honked, and Beth, my ever-popular sister, sailed out the
front door to meet her public. Her 3-inch clogs landed on the
unsuspecting, and now extremely moribund, Frodo.
</P>
<P>
   The summer was ruined, and things with Beth have, well, never
been quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Alec was more understanding. He knew Veronica didn't
mean to kill Stripe. ``I just miss him,'' he said, voice quavering.
</P>
<P>
   Alec dug the earth around the bird bath, consecrating the burial
ground with violets and pinwheels. ``I hope Stripe likes his new
home,'' he said. I conducted the funeral service with unusual
eloquence, I thought, despite a few snafus:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, God, for letting Spike be a part of our lives . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stripe,'' Alec corrected. (First rule of effective eulogies, I
noted: Don't muff the name of the deceased.)
</P>
<P>
   ``And for letting Stripe be such a good friend to Alec, and Alec
such a good friend to Stripe.''
</P>
<P>
   Before going to bed that night, Alec gazed out the window at the
fresh grave, lit melodramatically by the security light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Stripe knows he was my best friend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On his face was stamped the first sad lesson of friendship: To
make a friend, you must take the risk of losing him.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
