<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEWART-COLUMN06-COX     05-05 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All signs point to a pointless endeavor
 &HT;    By D.L. Stewart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The hotel elevator doors closed and the bearded
guy who had just gotten on did a double-take when he saw the
teen-age girl standing in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina, right? `` he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age girl nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, the bearded guy shoved a pen and a copy of USA Today
at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you sign this for me?''
</P>
<P>
   She took the pen and paper, scribbled her name and returned
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you make it to my daughter?'' the guy said, pushing the
back at her. ``Her name's Erica. With a 'c.' ``
</P>
<P>
   She took the paper again, scribbled ``to Erica,'' with a ``c,''
and returned it to him. By then, the elevator had reached the sixth
floor and Martina Hingis, the No. 1 female tennis player in the
world, made a quick and silent exit.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded guy got off a few floors later, clutching his USA
Today. I wondered exactly what he would do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Would he rush home and give it to Erica, with a ``c''? And would
she be so proud that her dad had met a celebrity that she would
sleep with the newspaper under her pillow for the rest of her life?
</P>
<P>
   Would they have the front page framed and hang it on their wall,
so their friends and neighbors could be impressed that the bearded
guy had ridden for six floors on the same elevator with a
professional tennis player?
</P>
<P>
   Or would this front page of USA Today wind up in a drawer
somewhere until eventually it turned yellow and brittle and then
found its way to a trash can with all the other stuff that had no
more value?
</P>
<P>
   I've never understood about autographs.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been able to figure out why a grown person would
spend an hour standing outside an arena dressing room in hopes that
some sneering, snorting guitar player would scrawl his name on
their scrap of paper?
</P>
<P>
   What compels someone to pay for the privilege of standing line
at an autograph session to get the illegible signature of a
24-year-old whose major contributions to the advancement of
civilization are the ability to throw a baseball and spit tobacco
juice?
</P>
<P>
   A celebrity's autograph could serve as a tangible reminder that
you had an encounter with someone famous, I suppose. Proof that you
once met a celebrity. But how much satisfaction can there be in an
autograph from a teen-age tennis player who has so little interest
in you that she can't be bothered saying ``hello,'' ``goodbye,''
``you're welcome'' or, even, ``excuse me, I'm getting off on this
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm aware that some autographs probably have financial value. So
if you're on an elevator with, say, Queen Elizabeth or the pope, it
probably wouldn't be a bad idea to have them sign your USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'd feel differently about autographs if I didn't have a
job that brought me in contact with celebrities on an occasional
basis. In more than 30 years I have encountered many famous
figures, some of whom are rarely seen in public, such as the
Montgomery County recorder.
</P>
<P>
   In all that time I have asked for only one autograph.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, I had an interview and breakfast with the most famous
person I ever met. Possibly the most famous person in the world.
When we were finished, he handed me an 8-by-10 photograph of
himself on which he had written:
</P>
<P>
   ``To D.L., Enjoy life, it's later than you think. Muhammad
Ali.''
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what he did with mine.
</P>
<P>
   D.L. Stewart writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
