<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4896 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-STILTSVILLE06-COX     05-05 2176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-STILTSVILLE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legendary Stiltsville facing its last sunset
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISCAYNE BAY, Fla. _ It's just after 6 p.m. on a Thursday and
while the rest of Miami descends into traffic hell on U.S. 1 or the
Palmetto Expressway, Chris Knight glides toward his little yellow
house in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Above him, the sky glows orange, on the edge of twilight.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath, the sea goes from green to blue to where you can see
the stingrays flapping their wings and sharks grazing the sea
grass. Pelicans and cormorants skim the water. Suddenly, on the
horizon, a stand of old fishing cabins rises on stilts out of
Biscayne Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Knight points. ``Can you see them?'' he shouts as the Cape
Florida lighthouse comes into view.
</P>
<P>
   It's like he's commuting through time.
</P>
<P>
   With Miami slipping farther away, it's not hard to imagine when
sportsmen scouring the globe for game fish wound up here, sitting
around Crawfish Eddie's beer and bait shack, telling tales of
tarpon and bonefish. Or when a meal at the snazzy Quarterdeck Club
cost as much as a night at a first-rate Miami Beach hotel and
yachts, drunkenly navigated, littered the flats. Or when Plucky
Pierre opened the fab Bikini Club in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But that was back when turtle kraals still had turtles and
riding Flipper cost only a couple bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Stiltsville is almost gone now. Of the original 30, only
Knight's Bay Chateau and six neighboring houses remain, desperately
clinging to their leases on the flats in Biscayne National Park's
180,000 acres. Come July, unless it can be convinced otherwise, the
National Park Service will evict the ``town'' when its 25-year bay
bottom leases expire. Private residences, even if they are largely
reserved for weekend use, have no place in a pristine, public
place, the Park Service says.
</P>
<P>
   Stiltsvillians are outraged. They believe they are a part of
history, a revered relic routinely featured in tours, books and
movies as an example of Miami's exotic past. They have sheltered,
at least for a night, every governor through Lawton Chiles. And
where else could a Carl Hiaasen protagonist slay a man with the
bill of a mounted marlin? When MGM needed a setting for Around the
World Under the Sea, Lloyd Bridges and Shirley Eaton came here. And
those Miami Vice boat chases? What would they be without
Stiltsville as a backdrop?
</P>
<P>
   But the community battle for recognition by the National
Register of Historic Places has so far failed. Without that
listing, the Park Service says it has no authority to renew leases.
</P>
<P>
   Park hasn't budged
</P>
<P>
   The park has remained adamant, despite letters of support from,
among others, South Florida's congressional delegation, the
University of Miami, the Greater Miami Chamber of Commerce and the
Dade Heritage Trust, which continue to use the houses. Just last
month, the governing board of the Florida Bar and the chamber of
commerce hosted parties there.
</P>
<P>
   With bureaucratic measures exhausted _ the studies, the reviews,
the committee meetings _ the politicians are left to wrangle. On
Friday, U.S. Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen called a news conference at
one of the houses to unveil new supporters: the state's House of
Representatives and five cities in Metro-Dade County that passed
resolutions of support. Gov. Jeb Bush has also stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Freedom Tower standing guard over Biscayne Bay to the
old coral homes nestled among the mangroves and palms in Coconut
Grove, the history of South Florida has been a struggle,'' Bush
wrote. ``For me, Stiltsville represents a harmony in that
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clubs came first
</P>
<P>
   Long before Miami's landscape was a canyon of high-rises, before
a basketball arena _ no, make that two arenas _ crowded the
skyline, Stiltsville was born.
</P>
<P>
   Its heyday for bawdy socializing spanned nearly three decades,
from the first shack erected by Crawfish Eddie Walker_ widely
considered the founding father_ to the Bikini Club. The clubs came
first, built on barges wedged onto the flats, and drew the wealthy
and the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time (outboard motor-maker) Ralph Evinrude would come
down, when he was between wives, he'd have big parties on his yacht
and the parties would kind of migrate between the yachts and the
Quarterdeck Club,'' said Capt. Bill Curtis, a legendary guide who
has been fishing the bay since 1949. ``I remember after some of
those parties on a weekend, boats would be strewn around the flats,
five to 10. Guys would get drunk and then they'd try to find their
way back through the channels. I used to have people charter me to
go out in their yachts just to have me navigate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bar, an ode to the pirate life, trapdoors in the floor
let patrons fish with a hand line. A talking parakeet strutted
along the bar while a caged treasure chest held parrots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were always trying to teach it dirty words,'' Curtis
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950 a hurricane wiped out Crawfish Eddie's shack and nearly
claimed the Quarterdeck. A new owner took over, but the place
deteriorated. Instead of world-class food, hookers became the draw,
Curtis said. Authorities took a grim view and after a raid on a
Miami Junior Chamber of Commerce party, the club kept a
considerably lower profile. In 1951, fire destroyed it once and for
all. (Rumor had it being burned to avoid salvage fees but that was
never proven.) In the early 1960s, Plucky Pierre opened his Bikini
Club _ any girl in a bikini got a free drink, Curtis said. But
within a year the authorities shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nearly 30 stilt cabins rose from the grassy flats.
The full-time Stiltsvillians brought a new sense of morality, ``a
family-type colony,'' said former Dade Circuit Judge Francis Knuck.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, the colony was nearly destroyed when Hurricane Betsy
blew through with 120 mph winds and an 11-foot storm surge. Sensing
a chance to seize control, Dade County ordered homeowners to follow
new building codes and prohibited reconstruction of houses more
than half destroyed. Then in 1980, Biscayne National Park expanded
to include Stiltsville and the beginning of the end began.
Hurricane Andrew added another nail when it destroyed all but the
last seven houses.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a 'planned assault'
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Park Service says it couldn't intervene if it wanted
to. For three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   When Congress adopted legislation expanding the park, it did so
to protect the Safety Valve, a marine feature at the mouth of the
bay, and failed to address the fate of Stiltsville. Second, park
rules allow and even encourage the leasing of buildings (it's
cheaper to lease property and have the lessee pay for maintenance).
But the buildings must be historic. Lastly, the park has a
management plan last updated in 1983 that includes Stiltsville's
removal. Changing the plan, a monumental task requiring public
hearings and federal review, would only be done for a major
alteration in the park, like the expansion, said Park
Superintendent Dick Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not some planned assault on Stiltsville by Biscayne
National Park,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But residents are skeptical. Frost, they said, promised not to
take a stand on the historic designation. Yet in January the
agency's Atlanta regional office wrote a letter opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea our regional office was going to write something
like that and they didn't let me know,'' Frost said Monday. ``I was
blindsided.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Frost had urged Stiltsville to pursue the historic
designation, but when staff at the National Register took a look at
the 33-page application, they rejected it. The problem? While the
community is older than 50 years, the surviving buildings are not.
</P>
<P>
   Long shot misses
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found that out, I said, oh, it's a long shot because
it's less than 50 years old,'' said Barbara Mattick, supervisor for
the state historic preservation office, which did recognize the
historic status of the community.
</P>
<P>
   There is a provision for preserving grounds if buildings no
longer exist, a kind of loophole Mattick hoped would fit
Stiltsville.
</P>
<P>
   But staff at the National Register didn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship of the seven remaining structures to each
other now appears to be so tenuous that the area no longer has the
cohesion necessary for a historic district,'' wrote Marilyn Harper,
the National Register's historian who rejected the application.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people really want to do is save these buildings and
getting them listed only goes a little way,'' she said recently.
``The decision really rests with the park. . . . It's too bad.
They're wonderful places and it must be magical to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Magical it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an only-in-Miami kind of place,'' said historian and
Miami-Dade Community College Professor Paul George. ``Age is not
the issue. It is a unique subculture of Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we have to have historic designation for the National
Parks to allow Stiltsville to stay when we have such tremendous
community support behind us?'' asked Knight, who still remembers
coming here as a kid when neighbors hoisted flags to alert others
of their arrival. ``When I run into (Florida State football coach)
Bobby Bowden, he doesn't know my name. He yells Stiltsville!''
</P>
<P>
   Boaters regularly use the houses as channel markers, and fishing
guides hide from storms under their eaves. In March, two Miami men
got caught in a sudden squall. One died. The other survived by
swimming to one of the Stiltsville houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've poled in there and kissed the ground under the house,''
said Capt. Bob Branham, a guide who's fished the bay for three
decades. ``When you're out there in a boat and lightning's coming
down and you can't see your hand in front of your face because of
the rain, it's nice to have a roof over your head.''
</P>
<P>
   The fish like that roof, too, Branham said. Rather than remove
the houses _ several years ago the Park Service ripped up old
pilings and ruined much of the neighborhood for fish _ he suggests
rangers take them over and use one for a ranger station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fine with me if the good ol' boys kept them and
took care of them, but I do feel a twinge, that that's not fair.
Why should we go to the trouble to keep them for these rich
bastards?''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis argues fish were more plentiful before the houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The houses aren't completely to blame, but partially. The
extra traffic drives game fish like bonefish, permit and tarpon
right off the flats.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekend boaters jam park
</P>
<P>
   But Stiltsvillians consider their existence peaceful compared to
the boaters and gas-spewing Jet Skis that jam the park by the
hundreds on weekends. Once-grassy flats teeming with life have been
stripped by boats running aground. On Easter Sunday, dozens parked
at Sand's Cut to unload a horde that idly sunned themselves on lawn
chairs sunk in the water. A Miami-Dade County marine patrol boat, a
kind of water traffic cop, parked nearby to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   When Laura Hicks Roberts first came to Stiltsville with her
family, she was 5 and there were no Club Nautico boat rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very quiet by comparison,'' she said. ``There were no
Jet Skis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world was a better place,'' her husband, Jeff, added.
``Now, at least once a month somebody in a rental boat pulls up and
asks for directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, a lawyer who took time off to raise three children, and
other residents have started a grass-roots campaign that has
collected more than 12,000 signatures to save the houses. She still
remembers the weekend her family bought their one-room, wood-frame
cabin furnished with a couple of futons and nothing worth stealing.
(Prices vary, but most cost about $25,000, Jeff Roberts said.)
</P>
<P>
   'An impressive date'
</P>
<P>
   ``One time we noticed a for-sale sign and basically by the end
of the day, my parents owned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the community has a kind of Rotary feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   Knight has ventured out on this perfect evening with a woman he
met through friends, for his second date. ``It's an impressive
date,'' Ruby Pezzi concedes. It seems like all of Miami is on the
water. As he pulls up to the Baldwin, Sessions and Shaw house to
check out a party _ the chamber has hired water taxis and invited
out executives new to town to get a taste of Miami _ the grandson
of Commodore Ralph Munroe, one of the founders of Coconut Grove,
waves from the deck. Across the channel, the governing board of the
Florida Bar is meeting. The president leans against a flag pole
while the president-elect screams, ``Chris!''
</P>
<P>
   With the sun sinking, Knight races to his own house to beat the
light. After he and his friends unpack their pte, wine and chicken
and rice dinners, Knight leans back in a deck chair, looking up at
stars invisible from the neon-lighted shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still waiting,'' he says, ``for the first good argument on
why they need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-05-03-99 2338E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
