<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM06-COX     05-05 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A quirky assemblage of historical items soon will be no more
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In February, the Atlanta Preservation Center moved
into the Rufus M. Rose house, one of the last Victorian residences
on Peachtree Street. Soon afterward, staffers were startled to hear
a woman's scream coming from the second floor. The landlord, Mary
Gene Elliott, was up there. Had she surprised an intruder? Had she
seen a ghost? No, she was just sorting through her late husband's
things and had come across a human skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Creek Indian,'' she says. ``I'd forgotten we had that.''
</P>
<P>
   For half a century, the red brick mansion across from Crawford
Long Hospital in Midtown Atlanta has housed a collection of
historical oddments that seems equally inspired by the Smithsonian
and Ripley's Believe It or Not. Strange and singular things wait
behind the locked door at the top of the stairs: Hitler's cigar
box, Davy Crockett's rifle, Margaret Mitchell's wing chair,
Napoleon's candlesticks, part of the rope used to hang the Japanese
warlord Tojo, the urine jar Franklin D. Roosevelt kept beside his
bed at Warm Springs, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the most unusual museum in Atlanta will get its
final curtain call as Mrs. Elliott and the Preservation Center open
the collection for what they say will be its last public viewing.
Jim Elliott, the antiques dealer who ran the Atlanta Museum, died
last September, and his son and widow are liquidating the estate.
She hopes the Preservation Center will buy the house. As for the
collection, she wants to sell it as soon as possible, perhaps to an
out-of-state dealer.
</P>
<P>
   On a damp, gloomy afternoon last week, Mrs. Elliott consented to
give a preview tour of the museum, which has been closed for almost
six years. Wearing an Olympic windbreaker, her gray hair pulled
back, the 65-year-old Atlanta native led the way up a carved wooden
staircase and past a cracked stained glass window and unlocked the
folding metal door to the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a long hallway lined with Civil War rifles opened onto
four dimly lit rooms filled with thousands of artifacts as tightly
arrayed as tools in an old-fashioned hardware store. The musty
randomness of it all confuses the senses. She pointed out one of
Eli Whitney's cotton gins, a shell from the siege of Atlanta, a
walking cane used by Lafayette, a chair said to have belonged to
Ethiopian Emperor Haile Selassie. The buses rumbling past the bay
windows seemed miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd show you the Conestoga wagon in the attic,'' she said,
``but it's a dark day and there aren't any lights up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who collected these curiosities was her husband's
father, J.H. Elliott Sr., a garrulous little fellow who founded one
of the South's most prominent appraisal houses. Not that he set out
to do that. Elliott was one of Atlanta's pioneer aviators and is
credited with laying out the first runway on what became Hartsfield
International Airport. He got into antiques after a nasty plane
crash, which he always managed to bring up when museum visitors
glimpsed one of his prize possessions _ a Japanese Zero airplane _
grounded in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott started the museum in 1938 at his first shop downtown.
He moved uptown in 1945 when he purchased the Rose house, a grand
old place with a colorful history worthy of his treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Rufus M. Rose was a distiller who advertised ``the best and
purest medicinal whiskies obtainable.'' In 1900, he commissioned a
5,200-square-foot townhouse to be built in the Queen Anne style on
Peachtree, down the street from where the Governor's Mansion was.
When Georgia voted to go dry in 1908, Rose moved his distillery to
Tennessee, but his family remained in the residence until the
1920s. It later became a rooming house, a welfare office and (rumor
has it) a bootlegger's den.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott and his son set up shop there and added to the
collection during trips to auctions throughout the United States
and Europe. They acquired new keepsakes as they appraised the
estates of the famous, from Martha Berry and Margaret Mitchell to
Bobby Jones and FDR (they handled the contents of the Little White
House).
</P>
<P>
   The museum attracted a steady business until attendance began to
dwindle during the '80s. In recent years, the doors usually stayed
closed as Elliott Jr. grew disabled with diabetes. Developers
approached him all the time, wanting to buy the house and demolish
it for new construction. But Jim and Mary Gene Elliott were
dedicated preservationists _ they had met at a preservation meeting
in the early '70s _ and were determined to see the house saved.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, after her husband died, Mrs. Elliott got a call from
Derek Aynsley, the new director of the Atlanta Preservation Center,
a nonprofit organization best known for its walking tours of
historic neighborhoods. Unbeknownst to her, he had talked to her
husband about the possibility of the center moving into the Rose
house. She thought it was a fine idea and offered Aynsley a
three-year lease on the main floor, with the hope that the center
could eventually raise enough money to buy the house from the
estate.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy. Aynsley estimates that it will take at least
$1.5 million to purchase the property, renovate it and fund an
endowment for its upkeep. That would be five times his annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in this house is not central to our core mission of
education and advocacy,'' he says, sitting before a tiled fireplace
in his new office, the former dining room. But he clearly wants to
stay here. ``There's no more appropriate structure in town for us
to get our sticky fingers on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Mrs. Elliott has put out the word on the
antiques grapevine that she wants to sell the collection soon and
intact. (Not including the Indian skull, of course; she says she
has contacted a Creek official about giving it a proper burial.)
Her best prospects, she says, are a dealer in Tennessee and a
museum in Illinois. She does not expect the collection to end up
with an Atlanta institution.
</P>
<P>
   The Margaret Mitchell House and Museum was interested in some of
the furniture and personal effects that had been part of the
author's estate. Mrs. Elliott wouldn't sell them separately.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious local suitor has been the Atlanta History
Center. Director Rick Beard says that a donor who was willing to
underwrite the acquisition is becoming impatient as negotiations
drag on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a loss for some of those things to leave
Atlanta,'' Beard says. ``But if she can get a million dollars for
them from someone in Illinois, more power to her. She won't be
getting that from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Price isn't the only sticking point. The History Center has
asked to see documentation proving the authenticity of some
artifacts _ a routine procedure in any acquisition. ``We're
skeptical,'' Beard says.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the first time anyone has wondered whether some of the
stuff in the Atlanta Museum is for real.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Elliott says that her husband and father-in-law got
affadavits and documentation to back up everything. She has stacks
of paper on a Ping-Pong table in her home to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if she's pressed on the question, she admits to some doubts
herself. ``I'm sure some of it is not what they said it is,'' she
says. ``Then again, when you hear the stories of how they got
things, there's always something logical behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the Tojo rope. This is the way she heard it:
</P>
<P>
   It seems that old man Elliott was friends with a general from
Georgia who witnessed the hanging of the Japanese premier for war
crimes. He was ordered to bring the rope back to Washington and
stopped in Atlanta on the way. Elliott got wind of it and leapt
into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you cut me off a piece of that rope?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The general wouldn't do it. ``I've got to take it to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott persisted. ``Does he know how long the rope is?''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about that rope: When you see the six-inch piece in
the display case, it doesn't look nearly thick enough to have done
the grim job it is supposed to have done. There's a story behind
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it came unraveled,'' Mrs. Elliott explains. ``I've got the
rest of it at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
