<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS06-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to contact Rev. Jesse Jackson to thank him for
getting our captured servicemen released. What is the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: Write him in care of Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, 930 E. 50th St.,
Chicago, IL 60615-2702. Or, visit the Rainbow/Push Coalition site
on the Internet _ www.rainbowpush.org _ and call up the
preaddressed message format where you see ``Click Here to
congratulate Rev. Jackson and the delegation of U.S. religious
leaders for the release of the three American soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to enter the lottery for tickets for next year's
Masters practice rounds. You've printed this information in years
past, but I didn't save it. Can you tell us again?
</P>
<P>
   A: To enter the random drawing, send a letter with your name,
address, daytime telephone number and Social Security number no
later than July 15 to: Masters Tournament, Practice Rounds, Augusta
National Golf Club, P.O. Box 2047, Augusta, GA 30903.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that the nation's worst school
massacre occurred decades ago, and it was instigated by an adult.
What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: That item probably was referring to an explosion May 18,
1927, in Bath, Mich., near Lansing. As recounted last month by the
AP, school board member Andrew Kehoe, angry that the building of
Bath Consolidated School had caused an increase in his taxes, and
fearing foreclosure on his farm, spent months stringing wires and
hiding dynamite in the school's basement. School administrators
thought he was working to save the expense of hiring an
electrician.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the tragedy, Kehoe drove away from the school two
minutes before the explosives detonated. Then he drove back and
detonated dynamite in his truck, killing himself and the school
superintendent. In the end, 38 children and five adults were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We enjoy the comic strip ``Mutts,'' which seems so true to
life for those of us who love animals. Can you give me any
information about the creator? The name is so small on the strip I
can't even read it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Patrick McDonnell created ``Mutts'' in 1994. What makes it
different from comic strips by other artists, he says, is that he
doesn't make his creatures humans in animal form. ``I'm really
trying to keep them like pets,'' McDonnell says. ``I haven't gotten
them up on two legs, walking around doing human things. I try my
hardest to keep them doing things animals would do.'' The strip's
lead characters are Earl the dog, and Mooch the cat.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell, 43, graduated from the School of Visual Arts in New
York. While still in school he sold a few illustrations to the
Village Voice, but his first real job after graduation was
illustrating Russell Baker's column for The New York Times, a job
he held for 10 years. McDonnell also has done TV work, including a
90-minute animated movie, and illustrations and comic strips for
such magazines as Parade, Sports Illustrated and Parents.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell lives in New Jersey with his wife, Karen; his dog,
Earl; and a cat, Meemow. ``Mutts'' is distrbuted to more than 400
newspapers by King Features Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently answered a question in Stars and Stripes about
the ``real'' name of Britain's royal family. Can you provide the
same information on the family name of the Japanese emperor?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no surname, in the style of the West, that follows
from one generation to the next, says the Consulate General of
Japan. The present emperor, and the scion of the oldest imperial
family in the world, is Akihito, whose original name was Tsugu
Akihito. Akihito was the fifth child and eldest son of Emperor
Hirohito and Empress Nagako. Hirohito, whose original name was
Michinomiya Hirohito, was the oldest of the four sons of Crown
Prince Yoshihito, later the Emperor Taisho, and of Crown Princess
Sadako.
</P>
<P>
   According to tradition, Akihito, who has been emperor since
1989, is the 125th direct descendant of Jimmu, Japan's legendary
first emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Other than the color of the shells, is there any nutritional
difference between brown and white eggs?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Egg color often assumes economic importance if there are
local prejudices in favor of certain shell tints, but they have the
same food value. And while some people claim that one or the other
is tastier and/or healthier, there's no firm evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the worst pollen for people who suffer pollen
allergies? I've been told it's from grass, but I'd like an official
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no single worst offender for everyone, said Dr.
Sandra Roberson of the Atlanta Allergy &AMP; Asthma Clinic, because it
depends on each individual person's allergies. If you're not
allergic to grasses, and the grasses are out, you won't have a
problem, she explained. However, if you're allergic to trees, you
might.
</P>
<P>
   The time of year also is a factor. Trees tend to pollinate
first, starting in early March and going through the spring.
Grasses come on their heels, going into the summer months. Then
weeds, with ragweed being the prototype, create pollen in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the ``minor players,'' which also can cause
problems for those who are allergic to them, Robertson added. But
again, they won't affect everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the schedule for releasing quarters commemorating the
50 states and their admission to the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Coins being issued this year commemorate Delaware,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia and Connecticut. The remainder:
</P>
<P>
   2000: Massachusetts, Maryland, South Carolina, New Hampshire,
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   2001: New York, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Vermont, Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   2002: Tennessee, Ohio, Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   2003: Illinois, Alabama, Maine, Missouri, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   2004: Michigan, Florida, Texas, Iowa, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   2005: California, Minnesota, Oregon, Kansas, West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   2006: Nevada, Nebraska, Colorado, North Dakota, South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   2007: Montana, Washington, Idaho, Wyoming, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   2008: Oklahoma, New Mexico, Arizona, Alaska, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, I read that the airlines send unclaimed
luggage and items people have left on planes to a place in Alabama
that sells them to the public. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be referring to The Unclaimed Baggage Center in
Scottsboro, Ala., which calls itself ``the lost luggage capital of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchandise comes from baggage that has gone unclaimed by
airline passengers, lost articles left on planes at airports, and
unclaimed air cargo. The store says it buys items only after
airlines and airports go through an extensive search in an attempt
to rejoin luggage and items with their owners, a process that can
take up to 90 days. Ultimately, those items unable to be matched
then go through the airlines' claims settlement process, which can
take more than three additional months.
</P>
<P>
   After that, items land at Unclaimed Baggage Center, 509 W.
Willow St., Scottsboro. Information: 256-259-1525. The baggage
center says about 60 percent of the items in stock is clothing,
with the remainder likely to include sporting goods, computers,
camera equipment, jewelry and specialty items.
</P>
<P>
   Q: James Rubin, spokesman for the State Department, appears to
be quite young for such a position. What is his background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rubin looks young because he is young. Born in New York in
1960, he received a B.A. in political science from Columbia
University in 1982, and a master in international affairs degree
from Columbia in 1984. Rubin once told the New York Times that he
was transformed when, during his Columbia years, Ronald Reagan was
elected president, and many people thought nuclear destruction
might follow. Rather than joining a protest group, Rubin devoted
himself to learning everything he could about nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1989, Rubin was research director for the nonprofit
Arms Control Association in Washington, serving as consultant to
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on nuclear arms control
issues. His other positions have included senior foreign policy
adviser to Sen. Joseph Biden Jr. (D-Del.); senior adviser and
spokesman for Madeleine Albright when she was U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations; director of foreign policy and spokesman for
the Clinton-Gore '96 campaign; and senior adviser to Albright after
she was named secretary of state. On Aug. 4, 1997, Albright swore
Rubin in as assistant secretary of state for public affairs, his
current position.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a ``Jeopardy'' rerun, the question was,``What was the
second-largest country after Russia?'' To my surprise, it was
Canada. With the breakup of the former Soviet Union, is Russia
still No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Before its breakup in 1991, the Union of Soviet
Socialist Republics, also called the Soviet Union, was the largest
country in the world. The constituent republic of the U.S.S.R. that
is now Russia, or the Russian Federation, is still the world's
largest country, and is almost twice as big as Canada. The
statistics: Russia, 6.6 million square miles; Canada, 3.85 million
square miles. The former U.S.S.R., for comparison: 8.65 million
square miles.
</P>
<P>
   End Take 1.
</P>
