<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS06-TAKE     05-05 1667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS06-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The House recently voted 424-1 to award Rosa Parks the
Congressional Gold Medal. Who was the one person who voted against
the honor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rep. Ron Paul (R-Texas) was the sole dissenter. But his vote
wasn't a reflection on Parks or her role in the civil rights
movement by refusing to give up her seat on a segregated bus in
Alabama in 1955, said Paul spokesman Michael Sullivan. For years
Paul has voted against what he calls such ``immoral'' uses of
taxpayer money as spending $30,000 to provide gold medals to
people. ``We feel it's inappropriate for Congress to be so generous
with taxpayer's money at a time when the future of Social Security
is uneasy at best, the military can't seem to find the money to pay
its retirees, and we can't seem to afford a tax-cut for
middle-class Americans,'' Sullivan told Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   Paul would support the idea of gold medals from Congress to
worthy recipients like Parks, Sullivan added, if each member of
Congress were willing to contribute $100 of his or her own money to
fund it. But that idea has gone nowhere each time Paul has proposed
it over the years, Sullivan said, so the congressman continues his
opposition to such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was advised to start collecting and saving the new $20
bills, as if I could afford to, because they all have the wrong
date. The bills came out in 1999, but they're printed with 1996.
Was this a mistake that might make them valuable to collectors?
</P>
<P>
   A: The date isn't wrong. The newly designed $20 bills, while
they were issued starting Sept. 24, 1998, are part of the Treasury
Department's Series 1996 notes, which also include newly designed
$50 and $100 bills. Save them if you wish, but they aren't likely
ever to become highly prized collector's items.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard a number of stories about where Vice President Al
Gore received his education. Did he attend school in Tennessee or
elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's his background. Gore, who was born March 31, 1948,
grew up in Washington, where he attended the exclusive St. Albans
Episcopal School for Boys. After that he enrolled at Harvard
University, where he received a B.A. in government in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Army as a reporter with the 20th
Engineering Battalion, which was stationed outside Saigon, Gore
pursued a number of activities, including writing for the Nashville
Tennessean. While working the night shift at the newspaper in
1971-72, he studied philosophy and phenomenology at Vanderbilt
University's Graduate School of Religion. Although he didn't obtain
a degree there, Gore explained that he went to divinity school ``to
study the spiritual issues that were most important to me at the
time.'' In 1974 he enrolled in Vanderbilt's Law School, where he
remained for two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he left law school to become a candidate for the House
seat being vacated by Democratic Rep. Joe Evins, who had decided
not to seek re-election. Gore won the Democratic primary and the
general election. You know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the area in square miles of the province of Kosovo?
What was the population before the latest strife and evacuation of
ethnic Albanians living there started recently?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kosovo's area is 4,203 square miles, making it slightly
smaller than Connecticut. Its population (1991) was just under 2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I enjoy Lisa Simeone, who now hosts ``Performance Today'' on
National Public Radio, but I wonder: Why is Martin Goldsmith no
longer on the show?
</P>
<P>
   A: Goldsmith, who joined ``Performance Today'' as music director
in 1987 and became its host two years later, began a leave of
absence March 22. NPR says he's writing a book about his parents'
``extraordinary lives in, and escape from, Nazi Germany.'' Simeone,
a regular guest host, will fill in until Goldsmith returns in July.
</P>
<P>
   The book, titled ``The Inextinguishable Symphony,'' will be
published next year by John Wiley and Sons. It will chronicle the
involvement of Goldsmith's parents, both classical musicians, in
the nearly forgotten Juedischer Kulturbund. The Kulturbund's
orchestras, opera companies, theater troupes and lecture series
were the only cultural outlets available to Jews under the Nazi
regime, NPR's Anya Grundmann explained, providing both important
channels for artistic expression for Jews and political cover for
the Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith's parents met in the Kulturbund's orchestra in
Frankfurt in 1936, and later performed with the orchestra in
Berlin. They escaped together to the United States in 1941, just
months before the Nazis cut off Jewish emigration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Congress had approved a $1.74
trillion budget. How does the Gramm-Rudman Act fit into that, if
all all?
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't. The Gramm-Rudman-Hollings Balanced Budget and
Emergency Deficit Reduction Act of 1985 went to a quiet death in
1993. While it was simple in intent and content _ setting specific
budgetary targets that Congress would have to meet over the six
fiscal years after it was enacted _ it apparently worked too well
for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to trim federal spending _ or to increase taxes _ enough
to meet its mandate would have resulted in across-the-board cuts in
domestic and defense outlays. For example, an across-the-board cut
reduced the 1986 budget by $11.7 billion. In fiscal 1987, the
threat of Gramm-Rudman's meat-ax approach to spending trimmed
another $83 billion. So a projected deficit of $296 billion in
fiscal 1990 was $124 billion instead, thanks to Gramm-Rudman.
</P>
<P>
   Congress voted to extend Gramm-Rudman's budget-balancing target
to 1993. Then, under President Bush's ill-fated budget deal with
Congress in 1990 that promised $500 billion in deficit reduction,
Gramm-Rudman was suspended. While Congress promised to bring it
back, it simply died with President Clinton's new budget plan. The
bottom line was that when the law began to force meaningful cuts in
spending, Congress balked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had understood that France at one time had ceased its
membership in NATO, so I'm surprised to see it's so active in
NATO's Serbia decision-making now. Can you trace France's history
in the organization?
</P>
<P>
   A: France was one of 12 nations whose foreign ministers signed a
treaty April 4, 1949, in Washington creating the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization for collective defense. Then, on March 10,
1966, French President Charles DeGaulle announced France's
intention to withdraw from the NATO integrated military structure.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't the same as ceasing membership in NATO, said
Blanca DePriest of the U.S. Information Agency. France retained its
membership, but wanted out of the military aspect of NATO. France
also asked that NATO move its headquarters from Paris to Brussels,
Belgium, because it didn't want the NATO military operations to be
on French soil.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, while France is involved in the NATO operations in
Yugoslavia, it isn't ``fully integrated'' into NATO, DePriest
added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The federal government must collect billions of dollars in
taxes from lottery winners nationwide. Where does this money go?
</P>
<P>
   A: The IRS doesn't differentiate between taxes paid on lottery
winnings and other income taxes paid. All such monies go from IRS
service centers into the Treasury Department's general fund by way
of the Federal Reserve Bank. The 1040 forms don't have a separate
category for listing lottery winnings; they're simply lumped into
the category ``other income.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The U.S. Constitution requires a census to be taken every 10
years. Who is to be included? It is just U.S. citizens? Citizens
plus resident aliens? Or everybody who's here, legally or
otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Census Bureau says it includes all people who are
residents of the United States except those living on the grounds
of an embassy, ministry, legation, chancellery or consulate,
because they're considered to be living on foreign soil and
therefore not residents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau also enumerates U.S. citizens overseas who are
working for the U.S. government, and their dependents living with
them. Private U.S. citizens living overseas who are not affiliated
with the U.S. government are not included in the census count.
Others not counted are citizens of foreign countries temporarily
living or traveling in the United States, because they have not
established a residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't differentiate between citizens and noncitizens,''
said Census Bureau spokeswoman Bea Piddock. ``We never ask if they
are legal or illegal, so that is immaterial.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you give me some information about May Day? How did it
come to be a day of celebration? Also, is there any connection
between May Day and the mayday distress call?
</P>
<P>
   A: May Day (May 1) is celebrated as a spring festival in many
countries and is traced to festivals of ancient Egypt and India
marking the revival of life each year after winter. The English and
other peoples whom the Romans conquered developed their May Day
festivals from the Roman observance Floralia, in which the Romans
gathered flowers to honor Flora, the goddess of springtime.
Eventually Floralia was combined with a Celtic celebration,
Beltane, which was held on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   In medieval times May Day became a favorite holiday in many
English villages, and other European countries also observed it,
with some attaching religious importance.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, Socialist and Communist countries began
honoring working people on the first day of May, with celebrations
of military might added later by the former Soviet Union and other
Eastern bloc countries.
</P>
<P>
   There's no connection with mayday, the international radio
communications distress signal, which is the anglicized spelling of
the French phrase(venez) m'aider, meaning ``(come) help me.''
</P>
<P>
   End.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
