<HEADER>
A4904 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHASTEWART-REVIEW0     05-05 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHASTEWART-REVIEW06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Painstaking hors d'oeuvres hardly qualify as a quick fix
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's almost too easy to take potshots at Martha
Stewart. The woman invites it.
</P>
<P>
   Just turn to the new Martha Stewart's Hors d'oeuvres Handbook
(Potter, $35).
</P>
<P>
   First, you have to get beyond the jacket, which has a rather
pitiful Stewart proffering a single hors d'oeuvre on a pink napkin.
She has the good grace to look chagrined by the lonely little
appetizer _ a far cry from the woman who once put real gold leaf on
a gingerbread house.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the book makes up for that inside with more than 220 pages
of detailed color pictures to tempt you to flip to a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Are you really ready to make grape cups, hollowing out each
little grape and then filling it with hand-molded rounds of goat
cheese? How about making potato wafers in a variety of shapes,
using a plastic template you have cut out with your trusty Exacto
knife? Tedium comes to a standstill in little appetizers with _
count them _ 10 layers of tiny thyme leaves, slices of fingerling
potatoes and goat cheese, assembled in a mini-muffin pan.
</P>
<P>
   If you had a team as big as Stewart has you might be able to
make the twice-fried plantain chips that are assembled into
miniature jerk chicken sandwiches, prettily tied with a blanched
chive.
</P>
<P>
   While the book has Stewart's name on it, it was produced by a
team. You didn't think she was still at home hollowing out cherry
tomatoes to serve a sip of soup, did you? Or spending her days
making miniature tortillas and green tea crepes by hand. Or, for
that matter, making her own potting soil? But call this team a
Stewart clone, for they have certainly adopted her spirit. She has
left her mark as well as her name.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, I decided to inspect the book with an open mind,
with a view to what I think is the biggest challenge: finding a
lineup of appetizers that a host without hired help can make ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The book is helpful in that respect. Introductions to recipes
indicate which can be made ahead. That does not necessarily make
them simple. Witness a jewel-like terrine studded with asparagus
and shiitake mushrooms, and wrapped in blanched leek.
</P>
<P>
   And recipes may not work. My first choice was a non-traditional
spicy bean dip layered with goat cheese, cilantro and green onion.
It required cooking black beans in order to have the necessary
liquid, but the recipe produced a mixture closer to soup than
scoopable dip.
</P>
<P>
   But any cook with a copycat flair can benefit from Martha's
entertaining techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Try using hollowed-out rounds and pullman loaves of bread as
serving pieces _ no, not for dip. Use them as containers to keep
sandwiches fresh during a party. Since height adds style, stack
crackers into veritable pillars for a more striking appearance.
Need more verticals? Cut the crudites into long strips and arrange
them in tall clear glasses like flowers. It's a much prettier
visual impact.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: annheller(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
