r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DREW06-COX     05-05 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DREW06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drew promise, personality win over Cards
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shawon Dunston calls J.D. Drew a superstar in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Mike Easler believes he's Wade Boggs with power.
</P>
<P>
   And St. Louis Cardinals manager Tony La Russa compares Drew, a
rookie from Hahira, to John Elway. And he's not talking about arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   As he began his football career, Elway was criticized for not
wanting to be drafted by the Baltimore Colts. Two years ago, Drew
was criticized for refusing to sign with Philadelphia after the
Phillies drafted him. He spent a season in the Northern League at
St. Paul, Minn., before re-entering the draft the next year and
signing with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, who strained his right quadriceps Monday while running to
third and sat out Tuesday's game, has been booed in some parks
after getting off on the wrong foot in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the baseball world thought, `Here's an
arrogant guy who was doing something real egotistical and
personal,''' said La Russa, who was won over by Drew when they met.
``There's a lot of comparisons between Elway and J.D. Drew: They're
really good men, and there's something that they stood for. And
it's not arrogance; it's not selfishness. It's a principle, but I
haven't asked what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa said he'll ask Drew to tell his Philadelphia story
``when we've been together longer, when he trusts me . . . to tell
me honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Drew, 23, isn't rehashing the reason he delayed his
major-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to get into it; it's all in the past,''
said Drew, whose agent, Scott Boras, also has been blamed for the
rift with the Phillies. ``I don't have any hard feelings against
Philadelphia. Things just didn't work out. St. Louis is a great
town, a great atmosphere and probably a better fit for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first game with the Cardinals, in September, Drew didn't
have the burden of high expectations. That was the night teammate
Mark McGwire hit home run No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   The next game, Drew hit a 438-foot home run against Cincinnati
in his fourth big-league at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in his first spring training, Drew started well, but
struggled at the end. The struggles carried into the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were coming up and saying, `Relax. You only got 40
at-bats. It's early in the season. You've got a long career,'''
Drew said.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, who was college player of the year at Florida State, has a
brother, Tim, in the Cleveland organization and another brother,
Stephen, playing in high school. ``They said, `Just go out there
and do what you've always done.' It helps to rebuild your belief in
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the hits weren't coming, Dunston said, ``He didn't
throw bats or curse. He doesn't curse, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew missed three games in late April with a sprained thumb
suffered in a collision at first base, then caught fire as a
leadoff batter. Against Montreal, he hit .364 with three walks, a
stolen base and seven runs. He tied a Cardinals record when he
scored five runs Saturday in a 3-for-4 effort against the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If J.D.'s doing his thing right, wherever you hit him, it's
going to work out,'' La Russa said. ``He's got a good attitude
about not having all the answers and wanting to learn. The best
thing that can happen this year is just be on a good ballclub and
be surrounded by guys he can learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy in a clubhouse with such veterans as McGwire, Eric
Davis and Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rookie, but he doesn't act like one,'' Dunston said.
``He's confident but not cocky. Everybody likes him. He's only 23,
but he's from the old school.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew is ``going to be one of the best players ever to play this
game,'' Dunston said. ``When they give him $100 million, you
wouldn't mind, because he's a class act.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Dunston teases him about his contract, a
three-year deal worth a guaranteed $7 million and as much as $11.5
million with bonuses. It's more likely he'll make $8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `You didn't sign for enough,''' Dunston said. ``He just
looks at me. He doesn't say anything. It's a compliment, because
he's so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
