<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NUHN-MINORLEAGUES     05-05 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NUHN-MINORLEAGUES06-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Gary Nuhn DAYTON DAILY NEWS
</P>
<P>
   They were in Scranton, Pa., watching their beloved Toledo Mud
Hens.
</P>
<P>
   They had already been through Rochester and Syracuse on this
trip, wearing their Mud Hen jerseys and hats. But this time the
brothers Ramlow _ Jim and Paul _ thought they were being hassled by
an usher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we came back to our seats, the guy asked to see our
tickets,'' Jim Ramlow said. ``The third time, I said, 'We're the
only guys here wearing Mud Hens shirts. Don't you remember us?' And
he said, 'I'm just doing my job.' But he wasn't asking anybody else
to see their tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though they had planned to stay in Scranton and see the Mud
Hens again the next day, the brothers decided they weren't going to
spend any more money there.
</P>
<P>
   They looked at their trusty minor league schedule and saw that
the nearest Detroit farm team was playing in Welland, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in the car at 7:20 the next morning and got to the
hotel in Welland at 1:30,'' Jim said. ``We thought it was a night
game, but it turned out it was Canada Day, so the game started at
1:30. Luckily, the ball park was right next to the hotel, so we ran
over and saw the game.''
</P>
<P>
   End of story? Not for these guys.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, they saw in a newspaper there was another game
that night in St. Catherine's, 20 kilometers away _ whatever that
is. So they drove over and watched that game, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Paul are minor league devotees. They grew up in Toledo,
thus their allegiance to the Mud Hens. Jim, who lives in
Middletown, is an operations coordinator for Rogers Jewelers. Paul,
who lives in Columbus, works in publicity for the U.S. Trotting
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Jim says he's ``over 40.'' Paul is 39.
</P>
<P>
   That was Jim walking around Courthouse Square in his Mud Hens'
uniform on Monday when the new Dayton minor league team unveiled
its name (Dragons), uniforms and logo, ``just to show my support
for minor league baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year for the past 11 years, the brothers have made one
week-long trip and another extended weekend trip to minor league
games, mostly but not always following farm clubs of the Tigers.
Their count is now 11 leagues and 63 parks. When Dayton starts next
spring, it's going to be a nice, easy 64th.
</P>
<P>
   Best player Jim has seen? Kirby Puckett when the Mud Hens were a
Minnesota farm team.
</P>
<P>
   Jim's closet is a testament to his devotion. He has six full Mud
Hen uniforms; three Jacksonville uniforms; and one Fayetteville
General uniform (Bull Durham, you understand).
</P>
<P>
   He also has 65 minor league caps, 25 of which hang on his
bedroom wall along with 16 team photos of various Tiger farm teams.
On his wall at work are 10 team photos of the Mud Hens.
</P>
<P>
   So I guess you love the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say that,'' Jim Ramlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Are you married?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not anymore,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not anymore. That's why we have the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers just returned from a week in Florida. They flew to
Tampa, saw games in Lakeland, Tampa, Lakeland again, Jacksonville,
Lakeland again and finally slipped in two major league games in St.
Petersburg because the Tigers were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 6:25 flight back home,'' Jim said. ``Game ended at
4:50, we were in line at the airport with our luggage at 5:20.''
</P>
<P>
   And why do they do this?
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing in the world is watching a winning baseball
team,'' Jim said. ``The second best thing is watching any baseball
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-05-04-99 1836E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
