<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MIAMI-WOODEN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wooden has knee surgery
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Shawn Wooden not only participated in the
Dolphins' mini-camp last week, the team's former starting strong
safety talked about how his left knee had recovered from the injury
that forced him to miss most of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost 100 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctors felt that Wooden was going to need some additional
surgery to remove scar tissue. So they decided to go ahead and do
it Monday, hoping that he will be fully recovered when training
camp opens in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' said Drew Rosenhaus, Wooden's agent. ``The
doctors say that this is par for the course in a rehab of this
magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden, 25, tore the anterior cruciate and medial collateral
ligaments in his left knee on the opening kickoff of the second
game of the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden's return will be part of one of the biggest off-season
questions for the Dolphins' defense: Who will start at strong
safety in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins coaches expect him to battle Calvin Jackson, who
started the final 15 regular-season games last year, and Marcus
Wimberly for the job.
</P>
<P>
   After team physician John Uribe performed the procedure at
HealthSouth Doctor's Hospital in Coral Gables, Wooden left the
hospital with Rosenhaus. No wheelchair necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was walking on it,'' Rosenhaus said. ``He's doing great. I
think the target is for him to be ready for the mini-camp in July
(13-15). But with Shawn, you never know. He might be ready
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins had high hopes for Wooden last season. He was on
the cover of the media guide as the winner of the team's community
service award. And two years after the Dolphins made him a
sixth-round draft pick out of Notre Dame, he was starting to look
like a steal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he won the strong safety job, starting 15
regular-season games and finishing second on the team with 121
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 season began well. In the opener at Indianapolis,
Wooden made 12 tackles. But on the opening kickoff of the following
week's game against Buffalo, he suffered the injury. He had surgery
the following day, then spent the rest of the year on the injured
reserve list.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson wasn't available for comment
Monday, but just last week he gushed about the makeup of the
secondary during one of the team's four mini-camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade our secondary for any secondary in the
league,'' he said. ``And I don't know if anybody's close. Now we've
got the one safety spot that's still up in the air. But ... we've
got the candidates that we should be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Guard Mike Sheldon signed a one-year deal Monday.
Sheldon, 25, appeared in nine games last season, starting two.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woods writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
