<P>
   STEWART-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ I've never understood about
autographs. I've never been able to figure out why a grown person
would spend an hour standing outside an arena dressing room in
hopes that some sneering, snorting guitar player would scrawl his
name on their scrap of paper? What compels someone to pay for the
privilege of standing line at an autograph session to get the
illegible signature of a 24-year-old whose major contributions to
the advancement of civilization are the ability to throw a baseball
and spit tobacco juice? (Stewart, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When you call home and there are
loud sobs on the other end of the line, it's never a good sign.
These were not the wails of a spouse at-the-end-of-his-rope, but
chest-heaving, end-of-the-world-sobs. The way the world can only
end when you're 7. And the world had indeed ended, for one very
small member of our household _ Stripe, a salamander my son adopted
as a pet. Worse yet, Stripe had not died a natural death. Alec had
covered Stripe's bucket with a dingy-white shawl that protected him
from the light, but not, unfortunately, from 3-year-olds. While
``playing'' with Stripe, Veronica yanked the tail off her brother's
pet. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I'm not surprised that
the Ten Commandments died in the Florida Legislature last week.
Senate Bill 52, which would have permitted the posting of The Ten
Commandments in public schools, courtrooms and government
buildings, didn't have a chance. That's because it wasn't handled
right. Good legislation must be flexible to manipulation by the
competing lobbies. There's got to be a little something in it for
everybody. But there was nothing in the Ten Commandments the way it
was presented. Just a lot of don't do this, don't do that. Florida
legislators needed more of a reason to embrace the Ten
Commandments. They needed some Ten Commandments pork. (Cerabino,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ You've got to feel sorry for a
candidate who finishes behind a homeless person with a beeper. How
do you explain that on your resume? My heart goes out to Ray
Vrudhula, a retired IBM engineer who faces the ignominy of coming
in dead last among all 17 candidates in Saturday's three Austin
City Council races. If this had been a NASCAR race, Vrudhula would
have been lapped and run over. Vrudhula even finished behind
Jennifer Gale, a pager-packing transient of questionable gender who
got 691 votes (2.1 percent of the vote) in the City Council Place 4
race for Beverly Griffith's seat. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ A fellow I know had brought
me a mess of poke salad. Maybe you're familiar with poke salad.
Soon you will be. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
