<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DOYLE06-COX     05-05 1806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DOYLE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doyle finds his place
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGRANGE, Ga. _ He sits behind the counter on a stool, a ``Gone
Golfing'' sign behind his left shoulder and a stack of mail on top
of the display case. A ringing telephone interrupts his search for
the electric bill, a brochure for a new range-ball picker and a
$315,000 check from the PGA of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivin' range,'' Allen Doyle answers. ``Uh-huh. . . . Yes, it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The caller wants to know if Doyle's Golf Center, down
Whitesville Road from LaGrange Mobile Homes and next to Becky's Bar
&AMP; Grill, is still open for business now that the lease-holder owns
a Rolex watch, a new $28,000 pickup truck and three-quarters of a
million dollars in 1999 Senior PGA Tour winnings.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite open for business, thank you. Nothing much has
changed at Doyle's Golf, a facility that makes the range in ``Tin
Cup'' look like a David Leadbetter Academy. The red frame building,
which fronts 11 acres of uneven turf, would not be suitable for
storing weedwhackers on the Senior Tour. But in LaGrange, where
Allen Doyle recharges after his recent euphoric weeks on the Senior
Tour, it's perfectly charming.
</P>
<P>
   What else would you expect from an ex-hockey player from Norwich
University who manufactured an abbreviated, slapshot golf swing in
a garage with an 8-foot ceiling? What better place to find a move
that could have been created from the genetic coupling of Bobby Orr
and Doug Sanders?
</P>
<P>
   ``Small bucket, please, Mr. Doyle,'' a customer says. Doyle, 50,
rings up three bucks on the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, an older fellow enters the shop. ``I just
want to shake your hand, 'cause you're the champ.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, when Doyle managed the American Legion course down
the road and was talked into paying $500 for the rights to the
lease, the range has been his comfortable pair of jeans. Years ago,
his daughters ran the place while Doyle was playing in Sunnehanna
Amateurs and Dogwood Invitationals. Now, Michelle and Erin are at
college, and Dad, when he isn't slashing at a ball on national
television, is behind the counter, overlooking the Titleist x-outs
and the animal head covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was at my house now, what would I be doing?'' Doyle asks.
``I'd be just sittin' there. . . . A place like this, you stay
grounded; you aren't worried. . . . The guys are around, which is
great, and, you know, you don't meet many (jerks) at a place like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle has just returned with his wife, Kate, from Charlotte,
N.C., where Bruce Fleisher beat him on the back nine for his third
victory. But at Doyle's, the congratulations are still coming for
what transpired so dramatically the week before. With a final-round
64, Doyle's second victory of the 1999 season became a senior
major, the PGA Seniors Championship at Palm Beach Gardens, Fla.
Fellow competitor Dana Quigley called it ``the best round Allen
Doyle might ever play in his lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's buddies are hanging around as usual on this Monday
morning. They call him ``A.D.'' Wearing penny loafers, Doyle is
hitting wedges for a photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to aggravate him,'' Tad Moore said jokingly. He
used to own a golf club company in LaGrange.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's friends want him to play nine holes, and despite the
stack of mail and a putting green that needs mowing, he is giving
it serious thought. Kate, meanwhile, is gathering Allen's dirty
laundry. Leading money-winner or not, there is no rest for the
weary. They will leave the next day for the stop in Birmingham.
Then they'll drive to Alpharetta, Ga. for the Nationwide
Championship. No ticker-tape parade is on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got on the front page,'' Doyle said. ``That's about all
we're going to get out of LaGrange.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Fagundes runs the Thrifty Car Rental and is part of the
regular group that plays with Doyle at Highland Country Club.
``He's as mentally tough as anybody out there,'' Fagundes said.
``He hasn't changed a lick, and it's funny _ he's made everybody
around him better. I was a 12 (handicap); now I'm a 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and his buddies usually practice on a better area of grass
behind the shop. There's a tractor parked there that Doyle uses to
work on his trajectory. When he's hitting wedges, the tractor is up
close and balls are lofted over it. The less loft on the club, the
more Doyle backs up the tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any dents in that tractor,'' Fagundes said.
</P>
<P>
   Framed articles of his world amateur standing throughout the
years adorn the walls at the golf shop. While Doyle is a newcomer
to some golf fans, he's no newcomer to golf's headlines. He won
three times after turning pro in 1995, including the Nike Tour
Championship at Roswell, Ga.'s Settindown Creek Golf Club, and the
next year, at age 47, he became the oldest rookie in PGA Tour
history. Doyle won six Georgia Amateur titles, played on two Walker
Cup teams, three World Amateur teams, one with Tiger Woods, and was
ranked the top amateur in the United States in 1994. He was the
medalist in the 1991 U.S. Amateur and lost in the 1992 semifinals
to Justin Leonard. Since Bobby Jones, there has been no greater
amateur player in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   His accomplishments make laughable his exclusion from the
Georgia Golf Hall of Fame. Without saying so officially, the
organization has barred Doyle because of unacceptable behavior that
occurred a decade ago during state amateur events. His temper could
get out of hand back then, but he has mellowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play these pro-ams; they love me,'' Doyle says. ``I played
the other day with Arthur Blank, the CEO of Home Depot. Now if this
guy had heard I was a (jerk), do you think he'd have arranged to
get me in his foursome?''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Doyle does not care about those things. This is the
nectar period of his life, and nothing bitter is allowed. A plan
that began as something to supply college education money for his
daughters has turned into a lottery jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said when I won the PGA Seniors it would take me 10 years to
make that here at the range,'' Doyle said. ``Everybody who tries
this has the opportunity to go around the carousel and grab the
brass ring. And if you pull the right one, it's a million dollars.
That's what happened to me. . . . It's a little mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy with a strange swing. The 6-foot-3, 210-pound
Doyle takes back the club barely past waist-high, but his power
comes from thick wrists and thumping forearms. His putting stroke
is almost a push shot. Sometimes the blade only comes back an inch
or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't believe how strong his hands and forearms and
wrists are,'' his caddie, Todd Byers, said. ``Plus, all those years
in skating built his legs up.''
</P>
<P>
   The swing still causes its share of double-takes. Woods, his
former World Amateur colleague, once said, ``Doyle has no
backswing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's probably not as odd as it looks,'' Doyle said.
``Probably a little slower than it looks, which would give you the
idea it's a little more fluid. . . . But it's short and choppy, you
know, like a slap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time Larry Nelson saw Doyle swing, he said, ``I had
heard about it beforehand. . . . But there are all kinds of swings
out there. That's why on the scorecard, they just ask you, `How
much?' Not, `How?'''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Inman, another Georgian on the Senior Tour, first saw
Doyle's swing during a round at The Farm in Rocky Face. Doyle had
not played in six months because of back surgery and topped his
first three tee shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it was his real swing,'' Inman said. ``On the
15th hole, he finally got one up in the air; he hits a bad chip,
throws his club and breaks it. Once I played with him again, you
see how good a player he was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You still get the first-time stuff when people see you,''
Doyle said. ``They say, `What the hell is this?' But out here,
you're not as odd as you'd be on the PGA Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said it was important for him to prove that a manufactured
swing from a lifetime amateur could compete with golf's stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I didn't,'' he said. ``That didn't play
any part in coming out, but it was still nice. . . . I mean, I've
been dismissed at every level, and don't think for a minute that
when I played last year and won tour school that any of these guys
were ready to admit that this guy can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle has established a few records that might never be broken.
Last year, he had top-10 finishes on all three tours _ PGA, Senior
and Nike. He has been at least a co-medalist at both PGA Tour and
Senior PGA Tour qualifying schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he has found his comfort zone with the Seniors. He made more
than $200,000 in two years on the PGA Tour, but he constantly faced
the odds of being short off the tee, and that put too much pressure
on his short game.
</P>
<P>
   The gap is much smaller on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, instead of 90 percent of the field outdriving me, it's
only 20 percent,'' Doyle said. ``And that's huge. Now, I'm on
pretty much an even playing field with those guys, and I might even
be a shade longer than a few of them with the irons. The guys out
here who bomb it, they don't hit it very straight. If you're
hitting three or more fairways than they are per day, they're
probably gaining nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He drives the ball so well and putts so well, it never puts
him under any pressure,'' Senior Tour player John Bland of South
Africa said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Tour's more relaxed, no-cut format has brought out
the finest in many players who were not huge stars on the PGA Tour.
Including Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried too hard on the other tour,'' Doyle said. ``I was
telling myself I didn't have much time to make things happen. . . .
Now I'm saying, `OK, you had a good nine. Let's go have another
good nine. Hit the golf shots. Don't worry about what everybody
else is shooting.'''
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, a typically frugal New Englander at a driving
range in LaGrange no longer worries about affording a used car for
one of his daughters or keeping an old car running until the doors
fall off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is the money,'' he said. ``I got to improve
mine and my family's lot in life. I mean, you're doing something
that you love doing, something you always did that you never made a
dime for.''
</P>
<P>
   His only regret is missing a perfect promotional gimmick on the
day he won the PGA Seniors _ pulling out a hockey helmet for the
walk up the 18th fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been like, `He's putting the helmet on,''' Doyle
said, laughing. ``When will be put the helmet on? Heck, it could
have been just like Red Auerbach's cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
