</P>
<P>
   TURN-OFF-TV (San Francisco) _ Diet and exercise programs usually
fail to prevent obesity in kids, but a simpler approach may yield
better results: turning off the TV, even if for an hour or less a
day. In a new study, Stanford University researchers studied nearly
100 elementary schoolers who cut their TV viewing by one-quarter to
one-third and, after a year, gained about two pounds less on
average than a matched set of their peers who kept up their normal
TV habits. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   PERSPIRATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Imagine needing to change your
shirt three or four times a day because of heavy perspiration. Or
being unable to take a test because your hands are too wet to grip
a pen. About 1 percent of people in the United States suffer
hyperhydrosis, a condition that usually strikes at puberty and
causes profuse sweating. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNTAINS (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's nothing quite as soothing as
the sound of water trickling from a fountain. The sound has soothed
people since ancient Greece, where public fountains were the norm.
Today, the residential fountain is used primarily as decoration,
incorporated as one part of the overall landscape or garden design.
By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
