<SLUG> BC-KLO-VOLUNTEERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGNERS SIGNING UP AS FIGHTERS FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ Struggling to communicate with his Albanian
comrades, Alexander Nunez Ortado, a 19-year-old Spaniard, looks a
bit bewildered as he turns over his passport and application to
join the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But what he lacks in language skills, Ortado makes up for in
wide-eyed courage and fiery determination to beat back the Serbs
and ``to make Kosovo free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortado is too young to remember the Spanish Civil War, but the
romantic history of the great battle has brought Ortado from the
northern Spanish town of Valladolid to this garbage-strewn Albanian
port.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, foreigners, came to Spain to fight against the
forces of fascist Francisco Franco. Albanians were among them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ortado wants to return the favor, helping the struggling
KLA in its war against the bigger and better-armed Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the refugees, the babies, on television and I started to
cry,'' Ortado said in Spanish. ``I said to myself, Alex, you have
to help them. Now, we are going to fight and we are going to free
all of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign volunteers are increasingly signing up with the KLA,
heading over on the ferry from Bari, Italy, to the makeshift
recruitment center at a beachfront restaurant here, KLA officials
said, though they have no accurate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds'' of foreigners, most with no Albanian bloodlines,
have offered to fight with the rogue army, said Bilall Sherifi, an
adviser to the KLA in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of them are reservists or former officers in their
home countries. The volunteers have come from the United States,
Portugal, Spain, England, Germany and France, he said. One teenage
girl from Chicago, whom he would not name, tried to sign up, but
she was refused because of her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all the intellectual and military world with us,''
Sherifi said. ``They have seen who are the criminals and who are
the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ortado and KLA officials insisted that the foreign soldiers
were not paid.
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment, KLA commanders insist, is not the problem. Every
day, 150 to 170 volunteers, most of them ethnic Albanians, make the
trek to Durres to join the fight, said Halim Krasniqi, a KLA
commander vetting the new troops here.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians organize bus trips for new recruits coming from
Europe; Ortado hooked up with a recent pack of volunteers in Bari,
and said he found them ``by instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Most new soldiers are ethnic Albanians who went to Switzerland
or Germany to earn money, and are now exchanging a Western paycheck
for an aged Kalashnikov, Krasniqi said.
</P>
<P>
   They include middle-aged men, skinny teenage boys, even women,
all of whom looked untrained but ready to fight as they lined up to
take the bus to training camps in the north of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Aida, a 27-year-old woman who was a history professor at the
University of Pristina, said she fled to Switzerland last year
because of troubles with the Serb police. Now, she wants to go to
the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not? It's an obligation to my country,'' she said. ``I
don't like war, but it's something I have to do. My people have
been massacred. Do you think I have to be a man to have courage?''
</P>
<P>
   At the Drenica bar, so named for the mountainous region in
Kosovo where the KLA was born, recruits fresh off the boat were
being herded the other day into a sign-up room, protected by armed
KLA soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   While a traditional meal of Albanian bean soup and bread was
served, small children stood on the tables, singing impassioned
songs about Kosovo and the KLA. ``Oh, my mother, please don't cry
for me, because I die for my homeland,'' sang a 6-year-old boy,
stretching his slender arms to the sky with heavy emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The recruits' passports were taken and dumped in a bag, ensuring
the soldiers would not be able to desert easily.
</P>
<P>
   Most recruits will have just three weeks of training, although
the newer ones will be used for support duty and not sent to the
front lines, Sherifi said.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA's greatest problem is a lack of weapons, particularly
big guns and tanks, Krasniqi and others said. Kransniqi estimated
the current size of the KLA at 35,000 soldiers. But without guns,
the recruits are limited to noncombat duty.
</P>
<P>
   None of the volunteers who arrived the other day had guns;
Ortado was the best-outfitted of the lot, with a new-looking army
uniform, boots, and a big knife slung in a leather sheath.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, of which Kosovo is a province, is under an arms
embargo. Albania is rife with small weaponry, such as Kalashnikovs
and rocket-propelled grenade launchers. But the KLA lacks the tanks
and other heavy equipment to match the firepower of the Yugoslav
military, KLA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO would be better off giving guns to the KLA, instead of
providing their own ground troops, Krasniqi said. That idea is not
popular with many NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   Arming the KLA is a delicate and politically loaded question for
the West, which has insisted it does not back independence for
Kosovo. Giving guns to the KLA would be tantamount to backing the
Kosovar Albanians' fight for independence, many fear.
</P>
<P>
   But Krasniqi said an influx of weaponry, not NATO ground
soldiers _ is critical to KLA success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own soldiers, and we know the territory,'' he
said. ``There is no need for American young people to die for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
