<SLUG> BC-NATO-CLARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK KNOWN FOR INTENSITY, BRAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Not long after NATO began bombing Serbia, NATO's
supreme commander, General Wesley K. Clark, promised to
systematically attack, disrupt, degrade, devastate, and ultimately
destroy Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's boss, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, quickly
withdrew the word ``destroy,'' saying Clark had misspoken.
</P>
<P>
   But those who know Clark say that was exactly what Clark meant
to say, and what he wants to do. But getting permission from his
political masters to destroy Milosevic's forces is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are both his sponsors and his bane. Clark is in a
job very few in the Army would have predicted he would get, and a
good number didn't want him to get it. Clark doesn't win popularity
contests in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   But he is extremely popular with the politicians that helped him
win the NATO command two years ago, and with those from the 19 NATO
countries who must approve his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with those who know him and who have worked with him
paint a portrait of contrasting images. Clark's admirers describe
him as a towering intellect, one of the most literate, urbane
generals in the world, a man who understands the complex
relationship between democracies and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Muhamed Sacirbey, the Bosnian ambassador to the United Nations,
said Clark has a great empathy for those who don't have the ability
to stand up to bullies, from the Bosnian Muslims who took the brunt
of punishment in the Bosnian war to the ethnic Albanians who have
been expelled from Kosovo today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is real compassion in all that military strategy,'' said
Sacirbey.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's detractors criticize him as an overly ambitious
micro-manager who does not inspire loyalty. Said one former
Pentagon official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity: ``I
don't know anyone who's worked for Wes who really likes him.''
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton stops here Wednesday to confer with top
NATO officials, it will be a reunion of two men who have a lot in
common, most recently their determination to get rid of Milosevic
once and for all after years of trying to negotiate with him.
</P>
<P>
   Although they did not know each other, Clark and Clinton grew up
in Arkansas. Clark was two years older than Clinton. Both grew up
without fathers, Clark's having died when he was 4. That's when his
mother, a Southern Baptist, took him from Chicago to Little Rock.
Clark later converted to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   It was only as an adult that Clark discovered that his
grandfather was a Russian Jew who escaped a pogrom a century ago,
the New York Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wes has that Clintonesque quality, in that when he
talks to you he makes you feel like you are the solitary focus of
his attention,'' said Sacirbey. ``I don't know if he's always
sincere. But I wouldn't confuse sincerity with integrity. I think
Wes Clark's integrity is unquestioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clark and Clinton went to Oxford as Rhodes scholars. But
while Clinton demonstrated against the Vietnam War, Clark was one
of the few Americans in Britain at the time who was willing to
defend US policy. After graduating from West Point, first in his
class in 1966, Clark studied philosophy at Oxford, then went to
Vietnam. There, as a 25-year-old first lieutenant, he made a name
for himself and won a Silver Star when he took four bullets in an
ambush but rallied his platoon to mount a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clark's critics do not dispute his bravery, something
Sacirbey saw first hand during the Bosnian war when a car plunged
off a mountain road near Sarajevo, killing three US diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wes Clark rappeled down the mountainside in his dress uniform
to recover the bodies,'' said Sacirbey. ``He was very calm. He was
obviously upset by what happened, but it didn't affect his ability
to deal with the job at hand. He didn't make it a political issue,
as others did. He focused on dealing with the human lives at
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey said Clark, who was the military adviser to US envoy
Richard Holbrooke during the Bosnian war, demonstrated that ability
to remain calm during the talks in Dayton that eventually ended the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Wes Clark, there wouldn't have been an agreement in
Dayton,'' said Sacirbey. ``He held it together.''
</P>
<P>
   A witty, well-read raconteur, Clark has the ability to win over
people who might not be inclined to like an American four-star
general. The Colombian novelist and Nobel laureate Gabriel Garcia
Marquez is one of them. Long a critic of US policy in Central and
South America, Garcia Marquez admits to having been charmed by
Clark's intellect when they met at the Panama Canal when Clark was
in charge of the Southern Command.
</P>
<P>
   In a recently syndicated column, Garcia Marquez described Clark
as ``a soldier who dreams of being a man of letters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an elegant man, who likes to stand on ceremony, and his
brothers-in-arms consider him a soldier of the old school, who
shares bread and salt with the troops and who cannot live without
knowing what other people think of him,'' Garcia Marquez wrote.
``What few people realize is that behind the four stars and a
mountain of insignia is an irresistible urge to be recognized as a
political intellectual and an ideologue of social welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia Marquez's take on Clark's self-image resonates with many
who know Clark. But his suggestion that Clark is a ``soldier's
soldier'' does not. Clark is not popular with most soldiers, the
way General Norman Schwarzkopf, the Gulf War commander, was. The
Army, in fact, opposed his appointment as head of Southern Command,
and as NATO supreme allied commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not pushed by the Army,'' said Lawrence Korb, a former
Pentagon official who is now studies director at the Council on
Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Korb said that many in the Army believe NATO should be run by
someone who has spent most of a career in Europe, while Clark was
known mainly for his work in Bosnia. But Clark's political contacts
have carried him beyond Pentagon personality clashes. Despite the
Little Rock connection, it is not Clinton but Clinton's national
security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, who is Clark's biggest
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has the patience of a long-distance swimmer, which he is.
He swims to stay in shape. In his book, ``To End a War,'' Holbrooke
said Clark's ``boyish demeanor and charm masked, but only slightly,
his extraordinary intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey believes that critics underestimate Clark when they
suggest NATO has started a war it can't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wes Clark has been underestimated his whole career,'' he said.
``If anyone can bring this to a successful conclusion, it's him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
