 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Common Windows 98 problems exposed 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Windows 98 is such a massive program that you can
never know enough about it. And that fact has produced good fodder
for the PC magazine industry. Take the May issue of PC Computing.
Its cover story is called ``Undocumented Window Secrets.'' Sounds
like the title of some show on the Fox network, doesn't it? Hype
aside, this article offers plenty of helpful hints. The article
identifies 15 common problems with Windows 98. They include such
things as slow Internet connections, clocks that lose time and
disappearing files. The article offers suggestions how to fix these
problems and more.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just corporate computer networks that are threatened by
the Y2K glitch. Many applications you keep on your home computer
are threatened, too. The May issue of PC Computing offers some
guidelines on how to kick the millennium bug off your home desktop
computer.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   There apparently is an unofficial movement under way by the
computer industry to digitize every classic board game. Leading the
charge is Hasbro Interactive. In its latest efforts, the company
has released two collections on computer CD. One is a title called
``Board Games,'' which features some of the best board games. Those
games include chess, checkers, pente, dominoes and connect four. On
the card collection title, called ``Card Games,'' you'll find
spades, cribbage, hearts and gin rummy, among many others. Both of
these CDs are available only for Windows computers.
</P>
<P>
   At last, there's a computer CD about animals that doesn't
involve shooting them. WizardWorks has released a new computer CD
called ``Bird Watcher,'' which calls itself ``an interactive
birding game.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bird Watcher,'' players view photos and video clips of
birds. And there's a game in which you play a raptor as it hunts
for rabbits and fish. ``Bird Watcher'' is available only for PCs
running Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Learn about the amazing complexity of the planet _ and learn
what is at risk because of a growing number of endangered plant and
animal species. National Geographic has set up a site that explores
this issue through picture, text and sound. You'll find the site at
tectonic
</P>
<P>
   .nationalgeographic.com/2000/biodiversity/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
