 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Server is the traffic cop for a home network 
By Gerry Yandel  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Paul Harvey says: ``And now for the rest of the
story ...''
</P>
<P>
   Several readers sent e-mail to warn me there is more to setting
up my in-home network than slapping some cable into an Ethernet hub
and wiring all the machines together.
</P>
<P>
   I had planned to write about what else it takes to split one
cable modem throughout the house. After all, I am learning a lot of
this stuff as I go, just as many of you are. But there's no sense
in putting off the inevitable. Let's talk about setting up a
network server.
</P>
<P>
   In order to simultaneously use one Internet provider address,
you'll have to make one of the machines on your network a traffic
cop and communicate with the other machines on your local area
network. In the simplest of terms, this means that one of your
machines will have to be able to talk to the rest of the machines
in your house. It will also allow all the machines to share a
single IP address, by letting you assign them all a secondary
address on your network.
</P>
<P>
   Your server software then acts as a translator between your
Internet provider and your own network, assigning the proper
packets of data to the proper IP addresses.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, say your son is online in his room playing
``Doom'' and you are online doing your banking in the den. The
server will send the packets of ``Doom'' data to the IP address in
the bedroom and the data from the bank's Web server to the IP
address in the den.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious way to set up your server is to buy a cheap PC
to be used only as a server and stash it with the cable modem. As
far as server software goes, there are several flavors and versions
available.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers suggested using Linux, some versions of which come
with Apache server software, but I am not quite at that juncture
yet. It's a learning curve I have been avoiding. (I did buy myself
RedHat 5.2 for Christmas, and I had a great time installing it. But
that's as far as I got.) One reader swears by the ``Linux Edge
Router,'' a small server and Linux kernel that'll run off a floppy
disk. It seemed straightforward enough to a Linux neophyte like
myself.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader suggested Wingate 3.0. A version called Wingate
Home is priced at $39.95 for three users and $69.95 for six users.
</P>
<P>
   The type of software you decide upon will dictate the hardware
required for your server. Linux Edge, like pretty much all
Linux-based servers, runs off a 486 with 16 megabytes of RAM.
Windows NT, obviously, requires a bit more power and, therefore, a
more expensive machine. Wingate Home works with Win95, 98 and NT,
and there are several other products out that will allow you to set
up a server in those operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   It also isn't necessary to have a separate server set up. Any of
your primary computers could also function as the server.
</P>
<P>
   But, with the cheap prices of 486s and Pentiums, there's no
reason not to get a machine to use solely as a server, and it's
probably more advantageous to have a separate server. Having a
machine functioning solely as a server will also bypass problems of
not having enough PCI slots and IRQs for your two Ethernet cards in
one machine.
</P>
<P>
   Also realize that an in-home network is not only for cable modem
sharing. One reader wrote about his in-home network of five
machines all sharing a 33.6 modem.
</P>
<P>
   Even when all five machines are online simultaneously, they get
acceptable access, he writes, although there can be a noticeable
performance drain if some of them are doing packet-intensive work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-03-99 1044EDT &QL;
</P>
