 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Don't blame Internet for kids' bad behavior 
By Frances Katz  
c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About a decade ago, in my hometown of Leominster,
Mass., two girls from my high school went home together after
school. Then they took a shotgun down from over the fireplace, went
up to a bedroom, put on some Jimi Hendrix and shot themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, everyone blamed Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   The local and national media converged on our town, putting up
huge satellite dishes in front of my school for our 15 minutes of
morbid fame. They wrote soul-searching articles on disaffected
youth in local and national newspapers. Quite a lot of time and
videotape was spent trying to find something to blame, some outside
influence that could have caused two teen-age girls to end their
lives one day after school.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, two troubled high school students in Colorado,
armed with more ammunition than some Third World countries, nearly
succeeded in their plan to murder everyone at Columbine High. In
the aftermath of this horrifying tragedy, the media once again is
searching for something to blame. This time it was their clothes,
the music they liked, the video games they played and the books
they read.
</P>
<P>
   When it was revealed they liked computers, everyone blamed the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to a ``Dateline NBC'' poll, 16 percent of adults
surveyed said that limiting teen-agers' access to the Internet
would keep teen-agers from feeling lonely, depressed and isolated.
Limited Web access will keep the jocks from picking on them and
somehow make the high school experience bearable.
</P>
<P>
   I beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   There were troubled kids before there was an Internet, and there
will be troubled kids long after the Internet becomes as quaint as
the radio or the newspaper. Amazon.com is not Earth's biggest
bookstore; instead it's the Internet itself. The Internet is the
biggest repository of information and misinformation ever
collected. For every disturbed kid asking Lycos to find
bomb-building sites, there are kids reading up on Kosovo, applying
to college, chatting with friends, taking ``How to tell if he/she
likes you'' quizzes or watching the ``Star Wars'' trailer for the
sixth or seventh time. Some of them are building Web sites that
include pictures of the family pet or a recent vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Not every kid with a Web site or Net access wants to blow up his
high school or glorify Hitler. Try a Yahoo! search for Leonardo Di
Caprio or Claire Danes and you'll find numerous fan pages built by
teens devoted to their favorite movie and music stars. Before there
were computers, their grandparents were doing the same thing _
making hard-copy scrapbooks of their favorite stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most teens and any adult worth talking to will tell you that
high school can be a painful experience even for the most
well-adjusted teen. High school can leave emotional scars that take
years to heal. I have friends still harboring grudges against the
person who beat them out for the lead in the spring musical, stood
them up on prom night or drove cooler cars.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of kids, I spent a lot of time listening to rock
music, watching TV, hanging out at the mall and talking to my
friends on the phone. There were lots of things I was sure my
parents, as much as they loved me, just wouldn't understand. But
even during my worst years of teen-age misery, I never once
considered blowing up my school, not because I didn't have America
Online to corrupt me, but because I knew it was wrong, and as black
as things may have seemed sometimes, I never thought that violence
was the answer to my problems.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold believed it
was the answer to theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, The New York Times and CNN are on the Web, but so is page
after page of material devoted to every radical fringe group
imaginable. For a troubled teen looking for something, anything to
latch onto, these sites validate their darkest, most disturbing
thoughts and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   But don't use the Internet as a catch-all excuse for everything
wrong with the kids today. If Harris didn't have Net access, he'd
have found other ways to carry out the massacre he had spent more
than a year planning.
</P>
<P>
   Harris may have had access to a vast store of information,
violent video games and Gothic music videos. It seems the one thing
he did not have and desperately needed was access to a network of
adults and peers who could help him cope with his violent feelings,
his despair and his rage. To borrow from William Shakespeare, ``The
fault lies not in the Web, but with ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-03-99 1043EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
