<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-STAR-WARS-WEB-HNS     05-05 1834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-STAR-WARS-WEB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORCE.NET BE WITH YOU: HOUSTON WEB SITE LEADS A GALAXY OF
INFORMATION FOR `STAR WARS' FANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When ``Star Wars'' blasted off in 1977, the biggest
forum where fans could mingle was in lines outside theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Now that seems like a long time ago in a galaxy far, far away.
Today's devotees of R2-D2 and the Force are closely entwined on the
Internet, which has propelled them from the dark ages of gleaning
tidbits in magazines to the cyberspace era of having all things
``Star Wars'' instantly at their fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace'' nears its May
19 release, this cyber fan base isn't just connected. It seems
almost omniscient.
</P>
<P>
   Just how know-it-all is this new breed of fan?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've got a copy of the script,'' said Scott Chitwood of
Houston, a founder of www.theforce.net, widely recognized as the
top ``Star Wars'' fan Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, through one of its many ``spies,'' theforce.net got
a copy of director George Lucas' screenplay for ``TPM,'' the first
film in his ``Star Wars'' prequel trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they it was posted it online. That would have been
going too far, Chitwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Even when theforce.net does leak information about the film, it
labels some items as ``spoilers.'' Those who want to wait and to
savor the movie's full impact can avoid such things while trolling
the site's many features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see both sides of it,'' Chitwood said. ``There are people
who really hate it _ who think we're ruining their Christmas
presents. But I think even Lucas feels it's kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some fan-run Web sites push the limits, posting shaky rumors
or facts that should stay secret awhile longer, such as which
characters in the new movie live or die.
</P>
<P>
   Even theforce.net got into hot water with Lucas when it carried
a sound clip of new comic sidekick Jar Jar Binks' voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Lucasfilm) called us personally and said, `OK, you've
had your fun. We love the fan sites, but this is going too far,'''
Chitwood said. ``And I agreed with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think hearing two lines of dialogue took away from the
film, but they've let us get away with so much that you've got to
respect their wishes. You can't just say, `Sue me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the plot ``is pretty much all out there,'' said Chitwood,
27, a civil engineer who designs offshore structures for Shell
Deepwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Web sites have posted the ending of the movie. We've got
that information, too, but there's no way we're going to run with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this would have been possible without the Internet's
elaborate networks of communication between fans and filmmakers
near and far. ``Star Wars'' is big-time on the Net, amassing about
7,000 sites in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, theforce.net is like a daily newspaper. Its home
page is subtitled ``Your daily dose of Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   News is posted daily _ often several times a day _ by Chitwood
and about a dozen colleagues, including co-founder Darin Smith of
Dallas, a friend from their days at Texas A&AMP;M University in College
Station.
</P>
<P>
   That's where theforce.net had its genesis in 1996, just as
``Star Wars'' mania began rising again, but before ``Star Wars''
was an Internet staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some sites, but we didn't see any doing what we
wanted: showing news and reviews,'' Chitwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Limited to campus, ``The Star Wars Page at Texas A&AMP;M'' drew mild
interest. It got a few ``hits'' (or Web visits) by Aggie Net
surfers, but when its creators finished graduate studies, they were
unable to pass it on. ``We'd hoped to hand it off to other Aggies,
but nobody else was interested,'' Chitwood said.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1997 _ with Chitwood employed in Houston and Smith in
Dallas _ they launched theforce.net on the Internet, bringing
aboard other far-flung fans they'd met online (including some they
still haven't met in person).
</P>
<P>
   Chitwood is editor ``by default,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different people do the job as time permits. But what I say
goes, so I take the heat, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Other staffers for the nonprofit site live across the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 26, an aerospace engineer, isn't as active now as before.
``Real life is taking over,'' he said. ``It's fun, but you can't
stay a little boy forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Working in its spare time, theforce.net crew has carved out such
high visibility that Lucasfilm monitors the site. It's also
contributed to stories in Newsweek, Entertainment Weekly and the
Houston Chronicle, as well as being featured on E! and other
television channels.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly operating costs of $2,000 (the site has a commercial
bandwidth) are covered by tiny sponsor ads, with excess funds going
to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the site has attracted 25,000 to 30,000 visitors per day.
When the second ``TPM'' trailer hit theaters and theforce.net had
it online, the site drew 40,000 visitors per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, we were lucky to get 5,000 a day, and when we
first started, 100 a day,'' Chitwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a high profile was first sparked by ``Troops,'' a parody by
Kevin Rubio, who set ``Star Wars''' Stormtroopers amid the motifs
of TV's ``Cops.'' Visitors flocked when theforce.net hosted his
video (which it still does).
</P>
<P>
   Then the first trilogy's ``Special Editions'' reached theaters
in '97, ``and that fed this to a large degree,'' Chitwood said. ``A
lot of kids were seeing the films for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by prequel news, which began as a trickle but
has become a flood, eclipsing standing site features such as
discussion forums, editorials, humor and fan fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we update the news every day, we have a loyal fan
base,'' Chitwood said. ``We've become part of people's routine.''
</P>
<P>
   High visibility has made theforce.net a logical place for those
with juicy tidbits to spill the beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look for this,'' Chitwood said. ``If somebody has
something they want to spread around, they come to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy sneaked onto the set (of ''TPM``) and took some
pictures. But we keep our sources anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sites are more like fan clubs _ including www.swgeeks.com,
Web home of the Greater Gulf Coast Star Wars Collectors.
</P>
<P>
   It's designed to unite club members _ roughly three dozen
people, mostly males _ in their pursuit of ``Star Wars'' toys, a
multibillion-dollar industry.
</P>
<P>
   They launched the club in 1997 to help members find toys at
retail and avoid paying inflated prices to collectibles dealers
down the line. Monday was D-Day, when the new film's toys arrived
in stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal was to get different sets of eyes out there
looking for our collections,'' said founder Blake Wright of
Houston. ``No member should have to buy a new `Star Wars' toy off
the secondary market from a dealer who gouges. We look out for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides staying in touch online, the fans also meet monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as crazy as people might think,'' said Wright, a
reporter for an international oil and gas newspaper. ``We're
normal. We have jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many fans that it's a broad spectrum,'' Chitwood
said. ``But most are average people. There are a lot worse
hobbies.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 30, bought original `Star Wars' toys years ago, but they
were destroyed in a fire in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drifted away after `Return of the Jedi' left theaters,
around 1984,'' he said. ``Then there was hardly anything new about
`Star Wars' until the summer of '95.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when a new wave of toys swept the market, with Hasbro
(the big toy licensee for `TPM') reissuing old `Star Wars' toys and
figures in updated forms.
</P>
<P>
   Wright started collecting again _ to look, not touch. He keeps
about 80 percent of his items sealed in their display boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chitwood, he's got a room at home filled with ``Star Wars''
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mythology,'' Wright said. ``America doesn't really have
its own mythology, but `Star Wars' gives us that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing really special about the story. It's good vs.
evil. But everybody can relate to it. And in 1977, no one had ever
seen anything like it _ had ever seen a `droid' or these other
worlds that Lucas created.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Davidson of Prince George, British Columbia, chief graphic
designer for theforce.net, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars is a fascinating universe from a sci-fi and fantasy
standpoint,'' he said. ``It's a timeless tale of good vs. evil _ of
the fall and retribution of Darth Vader.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, 21, wasn't born when ``Star Wars'' arrived in '77, but
still says he was there at the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in my mother's womb when she first saw Star Wars,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stream of news keeps him extremely busy. ``I could spend
more time on it but have to allocate,'' he said. ``Some people
might say we're too obsessive, but I have another life. There's
school, friends, hobbies, traveling, working out. And there's Star
Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Chitwood acknowledges the hype, but doesn't think the movie is
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see Star Wars on the cover of every magazine than
kids getting blown away in Colorado or other harsh realities. This
is a good escape while teaching kids good lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith calls Star Wars ``good clean fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Yoda _ the philosophy and wisdom he pours out. A
lot of fans blitz over that, but there's a lot of meat there. I
like the morals Lucas tries to pass on.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also favors Han Solo as ``a space cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright won't say who his favorite Star Wars character is.
Chitwood favors Darth Vader, while Davidson prefers Chewbacca.
</P>
<P>
   Other fans are excited about Darth Maul, a new red-faced
villain. ``We've probably seen 10 seconds of him in a trailer, but
he's already been embraced as one evil dude,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Vader, ``He's a good guy who's just misunderstood,''
Chitwood said.
</P>
<P>
   How did Chitwood's fascination start?
</P>
<P>
   He first saw ``Star Wars'' at age 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a loose tooth, and my dad said, `Let me wiggle that
tooth, and I'll take you to see Star Wars.' I said `No way,' but he
grabbed me and pulled the tooth right out and said, `Great. We're
going to see Star Wars.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried all the way to the theater _ and now this,'' Chitwood
said. ``Who would have thought?''
</P>
<P>
   Now he and many fans are scheduling vacation time so they can
see the new film the day it opens _ not that the plot will have
many surprises for him.
</P>
<P>
   Chitwood says he probably wouldn't have dug so deeply if he'd
known he'd uncover so much. ``But once you start digging into this
stuff, it's kind of addicting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we had a full description of the first trailer before
it came out, but when you go into the theater and see it with a
crowd and hear that music, you totally forget everything you knew
before and are just blown away. And I expect that to happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
