<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SEXOFFENDERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX OFFENDER INFORMATION GOES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By KATHLEEN INGLEY   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The eerie galleries of photos are just a few mouse
clicks away on the Internet. Rapists, child molesters and flashers
stare out from the screen. You can find their names, addresses,
ages and descriptions of their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Chandler man who spent 10 years in prison for
attempted sex acts with a 10-year-old. A few more clicks lead to
the Yuma man convicted of sexual abuse and attempted sexual
assault, who was jailed two years ago for failing to register as a
sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   You can check out molesters in Michigan, rapists in North
Carolina and Alaska's 1,600-plus sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a national rush to use the Internet to alert
the public to the identities and whereabouts of registered sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, 15 states were listing sex offenders on Web
sites, with more in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   And where the states are lagging, counties, cities and even some
individuals are setting up the lists. Arizona's system is scheduled
to go online in January, but four cities _ Chandler, Tempe, Tucson
and Yuma _ already list offenders on their Web sites, and Phoenix
may follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Some call the Internet a powerful tool for alerting people to
potentially dangerous neighbors. In Florida, a woman discovered
that a sex offender was helping with her son's Boy Scout troop.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that Internet postings can cause more damage than
they prevent.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if a database isn't updated when a sex offender
moves, innocent people may find their address identified as the
home of a molester.
</P>
<P>
   One couple in Ann Arbor, Mich., unwittingly bought a house from
a sex offender and then found their address listed on the Internet
_ with no way to get the state to take them off the site until the
man's actual address was found.
</P>
<P>
   Other concerns range from accidentally revealing the names of
victims to creating an instant mailing list for pornographers
looking for customers.
</P>
<P>
   The sex offender Web sites aren't an electronic version of
``wanted'' posters. All the offenders have gone through the courts.
They've served their sentences or are on probation. Now their names
and addresses are registered with local law enforcement, and
they're living out in the community.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet sites typically let you search for offenders by
county, city, ZIP code or name.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outstanding medium to present information,'' said
crime prevention officer Todd Mittness, who runs the Web site for
the city of Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Florida began publishing the identities of sex offenders on the
Internet in November 1996, apparently the first state to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Legal Enforcement credits the system with
thwarting some sex offenders before they had a chance to repeat
their crimes and for catching others who had failed to register.
</P>
<P>
   One sexual predator joined a martial arts class and was becoming
very friendly with a young girl in the group. A fellow class member
recognized the man from photos on Florida's Internet site. The
predator was arrested for violating his probation, which prohibited
contact with girls younger than 16.
</P>
<P>
   The offender who volunteered for the Boy Scout troop was on
probation and forbidden to have such contact with youths. His
probation was revoked and he was sent back to prison to finish his
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   California, on the other hand, steered clear of the Internet and
chose to offer access to its sex offender database through a CD-ROM
system in the offices of local law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Access is tightly controlled: You must sign a form, be 18 or
older and provide identification.
</P>
<P>
   The state wants to make sure that sex offenders themselves don't
tap into the database as a way to contact one another, team up or
swap pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Justice has set up booths at the
state fair and the Los Angeles County Fair so people can check out
the 69,000 listings on the CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Van Winkle, an information officer at the Department of
Justice, was helping at the state fair when a 19-year-old woman
decided to run her boyfriend's name just for fun. Then his name and
photo popped up on the screen. She was so upset that she began
hyperventilating, and first-aid workers had to be called.
</P>
<P>
   Of some 100,000 people who have checked the database, Van Winkle
knows of four women who were stunned to find their husbands' names.
</P>
<P>
   California has its own list of success stories, which are posted
on the Internet. There was the pizza deliveryman identified as a
high-risk sex offender, and the molester who was discovered
volunteering at a public school.
</P>
<P>
   And despite California's aversion to the Internet, some of the
state's listings have been posted independently by people who think
they should be available online. Taking advantage of a loophole in
the law, they copy down the information by hand and then put it on
a Web site. So far, the state attorney general has decided not to
challenge them.
</P>
<P>
   It's so easy to pull up the identity of sex offenders with a few
keystrokes that it's easy to ignore the standard warning posted at
Internet sites: The information could be wrong or out of date.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a weeping woman called up the American Civil Liberties
Union of Florida. Her ex-husband was a convicted sex offender just
being released from prison, and it was her address that showed up
on the Internet _ even though they were divorced years ago and he
didn't live there at the time of conviction.
</P>
<P>
   If the state is going to release ``such incendiary information
that can have such devastating consequences,'' said Howard Simon,
executive director of the Florida ACLU, it ought to make sure that
it's absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Ingley, who supervises the sexual offender/predator unit,
says Florida does periodic sweeps to check addresses.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the ACLU unsuccessfully tried to block the state's
sex offender Internet site after authorities acknowledged that 20
to 40 percent of the addresses were inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Arizona started verifying the addresses of its
nearly 10,000 registered sex offenders in January, a year before
the names of higher risk individuals are scheduled to go online.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``we have to be realistic,'' said Val Biebrich,
sex offender community notification coordinator. Although the first
round is the hardest, he already sees that Arizona won't be able to
double-check most addresses more than once a year. ``You'd have to
have a staff of 30 to 40 people to do it every 90 days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides mistakes, there's the question of security.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say it's tight. In Chandler, for instance, the site
is encrypted to keep out hackers. Plus, said crime prevention
officer Mittness, who runs the site, ``I'm the only one that has
the program and the password to get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics point out that hackers have broken into some of the
most secure sites in the nation, run by the Pentagon or the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   As people learn to surf the Web to find the names of sex
offenders, pranksters and revenge seekers could set up their own
Web sites purporting to list molesters, said Kim English, research
director at Colorado's Division of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think anybody has thought this stuff through,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Orlando area, there were several incidents in which
people used information from the state Internet site to create
phony fliers naming innocent people as sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Harassment is another worry.
</P>
<P>
   Days after California released its CD-ROM, one sex offender's
car was firebombed. However, state authorities traced the explosion
to teenagers playing with fireworks in an incident unrelated to the
sex offender database.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Web sites include stern warnings that it's illegal to
use the information to harass offenders. Dallas and several other
Texas cities go a step further, requiring people who access their
sex offender site to furnish their names and addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Internet push are warning of serious, unintended
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Orr, executive director of the Center Against Sexual
Abuse in Phoenix, fears that the identities of victims could be
accidentally disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   While some Web sites provide only the statute that was violated,
others give more detailed descriptions of the crimes, including
descriptions of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites in Arizona reveal that in one case the victim was a
man's 15-year-old stepdaughter and in another it was the daughter
of the abuser's live-in girlfriend. One Web site discloses that the
victims were 10-year-old friends of the molester's daughter _ and
it names the tiny town where the crimes occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Florida used to include graphic descriptions of sex offenses on
its Internet site, but a year and a half ago, it switched to giving
limited information about the crime and only the general age of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Still, victims' advocates wonder about wholesale broadcasting
the names of sex offenders when many crimes are incest. Nationally,
one in four imprisoned for sexual assault preyed on their own child
or stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ask ourselves, `What's the real goal here? Was this
necessary?' '' Orr said. ``Of all of the repercussions, has anyone
weighed the positive against the negative? I don't really feel that
anyone has.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is so new that it's hard to foresee how it will play
out.
</P>
<P>
   The local sex offender Internet sites in Arizona have been
online for less than a year. In talks with four offenders listed on
the Chandler and Tempe sites, none knew that their names and faces
were on the Internet, although some had heard the system was in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   None would be quoted by name. All were worried that their
families, some living out of state, would be humiliated. One
suggested that his adult son change his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outing'' people on the Internet could also thwart any
possibility of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schroeder, associate director of the ACLU of Southern
California, argues that the probability of repeat crimes is
actually increased ``by making someone's name public and thereby
having people hound the person from community to community,
becoming a wanderer without the ability to put down roots.''
</P>
<P>
   She received a letter from a middle-age man who was convicted of
a sex crime in his early 20s, did his time in prison and went
through therapy. He's now married, with children, living in a small
coastal town where he's a successful businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he lives in terror that someone will find his name among
the list of sex offenders. ``If one person discovers he's on the
list,'' Schroeder said, ``his business, his family, his life is
ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-04-99 0224EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
