<HEADLINE>
IF YOU'RE DULL, YOU'LL BE DULL ON THE WEB, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lately I have been whiling away hours in the nation's departure
lounges, hotbeds of cellular telephony. I am amazed to see the
near-constant use that some businesspeople squeeze out of their
flip-open digital-electronic clams.
</P>
<P>
   At Logan the other day, the man next to me phoned home to say
his flight was delayed by 20 minutes. Half an hour later: ``They're
pre-boarding.'' Then followed a third call to Part Unknown,
informing his doubtless fascinated spouse equivalent that rows 20
to 27 are ready for boarding. Who's paying for this? (His business,
subsidized by the taxpayer.) Who's listening to this? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Technology has given modern Americans what they've always
craved: an identity. Until recently there was only one person whose
whereabouts had to be known at all times: the president of the
United States. Monicagate revealed that the Secret Service operates
an electronic system that tells it which White House room the
president occupies. But now Everyman has his or her own Global
Positioning System (GPS) in continuous communciation with home
base. I wish I could intercept the cell-phone traffic emanating
from those tinted-window Range Rovers that are always tailgating me
on Route 128: ``There's a Honda in my way, honey. Should I pass him
or vaporize him?''
</P>
<P>
   Phones are only the start. The early years of the Internet gave
us screen names. My unbearably witty screen name used to be
Ishmalex _ ``Call me Alex'' _ d'ya get it? I've since reverted to
the name my parents gave me. For some, screen names weren't enough;
they became domains: Martha(at)marthastewart.com;
joyce(at)joycemaynard.com, and others.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. For just a few hundred dollars, you can join
the legion of Web cam devotees who chronicle their lives on
Internet sites. The Belgrade Web cam I've been monitoring seems to
have lost its juice, but for those of you with a zest for foreign
cybertravel, there's a Web cam inside the elephant house at
Amsterdam's Dierenpark Zoo. Boston's famous LaunderettCam at 668
Tremont Street is no longer operative (laundromat closed). But to
fully appreciate the blank torpidity of the genre, check in with
local hero James at www.eco-model.com/James/newwebcam.htm. I'm sure
Web surfers would flock to my hypothetical Web cam site,
www.athomewithalex. Watch Alex hector his children about watching
too much TV. One hour later, see Alex lunch out in front of a
meaningless Celtics-Knicks game.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever visited a university, you must know that hundreds
if not thousands of students on every campus maintain their own Web
sites. Here's one that I picked at random _
http://stu.cofc.edu/srbozema/ _ but it hardly matters, because
they're all the same. There are always a few pictures, of a child,
a best friend, or that last national park visited. Then you'll have
some tiny freebie fillip _ in this case, the dancing raisins _ the
requisite ``cool links'' to other sites, and usually a list of
dopey jokes. What Emile Durkheim said about suicide notes could
certainly be applied to ``personal'' Web pages: They are all the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Individuality is the opium of the 20th-century masses. The
cruelest fiction promoted by schools, advertising agencies,
politicians, and the stewards of the status quo is that everyone
has something to say; that your tastes are distinctive; that every
person matters. Chances are, you don't. For about half of recorded
history, no one had written an autobiography. Then a sardonically
self-aware bishop from a town called Hippo invented the genre with
``The Confessions of St. Augustine.'' Today's autobiographer: a
veejay (video jockey) named Lisa Kennedy Montgomery of MTV. Who the
hell is she?
</P>
<P>
   It's all quite delusory, the ``personalized'' copies of Time
magazine, the cool screen name, the endless line of homogenous home
pages stretching into cybereternity, the digital GPS navigator
Velcro'd onto the dashboard. To paraphrase a line made famous by
the Firesign Theatre: Why does it matter exactly where you are,
when you aren't any place at all?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
