<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-05 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ISN'T BLACK OR WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Littleton, the suburbs and their largely white denizens
had always found a way to avoid what they assumed was the uniquely
dark violence of the city, a violence that blackened and became
more remote with every media utterance of ``gang!''
</P>
<P>
   When black kids killed black kids in horrifying numbers in this
decade, the acts were depicted as so wild, so brazen, and so
animalistic that any attempt to remind America that these were
still children was pummeled into inaudibility.
</P>
<P>
   There was little concern about alienation, no huge dispatch of
trauma counselors, and no call such as the one made by House
Judiciary chairman Henry Hyde to examine this ``complicated
cultural moment'' and the ``root causes of a crisis among our
young.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was black kids killing black kids, a cacophonous legion
of academics and essayists told us this was evidence of a ``black
pathology'' and an ``underclass.'' This was perfect for a media
culture that seems bent on reinforcing white suburbanites who fled
the city by offering grossly disproportionate depictions of urban
black people as out of control, dependent, and addicted.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery of a ``black pathology'' came as the book ``The
Bell Curve'' revived the racist assertion that intelligence is
fixed at birth. Though America is too polite to agree with this
officially, the prison building boom, which paralleled cuts for
public education, was proof that the suburbs, the fulcrum of
national politics, got the message that ``black pathology'' is
incurable.
</P>
<P>
   The placing of black youth killers in this hopelessly separate
world of social disease has come at a cost to the suburbs. It has
cost them precious time in handwringing, so much that the angst has
become as inordinate as it is sincere.
</P>
<P>
   In white America there have been seven schoolyard shootings in
the last two years in which 17 people have been killed and at least
46 others wounded. But despite the shock that these things really
do happen far from black ghettos and their ``gangs,'' we are not
much closer to gun control or any large-scale attack on violent
culture. Instead, each incident has been allowed to run its course
as a shocking but ultimately aberrant event. Aberrant events need
no deep attention. America has never entertained the concept of a
``white pathology'' and only pays lip service to the idea that its
fate is tied to the ``black'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the suburbs have remained so convinced of their
innocence that even the worst of young white killers are described
in human ways that no young black killer could ever hope for. When
Kip Kinkel killed his parents and two classmates and wounded 25 in
Springfield, Ore., Newsweek wrote: ``With his shy smile and slight
build, 15-year-old Kip Kinkel has an innocent look that is part
Huck Finn and part Alfred E. Neuman _ boyish and quintessentially
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Littleton offers the suburbs a fresh chance to do something
about violence. All they have to do is look back to the land so
many of their denizens fled from. The cities.
</P>
<P>
   Most American cities have experienced major drops in homicides
in recent years. Boston was a standard-bearer in the area of youth
violence, going 2 1/2 years without a juvenile homicide, from July
1995 to December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the cities, the denizens who were bludgeoned by street
violence and particularly by the mowing down of young children
decided that enough was enough. On the surface, the main credit for
the drop in violence, the part most amplified by politicians and
the media, was law and order in the form of community policing and
taking the most violent offenders off the street.
</P>
<P>
   But people who really knew the whole picture knew there was a
renaissance going on. Churches, after years of having all the
impact of a burned-up, boarded-up storefront, renewed their
ministry to troubled youths. Male mentoring programs, particularly
in Boston, popped up in several locations to fill idle time with
education and nurturing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Many public schools instituted antiviolence curriculums.
Teenagers, some with government help and some on their own,
organized peer groups to reach out to troubled friends and steer
them away from guns and gangs. City governments began treating
violence as an issue of public health, making hospital and police
costs the basis for lawsuits by cities.
</P>
<P>
   The cities realized that they could not wait for gun control _
an issue that remains in firm control of the suburbs. They could
not wait for values to be dropped on them given the violent
entertainment produced by powerful corporations and our own
nation's penchant for military might. They could not wait because
they knew that the death of children meant not just funerals, but
dying property values and general fear.
</P>
<P>
   The cities stopped wringing their hands long ago. When the
suburbs dry their eyes from the horror of Littleton, perhaps they
can see that violence was never uniquely dark to begin with but was
quintessentially American. Any serious action on schoolyard
massacres starts with the recognition that black kids were never
all that evil or white kids all that innocent. All our children are
under assault by one pathology, our addiction to guns and our
thirst for violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
