<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARING FOR A PARENT OFTEN EXACTS A TOLL ON A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When her mother fell in December and it became
apparent that the 89-year-old could no longer live alone, Susan S.
White asked for time off from her employer, BankBoston Corp., to
find an assisted living arrangement for her.
</P>
<P>
   White, 62, a human resources professional at the bank, was given
three weeks of paid leave. ``Essentially, the bank converted some
of the sick days I had to what we call R-days, days you can use to
take care of a relative.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ryan, 52, and head of the Women's Commission for the City
of Cambridge, tells a different story. Over 18 years, she
accumulated 7 1/2 months of paid sick time. But in the spring of
1998, when her 86-year-old mother was dying of cancer, Ryan learned
that she could not convert more than seven days of her accrued sick
time into paid time off for family care. Ryan, who had already used
four of the seven days, needed at least two weeks to assist her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked long hours and squeezed out some comp time and used
some unpaid time, but it was really demoralizing and shocking to
me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two different workplaces; two different approaches to elder care
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As the labor force ages, the issue of elder care is becoming
more visible. The Conference Board, a New York research group,
reports that demand for elder care benefits is expected to outstrip
child care by 2003. A small but growing number of employers are
starting to respond to the burgeoning need.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Family and Medical Leave Act provides up to 12
weeks unpaid leave for workers at companies with 50 or more
employees, many workers cannot afford to take any unpaid time off.
Now, some employers are providing benefits that go beyond the act,
such as extended paid sick time to care for family members.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, fully 25 percent of all American workers cared for
an ailing parent in 1996, according to the New York-based Families
and Work Institute. By 2002, 42 percent of all workers will provide
some form of elder care, ranging from helping a parent find housing
to paying bills or performing essential tasks such as providing
meals and personal care. And, although middle-aged workers are
still more likely to be engaged in elder care, one in five people
in their 20s and 30s cared for an elderly relative in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the trend more evident than in the workplace, where
employers are reporting that requests for time off to care for
aging and ailing parents are increasing. At State Street Corp., for
example, unpaid time off for elder care now accounts for 15 percent
of all leaves, up from 8 percent just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Said Skip Schlenk, director of work and family programs at AT&AMP;T
Corp.: ``Elder care is becoming a big, big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   At BankBoston, 50 percent of the 63 extended family leaves
granted last year involved the care of an elderly relative. Workers
are permitted to use paid extended sick time (usually of two to
three weeks) to care for a family member. The bank also offers
assistance in finding nursing homes, medical care, or senior day
care.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T, where elder care inquiries represent one-third of the
17,000 calls received by the firm's family resource and referral
program, workers telecommute, use personal days, vacation time, and
flexible scheduling to meet their parents' elder care needs.
</P>
<P>
   While Ryan has asked the city of Cambridge to review its stance
on converting paid sick time to paid leave for family illnesses,
personnel director Michael Gardner said it was unlikely the policy
would change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees can use vacation time, plus any vacation time
(accumulated) from a prior year as well as compensatory time and
personal time for matters such as the care of a relative or family
member, and there also is flex time,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists say the coming elder care explosion will have a
profound impact on working adults, one that will not only test
their emotional and physical stamina but also will likely serve as
a critical measurement of a company's commitment to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Susan Kelley-Grasso, 42. When her mother became too ill
to live alone, she moved into her daughter's single-family home.
Kelley-Grasso relied solely on vacation and sick time when she
needed time off to provide care.
</P>
<P>
   A medical transcriptionist, Kelley-Grasso said being part of a
two-income household helped her meet financial costs. Still, those
months led to tensions on the job. ``I had assumed that because I
worked in a hospital people would understand what I was going
through,'' she said. But her managers didn't understand why her
mother, who was becoming increasingly confused and frail, could not
go to doctors' appointments alone. ``One day I thought I'd bring
her to the office just for a while in case the bus dropped her off
early (from a daycare center),'' said Kelley-Grasso. ``One manager
said, `No.' Then, the other manager said, `People usually ask about
taking their kids to work, but who would ever ask about bringing a
parent to work?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But some companies are helping their employees cope. Nationwide,
68 percent of all employers now offer flexible scheduling
arrangements, up from 53 percent in 1991, according to a 1996 study
by Hewitt Associates, a benefits consulting firm in Lincolnshire,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Muldoon, a senior consultant in BankBoston's work force
effectiveness unit, said the bank expanded its sick time policy
because it didn't want workers lying `` about why they were out or
saying they were sick when they were not. With this policy, they
can simply say my mother or father or child is sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Piktialis, 53, a senior consultant at Ceridian Performance
Partners in Boston, relied on flexible scheduling and paid time off
last year to help her 88-year-old mother, who had cataracts
removed. Then, in October, her mother-in-law, who is 89, was
hospitalized after a fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working in an environment where you can leave when you have to
is incredibly helpful,'' she said. ``You don't have to worry about
being penalized.''
</P>
<P>
   After her father was diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease in 1991,
Kathleen Duffus spent eight years caring for him. Almost overnight,
she became a caregiver while working full-time for a brokerage firm
and attending graduate school. ``So many things would come up
during the week,'' said Duffus, whose father died last year.
``There were emergencies and, for eight years, I saw to them. I
took a lot of time off from work.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duffus was lucky: When her father was evicted from a
nursing home, she received three weeks' paid leave. ``If I had not
received paid leave, I wouldn't have been able to pay my bills,''
said Duffus, now 31 and director of finance for the Alzheimer's
Association of Massachusetts. ``If you are out of work for weeks
without pay, then, on top of all the other issues, you develop a
whole other problem on your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure as a manager at Work Family Directions, a
benefits consulting firm in Brookline, Eleanor Chin could avail
herself of an array of work-family benefits, including paid time
off to care for both her elderly mother _ whose condition requires
doctor visits several times a week _ and her 11-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the sandwich generation, Chin didn't bother to
search for new work after she was laid off last year. Feeling that
few employers would be as flexible as her old boss, Chin launched a
consulting service from her home. ``I have definitely changed my
work so that I can meet my mother's needs and my daughter's
needs,'' she said. ``I've always tried to put myself in flexible
work situations,'' said Chin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, dissatisfaction with the benefits offered by US employers
has led some workplace advocates to push for laws that would offer
some pay to those who need time off to care for a parent. Most are
lobbying for temporary disability insurance that would cover elder
and child care and other wage replacement measures. So far only
five states offer temporary disability insurance that extends to
care of family members: New York, New Jersey, California, Rhode
Island, and Hawaii. These five states account for 22 percent of the
nation's private work force.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, five bills have been filed relating to paid
family leave, including two that would tap into the vast reserves
of the unemployment compensation fund to offer those who take leave
50 percent of their weekly wage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-05 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT RECOVERY PROVES WELCOME SIGHT FOR INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We could hardly believe our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Summit Technology Inc., the maker of vision-correcting lasers
flattened by self-inflicted disaster three years ago, has been
staging a furious stock rally to reclaim a good piece of its lost
value.
</P>
<P>
   Summit shares plunged from over 30 to below 4 in 1996 and stayed
in that neighborhood for more than two years. Suddenly, the story
changed and Summit stock has soared from 5 9/16 just six weeks ago
to 16 7/16 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sparks: improved performance benefiting from a hot market
and a promising turnaround plan, completion of an important
acquisition, and a broader following among investors.
</P>
<P>
   But what counts most is the rapidly growing popularity of the
medical procedure, available for several years, that uses lasers to
reshape a patient's cornea and improve or restore poor vision to
the point where eyeglasses and contact lenses are no longer needed.
The procedures, which are not covered by insurance, cost patients
about $2,000 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   Summit reports the number of procedures performed with its
lasers increased during the first quarter by 31 percent over the
previous three months and by 81 percent compared with the same
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at US Bancorp Piper Jaffray recently jacked up their
1999 estimates for all vision-correcting laser procedures to
865,511 from 755,464. They forecast the number will grow to 1.3
million next year.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Summit and just one other laser company own
nearly all of the US market, and each one of them collects a fee of
about $250 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: Summit, once the leader in its field, is now a
distant second. Competitor Visx Inc. controls about 75 percent of
the market, leaving less than 20 percent for Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Visx shareholders have made out better than anyone amid the
booming forecasts for procedure growth. Their stock has jumped from
21 last October to as high as 137 5/32. It closed Tuesday at 121
7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Summit may be behind now, but the outlook for the Waltham, Mass.
company was drastically worse two years ago. The company's business
practices, finances, and even technology came under fire as
Summit's shares plunged. Cofounder and chairman David Muller was
ousted by the board. A stolen US Food and Drug Administration
report on Visx that somehow made its way onto Muller's desk did not
help.
</P>
<P>
   There was another serious, longer term problem. Summit's
business strategy of operating 19 company vision centers, where
procedures were conducted, put the company at odds with the doctors
who were also its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company had a very bad reputation with doctors,'' said
Robert Palmisano, a former Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. executive who became
Summit's chief executive in 1997. ``There were a variety of
reasons, not the least of which was going into competition with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Visx got an important upper hand by winning
more FDA approvals for specific laser procedures. Visx equipment
came to be seen as superior and could be used on more patients.
Summit was a wobbly number two, at best.
</P>
<P>
   Summit has since ditched the vision centers and Palmisano
organized a sales force that emphasizes medical support and
practice-building help for physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of laser systems fell from about $500,000 to less than
$300,000. Both Summit and Visx saw the per-procedure fee as a
better way of making money. They pushed to get more equipment out
in the field or upgrade machines already in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a razor-blade deal in that we were willing
to give up a lot of the profit on the equipment so that we can get
procedures done,'' said Palmisano.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Summit closed on its $46.8 million acquisition of
Autonomous Technologies Corp. that may give the company a leg up on
new laser technology. Meanwhile, FDA approval already in the works
for Summit to perform procedures on more patients will probably put
the company on equal regulatory footing with Visx before the end of
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But business improvements aside, are Summit shares really worth
the prices they have reached in recent weeks? The stock now trades
at well over 100 times year 2000 earnings estimates by analysts who
like Summit.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems to boot: Summit's final turnaround isn't a
certainty and new competitors are sure to climb into the US market
eventually. Another sight-improving method that does not involve
lasers was approved by the FDA earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who recommend Summit stock use the same line that
propels Internet issues: You can't use conventional methods to
value this investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need to take a different approach,'' said analyst
Robert Faulkner of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``I think you need to make an
assessment of what this technology is worth.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of that argument: measure Visx's stock value and
divide it by the firm's market share, then do the same thing for
Summit.
</P>
<P>
   The math will suggest Summit is trading at a 40 percent discount
to the Visx stock value. Faulkner and analyst Francesca Migliori of
US Bancorp Piper Jaffray say Visx stock deserves some premium, but
not that much.
</P>
<P>
   But what if Visx shares are overpriced? Using a stock that has
advanced sixfold in less than seven months is an aggressive
yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Summit) business model itself is credible and
believable,'' said one analyst who declined to be identified.
``It's a matter of valuation. I'm thinking there might be some
takeover premium in the price of the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-KIDDER-ART-BOS     05-05 1778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KIDDER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACY KIDDER FINDS INSPIRATION IN WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON _ It's lunchtime at the Miss Florence Diner, and
Tracy Kidder heaves a happy sigh as he slides into a corner booth.
``This place at 4 a.m. is great,'' he announces. ``Of course, I
never would have come here at 4 o'clock in the morning before
working on this book.''
</P>
<P>
   He's referring to ``Home Town,'' his sixth book and something of
a departure for Kidder. Instead of the tightly defined narratives
that made him famous _ designing a computer in ``The Soul of a New
Machine'' (1981), say, or building a new home in ``House'' (1985) _
he presents a broad cross section of life as found in this small
Western Massachusetts city.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder, 53, became acquainted with the diner in its pre-dawn
incarnation during the course of many nights researching ``Home
Town'' in the company of Northampton police sergeant Tommy
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   It's O'Connor who provides Kidder with his narrative spine.
(What doesn't a cop get to see in a small city?) He also
demonstrates Kidder's special knack for finding remarkable people
to write about. O'Connor more than holds his own in a lineup that
includes Tom West, the Zen-master computer guru of ``Soul''; the
perfectionist carpenters of ``House''; Chris Zajac, the devoted
schoolteacher of ``Among Schoolchildren'' (1989); and Lou and Joe,
the retirement-home roommates of ``Old Friends'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all O'Connor's star power, Kidder's real protagonist in
``Home Town'' is Northampton itself. And there's no better way to
see it than with a Kidder's-eye view from the passenger seat of his
Lexus sedan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These fields belong to the Smith Vocational Farm. Realtors
like to point out the cow herd. Yet we're within walking distance
of downtown. You know, it's almost like Northampton's a perfect
little kingdom. It's got its own hospital. It's got a county
courthouse. It's got a college. It's got its own little waterfront
down by the river. It's got its own little airport. It's like one
of those towns in a Hardy Boys mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sociology is not what I'm out to write. I wanted to write
interesting stories,'' Kidder says of ``Home Town.'' ``Here's a
small town of just 30,000 people _ but it's as complicated as the
circuits of the human brain. I wanted to give some sense of the
complexity of it and the sort of delight in that complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that complexity is historical. Jonathan Edwards preached
in Northampton. Calvin Coolidge was mayor. Nancy Reagan and Barbara
Bush, as well as Betty Friedan and Sylvia Plath, attended Smith
College. The graham cracker and the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles
were invented here.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that complexity is social. Thanks to the presence of
Smith, Northampton's a classic New England college town: a citadel
of natural-fiber/NPR chic. There's a thriving arts community, and
designer coffee is easier to come by downtown than a wrench or
screwdriver. Not that Northampton lacks for buyers of wrenches and
screwdrivers. It has a long mill-town tradition, and there are
still working factories here. Noho (yuppie Northampton) and Hamp
(townie Northampton) peacefully coexist, but fault lines aren't
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith kind of bleeds into the town. This is Paradise Pond. The
president's house is over there. This is quite a great school. It's
been harmed by its reputation as being almost entirely populated by
real, in-your-face lesbians. It's not true, but I don't think
they've dealt very well with it. The administration, I don't know,
there are ways in which what Smith does and does not spend money on
just astonishes me . . . Here are the Smith riding stables below
us. You talk about mixing of symbols of social class? We're about
90 seconds from the Grove Street Inn, the homeless shelter in the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``House,'' Kidder describes a carpenter's surveying
instrument as ``a tool for imposing levelness on an irregular
world.'' He might just as well be talking about what he does in his
books. He brings literary order to the chaos of some small corner
of life, making of facts a kind of poetry of existence. Perhaps
only John McPhee, whom Kidder reveres, has a greater reputation as
a practitioner of nonfiction narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracy Kidder is a great storyteller,'' says Northampton mayor
Mary Ford. She says this as one who has been on the receiving end
of his abilities (Ford makes several appearances in ``Home Town'').
``He certainly caught me at some moments I wish he hadn't caught
me,'' she says with a chuckle, ``but they're real, so I can't
quarrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people like to tell stories. Others like to listen to them.
Kidder is among the few equally good at both. He has a
sweet-natured, open manner that seems pleasingly at variance with
his big shoulders and loafy forearms. (Kidder and O'Connor got to
know each other through working out at the same gym.)
</P>
<P>
   He speaks in a slightly out-of-breath tenor, and the words come
in eager bursts. ``I have these very vivid memories of Tracy
bounding down the hill at the building site,'' recalls William
Rawn, the Boston architect who figures prominently in ``House,''
and ``to bound'' may be the key Tracy Kidder verb. Even when
seated, he gives the impression of generally being on the way from
Point A to Point B. ``I've always run around,'' he confesses,
``moving too fast from one thing to another.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Another item in the perfect little kingdom, it has its own
jail, with the prettiest view _ and the worst _ in the whole
county. Like a lot of things in Northampton, it's very desirable
(as jails go). The superintendent showed me the sheaf of letters he
gets every week from inmates throughout the state asking for a
transfer. Part of it was Northampton allowed smoking. Look at this
view: There's the Holyoke Range all before you, yet behind us is no
place you'd want to spend June _ and from in there you don't get
the view.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kidder lives in Williamsburg, a 20-minute drive from downtown
Northampton, with his wife, who's an artist. They have two
children: a son, who lives in San Francisco and works for a large
clothing firm; and a daugther, who's a junior at Brown. Kidder
comes into Northampton often, ``at least a couple of times a week,
and often more,'' to shop and run errands. He's come to cherish the
place, though he didn't always feel that way. ``I had a girlfriend
at Smith when I was in college _ and I couldn't wait to get out of
here. It seemed like such a dingy, dull town.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Oyster Bay, N.Y., and part of his appreciation for
Northampton and environs stems from the fact that ``most of Long
Island has disappeared under a cloverleaf.'' Kidder graduated from
Harvard and then spent a year in Vietnam, as a lieutenant in Army
intelligence. ``There was combat all around us, but we weren't in
it,'' he says. ``I was a pretty bad soldier, to tell you the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return, Kidder wrote a novel ``about the experiences I
didn't have in Vietnam.'' It remains unpublished. He attended the
University of Iowa Writers' Workshop, where one of his teachers was
Atlantic Monthly contributing editor Dan Wakefield. Kidder began
writing for the magazine (he has himself been a contributing editor
since 1982). An assignment to cover the Juan Corona mass-murder
trial in California led to his first book, ``The Road to Yuba
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1976, came the move to Williamsburg. ``We
were broke, basically, and trying to find a decent place to live.''
Kidder's credit rating significantly improved with the publication
of ``Soul.'' It became an enormous bestseller, won a Pulitzer
Prize, and remains Kidder's best-known book.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Soul'' not only eased Kidder's financial
concerns. It allowed him to stay close to home. The ``House''
carpenters are neighbors of his. ``Among Schoolchildren'' is set in
Holyoke, just down Interstate 91. Linda Manor, the ``Old Friends''
retirement home, is on the road from Williamsburg to downtown
Northampton. ``I'm making my own Yoknapatawpha County here,''
Kidder says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's downtown, with all these wonderful 19th-century
buildings: urban renewal just totally missed this place, thank God.
Yes, it looks boutiquey. A lot of coffee is sold, and what's sold
with that coffee is a beautiful downtown where people think they
used to live or would like to have lived. This place is packed with
people who want something you can't get in a mall. It's sort of a
mild freak show _ certainly mild compared to Berkeley, say. But
it's quite entertaining, and Northampton has a very lively night
life for a town its size.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The origins of ``Home Town'' lie in Haiti, which Kidder visited
in 1994 for The New Yorker. ``I just remember being there and
seeing a place where almost nothing worked. I started thinking
about how (Northampton) was a place that seemed to work very well
indeed, and I wondered why . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was a little hesitant. First, I thought, what is there
really going to be to tell about a town that's so comely and
successful that won't be the standard historical-society sort of
thing? I was talking to O'Connor, and he said to me, `You don't
remember me, do you?' I said no, and he said that he'd stopped me
for speeding five years ago and given me a ticket. I did remember
it then. He'd said `Have a nice day,' and when he was done I wanted
to choke him! The reason I certainly remembered this was he stopped
my wife the same day and didn't give her a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, he said `Why don't you come out riding with me in the
cruiser one night and I'll show you a Northampton you never knew
existed.' . . . I said sure, and he was as good as his word. It was
like some of the roofs came off: I suddenly saw a town that didn't
seem as simple, or as uniformly agreeable, as it had before.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's an FBI agent now and lives in Washington, D.C. As for
Kidder, he's in no hurry to move from Yoknapatawpha North. ``There
have been times when I've thought I was bored with it and wanted to
live in someplace like New York or Boston or San Francisco, but
every time I go traveling and come back here I feel so relieved.''
For once, he's fully at rest, with not a hint of bounding. ``It's
been a nice place to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
