</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSTITUTION-COPY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE COPY OF US CONSTITUTION TO GO ON DISPLAY IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After weeks of debating a draft of a new constitution,
delegates to the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia
appointed a committee on style to prepare a final version in
September 1787.
</P>
<P>
   Gouverneur Morris did most of the work and on Sept. 17, after
several more days of revision, it was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 500 copies of the final text had been secretly ordered
from a printer for distribution to the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only nine of those copies still exist. One of them will
be on display in the new federal courthouse in Boston for at least
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The rare copy of the final text is the only one that will be
readily accessible to the public. The eight others are in private
or public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the copy being loaned to the Boston courthouse,
Doroth Tapper Goldman of New Canaan, Conn., said US Supreme Court
Justice Stephen G. Breyer, a friend and former federal appellate
judge in Boston, urged her to display the historic, six-page
document here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an admirable document that has enabled us to survive 200
years of differences in race, national origin, and religion,''
Breyer said in a rare phone interview from his chambers in the
Supreme Court. ``These differences are resolved in court, and I see
that, I see it, sitting on my bench because it is happening in
front of me every day.
</P>
<P>
   The precious document will be on exhibit beginning Sept. 17,
Constitution Day, in the second-floor rotunda of the courthouse on
Fan Pier. It will be the focus of an education program by the
Boston Bar Association and the Harvard Graduate School of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   US Court of Appeals Judge Sandra L. Lynch said the exhibit will
provide tourists, students and teachers an opportunity to read the
Constitution and then walk into any courtroom to see it in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can watch judges handle constitutional issues like the
right to a jury trial, habeas corpus, the commerce clause,'' said
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch and Chief US District Judge William G. Young hope the
exhibit will make visitors more familiar with the structure of our
government and clear up ``fundamental misconceptions'' about how it
operates.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she said, a recent poll shows that 39 percent of
the public erroneously believe a defendant has the burden of
proving his innocence in court.
</P>
<P>
   The copies printed for the delegates gave the general public the
first glimpse of the details of the proposed new government.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Leventhal, co-chairwoman of the Boston Bar Association's
Constitution project, said an allotment of copies was given to each
of the 55 convention delegates to take home, circulate among
friends and colleagues, debate, reprint and read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was used for teaching then, and we are going to use it
again to teach,'' Leventhal said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1787, Leventhal said Benjamin Franklin ordered extra
copies sent to Massachusetts because of the strong initial
resistance to the Constitution here _ a position based on the lack
of a bill of rights, which was not adopted until later.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Constitution, which predates the federal
version, begins with its own Declaration of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jacob Shallus' famous handwritten signed parchment of the
US Constitution on display at the National Archives in Washington,
the copies were printed on cotton pages, which are more durable,
Leventhal said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's copy was purchased by her late husband, New York real
estate developer S. Howard Goldman, for $175,000 at a Sotheby's
auction in 1988. She said she has traced it back through private
hands about 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want younger adults and older adults to have an authentic
experience with an original document,'' said Goldman, a Tufts
graduate who lived in the Boston area for 29 years. ``I find it
very exciting every time I look at it. Perhaps it was one of the
copies that was read in front of Independence Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's ties to Boston go back to 1961 as a law student at
Harvard University and later as a Harvard professor. He sat on the
federal Appeals Court in Boston for 13 years until being named to
the Supreme Court in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As the former chief judge of the US Court of Appeals for the
First Circuit, Breyer was instrumental in developing a new federal
courthouse for Boston. By his own account, he became obsessed with
making it ``perfect'' and was intimately involved with every detail
of its conception and construction.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer, 60, who jokes that he is just now beginning to feel like
a full-fledged Bostonian after all these years, says the city
steeped in the founding of this country is the perfect home for the
document.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is the place that for 200 years has itself embodied
these ideas,'' Breyer says. ``It is the city on the hill, it looks
out toward the seas, it has always had a history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
