<HEADLINE>
SALB KEEPS HER SHOTS ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Amanda Salb heads to Williams College for the ECAC track
and field championships this weekend, she will take with her the
longest throw in the nation (45 feet, 3 3/4 inches) this season for
Division III shot put. She will take with her the 1998 Div. III
national championship. She will take with her the New England Div.
III championship she won last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What the Mount Holyoke senior won't take with her, said coach
Tina Lee, is an ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very humble woman,'' said Lee. ``That's part of what
makes her so good to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say the 21-year-old Salb, from rural Arkansas, was
born to be great. Her father, after all, is Karl Salb, a six-time
NCAA champion shot-putter for the University of Kansas in the late
1960s and early '70s. Her mother, Jessie, threw the shot, too, in
college: that's how her parents met. But mostly, said Lee, Salb is
good because ``she's very hungry, not to be a national champion but
to do her best.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the first Mount Holyoke woman ever to win an
individual NCAA Div. III championship was hardly determined to
compete for the Lyons. When she was still in high school and got
the first brochure in the mail, her reaction was, ``It's a women's
college! Omigod! And I threw it away. But the second or third one I
got, I started to look at it.'' After Salb and her mother drove up
to see the campus and she learned the school had a strong program
in biology, she was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Salb is set to get her degree on May 23, the
day after she gets back from defending her NCAA shot put title at
the national championships in Berea, Ohio. She will leave South
Hadley not only as an All-American in track and field, but also as
the school's all-time leader in rebounds and steals in basketball,
where she played center/forward. After graduation, she will head to
an internship at the Wildlife Center of Virginia, where she will
spend the summer as an animal caretaker before going on to
veterinary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't really thought about it,'' said Salb, when asked if
she would continue with track and field after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, definitely,'' said her coach, when asked if Salb had the
talent to compete nationally at the post-collegiate level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides being very strong, there's her speed,'' said Lee.
``She has that internal fire that a coach can't dictate, can't
measure. That's what made her get to where she is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: volunteers
</P>
<P>
   The folks organizing the Women's World Cup in Foxborough are
looking for volunteers. Drivers (you must be at least 21),
ambassadors, and other helpers minimum age: 14) are needed. Games
will be played at Foxboro Stadium on June 20 and 27 and July 4. For
an application, call Don Mauch, the venue staffing manager, at
508-384-9217. Although 60,000 tickets have already been sold for
the five games to be played at Foxboro, seats still remain. Call
800-WWC-TIKS for individual tickets, 877-GET-REVS for groups of 30
or more or for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mad Dog goes coed
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Mad Dogs professional baseball team is adding
a woman to its roster. The Mad Dogs, based in Lynn, have signed
Tammy Holmes an outfielder who played with the now defunct Colorado
Silver Bullets. Holmes, who led the team in batting average (.341)
and RBIs (42), was on the volleyball team at the University of
California at Davis, and was trying to earn a spot in the ABL
before it folded. The Mad Dogs open their fourth season on May 28
at Fraser Field in Lynn against the Allentown (Pa.) Ambassadors . .
. Ireland's Catherina McKiernan plans to make her American marathon
debut at the LaSalle Banks Chicago Marathon on Oct. 24. It will be
her fourth marathon, after winning her first three. McKiernan's
personal-best time is 2 hours, 22 minutes, and 23 seconds, the
seventh-fastest in history . . . Sarah Russell, the Harvard
basketball standout who also founded a community service program
for varsity athletes, was recently named winner of the Harvard
College Women's Leadership Award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Bickelhaupt of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
