<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERING UP TOP-DRAWER MUSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emptying Out The Desk Drawer of the Sports Mind . . .
</P>
<P>
   What's Wrong With Sports Dept.: You know and I know that there
isn't one kid among the top 100 high school basketball players who
would list Joe Dumars among his top five favorite players, and yet
there isn't a single player in the NBA more worthy of emulation,
both on and off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-astute Elaine Ryan says they should not have bothered
to play an NBA season, and she happens to be 100 percent correct.
</P>
<P>
   If I ran a club on Lansdowne Street, I'd try to hire that Cuban
second base umpire as my chief bouncer, pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Griffey's gonna hit 60, and it will be like being the
third man on the moon. But whether he hits 50, 55, or 60, he is the
best player in the game; you know.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Drew: Larry mangled his index finger even worse before he
played a day of pro ball, and he did reasonably OK. You can just
forget that second career as a hand model.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens may have set himself up to be bashed a bit by the
many contradictory things he has said, but wasn't a big issue in
the Joe Morgan era the fact that Clemens was regularly throwing
130-140 pitches a game and refusing to come out?
</P>
<P>
   If Lamar Odom doesn't come out, stop worrying about Cleveland
having Rick Pitino's No. 1 pick. There's nobody else worth crying
about.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL should have gone to two referees 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the NBA playoffs come, underestimate San Antonio, and
especially the better-than-you-think Avery Johnson, at your peril.
</P>
<P>
   The real story coming out of the Patriots stadium saga is that
it underscores the truly pathetic way our commonwealth does
business. I say this just in case you missed Joan Vennochi's
brilliant take on the matter on Tuesday's op-ed page.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like a textbook example of Yankee imperialism, take a
look at what we've done to the helpless Canadian cities trying to
compete in their sport.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever had a better day than the late Joe Adcock did on
July 31, 1954, in Ebbets Field: 18 total bases via four home runs
and a line-drive double that missed going out by a foot. He also
was the first man to plant one in the Polo Grounds bleachers. Had
to be the best player ever to come out of Coushatta, La.
</P>
<P>
   He may have started his dominance a tad too late, but if he
keeps doing what he's been doing for four or five more years (he's
33), Craig Biggio could be in the midst of a Hall of Fame career.
Betcha didn't know he's averaged 126 runs a year since '95 (to go
with 88 in strike-shortened '94).
</P>
<P>
   Someone who just came back from hanging out with the Cubs tells
me Sammy Sosa is muy gordo. You know, one too many cheese
enchiladas during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   This just in. Mike Ditka has finalized his personal services
arrangement with Ricky Williams. Mon. _ Drives kid to work. Tue.
(the standard day off) _ Mows lawn. Wed. _ Shines shoes. Thu. _
Does the marketing. Fri. _ Cleans the house. Sat. _ Answers
correspondence. Sun. _ Gives ball 35 times.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, I can see Larry Bird returning to civilian life
next year. And Kevin McHale makes two.
</P>
<P>
   Our dour GM was right. Jose Offerman most certainly has replaced
Mo's on-base capability. Now, Duke, about Part B . . .
</P>
<P>
   The ever-charming Albert Belle showed his disdain for Peter
Angelos's attempt at international diplomacy by watching 11
straight pitches go by in successive ABs, being called out on
strikes each time.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Melrose, Barry Melrose, where is your hair?
</P>
<P>
   OK, Messrs. Jacobs and Krezwick: It's Year 4 of the Fleet and
we're still waiting for some photos and murals and, you know, stuff
on the walls to let people know they're in the home of the 16-time
world champion Celtics and a Bruins franchise that has given us
Shore, Schmidt, and Orr. Oh, I forgot. The good stuff's all in
``Legends,'' isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   No one ever has worn the backup QB mantle more comfortably than
Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins fans, just what you don't want to hear: The Great Gretzky
says he hated Ulf Samuelsson when he played against him, but that
the chippy Swede turned out to be ``the best teammate I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   A Dumars addendum: A big issue in his draft ('85) was which one
of four perceived equal guard prospects did you like between 15 and
25. Dumars went 18th to Detroit. The others? Steve Harris (19th,
Houston), Terry Porter (24th, Portland), and Sam Vincent (20th,
Boston). Two big hits, two bad misses. Never doubt that the entire
enterprise is anything other than an inexact science.
</P>
<P>
   When Duke starts losing 'em early to the NBA draft, college
basketball as we know it is over.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who the best quarterback of all-time was, but I
don't get this full-fledged Joe Montana adulation, when it was
quite clear he was a ``system'' quarterback, and neither a Dan
Marino pure passer nor a John Elway athlete. Out of context, there
are plenty of guys I'd take over Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Mr. King. You couldn't have called the book, ``The Girl
Who Loved Mariano Rivera,'' could you?
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken says he's baffled by the public's desire for input on
his ``private'' decision to retire or not to retire, but he wasn't
objecting when that same public rallied to his cause at various
contract times, did he? For what it's worth, Cal, people would
rather not see you looking old and feeble.
</P>
<P>
   My solution to this Kosovo mess: lock Pat Burns in a room with
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
