<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIZZLY VETERAN HELPS YOUNG BRUINS BEARD PLAYOFF FOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They are a Gillette salesman's dream. They are
two-blade, three-blade, four-blade tough. They are enough to make
the director of razor blade engineering call in Edward Scissorhands
for a secret consultation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have made it through the first round of the playoffs
and victory is written all over their faces, in the form of beards,
goatees, mustaches, and some unreasonable facsimiles. They are in
character, playoff face, maintaining the tradition that says real
men don't shave when it comes time to chase the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not like Grizzly Adams over there,'' said Kyle McLaren,
comparing his sparse beard to the thick blanket that covers Ray
Bourque's face. ``It's just tradition. Playoff beards . . . or, for
some of us, facial hair.''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Axelsson is among the follicly challenged, the
beard-impaired. The 24-year-old Swede has joined this hair club for
men, but it takes a close look to make sure he hasn't had a close
shave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun thing,'' said Axelsson, adding that the same
tradition lives on in Europe, too, when elite teams enter the
playoffs. ``There's nothing wrong with it, but I don't think I'll
keep it when I'm finished.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Bourque's 20th season, his 19th playoff tour. The Round
1 clincher over Carolina Sunday night was his 174th postseason
game. He has grown playoff beards short and long, the Bruins making
it to the Cup finals twice in his tenure, which makes him somewhat
of an expert on this, shall we say, growth industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I like the idea, some days I don't,'' he said,
following Tuesday's workout here. ``I'm always thinking, `OK, do I
shave it after every series? What should I do here, trim it, carve
it, what?' I think I'm going to be trimming it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is now 38 years old, and splashes of gray dapple Bourque's
springtime beard. Silver circles the size of half-dollars have
sprouted up halfway down his cheeks. His chin is flecked with
silver. The baby-faced kid who arrived here in '79 may play like a
teen-ager, but his playoff beard tells the undeniable truth, that
age catches up to all of us.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Bourque has carried a photographic image in his
head, a snapshot of what he would look like if his Bruins won the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He would be holding it. Click.
</P>
<P>
   He would be hugging it. Click.
</P>
<P>
   He would lifting it high, passing it to teammates, shaking it
madly. Click. Click. Click.
</P>
<P>
   And his cheeks, said Bourque, would be sunken. The picture
wouldn't hide that. The beard wouldn't disguise it. To win 16 games
across April and May and June would leave a man looking emaciated,
battle-worn, the Cup a true testimony to the pound(s) of flesh it
extracted.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday morning, a quarter of that photo has developed.
The Bruins need 12 more victories to land their first Cup since
1972. Bourque's chances of seeing that mental image someday being
portrayed in print or on video have dwindled. He has this playoff
season, maybe another, but maybe not. Maybe this is all there is.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque looks around the dressing room now and sees kids like
Hal Gill, Anson Carter, Sergei Samsonov, and refers to the Bruins
as ``their team.'' He doesn't have to look in the mirror and see
Father Time's silver thumbprints to know the future. Time is
passing. So, too, is the torch.
</P>
<P>
   In all the jubilation Sunday night, in the moments immediately
following the series triumph over Carolina, some subtle but telling
humor played out on the ice. The kids in the Black 'n' Gold
uniforms didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of us went over and said our piece to (Byron Dafoe),''
recalled Gill, now finishing up only his second season. ``You know,
we said the usual stuff, `Hey, great job, great job, how to go.'
Then a bunch of us just stood there and looked at each other and
wondered, `OK, what do we do now? Do we shake hands? Do we go back
to the bench? Do we leave?' ''
</P>
<P>
   After two decades, Bourque knows the end-of-series drill. He was
the one who finally commandeered the kids and moved them through
the line, the way an uncle would nudge a niece or nephew through a
wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' recalled Bourque. ``They were just standing
there and I'm like, `It's all right, guys, go shake hands now.'
You've got the Carolina guys out there at center ice, just
standing, and nothing's happening, and you could tell they were
thinking, `Uh, you know, we'd like to get out of here.' Hey's it's
the first time for a lot of our guys. They don't know, they have to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they know, now that they've got some idea of how good
playing hockey can feel this late into the season, Bourque the good
shepherd wants them to let the feeling go, grow with it. In '88 and
'90, it led to trips to the finals. Those were the days when the
Bruins were postseason shoo-ins and strong playoff runs, though by
no means absolute, weren't unexpected. No one stood around when a
series was won and looked to the captain for a primer on victor's
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next series, they'll know,'' said Bourque. ``That's the
best part about this right now: When you find out how good it is to
win, how great it feels, you miss it if you're not in it. You win
and you realize the urgency of it. It's why you're here. You
realize the importance of making it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guys have to taste that to know it. It's why it was so
important for us to win a series like that. Last year, we played
great in that series against Washington, but we had nothing to show
for it. They found out then that close isn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's opening series provided hints that something good
could happen, perhaps sooner rather than later. The Bruins will
face a better goaltender in the next series, and a more refined
offense, but Bourque hopes his young, emerging teammates, the
future stars of the team, don't sit back now and think that their
true chance to win will come in some later Thursday. They're here,
they're in it, and the last five years serve as proof that there
are only so many opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the ups and downs, the grinding, that make you grow,
that make you better,'' said the captain. ``This is their team.
There are a lot of young guys here, key guys, who are going to make
up this team for a lot of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Round 2 is about to begin. The Bruins finished off the
Hurricanes with three straight victories, the first time they've
won three in a row in a series since polishing off the Canadiens in
the second round in '92.
</P>
<P>
   The kids are coming into their own. Their goalie is a sure
thing. Can they be considered a favorite in any series the rest of
the way? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   But the oldest, wisest, and grayest beard among them doesn't
believe .
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to realize that it is their team now,'' said
Bourque. ``and that they don't have to wait a couple of years to
make something out of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
