<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PIZZELLE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     05-05 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIZZELLE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 SOMERVILLE, Mass.: ... drying rack.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her mother's recipes turned out to be notes. She used coffee
cups and soupspoons to measure ingredients. ``The hardest part was
getting her recipes to come out the way she made them,'' says
Sullivan. Her mother used a 2-pound container of ricotta for her
ricotta pie. The original instructions said something like: ``Add
as much flour as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, she says, ``I made Easter bread about 50 times
before I got it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the recipes Ferri had learned from her Roman
sisters-in-law evolved into easier dishes, a change reflected in
the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worked,'' says Sullivan. ``You take many shortcuts when
you start working.'' A pasta e fagioli, for instance, the pasta and
bean dish, is made with canned beans and canned tomato sauce. ``If
she had leftover tomato sauce, she would use it,'' says Sullivan,
``but if she didn't, well, off to the supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   On holidays, there might be 20 people around the table. A
typical Sunday dinner table would be laid end to end with pork
roast or chicken, broccoli rabe, stuffed peppers, eggplant
Parmesan, artichokes, and pasta. Ferri was famous for her ricotta
gnocchi and spinach ravioli.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed close to her sisters-in-law. For holiday meals, they
cooked together and each also made more food at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ferri's pizzelle, of course, were always on the menu. And she
still seems to run a private bakery. A granddaughter visits and
goes home with a tin. So does anyone from out of town. She gives
pizzelle to a friend who drives her somewhere. The neighbor who
shovels her front walk finds a batch on his doorstep later that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend calls at 7 a.m.,'' says Ferri. ``I make three-egg
pizzelle. I'm done by 7:30.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, Ma. You make the best pizzelle anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JENNIE FERRI'S PIZZELLE
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 sticks margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat the eggs and sugar. Add the melted
margarine (which is cool but not hard). Add the vanilla. Sift
together the flour and baking powder, and add to the egg mixture,
stirring until fully absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the pizzelle iron until hot (approximately 15 minutes). If
the iron is not hot enough, the dough will stick. Drop a small ball
of dough into the center of the iron. Close the lid and wait about
20 seconds. The dough should be cooked and golden brown when the
lid is lifted. Remove from the grid.
</P>
<P>
   Drop a scant tablespoon in the center of the grid for each
pizzelle. Each one should take approximately 45 seconds to cook.
(You may need to experiment with your particular pizzelle machine
to get the right length of time for each one). Store in an airtight
container to keep crisp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
RISOTTO
</P>
<P>
   Unlike northern Italian risotto seen on menus now, this southern
version is a layered dish in which rice, tomato sauce, tiny
meatballs, and cheese are baked together. It hardly requires any
attention from the cook. ``This is the way my aunts taught my
mother to do it,'' says Vilma Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups rice, uncooked
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (approximately) tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tiny meatballs (see recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces scamorza or mozzarella cheese, shredded or thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Romano or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Boil 5 cups of water. Add the rice and cook until all the water
is absorbed, about 25 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a large casserole, pour about 1/2 cup of the tomato sauce and
spread to cover the base of the dish. Pour in a third of the rice.
Spread the tiny meatballs and mozzarella over the rice and add more
sauce. Sprinkle a third of the grated Romano on top. Layer the rice
and other ingredients until all are in the casserole, ending with
the spaghetti sauce and cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a 350-degree oven for 30 minutes or until the cheese
melts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
TINY MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Italian bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Place the ground beef in a medium bowl. Add the remaining
ingredients and mix well. Roll into tiny balls about 1/2 inch in
diameter _ approximately 1/2 teaspoon of the mixture. (Wetting your
hands with water will help to keep the mixture from clinging to
your skin.) Fry in olive oil over medium heat, browning all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 35 to 40 meatballs.
</P>
</TEXT>
