<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PIZZELLE-2TAKES-     05-05 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIZZELLE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIZZELLE FROM NANA'S KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERVILLE, Mass. _ The pizzelle irons are wrapped in crinkly
plastic supermarket bags and stored in the back pantry. There are
several of them, but Giovanna ``Jennie'' Loverro Ferri, age 99,
really likes only one, and that's the iron her daughter pulls out
and unwraps. It's about 30 years old and has been repaired many
times. Once, when her daughter took it to Cross Hardware in the
North End to get it fixed, the store etched her name and the date
(1971) on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Ferri has already made the batter for the pizzelle
(peat-ZEL-le), a crisp Italian pastry. She used three eggs. ``My
mother doesn't use recipes,'' says Vilma Sullivan. ``She goes by
the number of eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six eggs?'' Ferri had asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Ma, three's enough,'' answered Sullivan. Six eggs would
have produced so many thin, sugary, vanilla-scented rounds, they
could have served
</P>
<P>
   NANA, Page E4 &QL; 
most of their Somerville neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Ferri returned the six-egg bowl to its hook in the pantry
and pulled off the three-egg bowl. In loafers and sweat pants, her
cane propped on the back of a chair, she began a pizzelle lesson
that she could probably give in her sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Ferri will turn 100 on June 24, and since her retirement in the
late '60s from her job as a raincoat stitcher for Byron Clothing in
Davis Square, Ferri has baked almost every single day. She shares a
two-family house with her daughter Vilma and son-in-law Eugene
Sullivan. She has poor hearing and macular degeneration, and she
has suffered from arthritis in her back and legs since the age of
40. But she's agile enough to stand and cook for hours. For Easter,
she made ricotta pie, lasagna, and of course pizzelle. Two weeks
ago, it was a pot of chicken soup. Last week, she made her famous
gnocchi.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't cook much this winter, because she fell in Florida in
February and her leg was too swollen to stand on. But all the
health aides and nurses are gone now, and she has resumed normal
life.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoons are reserved for Oprah. Mornings she bakes.
</P>
<P>
   Vilma Sullivan is the assistant. ``I need the egg beater,'' says
Ferri.
</P>
<P>
   ``The egg beater or the mixer, Ma?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Egg beater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This, Ma?'' asks Sullivan. She holds up the mixer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You said the egg beater.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferri shrugs. She breaks the eggs against each other to crack
them into the bowl. Next she pours in a melted stick of Promise
margarine from another bowl.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the margarine bowl is empty, Ferri moves it to the
far corner of the table. Sullivan whisks it away. ``She is Mrs.
Clean,'' Sullivan whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Ferri adds 3/4 cup of sugar to the bowl, then uses the electric
mixer to beat the mixture until it is thick and smooth. She
measures 1 1/2 cups of flour and sifts it into another bowl, then
beats it in with 1 teaspoon of vanilla extract. The mixture is
about the consistency of pancake batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the eggs are too small,'' she says, ``you put in a little
more flour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma, you didn't make these in Italy, right?'' Sullivan
practically has to shout. Her mother can't wear a hearing aid
because of tinnitus, a form of nerve damage that causes ringing in
her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never made pizzelle in Italy,'' Ferri says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's family came from Rome,'' explains Sullivan, ``and
my mother's siblings did not live here then.'' So she learned to
cook from her husband's sisters, who lived near her in Gardner.
``She doesn't cook like a Barese,'' says Sullivan. ``She cooks more
like a Roman. The food is worlds apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Ferri was born in 1900 in Cassano Murge in the province
of Bari, near the ankle of the boot-shaped Italy, a region
surrounded by mountains. She was the third of seven children born
to a coppersmith who had a little shop in the town of 7,000
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Her father decided to bring his family to America and left
before them to get settled. During his absence, the children were
playing where they shouldn't have been and there was an accident
that changed everything. ``It was in a building across the
street,'' explains Ferri. ``Someplace where you washed clothes.
They put lye in the clothing. My sister reached over the basin and
it blew up and blinded her. She was 8 or 9 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   So their father returned to Italy and stayed there, Ferri says,
because US Immigration wouldn't accept her sister and he wouldn't
leave her behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always with my father,'' says Ferri.
</P>
<P>
   ``She means she was her father's favorite,'' explains Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   When Ferri was 19, she asked her father if she could go to
America. ``He said no.''
</P>
<P>
   She went anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanna Loverro married Umberto ``Albert'' Ferri in 1923, and
they had two daughters, Vilma and Anna. Before the girls were born,
the couple took in Jennie's brother Joseph's children, Tina and
Felix, who had nowhere to go when their father divorced their
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Two of her sisters also came here, Anna and Domenica (who will
turn 90 this summer), as well as another brother, Santo. Grazielle,
the sister who was blinded by the accident, regained partial sight
but never left Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Ferri died in 1982 after a long bout with Parkinson's
disease. Jennie Ferri's daughter Anna Viglione lives in Florida
with her husband, Salvatore. They have three children: Joseph in
Woburn, Gail in East Bridgewater, and Steven in Boston. Vilma's
son, Eugene Jr., lives in Medford.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Viglione is a producer of Video Radio. A tape he made
that shows his grandmother cooking doughnuts, chocolate chip
cookies, and pizzelle has run on several local cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Ferri also has her own cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   When she turned 95, her family threw a huge birthday party. As a
souvenir, Sullivan, who is a senior editor in the publications
department of Tufts University, took all of her mother's
handwritten recipes and turned them into a spiral-bound book. On
the cover, Jennie Ferri as a very young woman stands beside her
younger sister Domenica.
</P>
<P>
   In an introduction to the book, Sullivan contrasts life then and
now. ``There were no electric mixers, blenders, pasta machines,
bread mixers with kneading capabilities, and ravioli makers in my
mother's early years,'' she writes. ``All doughs were kneaded by
hand (giving the arms great muscle tone _ no weight lifting
needed).''
</P>
<P>
   Ferri used a 2-foot-long rolling pin, called a ``stenamassa,''
Sullivan writes, to roll out pasta, pie crusts, and doughnuts.
``Noodles were created from pasta dough by rolling the dough out
over a `chitarra,' a contraption that resembled a small portable
hand-weaving loom framed in wood,'' which sliced the dough. The
stenamassa was then balanced on the arms of two chairs to serve as
a drying rack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
