<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE GETS SOMETHING FOR NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He wanted, more than anything else, to experience the
thrill of playoff victory. He had already tasted the agony of
playoff defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to feel what his captain, Ray Bourque, told him would
be something very, very special.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't care whether it took four games or seven. He didn't
care whether he rang up a shutout or let a few get by him. He just
wanted to win.
</P>
<P>
   And now that Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe has one notch in his
belt, he wants another. He, and his teammates, have become, in the
words of coach Pat Burns, ``greedy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And why shouldn't they be?
</P>
<P>
   Their confidence level is off the chart and they have a goalie
who's hungry and unquestionably playing the best hockey of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Dafoe was pretty lucky in Sunday's series-clinching 2-0
win over Carolina, with the Hurricanes missing four open-net
chances, but he was good when he had to be. A 31-save shutout
night, regardless of how it comes about, is a 31-save shutout
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dafoe's second shutout of the series and third of his
playoff career. In the six-game set with Carolina, he stopped 154
of 164 scoring bids (.939 save percentage) and posted an
eye-popping 1.46 goals against average. With those kinds of
figures, it's no wonder the Bruins are thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence that builds in this room, you know, the further
we go, the better it gets,'' said Dafoe. ``We're a pretty confident
bunch of guys right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win the first round, and sometimes they say that's the
hardest round, just to get out of it, and after that, who knows
what can happen? We're just going to go out and have fun and try
and win another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe acknowledged that he and the Bruins were very fortunate
Sunday that they weren't blown out of the Vault in the second
period, when Carolina outshot them, 16-3, and missed what 'Canes
coach Paul Maurice said were ``four gimme putts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely came hard and I was fortunate,'' said Dafoe.
``I made some saves when I had to, but I also had a couple of empty
nets and they put some plexiglass up or something. I don't know
what happened, but obviously with them not getting a goal and us
taking a 2-0 lead going into the third, I like our chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of realized we got away with something there and
weren't going to let it happen again in the third period, and
that's exactly what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins tightened things up considerably in the final 20
minutes and allowed Carolina just four shots on Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt for the first time in six games he gave up some big
rebounds,'' said Carolina's Keith Primeau. ``I can't even count the
number of solid chances we had. I don't know if we have any more
chances in this locker room. But he turned us down time and time
again. It was just that Byron Dafoe played out of his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Solid, yes, but ``out of his mind'' may be a stretch. After all,
Dafoe came into the series with 32 wins, a 1.99 goals against
average and an NHL-high 10 shutouts. Those were figures he was
delighted with, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying all along I was looking for the playoffs,''
said Dafoe. ``I've never done anything on my own in the playoffs as
a starting goaltender and this is the year I want to go somewhere.
I want to do something and I feel that we have the type of team
that can beat anyone in this league on any given night.''
</P>
<P>
   When the final horn sounded, Dafoe and his mates congratulated
each other, then went through the Stanley Cup ritual of exchanging
handshakes with their opponents. When Dafoe met Arturs Irbe, the
two embraced and swapped pleasantries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arturs told me, `Great series,' and said, `Go out and prove
them wrong,' '' said Dafoe. ``I have a feeling he was kind of
talking about the All-Star snubbing and stuff like that. Very nice
words from him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TURNING IT AROUND &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
A year ago, Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe played well in the first
round of the playoffs against Washington _ and lost the series in
six games. This year, Dafoe played even better in the first round
against Carolina _ and won the series in six games. Here's how
Dafoe's numbers stacked up in each series. &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1998 vs. WASHINGTON! 1999 vs CAROLINA &QL; 
! Shots! Saves! Result! Shots! Saves! Result &QL; 
