<HEADLINE>
DOOM, RHETORIC AT THE CLICK OF A MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ So this was the heart of darkness of the culture
of carnage. I was playing Eric Harris' version of Doom II, called
U.A.C. Labs, which he put on his Web site three years ago with a
big ``Whatsup all you doomers out there!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, I couldn't even get near the heart of darkness. The first
time I tried to fight my way into the spaceport occupied by zombie
warriors I was shot down after only getting around two corners of
the maze.
</P>
<P>
   I did have the satisfaction of seeing two zombies blown to bits
in the sights of my semiautomatic pistol. They made wheezy
electronic ``ughs'' and their heads flew into red electronic
chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Realistic? Maybe if you're a kid out of touch with reality.
</P>
<P>
   In Harris' version of the game, you don't have to stop to pick
up as many new clips of ammo. You can just keep firing.
</P>
<P>
   That feature came in handy for me. My most violent previous
video game was Ms. Pac-Man. The only one I was any good at was
Pong.
</P>
<P>
   One very unrealistic thing about Doom II: You get to reincarnate
yourself every time you're killed.
</P>
<P>
   I came back a couple of times, shooting my way through
zombie-infested mazes until I found a sawed-off shotgun, a weapon
chosen by Harris and his friend Dylan Klebold to massacre fellow
students at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Doom II manual says: ``Combat shotguns are double-barreled,
sawed-off killing sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   There I was looking down the sawed-off barrels of the killing
stick in Harris' version of Doom II. I kept thinking about school
hallways and forgot the maze. The barrels flew in the air in
recoil, but a demon destroyed me because I was too shook to get the
gun on target.
</P>
<P>
   I had been told that Doom II was brutally realistic. Instead, I
found it unrealistic, repetitive and a waste of time _ after the
initial rush of trying to shoot monsters shooting at me.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part was playing Harris' personally designed version
of Doom II and running around a building with a double-barreled,
sawed-off killing stick.
</P>
<P>
   The game wasn't upsetting. Reality was _ the reality that came
three years after Harris programmed the difficulty level of his
version as ``Well, just stick with ultra violence.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd say the makers of Doom and other video games are in trouble,
just on the basis of that one comment in the manual about
``double-barreled, sawed-off killing sticks.'' Here's what kind of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they continue to market death and degradation to our
children _ and pay no heed to the carnage _ then one way or
another, the government will act,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   He said that goes for the Hollywood branch of the culture of
carnage, too. But Hollywood is the culture of Clinton, so who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, told a Senate hearing Tuesday that the
government should borrow tactics from the attack on the tobacco
industry to take on Hollywood and the video game industry. He said
the government should examine marketing practices, which are
clearly targeting teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take any research. Who goes to movies? Who plays
video games? Just look at the Doom II box, with its futuristic,
shotgun-armed trooper.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a parental warning in case they miss the monster
and guns. It says, ``Violence: blood and gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the little symbol for violence is an anarchist's bomb
with a lighted fuse, the kind depicted in Mighty Mouse cartoons
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   So here's my problem with Doom II, besides the fact that I had
to run around corridors with an electronic version of Harris'
sawed-off shotgun. It's tedious. Only a kid who's twisted to begin
with could model the end of his life, and the end of a lot of
lives, on such silly crap.
</P>
<P>
   When Harris posted his version of Doom II, he warned people not
to change anything. ``If you do, I will blow you up,'' he wrote.
``And it will not be cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that just a teen-ager talking, or was it a warning clearly
seen in retrospect?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Our lawmakers certainly act like they do. Lawmakers
have to pass laws, so they've sprung into action. They're off on
one of their periodic scapegoat hunts. A very bad, inexplicable
event is leading to some bad, useless proposals.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes of shooting zombies in Doom II, I realized
that millions of kids had played this game and hadn't gone on to
real carnage. Most kids are smart enough to know what's real. The
kids that don't are in more trouble than a video game could cause.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
