<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-05 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE SUN SHINE ON DEATH ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California reinstated the death penalty 20 years
ago. Considering what the punishment has come to represent, isn't
it time we bring the ritual of executions into line with reality?
</P>
<P>
   After all, there are more than 500 people on death row in
California. We need an updated formula to deal with such a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, we should stop executing people in the dead
of night in discreet little prison rooms that hold but a handful of
witnesses. Criminals are the ones who tend to commit their illegal
deeds after midnight in secretive, out-of-the-way places.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the state behave as if it, too, had something to
hide? Aren't we proud of what we're doing?
</P>
<P>
   Executions are the will of the people. Nearly 80 percent of
American adults say they are in favor of them.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get the action outside in the sunshine where it belongs
and schedule executions for noon or 2 p.m., instead of 12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Let's perform them in some place that will hold thousands of
spectators _ like a ballpark during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing prevents us. Because we Californians no longer kill with
the electric chair or gas chamber, a convicted man or woman can be
injected with lethal chemicals anywhere there are a gurney and a
few leather straps.
</P>
<P>
   Daytime public executions also would go a long way toward
helping us attain the most important aim of modern state-sanctioned
killing.
</P>
<P>
   No, we are not talking about crime deterrence. In the 12 states
that prohibit capital punishment, the murder rate is 3.5 per
100,000 population. In the 38 states that allow executions, the
rate is actually higher _ 6.6 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for the time-honored argument that ``executed killers won't
kill again,'' it is no longer the deterrence trump card it once
was. A sentence of ``life without parole'' accomplishes the same
end.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is the primary aim of capital punishment today? In the
old days, executions were viewed as the grim but unavoidable duty
of a dispassionate and detached state, carrying out a uniformly
prescribed formula for justice.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we know that the death penalty is anything but uniformly
prescribed. In California and the rest of the nation, capital
punishment is disproportionately the sentence for killers who are
minorities and from backgrounds of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, state-sanctioned killing has evolved into a very
passionate and attached act; it exists to provide ``healing'' and
``closure'' for the relatives of murder victims.
</P>
<P>
   Their names and long wait for ``justice'' are continually
invoked by lawmakers and held up as the colossal counterweight to
any convicted killer's remorse, rehabilitation or mitigating mental
or physical circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Pete Wilson was a particularly forceful proponent of
such healing-through-execution. When federal prosecutors accepted
Theodore Kaczynski's plea bargain for life without parole, Wilson
said he was ``deeply disappointed and disturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone not only was ``a jury's right to decide whether (Kaczynski)
should have faced the death penalty,'' but the relatives of
Kaczynski's victims, Wilson said, ``have been cheated out of''
their opportunity for ``closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, who is staunchly pro-death penalty, seems
similarly inclined. In his first clemency plea case in February,
Davis turned down Jaturun Siripongs' plea for mercy. Much more than
Siripongs' remorse and rehabilitation in prison, Davis said he was
moved by a ``direct, honest and eloquent'' letter written to him by
the daughter of one of Siripongs' two victims.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, despite pleas by Vietnam veterans and veteran
prosecutors, Davis denied Manuel Babbitt's petition for clemency.
He was executed early Tuesday at San Quentin.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 500 executions awaiting, shouldn't we
Californians optimize the potential for healing and closure?
</P>
<P>
   Come, let us move the death chamber out of the Dark Ages and
into the light of a new, more communal era. Let us fill the
coliseum and share in the vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
