<SLUG> BC-ADIRONDACK-GUIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST ADIRONDACKS GUIDE STANDS OUT IN CROWDED FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DENNIS APRILL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Adirondack Mountains of New York state cover
a vast area that seems to lure as many authors as tourists. Just
when you think every base has been covered, every aspect of the
6-million-acre park written about ten times over, along comes a new
book that creates its own niche.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Longstreet Highroad Guide to the Adirondacks'' is one of
these books. Author Phil Brown has written a travel guide and much
more. The wealth of information he presents goes beyond that found
in other field guides.
</P>
<P>
   For one, he covers the entire Adirondack Park, beginning with
its history, both geological and human. He divides the Adirondacks
into 10 regions, which, because of the geography of the area, is
not an easy job. The Adirondack Park is a mixture of ecosystems,
where you find such northern species as moose and fish and more
southern animals like opossum and timber rattlesnakes.
</P>
<P>
   Within each of these regions Brown describes ``the best of what
the Adirondacks have to offer, including hiking, camping, fishing,
canoeing, cross-country skiing, mountain biking, and horseback
riding.''
</P>
<P>
   For each mountain, pond or place of interest, the author not
only gives important and interesting information, but also precise
directions, facilities available, dates open, fees, and, in the
case of mountains, degree of difficulty, elevation and trail
length. It seems as though nothing is left out. That alone
impressed me, for I, too, am an author of an Adirondack trail guide
and know the amount of work and eye to detail needed to cover just
one trip, much less the entire park.
</P>
<P>
   But this book is not just an encyclopedia of useful information;
included with the text is a wealth of natural and cultural history
of the region. For example, in the section on Lake George, which
encompasses 35 pages, there are three maps, eight illustrations,
more than 20 destinations, with more side trips in each, and four
sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   These sidebars, darkened to stand out from the regular text,
contain some very interesting information. The ones in this section
cover the Adirondack Mountain Club and its history, the legend of
Rogers Rock, the Red Eft, and acid rain. (This sidebar might
actually be better placed in the western Adirondacks, where acid
precipitation is destroying aquatic life in lakes and ponds on a
grand scale.)
</P>
<P>
   Even more helpful information is found in the appendixes at the
back of the book. Here, Brown lists books and references,
conservation organizations, outfitters, tourism information, map
sources and special events, fairs and festivals in the Adirondacks.
High-quality illustrations by Danny Woodard of Loganville, Ga.,
complement the text and are sprinkled about the book in what seems
to be a random manner.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is eye-catching and unpredictable, since the
illustration pictured does not always reflect the flora or fauna
found in that particular chapter. The drawing of the boreal
chickadee, for example, is placed in the Lake George section
opposite the Submerged Heritage Preserve, the site where a French
and Indian War gunship sank, an unlikely place to find this bird.
Such an illustration might be better placed in the section
describing Bloomingdale Bog or some other boreal wetland.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous maps, number coded with text descriptions, liberally
dot the book and are very helpful in pinpointing the various points
of interest. Italicized scientific names are used for all flora and
fauna, and these terms, surrounded by parentheses, can slow reading
a bit. But, for those skimming the guide or looking for specific
destinations and trip overviews, the scientific names are easily
read through and add to the precision of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a former copy editor for the Albany Times Union, lets his
sense of humor shine through at times. Here's one example from the
High Peaks Chapter where he examines the frequent use of Indian
names in the Adirondack Mountains:
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging by place names, one might get the idea that Native
Americans visited the High Peaks Region as often as Adirondack
Mountain Club hikers. There is an Indian Pass, an Indian Falls, an
Indian Carry, and an Indian Head. Then there are the many
aboriginal names, some of dubious authenticity: Tahawas,
Nun-de-ga-o, Oseetah, She-gwi-en-dank-we.''
</P>
<P>
   From reading his guide, it is clear to me that Phil Brown has
spent a lot of time traveling and researching the Adirondack
Mountains. The information he presents is not only
all-encompassing, but up-to-date. In the Far North Region, for
example, he describes a stand of white birch on Lyon Mountain
``bent over like ballerinas; they have been frozen in that pose
since an ice storm of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor enthusiasts _ whether hikers, canoeists, mountain bikers
or just plain sightseers _ will find the ``Longstreet Highroad
Guide to the New York Adirondacks'' an important addition to their
Adirondack collections.
</P>
<P>
   For as the author so aptly put it in his preface:
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot guarantee that this book will find you a moose, but I
do hope it makes the search more enjoyable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
