<SLUG> BC-PERSPIRATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVY SWEATING MAY BE SIGN OF BIGGER HEALTH PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Imagine needing to change your shirt three or
four times a day because of heavy perspiration. Or being unable to
take a test because your hands are too wet to grip a pen.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has sweaty palms once in a while. People who exercise
or work outdoors also perspire to some noticeable degree. That's a
normal function of our bodies, which routinely produce sweat in
response to anxiety or to cool the body.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, for reasons that aren't always clear, people
produce excessive amounts of perspiration. Such heavy sweating
becomes a medical problem when it interferes with daily activities,
like shaking hands or working. Besides the social embarrassment,
such sweating can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had patients who've electrocuted themselves with
appliances,'' said Dr. Bruce McCormack, a neurosurgeon in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Known as hyperhydrosis, the condition usually strikes at
puberty. That's when the apocrine sweat glands, those located in
the hairy parts of the body, kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people who have excessive sweating have trouble
writing,'' said Dr. Bernard McEvoy, the emeritus chief of
dermatology at Ellis Hospital in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their paper gets all wet. It's very difficult,'' McEvoy said.
``It's not awfully common but the people who have it feel like
they're alone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Perspiration is already a function that most of us try to
ignore, with antiperspirants and deodorants that reduce or cover up
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1 percent of people in the United States with
hyperhydrosis, those over-the-counter solutions offer no relief.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, physicians may be able to identify the cause
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive sweating can sometimes by symptomatic of other medical
conditions, including pituitary or thyroid problems. More often
than not, physicians don't know the specific trigger, although they
believe it's linked to the nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   As a first line of treatment for hyperhydrosis, physicians
usually recommend their patients use a concentrated,
prescription-strength antiperspirant on the parts of the body that
perspire, including hands, feet and underarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work in 60 to 70 percent of the people I see,'' said Dr.
Mitchell Singer, a dermatologist in Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   Other options include a battery-operated device that transmits a
tiny electronic signal through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current stimulates the sweat glands to drain them out,''
McEvoy said.
</P>
<P>
   A newer treatment involves injecting a small amount of toxin
into the palms or underarms. This potentially lethal toxin, when
tamed and distilled, interrupts some nerve signals, and is
currently used to treat muscle disorders and wrinkled skin. In some
patients with hyperhydrosis, it can stop sweating for up to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another approach is endoscopic surgery to cut the nerves
that transmit signals to the sweat glands.
</P>
<P>
   As with any major surgery, however, there are risks, including
injury to the nerves that control the eyelid and pupil. Another is
compensatory sweating or excessive sweating that occurs in other
parts of the body, including the chest, thighs and legs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time most of McCormack's patients opt for surgery,
they've exhausted other solutions. ``I've had someone who was fired
because he stained the papers in the office,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1324EDT &QL; 
