<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-LOVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE STUDENT EXCELS IN WORLD DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Julie Barber insists she doesn't fear sharks. She
respects them, but the creature that inspired ``Jaws'' is just
another fish in the sea as far as she's concerned.
</P>
<P>
   She knows firsthand, too. She has rubbed shoulders with sharks,
so to speak. She was diving off the Great Barrier Reef in Australia
last year and encountered sharks. And she wasn't afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharks are not really threatening. A lot of them are
considered to be aggressive, and they attack from above,'' Barber
explained. ``They're predators and that's their natural behavior. I
respect that. I mean, I wouldn't go diving with a great white, but
I think sharks are really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, 21, is hoping she will encounter countless more sharks
during the year ahead. Barber, who will graduate from the
University of New Hampshire later this month with a major in marine
and freshwater biology and a minor in environmental conservation,
was named scholar of the year by the Our World-Underwater
Scholarship Society, a 25-year-old nonprofit organization. She has
so far received $20,000 for traveling and food expenses, as well as
state-of-the-art equipment from Rolex, Nikon, Kodak and the
society's myriad other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to spend the next year diving and doing research on as
many as four continents, beginning her adventures on the East
Coast, working her way to Florida and then California before
visiting the Red Sea and Galapagos Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship society contacts will house her along the way,
and provide numerous educational opportunities, including a chance
to spend a week diving with the experts at National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I won the sweepstakes,'' Barber said. ``This is
going to be a great year, a year of diving and research and
traveling and awesome education and it's all paid for. It's an
awesome educational opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, who is from the eastern New York town of Valatie, has
been infatuated with the ocean since she was in kindergarten and
her parents took her on a whale watch. None of her girlfriends
shared her interest, so she broadened her approach at Ichabod Crane
High School and founded the environmental club Students Against
Violating the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But her passion was the sea, and what lived beneath the surface.
She took her first dive in high school, during a family vacation to
Aruba. She knew she wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   Barber chose her college based on its marine biology and
underwater programs. The University of New Hampshire has five
different marine laboratories, as well as research vessels. The
school is located 15 minutes from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love diving in New England, because most people don't,'' she
said during a recent telephone interview. ``I go diving here in the
middle of winter in a wet suit. The water's about 32 and you can
stay under about 20 minutes. Then you get out and sometimes there's
a snowstorm. It's beautiful beyond words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The water here is more nutrient-rich than it would be in a
coral reef,'' she said. ``There's a lot of invertebrate life. If
you know what you're interested in and know what you want to see,
you can see it diving in New England. And the nighttime diving here
is really cool. Everything around you glows. It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Harris, professor in marine biology at New Hampshire and
Barber's adviser for her honors thesis, noted that while most
students enter the program fascinated with marine mammals, they
soon move on to other areas. Few pursue their interest in depth, he
explained, but Barber has never veered off course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie is a nice combination of being very bright and capable
and curious and outgoing in a most positive way,'' Harris said.
``There have been a couple of other students over the years who
have applied for this scholarship and hers was one of the easiest
letter of recommendation I've written.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
