<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONOPOLY-PARKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL PARKS NOW AVAILABLE FOR MONOPOLY MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Parker Brothers, a division of the toy and game
maker Hasbro Inc., introduced another special edition of Monopoly
to mark Earth Week, the tribute to the environment celebrated in
late April.
</P>
<P>
   This version of the game _ there are 50 of them in all _ is
backed by the National Park Foundation, which gets a percentage of
the proceeds from sales. But there's something a little off-kilter
here.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Brothers' idea of tipping a cap to Earth Week is to let
people buy up National Park properties and charge fellow players
rent to drop in, a study in gouging that folds well into the
tradition of American commercialism. The National Parks edition of
the game is directed at nature lovers who ``can vie to land on some
of the most valuable, tranquil and serendipitous property in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The first park for sale is the National Mall in Washington,
D.C., which goes for $60 and calls for a charge of $2 when other
players land there. Mount Rushmore, too, sells for $60, and then
prices get truly weird.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Canyon, which some see as the crown jewel of the 28
national park slots on the Monopoly board, goes for a measly $140 _
the same as Glacier Bay, less than Hawaii Volcanoes. (Some Tammany
pork, perhaps, set aside for a cigar-chomping wheezer feeding
politicos cash under the table.)
</P>
<P>
   Valley Forge and Gettysburg sell for $180 and Little Bighorn for
$200. Following the board around, the Badlands are available for
$220 (rent $18), and the asking price for both the Everglades and
the Great Smoky Mountains is $300. A payout of $75 has to be made
if a player lands on the ``Dinner at Ahwahnee'' square, and the
Broadway and Park Place of the National Parks edition are Yosemite
($350) and Yellowstone ($400).
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone worth $50 more than Yosemite? Hmmmmmm. More funny
business.
</P>
<P>
   National trails like Window and Limberlost take the place of the
railroads, while Chance and Community Chest cards have been changed
to read ``Volunteer at Point Reyes National Seashore _ Collect
$100,'' ``Park Closed Due to Flood _ Go Back 3 Spaces'' and
``Caught Looting Archeological Dig _ Go to Jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of homes and hotels, the game offers tents and ranger
stations, and the metal play-pieces include a hiker, canoe, tent,
ranger hat and grizzly bear.
</P>
<P>
   Like other special editions of Monopoly, the National Parks game
sells for $35. Special editions produced by the Rhode Island toy
and game maker already include NASCAR, Harley- Davidson, bass
fishing, the Napa Valley, Cincinnati, Super Bowl XXXII, golf and
the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Others due out this year include Marvel Comics, Mustang cars and
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARFUNKEL-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      05-05 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARFUNKEL-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMON &AMP; WHO? GARFUNKEL MAKES HIS OWN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - While talking with Art Garfunkel, the unspoken
question hangs in the air, creating an odd bit of tension.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like having a conversation with O.J. Simpson and
dancing around the subject of Ronald Goldman. Or speaking with Bill
Clinton but politely avoiding any references to a certain
beret-wearing brunette.
</P>
<P>
   With Garfunkel, possessor of one of the most virginal voices in
pop music, the million-dollar question has to be, Why the heck is
Paul Simon so amazingly famous and his former singing partner is .
. . well, not?
</P>
<P>
   Being polite, one doesn't ask. But the 57-year-old Garfunkel
does discuss his sometimes prickly relationship with Simon, a
partnership that was one of the most celebrated in music history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great motivating effect on each other,'' he says, a
tad professorial from his New York home. ``We were impressed with
each other, and we worked to impress the other one. It was like an
electric buzz between us.''
</P>
<P>
   The duo of Simon &AMP; Garfunkel originally disbanded in 1970, six
years after their first album, ``Wednesday Morning, 3 A.M.'' In
between came a number of astonishingly crisp and lasting songs that
helped define the turbulent time: ``Mrs. Robinson,'' ``The Sound of
Silence'' and ''Bridge Over Troubled Water,'' among many others.
</P>
<P>
   Garfunkel's almost feminine tenor was one hallmark of the duo.
The other was Simon's prolific songwriting ability, because
Garfunkel wrote virtually none of the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both complemented each other quite nicely,'' Garfunkel
says. ``I had very good ears for what he was doing. I quite enjoyed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But once the partnership came to an end, Simon moved from
adventurous strength to strength. He's still big news in 1999, as
he gets ready to launch a nationwide arena tour with Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   As for Garfunkel, he didn't stagnate. But hit songs like 1973's
pretty ``All I Know'' and a 1978 version of Sam Cooke's ``Wonderful
World'' were pleasant without really being essential. A film career
peaked early with 1971's ``Carnal Knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years after the breakup, Garfunkel seemed to merit the
most attention whenever he reunited with Simon. There was a 1975
``Saturday Night Live'' appearance and 1981's mammoth Central Park
concert. But other than those occasional moments, he seems to have
dropped from the celebrity radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's not surprising. For one, even though he has kept
a journal for years and has published a book of poetry, Garfunkel
is not a songwriter. It's something that puzzles him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see the oddity of it,'' he muses. ``It's been too much of
a compelling question mark through the years. I write melodies
effortlessly. As a harmony person, I'm (begin ital) always (end
ital) writing melodies. But maybe if my head was just tilted
another four degrees, it would be different.''
</P>
<P>
   He's in the midst of a tour that he has been on since last July,
bringing hits from both phases of his career. He happily trots out
the classics for nostalgic boomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a member of the audience, I'd want to hear the
hits,'' he says. ``But for me, I particularly love it when
something goes wrong. At those moments, the performer gives you
some information about who they are. You can see this so-called
star, and see how they react when there is horrific feedback or
when the arrangement goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's natural to wonder if he misses performing with
Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's the duo, it's its own art form,'' he says. ``There
were a lot of advantages. I had to find my way without him. But
now, I quite enjoy being able to set up on my own, to sing what I
want to sing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1423EDT &QL; 
