<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Dateline to kum, Germany) _ President Clinton
goes to NATO then Germany, talks to troops, vows to intensify the
Kosovo campaign. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Military developments; the
Pentagon offers an explanation of the Apache crash. By Steven Lee
Myers and Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHE (Tirana, Albania) _ The death of two U.S. airmen
in an Apache crash early Wednesday underscores the terrible terrain
problems the helicopters face in Albania and is latest setback to a
mission that has gone poorly since it was first announced over a
month ago. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments in planning for the
introduction of ground troops into Kosovo. By Eric Schmitt and
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ At Pristina's main hospital,
Yugoslavia's second biggest, Serbs and Albanian medical workers
feel obligation to stay in the war zone and work. They talk about
how they cope and about the various bomb injuries they see. Some
patients from the bus bombed on a bridge over the weekend are
there, along with some soldier patients. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Undated) _ Kosovar refugees begin arriving
at Fort Dix in New Jersey. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others stories on the the impact of
the long campaign on the new government in Germany, Kosovo
developments from the United Nations and a feature on the growing
prominence of Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ There is intense pressure on
Yitzhak Mordechai, who is running third in polls, to drop out of
the election. If he stays in, he could give victory to Netanyahu,
his arch-enemy. If he drops out and joins with Barak, Netanyahu
could lose in first round. By Deboarh Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ELECT (Edinburgh) _ Millions of voters in Scotland and
Wales head to the polls on Thursday to elect new assemblies as part
of a historic devolution of power from London promised by British
Prime Minister Tony Blair. Some 4 million Scots are eligible to
cast ballots for the Scottish Parliament, their first chamber for
300 years, while in Wales more than 2 million voters can turn out
to elect the country's first ever elected house. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-NUKE (Washington) _ The heads of three U.S. nuclear
labs testify before Congress. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS (Mexico City) _ The Mexican government blocks a
California group from delivering wheelchairs and other aid to the
restive province of Chiapas. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-DEBTS (Washington) _ With a record 1.4 million people
filing for personal bankruptcy last year, the House is expected to
approve legislation that will make it harder for many consumers to
discharge their debt. Expect a late vote. By Steven Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Republican moderates meet with
Speaker Hastert to demand a vote on campaign finance. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-INCOME (Washington) _ A Kentucky study finding that
low-income schools can perform as well as higher-income ones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-STORM (Oklahoma City) _ Ledeall: Oklahoma City tries to
recover and has flashbacks to the bombing aftermath. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-SEARCH (Oklahoma City) _ Families search for bodies in the
rubble as officials say the death toll may rise. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-POLICE (Oklahoma City) _ Many of the homes that were
destroyed in one neighborhood were owned by police and fire
fighters who are helping others cope with disaster. By Michael
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Developments: The man
who drove two hours to Littleton to put up 15 crosses and then tore
them all down after one victim's father took down the crosses for
Klebold and Harris has come back to put up crosses again, 13 this
time. Meanwhile, more is known about how the two shooters got into
the school (they had keys) and how they just happened to meet the
guy who gave them the TEC-9. Plus an estimate of the price tag for
putting Columbine High School back together again: $50 million. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   MATH-EDUC (Undated) _ Seven governors, including Gray Davis of
California, endorse a new eighth-grade mathematics test and
curriculum designed to bring U.S. students up to the levels of
foreign countries which score consistently higher than the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (``a'' code) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-DONATION (Washington) _ Early next year, Pennsylvania
will become the first state in the nation to offer a financial
incentive _ roughly $300 _ for the donation of organs. By Sheryl
Gay Stolberg. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-ECON (Nablus, West Bank) _ A Palestinian economy is
emerging, being built with offshore Palestinian money in
anticipation of statehood: the Palestinian stock exchange, the
first Palestinian television assembly plant, and the headquarters
of PalTel, the Mideast's only privately owned phone company. And
all are offshoots of the Palestinian Development and Investment
Co., or Padico, a Nablus-based holding company run by Munib
R.Masri. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE (Undated) _ Folo on the complex deal reached
between AT&AMP;T and Comcast in the battle for the cable television
company MediaOne.
</P>
