   With
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-BOX (San Francisco) _ What this means for settop
box technology. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 39 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was down 3 points, while the Nasdaq
composite was down 22 points. Stocks in Europe were lower: the
FTSE-100 down 1.4 percent, Frankfurt down 1.5 percent. The Tokyo
markets were closed again for a holiday; Hong Kong stocks were
little changed. Treasury prices are slightly lower, with the yield
at 5.72 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   NATSEMI-PCS (San Francisco) _ National Semiconductor says it is
getting out of the PC chip business. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ The Senate continues debate on
financial services legislation and votes on a Democratic substitute
and other amendments. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   FED-REPORT (Washington) _ Fed releases its beige book report on
the U.S. economy by region.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-SURCHARGE (Washington) _ The FCC issues a status report on
the surcharge levied on long-distance phone calls that is used to
help connect schools to the Internet, and announces an adjustment
in the fee. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVEST (Moscow) _ Investors who plowed money into Russia
a few years ago, lost their shirts in the August default and found
they could not take money out of the country are now doing what
would appear to be the unthinkable: plowing more money into Russia.
The prospect of increased foreign investment, coupled with a
positive reaction to a renegotiated loan with the International
Monetary Fund, has sent the Russian stock market to its highest
level since the economic crisis last summer. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column,
on private Social Security accounts. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
