<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5166 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUMBEL-SPI &LR;      05-05 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMBEL BACK IN THE `PUBLIC EYE' AS A MORNING HOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Bryant ``Will You Still Respect Me in the Morning?'' Gumbel
is going back to the breakfast shift. Why, you ask, would he return
to the ham-and-eggs scene after tasting USDA prime-time?
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one thing, no one seemed to notice Gumbel in the
gloaming. His ``Public Eye With Bryant Gumbel,'' the CBS evening
newsmagazine for which he forsook his NBC roots two years ago,
wasn't exactly in the public eye. CBS canceled it after less than a
year, and Gumbel has been cooling his heels _ and his fat five-year
contract _ ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Second, with apologies to Tom, Dan, Peter and the nightly news
crowd, mornings are the new battleground. ABC didn't put Diane
Sawyer and Charles Gibson back on ``Good Morning America'' simply
as a public-relations stunt. Remember when they took over in
January? It was billed as a temporary thing. But what's great about
a temporary thing is that you can still say it's a temporary thing
three years from now. Technically, I suppose Dick Clark's gig on
New Year's Eve is just a temporary thing.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's return to the a.m. shift, as the host of CBS's morning
show _ it probably won't be called ``This Morning'' _ doesn't
happen until Nov. 1, once CBS has finished building a new
street-front home a la NBC's ``Today.'' But Tuesday's announcement
was still momentous enough to be tendered jointly by Leslie
Moonves, president and CEO of CBS Television, and Andrew Heyward,
president of CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is Bryant Gumbel, king of the interrogators,
honcho of hauteur, the guy who spent 15 years at ``Today'' and had
much to do with its being the top-rated player in the morning-news
game. Oh, yeah. Moonves and Heyward also mentioned that Steve
Friedman is part of this new deal. Friedman, who will be senior
executive producer of Gumbel's show, did two stints at ``Today'' in
his 16 years at NBC, both during Gumbel's tenure. It was under
Friedman that ``Today'' regained the No. 1 morning spot, so CBS
evidently thinks mornings are worth fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to being a major player in morning
television,'' Moonves said via press release. ``With today's
announcement, we have the elements in place to build upon the
progress already generated by Andrew Heyward and his current
morning-show team. You don't build a facility like this unless you
intend to fill it with the most gifted people in television _ and
we have that with Bryant Gumbel and Steve Friedman.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, Heyward: ``There's only one thing better than having
Bryant Gumbel and Steve Friedman return to morning television, and
that's having it happen on CBS. They don't just know how to compete
in the morning; they know how to win. And that's what we ultimately
intend to do, with a program that's smart, timely, fresh and
engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew! All of that must make Mark McEwen and Jane Robelot feel
just ducky. They're the current hosts of CBS's ``This Morning,''
co-architects of Heyward's ``progress'' and soon-to-be frequent
fliers at Kinko's.
</P>
<P>
   No word on who might be co-hosting with Gumbel. The name of ABC
news anchor Elizabeth Vargas always surfaces at times such as this.
And at least one newspaper report on Tuesday floated Deborah
Norville, Gumbel's one-time partner at ``Today,'' as a possibility.
Both, however, are generally perceived as icy (Norville's
appearances on ``Hollywood Squares'' notwithstanding), and Gumbel
alone is good for an acute case of freezer burn.
</P>
<P>
   Better to go after a warmer persona. The choice here would be
someone like Margaret Larson, another ``Today'' alum. Like Gumbel,
Larson is whip smart, self-assured and incredibly articulate.
Unlike Gumbel, she's disarming and approachable _ a perfect
complement to Gumbel's seeming brusqueness.
</P>
<P>
   Last time we talked, Larson said she had no desire to return to
a full-time, high-profile network job. Can't blame her, really. The
former Seattle TV anchor now works part time for ``Dateline NBC''
and gets to live in Seattle. Admittedly, not a bad gig. But if CBS
wants to win in the morning, it would do well to find a Larson
clone to team with Gumbel. While ``Today'' remains No. 1, it's not
as good as it was when the ``cool'' Gumbel teamed with the ``warm''
Katy Couric.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Ling, 25, is the new co-host of ABC's ``The View.'' Ling
beat out more than 17,000 wannabes seeking to replace Debbie
Matenopoulos, who was dismissed from the morning chatfest four
months ago. Most recently, Ling was a reporter for ``Channel One
News,'' a news show broadcast to high schools and middle schools
nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
