<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-JACKSON-AZR &LR;      05-05 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JACKSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MAY HAVE DONE JOB TOO WELL  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MAY 5 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Perhaps nothing more clearly demonstrates the paradox
of the Rev. Jesse Jackson's successful effort to free three
American servicemen from their Serbian captors than the photo of
Jackson and Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic holding hands
and praying.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to imagine what, in fact, the Butcher of Kosovo
is praying for: The swift departure, safe or otherwise, of every
ethnic Albanian from Serbia. And it is equally easy to envision
Jackson's intercession helping to get that prayer answered.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was wonderful seeing the smiling faces of the three
young American soldiers in the company of the American minister who
persuaded the Serbian strongman to release them. Their families are
relieved and grateful. Americans who fretted for their safety are
exultant. But, no, this is no way to run a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope no American has any (impression) that Mr. Milosevic has
become a Boy Scout,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., on CBS'
``Face the Nation'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is the indifference among the American public to
whether he is a Boy Scout or a butcher that Milosevic is likely
counting on.
</P>
<P>
   No one's fool, he understood that until the NATO bombs began
dropping on his nation, few Americans knew Belgrade from Belfast.
He also knew they would tolerate few, if any, casualties to protect
residents of a Serbian province almost none of them had known
existed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, fumed conservative commentator William Kristol,
Jackson ``is behaving as an instrument of Milosevic's propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's avocation as a freelance diplomat has earned
impressive results. In 1990, he helped manage the release of more
than 700 women and children who were being used by Saddam Hussein
as human shields during Iraq's occupation of Kuwait. And in 1984,
his banner year, he effected the release of a downed U.S. Navy
pilot from Syrians in Lebanon and 22 Americans and 26 Cubans from
Cuban prisons. But the minister's problem may be that he does his
``job'' too well.
</P>
<P>
   The very Balkan dilemma that Jackson now creates for President
Clinton and his NATO allies is that his mission will succeed
entirely _ that it will help end the bombing and bring parties to
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   If that occurs, Milosevic wins, since bombs will have ceased
dropping on Serbia while hundreds of thousands of Kosovars languish
in the muck and mire as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Who will go, then, to rescue them? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5175 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-PROGRAM-HNS &LR;      05-05 0447
