<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-PROGRAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY BOOST AIDS PROGRAM WITH $1M DONATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS and ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Backed by a $1 million corporate donation, Mayor
Willie Brown has launched an AIDS and HIV program that will focus
on education, prevention and awareness, especially for minorities,
women and young gay men.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor hopes the program, which he announced Tuesday as
another way to stem the spread of HIV and AIDS, will encourage
other businesses to contribute $5 million over five years to the
program. DuPont Pharmaceuticals donated $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an increase in the number of people infected,
particularly in communities of color. The education and information
has not penetrated (there) the way it should have,'' Brown said
Tuesday in announcing the city program.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont President Nicholas Teti, who participated in the program
announcement, said: ``Adequate funding often turns a new idea into
a successful idea. DuPont's $1 million grant sets the initiative on
the path to success. We're inviting other businesses in San
Francisco to help us raise $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS activists weren't necessarily overjoyed by the DuPont
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   When word spread last year that DuPont's new AIDS drug Sustiva
would cost much more than other drugs in its class, activists
formed a Fair Price Coalition and went to the company's
headquarters to try to persuade DuPont to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   They had little success, according to Linda Grinberg, a member
of the coalition and a Los Angeles AIDS activist.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Getty, an AIDS activist who takes Sustiva, called the
company's announcement a public relations move to try to deflect
attention from its pricing policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than give in and reduce the price of the drug, they're
throwing this money around,'' he said. ``I'm not against
prevention, I just don't know if I want to pay for it when I buy my
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Teti acknowledged the controversy over the price of Sustiva but
said, ``We felt that it was priced extremely fair.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials say the money raised from the program could make
a lot of difference to prevention programs, which now have an $11
million a year budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``A million a year on an $11 million budget will make a big
difference,'' said Norm Nickens, deputy director of the Department
of Public Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
