<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON _ SPANGDAHLEM AIR BASE, Germany _ President
Clinton met with U.S. troops and humanitarian officials here
Wednesday to reassure them of NATO resolve of it air campaign to
bring Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic back to the
nergotiating table for peace in Kosovo province. Clinton sounded a
defiant tone after whirlwind early-morning meetings with NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana and NATO commander Wesley Clark in
Brussels. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHES _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ For the second time
in two weeks, one of the much-hyped Apache attack helicopters, has
crashed on a training mission in Albania. We folo-up on what
happend and what this means. Developing. (Albright, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JESSE _ ATLANTA _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson, while in
Atlanta for CNN World Report Conference, visits a local church.
(GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ Looking for more details on
refugees coming to Atlanta. (Whitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, Germany _ The reaction of the
troops here to President Bill Clinton's visit and pep talk on
Operation Allied Force. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Holmes, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE-INTERNET _ WASHINGTON _ Reacting to the Littleton massacre,
the Internet industry is moving rapidly to show itself operating in
a responsible way. At a White House event Wednesday hosted by Vice
President Al Gore, the industry unveiled measures to help parents
protect their children from the dangers of the Internet. (Glass,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   E-RATE _ WASHINGTON _ Thousands more schools should get federal
help in financing their ties to the Internet next year, FCC
Chairman Bill Kennard said Wednesday. Kennard said he wanted the
program funded at its full $2.25 billion, a sharp increase from
last year. But the politically touchy program needs the approval of
the full FCC. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MATH-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ In an effort to assure a continuing
supply of math-skilled workers, some companies are offering
financial support to states that require their schools to offer a
specified math curriculum. Program is to be launched Wednesday by
chairmen and CEO's of Fortune 500 companies. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTARECORDS _ ATLANTA _ The Georgia attorney general's
office, in its strongest declaration yet that the Atlanta Olympic
records are public, has asked under threat of lawsuit for Olympic
officials to turn over files that they consider private. (Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-VACCINE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Franciscan Medical Center will
develop and test the first cancer vaccine of its kind on up to 40
local patients in the next several months. WITH info box at end of
story. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCORCHER _ Six Flags christens its new stand-up roller coaster,
The Georgia Scorcher, on Wednesday. We're there to check it out.
The May 5 event will begin at 10 a.m. with a group of Georgia
firefighters riding the coaster in full battle gear with arches of
water from the fire hoses sprayed over the coaster. Gary Slade,
editor of Amusement Today and ``thrill ride expert'' will be there
to check out Six Flags' newest coaster. (Reinolds, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12-15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
