<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEGAS-SIGHTS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEGAS-SIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORLEANS VISIT MAY INCLUDE OTHER DEGAS STOPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim included) 
(Eds.: Also see: Degas-review) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ If the just-opened Edgar Degas exhibit makes an
impression, you may want to explore other locations linked to the
French painter who visited in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   Your first stop should be the lovingly restored Degas House at
2306 Esplanade, just a short drive from the New Orleans Museum of
Art. Listed on the National Register of Historic Places, the house
is a museum that focuses on the legacy of Degas, who lived in the
home with his Creole relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The house was about 20 years old when Degas, then 38 and living
in Paris, arrived in New Orleans. The original house was twice as
large, but in the 1920s it was cut in half to create the
mirror-image homes known as the Degas House and Degas II.
</P>
<P>
   The Degas Foundation, which purchased the structures and is
responsible for their restoration, has mounted a series of exhibits
in conjunction with the NOMA event. Visitors will find displays
focusing on architecture and the yellow fever epidemic (which
felled several of Degas' family members) as well as a time line
that traces the painter's life.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors also will see the rooms in which Degas painted.
According to foundation director David Villarrubia, the artist's
failing eyesight forced him to work indoors. He often painted in
what is now the breakfast room. Among the 17 works he completed
while living in New Orleans are ``Portrait of Estelle'' and ``A
Cotton Office in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   The home is open for tours 9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily. Admission is
$10. Call 504-821-5009.
</P>
<P>
   Other Degas houses to see are the Pitot House and the
Hermann-Grima House.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitot House, an exquisite West Indies-style plantation house
that overlooks Bayou St. John, is a short walk from the NOMA.
Constructed in the late 1700s, the house was the home of Degas'
maternal grandmother. It is furnished in period antiques. Located
at 1440 Moss St., the Pitot House is open to visitors 10 a.m.-3
p.m. Wednesdays through Saturdays. Admission is $3 ($1 for
children). Call 504-482-0312.
</P>
<P>
   The historical Hermann-Grima House is hosting ``An Evening With
Edgar Degas.'' The performances, offered at 5:30 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays through Aug. 31, feature conversations with
Degas, played by an actor. The shows will be held in the courtyard.
Tickets are $12.50. Call 504-525-5661.
</P>
<P>
   Three French Quarter restaurants are offering a Degas Creole
dinner after the show. The price includes the performance, meal,
tax and gratuities. Cost for the Gumbo Shop is $45; Arnaud's, $70;
and Galatoire's, $75. Call 504-522-5555 for tickets and dinner
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Two other New Orleans restaurants have created Degas-inspired
menus. The Degas Cafe, located at 3127 Esplanade, is just a short
distance from the NOMA and the Degas House.
</P>
<P>
   The casual bistro concentrates on French cuisine during its
daily lunch and dinner, while brunch is offered on Saturdays and
Sundays. Its Degas specials are for lunch and, if you get lucky,
your waiter may be David Musson, a real blood relation to Edgar
Degas. Call 504-945-5635.
</P>
<P>
   At the Upperline Restaurant, visitors are greeted by large
paintings by Martin LaBorde, a local artist known for his whimsical
works. Each of the three works on the outside of the building
features Degas icons such as ballet dancers.
</P>
<P>
   The Degas menu spotlights specialties such as Crispy Soft Shell
Crab With Crawfish Mirliton Hash and Louisiana Hot Sauce Beurre
Blanc and Creole Tomatoes With Arugula, Goat Cheese and Pistou.
Call 504-891-9822.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also in conjunction with the Degas exhibit, two hotels are
offering packages that include accommodations and exhibit tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Located at 500 Canal St., the Sheraton New Orleans provides two
exhibition tickets and a room for one night for rates starting at
$129. Call 877-663-3427.
</P>
<P>
   The Dauphine Orleans Hotel, located in the French Quarter at 415
Dauphine, offers a two-night package, which includes two tickets,
the ``Evening With Degas`` at the Hermann-Grima House and dinner at
Arnaud's, for $369. Call 800-521-7111.
</P>
<P>
   Destination Management provides a Degas in New Orleans package
that covers two-night's lodging, exhibit admission and a city tour
for fares starting at $129 per person (double occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For New Orleans visitor information including hotel packages,
attractions and events, call 800-672-6124 or access
www.neworleanscvb.com. For more information about the Degas
exhibition, call 504-488-2631 or access www.noma.org.
</P>
