<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEGAS-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      05-05 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEGAS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEGAS IN THE BIG EASY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Drawing, Edgar Degas said, is not ``what one sees,
but what one must make others see.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in New Orleans the fall of 1872, the city was in
political, social and economic upheaval. In those years following
the Civil War, the population was less than 200,000, with power
concentrated in Northern hands; emancipation was nominal; and
corruption was endemic.
</P>
<P>
   But during his five-month stay, the soon-to-be-famous French
Impressionist saw little of the Crescent City and painted none of
it. Instead, he focused on his American Creole family.
</P>
<P>
   The smart and entrancing exhibition ``Degas and New Orleans: A
French Impressionist in America'' in the New Orleans Museum of Art
is a record of that visit.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in the uneasy, segregated city in October 1872,
Degas was 38. Unlike his two brothers, who had moved to New Orleans
in pursuit of wealth, the artist was seeking respite after serving
in the National Guard during the Franco-Prussian War and resting
his weakening eyes (Degas went blind in one eye late in life).
</P>
<P>
   He lived withhis mother's brother, Michel Musson, and his family
in a fine two-story house with wrought-iron balconies and 14-foot
ceilings on Esplanade Avenue. Its light-filled rooms near Bayou St.
John insinuated themselves into the artist's portraits of cousins,
aunts, grandnieces and grandnephews, who came and went through the
lovely spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition features 17 of the estimated 24 paintings Degas
created during his stay, which lasted through March 1873,
complemented with works that pre-date and follow it. A supplement
of material, such as photographs and correspondence between the
Musson and Degas families, and assorted objects, such as the sofa
from the Musson living room featured in one of the paintings,
creates a fresh context.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor can discern the flow of the artist's life and gain
insight into such characters as his cousin Estelle, a frequent
model and an unwitting protagonist in the family saga.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, Degas was at a crossroads, and here, too, the
exhibit reveals transformations as subtle as they are crucial.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of it all is ``A Cotton Office in New Orleans''
(The Cotton Exchange, 1873) a painting whose modest size belies its
pivotal role in the artist's development and the impact it had on
the public.
</P>
<P>
   In this stark interior scene, Degas explores spaces and the
diagonal composition that will characterize the revolutionary work
to come. He limited his palette to black, cream and ochre tones,
devoting his potent powers of observation to render 14 distinctive
portraits and a dynamic environment in rich variety of brushwork.
</P>
<P>
   Musson sits in the front of the picture, left of center, his
legs cut off by the edge of the canvas. He is studying the sample
of cotton in his hand. On the left edge, Degas' brother Achille
leans casually against the window. His other brother, Rene, sits
dead center of the picture, his legs stretched before him as he
reads the Daily Picayune. Balancing this mid-ground is a
shirt-sleeved John Livaudais, the company clerk, who stands by the
right edge of the picture, examining the ledgers on the desk.
</P>
<P>
   Details such as the basket of trash, planted in the same plane
as Musson, and the texture of the cotton samples on the table
surrounded by potential buyers, complete the scene in which the hum
of activity is nearly audible. Degas finished this painting after
his return to Paris and entered it in the first Impressionist
exhibition in 1874, where it was acquired by the museum in Pau.
</P>
<P>
   The marvelous articulation of both bodies and space in ``The
Cotton Office'' is suggested in another composition, ``The Song
Rehearsal.'' This interior is believed to be of the Musson home on
Esplanade, where two women _ the one on the right presumably
Estelle _ entertain themselves and the unresolved figure at the
piano.
</P>
<P>
   Individual portraits are abundant in this exhibit curated for
NOMA by Gail Feignebaum. Sketches and finished paintings describe
the artist and his family for their own sake, but also as character
studies and figures for larger compositions. Drawings of Degas'
sisters Therese and Marguerite accompany his iconic ``Self-Portrait
in a Soft Hat'' (1857) in the introductory gallery, the assurance
of his line conveying precise likenesses and as well as suggesting
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Estelle, the most frequent subject, was Musson's daughter and
the wife of Degas' brother Rene. We meet her first in a group
portrait Degas drew in shades of gray watercolor and charcoal in
1865. Degas' aunt is seated on an armchair with her daughter
Desiree standing to her left, right arm extended on the mantle, and
Estelle seated on the floor at her feet. Estelle had been recently
widowed, and the three women were in Paris escaping the Civil War.
Estelle's eventual blindness is evident in her wayward gaze that is
also filled with sadness.
</P>
<P>
   We find her time and again in the New Orleans pictures, after
she's married Rene. In one especially beautiful painting, the
pregnant Estelle, wearing a black dress, stands by a table
arranging flowers in a vase. In his inimitable manner, Degas
combines large areas of indeterminate space _ the brushy
transparency of the brown wall behind the figure and the liquid
green of the window at her side _ with carefully described details.
In this thoughtful picture, the sharp focus on the red gladioli and
white roselike blooms in the center draw attention to the delicate
hand that arranges the flowers, which in turn draws attention to
her sightless, gentle face.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ---------------------- &QL; 
INFORMATION BOX &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Degas and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in America'' &QL; 
Where: New Orleans Museum of Art, City Park; 504-488-2631 &QL; 
When: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Sundays. Through Aug. 29. &QL; 
Tickets: $10 adults, $9 seniors and students, $5 boys and girls age
3-17. 800-409-9959.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
