<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-EGOLAND06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now you see him, now you don't
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cover of Robbie Williams' first solo album is a snapshot of
the saucy British popster with his face half-hidden by a turtleneck
sweater. It's as apt a visual metaphor as any for the music within,
which sells the singer as generic pop product while obscuring much
of his personality.
</P>
<P>
   After splitting from the British teen-dream group Take That
(``Back for Good''), Williams set about changing his image. His
evolution from bland pinup to puckish rocker has earned him
incredible success in Britain, where he regularly tops the charts
and sells out stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ego Has Landed'' attempts to sell Williams to America. As
such, it plays like a catalog of previously proven, radio-friendly
formulas. ``Lazy Days'' kicks off the album with a warmed-over
Oasis hook. The ballad, ``No Regrets,'' sounds like George Michael
at his most moony. ``Win Some Lose Some'' pilfers its bouncy beat
from John Waite's bag of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in all the pop cliches and slick production is the
memorably daft jokester who punctuates live performances with
off-color anecdotes, bigger-than-life gestures and jittery,
aggressive dancing. Only the arch rocker ``Let Me Entertain You''
and the delightfully irreverent ``Jesus in a Camper Van'' offer any
hint of the devil within.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ego Has Landed''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Williams. Capitol. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
