<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-JUSTOUT06-COX     05-05 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-JUSTOUT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Body and soul: Two approaches to the spiritual
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spiritual fodder in music these days comes in two varieties:
Christian pop and New Age float. Whatever happened to music with
the religious vigor of Martin Luther, striding up the steps of
Wittenberg Cathedral to nail those 95 theses to the door? Instead,
we have ``The Prayer Cycle: A Choral Symphony in Nine Movements,''
by Jonathan Elias and a staff of electronic elves. Never in this
world did Alanis Morissette sing (in Hungarian, yet) in the same
room as James Taylor, Linda Ronstadt, the American Boychoir or any
of the other 10 classical, world-music and pop artists summoned to
contribute to this event. Everything was put together from
separately recorded tracks by some guys twiddling a bunch of knobs,
and the music sounds exactly that bloodless.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, there's an unpretentious little album by the San
Antonio Vocal Arts Ensemble of music written by European and Latin
American composers to honor the appearance in 1531 of the Virgin of
Guadalupe to a Nahua Indian called Juan Diego. SAVAE is the real
thing: flesh-and-blood singers and musicians, performing works from
the cathedral archives of Mexico City by a Guatemalan Indian
composer, Tomas Pascual (circa 1595-1635), and Don Antonio
Valeriano, the Spanish priest who took down Juan Diego's story. The
songs are as simple and wholesome as bread, and as nourishing to
the body and soul.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prayer Cycle''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Sony Classical. Nine tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   ``Guadalupe: Virgen de los Indios''
</P>
<P>
   SAVAE (San Antonio Vocal Arts Ensemble). Iago. 16 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constittuion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
