<HEADER>
A5226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS06-COX     05-05 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge, Steve Dollar and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``A Good Day for the Blues''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Brown. Bullseye. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in a New Orleans studio, the 70-year-old R&AMP;B legend is
in superb form on her latest outing. With Brown's experience, she's
able to seamlessly explore the tricky territory between blues and
jazz with ease. Longtime players, including tenor saxophonist Bill
Easley and Hammond organist Bobby Forrester, give Brown enough room
to work, too. Brown's three-minute improvisational riff on ``Can't
Stand a Broke Man'' showcases her trademark wit, while the hurt in
the singer's voice on ``A Lover Is Forever'' is just as convincing.
The album's only misstep is the singer's decision to cover R.
Kelly's ``I Believe I Can Fly.'' Brown has earned her place in R&AMP;B
history; Kelly has barely left the nest.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiem''
</P>
<P>
   Branford Marsalis Quartet. Columbia. 8 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, this lively, sure-footed session would merit notice
as saxophonist Branford Marsalis' most happening album in years.
But the death of longtime Marsalis associate Kenny Kirkland, not
long after making the recording, lends the occasion a bittersweet
vibe. Marsalis wisely chose not to spruce up what mostly amounts to
first takes. This not only leaves the late pianist's sparkling
improvisations intact, it guarantees the sometimes feverish
spontaneity that's the heartbeat of any great working band. The
well-rounded set emphasizes graceful, blues-limned balladry (``A
Thousand Autumns'') and Mingus-inspired gospel grooves (``16th St.
Baptist Church''), with fierce, knotty sax solos and fluid group
dynamics compensating for the unavoidable pastel tones of Marsalis'
forays on soprano. The highlight is a new version of ``Lykief,''
which launches a lilting theme (sounding a little like something
Ornette Coleman would cook up) into hyperspace and back again, and
features the versatile Kirkland in vigorous, free-flowing mode.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``A Day in the Life''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Benet. Warner Bros. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sensitivity'' Eric Benet displayed on his 1996 debut may
lead listeners to his second album, but upon arrival, the trail
goes kind of cold. The airy R&AMP;B singer who had trouble garnering
attention his first time out is going about his love songs a bit
differently this time. Instead of pretty paeans to the opposite
sex, he opens with an order to ``hike up that skirt'' (``That's
Just My Way''). Then on ``Something Real'' he borrows, strangely,
from gangster rappers Dr. Dre and Snoop Doggy Dogg's ``Nothing but
a `G' Thing.'' But just before you toss Benet aside as another
artist whose bravado is not only unbelievable, but distancing, in
he comes, roses in hand, warm Hammond organs prominent, ready to
``Love the Hurt Away.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
