A5232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATH-MONEY06-COX     05-05 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATH-MONEY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIG BUSINESSES STARTS $2 MILLION, 10-STATE MATH PLAN
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eighth graders in 10 states will take similar math
courses and the same annual math test under a $2 million initiative
announced Wednesday by some of the nation's biggest businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth grade was targeted because in math tests administered in
41 countries, American eighth-graders ranked 28th, behind countries
with far fewer resources, such as Thailand and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighth grade is the turning point where our kids either slide
further into mediocrity or _ as we hope _ they rise to world-class
performance,'' said Louis V. Gerstner Jr., chairman and chief
executive officer of IBM Corp. Joining IBM in financing the
experiment are the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., the Boeing Co., Eastman
Kodak Co., Prudential, and State Farm Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois, Indiana, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New
Hampshire, North Carolina, Vermont, Washington and Wisconsin were
the 10 states that signed up for the partnership with the
sponsoring organization. Known as Achieve, it is a nonpartisan
organization formed after the Education Summit of 1996 by governors
and big companies.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million will pay the states to coordinate efforts by
local and state educators to define common standards, instructional
materials, teacher-training needs and tests. The businesses hope
this ``bottom-up'' approach will satisfy the objections of some
local school officials to President Clinton's proposal for
voluntary ``top-down'' national standards, Gerstner said.
</P>
<P>
   The new math teaching aids and training would be used in the
2000-2001 school year, and a trial run at administering the
10-state test would be conducted in the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, most school districts in most of the 10 states
would be using the new curriculum and tests routinely by the time
today's fourth-graders are in eight grade.
</P>
<P>
   While 49 states have adopted academic standards for math, and
most of them conduct statewide tests, the tests and their grading
vary wildly. In some states, 80 percent of the students pass, and
in others, more than half fail.
</P>
<P>
   William Schmidt, a nationally known math researcher, said that
most states include algebra and geometry in the descriptions of
their eighth-grade math courses. ``But,'' he added, ``the bulk of
what is asked on our eight-grade math tests is content that other
countries expect 5th and 6th graders _ or younger students _ to
master.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not good enough for companies like Boeing, where half the
217,000 employees have college degrees and the others need to
understand the mathematics in engineering instructions, said the
aerospace firm's chairman and chief executive officer, Philip M.
Condit.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said businesses are helping the states unite behind
tough, identical standards for math courses because it is cheaper
than the two major alternatives - teaching math to all new
employees or moving operations to a country with higher standards
in math.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the participating states will save money, since they
will be sharing the high expenses of developing new standards,
curricula and tests with each other, said Gov. Tommy Thompson of
Wisconsin. He said developing one of the statewide tests in
Wisconsin cost his state $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
