<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; tab-z
r c &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     05-05 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 23, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We have a brick house that is over 50 years old and some of
the mortar joints have started to crumble with sections even
falling out. I've been told by a bricklayer that the joints need to
be repaired by tuck pointing. The price he quoted was way too high
for us to afford. But since most of the cost would be for
time-consuming labor, I thought I would like to try doing the job
myself. Are there any special tools or techniques I need to know
about that will make the job easier or more effective?
</P>
<P>
   A: If there is a great deal of tuck pointing to do then it would
be advisable to buy several specialized tools: a tuck pointing
trowel, a tuck pointing chisel and a hawk. You will also need a
small hand-held sledge hammer or other hammer suitable for striking
metal. Use the hammer and chisel to remove all of the old mortar
that is cracking or crumbling down to a depth of at least half an
inch. Brush out debris and dust, then clean with a light spray from
a hose. Mix up some tuck pointing mortar and put a large glob onto
the surface of the hawk, then while holding the hawk against the
surface of the brick, use the tuck pointing trowel to pack the
mortar tightly into the recessed joint between the bricks as shown
here. Before the mortar sets up completely smooth off and tool the
surface of the new mortar joint to match the existing mortar joints
by using either a special brick jointing tool, or the point of a
small triangular trowel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently purchased a house that has vinyl-coated aluminum
siding on the outside. I know that aluminum siding can be repainted
and have read how to do this. But I'm not sure if this also applies
to vinyl-coated (also called vinyl-clad) aluminum siding. If so, is
there a specific type of paint that should be used?
</P>
<P>
   A: I believe that what you are referring to is aluminum siding
that has been factory coated with some type of paint or a finish
that is similar to paint. If so this can be successfully painted
over with a good grade of latex house paint _ preferably one that
specifies on the label that it is suitable for use on aluminum
siding. However, if your siding is actually coated with some type
of plastic coating, then it might be best to check with the
manufacturer of that siding. If this is not possible, test the
paint on one small area before going ahead with the whole job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a fireplace in the basement and one in the family
room directly over this. Every time we build a fire in the basement
fireplace smoke seems to fill up the basement. Can this be because
of the way the two fireplaces are situated directly above each
other?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each fireplace should have its own flue. If both share the
same flue, then this could definitely be causing a problem. You
should never have a single chimney flue venting two fireplaces, or
one fireplace and a furnace. If one of the fireplaces was added
after the house was built and the contractor tapped into or
connected up to the same flue, that could be the problem (it could
also be a possible fire hazard). If there are separate flues for
each chimney, then there may be a structural problem with the
chimney such as leaks in the flue lining, or a partial blockage in
the one going to the basement. This should be checked out by a
professional chimney sweep or a contractor who services fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When it rains heavily I get water trickling in through cracks
in one of my basement walls directly under one of the windows.
There is a hill behind this wall and the window is below ground
level with a recessed well around it. Should I patch the cracks in
the concrete wall under the window, or should I put down drain tile
to carry the ground water away?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think patching the cracks will solve your problem.
Waterproofing the outside of this wall and installing drain tile
along the footing would be the most effective, but this is
expensive. You might try diverting the ground water that runs off
the hill by digging a trench uphill of the house and parallel to
it. This should be at least 10 feet away from the foundation and
about 12 inches deep and 12-18 inches wide. Fill this trench with
gravel and make sure the trench extends past the house on each
side. It should also slope downward at each end so that water can
flow out of the ends easily. Water coming down off the hill will be
caught in the trench and diverted around each side of the house
instead of running against the basement wall.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``TUCK POINTING TROWEL'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: After chiseling out old mortar, fresh mortar is packed
into each joint using a hawk and special tuck pointing trowel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
