<TEXT>
<P>
   A sweet love letter to Ryan and Hanks
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Lubitsch's beloved 1940 film ``The Shop Around the
Corner'' hits the Internet age, giving director and co-writer Nora
Ephron a chance to reunite Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan in a story ideal
for their charms.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks plays Joe Fox, scion of a bookstore-chain business that's
inexorably wiping out mom-and-pop shops. Such as the one owned by
Kathleen Kelly (Ryan), a children's book nook called, yes, the Shop
Around the Corner. She's carrying on a romantic e-mail
correspondence with a man she knows only as ``dear friend.'' Even
if you haven't seen the original movie, you can probably guess the
rest. Yep _ unbeknownst to either party, Joe and Kathleen, who
openly spar over the buffet table at West Side parties, are each
other's electronic sweethearts.
</P>
<P>
   The movie give us a glossy, storybook Manhattan of clean streets
and cozy, well-decorated apartments, plus a lively supporting cast
including Steve Zahn, Jean Stapleton, Greg Kinnear and
scene-stealer Parker Posey. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
