A5241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MOMS06-COX     05-05 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MOMS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movies with a place in their heart for Mom
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   M is for the many movies she gives us.
</P>
<P>
   There are good moms (Irma P. Hall in ``Soul Food'') and bad
(Anjelica Huston in ``The Grifters''). Mysterious (Faye Dunaway in
``Chinatown'') and downright spooky (Piper Laurie in ``Carrie'').
Funny (Mildred Natwick in ``Barefoot in the Park'') and frightening
(Bette Davis in ``The Little Foxes'').
</P>
<P>
   There's a video to go with every kind of mother. So for Mother's
Day, here are a few favorites:
</P>
<P>
   ``Places in the Heart'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   Sally Field won her second Oscar as a resourceful Texas woman
who, after the shooting death of her husband, gathers the strength
to save her family farm.
</P>
<P>
   Her best mommy moments: Calling the kids together for the
pull-no-punches talk that starts, ``Somethin's happened to your
Pa''; fearlessly heading into tornadic winds to find her son.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Elvis _ The Movie'' (1979).
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Winters plays a dead-on, tired queen mum to the King of
Rock 'n' Roll (Kurt Russell).
</P>
<P>
   Her ultimate mommy moment: Silently sitting in all-glitter
Graceland and watching a big, faux-snow-drenched mechanical
Christmas tree go 'round and 'round.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Manchurian Candidate'' (1962).
</P>
<P>
   Angela Lansbury plays the manipulative matriarch of a
politically astute and opportunistic family. She's diabolical with
her brainwashed son (Laurence Harvey).
</P>
<P>
   Her worst mommy moment: Heck, she's nothing but evil.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Great Santini'' (1980).
</P>
<P>
   Blythe Danner (she's Gwyneth Paltrow's mother in real life)
struggles against the inevitable family dysfunction wrought by her
semi-psychotic husband (Oscar nominee Robert Duvall).
</P>
<P>
   Her memorable mommy moment: Her voice-over as her troubled high
school son (Michael O'Keefe) reads her loving note on his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Lion in Winter'' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Hepburn is one fiery wench and an Oscar winner
opposite Peter O'Toole in this remarkably acted tale of British
royal treachery.
</P>
<P>
   Among her manipulative mommy moments: Bargaining with her trio
of loutish grown boys in an attempt to land her favorite (Anthony
Hopkins) the throne.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner?'' (1967).
</P>
<P>
   Even though she won the Oscar here, too, it's not Katharine
Hepburn who's the most effective mom in this interracial love
story. It's Beah Richards.
</P>
<P>
   Her indelible mommy moment: Explaining love to her son (Sidney
Poitier).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Therapy begins by looking at Ma. This is Albert Brooks' often
hilarious treatise on a man coming home _ and connecting with his
mom (Debbie Reynolds) _ to understand himself.
</P>
<P>
   Among her great mommy moments: She makes salads to last all week
_ and freezes them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' (1963).
</P>
<P>
   You're right. Mom's not seen in this movie. Atticus Finch's
(Oscar winner Gregory Peck) wife died four years before this noble
story begins.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Finch is still a remarkable presence in one of the best
movies ever made. It comes after Atticus' kids, Jem (Phillip
Alford) and Scout (Mary Badham), have been tucked into bed in
separate rooms. In the still of the darkening night, they lay their
heads down on pillows and do what many young siblings do before
sleep overtakes them. They talk, trying to make sense of their
world.
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``How old was I when Mama died?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Two.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``How old were you?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Six.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Old as I am now?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Ah-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Was Mama pretty?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   (The camera pans to Atticus, sitting on the porch swing, his
head lowered, as his children's voices hang in the night.)
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Was Mama nice?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Ah-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Did you love her?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Did I love her?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Ah-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Do you miss her?''
</P>
<P>
   Jem: ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
