<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, May 6:
</P>
<P>
   FARM-SINGLES (New Weston, Ohio) _ On Singles in Agriculture, a
group that sprang up several years ago to provide solace and social
life to farm people. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   CALLENDAR-HOUSE (Tivoli, N.Y.) _ A decade ago, Pierre Moulin and
his partner, Pierre (Peter) LeVec _ the couple known far and wide
as Pierre Deux, as much for their joyous Provencal style as for the
colorful French cottons they sold at their fabric and antiques
emporia _ bought this late-18-century Hudson River house and its 47
acres, and started inviting friends, relatives and strangers for
parties and teas, and concerts in the old emerald-green carriage
house north of the main house. Now, with great regret, Moulin, 72,
has decided to part with Callendar House, and he has spent a mellow
Saturday afternoon recounting the highlights of his decade there.
By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBS-PSYCHE (Undated) _ At a time when the renegade sprawl of
suburbs is being intensely scrutinized, the troubling vision of a
nation re-pioneered in vast tracts of disconnected communities has
produced uneasy discussion about the psychological disorientation
they might house. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-DESIGN (New York) _ In the American Century exhibition
that recently opened at the Whitney Museum of American Art, the
first five decades of the 20th century are represented by nearly
1,000 artworks, a variety of cultural artifacts, like film clips,
plus a few dozen carefully culled examples of the decorative arts
and industrial design. Mostly, the design objects are used to
underscore points made by the art, as if to say, ``The artists
don't lie; this is how the world truly looked.'' By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-IN-CELEBRATION (Celebration, Fla.) _ Less than a week
after we moved to this new town being built by the Walt Disney Co.,
a neighbor dropped by to chat and the topic turned to children. One
of the great things about living here, the neighbor said, is that
the kids will have so many adults watching over them. We were
somewhat taken aback, thinking that perhaps Celebration would be
just a little too neighborly for us, but as we conclude our second
year here, we have come to see a measure of wisdom in that
neighbor's point of view. By Frantz and Catherine Collins.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HOMES-FIRE (Carpinteria, Calif.) _ Splendor among the
oaks, especially in the secretive canyons winding up into the
mountains of Southern California, comes with the sobering caveat of
fire _ walls of it, superheated and deadly. The house that embraces
nature here must also defend itself from her tinderbox. By Joseph
Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
