<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINESE-TREASURES-HNS     05-05 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-TREASURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 U.S. MUSEUMS TO EXHIBIT TREASURE FROM ANCIENT CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GERALD D. ADAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Climaxing more than seven years of diplomatic
effort, a blockbuster collection of Chinese archaeological
treasures will be exhibited at three U.S. museums this year an
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology,'' featuring a
collection 248 pieces that are among the earliest ever known, will
go first to the National Gallery in Washington, then to the Houston
Museum of Art before ending at the Asian Art Museum in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts include gold, silver, jade, bronze, porcelain and
textile items, some of which date back thousands of years to the
Stone and Bronze ages. All have been gathered from archaeological
discoveries made in graves during the last quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show will be truly fabulous ... all these items are
utterly staggering,'' Emily Sano, director of the Asian Art Museum,
said during Tuesday's announcement. The exhibit will be on display
in San Francisco for 12 weeks beginning June 17, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit in this country _ following more than seven years of
high-level negotiations between art and diplomatic officials of
China and the United States _ would mark the first time that all
the works have been gathered into a single exhibit and sent abroad,
said Michael Knight, the Asian Art Museum's curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are national treasures whose value is so great that I
cannot believe the Chinese are allowing them to go out of the
country,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington opening will take place in September. It will
then go to Houston before arriving in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The immense exhibit will require the Asian Art Museum, located
in Golden Gate Park, to displace every work on the first floor to
create sufficient space.
</P>
<P>
   It includes ``some first-rate, very interesting materials,''
said David Keightley, a history professor emeritus at the
University of California at Berkeley and a specialist in early
Chinese Bronze Age works.
</P>
<P>
   Among objects due to be exhibited are Neolithic (late Stone) Age
jade ritual objects and jewelry estimated to be 5,000 to 6,000
years old, some gathered from digs near Shanghai, others from
Liaoning province in northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
   Dating to the Bronze Age are a series of life-size bronze
figures from Sichuan, which Sano said indicated ``a completely
different bronze culture'' from any previously known.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze works, which are from the Shang Dynasty, are about
3,000 years old and include what Knight described as ``bizarre
masks with eyes that stick out from the head on five-inch stems.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Sano and Knight raved about the 2,000-year-old Xi'an
warriors in the collection. Made of clay, they date to the first
Chinese dynasty, the Qin, and include a group of life-size horses
as well as a chariot.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous Chinese shows that have been seen in San
Francisco, the Golden Age focuses on archaeological finds made
since the beginning of Communist rule in China 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides prehistoric items, the collection will also include
works dating from the Qin period, the Western Han, Northern Wei,
Northern Qi and Tang dynasties.
</P>
</TEXT>
