   TORNADO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ As Oklahoma City counts its dead and injured,
devastated neighborhoods slowly begin to open, allowing the
survivors to see what became of their worldly possessions. By JACK
DOUGLAS JR. and ANDREW BACKOVER. Story will move in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-RECONSTRUCTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ One of the first places hit by Monday's devastating
tornado was Bridge Creek, a tiny town between Chickasha and
Oklahoma City. Eleven people died in Bridge Creek as the twister
raked through with winds of more than 260 mph. Forty miles away in
Oklahoma City and its suburbs, residents scrambled to get out of
the way of the approaching storm. Most made it, although their
homes were flattened. Others weren't so lucky. On Wednesday,
Oklahoma City tried to salvage something from its second disaster
in four years. A reconstruction of the past 48 hours. By MITCHELL
SCHNURMAN. Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DEAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The 38 dead in the Oklahoma City area included a
family of four, aunts, uncles, cousins, those who ran and those who
couldn't. A series of vignettes about those who didn't make it. By
DEANNA BOYD and REBECA RODRIGUEZ. Story will move in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DEJA VU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Residents of Oklahoma City may be feeling a
collective sense of deja vu. It all seems to have happened before :
the sirens, the destruction, the grieving. This time, in the midst
of the city's second disaster in four years, residents are using
lessons learned from the terrorist bombing of the Murrah Federal
Building on April 19, 1995. By MILES MOFFEIT. Story will move in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-HOUSING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ As many did in 1995 after the bombing of the
federal building, the people of Oklahoma City are opening their
doors to strangers in need. Apartment complexes with vacancies are
offering shelter. The University of Oklahoma is opening its dorms.
Those whose homes escaped damage are inviting strangers to bunk
with them as long as necessary. Story will move in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
