<P>
   DEGAS-NEW ORLEANS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The only major French impressionist artist to
visit the New World, Edgar Degas made a personally and artistically
important visit to his mother's native city of New Orleans in late
1872, during which time he painted a group of memorable images
included in a landmark show at the New Orleans Museum of Art. By
JANET TYSON. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Stride piano flourished 60 years ago in Harlem via
such giants as Fats Waller and Willie ``The Lion'' Smith and
subsequently faded into obscurity. These days, one of the leading
practitioners of the form is Judy Carmichael, a blond Californian
who fell in love with the music in her 20s and has since recorded
seven CDs and toured as far away as China. She talks with pop music
critic Dave Ferman about her love of music and the need for
preserving the history of jazz. By DAVE FERMAN. Story will move in
``e'' entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
