<P>
   FOOD-CENTURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In the 1920s, Prohibition limped along, while
speakeasies and organized crime did a roaring business. Another
look at developments in food and dining over the past century. By
BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move in ``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ There is no more holy subject in Texas than barbecue.
Yes, you could say Friday-night football ranks high, but even those
games are preceded by a barbecue. The same goes for the college
game and what little is left of the professional sport. No,
barbecue is the energy source that drives the state. It is as
important as oil and gas. Politics cannot be conducted in Texas
without barbecue. Anything worth doing is worth doing over a
barbecue. And if you barbecue in Texas, you use beef. That is going
to make ``Barbecue America, A Pilgrimage in Search of America's
Best Barbecue'' (Time-Life Books, $24.95) a difficult sell south of
the Red River. By ART CHAPMAN. Story will move in ``d'' food and
dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEER NUT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Growing up Catholic has its share of weird memories:
itchy little scapulars worn around the neck during Lent that
scraped tender young skin raw. Or trying to accumulate enough
plenary indulgences for a visa to that strange, murky bus stop on
the road to heaven known as Purgatory. Not to mention a lifetime's
worth of guilt, remorse and eternal damnation just for one lousy
spring break's worth of impure thoughts, words and deeds. But like
the pope said, ``Hey, eternity ain't easy, pal.'' Or words to that
effect. On the other hand, Catholics have St. Arnold, the patron
saint of brewers. By BRIAN MELTON. Story will move in ``d'' food
and dining category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Cut through the partisan rhetoric and ideological
claptrap surrounding the recent murderous rampages by schoolkids
and the message from these folks is clear. Each side is blaming the
recent killings in places such as Littleton, Colo., and Jonesboro,
Ark., on a precious freedom guaranteed by the Constitution _ either
freedom of speech or the right to bear arms. By BILL THOMPSON.
Story will move in ``k'' commentary category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
