   _
</P>
<P>
   THE RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   COBB SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   8 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chopped iceberg lettuce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped leftover cooked turkey breast (8 to 10 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 hard-cooked eggs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium plum tomatoes, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 medium ripe avocado, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet, cook bacon over medium heat, turning until
crisp. Drain on paper towels. When cool enough to handle, crumble
bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Make a bed of the lettuce and top with the individual
ingredients arranged in a pattern, either strips or in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   Combine oil, vinegar, mustard and garlic cloves and serve on the
side so each diner can dress his own salad.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 578 calories, 45 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, grams protein, 284 milligrams cholesterol, 698
milligrams sodium, 71 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''365 Main-Course Salads'' by Carol Foster (HarperCollins,
$12.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   3 large green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   4 medium ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   6 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   Cut vegetables in small chunks and mix. Cook bacon until crisp,
break into pieces, stir in chili powder and vinegar over bacon and
when it boils up, pour over vegetables. Serve on lettuce leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 110 calories, 5 grams fat, 16
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 7 milligrams cholesterol, 144
milligrams sodium, 37 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Woman's Club of Fort Worth Cook Book'' Compiled by Mrs.
Clyde A. Lilly and Mrs. Olin Davis (Published 1928, out of print)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   `HE' SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3
</P>
<P>
   6 pieces hot buttered toast
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   6 crisp lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   12 slices tomato
</P>
<P>
   12 slices Bermuda onions
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Place between hot buttered toast one lettuce leaf; on top of
this, 2 slices of tomato, 2 of onion and 1/2 teaspoon parsley.
Cover with mayonnaise. A little extra salt may be added as tomatoes
always absorb more salt than any other vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per sandwich: 245 calories, 13 grams fat,
38 grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol,
369 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Woman's Club of Fort Worth Cook Book''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 chickens, cut into serving pieces
</P>
<P>
   8 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 quart milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons melted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 heaping teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Gravy:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Place chickens in pot with just enough water to cover. When
boiled quite tender, season with salt and pepper; let them simmer
10 to 15 minutes longer. Take chicken from broth and remove all
bones. Place meat in well-buttered pudding dish, season again, if
necessary, adding a few bits of butter.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs until light. Add the milk, butter, salt and baking
powder. Add enough sifted flour to make a batter like pancakes.
Pour over chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 1 hour in 350 degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   Make a gravy of the broth that remained from the cooking of the
chicken, adding a tablespoonful of flour stirred in a third of a
cup of melted butter; let it boil up, putting in more water if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot in a gravy boat with the pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 654 calories, 28 grams fat, 52
grams carbohydrates, 45 grams protein, 344 milligrams cholesterol,
787 milligrams sodium, 39 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The White House Cook Book,'' by Hugo Ziemann and Mrs. F.L.
Gillette (Published 1924, out of print)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STRIPED PARFAIT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Food coloring of choice
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces baking chocolate, melted
</P>
<P>
   Boil sugar and water together gently until it spins a thread.
Add this very slowly to the beaten egg white, beating constantly
until thick.
</P>
<P>
   Add vanilla and salt and combine with the stiffly beaten cream.
Leave one portion of the mixture white.
</P>
<P>
   To another part, add food coloring to make any color desired.
</P>
<P>
   To a third portion, add melted chocolate. These may be frozen in
small pans, slipped into the Frigidaire freezing compartment or may
all be frozen in one tray, separated by oiled paper. Any
combination of colors may be placed in layers in a parfait glass.
This is an excellent way to carry out a color scheme for a party.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 410 calories, 35 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 110 milligrams cholesterol,
79 milligrams sodium, 76 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``Frigidaire's Frozen Delights'' (published 1927,
out of print)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Louis Rukeyser's ``Book of Lists,'' (Owl, $15.95); John
Mariani's ``The Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' (Hearst,
$19.95); ``Soda Pop! From Miracle Medicine to Pop Culture'' by
Gyvel Young-Witzel and Michael Karl Witzel (Town Square Books,
$35); ``The Food Chronology'' by James Trager (Owl Books, $22.50);
``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren (Macmillan, $25);
``Mechanical Brides'' Cooper-Hewitt National Museum of Design
(Princeton Architectural Press, $18); ``Jewish Cooking in America''
by Joan Nathan (Knopf, $30); American Frozen Food Institute; ``The
Motley Fool's Rule Breakers, Rule Makers'' by David and Tom Gardner
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25); ``Revolution at the Table: The
Transformation of the American Diet'' by Harvey Levenstein (Oxford,
1988); ``Neighbor, How Long Has It Been?'' by Wallace O. Chariton
(Self-published; $14.95); ``Eating in America: A History'' by
Waverley Root &AMP; Richard De Rochemont (Morrow, 1976); McDonald's;
Kraft; ``We Remember'' by Jeanne Marie Laskas and Lynn Johnson
(Morrow, $25).
</P>
<P>
