<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CENTURY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: in metal cans. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1921: The first White Castle hamburger stand opens in Wichita,
Kan. The white of the stones suggested cleanliness, the castle
facade suggested stability. The little burgers are 5 cents apiece
and are marketed with the slogan ``Buy 'em by the sack.'' The first
paper napkins come on the market in 1925, and the White Castle
locations followed that by developing a folding paper hat that
could be changed often. ``Programmic'' architecture becomes the
rage in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   1921: The American Birth Control League (later Planned
Parenthood) is founded by Margaret Sanger and Maryware Dennett.
</P>
<P>
   1921: Table-salt makers iodize salt with potassium iodide to
prevent goiter, an enlarged thyroid, but the process is not
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   1922: Two Canadians isolate the hormone from canine pancreatic
juices to save the life of a child dying of diabetes. This will
lead to the first commercial insulin _ the first treatment for
diabetes other than diet limitations.
</P>
<P>
   1923: The May issue of Women's Home Companion publishes an
article that includes the lines, ``With the revolution in clothes
has come a revolution in our attitude toward avoirdupois. Once
weight was an asset: Now it's a liability, both physical and
esthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   1923: Sanka Decaffeinated Coffee is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1924: Tijuana restaurant owner (and Italian immigrant) Caesar
Cardini comes up with the showy, tableside-prepared Caesar salad.
Later, the International Society of Epicures in Paris votes the
dish ``the greatest recipe to originate from the Americas in 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   1924: Wolf Brand Chili goes into big-time production.
</P>
<P>
   1925: The average American homemaker prepares all her food at
home. By 1965, 75 percent to 90 percent of the food she uses has
undergone some sort of factory processing.
</P>
<P>
   1925: Postum Cereal Co., now General Foods, buys the rights to
Jell-O, invented in 1897 by Pearl Bixby Wait of LeRoy, N.Y. In the
late 1800s, cooks were moving away from heavy desserts by making
gelatin dishes from dried sheets of prepared unflavored gelatin.
This was a laborious process.
</P>
<P>
   1925: Using cars as a dining venue begins in the 1920s. Merging
the popularity of cars and soda fountains, pharmacies like the
Highland Park in Dallas hired male runners to carry ice cream and
soda to vehicles lined up at the curb.
</P>
<P>
   1926: Milk Duds are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1926: Cobb salad, a chopped salad made with avocado, lettuce,
celery, tomato, bacon, chicken, chives, hard-boiled egg, watercress
and Roquefort cheese, is created at the Brown Derby in Los Angeles
by owner Bob Cobb to use up leftovers. The Brown Derby was one of
many examples of restaurant ``programmic architecture'' springing
up along the nation's roads.
</P>
<P>
   1926: The Russian Tea Room in New York City is opened by members
of the Russian Imperial Ballet. It becomes a meeting place for
Russian artists, writers and musicians as well as America's
show-business crowd.
</P>
<P>
   1926: The Paris Coffee Shop opens in Fort Worth with 12 stools
and a luncheon counter. Today, the restaurant is across from the
original site on Magnolia Street.
</P>
<P>
   1927: Pez is introduced in Austria as a peppermint breath mint
for smokers. In 1948, the plastic dispensers are introduced. In
1948, the United States begins to manufacture the brand and market
it to children.
</P>
<P>
   1927: General Electric introduces the revolutionary monitor-top
refrigerator. The motor was sealed in a case that perched on top of
the appliance, and it required no maintenance. As production picked
up, the price fell from $600 for the clunky 1920 model to an
average of $90 by 1940. But until after World War II, many people
used iceboxes, which had to be constantly reloaded with ice and the
trays of water underneath discarded. Even $90 was a lot of money.
``No more worry while away,'' an early ad stated. ``The cost of
spoiled and wasted foods no longer interferes _ electric
refrigeration keeps them fresh and pure for days. Go away when you
like _ return to find the most delicate foods in perfect
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   1927: Kool-Aid is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1928: Sliced bread is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1928: The Bureau of Prohibition reports that nearly 70,000
doctors are using alcohol prescription books. Doctors could
prescribe 1/2 pint per patient every 10 days, but they couldn't use
more than 100 prescriptions (one book) every 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   1928: Broccoli is new to the United States and leads to the New
Yorker cartoon by Carl Rose (with a caption by E.B. White) that has
a young child saying, ``I say it's spinach, and I say to hell with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   1928: Velveeta Process Cheese Spread is introduced. It's
promoted as a product that children will like.
</P>
<P>
   1929: Clarence Birdseye masters the quick-freezing of
vegetables. His patents allow all sorts of fresh foods to be sold
from low-temperature cases in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   1929: The ruby variety of grapefruit is discovered as a mutation
on a McAllen farm.
</P>
<P>
   1929: Nestle purchases Peter's Chocolate, a European company
specializing in chocolate for chefs and bakers. That company
developed the world's first milk chocolate, using Henri Nestle's
condensed milk. Nestle's first claim to fame was developing the
first infant food in 1867 in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   1929: Oscar Mayer Wieners introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1929: The stock market crashes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
