<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CENTURY-3200(3Ta     05-05 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CENTURY-3200(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE 1920S, SPEAKEASIES AND ORGANIZED CRIME DID A ROARING
BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Roaring '20s began on a down note and ended in a funeral
dirge. But in between, much of America had itself a grand old time.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibitionists, busy in America since early in the 19th
century, finally got their way in 1919 when the Volstead Act was
ratified, making it illegal to produce, sell or distribute
alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   What brought the country to the banning of evil rum was an
unhappy coincidence of hard industrial conditions in cities that
drove many to drink heavily, a policy of saloons offering ``free
lunches'' so that workers would ring up big liquor sales, and a
turning against immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The last is particularly odd in that Italians and Jews had the
lowest rates of alcoholism in the country. The German immigrants,
from a tradition of brewing, were unfortunate victims of World War
I memories.
</P>
<P>
   But much of Prohibition was window dressing. At the 1920
Democratic convention, delegates drank illegal whiskey catered free
by San Francisco's mayor. Journalist and curmudgeon H.L. Mencken
wrote, ``Even in the most remote country districts, there is
absolutely no place in which any man who desires to drink alcohol
cannot get it.''
</P>
<P>
   And organized crime came into its own. Chicago bootlegger John
Torrio made so much money from 1920-1924 that he retired to Italy
in 1925 with a fortune of $30 million. Al Capone was Torrio's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants, usually dependent on wine and liquor sales, closed
by the droves. Many installed soda fountains to draw customers.
And, of course, the speak-easy was born. These portable parties
were epitomized by the operations run by Mary Louise Cecilia
``Texas'' Guinan. Although often arrested for running speak-easies,
Guinan gigged the police by wearing a gold police whistle around
her neck, and greeted her customers with the phrase ``Hello,
sucker.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these disquieting developments on the crime front, the
business of America's business was chugging along. In 1924, the
number of cars produced by the four leading European car makers
equaled only 11 percent of the amount of autos manufactured in
America. The working class could have the cars, the middle class
was starting to take airplanes. America was the economic power of
the world, and its people were feeling their oats.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration Act of 1924 restricted immigration from Asia,
Latin America, Africa and Eastern Europe, and Americans were into
being Americans. Without an influx of new immigrants, the earlier
arrivals were a captive audience for the ``Americanization'' of
their diet. A program in Southern California aimed to teach
Mexican-American girls to abandon their diet composed of
vitamin-rich sauces made from tomatoes, chiles, nuts and cheese in
favor of white sauce _ made from flour, butter and milk _ and hard
sauce, a sugar/butter combination.
</P>
<P>
   The war behind them, American middle-class women were ready to
cut their hair, step out into jobs and have a good time. Problem
was, the working classes were ready to do the same thing. So
instead of the standard jobs of cleaning house and helping the
missis with the children, jobs in factories and offices got the
nod. Middle-class women became dependent on their own cooking and
housekeeping skills.
</P>
<P>
   These women had big business ready to help them in those daily
chores. Between 1921 and 1929, the home appliance industry tripled
its output. Americans spent $667 million on household appliances, a
500 percent increase over 1909 purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pickford, Theda Bara and Rudolph Valentino, the era's movie
idols, promoted the idea of being thin. This, compounded by home
economics classes in schools and the availability of womens'
magazines, started America on its ongoing war against fat.
</P>
<P>
   Although kitchens were still built at the rear of houses, it
became common to locate the sink beneath a window so the person
washing dishes (now more likely the homemaker than a paid employee)
could enjoy a pleasant view.
</P>
<P>
   Still obsessed with sanitation, enamel work surfaces began to
replace zinc and wooden tops on the very popular Hoosier cabinets.
Designers began introducing color into heretofore all-white (read
clean) kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen was still considered a workstation, and eating was
almost always done in an adjoining breakfast room or dining room.
</P>
<P>
   America was still obsessed with progress, which meant prepared
foods, foods in cans, particularly. Although flavor may have
suffered, Americans no longer had a ``winter'' diet of meat and
bread and a ``summer'' diet of fruit and vegetables. Mostly,
Americans were in high cotton.
</P>
<P>
   But that was all about to change. October 1929 saw the stock
market crash and a country that was faced with the worst economic
trial of its history.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1920: Prohibition goes into effect in January. Although drinking
will continue and lead to the establishment of secret speak-easies,
Prohibition leads to an increase in sales of coffee, soft drinks
and ice-cream sodas. Many bars convert to soda fountains or
tearooms to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   1920: The 19th Amendment, giving women the right to vote, is
ratified.
</P>
<P>
   1920: From now until 1935, sales of lettuce triple _ most of it
the iceberg variety. The variety is a boon to growers and
suppliers, who find they can ship the dense heads nationwide with
little to no damage to the lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   1920: La Choy Food Products gets its start in Detroit. A grocer
teams up with a Korean he has known since both attended the
University of Michigan to sell bean sprouts in jars. In 1922, the
pair begin canning the sprouts in metal cans.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
