<SLUG> BC-CIR-NEANDERTHAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEANDERTHAL ORIGINS? SOME SITES TO EXPLORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neanderthals are not with us anymore _ or are they?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists generally agree that the stocky, heavy-browed people
with the low craniums _ inaccurately thought of as dimwitted cave
men _ disappeared as a distinct group about 30,000 years ago after
roaming across Europe and Western Asia for almost 300,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   DNA tests reported last year suggest that Neanderthals were a
separate species that had no common ancestor with Homo sapiens for
the last 550,000 years. But the recent discovery of a possible
hybrid skeleton in Portugal now suggests that Neanderthals and
modern humans interbred, and that many of us are at least a little
bit Neanderthal.
</P>
<P>
   If one is trying to learn about anthropology on line,
Neanderthals can help shed light on who we are by showing who we
aren't. One starting point is the Neanderthal Museum
(www.neanderthal.de). It lies in the Neander valley near
Dusseldorf, Germany, where the first fossil of the group was
discovered in 1856. The museum opened in 1996, and drew 250,000
visitors its first year.
</P>
<P>
   Its Internet site summarizes and illustrates recent new finds at
the original discovery sites. The museum's foundation is holding a
special ``family get-together'' this spring to highlight the new
discoveries: it exhibits for the first time bone fragments from all
10 sites in Germany where Neanderthals have been found.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also offers a publication service for academics who
want to see their research posted on line. The Web site provides a
history of Neanderthals and, like most other Neanderthal sites,
discusses a broad sweep of anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   A large site, with fascinating illustrations, plenty of side
pages and links, was created by Kharlena Maria Ramanan, a PhD
candidate in physical anthropology at Indiana State University:
(thunder.indstate.edu/ramanank/index.html).
</P>
<P>
   ``Neandertals were the ancestors that nobody wanted,'' she
writes in her introduction, explaining that the stereotype of the
stupid beast-like shuffler on bent knees, with toes splayed out,
was based on a French paleontologist's failure to see that the old
man whose skeleton he was examining had suffered from severe
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   She includes separate pages on aspects like tools, shelters, Ice
Age conditions, diet, burials, fire, possible speech and theories
about the fate of the species. Anyone thinking that Neanderthals
were stupid should try making a simple Mousterian knife or scraper
blade, which she describes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common questions I find myself asking about
Neandertals,'' she wrote by e-mail, ``is exactly what happened to
them. Did they become extinct? Did they interbreed with
Cro-Magnons? Are they a part of our ancestral evolutionary line or
a dead end?''
</P>
<P>
   On-line searching for Neanderthals can turn into wild-goose
chases because of a plethora of religious sites, some of them
fairly stealthy, that purport to ``objectively'' deny evolution and
other modern science.
</P>
<P>
   The Talk.Origins Archive, www.talkorigins.org, is a good
antidote. An offshoot of the Talk.Origins Usenet discussion group,
in which creationists and catastrophists argue with nonbelieving
opponents, the Archive collects essays and articles that explore
evolution from a mainstream scientific perspective. To give the
debaters a reference point, the Talk.Origins Archive has many
articulate overviews of important evolutionary subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Neanderthals have nine listings in the Archive's frequently
asked questions on fossil hominids:
(www.talkorigins.org/faqs/fossil-hominids.html). They include the
``Old Man'' of La Chappelle-aux-Saints, whose misinterpretation
popularized the stereotype of the stooping ape-man.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a mention of the skeletons in the Shanidar cave in
Iraq. One of them was covered with pollen, leading to a disputed
theory that offerings of flowers had been placed on the body and
that this was the oldest-known ritual burial.
</P>
</TEXT>
