<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKBOOK-MOM-RECIPES1     05-05 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOK-MOM-RECIPES1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A cookbook for every mom
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know there's no one like your mother. But we're sure there's
a cookbook out there just for her. Even if she doesn't cook. The
fact is, cookbooks today also can be photographic essays, personal
journals or historical records as likely to arouse imagination as
appetite _ thus they make lovely gifts. There are everal new
cookbooks among the spring releases that look ideal for Mother's
Day. We give you a quick look at some of those, along with a few
others that we know moms will love. To help you out, we've targeted
the selections to types of mothers. And though yours surely is
unique, we hope you'll see one here that will appeal to her.
</P>
<P>
   The New Mom
</P>
<P>
   For the mother of infants, toddlers and finicky children, First
Meals by Annabel Karmel (DK Publishing, $16.95) is a must. Karmel
is a mother of three, an expert in child nutrition and a Cordon
Bleu chef. Research began for this book when her first child simply
wouldn't eat much. She went to the library to look for cookbooks
that might help but didn't find any.
</P>
<P>
   So she took her creativity to the kitchen and began
experimenting. Recipes begin with ``first foods'' for infants 4 to
6 months old. Karmel explains all the necessary equipment, from
bibs to blenders, and then gives puree recipes. A similar approach
is taken for several stages of development, ending with a chapter
aimed at children 3 to 5 years old. The emphasis is on healthy food
creatively presented _ most recipes were tested by a panel of
children.
</P>
<P>
   This Sleeping Cannelloni is a great example of Karmel's work.
It's aimed at the 3- to 5-year-old, with the goal of getting them
interested in ``international'' tastes. Little mushroom faces and
black olive boots make for whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping Cannelloni
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 40 minutes Cooking time: 50
minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the cannelloni:
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound frozen spinach
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1small garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2cups sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons light cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8cannelloni tubes (6 ounces dry)
</P>
<P>
   For the cheese sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup each grated Gruyere and cheddar cheeses
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   For the decoration:
</P>
<P>
   Ready-made tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   8sauteed mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup grated cheddar
</P>
<P>
   8black olives
</P>
<P>
   Tiny green bell pepper bows and squares (for eyes) and red
pepper strips (for mouths)
</P>
<P>
   Place the spinach in a pot without water, cover and cook over
low heat for 5 minutes, or according to package instructions.
Squeeze out any excess water.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a skillet, add the onion and garlic, and
saute until softened. Add the mushrooms and cook for 5 minutes.
Stir in the flour and cook for 1 minute. Add the cooked spinach,
stir in the milk and cook for 2 minutes. Remove the skillet from
the heat, stir in the cream and season with salt and pepper to
taste. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly grease a 10-by-8-inch
ovenproof dish. Use a teaspoon to fill the cannelloni tubes with
the stuffing, then arrange them in the dish in a single layer.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce, melt the butter in a pan over low heat, add
the flour and stir to make a paste. Cook gently for 2 minutes, then
whisk in the milk and cook, stirring, until thickened. Remove from
the heat, stir in the cheeses until melted, add the mustard and
season with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over cannelloni, transfer to the preheated oven
and bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To decorate: Use tomato sauce to make a turned-down sheet and
arrange the olives as feet. Make slits in the mushrooms, punch in
green pepper eyes and red pepper mouths, and use the grated cheese
as hair, adding green pepper bows.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 294 calories, 12 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 26 grams carbohydrates, 48
milligrams cholesterol, 248 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
