<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOKS-MOM06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A cookbook for every mom
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pssst. Mother's Day is peeping around the corner at
you. That means you need a gift for dear Mom by Sunday. This
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all the perfect children are on top of this. They
already have a thoughtful gift wrapped in the most sentimental
paper and bow. They've ordered the flowers, have the Mother's Day
menu planned and the groceries bought.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a sibling to one of these perfect people, you could
call 'em up and beg to put your name on the card.
</P>
<P>
   But we have a better idea _ swing by a bookstore or hop online
and select the perfect cookbook for Mom.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if your mother is the ``make everything from
scratch'' chef or a ``get it done in 15 minutes'' cook, there's a
new book on the market for her. Even if she doesn't cook at all,
some make great reading.
</P>
<P>
   Like Amanda Hesser's ``The Cook and the Gardener: A Year of
Recipes and Writings From the French Countryside'' (W.W. Norton,
$32.50). Hesser spent a year working as a cook at the Chateau du
Fey in Burgundy, home of the famed cooking school LaVarenne. There,
she befriends a crusty, wise old gardener, and the story of their
relationship unfolds in a month
</P>
<P>
   -by-month account of the life on the estate, complete with 200
seasonal recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Is Mom way too busy to cook, much less garden? Then ``The
15-Minute Chef'' (HP Books, $15.95) is the book for her. After all,
she deserves to eat well, and so does her family, no matter how
busy the brood is. It has 500 ``fast and fabulous recipes''
compiled by longtime food editor Patricia Mack of The Record in
Hackensack, N.J. And we do mean fabulous, from the deviled steak to
the eggplant Neapolitan. Each recipe comes with suggestions of
prepared items that can be served with the entree to make a
complete meal.
</P>
<P>
   Does the mere sight of chocolate bring a smile to your mother's
face? Then she really shouldn't live without Nick Malgieri's
``Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to Extravagant Showstoppers''
(HarperCollins, $35). The title pretty much says it all; the cover
photo of an elaborate chocolate ribbon atop a ganache-covered cake
will make her swoon. For those with a sweet tooth with a wider
range than chocolate, there's Melanie Barnard's ``Short &AMP; Sweet''
(Houghton Mifflin, $25), with oodles of recipes for quick desserts.
As we gleaned the latest selections, we found a book for almost
every kind of mom: the one who loves to cure what ails you; the mom
who's a gourmet cook; the mom who's pulling her hair out trying to
get her youngsters to eat; and the one who truly loves to indulge.
</P>
<P>
   There's surely one for your mom _ more perfect than anything
that always-perfect brother or sister has cooked up.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
