<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOK-MOM-RECIPES2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mothers Day cookbook recipes
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gourmet
</P>
<P>
   So you're one of the lucky ones. Someone with a mom who loves to
cook; who lives to cook. She already has several bookshelves full
of cookbooks and every gadget on earth. She knows where to find
kaffir lime leaves or palm sugar paste. She takes cooking classes
and is always among the first at a new gourmet restaurant. She may
not own a restaurant, but by golly, if she did. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this mom would be comfortable in the company of her
sisters, like Nancy Oakes, chef of top-rated Boulevard in San
Francisco and Ann Cashion, chef of Cashion's Eat Place in
Washington. At the very least, she'll enjoy reading and cooking
from Women of Taste: Recipes and Profiles of Famous Women Chefs by
Beverly Russell (Wiley, $19.95.) The book includes profiles of 32
female chefs working in some of the finest restaurants in the
country, along with several recipes. Some recipes are complicated _
sure to challenge the cook who loves a challenge. Others, like this
Yellow Peppers and Onion Salad, are easy and should be great
accompaniments to summer meals. It's from Sarabeth Levine of
Sarabeth's Kitchen in New York, and some should be kept in the
refrigerator all summer long.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Peppers and Onion Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   8 yellow peppers
</P>
<P>
   Boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 large Spanish onion, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Wash peppers and cut in half. Remove stems and seeds. Add
peppers to boiling water, cooking just long enough to soften the
skins, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a slotted spoon, remove peppers from pot and put into a
colander. Place colander under cold running water to cool peppers.
Put pepper halves on paper towels to dry. Peel skins and cut
peppers into 3/4-inch wide strips. Put peppers in a stainless steel
bowl and add onion, rice and cider vinegars, oil, parsley, salt and
pepper. Mix, cover and chill in refrigerator for 2 hours before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 155 calories, 1 gram protein, 14 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 80), 8 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 4
milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Bon Vivant
</P>
<P>
   Did your mother refuse to ever surrender her butter? Is she no
stranger to duck fat and lard? Is her idea of total indulgence an
intensely flavored, outrageously rich meal? If she can get the Food
Network, then ``Two Fat Ladies'' is probably her favorite show.
Even if it isn't, she'll find the third book by the English diva
hosts Clarissa Dickson Wright and Jennifer Paterson deliciously
decadent.
</P>
<P>
   In The Two Fat Ladies Full Throttle (Clarkson Potter, $27.50),
Mom can find out how to make Cheese Zebras With Parmesan Ice Cream
or Salmon Filets With Leeks and Cream. We liked this Wylde Green
Chicken, which is a dish Wright invented while visiting a friend
and her godchildren, who live on Wylde Green Road in Birmingham,
England. They loved it so much they urged her to write it down.
Wright said the dish is designed to ``deal with the problem of
tasteless chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Wylde Green Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: at least 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 16-18 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons crunchy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon each salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark rum or wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the peanut butter, garlic and 1 tablespoon oil. Lay
the chicken breasts in a dish, pour the mixture over them, turning
and working into the flesh. Let stand for at least 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat the remaining tablespoon oil and stir
in the mustard, paprika, salt and pepper. Tip the chicken breasts
with the marinade into the pan and saute until they are brown,
about 3 minutes per side. Cut them in pieces while they are in the
pan. Add the chili sauce, rum or vinegar and water and cook over
low heat until done, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with new potatoes or rice and a green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 263 calories, 37 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 2 grams carbohydrates, 96
milligrams cholesterol, 515 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Preservationist
</P>
<P>
   There are those mothers who will spare no effort to preserve the
family history. They have the family tree outlined on the home
computer. Family photos, from the century-old faded portrait of the
great-great-grandfather to last week's snapshot of the new
grandbaby, are all neatly organized and labeled in photo albums.
And their recipe boxes are bulging with cards and faded clippings
from old newspapers, complete with notes written in Grandmother's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Vale Farrar Kelley got the bright idea to organize her mother's
collection and make a cookbook of it, simply titled Recipes My
Mother Gave Me (Time-Life Books, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said the project originally began as a holiday gift for
all those friends and family who were constantly asking for
recipes. Coming from a military background that had her family on
the move a lot, Kelley's recipes have a variety of regional
influences, from Texas to the Philippines. There's space at the end
of each chapter to personalize with your own family recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are good home cooking, but not just meat and
potatoes. There's Mom's Eggplant and Fried Green Tomatoes and Mom's
Homemade Fish Rub. Daddy is in there, too, with a recipe for Frozen
Margaritas, and numerous recipes from other family members and
friends. We chose Champagne Punch _ perfect for showers, parties
and special Mother's Day buffets.
</P>
<P>
   BEVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Champagne Punch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 30 (3-ounce) servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: several hours
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces frozen lemonade concentrate
</P>
<P>
   2 cups gin
</P>
<P>
   1 quart ginger ale
</P>
<P>
   1 quart champagne
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients and chill; or, chill all ingredients before
making. Pour over block of ice into a large punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment needed: punch bowl set.
</P>
<P>
   For Pink Champagne Punch: Use pink lemonade and add 4 ounces
grenadine.
</P>
<P>
   Block of ice or ice ring: Place cherries or small flowers
(daisies, leaves, geraniums) in a ring mold or small pan. Add cold
water to half fill and freeze. Add more water to fill remaining
half and freeze. When completely frozen, dip in warm water to
remove from mold and add to punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Can be doubled or tripled for a larger gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 83 calories, no protein, no fat, 6 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 4 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Armchair Traveler
</P>
<P>
   For the mother who loves to travel to far places while never
leaving her favorite reading chair, Colette Rossant has a story to
share. Rossant, who is French, spent her youth in Egypt, and in her
new book, Memories of a Lost Egypt (Clarkson Potter, $20), she
reveals all the rich recollections of her childhood. And luckily,
many of them are food memories _ the joyous wedding feasts, the
mango tree in the family garden and her Grandmaman's bimonthly
poker game, for which Rossant often helped prepare snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Rossant is now a columnist for the Daily News in New York and a
frequent contributor to many food and travel magazines. This book
includes not only great stories, but great recipes that bring alive
Egyptian cuisine, like this one for angel hair pasta with nuts and
raisins. It's an unusual preparation, but oh so delicious. Rossant
suggests serving it with hot chicken.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Angel Hair With Nuts and Raisins
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces uncooked angel hair pasta
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons raisins
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Break pasta in 3-inch pieces; set aside. In a skillet heat 2
tablespoons butter with the oil. Add onion and saute until
transparent. Add pasta and fry until golden brown. Cover with
chicken broth, bring to a boil, then lower heat and simmer until
all the broth is absorbed, 18 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, roast almonds and hazelnuts in oven until golden.
Remove from oven. In a small skillet, heat 1/2 tablespoon butter.
Add raisins and saute until the raisins puff. Mix raisins with nuts
and add to pasta. Serve hot with roast chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 402 calories, 10 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 51 grams carbohydrates, 22
milligrams cholesterol, 484 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Nurturer
</P>
<P>
   Does she always make you chicken soup when you are sick? Did she
lecture you to eat your spinach when you were a kid? Does she
always have a ready diagnosis and a remedy, like ``you need to get
more vitamin D?'' Then your mom would welcome Food for Health &AMP;
Healing (Better Homes &AMP; Gardens, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   It offers basic guidelines on healthful eating and food safety,
then it devotes individual chapters to ailments from asthma to
Parkinson's disease and offers nutritional advice for prevention
and treatment. For instance, it says antioxidants like vitamin E
may help prevent the degeneration of brain cells that causes
Parkinson's. Safflower oil, fortified cereal, wheat germ and
soybeans are all good sources, the book advises.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the final chapter is devoted to healing recipes like a
North African bean stew, loaded with beta carotene, another
antioxidant that helps keep the immune system healthy. These Ginger
Oatcakes caught our eye. The oats and fat-free milk make them
healthy; the crystallized ginger makes them delicious.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Oatcakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 pancakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 4 minutes per pan
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fat-free milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup quick-cooking or regular rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   3 slightly beaten egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 slightly beaten egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark-colored corn syrup or molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped crystallized ginger or 1/4 to 1/2
teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Fresh blueberries or sliced banana (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Orange marmalade or maple-flavored syrup (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan heat milk over low heat just until hot,
stirring occasionally. Stir in oats. Remove from heat; let stand
for 5 minutes. Combine egg whites, egg, oil and corn syrup or
molasses; stir into oat mixture. In a medium bowl combine flour,
ginger, baking powder, cinnamon, baking soda and salt. Add oat
mixture all at once to flour mixture; stir just until moistened.
Batter may be covered and stored in the refrigerator for up to 2
days.
</P>
<P>
   For each pancake, pour a scant 1/4 cup batter into a hot,
lightly greased heavy skillet. Cook over medium heat until golden
brown, turning to second sides when pancakes have bubbly surfaces
and edges are slightly dry. If desired, serve pancakes topped with
blueberries or banana and marmalade or syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 106 calories, 4 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 27), 15 grams carbohydrates, 18 milligrams
cholesterol, 189 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Hostess
</P>
<P>
   This one's for the mother who knows how to make guests feel
special, whether it's a party of five on the porch or 50 in a
reception hall. The smart and savvy entertainer who doesn't have to
rediscover the art of the cocktail party because she never lost it.
</P>
<P>
   She's probably borrowed some ideas from Martha Stewart over the
years. But she'll love the fact that more than 300 recipes for
fabulous finger foods have been gathered together in Martha
Stewart's Hors d'Oeuvres Handbook (Clarkson Potter, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ideas, like scooped-out grape cups or 1-inch
breadboxes, seem a little too time consuming, unless of course
mother has a staff. Others, like the miniature jerk chicken
sandwiches tied with chive ribbons, are a tad too precious, but
then we've come to expect that from Martha. But many of the
recipes, like eggplant crisps, sesame-crusted chicken salad tea
sandwiches and figs in a blanket, are downright right-on and would
make any party a hit.
</P>
<P>
   These Blue Cheese Popovers are easier than most _ no hot pans or
hot oil are required. They'd be lovely for Mother's Day brunch.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cheese Popovers
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 dozen
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: 2 hours or more
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-18 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted, plus more for tins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 ounces blue cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon roughly chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk together eggs, milk, melted butter,
flour, salt and pepper. Whisk in cheese and thyme. Transfer the
batter to an airtight container, cover and refrigerate for at least
2 hours or up to 1 day.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Generously butter mini muffin tins
(with 1 1/2-inch cups). Stir batter to mix well. Fill each cup to
the top with the chilled batter. Bake until golden and puffed, 15
to 18 minutes. Repeat until all the batter is used. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 23 calories, 1 gram protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 46), 2 grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams
cholesterol, 29 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
