</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOK-MOM-RECIPES3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mothers Day cookbook recipes
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Purist
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your mom shuns the frozen and canned foods aisles,
insisting on serving her family only what's fresh and ripe at the
moment _ plucking the ingredients directly from the soil. Or maybe
she just fantasizes about it.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, she should devour The Cook and the Gardener: A Year
of Recipes and Writings From the French Countryside (W.W. Norton,
$32.50), the eloquent account of how a young American cook _ with
tenacity, respect and bribes of bread and homemade jam _ pried from
a gruff old Frenchman the mysteries of the magnificent chateau
garden he tended.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Hesser was working for Anne Willan at Ecole de Cuisine La
Varenne, the famed cooking school in Burgundy, when she became
acquainted with Monsieur Milbert, the gruff and intensely private
gardener whose ``tolerance for an intruder is even lower than his
tolerance for the unexpected frost.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hesser, now a food writer for The New York Times, was
determined to win his trust so that she could better understand
``why thyme's intensity fluctuated, why the leeks sweetened with
age, when the raspberries would be at their peak.''
</P>
<P>
   The vivid prose is as irresistible as her simple but
sophisticated recipes, which are arranged by season and prefaced by
essays describing her experiences in the garden and at the stove.
There's nothing contrived here; each is clearly influenced by what
was fresh and ripe at the time. So in that spirit, present Mom with
a chervil plant or some other fresh herb from the local nursery,
and she just may be inspired to take her gift straight to the
kitchen _ perhaps to whip up this lovely lunch.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Egg Salad With Tarragon, Chervil and Chives
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 11 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Don't use new eggs here _ they won't peel easily.
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons best-quality olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 handfuls tender Bibb lettuce, trimmed and washed
</P>
<P>
   2 handfuls lamb's lettuce, trimmed and washed, or mesclun
</P>
<P>
   Coarse or kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon chopped tarragon leaves (about 1-2 branches)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon chopped chervil leaves (about 4 sprigs; if not
available, increase the tarragon to 6 branches)
</P>
<P>
   4 blades chive, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Hard-boil the eggs: Bring a large pot filled with water to a
boil. Add the eggs and cook for 11 minutes. Plunge the eggs in cold
water and peel them. Sometimes it helps to run them under cold
water as you peel them. The water runs between the thin skin that
covers the egg and loosens it, making peeling much easier. Use a
thin knife to cut them in half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk 2 tablespoons of the olive oil, the
mustard and the cream until well-emulsified and smooth. Dress the
greens: In a large mixing bowl, combine the greens, season with
salt and pour over the remaining tablespoon of olive oil. Toss well
to coat all the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Pile the greens on a large round plate. Set the egg halves on
the greens in the center of the plate. Season them with salt and
drizzle on the mustard dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Generously sprinkle the herbs over them, and then some pepper.
Serve immediately. If the eggs are slightly warm, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 217 calories, 10 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 78), 2 grams carbohydrates, 319
milligrams cholesterol, 122 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Vintage Mom
</P>
<P>
   For the mother who is up early on Saturday morning scouting out
flea markets and yard sales for vintage tablecloths, weathered
rolling pins and original Fiesta dishes, Mary Engelbreit's Queen of
the Kitchen Cookbook (Andrews McMeel, $24.95) is the answer.
Engelbreit is a popular artist whose artwork is licensed for all
sorts of products, from calendars to magazines. People magazine
described her as the ``Norman Rockwell of the nineties.'' Her
sentimental artwork appears throughout this cookbook, along with
colorful, homey photographs.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 100 recipes, many developed by Miriam Rubin,
a graduate of the Culinary Institute of America who also worked in
the famed Four Seasons restaurant in New York. The recipes range
from the nostalgic, like diner-style meatloaf, to the seasonal,
like triple-berry summer pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we offer a recipe for Roasted Asparagus With Lemon and
Pine Nuts _ a simple and elegant spring dish.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Asparagus With Lemon and Pine Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds asparagus, tough ends trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon loosely packed slivered lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pine nuts or slivered almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Oil a 13-by-9-inch baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Put asparagus into the prepared baking dish. Sprinkle with the
oil, lemon zest and 1/2 teaspoon kosher salt, turning the asparagus
until evenly coated with the oil. Roast the asparagus, turning
stalks a few times for 15 to 20 minutes, or until tender.
</P>
<P>
   Season the asparagus with pepper and transfer to a serving
platter. Sprinkle the asparagus with the pine nuts, garnish with
the lemon wedges and serve hot or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 85 calories, 3 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 65), 6 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 121
milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Supermom
</P>
<P>
   You know the kind. They work all day, then dash from the office
to pick up the kids at the soccer game and scurry home for a quick
meal before the PTA meeting at school. They love good food; they
just don't always have time to prepare it. The 15-Minute Chef by
Patricia Mack (HPBooks, $15.95) should be her new kitchen manual.
She'll be able to put a delicious meal on the table faster than
Superman can change in a phone booth.
</P>
<P>
   Mack is the longtime food editor of The Record in Hackensack,
N.J. Her book includes 500 recipes, all requiring just a few
ingredients and short cooking times. Many of the recipes can be
whipped together with ingredients that are usually found in a
reasonably stocked pantry. At the front of the book, there's a page
of lists of things to keep in the refrigerator and on the shelves
and some gadgets (like kitchen shears and a hand-held blender) that
will help save time.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the recipes are easy and fast, they don't
sacrifice taste. This Deviled Steak is a perfect example _ it's a
snap to prepare, but good enough for company.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Deviled Steak
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 (1 1/2 pounds) boneless beef
</P>
<P>
   tenderloin, cut in 1-inch thick slices
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Dash of freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler. Place tenderloin on a broiler pan rack that has
been sprayed with nonstick cooking spray. Broil tenderloin 4 inches
from source of heat for 4 to 5 minutes. Turn and grill for 4 to 5
more minutes for medium-rare or to desired doneness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine sherry, butter, mustard, Worcestershire sauce
and pepper in a small saucepan over medium heat. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until bubbly. Stir in the parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon sauce over broiled tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 270 calories, 32 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 1 gram carbohydrates, 103
milligrams cholesterol, 155 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Chocoholic
</P>
<P>
   We know a few folks who don't like chocolate. We've submitted
their names for the X-files. We're pretty sure Nick Malgieri's
Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to Extravagant Showstoppers would
appeal to most moms. And just about everyone in their family, too.
Malgieri is director of the baking department at Peter Kump's
Cooking School in New York, and he offers 380 luscious recipes that
promise to ``send a shiver of delight down the spine of every
chocolate lover.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening chapter covers chocolate basics, from history to
handling. Then it's on to Swiss Chocolate Hazelnut Cake,
Supernatural Brownies, Chocolate Brioche Pudding With Raisins and
Rum and Frozen Chocolate Bourbon Souffle.
</P>
<P>
   We chose one of the simple classics to get you started _ a
chocolate custard pie. There are only a few ingredients, and if you
cheat and get a ready-made pie crust, you could actually make this
for Mother on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Custard Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: several hours
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups half-and-half (or 1 1/4 cups each milk and cream)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces bittersweet chocolate, cut in 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   For the crust:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut in 10 pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   Water (as needed)
</P>
<P>
   When ready to bake the pie, set a rack in the lower third of the
oven and preheat to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: Combine the half-and-half and sugar in a
saucepan. Whisk once or twice to mix and bring to a boil over
medium heat. Remove from heat and whisk in chocolate until smooth.
Continue to whisk until chocolate is melted.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, whisk the eggs with the rum and spices.
Whisk in the chocolate mixture, only until mixed. You want to avoid
making a lot of foam on the custard.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the custard into another bowl and skim any remaining foam
off the surface.
</P>
<P>
   For the crust: In the food processor _combine flour, sugar, salt
and baking powder and pulse several times to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Add butter. Pulse to mix butter in completely. When the butter
is incorporated correctly, there should be no visible chunks of
butter, but the mixture should remain cool and powdery.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg with a fork and add to work bowl. Pulse until dough is
well-combined and begins to hold together. If the dough does not
easily form a ball, add 1/2 teaspoon water, repeating if necessary,
until it does.
</P>
<P>
   Remove dough from processor, press into a disc and wrap in
plastic. Chill dough until firm or for up to several days before
using.
</P>
<P>
   To mix dough by hand _combine dry ingredients in a mixing bowl
and stir several times to mix. Rub butter in, mixing it gently with
fingertips, until it becomes a fine crumble. No visible pieces of
butter should remain, but mixture should stay cool and powdery.
Beat egg with a fork and stir into dough mixture. Continue stirring
until dough holds together in a mass. Wrap and chill as above.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out dough and fit into a 9-inch pie pan. Pour filling into
the pie shell and bake for 35 to 45 minutes, or until all but the
very center of the filling is set. Cool the pie on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with whipped cream or plain.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (includes crust): 416 calories, 11 grams protein, 28
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 60), 34 grams carbohydrates,
246 milligrams cholesterol, 261 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The Sweet Tooth
</P>
<P>
   Even busy moms like to slow down for dessert, though often they
find they just don't have the time to make homemade goodies.
Melanie Barnard has streamlined the preparation of many desserts,
delivering an impressive volume called Short &AMP; Sweet: Sophisticated
Desserts in No Time at All (Houghton Mifflin, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Mom can learn how to make cakes in a single bowl without sifting
flour, creaming butter or separating eggs. The book includes
several recipes for fruits _ both cool and warm. There are
custards, puddings, cookies and tarts.
</P>
<P>
   We tried this Blueberry Corn Cake. A little shifting of the
cornmeal and flour proportions and the use of heavy cream make this
traditional dinner bread a delightful dessert. Barnard suggests
serving with a dollop of lemon curd or lemon yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Blueberry Corn Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 18-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter for greasing pan
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh blueberries (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Butter an 8-inch square baking pan.
In a mixing bowl, whisk together the flour, sugar, cornmeal and
baking powder. In a smaller bowl, whisk together the cream, melted
butter and egg. Stir the liquid ingredients into the dry
ingredients just until blended, then stir in the blueberries.
Scrape the batter into the prepared pan, smoothing the top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until cake is firm and golden, 18 to 20 minutes. Let cool
slightly, then cut into squares and serve warm or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Note: When fresh blueberries are not available, substitute dried
blueberries or cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 230 calories, 3 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 26 grams carbohydrates, 89
milligrams cholesterol, 135 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
