<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Myriad sites let you share recipe ideas and memories
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For many of us, a bedrock memory that lasts a lifetime
is of Mama making magic in the kitchen. As small children, it was
in helping her prepare endless meals that many of us first learned
to take pride in our accomplishments, the joy of giving, to
experiment and to create.
</P>
<P>
   Time, distance and hectic modern life may dim these childhood
memories of cooking and shared family meals with Mama presiding
over it all. But now, the Internet presents a whole new way to
recall this safer and simpler time.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites also give you a chance to share with others and
preserve some of your personal thoughts as well. Here are some
places you may want to visit this Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   SETTING THE STAGE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To set the tone for your trip down memory lane, you must first
visit members.tripod.com/(tilde)cmurchison/holidays /mother.html.
Get ready to sing ``M is for the Million Things She Gave Me'' and
realize what an amazing medium the Internet is.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Search out ``stories around the family table'' at Ragu's
extensive site at www.eat.com/ for a real treat. You will find
essays submitted by people telling their favorite memories of
family meals, and you can contribute yours. This is a special site.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another site to pay a special tribute to your mother and read
the thoughts of others is at www.holidays.net/cgi-bin/momindex.cgi.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUTES THE WORLD OVER
</P>
<P>
   Many people use the Internet to post tributes to their mamas,
and most include recipes. There are many hundreds. Here are just a
few you may want to visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See www.geocities.com/Vienna/5134/mama.html for a tribute to
one Hettie May Long Johnson, a Cajun mama with 12 kids.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A tribute to a Cuban mama can be found at ``La Cocina Cubana''
at www.bpe.com/food/single-articles/cubana.htm. Elaine Sosa starts
her article with, ``I grew up eating better than most kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Italian mamas are represented by a tribute to Mama Vigiano at
www.infoplexcorp.com/ipinfo/mamav.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You can find a tribute to Bergit, a Norwegian mama, and her
recipes at
www.geocities.com./Heartland/Flats/9234/mamasrecipes.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Share your mother's favorite recipes for a cookbook that a
group called ``Mothers Voices'' is putting together called
``Comfort Foods'' at www.mvoices.org/forms/cookbook1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   NOW TO THE KITCHEN
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Let's Get Cooking With Mama'' at
www.geocities.com/NapaValley/2950/ flat-out rejects gourmet recipes
that use obscure ingredients. Here you will find a host of
old-fashioned, easy-to-make, passed-down family recipes. The site
urges you to contribute old-home recipes to the site to ``keep your
heritage alive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A rush of nostalgia is guaranteed when you search out the
recipes in the categories ``Moms'' and ``Mom's Best'' at
www.recipeland.com/newsite/indexcategories.epl.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING DOWN TO BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   When you have had enough nostalgia and are ready to think about
making it a great day for your mom, check the following:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The online version of Ladies' Home Journal at www.lhj.com
offers a wonderful Mother's Day edition that includes
easy-to-follow instructions for the perfect breakfast-in-bed tray,
Sunday brunch, flower arranging and a host of other things you can
do to make it a great day for Mom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For great ideas and recipes for a brunch, go to
food.homearts.com:80/thoughts/enter/46enta36.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Find recipes for kids to make on Mother's Day at
ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/bploegstra/mother.htm.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Banana Split Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (1 pint) chocolate nonfat ice milk or frozen nonfat
yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 prepared 9-inch graham cracker pie shell
</P>
<P>
   2 medium bananas, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup thawed lowfat whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chocolate syrup
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer or food processor on medium speed, beat
frozen ice milk or yogurt until smooth. Using a spatula, carefully
spread over the prepared crust. Cover with plastic wrap and freeze
until firm, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, slice bananas and arrange in a circle over the ice
milk or yogurt. Spread topping over bananas and drizzle with
chocolate syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: Substitute 2 cups fresh strawberries for the bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 257 calories, 6 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 30), 40 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 316
milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constituion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
