<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ENTREPRENEUR06-C     05-05 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ENTREPRENEUR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta entrepreneur aims to help foodies' dreams come true
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So you think your mother's marinara sauce is good
enough to bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Have you told Aunt Jane a million times that if she'd only slap
a label on those jars of pear honey, she'd make a mint?
</P>
<P>
   How about your own secret recipe for barbecue sauce that always
keeps the folks at neighborhood cookouts coming back for more?
</P>
<P>
   Jake Rothschild is ready to help. Twelve years ago, the
36-year-old entrepreneur created an all-natural cocoa mix that he
has successfully marketed, and now he's spun off a whole line of
</P>
<P>
   J D Rothschild &AMP; Co. food products.
</P>
<P>
   He creates many of them from a new kitchen in Atlanta's old
Fourth Ward, a space that he and some partners have worked to
renovate over the last two years. It's at 676 Highland Ave. N.W., a
small block of storefronts that includes the Roman Lily Cafe.
There's a gourmet carryout business called Whisk in the front of
his building, and an ice cream parlor will open in the back in a
few weeks, where the gourmet food products also will be available.
</P>
<P>
   But to get maximum use of the space ad the kitchen, Rothschild
is launching a small-business incubator for folks interested in
creating and marketing a gourmet food product.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so many people say they wish they could do what I'm
doing,'' he said. ``And I love to coach and teach, and I definitely
have the expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild and his partners, Trent Fisher and Kate Yeager, will
walk people through all phases of a project, from developing the
recipe, finding the ingredients, obtaining U.S. Food and Drug
Administration approval, designing the packaging and creating a
business plan. The fee is $50 an hour, with a free initial
consultation. Rothschild estimates that most people will need about
10 hours of instruction, which will include using the FDA-approved
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild got his start while working at the Hardback Cafe in
Chapel Hill, N.C., as a college student. He would complain about
the hot chocolate served there _ the mix was heavy on preservatives
and light on taste. So his boss challenged him to come up with
something better. Rothschild made several attempts, struggling to
find just the right ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he settled on a mix that uses whole milk powder, whole
cream powder and a high grade of cocoa. The result is a hot
chocolate so creamy that it's hard to believe it's from a mix. The
cafe sold 115 cups in the first week, and the cocoa mix has been
more or less a part of Rothschild's life, if not livelihood, ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild's first job out of school was in marketing for Turner
Broadcasting, where he tossed some cocoa mix into the gift baskets
that TBS sent out that year to celebrities and supporters. A
supervisor told Rothschild that he should ``do what Ted would do''
and take his passion for the product and run with it.
</P>
<P>
   So he began marketing the mix, snaring local and national
accounts such as Happy Herman's and Macy's. Through the years, he's
learned the ups and downs: When Macy's hit financial hard times, he
took a hit, too. He tried his hand at running a coffeehouse, the
popular Mocha in Morningside, but eventually chose to work full
time on marketing the cocoa and expanding into other products, such
as preserves and vinaigrette dressings. He now has 45 national and
local accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild credits Atlanta coffee roaster John Martinez as a
guiding hand through the years; now he wants to mentor others
through his incubator program.
</P>
<P>
   His first advice: Keep the day job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to ask a lot of questions, not just tell people
how,'' Rothschild said. ``We will push them to look at why they
want to do this and even if they want to do this. I know a lot of
folks in the corporate world who have that fantasy that one day. .
. . They should probably keep their job and wet their whistle
first.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the incubator program, or to purchase
Rothschild products, call 404-581-0420.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Joournal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
