<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP06-COX     05-05 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orange slices, cream, sherbet whip this treat into shape
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Hunter of Atlanta sent the recipe that most
closely matches Samantha Svensson's recent plea for a mandarin
orange dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Svensson remembered the oranges, gelatin and sherbet, but was
unsure whether it included whipped cream. Several other readers
offered versions with canned pineapple or frozen whipped topping.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Orange Gelatin Dessert
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 hour and 10 minutes to 2 hours, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 small (3-ounce) or 1 large (6-ounce) package(s) orange gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 pint orange sherbet
</P>
<P>
   1 can (11 ounces) mandarin orange slices, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve gelatin in boiling water according to package
directions. Add sherbet and mix well. If sherbet is too hard,
soften in microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Place in refrigerator to set partially, about 40 minutes to 1
hour. Add orange slices, then fold in whipped cream. Place in oiled
1 1/2 quart ring mold. Refrigerate 30 minutes to 1 hour, or until
set.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 353 calories, 12 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 42 grams carbohydrates, 60
milligrams cholesterol, 94 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anne Christensen of Decatur (Ga.) is looking for a mincemeat
custard pie.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June S. Florence of Douglasville (Ga.) didn't have a pencil
handy, but hopes someone else did, during a recent television
cooking show. In it, a California chef prepared a Cobb salad that
included thinly sliced lettuce and lots of chopped fruit, but no
pasta or meat.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Send food news to Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The
deadline is noon two Mondays before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Editor: Susan Puckett at spuckett(at)ajc.com. 404-526-5443.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant editor: Marcia Langhenry at mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
404-526-5418.
</P>
<P>
   Food and nutrition writer: Reagan Walker at rwalker(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   404-526-5856.
</P>
<P>
   Food writer/dining critic: John Kessler at jkessler(at)ajc.com.
404-526-5452.
</P>
<P>
   Locating recipes
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the Stacks Information Service can search our
archives from 1985 to the present to locate recipes for your
favorite dishes. Recipes can be mailed or faxed. Items are $3 each,
$1 extra if faxed. Please leave a voice mail message with your
request at 404-614-2610. If you would rather do your own search on
the World Wide Web, access stacks.ajc.com. The fees: $5.95 for
adults, 24 hours, maximum 20 articles; $2.95 for students, 24
hours, maximum 10 articles; monthly, $9.95, maximum 100 articles.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA, 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
