<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-GLASGOW-ARCHITECTUR     05-05 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GLASGOW-ARCHITECTURE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURING FROM VICTORIAN TO A MODERN MODE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland _ This city has never been known for its
devotion to contemporary architecture. Despite the recent incursion
of Sir Norman Foster's bold exhibition center, which opened last
year and which is known as ``the armadillo,'' the city has mostly
been a place where planners appreciate an old Victorian building
and where Charles Rennie Mackintosh, the great innovator of the
late 19th and early 20th centuries, is still revered.
</P>
<P>
   But Glasgow, which was named the United Kingdom's City of
Architecture and Design for 1999, is looking to the future. Through
the end of the year, it is devoting itself to architecture and
design through a program called Glasgow 1999, a dizzying array of
more than 300 exhibits, building projects, competitions,
conferences, educational programs and special events.
</P>
<P>
   The $62.7 million program, though wide ranging, is placing
particular emphasis on the way architecture and design affect
everyday life. The highlight will be the opening in late June of
the Lighthouse, an architecture, design and urban-planning center
meant to make Glasgow an architectural magnet for the world.
</P>
<P>
   The city has long been proud of its tradition of taking old,
abandoned buildings in the center of town _ like the stately banks
that flourished from tobacco, shipbuilding and ironworks money in
the 18th and 19th centuries _ and finding ways to convert them into
stores, restaurants, apartments and the like.
</P>
<P>
   In the same spirit, the $19.6 million Lighthouse is to be the
new incarnation of the old Glasgow Herald building, Mackintosh's
first major building. Having stood abandoned since The Herald moved
out in the 1980s, the building is being reconstructed by the
Glasgow architects Page &AMP; Park.
</P>
<P>
   When complete, it will be Europe's largest center for design and
architecture, said Sarah Gaventa, a spokeswoman for Glasgow 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction incorporates a startling mix of old and new,
including a tower rising up one side of the old building from which
its new name derives. While preserving Mackintosh's original red
sandstone facade, the architects have built an extension that they
describe as ``a battery pack'' in glass and copper.
</P>
<P>
   About half the size of the original building, the extension
creates a new entrance and houses things like escalators and
elevators. A glass and copper platform, soaring above the building,
will provide spectacular views of the city, while the Lighthouse's
cool, white, contemporary interior is designed to be versatile for
myriad purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Among other features, the Lighthouse will have an interactive
center on Mackintosh's life and work, five areas for permanent and
temporary exhibits, a 100-seat conference room, a cafe and a number
of study centers. ``It's about raising aspirations, about making
people better able to understand why design is relevant,'' Ms.
Gaventa said.
</P>
<P>
   In being selected the year's architecture city, Glasgow beat out
its archrival, Edinburgh, because of Glasgow's ``people-based''
approach to design, Ms. Gaventa said. ``There's a lot of civic
pride here _ people love their city _ and the judges felt that
Glasgow wasn't about grand structures and elitism,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, sponsored by the British Arts Council, provides
the winner a small amount of money and a large amount of favorable
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow is helping to develop a variety of local projects. For
example, it is providing $825,000 to community groups to build
playgrounds in schools and therapy centers at AIDS clinics. It is
also spending $4.1 million in a collaborative effort with artists
and architects to transform five derelict spots around the city
into playgrounds, gardens and other working public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   And this summer, Glasgow plans to open Homes for the Future, a
$16.5 million project in which seven architects and five developers
have joined to create 100 innovative apartments and town houses on
an abandoned site in a once grand section of Charlotte Street.
</P>
<P>
   The project is made up of a number of mini-apartment buildings,
each reflecting the individual taste and vision of the architect.
One slender, five-story tower, designed by the Ushida Findlay
Partnership, is gently curved to evoke Glasgow's shipbuilding
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a pair of buildings known as
``Introvert/Extrovert Houses''; designed by the firm RMJM Scotland,
the buildings each have one side of glass and light and another
almost without windows. The project's acre-and-a-half site has been
home to many things, including an infirmary and a factory, but has
long been derelict, gaining the sort of stigma that usually drives
developers away.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that Homes for the Future will help lure back
Glaswegians who have abandoned the inner city for the suburbs.
``It's about restarting city living, showing a positive approach to
the city center as a place to live,'' said David McAllister, the
principal architect for the firm ROCK DCM, which planned and is
managing the project.
</P>
<P>
   The homes, McAllister said, are not just ``dinky houses'' but
apartments and town houses of various sizes that have been designed
by cutting-edge firms taking new approaches to heating, lighting
and the use of interior space; as such they are meant to be
prototypes, he said. The first tenants are expected to move in this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The homes are priced from $74,000 to $223,000, and some are
available through Glasgow's liberal subsidized-housing program or
as rental properties. A second phase, of 200 more homes, is to be
completed by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow 99 also includes a parade of special exhibits. For the
last few months, the Old Fruitmarket in the center of town has been
the site of a challenging exhibition called ``Vertigo: The Strange
New World of the Contemporary City.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the critic Rowan Moore and designed by the
architectural firm of Caruso St. John, ``Vertigo'' is meant to
provoke as much as to teach, using architectural drawings and
models, videotaped interviews and other audiovisual means to
explore the use of space and the myriad purposes of urban projects,
including Richard Rogers' Millennium Dome in Greenwich, England;
Kazuyo Sejima's high-density public housing project in the suburbs
of Gifu, Japan, and the new World Financial Center in Shanghai. The
exhibit closes on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Among dozens of other exhibits are ``Home,'' which examines the
way people live and how home design has been transformed in the
20th century (it runs on the Glasgow Green from June 14 to Oct.
31), and ``Mies Van Der Rohe: Architecture and Design in Stuttgart,
Barcelona and Brno,'' which runs at the Burrell Collection from May
14 to Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of Mackintosh looms large, of course, not least
because of the resurrection of his prized Herald building. But one
Glasgow 1999 goal is to show that he wasn't the town's only
architect in earlier times. So recognition is also being given to
Alexander (Greek) Thomson, Glasgow's great mid-Victorian architect,
who preceded but has long been overshadowed by Mackintosh.
</P>
<P>
   One of Thomson's most important buildings, Holmwood House, an
ornate villa he designed for a wealthy Glaswegian family, is open
to the public after a two-year restoration by the National Trust
for Scotland. Now, on the house's handsomely decorated walls,
visitors can see the nymphets and classical semi-nude figures that
nuns had painted over when they ran a Roman Catholic School there
in the 1950s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Thomson, whose buildings reflected Greek,
Persian, Hindu and Egyptian influences and whose work has often
been compared with that of Frank Lloyd Wright, is to have his first
major exhibition, ``Alexander Thomson: The Unknown Genius,'' at the
Lighthouse, from June 11 to Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Deyan Sudjic, who is directing the yearlong program, said he
hoped that Glasgow 1999 would leave more than a physical mark on
the city. ``Even more important is the climate of ideas which will
survive,'' he said. ``The year is trying to say: `Look at design
differently. It's not something other, something alien.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
