<HEADLINE>
HEY, PILGRIM, CHECK OUT SAINT ARNOLD'S `HOLY WATER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up Catholic has its share of weird memories: itchy
little scapulars, worn around the neck during Lent, that scraped
tender young skin until it was raw. Or trying to accumulate enough
plenary indulgences for a visa to Purgatory, that strange, murky
bus stop on the road to heaven. Not to mention a lifetime's worth
of guilt, remorse and eternal damnation just for one lousy spring
break's worth of impure thoughts, words and deeds. But, as the pope
said, ``Hey, eternity ain't easy, pal.'' Or words to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Catholics have St. Arnold, the patron saint
of brewers.
</P>
<P>
   And as far as I know, Catholicism is the only religion that has
intentionally beatified an imbiber. To paraphrase British author
and professional cynic David Lodge, ``Now, that's my kind of
mumbo-jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me in a roundabout way to the Saint Arnold Brewing
Co., founded as Houston's first microbrewery in October 1993.
Offering three beers year-round, and five seasonal brews, Saint
Arnold uses no additives or preservatives and doesn't pasteurize,
letting the flavors shine through.
</P>
<P>
   Take its Winter Stout, for example, released Dec. 15. It's a
malty, creamy brew with strong caramel and coffee accents derived
from a specialty Caravienne malt imported from Belgium. A
combination of domestic Cascades and Liberty hops produces a hint
of floral and citrus. The brewery also says that the light
fruitiness is derived from a proprietary yeast strain.
</P>
<P>
   My only caveat (yes, it's Latin; get over it) _ I wanted a bit
more chewiness in the texture instead of a somewhat pervasive
wateriness. On balance, however, Saint Arnold's gets my official
Imprimatur (Seal of Approval).
</P>
<P>
   But how, you inquire, did Arnold achieve sainthood? Glad you
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Born to a prominent Austrian family in 580, St. Arnold was
proclaimed bishop of Metz, France, in 612, and spent his holy life
warning peasants about the dangers of drinking water. Beer was
safer, he opined; ``From man's sweat and God's love, beer came into
the world.'' He died in 640. A year later, the people of Metz
requested that his body be exhumed and reburied in their Church of
the Holy Apostles. During the arduous trip, the tired porters and
followers stopped at a tavern in Champignuelles. There was only one
mug of beer to be shared, but that mug never ran dry, and all the
thirsty pilgrims were satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of puts a new spin on the term ``holy water,'' eh?
</P>
<P>
   (Brian Melton writes a beer column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-SINGLES-900&AMP;ADD-     05-05 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-SINGLES-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCRAMBLING TO FIND CUPID IN A HAYSTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Ohio, Ind., Neb., N.D., S.D.  
 (jt)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW WESTON, Ohio _ Myron Stammen was still milking his cows when
his guests arrived one Saturday evening, but nobody seemed to mind.
It was an understanding crowd, single farmers like himself, well
aware of the demands and routines of farm life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if it hadn't been raining buckets all day, it's a good
bet that fewer of the farmers would have been able to break away
from their own fields to make it to Stammen's. Some drove hours to
this stretch of corn and bean country in western Ohio, coming from
across the state, from Indiana, Illinois, even upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   They were all part of Singles in Agriculture, which sprang up to
provide solace and social life to farm people. On this evening, 35
men and women, mostly in their 40s and 50s, piled into the
high-roofed white barn that Stammen had cleared of tractors and
equipment and hung with green and yellow crepe paper streamers.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had brought covered dishes, and they were laid out on a
table Stammen usually uses for work tools: deviled eggs, country
ham, berry pies. The guests square-danced and did something called
a waterfall, where the men and women line up and dance with
whoever's next in line. The highlight came when everyone sat on hay
bales near the silage wagon and the combine heads to watch videos
of a plowing contest. Stammen was proud to present the plowing
display: the contests are feats of skill, he says, because the
field has to be plowed so straight it looks like ``a pair of
corduroy jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also hopes that at one of these events, he will meet a
woman who will want to share his life on the 330-acre farm he is so
proud of. At 40, Stammen, with his compact build and hands
work-roughened to the consistency of sandpaper, has been looking
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   A typical brushoff, he said, came from a woman he had a date
with about 10 years ago. ``When I picked her up, she asked me what
kind of farmer I was, and I said I was a dairy farmer,'' he
recalled, still smoldering as he pushed up the sleeves of his plaid
snap-front shirt. ``She took one look and said, `Oooh, that sounds
like work.' Well, if I could have, I would have put the car in
reverse and told her to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a single farmer isn't just a temporary inconvenience these
days. Farm life can be a hard sell, and it's getting harder all the
time. Stammen needs someone who appreciates the fact that his days
and a good part of his evenings are absorbed with his 140
Holsteins, a scattering of hogs and his careful rows of grain. He
needs someone who doesn't mind that his mother lives on the farm,
that a trip to town takes you to New Weston, Ohio (population 148),
and that the closest big city is 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The demographics of farming are not exactly a Cupid's dream.
There are fewer and fewer farmers: in its 1997 census, the
Agriculture Department found only 1.9 million farms, half as many
as 40 years before. Farmers are also older, and the department says
that more than 90 percent are men. (That figure doesn't include
women who work farms with their husbands, only those who are the
sole or primary farmer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to meet people out in the middle of the prairie,''
said Fred Scheevel, 45, a bachelor farmer who raises cattle and
grows corn and wheat on land his grandparents began farming on the
border of Minnesota and Iowa around the turn of the century. ``A
lot of the females in this part of the country are ladies who came
from farm backgrounds and know how tough it is. Once they get off
to school, they're gone. They're headed for better-paying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheevel, who lives ``a good two miles from the nearest blacktop
road,'' has tried his luck with those who have stayed close to home
and has had more than his share of fix-ups and blind dates. But the
women don't stick around for long. ``There's a lot of nights where
you're just tired, and, oh, you fall asleep reading the paper,'' he
said. ``A lot of them figure that's not their kind of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Farming is getting more expensive, too. Farms are getting
bigger, as farmers leaving the business sell out to those still in
it. Equipment, chemicals, computers, insurance _ they all cost more
money. And farmers have been buffeted by low prices for things like
wheat and hogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am trying to live with income from 20 years ago,'' said
Stammen, who is $300,000 in debt. ``For a lady to accept me in a
relationship with that type of responsibility, it's a real
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The money crunch can put added pressure on single farmers to
marry: they need help on the farm or a second nonfarm income. But
it also makes it harder for them to make the effort to find a mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling to meet someone costs money,'' said Bill Rosin, 50,
an organic farmer who lives near Selby, S.D., not far from the
North Dakota border. Rosin said he was ``pretty serious about a
girl a couple of years ago,'' but she would have had to give up her
job to move. ``She kind of wanted a guarantee that we'd prosper out
here,'' he said. ``There aren't any guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its freedom and fulfillment, farm life can be isolating.
Neal Rau, 39, who raises cattle and grows grain with his parents in
Medina, N.D., said he began a Dale Carnegie course 32 miles away,
in Jamestown, ``just to get back some of my social skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Heinze, 45, who farms near Dazey, N.D., believes his
marriage of 15 years failed largely because his wife didn't share
his enthusiasm for raising cattle and growing sunflowers, barley
and alfalfa. After his divorce five years ago, Heinze thought he
would be remarried within a year. But it hasn't worked out that
way. He has trolled the bars in Fargo, 72 miles away, but ``it's
hard to talk to city girls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers who have tried dating services say they often come up
empty. And as if to underline the distance between the single
farmer and true romance, a rural Midwestern singles newspaper is
crammed with advertisements for mail-order brides: ``Beautiful
Filipina Ladies Want You!'' and ``Exotic Pacific Island Ladies Seek
Correspondence!''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Singles in Agriculture has become an important
social outlet. The group grew out of a 1984 article in Farm
Journal, ``Finding a Mate Got You Buffaloed?'' The magazine invited
readers looking for mates to send in their own little personal
notices. When 2,700 poured in, the editors encouraged the formation
of a rural singles group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
