<HEADER>
A5383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-SINGLES-2NDTAKE-     05-05 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-SINGLES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW WESTON: singles group.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nearly 1,300 members in more than 40 states _ men and women
who farm or have farm backgrounds _ Singles chapters plan events
like the trip to the Ohio Beef Expo and Trade Show or the South
Dakota Farm Show Fling. Some farmers travel hundreds of miles for
these weekends, looking for mates or simply to socialize. They chat
as they eyeball the latest in milking machines or farrowing pens.
There might be a tour of Oklahoma City's Cowboy Hall of Fame or a
hayride on a Minnesota farm. At night, there is almost always a
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking and smoking are frowned upon, and cohabiting in the
hotel rooms ``is definitely, definitely discouraged,'' said Dee
Pounds, the vice president of Singles in Agriculture, a farmer
turned Culligan man from Falls City, Neb. And there is usually a
church service on Sunday. ``It's a real good organization,'' Pounds
said. ``It's got good morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Every event ends with a kind of group hug, where the members
form two concentric circles, men in one, women in the other. The
circles rotate so that each man ends up hugging each woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're single, sometimes you don't get that many hugs,''
said Jan Hladik, a 55-year-old widow who was at Stammen's
gathering. ``You're alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to some farmers is the organization's singles
directory, issued four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Porter, 36, who works his parents' farm near Grandin, N.D.,
got four or five letters after posting this pitch:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tired of being Mr. Nice Guy, but that's who I am. This
brown-haired, nonsmoking dairy farmer has been looking for love and
friendship in all the wrong places. Green acres is the place I'll
be. Farm living is the life for me. Go ahead, write me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has written back and thinks he might like a woman in Illinois
who hauls asphalt in a semitrailer rig.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Jones, a member of the Ohio chapter, found Bill Rosin
through the directory and even went to see him in South Dakota
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his having to feed his cows and all, he just couldn't
leave, so I went out there,'' said Ms. Jones, who is an egg grader
for the Agriculture Department. ``I thought it was going well, but
he just put on the brakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosin said that Ms. Jones ``kind of put me on the spot and said,
`Commit or I'm gonna move on.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess she kind of fell for me faster than I was ready for,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Stammen's Saturday-night party, Ms. Jones, who is 40 and
divorced, said she was really hoping to settle down with a farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people in the city don't have the family values I
was raised with,'' said Ms. Jones, who grew up on an egg farm near
Toledo. ``Sure, when I was 18, I thought farm guys were pretty
boring, but now, with what I've been through, boring would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some singles have had more dating success. Liz Fallis, 55, an
accountant from Shelbyville, Ind., showed up at Stammen's with
Gordon Pavey, 60, whom she has been dating since they met a few
months ago through the Indiana Singles chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Stammen knows that many members attend just for the dancing and
socializing, but he believes the events should have an educational
component, too. The plowing show was carefully planned, with a
speech by Bill Goettenoeller, a champion plower, who used a felt
tip pen to draw a schematic diagram of fields and furrows on an
easel and advised the farmers to ``always plow straight, because
even a badly plowed row looks better straight.''
</P>
<P>
   At one of his barn dances, Stammen had a friend who teaches
psychology at a community college give his guests a personality
test. On Valentine's Day 1998, he invited the editor of Successful
Farming magazine to speak. ``He spoke on the 10 focuses of family
farming, how to add joy to your family farm,'' Stammen said. ``I
was disappointed people weren't as interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Stammen has met a few women through Singles in Agriculture, but
nothing has worked out yet. Recently, he had hopes for a dairy
farmer's daughter from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought me and her had some very nice positives,'' he said.
But she wouldn't give him her number. ``I didn't think my asking
for her phone number was out of line, being that she was so far
away. I guess I was barking up the wrong tree.''
</P>
<P>
   At his party, Stammen's hopes were piqued by a woman from
Lafayette, Ind., who danced with him and seemed to enjoy the tour
of his house and farm. But when Stammen called to ask her out, the
response was discouraging. ``I was told this point-blank: that I
worked too much. She said, `You have to have some fun in life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that romantic near miss, Stammen blew out a quiet
breath. ``I've been through this process so many times,'' he said.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
