<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GYM-COMPUTER-ART-     05-05 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GYM-COMPUTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FITNESS COACH WITH A MUSCULAR MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Wash., Pa., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By VERNE KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The fit and not so fit were straining on weight
machines and panting on treadmills the other night at the Ketchum
Downtown YMCA. Grimacing with effort and dripping with sweat, they
toned bodies that, in some cases, showed signs of a few dietary
indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring the scene was a personal trainer who counted every
pound lifted and offered advice like ``go slower.'' But this
trainer lacked the defined muscles and tight shirt typical of such
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer, tucked away in another room, was a computer. What
it lacked in physical strength it made up for in its ability to
monitor nearly every piece of fitness gear, recall the workouts of
hundreds of members and calculate the calories burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, you carried a card and filled it out _ when
you remembered to bring it,'' said Mounir Ghaly, a bank marketing
manager who was at a computer kiosk and scrolling through detailed
lists of his workouts. ``This keeps track of everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   In many gyms, members manage their own fitness routines or pay
for a personal trainer to help them. But now some gyms are using
computers that remind exercisers how many leg curls to do, what
height to place the seat, how many minutes to run on the treadmill.
People can also use the systems to communicate with the gym staff
by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   While such features may help the customer, they are also
intended to benefit the gym, by making the equipment more
accessible to people who otherwise might not take out a membership.
These electronic trainers also let the staff monitor clients'
attendance, perhaps reducing the dropout rate by giving the gym
information that can be used to sell membership renewals or
encourage customers to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can print out a member's record and say, `This is the level
where you started, this is where you are now, and this is how many
calories you burned last month,''' said Rosanne Malogolowkin, the
fitness and health director at the Ketchum Downtown YMCA. ``It
helps their motivation a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of such technology may be too great for some
fitness centers. In addition, some patrons are reluctant to use
these systems, and others cannot use them because the kind of
exercising they do is not compatible with wires and sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Herb McMillan, an airline pilot, who was loading a bar with
weights at the YMCA, would have to type all of his lifting records
into the electronic trainer by hand because the kind of exercising
he does cannot be tallied by the computer. Instead, he keeps mental
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always done it this way,'' McMillan said. ``I'm
old-fashioned. I'm a creature of habit.''
</P>
<P>
   To use the electronic trainer here at this vast YMCA, members
must complete a medical evaluation by staff members and try out the
fitness equipment with one of the gym's counselors.
</P>
<P>
   After getting set up, members log on to the system and call up
their routines. Each person enters a personal identity code at a
kiosk that looks like an automated teller machine and then again at
touch screens on each piece of fitness equipment.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening, Eve Bonham, a legal secretary, was ready to
work her pectorals on an inclined bench press machine. After
entering her personal code, Ms. Bonham followed the instructions on
the display screen to raise the seat to the fifth rung and set the
weights at 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then she started lifting, keeping her eyes on the screen as it
counted down to her goal of 8 to 12 repetitions. A graphic told her
how far to push the weights and pull the handles back. She avoided
getting a beep for bad form, which can mean having to do the
repetition over.
</P>
<P>
   In a few instances, the instruction ``go slower'' appeared
because the computer had decided that Ms. Bonham was pumping iron
too quickly to give her muscles an optimum workout. But in the end,
she did well enough to receive a few beeps of praise and a ``good
job'' on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I like that sound,'' Ms. Bonham said as she pressed
``done'' and read the instructions for which machine to visit next.
``It says, `Good job, top of target,' like it's congratulating
me.''
</P>
<P>
   What guides exercisers through their routines here is the
Fitlinxx interactive fitness network, made by the Fitlinxx company
of Stamford, Conn. Its system has been on the market since 1995 and
is used by about 200 gyms in the United States, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The other major manufacturer of electronic trainers is
Technogym, based in Italy. Its equipment, called the Technogym
system, has been sold since 1996 and is used by nearly 66 fitness
clubs in the United States, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 35 percent of all new gym members quit in the first year,
according to the International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub
Association. But Fitlinxx says the dropout rate in Fitlinxx gyms
averages 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Tyner, marketing manager at the Seattle headquarters of
Technogym's American subsidiary, said her company's product enabled
gym staff members to better track clients' progress.
</P>
<P>
   She gave the example of a fitness counselor, who, by reviewing
the records, spots a slacking client and tells him: ``Hey, Joe,
you're not doing your ab crunches. You can't improve if you don't
do the training.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Fitlinxx setup, every fitness machine is wired to a central
computer. Data, like the number of pounds an exerciser lifts, are
sent to the computer and added to a person's file. Nearly 1,300 of
the Ketchum Downtown YMCA's 6,300 members are enrolled in Fitlinxx.
Using the system is free with a regular membership.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In looking through his records, Ghaly, the bank manager, noticed
that he had an e-mail message from a human fitness counselor who
wrote ``you did very well today'' and asked about scheduling an
appointment. The file also showed that Ghaly had lifted 7,228
pounds in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't come in today, I think I would have fallen below
target,'' he said after deciphering a chart on the screen that
showed he had burned 1,000 calories from exercise in the last
month, equal to about 90 minutes of jogging.
</P>
<P>
   Technogym offers mostly similar features with a few differences,
like providing a video demonstration of how to use fitness
equipment and telling treadmill users at the end of their jogging
that they have completed, for example, the equivalent of 10 percent
of the New York City Marathon, with the distance shown on a map of
the route.
</P>
<P>
   The Technogym system has a wireless design linking the exercise
machines to the central computer and gym kiosk. Exercisers must use
the equivalent of a personal floppy disk. They insert computer
keys, about the size of house keys but with microchips embedded,
into the fitness machines' consoles.
</P>
<P>
   The keys are programmed with users' workout routines and record
their performances. Exercisers automatically download the data from
their workout when they insert their keys into the kiosk to sign
out.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from assisting exercisers and helping to alert the gym
staff to people who might be at risk of quitting, electronic
trainers also put staff members under scrutiny. The computer
records allow gym managers to more easily single out employees
whose clients have a high dropout rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to assess which fitness counselors are doing well
and which aren't,'' said Ms. Malogolowkin, the YMCA's director of
health and fitness. ``That way you can give them extra training.''
</P>
<P>
   One market where electronic trainer manufacturers expect growth
is in hospitals, to help people with heart problems, diabetes and
sports injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 620 patients are enrolled on Fitlinxx at any one time at
the Healthplex Sports Club, a fitness center for patients and the
public that is part of the Crozer-Keystone medical campus in
Springfield, Pa., said Steve Morgan, the sports club's director of
health and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   The system allows physical therapists to be sure that clients
are following instructions, Morgan said, offering closer monitoring
without having to pay for more therapists.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the venue, electronic trainers are not cheap.
Setting up an average gym costs at least $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   But some in the gym industry think that is too much of an
investment for the return.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the amount of money you have to spend versus the benefits,
these systems cost too much,'' said John Platero, director of
personal training in the California clubs of L.A. Fitness, a chain
based in Newport Beach, Calif. ``It's just another gadget to get
people to exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Fitness does not have electronic trainers but does have a
computer in at least one of its Arizona health clubs that gives
video demonstrations and exercise recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Niemeyer, a record company manager who goes to the YMCA
gym three times a week, said she was too lazy to use Fitlinxx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably has to do with the time factor and, shall we say,
fear of the unknown,'' Ms. Niemeyer said while sitting on an
abdomen exercise machine. ``I haven't even given it the benefit of
the doubt. This is where I really try to forget everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ina Van Der Laan, a city transportation engineer, uses the
electronic trainer diligently. A little breathless after a
30-minute stationary bicycle ride, Ms. Van Der Laan questioned how
much it really helped her get in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system keeps me honest,'' said Ms. Van Der Laan, who also
works out with a human trainer.
</P>
<P>
   But scrolling through her fitness records, clearly pleased to
add up the burned calories, she said: ``This isn't anything you
have to have. This is fun to look at, but it doesn't drive me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
