<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE GOOD BBQ OUTSIDE TEXAS? THESE GUYS SEEM TO THINK SO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no more holy subject in Texas than barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you could say Friday-night football ranks high, but even
those games are preceded by a barbecue. The same goes for the
college game and what little is left of the professional sport.
</P>
<P>
   No, barbecue is the energy source that drives the state. It is
as important as oil and gas. Politics cannot be conducted in Texas
without barbecue. Anything worth doing is worth doing over a
barbecue. And if you barbecue in Texas, you use beef.
</P>
<P>
   That is going to make ``Barbecue America, A Pilgrimage in Search
of America's Best Barbecue'' (Time-Life Books, $24.95) a difficult
sell south of the Red River.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Rick Browne and Jack Bettridge, ``Barbecue'' is an
open-minded book that includes everything from California salmon
barbecues to clams and mussels and oysters on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the writers _ who admit they knew little of barbecue
until they were well into their 40s _ herald the pig-pit cultures
of Arkansas and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   They don't even skip the pedestrian grilling practices for
chicken, hot dogs and bologna.
</P>
<P>
   That will be off-putting to a lot of Texans. Here, we might
grill fish, but we don't barbecue clams and mussels. In this state,
barbecue is a recognized religion and must be accompanied by dry
rubs, mesquite wood and abounding reverence.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is just ``cooking out.''
</P>
<P>
   Texans will take heart in knowing that there are other places on
the planet where barbecue is revered. For three years, the authors
traveled the United States. They found the Midwest mecca of
barbecue in Kansas City; they went to the Mardi Gras of mobile
smokers at the annual ``Memphis in May'' cook-off.
</P>
<P>
   At one of his first cook-offs, Bettridge (who openly admits
being from Connecticut) received his initial communion of sorts. He
writes: ``The taste of pig and smoke and spice and sauce, all
commingling in meat so tender I hardly needed teeth to eat it. I
pressed it to the roof of my mouth with my tongue, savoring the
complexity of the flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, the co-author and photographer, you should know, is from
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The two writers did get to Texas on their cross-country trek.
After covering the Possum Town Pork Forkers and Aporkalypse Now at
the Memphis cook-off, they came through Fort Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Here, they met the tastes and reputation of Sonny Bryan's in
Dallas. Also, they caught Jim Griffin of Wichita Falls cooking for
a Knights of Columbus Hall in Arlington, and Dennis Keuter smoking
away for a VFW Post in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   The writers acknowledge Texas as the premier spot for barbecued
brisket. But they in no way discount the curls of smoke that arise
from the rest of the land.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the scene to be found somewhere in America every
weekend, they write: ``So much smoke wafts across the horizon that
it looks like some kind of industrial inferno. On closer
inspection, it turns out to be the fumes put off when 300 teams of
barbecue fanatics take over three huge parking lots and cook up
something delectable!''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a recipe from ``Barbecue America.'' It is a different
but doable concoction for smoked chicken. A couple of changes have
been made to adapt it to home use.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BEER BUTT BIRD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   One 4- to 5-pound chicken
</P>
<P>
   Dry rub:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon raw sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon onion powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry yellow mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely ground sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Basting spray:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Steaming liquid:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces of your favorite beer (canned fruit juice can be
substituted)
</P>
<P>
   Wash, dry and season chicken generously inside and out with rub.
Work mixture well into skin and under skin wherever possible. Set
aside, covered, in refrigerator for approximately 2 hours. Drink
half the can of beer if you like. Insert the can, and the remaining
beer, in the chicken cavity so that the legs and the can itself
hold the chicken upright. Place on smoker grill. This positioning
does two things: First, it helps drain off fat as the chicken
cooks; second, the beer steams the inside of the chicken, making it
very moist.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke 2 to 2 1/2 hours, spraying with basting spray several
times, until chicken is done and internal temperature is 180
degress for whole chicken. Carefully remove the bird from the grill
and ease the can out of the cavity. Place on serving tray and
carve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 324 calories, 19 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 108 milligrams cholesterol,
431 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
