<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS &LR;      05-05 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE NOT OVER FOR BROTHER OF EXECUTED MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALF MOON BAY, Calif. _ With his favorite West African music
playing on the stereo, waves crashing in the distance and an
endless expanse of blue sky stretched out before him, William
Babbitt smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't cried since I left my brother's lifeless shell,'' he
said Tuesday, 12 hours after watching his brother, convicted
murderer Manuel Pina Babbitt, put to death by lethal injection in
the old gas chamber at the San Quentin Prison.
</P>
<P>
   After waging a long, tiring and ultimately futile campaign to
save his brother's life, William Babbitt, 56, said he was happy to
know that his brother was at peace. But he said his battles were
not over.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue to speak out against the death penalty, which
he called ``a form of ethnic cleansing,'' and to help people who
find themselves in the same dilemma he was in 18 years ago: turning
a loved one in for a violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1980, after hearing about the killing of an elderly
Sacramento woman, Babbitt suspected his younger brother of
committing the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Schendel, 78, was found badly beaten in her apartment, her
dentures broken and her pillow soaked with blood. He knew Manuel, a
Vietnam veteran, was psychologically damaged by the trauma of
combat, but he had never imagined him capable of murder. Then, he
found a lighter with the initials ``LS'' in Manuel's coat pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt went to the Sacramento Police Department, saying he
wanted to get counseling for his brother and offered to apprehend
him. He said he had been given assurances his brother would get the
necessary help.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of a taped arrest interview with
Manuel Babbitt, Detective Terry Brown says, ``You know you're not
gonna go to the gas chamber or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Police Department says it never made any promises
to either Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   William Babbitt said he deserved some recognition for what he
had done and is furious at Gov. Gray Davis for denying the clemency
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor slapped me in the face after I did the
right thing,'' said Babbitt, his face slightly hollow after four
days of fasting. He said he was fasting to atone for not taking his
brother off the streets earlier and for the pain inflicted on both
families.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the state to enact a law that would prevent a person
from getting the death penalty if a family member has turned him
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did to Manny sends the wrong message,'' he said.
``This can happen to any family. There's going to be grandmas or
aunties out there _ maybe they know their loved one did that
shooting at the mom-and-pop store down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, his wife, Linda, a nephew and a grandson spent Tuesday
relaxing in Half Moon Bay. The Babbitts, who live in Sacramento,
have raised five children in close to 30 years of marriage _ three
of Linda's from a previous marriage and a niece and nephew of
William Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   William Babbitt was the only relative his brother would allow as
a witness to the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his last words to me was, `Billy, don't beg,''' Babbitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, the day after he turned 50, Manuel Babbitt was
strapped down in ``the gray wolf,'' his term for the death chamber.
The gray wolf, Babbitt explained, is a predator often used as a
scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel looked at his brother, smiled, then closed his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   William Babbitt smiled back and remained smiling for most of the
eight minutes it took for the lethal poisons to stop Manuel's
breathing and heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was smiling because I knew Manny's pain and suffering was
over,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   He also looked over to the Schendel family, seated in a
semi-circle just a few feet from the windows of the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pleaded to meet the gaze of those who readily accepted the
demise of my brother,'' he said. ``I wanted their eyes to meet my
eyes because I wanted them to know everything's going to be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Schendel family did not look at him. He said he
harbored no malice toward them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
