<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DEBT-TECH-ART-2TA     05-05 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DEBT-TECH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN COLLECTION SOFTWARE RUNS, DEBTORS CAN'T HIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kan., Minn., Calif., Mo., Ga., Colo. Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Americans taking on more and more debt, high-tech
collection tactics are making it easier to find debtors and
encourage them to pay up. Or else.
</P>
<P>
   Debt-collection software with names like the Sting, Optimizer
and Determinator help collection agencies find elusive debtors,
phone them and make a plan for them to pay off what they owe.
Programs using artificial intelligence can gauge the likelihood
that a debtor will pay up, and they can match debtors with
collectors who fit their style.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about the customary ways of thinking about
how people buy and sell things with credit, the old paradigms are
being outstripped by new technology,'' said Ronald Griffin, a law
professor who teaches a debtor-creditor relations course at
Washburn University in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   As of February, American consumers had amassed $1.3 trillion in
outstanding installment debt, up 7 percent from the previous year,
according to the Federal Reserve. In 1997, the most recent year for
which data are available, debt totaling $247.4 billion was sent to
collection agencies, which recovered $32.2 billion that year,
according to the American Collectors Association, a 3,600-member
trade group based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Modern debt collectors look back with some nostalgia at the days
when they worked from 4-by-6-inch index cards in shoeboxes. Now
computers dig through proprietary databases, find and dial numbers,
determine when debtors are most likely to be home, improve the
efficiency of telephone collection centers, calculate how risky a
holder of a credit card or mortgage is and generate letters and
scripts for phone calls. With some of these applications running,
you can't hide.
</P>
<P>
   Debt collection agencies rely on the sale of bad debt. After a
bill is overdue for a certain length of time, credit card companies
and other creditors often sell the debt for pennies on the dollar
to agencies, which are allowed to keep anything they can extract
from the debtor.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth it for the creditor, which can at least collect
something on debt that would have been a total loss otherwise, and
it's worth it for the collection agency, which is more skilled and
experienced than Visa and Chase Manhattan in the art of mining
deadbeat accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the collector's first step is to find where to find
the debtors _ or customers, as they are called at one agency,
Exterra Private Recovery in Walnut Creek, Calif. (``We don't allow
the D word here,'' said Barbara Price, the company's co-founder and
executive vice president.) Banks and other credit providers want to
keep customers by having collectors work out a payment plan _
courteously.
</P>
<P>
   Computer terminals from far-flung locations can use the Internet
to tap into the system, so some collection agents can work from
home. That is a boon to at-home parents, handicapped workers and
agencies hungry for skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   One star account manager, Priscilla Corley, has been with
Exterra since it opened in 1997. Using databases and software made
by Rothenberg Systems International, Ms. Corley finds people with
bad debt by tracing them through other creditors listed in their
credit reports, who might know the customers' whereabouts. The
agency also uses a variety of other directories and databases.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday, Ms. Corley was on the phone while
studying her computer screen, narrowing in on a lead. She got the
caretaker of the debtor's mother to give her the phone number of a
close relative of the debtor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Corley, who recently won a lease for a 1999 Cadillac from
Exterra for her productivity, handed the number over to her
partner, Marla McCown, to follow up. Ms. McCown's wall is covered
with 10 overnight mail envelopes, marked with the dollar amounts of
the payments that arrived in them.
</P>
<P>
   Then a manager announced the amounts collected during the
morning. Everyone stood and waved plastic noisemakers that are
shaped like hands, creating a clackety applause. Managers want to
keep the job interesting, in a field where annual turnover rates of
40 percent to 80 percent are common. It can be frustrating for
callers to find debtors and put up with verbal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Once debtors have been found, collectors try to get in touch
with them by phone or through the mail or through neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Dialing software places the calls, and, if a person answers, the
machine passes the person along to an available collector. That
saves the collector the trouble of dialing or dealing with busy
signals or answering machines. The dialing software that automates
this task includes programs like the Optimizer, by Centerforce
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The dialers' software is called predictive because it has a
strategy. ``The odds are, if you're not there Monday at 9 a.m.,
then you won't be on Tuesday or Wednesday at 9 so the machine will
try again at noon, in the afternoon and the next day in the
evening,'' said Jon Mazzoli, senior vice president at Outsourcing
Solutions, a collection agency in Chesterfield, Mo., that tries to
track down 10 million debtors a year.
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing Solutions' technology can predict when a collector
will finish a call, dialing the next call so the collector can go
straight to the new debtor without losing any time. (This is the
same technological advance that brings you those hang-up calls at
supper time from telephone solicitors.)
</P>
<P>
   In half the debt-collection and sales offices with predictive
dialers, collectors have been able to triple the time they spend on
the phone talking to people, to 45 minutes an hour from 15 minutes,
said Tom Buiel, the vice president for domestic sales at Melita
International, a telecommunications software company in Norcross,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Many collectors use a computer scoring system to figure out the
likelihood that a bad debt will be paid. Some programs way use
artificial intelligence so they ``learn'' from and incorporate
earlier collection results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We typically look at several hundred characteristics, 300 or
400 or 500 characteristics, for an individual,'' said Bernhard
Nann, president and co-founder of Narex, in Lakewood, Colo., a
company that was set up in 1995 to develop debt collection programs
that use artificial intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Based on information about the debtor _ like the size of the
person's previous debts and how quickly they were repaid _ the
company determines which kinds of letters and calls the person
should receive. Or it decides that the debt is ``self-curing,''
something that will be paid without a reminder. The results are
plugged back into the system to help the software make future
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The computer screens collectors see can also help direct their
work. In Sweden, one program puts a face with either a smile or a
frown on the account on the screen, which tells collectors what
tone of voice to use with the debtor, said Susan Magrino, vice
president of Rothenberg Systems International. And Magellan
software provides scripts that tell collectors which questions to
ask after gathering each bit of new information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine does the thinking, so the agent doesn't have to,''
said Diane Katzaman, a senior product marketing manager at Melita,
which created Magellan.
</P>
<P>
   Software can also rate consumers' creditworthiness. The Fair,
Isaac Co., a credit scoring company in San Rafael, Calif., that was
founded in 1956, was one of the first to take many factors into
account to come up with a credit rating. While many consumers
complain about the rigidity of such scores, some in the debt
collection industry say the scores are fair because they disregard
race, sex, religion and birthplace, focusing more on credit
histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Machines are absolutely dead fair,'' said Ted Crooks,
executive director of the scientific staff at HNC Software, which
creates debt scoring programs. ``They don't know what color you are
or anything about you _ they just know the data and the account
history, and that people with data like yours had this kind of
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology like this will benefit all of society, said Vijay S.
Mookerjee, an associate professor of information systems at the
University of Washington Business School. For small-scale lending,
``it is just not cost-effective for the bank or lending agency to
use human capabilities to do that when you can really boil it down
and optimize the profile and do it automatically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So do all of these innovations result in the collection of more
money? The results are mixed. Recovery rates at consumer collection
companies reached a four-year high in 1997, according to Credit
Collections News and the Credit Collections Directory, with an
average recovery rate of 24.5 percent among the 300 agencies
surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Collectors Association traced a decline in the
percentage of debt that was collected by about 300 agencies, to 13
percent in 1997 from 22 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting debt may be easier now because the careful screening
and scoring of people applying for credit means that bill payers
are more likely to be reliable. The strong economy also makes it
easier to collect debts. And because creditors almost always regard
fresher debts as easier to collect, some creditors are placing
their overdue accounts with collection agencies sooner than they
used to.
</P>
<P>
   But some creditors are waiting longer before turning to
collection agencies. Now that more high-tech collection tools are
widely available, a creditor will often try to use them first,
before selling debts to an agency. Skimming the cream off their
debts, many banks and credit card companies are dealing with the
fresher, more easily collectible debts themselves, leaving the
harder, older ones for the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're being asked to do more and more for their clients at
less and less of a rate,'' said Toni Nuernberg, the chief operating
officer of the American Collectors Association.
</P>
<P>
   They are asked to be more efficient and, yes, nicer than they
used to be. As Ms. McCown sifted through the form letters she can
send from Exterra _ the Demand letter, the Broken Promise letter,
the Broken Promise on Settlement letter _ she explained her
philosophy of working with her ``customers'': ``Just be nice, and
give them the opposite from what they're giving you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
