<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUNDRA-HAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL-SIZE TUNDRA PASSES COWPOKES' `HAT TEST'   
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS PHOTO CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 TEST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICKENBURG, Ariz. - Leaning on a tailgate, the three cowboys
were talking pickup trucks. Full-size pickup trucks. Uniquely
American. Big as the land.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, they'd be discussing the merits of Chevys and Fords,
maybe a Dodge, with such names as Silverado, Ram or Laramie.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were checking out a newcomer, something they'd
never seen before, something that seemed sort of heretical. It was
a full-size pickup truck, all right, but it was built by Japanese
automaker Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboys seemed unsure how to judge the interloper, until one
of them, C.W. Williams, piped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's give it the hat test,'' he said. His partners nodded in
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The hat test?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's nothing worse than getting into a truck and
finding out your hat don't fit,'' said Williams, 53, a Wyoming
cowboy in a broad, well-worn Stetson rolled up on the sides and
curled down fore and aft.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they sat behind the wheel of the new pickup to
sample the headroom, or this case, hatroom. And each proclaimed the
Toyota fit for a cowboy, complete with hat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Williams and his buddies, Willum Mallernee and Jeff
Deming, agreed that the Tundra cab is small compared with the
domestic competition. And they found it to be a bit short in the
stirrups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legroom could be better,'' said the lanky Deming.
</P>
<P>
   The new Toyota Tundra represents the first-ever offshore assault
on the American institution of big pickup trucks. It has all the
needed credentials: a large profile, rugged looks and a brawny V-8
engine.
</P>
<P>
   But truck guys are a stubborn lot, loyal to their brand, and
possibly slow to accept a full frontal attack on their favorite
work-and-play vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had Fords all my life, and convincing me to switch is
gonna be tough,'' Williams warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a Chevy guy,'' added Mallernee, 25, also of
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboys were gathered just outside the main corral at Rancho
de los Caballeros, a resort and dude ranch where they work winters
while waiting to return to their homes up north to ride herd in the
warmer months.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the heart of pickup-truck country, and this is where
Toyota chose to make the Western U.S. media introduction of its new
truck on Thursday. Parked beside a rustic rail fence and a towering
stand of paddle cactus, and surrounded by the fragrance of the
milling horses, the Tundra's message was loud and clear: There's a
new gun in town, and it feels right at home in a classic scene from
the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   But for many drivers of full-size pickups, it's the traditional
image of the American pickup, romanticized in countless movies and
commercials in dusty pastel, that has so much appeal. It's the
image that lures business executives and high school seniors _
including a growing number of women _ into the cabs of pickups.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, newcomers often buy their first pickups after a
short time in the state. And in one sobering statistic, Chevrolet
pickup trucks usually come in first as the most-often-stolen
vehicles in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Higgins, a Toyota market planner for pickup trucks, said
the Tundra launch is the biggest thing that Toyota has done since
it unveiled its Lexus division in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The full-size pickup represents a bold move on the part of
Toyota that is not without risks, and a huge investment, Higgins
said. But it vies for a fat piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toyota now has a truck that will compete head to head in the
largest, most competitive, most lucrative segment in the auto
industry,'' Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   But that segment is a hard nut to crack, Higgins acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a segment-loyal and brand-loyal consumer who has
purchased and replaced domestic full-size pickups over and over, in
some cases, for generations,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   How large is the pickup-truck market? Huge. In the 1998 calendar
year, the Ford F-series pickup truck was by far the top-selling
vehicle in the United States, racking up 836,629 units, the most
for any vehicle in two decades. Chevrolet Silverado and its
corporate twin, GMC Sierra, totaled 698,809 trucks sold.
</P>
<P>
   Those are big numbers. Compare them with the top-selling
passenger car for 1998: Toyota Camry hit 429,575 for first place.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year, Toyota plans to build just 100,000 Tundras,
which it expects to sell easily.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Tundra has going for it is that, although it was
designed in Japan and sold by a Japanese company, it's made at
Toyota's new Indiana plant, built specifically for the Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   But is it possible to lure pickup drivers from their Fords,
Chevys and Dodges?
</P>
<P>
   There are several distinct types of pickup-truck drivers,
according to automotive analyst Jim Hall of the Detroit-based Auto
Pacific Group, and the Tundra will appeal to some but not others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Toyota) are going after the recreational user, the guy
who has some change to drop on a new truck,'' said Hall, noting
that most of the Tundras will be four-wheel-drive and all of them
will be of the less-hearty but more-drivable half-ton variety.
</P>
<P>
   However, many pickup drivers like the large size and heft of the
domestic trucks, he said, and they are unlikely to be won over by
the marginally smaller, lighter Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not into bulk, the Tundra has everything: good
looks, a great engine,'' Hall said. ``It's a half click down. It's
smaller than the other trucks, there's no doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that's buying bulk is going to continue buying bulk.''
</P>
<P>
   C.W. Williams said he's sticking with Ford. After all, his truck
is a work vehicle, and he's found that Ford serves him well.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix electrical engineer Don Patton, who drives an aging
Chevy pickup, uses his truck for basic transportation, as well as
camping and household chores. His son, Chris, also drives a Chevy
pickup. And his wife, Rita, can usually be found in the family's
Chevy Suburban, which is built off the full-size pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Don Patton doubted he would ever switch brands, mainly for
practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to Chevys, and I know how Chevy does things,'' he
said. ``When something breaks, I know how to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry Dodd, owner of European Detail, an auto-detailing service,
is one of those drivers who uses a pickup truck for fun and
styling, not for hard work. He recently defected from Chevrolet to
Ford and said he might be willing to switch over to Toyota if it
has the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in seeing what this Toyota looks like,'' Dodd
said. ``If I like the body of the truck, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked Japanese engineering, but I never liked
their look. I'd be interested if it was eye-appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said it's not the new Tundra, Toyota's first foray into
uncharted waters, that should worry the Detroit manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern the Big Three need to have is not this vehicle but
the next one,'' Hall said. ``The question is: When they build the
next generation, will they go up in size?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do, the Big Three might be in for an awakening.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Toyota Tundra LTD &QL; 
 &QL; 
