<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALLENDAR-HOUSE-ART-2     05-05 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALLENDAR-HOUSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME AND THE RIVER: A HOUSE WELL LIVED IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIVOLI, N.Y. _ The lowering sun illuminates the monumental
columns of the Hudson River house like a kindly searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, even though it is barely past 5 o'clock, the occupants
of the grand house are winding down their activities. Pierre
Moulin, white-haired and 72, who owns Callendar House, has begun to
tire; he is very ill. Mara Prologo, the cook and household major
domo, is heading to her sitting room, a few doors from the
slate-floored kitchen. Two of Moulin's younger friends, David
Graham and Frank Appleton, are buttoning up the house for the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always this way.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Moulin and his partner, Pierre LeVec _ the couple
known far and wide as Pierre Deux, as much for their joyous
Provencal style as for the colorful French cottons they sold at
their fabric and antiques emporiums _ bought the late-18th-century
house and its 47 acres. They started inviting friends, relatives
and strangers for parties and teas, and for concerts in the old
emerald-green carriage house north of the main house. These genteel
revels often crowded the midnight hour, and just as often, passed
it by.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with great regret, Moulin has decided to part with
Callendar House, and he has spent a mellow Saturday afternoon
recounting the highlights of his decade there. The house, he said
with a sigh, ``is too big for me now.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Pierres first saw the house, they had just sold the
Pierre Deux fabrics line. Antiques dealers as well as fabric
importers, they thought they might end up in France or perhaps
somewhere near Woodbury, Conn., a town full of dealers, with an
auction house. If they chose France, Moulin would be home; he was
born near Paris. LeVec was born in St. Louis. ``I am French, so I
am Pierre,'' Moulin explained. ``He was American so I called him
Pete.'' LeVec had suggested Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, friends had begged them to look at Callendar
House, one of the few great Hudson River mansions still in private
hands: it was built by Henry Gilbert Livingston, whose country seat
was next door. He promptly sold off the new house _ to a relative
who, in the 1830s, added the house's most memorable feature, the
Greek Revival colonnade across the front, overlooking the river to
the west and, to the south, the river's North Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grumbled all the way up,'' Moulin remembered. He was
ensconced in a worn plaid armchair next to a rip-roaring fire in
the little first-floor study; a pug named Fred rested its many
chins on his ankle. ``It was rainy and dreary and much too far to
drive and on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   But they adored the house, although they found the furnishings
``not completely to our taste,'' Moulin said, with obvious tact.
``It was not a happy house _ it was not whimsical. But the bones
were there. When we retired, we wanted to have the homestead, with
the dog, with the friends and the children.'' (Although he speaks
English with near perfection, Moulin retains his French accent,
along with a certain Gallic habit of adding ``the'' before a few of
his nouns.)
</P>
<P>
   So they bought Callendar House (which a former owner, Jean de
Castella, who raised thoroughbred race horses there, had renamed
Tivoli) and immediately began to turn it into a homestead. They
cleared vistas through overgrown scrub. They planted fruit trees.
They did over every room, recreating elegant bedrooms overlooking
the Hudson, the canopy beds laden with their country cottons. (In
Moulin's bedroom, a wall was taken out to double the size; the
canopy posts, hidden by yards of material, are really steel
pillars, supporting the 10-foot ceiling.)
</P>
<P>
   They replaced most of the fireplace mantels _ which Moulin is
sure were turn-of-the-century replacements, too brown and heavy for
the sunny house _ preferring 18th- and 19th-century French marble
mantels. In the downstairs hall, which bisects the house from front
to back, they installed elegant 18th-century boiserie, shipped from
Paris by a friend, who to this day refuses to say where he found it
_ except that it was ``a little chateau in Provence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put down black and white marble on the floor,''
said Moulin, who used a walker to gallantly escort a reporter
around the first floor. ``But not only was it heavy, but it was a
little too expensive for us at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they had the floor painted a trompe l'oeil parquet de
Versailles. ``It didn't come out too badly,'' he said, gazing down
the hall through the Federal arched doorway, across the columned
porch, across the spring-green lawn and down to the sparkling wide
river beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The very first year the two men lived in the house (only the
dining room was finished, with the same blue-and-white fabric,
brushed blue china cupboard and Chinese rug it has now) they held
their inaugural Bastille Day party, an annual event that continued
until LeVec's death a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   For another party in those early years, they unveiled their
restoration of the sitting room, the 45-by-25-foot living room
added to the first floor by McKim Mead &AMP; White when the firm
remodeled the house around 1910. The room's walls had been the
source of debate: Moulin said he didn't know what to do with the
eccentric murals _ owls, ferns and fronds, scattered about the
rough brown plaster _ painted in 1921, the first commission of Olin
Dows, a young Harvard graduate, who was a weekend guest at
Callendar House.
</P>
<P>
   The walls, truth to tell, had gotten a bit dingy, and in the
end, the murals were freshened and the furnishings chosen to
complement the airy combination of blue-grey and brick red. The
resulting scheme, with its baby-blue linen sofas and an elaborate
brick-colored birdcage with a pale blue door, is one of the few in
the house that are devoid of the jolly, primitive French cotton
prints so associated with the Pierre Deux name.
</P>
<P>
   Although the house is indubitably American, a combination of
Mount Vernon and Gracie Mansion, most of the furnishings are
French. Moulin makes a case _ perhaps a shade defensively _ that
the Frenchification of Callendar House is in keeping with
Lafayette's visits to the surrounding countryside, bringing
wagonloads of French furnishings and accessories as petits cadeaux:
extravagant house gifts for his hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fine Hudson River landscapes,'' Graham said during a
tour of the house, gesturing to four small paintings hung in each
corner of the dining room. ``They are four of the only American
things in the house.'' (Then, to his credit, he laughed: ``Did you
ever see `Lettuce and Lovage,' the play where the tour guide makes
it up as she goes along? I pride myself as an expert at it!'')
</P>
<P>
   Then Moulin, tired from his battle with cancer but ever the
host, shouted that it was teatime. His guest sat sipping tea from
fragile canary-yellow porcelain cups painted with yellow and red
flowers, a wedding gift to his mother. Under Mrs. Prologo's
watchful eye, the group ate freshly baked butter cookies. (``I
really can't have any of those,'' Moulin said wistfully, then
succumbed to just one.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Moulin said he decided to put Callendar House on the market
``right away.'' (It seemed too gauche to ask him the price; Heather
Croner, the Millbrook real estate agent who is handling the
property, said it is $4 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult decision,'' he explained. ``I thought
of selling it when Pete died, but I've had so many friends who did
it too fast, and made the wrong decision. I waited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it is because of my own health,'' he continued. ``If I am
lucky to do well, I would like to travel, and this big estate is
difficult to care for, even with good people. So I have enjoyed the
Callendar, but it is too big for me now. If I could find the person
who falls in love with it, I would be happy.'' He paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, now that I've decided to sell, I don't want to
make the big drama,'' he said. ``First, because I love it too much.
And second, why not just make a clean break? I am hoping so much
that the next people will love it the way I do, and will, also,
make it a real homestead. The way Pete and I did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
