<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORPORATEZEN-TEX     05-05 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATEZEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDDHIST PRINCIPLES HELP WORKERS COPE, AUTHOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if you didn't have enough to do every day at work, now comes
this:
</P>
<P>
   Enlightenment under fluorescent lights.
</P>
<P>
   Nirvana at the budget meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as unlikely as it sounds. Centuries-old Eastern thought
and relaxation techniques may be the answers to the various ills of
the working life, where stress, jealousy, greed and various deadly
sins often abound.
</P>
<P>
   That's according to Massachusetts author Llama Surya Das, who
says the workplace is one of the most rewarding places to practice
Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   Das is busy hyping his newest book, ``Awakening to the Sacred,
Creating a Spiritual Life From Scratch'' (Broadway Books, $26), now
in bookstores. If the mantra sounds a little familiar, it's because
the author hit the religion charts in 1997 with ``Awakening the
Buddha Within, Eight Steps to Enlightenment'' (Broadway Books).
</P>
<P>
   Das, a self-described Long Island Jewish boy named Jeffrey
Miller, left his American self behind in the 1970s and spent nearly
30 years in Asia studying Tibetan and Zen Buddhism. He recently
returned stateside, transformed as an author and seminar leader.
</P>
<P>
   In his books, Das distills the ancient philosophies of Buddhism
_ meditation, breathing exercises, yoga _ into simple techniques
that time-stressed Americans can practice.
</P>
<P>
   Even short, spiritual pauses help establish awareness and make
us better at dealing with stressful situations, he says. No more
hurling curses at a jammed computer printer. No more sneering at
the boss. You can't do that while breathing deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Das calls the technique ``tapping into our innate sanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say God is everywhere and we can connect any time. In
Buddhism, we connect with something that is already within us. ...
Rather than feeling lost or scattered, we feel grounded,'' Das
says.
</P>
<P>
   Das believes that fewer people today are inclined to follow a
dogma-based religion, in which a sense of the sacred is confined to
one hour on the Sabbath and hope for divine help is saved for the
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says, many people are seeking spiritual improvement
that they can feel in the here and now, every day, even at work.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism in the workplace is a way of affirming what Buddhists
call ``right livelihood,'' he says. Work is not just a way to earn
a paycheck. Work is what we do to make a better world and make
ourselves better people. Work should be ethical, nonviolent and
done with subdued passion, he says.
</P>
<P>
   With that philosophy, Das becomes something of an anti-Dilbert,
trading cynicism for niceness and hope, and replacing competition
with collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to make a life, not a living,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sample of Llama Surya Das' tips for surviving the
workplace:
</P>
<P>
   The loving kindness exercise: ``Visualize your boss and bathe
him in light. As you do this, chant these words to yourself, `May
you be happy, may you be peaceful, may you be fulfilled.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The boss-meditation is calming and allows you to become a better
person even if it doesn't help the boss, Das says. (And it probably
is more effective than that old non-Buddhist technique of simply
picturing him in his underwear.)
</P>
<P>
   The minimeditation exercise: ``Stop what you are doing and just
sit there. Relax and just drop everything. Breathe in and out,
slowly, three times through your nose, paying attention to each
breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Give yourself three minutes if you can, or try the even simpler
version: 15 seconds during which you breathe, smile and relax three
times in a row. You can do it at a meeting. Breathe in and pull in
wisdom, goodness and patience; breathe out the bad forces of
contempt, rejection and the taste of old, stale office coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The haiku exercise: Haiku helps the writer focus on a subject or
emotion and simplify it. It is a form of meditation. Traditionally,
a haiku is composed in three lines, with the first line containing
five syllables, the second seven syllables and the last five
syllables, such as:
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating Monday,
</P>
<P>
   I am fixing to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Who blocked my car in?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Buddhist approach to asking for a raise: There is no
Buddhist approach to asking for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddha was born to a wealthy family, but walked away from it
all to search for enlightenment. So Buddhism doesn't have a whole
lot of advice for those seeking wealth as opposed to knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
