<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIMMICK-THEATER-REVIE     05-05 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIMMICK-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GIMMICK:' A RHAPSODIC EMBRACE OF LANGUAGE IN A CRUEL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The door opens on an empty stage, a world clean out
of love. Into this inhospitable domain, the symbolic habitat of a
barren upbringing, marches Dael Orlandersmith, imposing in shape,
and even more so in the shape of her suffering.
</P>
<P>
   For the duration of ``The Gimmick,'' her scorching new solo
piece, Ms. Orlandersmith fills the New York Theater Workshop with
the outsize proportions of her formidable fury. She fills the space
with other things, too: a rhapsodic embrace of language; the
memories of a hobbled cast of Harlem characters brought low by
drugs, booze and hopelessness, and an absolutely iron-fisted
determination to lay on you something of the sting of pitiless
rebuke slapped on her throughout her ``why me?'' of a childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlandersmith has touched on aspects of this tale in her
previous one-person shows. But works like the 1996 ``Monster,'' in
which she explored her precocious sense of alienation, now seem to
have been mere rehearsals for the more nuanced narrative of ``The
Gimmick,'' which opened last night. It is no exaggeration to say
that in this production, ably directed by Chris Coleman, Ms.
Orlandersmith practices a kind of verbal Impressionism; as if to
intensify the rainbow of moods she communicates, the words for the
various colors she describes in the piece are projected
intermittently onto the back wall of the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The literalness of this device has a clear purpose, linking the
stories of the two main characters of ``The Gimmick,'' a pair of
ghetto friends, Alexis and Jimmy, who grow up in abject parental
neglect but nevertheless aspire to careers as a writer and a
painter. It is through her alter ego of Alexis, deserted
emotionally by an alcoholic single mother, forced to eke out a
rage-stoked existence in her psychic orphanhood, that Ms.
Orlandersmith helps an audience to see all the colors of her
struggle. It is through Jimmy, a gifted artist who is demeaned,
beaten and ultimately egged on to drugged oblivion by a
spite-driven father, that the actress seeks to illustrate a tragedy
of Harlem in more mysterious shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis' obsession with Jimmy is the least involving aspect of
``The Gimmick'' _ of all the characters portrayed by Ms.
Orlandersmith, Jimmy is the only one who fails to pass the
believability test _ but it is a minor failing; Jimmy remains a
useful receptacle for Alexis' bottomless pool of yearning, a
condition brought on by Alexis' intense sense of isolation, a
state, in Ms. Orlandersmith's crystalline phrasing, of feeling
``cold low alone.'' It is, in fact, in these characterizations of
Alexis' interior life that ``The Gimmick'' unveils an unflagging
power to enlighten. At times the illumination is almost blinding.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlandersmith is unapologetically large; in a shapeless
black smock and long, gold and straw-colored braids, she's a vision
of self-assertiveness. Alexis is the name she gives, in a sense, to
her own embryonic artistic ego, and one can clearly sense, as
Alexis grows in Ms. Orlandersmith's telling into young adulthood,
the hard shell being constructed by this secretly soft and easily
wounded young girl. (The armor must be applied before it can be
removed again.) Wandering at Jimmy's instigation, for example, into
an East Side boutique to buy a dress, Alexis absorbs the brunt of
the white establishment's contempt; the saleswoman trots over with
the only item in her size, a man's extra large shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world,'' she says, ``does not like big black girls at all,
not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis arms herself against the cruelties of this world,
perceived and real, and over the course of the 85-minute show, Ms.
Orlandersmith details both her escapes from and confrontations with
her own consuming anger. The show tracks her development from about
the age of 8 to adulthood; her pique is continuous. There is a
wonderfully revealing interlude on a Manhattan street in which
Alexis, embittered over Jimmy's romantic defection, takes her
revenge on a random white girl, throwing her intimidating body in
the girl's path and subjecting her to a barrage of epithets. In an
internal monologue, the speaking voice of her more vulnerable self,
Alexis expresses utter revulsion at her own callousness.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort is available, too, however, in the form of a
compassionate librarian at Alexis' library branch. Encouraging the
youngster's infatuation with learning, the librarian becomes
surrogate mother and tutor. She is the only adult to impart
anything like affection, and one of the marvels of ``The Gimmick''
is the demonstration that a tiny droplet of tenderness is all the
encouragement the needy little girl requires to survive, to nourish
her desire to live outside and beyond her outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Lighted by Matthew Frey with a feel for the dignity of Ms.
Orlandersmith's terrible and touching anecdotes, ``The Gimmick'' is
designed as a sharp reflection of a writer's cold-eyed communion
with her world. (The meaning to her of ``black'' is conveyed with
exactly the right grammatical subtlety in one of the projections.)
In their particulars, the tales she tells may not seem startlingly
unfamiliar; again and again, readers and movie- and playgoers have
lived vicariously through this kind of struggle. But Ms.
Orlandersmith is herself wholly original, a riveting combatant in a
story, like all war stories, that stamps her as one who has been
there.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GIMMICK'
</P>
<P>
   By Dael Orlandersmith; directed by Chris Coleman; sets and
costumes by Scott Pask; lighting by Matthew Frey; sound by Kurt
Kellenberger; production stage manger, Martha Donaldson. Presented
by the New York Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   With: Dael Orlandersmith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
