<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-DESIGN-450&AMP;A     05-05 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-DESIGN-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLIANCES WITH LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the ``American Century'' exhibition that just opened at the
Whitney Museum of American Art, the first five decades of the 20th
century are represented by nearly 1,000 artworks, plus a few dozen
carefully culled examples of the decorative arts and industrial
design.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the design objects are used to underscore points made by
the art, as if to say, ``The artists don't lie; this is how the
world truly looked.'' Gerald Murphy's bright, montagelike 1920s
paintings of safety razors and cocktail shakers, for example, share
space with actual cocktail sets.
</P>
<P>
   But smack in the middle of one gallery is a big, undulating
display case stocked with streamlined products, most from the
1930s. Suddenly, the design objects are the stars, and the art
plays a supporting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real moment in which the decorative arts take a
leadership position in describing the values of the times,'' said
Barbara Haskell, the show's curator, explaining why these
once-mundane items deserve to be center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seems strange that these appliances have made their
way from America's kitchens and broom closets and into the museum's
vitrines. Not that these objects are obscure; on the contrary, most
of them have been shown before. The Petipoint iron, manufactured in
1941 by Waverly Tool Co. of Sandusky, Ohio, and the 1937 Electrolux
vacuum cleaner, humble as they may appear, are both alumni of the
Brooklyn Museum's 1986 ``Machine Age in America 1918-1941''
exhibition. Kem Weber's 1934 Zephyr digital clock was in the ``What
Modern Was'' show mounted by Montreal's Museum of Decorative Arts
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   While great works of art are relatively rare, great products _
ones that speak eloquently of their time _ should be abundant. Yet
certain objects have been exhibited repeatedly and gain stature
with each public exposure. The Model 302 telephone by Henry
Dreyfuss is, by now, almost as familiar as Grant Wood's ``American
Gothic.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Kaplan, the associate director of Miami Beach's wildly
eclectic Wolfsonian design collection, was one of the consultants
who gave recommendations to Ms. Haskell. While Ms. Kaplan can offer
no single theory to explain why certain objects achieve masterpiece
status, she maintains that products had to be seductive to sell in
the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stayton, the curator of decorative arts at the Brooklyn
Museum, also a consultant on the ``American Century,'' said that he
and his colleagues didn't intend to promote such familiar objects.
``We said, `Let's not pull up the chestnuts,' '' he recalled. ``But
when you're trying to tell a story, the reason there are chestnuts
is because they tell it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The real issue, then, is which story you want to tell. Ms.
Kaplan points out that during the 1920s and '30s, a period the
Whitney links with the ascent of modernism, a revival of colonial
style was in full swing. As Loewy and Dreyfuss sculptured an
aerodynamic future, John D. Rockefeller Jr. was busy rebuilding the
past at Colonial Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, each consultant had favorite objects that didn't make
the cut. For Stayton, it was the 1927 coffee service called ``The
Lights and Shadows of Manhattan'' by the Danish silversmith Erik
Magnussen. Stayton is intrigued by the way it translates the
``visual impact of Cubism into the decorative arts.'' Ms. Kaplan
couldn't talk the Whitney into a 1930s reproduction of an
18th-century settee by Wallace Nutting, the leading proponent of
neo-colonial style, but she did secure a place for a largely unsung
meat slicer, Model No. 410, a k a the Streamliner, designed by one
Egmont Arens and made by Hobart in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about the meat slicer,'' said Ms. Kaplan, noting
that streamlining was a technique for cutting wind resistance in
trains and airplanes, ``is that it's the ultimate example of a
streamlined form in an object that isn't going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But this meat slicer is going places. It had its debut in the
Wolfsonian's 1995 opening exhibition in Miami Beach, which then hit
the road. ``Everywhere it went, people loved it,'' Ms. Kaplan said.
Now, the Streamliner is on display at one of New York's leading
museums. No telling where it will go next. The world is its deli
counter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
