<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLASHING AROUND ROOF JOINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A house roof has joints between roof sections and around vents,
skylights and chimneys. These joints are vulnerable to leaking
because they usually connect different materials that expand and
contract at dissimilar rates. The joints may also separate as the
house settles.
</P>
<P>
   Builders protect these joints by covering them with flashing, a
flexible material like aluminum, copper, galvanized steel or
neoprene, to repel rain and snow. As long as the flashing remains
intact, the joints will be impervious to moisture, but with
continued exposure to the elements some deterioration is bound to
occur.
</P>
<P>
   An annual spring roof inspection should include a close
examination of the flashing as well as the shingles. Naturally,
this entails climbing up on the roof. Choose a warm, dry day for
this, and wear shoes with nonskid soles. Do not attempt to climb on
the roof if it has a steep pitch or if you are unsteady on heights.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing with extensive damage should be replaced; this is a job
for a professional. Minor damage, a small hole or a patch of
corrosion here and there, can be patched. You can usually make the
repair yourself by cutting a patch from the same material as the
flashing. First, measure the damaged area, then cut a patch large
enough to cover it. Make sure the patch is broad enough to extend
under the shingles on either side of the damaged area.
</P>
<P>
   Lift up the shingles (be careful; if they are cold they will
crack) to break the seal around the flashing, then use a stiff
putty knife and wire brush to clean the flashing of dirt, rust and
old roofing cement. Apply a generous bead of new roofing cement to
the back of the patch, then position it so it covers the damaged
area. Slip the edges of the patch under the adjacent shingles.
</P>
<P>
   Press down on the patch to distribute the roofing cement
underneath, then apply a bead of roofing cement around the edges.
Use a putty knife to smooth this bead and feather the edges to the
surrounding area. This will keep the bead from becoming a small dam
on a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Vent flashing fits around the plumbing vent pipe that projects
through the roof. This flashing is usually a single piece of
flexible metal with a neoprene collar that hugs the pipe. When vent
flashing is damaged or corroded, it should be replaced. This,
however, is not difficult and well within the skill range of the
average do-it-yourselfer.
</P>
<P>
   First use a pry bar to gently lift the shingles on either side
of the vent. Scrape away any old roofing cement under the shingles
and around the vent pipe. Slip the new flashing over the vent,
making sure the neoprene collar fits tightly around the pipe. Lift
the shingles above and on either side of the pipe and slip the
flashing underneath. The bottom edge of the flashing should overlap
the shingles beneath so it sheds, not traps, water.
</P>
<P>
   Drive a couple of roofing nails along the top edge of the new
flashing. These nails should be placed so they will be covered by
the overlapping shingles. Cover the nailheads with roofing cement
and apply a generous bead of cement under the shingles, then press
the shingles in place.
</P>
<P>
   The flashing around the chimney is complex because it is made up
of a number of pieces. At the foot of the chimney, facing the
eaves, is the front-base flashing. It is a single piece of metal
that bends down over the shingles and covers the first course of
bricks on the chimney. Two tabs bend around on either side of the
chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite this side of the chimney, facing the peak, is another
piece of metal, called the back-base flashing. It is similar to the
front piece except it runs under the roof shingles. The step
flashing covers the lower sides of the chimney. Step flashing is
made up of overlapping pieces of metal that run under the shingles
and bend up the sides of the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   The top seams of the chimney flashing are covered by separate
pieces of metal called counterflashing. The counterflashing is
embedded in the mortar joints of the chimney, and it bends down
over the other flashing elements.
</P>
<P>
   Before replacing the chimney flashing, you must carefully bend
up the counterflashing. Pull back the roof shingles (this is not
necessary with the front-base flashing) and clean away the old
roofing cement. Remove the old flashing and cut new pieces from the
same material. Slip the new piece in place and bend down the
counterflashing. Seal all the seams with roofing cement. Finally,
apply roofing cement to the underside of the shingles and press
them down against the flashing to form a seal. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
