</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW E-MAIL TRAVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where does this e-mail message live from the time I hit the
`send' key to the time you read it?
</P>
<P>
   A: An e-mail message is passed along by many different computers
until it reaches its destination, just as postal mail is handled by
letter carriers and a network of post offices until it is delivered
to your mailbox. In many systems, once you hit the `send' button,
your e-mail message goes to what is called a SMTP (simple mail
transfer protocol) server. This server checks the address on the
message and forwards it to the mail server of your intended
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   A mail server is a computer that contains electronic mailboxes
for each of its users. If you have an account with Earthlink, for
example, you have an electronic mailbox on Earthlink's mail server.
Until you log onto your Internet service provider to retrieve your
messages, the mail waits for you in your electronic mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is fast and convenient, but not as private as you might
think. Because a message goes through several different computers
on its journey, it is possible for other people to intercept it.
And because mail is kept on servers that are often backed up and
archived (especially in corporations), you cannot assume that a
message is gone forever just because you delete it from your
computer So be sure to think before you send.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. Biersdorfer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
