5, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-GUNS-ANALYSIS. An analysis of various gun bills. (500
words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-FCC-STEARNS. (FOR THE HOLLYWOOD REPORTER.) A lawmaker
from a key House panel has harsh words for the Federal
Communications Commission. Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., criticized
the agency for its slow deregulation of the broadcast industry.
(300 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE. In the wake of the Littleton
shootings, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott has chosen U.S. Sens.
Wayne Allard and Ben Nighthorse Campbell of Colorado to serve on a
Republican task force to examine ways to reduce the incidence of
youth violence. (300 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-KOSOVO-LAWSUIT. Two GOP congressmen from Colorado have
asked a federal judge to declare the air war against Yugoslavia
illegal and order President Clinton to end the conflict within a
month. U.S. Reps. Bob Schaffer of Fort Collins and Tom Tancredo of
Golden are among 17 House members to file a lawsuit alleging that
Clinton ignored the Constitution when he directed American forces
to bomb Serb targets without congressional approval. (500 words.)
By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-VIET-WALL. Richard B. Fitzgibbon was killed in
Vietnam in 1956, but because of regulations his name was never
inscribed on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. Today, Richard joined
his namesake son who died nine years later serving in the same war.
(500 words.) By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO-SPY. A disturbing series of failures and missteps by
government officials allowed alleged spy Wen Ho Lee to remain in a
sensitive position at Los Alamos laboratories for years. (600
words.) By Kelly Hearn
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-ACHIEVE. Wisconsin will be one of 10 states entering a
Mathematics Achievement Partnership to respond to weaknesses in
middle school math performance, Gov. Tommy Thompson announced at a
press conference in Washington Wednesday. Thompson serves on the
board of directors of Achieve Inc., an independent organization
that serves as a resource center to states to help them raise
academic standards and improve student performance. (450 words.) By
Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-DAIRY. Wisconsin Democratic Sens. Herb Kohl, Ron Kind
and David Obey testified before an agriculture committee hearing
Wednesday on the USDA's new milk marketing reform proposal. The
Badger State lawmakers said Congress should not try to overthrow
the proposal because regional politics will erode the independence
of the USDA's decision. (450 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
