<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVING-IN-CELEBRATION     05-05 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-IN-CELEBRATION-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THE ISOLATION BARRIER IN CELEBRATION, FLA. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
Douglas Frantz, a national correspondent for The New York Times,
and Catherine Collins, a writer, are the authors of ``Celebration,
U.S.A.,'' to be published in September by Henry Holt &AMP; Co. 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ and CATHERINE COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CELEBRATION, Fla. _ Less than a week after we moved to this new
town being built by Walt Disney Co., a neighbor dropped by to chat,
and the topic turned to children. One of the great things about
living here, he said, is that the kids will have so many adults
watching over them.
</P>
<P>
   We were somewhat taken aback, thinking that perhaps Celebration
would be just a little too neighborly for us, but as we conclude
our second year here, we have come to see a measure of wisdom in
that neighbor's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   On an important level, the New Urbanist elements of Celebration
contribute to a sense of community that creates a cocoon of sorts
around the children. It doesn't replace parents, and it isn't a
grant of immunity from crime or problems. But the housing density,
sidewalks and knowing your neighbors translate into a high degree
of freedom for our children and a level of comfort as parents that
are both new to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I don't have any teen-agers, I know a lot of
them,'' said Kathy Johnson, the executive director of the
Celebration Foundation, which administers community programs and
coordinates volunteer efforts in town. ``I know them well enough
that if I saw them doing something wonderful I would praise them,
and if I saw them doing something wrong I would tell their parents.
There is a kind of shared parenting here in Celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no new development in the United States has undergone
the publicity and scrutiny of Celebration, located some 20 miles
southwest of Orlando. Since the initial residents moved in nearly
three years ago, the town has grown to more than 2,000, and
ultimately Celebration is to have 8,000 homes and 20,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what drew people like us to Celebration was the search
for an alternative to the isolation of modern suburbs, like
Westport, Conn., the last place we lived before moving here. If
residents weren't exactly looking for a return to small-town
America, they were trying to find that lost sense of
neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned notion of looking out for each other,
especially the children, has been a natural outgrowth of design
elements like front porches, tree-shaded sidewalks and placing the
school and the business district smack in the middle of town.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to amenities aimed at pleasing the adults who pay the
mortgages, children congregate in the parks, collect on the benches
outside the stores and race through town on Rollerblades or
bicycles, all under the watchful eye of adults.
</P>
<P>
   Our school-age children _ Nick, 13, and Becky, 11 _ know that if
they get into trouble, we'll hear about it. If an older teen-ager
is driving too fast, you can bet the phone will be ringing at his
or her home before he or she is in the door.
</P>
<P>
   But there are benefits for teen-agers, too. ``A lot of kids get
on the wrong track because their parents work and there's no one to
turn to,'' said Tracey Pellegrine, a 16-year-old junior who is the
president of the student government at Celebration School. ``Here
we have plenty of support from other adults. I know our neighbors.
I can call them, even to ask simple things, like, `How do I do a
bleach load in the laundry?'''
</P>
<P>
   She said that her younger sister, Wendy, and her friends enjoy
enormous freedom because they are mobile. On any given afternoon,
the community pool at Lakeside Park is thronged with children of
all ages, while their comrades zip along the sidewalks on
Rollerblades or gather in impromptu groups on the bridge between
the park and downtown. On most Friday nights, 20 or 30 kids attend
the local movie together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The design of this town helps to fight the isolation that so
many children face today,'' said Darcie Rudsinski, a teacher at the
school. ``It allows them to interact, to build relationships,
rather than sit home in front of a television. It lets kids be
kids, the way they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But life is not perfect for teen-agers in Celebration. The
biggest complaint among them is the lack of a place of their own.
Just as adults meet at Barnie's for coffee in the mornings or at
Max's Grille for a beer in the evenings, teen-agers would like
another athletic field or a playground at the school, or a skating
or youth center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planners left out a youth center or a boys' and girls'
club, like most successful urban centers have,'' said Joseph Judge,
who owns a bicycle shop in town.
</P>
<P>
   Peter S. Rummell, the former president of Disney's development
arm and the originator of the Celebration idea, said that the
town's planners rejected building a youth center in favor of
gathering spots like Lakeside Park. ``The only thing teen-agers
really want is to be with other teen-agers,'' said Rummell, now the
chairman and chief executive of St. Joe Co., a development business
based in Jacksonville, Fla. ``You need to provide places for them
to do that, and you need to encourage civil tolerance.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes civil tolerance is tough to come by for kids. Not long
ago our son, Nick, was filming a Rollerblading video as a school
project in front of a business downtown. As his friends launched
themselves toward the camera, spinning in midair, a storeowner came
out to complain and ordered the children off the sidewalk and onto
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a place to blade,'' Nick complained after the
incident. In much the same vein, teen-agers and adults alike
complain about the lack of walking and biking trails promised in
the original promotional literature. A recent brochure for the town
used a photograph of a family biking along a scenic trail _ only
the trail was a cart path on the golf course, which is off limits
to bikers, bladers and walkers alike.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants, however, could not be more accommodating when it
comes to children. Every day after school, an endless stream of
teen-agers strolls or rolls through the door of Village Mercantile,
a clothing store downtown. Some stop by to say hello. Others use
the phone to check in with parents at home or at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second or third day we were open, a kid came in asking
for change to call home,'' said Dottie Mathison, who owns the store
with her husband, Jerry. ``I'm a mother, and I thought it was great
that this kid needed to call home, so I said, `Don't waste your
money. Use my phone.' And it's gone from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Other times, children come in seeking advice. One girl stopped
by recently and said she had just had a minor traffic accident.
When she asked what she should do, Mrs. Mathison recalled, ``I said
to go home and tell her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   As parents, we take comfort in the close-knit nature of the town
and have allowed Nick and Becky more freedom than they have had
elsewhere. They have rules about checking in, and they get regular
lectures about realities like crime and drugs. But Nick and Becky
and all of their friends, older and younger, say that they have
more freedom in Celebration than anyplace they have ever lived _
even if the town wasn't specifically designed for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
