<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RUSHDIE-PROFILE-     05-05 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RUSHDIE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GROUND' ROCKS FOR RUSHDIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Broadly speaking, it's nice to be able to change
the subject back to books,'' Salman Rushdie says softly.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' his new epic about
love, rock 'n' roll, exile, the perils of celebrity and a laundry
list of other themes.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old India-born novelist has come to Los Angeles for
BookExpo, the annual convention of independent booksellers and
trade publishers, to pump his seventh work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the ``other'' subject _ the death threat he has
lived under since 1989, when Ayatollah Khomeini deemed ``The
Satanic Verses'' blasphemous to Islam _ remains a shadow on the
wall. Witness the precautions you don't normally associate with an
author interview.
</P>
<P>
   A sit-down session with Rushdie begins in the booth of his
publisher, Henry Holt, on the floor of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   You are frog-marched out of the building _ there's a schedule to
keep _ and into a waiting dark-colored Ford Ranger parked
unobtrusively at the curb, its engine idling.
</P>
<P>
   Through the streets of downtown Los Angeles you go, finally
stopping at the unmarked side door of a hotel. Your escort punches
in the code that unlocks the door. Up you pass through a stairwell
that opens onto a hallway, where you're greeted by Rushdie's
smiling publicist and two men in dark suits who look at you but do
not smile at all.
</P>
<P>
   Then you're ushered into a sitting room, where Rushdie, dressed
in a soft, brown suit, rises from a couch to greet you.
</P>
<P>
   Before embarking on these press interviews, Rushdie gave an
invitation-only reading at the convention Thursday. (While in L.A.,
he also reportedly taped a segment of ``Politically Incorrect'' and
made a surprise appearance at the Los Angeles Public Library to
read from his new book.)
</P>
<P>
   And in mid-April, he gave an advertised-in-advance public
reading at Cooper Union in New York _ security officers checked
attendees with a hand-held metal detector. He's done similar
readings in London, Amsterdam and Rome.
</P>
<P>
   All this rush of Rushdie simply indicates he has ``resumed
normal service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time of abnormal service. And as you can
see,'' _ he nods toward the unsmiling men in the next room _
``there's still one or two abnormalities.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the Iranian government announced last year that it no
longer supported carrying out Khomeini's ``fatwa,'' the threat has
diminished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What remains is that, as we all know, Iran is a fragmented
leadership and there are groups that don't agree with what the
government says, so there's still some residual risk of that sort.
But those people's ability to act is obviously much less than
state-sponsored terrorism, which is what we were facing for the
previous 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my view is, `the hell with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Polite, with a hint of British chill, articulate, soft-spoken,
Rushdie answers the obligatory questions about death threats but is
clearly happier when the subject turns to his book, which has been
getting mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' is an exuberant, inventive tale
that spans three continents and is told in pun-packed prose with
allusions that range from Eastern religion to Western rock 'n'
roll. The protagonists (and lovers) are a pair of Indian rockers
who become world celebrities _ think of a parallel universe in
which Madonna and Mick Jagger were born in Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie's love of rock 'n' roll is neither an affectation nor a
new passion. He grew up listening to it in India. Bill Haley rocked
not only around the clock but around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed with which (rock) got 'round the world is really
quite startling because it did it at a time when the world had not
been globalized,'' Rushdie said, adding that rock arrived in India
before television.
</P>
<P>
   Western rock didn't seem alien to him and his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a kind of universal language of youth. ... It probably
got everybody's feet tapping in much the same way, all around the
world at the same time. It was kind of rebellious and oppositional
and contraband music in exactly the same way as here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among his early favorites: Haley, Elvis, Jerry Lee Lewis and
``Ricky Nelson, God help me.'' These days Rushdie numbers among his
friends Lou Reed and U2 lead singer Bono. The Irish band has
written and recorded a song employing lyrics Rushdie penned for the
book. (Look for ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' the tune, on U2's
next album, due in September.)
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie has always been a novelist with a grand reach, so people
may be surprised that something as low culture as rock 'n' roll
figures so largely in the book. They shouldn't be, Rushdie said. A
writer should respond to the whole culture of his time, not the
highbrow bits.
</P>
<P>
   The action of the novel begins in India and moves to England and
then America, mirroring the rise of American popular culture to
world dominance in the postwar period. What better vehicle than
rock to illustrate that trajectory?
</P>
<P>
   ``All my writing has been very interested in popular culture,''
Rushdie said.
</P>
<P>
   The inescapability of celebrity is a major theme in the book.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' is about love, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an age which is, on the one hand, disgustingly sentimental
and, on the other hand, disgustingly cynical, I wanted to write
seriously about love in a way that was neither of those things,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how living under the ``fatwa'' has changed him as a
writer, he said it taught him ``both the very dark lessons about
hatred and bigotry and intolerance'' and the ``much more important
lessons about love ... from all sorts of people, not just my wife
and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie's second marriage failed not long after the ``fatwa,''
and in 1997 he married editor Elizabeth West. The couple have a
2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I think back on it, that's what sticks in my memory _ not
the hostility but the affection and solidarity and concern. All
that wrapped together you call love. That's why the business of
writing about love has moved closer and closer to the center of my
work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
