A5510 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEGAS-NEWORLEANS-TEX     05-05 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEGAS-NEWORLEANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAWING INSPIRATION: NEW SHOW DEPICTS DEGAS' FAMILY LIFE IN NEW
ORLEANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ When Edgar Degas stepped from the train into New
Orleans in late 1872, he was greeted not only by members of his
mother's family, the Mussons, but also by a bewildering welter of
dazzling light, intense heat and humidity, a hubbub of bodies _ as
many black as there were white _ and lush vegetation. For the
Parisian, cosmopolitan though he was, it was an unnervingly exotic
scene.
</P>
<P>
   And one he never painted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the story of Degas in New Orleans did make for pictures _
works far ahead of their time in psychological content and formal
composition _ that in turn have made for a remarkable new
exhibition at the New Orleans Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Degas and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in America''
features 40 works by Degas, including 17 that he painted in the
Crescent City, as well as related family letters, furniture,
jewelry, photographs and other historic materials. Assembled under
the leadership of curator Gail Fiegenbaum, the exhibit is the
centerpiece of a statewide celebration of French history and
culture called FrancoFete.
</P>
<P>
   Degas, whose mother was born in New Orleans, was the only French
impressionist to sojourn to the New World. When he arrived on the
banks of the Mississippi, Degas was a mature and thoughtful 38, but
still in the formative stages of his career. His familiar paintings
and pastels of ballet dancers and washerwomen still were ahead of
him, although numerous family portraits had established Degas as an
artist who loved to focus on a narrow range of subjects, then
reinterpret them endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Family was the overt reason for Degas' visit _ his fondness for
his relations was sincere and profound _ but he also needed to
clarify his sense of himself as an artist. He left New Orleans
about five months later, clearly focused on what he needed to do,
one reason for this exhibition's importance.
</P>
<P>
   But, as in the case of any show worth its salt, the real merit
of ``Degas and New Orleans'' lies in the penetrating pictures it
assembles, images that gain impact by being shown together.
</P>
<P>
   Small enough that each work can be savored in depth, this is an
essential exhibition for anyone interested in Degas. But it also
would be invaluable viewing to anyone who cares about modern
painting: It's no exaggeration to say that some of its pictures
look ahead not only to impressionism, but to the post-impressionism
of Cezanne, to the cubist-inspired works of Matisse and even _ in
one tiny, chilling portrait of Degas' cousin, Estelle _ the work of
the late-20th century German painter Gerhard Richter, many of whose
images are taken from the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   History buffs will enjoy the sprawling family tree the NOMA has
delineated, which seems to connect Degas with almost every other
Creole family in New Orleans. The only fault is a life-size
re-creation of the Musson family's porch, installed perhaps in the
fear that art alone would not seize visitors' imagination.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other organizations are highlighting Degas
connections around the city. Several houses and commercial
buildings were either built by or inhabited by Musson family
members.
</P>
<P>
   The most relevant, the cotton-factoring office represented in
Degas' New Orleans masterpiece, has been given over to a business.
The other important site, the Musson family house where Degas
painted several pictures of his female relations, has been
restored, but rather clumsily.
</P>
<P>
   Only here and there _ on the balcony of the Musson house on
Esplanade, for example _ is the scene sufficiently quiet and
pleasantly haunted to imagine the artist socializing or at work.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, though, is that this partial failure to place
Degas' work into the context of the city is entirely appropriate to
the nature of what Degas was doing during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Degas was not a painter of the appearance of
places and things. He may have been fascinated with what he saw in
tumultuous, Reconstruction-era New Orleans _ certainly the residue
of colonial gentility and the mixing of races and cultures
intrigued him _ but he considered himself another sort of artist.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of setting up on the levee and painting men loading
barges, Degas stayed indoors and painted mesmerizing portraits of
his cousins and their children. Thus we see Mathilde Musson Bell,
garbed as a nurse, seated within the confining frame of a doorway.
Or an exquisite portrait of Estelle Musson Balfour De Gas (Degas'
father's spelling of the family name), her left eye bandaged,
enduring her progressive blindness with great courage.
</P>
<P>
   Degas' choice of subject was also influenced by trouble he was
having with his own eyesight _ and he was terrified that the city's
tropical light would blind him. Finally, the hot, humid air
stripped Degas of energy for most of his visit: Only toward the end
did he get out much _ when he painted ``A Cotton Office in New
Orleans,'' a portrait of his male relations as their business was
going bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   On loan from the municipal museum in Pau, France, ``A Cotton
Office'' was the first impressionist painting to be purchased by a
museum. Included in it are portraits of Degas' uncle, Michel Musson
(seated in the foreground, inspecting a swatch of cotton); his
brother Achille (the dandy leaning on the counter at the left); and
his other brother Rene (reading a newspaper).
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, here Degas did seek to convey information about the
particulars of time and place. But, even though he carefully
reconstructs the room and the roles of its denizens, he nonetheless
presents a tension-filled study of individuals in the midst of
ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Ruin, turmoil, suppressed suffering. All makings of the soap
opera that seems to have characterized Degas-Musson family life and
_ as local historians love to point out _ the history of New
Orleans, a haunted city that was briefly home to one of Europe's
greatest artists.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Degas and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in America''
</P>
<P>
   Through: Aug. 29
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Museum of Art, City Park, New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   Information: (504) 488-2631
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $10 for adults, $9 for senior citizens, $5 for
children ages 3-17
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
