<HEADLINE>
CARMICHAEL TAKES JAZZ ACCLAIM IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historically, most stride piano players are African-American men
_ and dead.
</P>
<P>
   Stride is a demanding, highly rhythmic, jaunty style of solo
piano that flourished in Harlem during the '20s and '30s. It was
party music, a precursor of big-band swing, and for a time (via
Fats Waller, James P. Johnson and Willie ``The Lion'' Smith) wildly
popular, the sophisticated, big-city equivalent of solo acoustic
guitar Mississippi Delta blues.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later, stride is all but jazz history, left to a
handful of serious players and a small but devoted coterie of fans.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Judy Carmichael, a funny, talkative, blond
Californian who never even heard stride until she was 22 but has
since learned to play it on a par with her musical heroes _ so
well, in fact, that Count Basie nicknamed her ``Stride.''
</P>
<P>
   In background and appearance, Carmichael is as far away from
those Harlem masters as can be. But for years, she has been
receiving raves as one of stride's foremost modern practitioners;
she has recorded seven CDs and in 1992 was the first jazz musician
sponsored by the U.S. government to tour China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met some people who told me later that they walked into a
club where I was playing, saw me and walked out _ they couldn't
believe someone who looked like me could play,'' Carmichael says.
``People used to think I was nuts; they couldn't believe I wanted
to do this for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael discovered stride via a recording of Basie playing
with Bennie Moten in the '20s, and for a while she alternated
ragtime and jazz. Six months later, she got a job playing at
Disneyland, where she met Basie, his guitarist, Freddie Green, and
jazz vocalist Sarah Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed at Disneyland for five years and then moved to New
York and released her first, Grammy-nominated record, ``Two-Handed
Stride,'' which was later released on CD as ``And Basie Called Her
`Stride.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has toured the world and has continued to study
the history of jazz piano. Several years ago, she received a grant
from the National Endowment for the Arts, which she used to design
a program detailing the history of jazz piano. She has taken the
program to colleges nationwide and has written two books on jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to educate people; when I started, only older
people knew what stride was,'' she says. ``But I mainly play stride
because I love it. It's just a great way to play piano.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to touring, Carmichael has recently been gathering
interviews for her upcoming ``Jazz Inspired'' series, which will
begin airing on National Public Radio in March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what this means to me,'' she says. ``It's
about fascinating, creative people who connect to jazz because of
the wonderful music it is. If people hear that Robert Redford says
jazz changed his life, maybe they'll give it a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks partly to last year's swing revival, Carmichael says, she
has noticed her audiences skewing younger these days. The trend,
she says, suits her just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people under 40, I'm their image of what a stride player
is,'' she says. ``They don't know about Fats Waller. They just like
the music. They think it sounds like the Gap commercial, with the
people dancing to swing music. These people know about stride
because of me. That's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman writes on pop music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
