<SLUG> BC-E-RATE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FCC CHAIRMAN WANTS MORE INTERNET FUNDS FOR SCHOOLS, LIBRARIES
 &HT;    400&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    Eds: Note state inserts following 5th graf.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Discounts to schools and libraries for
telecommunications and Internet connections would double next year
under a plan unveiled Wednesday by Chairman Bill Kennard of the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we follow this course, we will be able to wire (another)
528,000 public school classrooms to the Internet,'' Kennard said.
``We will be able to connect one-third of public schools throughout
rural America.''
</P>
<P>
   That would allow the nation to reach the goal set by Vice
President Al Gore of connecting virtually every public and private
classroom to the Internet by the year 2000, said Education
Secretary Richard Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he wants the FCC to authorize the legal maximum of
$2.25 billion in discounts for schools and libraries during the
year that begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the program's first 18 months, which will end in June, more
than 25,000 schools, libraries, districts and system received $1.66
billion in discounts _ equal to about $1.1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The money comes from the e-rate, the ``universal access'' fee
that the FCC requires be paid by phone companies, most of which
pass it along to their customers under a system that costs the
average residential customer just under $1 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard apparently has the votes on the FCC to pass his plan
under existing law. But there is a slight chance that Congress
could block that by approving bills by some Republicans in Congress
who want to reduce or eliminate the fee.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Tancredo, R-Colo., and 14 Republican cosponsors have
introduced the ``E-Rate Termination Act.'' Tancredo has denounced
the e-rate as ``an unfunded mandate on the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., and five cosponsors from both parties
have proposed ending the program after five years, and Reps. Billy
Tauzin, R-La., and Conrad Burns, R-Mont., want to cap annual
spending at $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Klink and Tauzin bills would also collect the money through
an excise tax, rather than a fee. That worries religious school
leaders, because giving tax money to church-sponsored activities is
so controversial that such a change might hurt their chances of
getting a share of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer groups are also skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chairman Kennard can fund it without increasing my phone
bill, we won't squawk, but I'm suspicious,'' said Mark Cooper,
director of research for the Consumer Federation of America. ``If
he wants to fund this program, he should cut the fat somewhere
else, like lowering the subscriber line charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he believed that fee changes under consideration by
the FCC could offset the extra cost of his increase and leave
long-distance companies with $500 million that they could either
keep or use to lower their charges to customers.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of teachers, librarians, Catholic bishops,
farmers, school psychologists, education officials and two other
members of Clinton's cabinet joined in praising Kennard's plan.
</P>
<P>
   It will be adopted, and all efforts to slash it will fail,
supporters predicted when Kennard announced his position at a
meeting in the Washington headquarters of the National Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 32,000 applicants seeking $2.45 billion in the
year ahead should make their plans on the assumption that at least
$2.25 billion will be approved, said Lynne Bradley, deputy
executive director of the American Library Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have 80,000 schools and libraries where the parents, the
teachers, the administrators, the library and school board members
would arise if these discounts didn't continue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
