u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-INTERNET-1stlede     05-05 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-INTERNET-1stlede0506-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1stlede writethrough to eliminate duplicate words in fourth
graph
 &HT;    
 &HT;    INTERNET TO OFFER ONLINE TOOL TO HELP PROTECT KIDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- In the wake of the Columbine High School killings,
15 of the nation's top Internet firms came together Wednesday to
offer parents a set of easy-to-use tools aimed at protecting their
children from online violence, smut and hate.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the initiative at a bipartisan White House
briefing, Vice President Al Gore said: ``When it comes to the
Internet, too many parents feel now they are faced with a false
choice between unplugging the computer in the family room or
spending every moment of their lives looking over their child's
shoulder to make sure they are not wandering into some dangerous
online alleyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry initiative, Gore said, provides ``a third choice
(and) a better way'' -- in the form of a resource guide, dubbed the
``parents protection page.'' When the project is fully implemented
_ by July _ one mouse click from Web sites that account for 95 per
cent of all Internet traffic will take users to the
all-encompassing child-proofing guide.
</P>
<P>
   The service will give parents rapid access to as many as 80
features intended to provide them with more control over their home
computers. From the new protection Web site, parents will be able
to:
</P>
<P>
   - Deploy the latest blocking and filtering programs that can
limit access to violent game sites, hate groups and other materials
that adults deem are bad for children.
</P>
<P>
   - Monitor which Web sites and chat rooms their children have
visited.
</P>
<P>
   - Set time limits on their children's online sessions.
</P>
<P>
   - Get information on how to report criminal activity, with links
to such sites as the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children tip line.
</P>
<P>
   - Utilize pointers to ``kid-friendly'' sites that offer good
educational content.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gore is the leading Democratic presidential candidate,
some industry leaders feared they would be used in a political
response to the national outcry over last month's slayings in
Littleton, Colo. The killers maintained an Internet hate site that
hinted at the massacre-to-come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really had to scramble to find some Republicans to join
in,'' said Kathryn Montgomery, president of the Center for Media
Education. ``Some Internet folks refused to come because they
thought it smacked too much of a political event.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem was solved, however, when Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, R-Colo., agreed to join him in the Roosevelt Room, along
with Sen. Leahy, D-Vt. Speaking first, Campbell said, ``Now is not
the time to point fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore ranks among the nation's most computer savvy politician and
clearly hopes to parley that extensive knowledge in the 2000
presidential campaign. But he has also stumbled, earning widespread
scorn by claiming in March that he had ``created'' the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   While the direct cause of the killing spree by two Colorado
teenagers remains unknown, polls show that many Americans blame the
tragedy on the supposedly dangerous influence of the Internet --
along with access to firearms, violent TV shows and video games and
poor parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been talk on Capitol Hill and elsewhere over
the years about the need to improve online protection for young
people, industry leaders clearly felt the need to move quickly to
ease parental concerns in the aftermath of the Colorado shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 firms joining in the voluntary child-protection program
are America Online, AT&AMP;T, (at)Home, Bell Atlantic, Commercial
Internet Exchange, Disney, Excite, Lycos, MCI, Microsoft,
MindSpring Enterprises, Netscape, Network Solutions, Prodigy and
Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
