A5518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-FEUD-HNS &LR;      05-05 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-FEUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FOOTBALL AFFAIR TURNS SOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for DEBARTOLO)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ She says he's having her husband followed. He
says her husband put a photo of their departed mother in a drawer.
</P>
<P>
   No, they're not warring siblings yammering at each other on
``The Jerry Springer Show.'' They're the owners of one of the
prized franchises in professional sports, the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through high-priced, public-relations agents, they
wrangle, openly and bitterly, over matters most would keep in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The latest: John York, husband of Edward J. DeBartolo's
estranged sister, Denise DeBartolo York, had DeBartolo's
possessions removed from his old office at the 49ers' headquarters
in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo spokesman Rick Rice said Tuesday that DeBartolo's
belongings _ including a photo of his late mother, Marie _ were
``stuck in drawers and closets'' to make room for other occupants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's not pleased,'' Rice said. ``It's petty.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, York spokesman Sam Singer said some people secretly
tailed John York while he was in the San Francisco area recently.
York suspects they were paid by his brother-in-law, Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo knows nothing about anyone following his sister's
husband, Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's vacant office will be shared by John York and Keith
Lenhart, both vice presidents of the 49ers. ``John and Keith
Lenhart moved his stuff out of there,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Singer confirmed the move, but cast it in a different light,
saying it was pursuant to the suspension accord DeBartolo reached
with the National Football League in March.
</P>
<P>
   Under that agreement, DeBartolo accepted discipline for his role
in a Louisiana gambling-and-bribery case. The agreement permits
DeBartolo to return to the club in February 2000, but prohibits him
from keeping an office at 49ers' headquarters until then.
</P>
<P>
   Singer said club facilities manager Anthony Lozano was
instructed by York and Lenhart to notify DeBartolo of their plans
``because they need the space and per the commissioner's
instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that when DeBartolo was contacted two weeks ago, the
club co-owner asked only that the photo of his mother be mailed to
him, and it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team needs the space. A lot of people are doubled up,''
Singer said. ``Eddie had very few belongings, and 99 percent of
them were put in drawers in the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The office adjoins offices occupied by club general manager Bill
Walsh and football operations director John McVay.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo and York co-own the Youngstown, Ohio, family
corporation that owns the team. They are suing each other in courts
in San Francisco and Ohio over alleged misconduct relating to their
legal obligations to each other.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo says he expects to regain control of the team. York
says her intention is to keep the team and run it with the help of
her husband, but she would not rule out a separation of financial
interests, allowing the 49ers to remain in her brother's hands.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue is the club's value. DeBartolo contends York is
legally obligated to sell him her interest in the club, for roughly
$175 million _ half its estimated value, according to DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   But York claims the club is worth much more than $350 million,
based on sales of other NFL franchises since late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Singer said that last month John York noticed that he was being
followed during a visit to the San Francisco area to make
preparations for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Rice denied that DeBartolo had hired a private eye to follow
York.
</P>
<P>
   A source in the Yorks' camp also alleged that DeBartolo has
talked to friends and associates about moving the team to Florida,
if and when he wins control of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie has gone around and said to a variety of people that if
he owned and ran the team, he'd move to Florida,'' said source
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice said DeBartolo had no plans to move the club to
Florida. ``The team move is absolutely not something Eddie's
talking about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both DeBartolo and the Yorks have said, repeatedly, that they
intend to remain in San Francisco and to build a new stadium for
the 49ers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
