<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCERS-DEPART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIENCE FAVORITES LOOK PAST THE FORT WORTH DALLAS BALLET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORTH WORTH, Texas _ If they were attorneys or politicians or
doctors, they would just be getting started.
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Edson and Maria Thomas are dancers. For over a decade,
together with Maria Terezia Balogh, they were among the most
visible and admired figures at Fort Worth Dallas Ballet. Now in
their 30s, Edson and Thomas are ending their careers with the
company _ but not the way they would have planned.
</P>
<P>
   Artistic director Paul Mejia, whose devotion to the Balanchine
style and repertoire built a loyal, sophisticated audience after he
took over Fort Worth Dallas Ballet in 1987, resigned at the apex of
his career in January 1998, in the midst of a scandal involving
sexual harassment allegations. Benjamin Houk took over as artistic
director in summer 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Balogh, who had married Mejia the previous summer, was initially
listed as a company member for the 1998-99 season but has not
performed under Houk. Thomas and Edson remained with the company
but gradually disappeared from the spotlight. When contract
renewals were issued this year, neither Thomas nor Edson was
offered a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Edson, 36, has been the company's principal male dancer for more
than a decade in roles ranging from a traditional romantic prince
in ``Cinderella'' to the title role in the cool, mythic ``Apollo''
of Balanchine. This weekend, he will dance with the company for the
last time, performing in ``Coppelia'' in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas quietly ended 12 seasons of Fort Worth performances in
last month's Bass Performance Hall run of ``Coppelia.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Edson have declined to talk about their departure
from the company, except to say that it was not their decision.
But, at a recent interview at Edson's 70-year-old house in the
Fairmount neighborhood of Fort Worth, they put a perspective on
moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Edson, who graduated from high school in Arlington and spent a
semester at Rice University in Houston before pursuing dance full
time, has plenty of projects to keep him busy _ including the
renovation of the house, which he shares with his partner, Gregg
Howard.
</P>
<P>
   More dancing is a possibility _ ``I wouldn't rule it out,''
Edson says. However, retirement looms for any dancer after 35. And
performing is not quite as important to Edson now as teaching and
choreographing.
</P>
<P>
   Edson has built a working relationship as a choreographer and
teacher with the Lone Star Ballet in Canyon. He also choreographed
the Dallas performance of the touring ``Salute to Vienna'' New
Year's concert, with conductor Phillipe Entremont.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas began preparing for her departure from ballet when she
was 25 and had a role in Casa Manana's production of Bernstein's
``On the Town,'' in which she mostly danced but spoke a little.
</P>
<P>
   Thus discovering an interest in acting as well as dancing, she
took acting classes. By 1996, she won the role of the tough-talking
lesbian sister of the groom in Alan Ball's ``Five Women Wearing the
Same Dress'' at Circle Theatre in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   This week, she is playing the role of Christina in Casa Manana's
production of ``A Chorus Line'' at Bass Hall; she has also appeared
in local productions of ``Philadelphia Story,'' ``Jake's Women,''
``Oklahoma'' and ``Don't Dress for Dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of four children, born and reared in the Chicago
suburb of Roselle, Thomas started dancing at 7. At 15 she joined
the Chicago City Ballet, then directed by Mejia and the renowned
Balanchine ballerina Maria Tallchief. When the Chicago company
closed in 1987, she auditioned for several companies and accepted
an offer from Mejia for a job in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fort Worth Dallas Ballet is a relatively small company
in national terms, Thomas knows that it was a perfect fit for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've danced roles good dancers at larger companies would never
get to dance,'' she says. ``Some dancers are happy being in the
corps at the New York City Ballet, but my goal was to be able to
dance great roles, and I got to,'' she says. ``For 17 years, I got
to work with Paul Mejia. And for 11 years, I got to work with Todd
as a partner; he always knew what I needed. A lot of dancers move
from company to company and never get that continuity. I've been
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas married company member Frederic Trenary in 1995; Trenary
retired from dancing in 1998 and is working in phone tech support
in the computer field while studying for certification as a
Microsoft systems engineer. Thomas, an animal rights advocate, and
Trenary currently share their secluded east Fort Worth house with
numerous cats. For now, Thomas will continue to develop her acting
skills and credentials with the hope of building her second career,
although she and Trenary intend to have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be strange not to be in a ballet company,'' she says.
``I decided I was going to be a ballet dancer when I was 10; for so
long, it was my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas might eventually leave Fort Worth, either for the sake of
her career or that of her husband. But Edson thinks that he is not
likely to move.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Arlington with his family as a teen-ager, when there
was no professional company in Fort Worth. He spent summers at the
School of American Ballet and was a member of the now-defunct
Dallas Ballet in 1984-85, before joining the Fort Worth company in
1986. He dreams of producing a piece of choreography that would be
picked up and performed by major companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always `what-ifs' in life,'' he says, when asked if
he wishes he had pursued a career in a major dance center, rather
than being a big fish in the small pond of Fort Worth. ``Working
with Paul was an education. Just having the chance to do the
Balanchine ballets was exceptional. The ballet board here has been
dedicated, and I owe them my thanks for making this company what it
is. Fort Worth has made itself home for me, and I'm looking forward
to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
