<SLUG> BC-CIR-DEBT-INFOGLIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL STRATEGY FOR SORTING THROUGH SHIFTING IDENTITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One high-tech computer aid for tracking people down, often
useful for debt collectors, is made by Infoglide, a company that
has figured out ways to find some people who regularly change their
identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what clever criminals do,'' said Jay Valentine, chief
executive of Infoglide, in Austin, Texas ``They don't choose
123-45-6789 if they're making up a Social Security number. We can
find similarities with the numbers they use, subtle similarities,
and can put together tremendously strong correlations to show that
they're the same person, trying to get credit as a new person, even
though they're a deadbeat on their other credit files. And we can
create a profile, asking, Is this person likely to respond to us
calling them? Or to a threat? Or a subpoena?''
</P>
<P>
   Infoglide's Fraud Investigator software, which is powered by the
company's Similarity Search Engine, is used by three of the largest
credit bureaus in the country, the company said. It can help
determine similarities in delinquent accounts under different
names.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you are looking for contact information for a
debtor in a large database of accounts receivable, you can enter
the person's full name into the search engine and it will present a
list of possible matches, ranked according to how likely it is that
the entry is for that person. The company gives online examples of
how this works in two scenarios
(www.infoglide.com/pages/thumbdemo.htm).
</P>
<P>
   While the software is often used by debt collectors, it is also
used by people investigating things like insurance fraud and
criminal investigations. The company gives an example of what might
be turned up by such an investigation: ``You notice that the names
seem similar. Could this be the same individual with his name
accidentally mistyped or intentionally altered? You notice that the
first and last names in the similar claim are switched while the
middle name remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the address is slightly different. The street number has
two transposed digits, 2506 versus 2605. There is a different
apartment number and the ZIP code has 30 in one listing and 03 in
the other. With these similarities in the data, you suspect that
this similar claim is for the same individual.
</P>
<P>
   Either there was a data entry error, or the claimant
intentionally gave your company false data _ data just close enough
to the real information that they could later blame on an `honest
mistake' or `communication error.'''
</P>
<P>
   Credit investigators can look through a variety of databases for
a debtor's name or a close approximation of it, or information like
a Social Security number or address. The software presents 3-D
graphs with towers of data indicating how often a debtor appears in
the database.
</P>
<P>
   Thus records for James Stevens, Jim Stephens and JK Stevns can
appear together, and if there are matches among their addresses or
Social Security numbers, the likelihood that the references are all
for the same person is considered high. Tracers who hit a dead end
looking for James Stevens can find their man by looking for Jim.
</P>
<P>
   Infoglide was founded by David Wheeler, a computer scientist who
developed the search techniques for finding criminals after the
1981 murder of his father went unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology has been used to crack insurance fraud rings
and to hunt down criminals on the lam. ``Even a slight name change,
like W.J. Davis and Billy Dhaves, will make someone invisible to
most computer systems,'' Valentine said. ``The average person who
is a skipper will modify his or her name six times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
