<HEADLINE>
MY CEREAL PACKS A BIG PUNCH, JUST LIKE ME!
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday May 7)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   News item: Tempestuous Baltimore Orioles outfielder Albert Belle
has come out with his own brand of breakfast food called Slugger
Cereal.
</P>
<P>
   First off, I just want to say that I object to the word
``tempestuous.'' The dictionary defines tempestuous as ``violent''
or ``turbulent'' and that is not the way I see myself at all.
</P>
<P>
   It's you (bleeping) people in the (bleeping) media who use words
like this to describe me, which is why it's all I can do to resist
the urge to pick up all of you (bleepers) by your pencil necks and
shake some sense into you.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, I don't usually talk to you media (bleeps) because
all you're interested in is why I ripped a telephone off the
clubhouse wall, upset the buffet table or pushed Hannah Storm down
a flight of stairs, none of which has anything to do with baseball,
which is what I came here to play.
</P>
<P>
   I went 2 for 4 yesterday with a double and a home run and all
you jackals wrote about was that insignificant incident during
batting practice when I jumped into the stands and gave a little
lesson in manners to that mouthy kid with the colostomy bag who had
been pestering me for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   If you were going to write about anything, you should have
written about how dangerous people like that are because I wound up
cutting my fist on his wheelchair and now I can hardly swing a bat,
even the ones I've filled with cork.
</P>
<P>
   The fans have got to realize that when I'm on the field, I'm at
work and I'm not to be bothered. What would you do if someone came
up to you while you were writing a story and said, ``Hi! You're my
mother's favorite sportswriter! Would you mind signing this cap? It
would really brighten her day at the nursing home!'' I'll tell you
what you'd do. You'd pick the (bleeper) up by his ears and slam him
against a wall or maybe throw him out a window if you happen to
work on one of the upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's what I'd do. But enough about me. I'm here to
talk about my new breakfast cereal called Albert Belle Slugger
Cereal. It doesn't contain any of those (bleeping) vitamins and
minerals that kids hate, plus it's loaded with sugar, so your
little ones will have plenty of energy to deal with anyone who
might try to mess with 'em. Ha ha! I'm just joking, you gullible
(bleepers)! I'm just trying to show you that, yes, Albert Belle is
intense, but he's also got a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Take Halloween night a couple of years ago. Some kids were
messin' with me, ringing my doorbell and then running away. You
know, bein' kids. Some other ballplayers might have yelled at the
kids or maybe ignored them until they went away, but Albert Belle
wanted to show these kids that he can take a joke so I hopped in my
Mercedes and took off after them so I could deliver some Halloween
treats to them personally.
</P>
<P>
   Those little (bleepers) were quick, I'll tell you what. The
Orioles could use some speed like that in their lineup. Maybe dress
the players up in Freddy Krueger costumes instead of those silly
outfits with the bird on them. Ha ha! Just another joke, you
(bleepin) morons!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I'm fishtailing down the driveway, slingin' gravel
everywhere, trying to catch up with these kids so I could give each
one of 'em a nice, big Hersheys ``kiss'' and they're runnin' away
from me like I'm tryin' to kill 'em or something.
</P>
<P>
   I had to give up after I clipped a mailbox and my car skidded
into somebody's swimming pool, but I think the kids definitely got
the message that Albert Belle is a fun guy to hang out with on
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I wish the little (bleepers) were here right now so we
could share a bowl of cereal.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
