<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A line of showers and thunderstorms will form ahead of a cold
front sweeping east from the lower Ohio and Tennessee Valleys and
the central Gulf Coast States on Thursday. A few storms may reach
severe levels during the first part of the day as lifting of humid
air from the Gulf of Mexico by the front is augmented by a trailing
jet stream disturbance. Large hail and damaging winds are possible
in a few areas. The threat of severe weather will gradually
diminish thereafter as the jet stream disturbance moves northward.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to locally heavy rains are possible across portions of
the central Great Lakes region as invading moisture from the Gulf
of Mexico teams with an upper-level low pressure system over Iowa
and arriving jet stream disturbances from the south. Rainfalls
between 1 and 3 inches are possible. Rain may be accompanied by
thunder and small hail in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, cool, wind-blown rain will dampen parts of the
northern Plains. Gusty winds from the north will average 15 to 25
mph from the Dakotas to Nebraska. Rainfalls will generally be light
to moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will escort a cold front into the Pacific Northwest
Thursday. In the wake of the front, scattered showers will persist
as a trailing jet stream disturbance arrives from the Pacific.
Later in the day, isolated thunderstorms are possible east of the
Cascades in Washington and Oregon as the disturbance approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a widely separated showers will affect the northern
Middle Atlantic States as a warm front approaches from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rare Video
</P>
<P>
   The striking video of two tornadoes attached to the same
thunderstorm over Oklahoma on Monday captured a rare event. The
thinner twister was likely associated with the weakening stages of
a small, rotating low pressure system, called a ``mesocyclone,''
that formed within the thunderstorm. Though deteriorating, the
aging low provided a favorable environment for a new mesocyclone to
form by circulating rain-cooled air in its wake toward warm, humid
air ahead of it. Along the boundary between the contrasting air
masses, a new mesocyclone spawned the massive tornado also shown on
the video.
</P>
</TEXT>
