<HEADLINE>
HOW VOLKSWAGEN GOT THE BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: During a Volkswagen Jetta commercial, a couple in the car
play a CD and it appears that everything outside the car is moving
to the beat of the music. What is the name of the song and who
recorded it? _ C.P., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The song, ``Jung at Heart,'' was composed for that commercial
by Peter DuCharme, also known as Master Cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   ``DuCharme was specifically asked to write the music at 94 beats
a minute _ the cadence, it turns out, of a brisk walk _ so that the
physical movement in the ads could be in harmony with the chords,''
according to ``AdWeek.'' ``During the shoot, that beat was blared
over loudspeakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The song isn't available yet on CD, but Volkswagen has made it
available for free download on the World Wide Web at
www3.vw.com/vwworld/music.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is K used as an abbreviation for 1,000 in terms like the
``Y2K problem''? _ O.M., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: K is an abbreviation for kilo, the Greek word meaning ``one
thousand'' that also shows up in metric terms such as kilogram and
kilometer.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is shorthand for the year 2000, and it appears most often
when describing computer problems anticipated to occur on Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem involves computer programs and hardware that
represent years as two digits instead of four: 99 instead of 1999,
98 for 1998, and so on. The changeover from year ``99'' to year
``00'' is expected to cause many computers to run incorrectly or
stop running entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I obtain Dash laundry detergent? _ L.N., via the
Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Dash, introduced by Procter &AMP; Gamble in 1929, is not
presently being sold in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The detergent is one of the company's main brands in France,
Germany, Italy, Spain and other countries in Europe, the Middle
East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Dash and other Procter &AMP; Gamble
products, call the company's consumer relations line at (800)
543-0485 or visit the World Wide Web site www.pg.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
