<HEADLINE>
PHONES AT A PREMIUM ON THE ALBANIAN BEAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The refugee crisis in Albania has given birth to a minor crisis
of a different sort: journalists in need of mobile phones. At the
beginning of April, the state-owned monopoly provider of mobile
service, Albania Mobile Communications, canceled the roaming
agreements that allowed subscribers from foreign services to make
calls on its network. ``Our system was overloaded, mostly by
journalists,'' said Rauf Elmas, an Albania Mobile executive.
</P>
<P>
   That severance led to not only an onslaught of complaints from
roaming partners, but opportunity for certain Albanians. Albania
Mobile subscribers and distributors are ``renting'' the cards that
digitally identify them as customers of the Albanian provider when
inserted into handsets compatible with GSM, the European standard
for mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   When NBC News set up shop in Albania, they took Iridium
satellite phones and GSM phones they had rented from an American
company, Cellhire. When the GSM phones failed, NBC ended up renting
three Albania Mobile cards and phones. ``It's unbelievable what
they charge _ $900 a month just for the phone, and usage is
extra,'' said Ira Kurti, an Albanian working as an assistant
producer and translator for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Elmas of Albania Mobile said that the problem should be
alleviated by the end of June, when Albania's capacity will be
expanded to 20,000 subscribers from 8,000. He said that at least
400 Albania Mobile cards were being rented to journalists by
regular subscribers and that he even had a friend who had purchased
four subscriptions, anticipating that foreign journalists would
need to call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``These events have been very convenient for Albanians who have
phone cards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Oehmke &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS E-MAIL LINKED TO A PAGER
</P>
<P>
   SkyTel Communications Inc., together with American Mobile
Satellite Corp. and pager manufacturer Research in Motion (RIM)
Ltd. earlier this week announced a nationwide wireless e-mail
service that operates with a new RIM pager.
</P>
<P>
   Available next month, the new service, dubbed eLink, will allow
users to send and receive wireless messages using their existing
e-mail address, rather than adopting an address unique to the
paging service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read your mail and reply and when the recipient gets
the message, it looks like you replied right from your desktop,''
said Dan Croft, vice president of messaging services at American
Mobile, which owns a satellite and terrestrial communications
network. ``They have no idea that you sent it wirelessly.''
</P>
<P>
   The new RIM Interactive Pager 850 carries a suggested retail
price of $359. It includes a docking cradle that simultaneously
recharges the pager's battery and synchronizes address book,
calendar, and to-do information with a desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The eLink service will cost $59.95 per month. Croft said the
high price will confine the service to the corporate sector,
placing it out of reach for most home users. ``We're still a couple
of years away from the consumer wanting wireless access at an
affordable price away from home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Hafner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIEWING THE PC THROUGH EYEGLASS LENSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wearable computers have gotten their share of hype over the last
few years, but even technologists will admit that bulky gadgets
aren't in vogue. MicroOptical, a company in Westwood, Mass., aims
to change that with what it calls EyeGlass Displays, or EGDs for
short.
</P>
<P>
   A person wearing the glasses can view Web pages, pager numbers,
television, or any other visual information by looking through the
lenses. The information comes from a palm-sized computer that
attaches to the viewer's belt. Thin cables from the computer carry
the data behind the ears, to a microdisplay unit at the temple. The
microdisplay sends the picture through the lens, which contain
embedded mirrors that reflect information into the viewer's eye.
When the computer is on, the picture looks like a miniature
computer screen floating in front of your face. When the computer
is turned off, the EGD can be used like a normal pair of
eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Holzel, MicroOptical's vice-president of sales and
marketing, is now marketing the EGDs, as well as a clip-on version,
to medical-instrumentation companies. Doctors could use the glasses
to get critical medical information without having to look away
from a patient, Holzel said. ``Or you could go into movie
theater,'' he added, ``and get subtitles that only you would see.''
Lisa Guernsey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODIGIOUS USE OF PRODIGY LEADS TO TERMINATION
</P>
<P>
   You might think that the meaning of the word ``unlimited'' is
very clear but, if you're Internet service provider is Prodigy,
think again. The company, which advertises ``unlimited service''
for $19.95, recently informed more than 100 customers that their
accounts would be terminated because of excessive usage.
</P>
<P>
   The customers, who pay $19.95 a month for unlimited service,
were told that their accounts would be terminated because they had
been identified as excessive users, said Dan Levine, a Prodigy
spokesman. Although there is no specific cap on the number of hours
a customer can stay connected, Levine said, ``We identified during
routine network maintenance a number of accounts where the
excessively high levels of activity were symptomatic of improper
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Prodigy sent email to nearly 300 excessive users to
``ask if they were forgetting to log off or if a user's password
was stolen and used by someone else,'' Levine said. Customers who
did not respond received a follow-up message a few weeks later,
Levine said. ``The language was stronger. But if they have a
legitimate reason for being connected for so many hours, we won't
terminate their accounts. We heard, for example from a few users
who said they were permanently disabled and needed to maintain a
constant connection to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet service providers that advertise unlimited
service also try to limit usage. For instance, both Mindspring and
America Online employ features to automatically log off any
customer whose computer remains idle. Mindspring will log off a
customer after 30 minutes of idle time; AOL will log off a customer
after 10 minutes. Prodigy, however, has no idle disconnect feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's actually considered a benefit of our service,'' said
Levine of Prodigy. ``But that's why we're trying to change the
behavior of people who routinely log on and then don't log off even
when they walk away from the computer for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Slatalla &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING AN ANNIVERSARY FOR BAR-CODE SCANNERS
</P>
<P>
   Attention, presidential candidates: May 5 marked the silver
anniversary of the bar-code scanner. Twenty-five years earlier, the
NCR Corp. introduced the device at the 1974 annual convention of
the Super Market Institute. Six weeks later, a ten-pack of
Wrigley's Juicy Fruit gum became the first retail item ever to be
purchased with the technology when it was swiped across a scanner
at the Marsh Supermarket in Troy, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The White House greeted the Universal Product Code and bar
scanners with enthusiasm _ ``It's the wave of the future, and I'm
very upbeat on the system,'' said Virginia Knauer, special
assistant for consumer affairs to the president of the United
States _ but the technology didn't always return the favor. In
1992, President George Bush, fighting the impression that he was
out of touch with voters, was pilloried for being allegedly amazed
when he saw one of the then-ubiquitous scanners in action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
