<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CHAIRS-NYT &LR;      05-05 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHAIRS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC-CARPET CHAIRS OF VIRTUAL REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a seat in a chair of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Put your feet up in the Flostation, for example, and immerse
yourself in a virtual-reality landscape, accompanied by sounds,
video, vibrations and aromas that match the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Try a huge leather office chair called Smartspace, with its own
Internet connection, video projectors, display screens and embedded
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Or sit down in an ``augmented smart chair'' that senses your
every move _ and then corrects your posture.
</P>
<P>
   All three chairs are being developed by researchers who are
determined to make a piece of furniture that is more than a place
to sit. They envision chairs that are part computer, part
multimedia space, part communication device.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to wipe the slate clean,'' said Brian Park, the
developer of the Flostation. He said he had wanted to break away
from the traditional notion of a chair that is pulled up to a desk
to face a boxy computer monitor. ``I wanted to make it really an
experience within cyberspace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find these chairs in an Ethan Allen showroom any time
soon, but Park has opened an online business called Flogiston
(www.flogiston.com) and is starting to sell the Flostation chair
for about $5,000. (The name Flogiston comes from phlogiston, the
name of an imaginary element once thought to be given off during
burning. The 18th-century quest for phlogiston marked a transition
between chemistry and alchemy; Smart thinks that today's
intellectual understanding of cyberspace is in a similar
transition.)
</P>
<P>
   The Smartspace chair (innovate.bt.com/showcase/smartspace) is a
little farther away from the marketplace. British
Telecommunications hatched the idea and is in the process of
licensing it to a yet-undisclosed commercial manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The augmented smart chair is a research project that started at
the Media Laboratory of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
and is now being continued at Purdue University. Hong Z. Tan, a
Purdue engineering professor who is leading the project, says that
its still too early to predict when the chair might become a
commercial product, but prototypes have already been tested at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   The Flostation is devoted to entertainment and relaxation. It is
designed to help people experience virtual reality in comfort,
without having to stand up and don a bulky helmet. When seated in
the reclined chair, your body is almost lying down, with your knees
slightly bent _ the same position that Park says is most
comfortable to astronauts in zero gravity. He calls it the human
body's most comfortable state.
</P>
<P>
   The chair is topped with a metal dome that can be pulled over
your head, much like the hair dryers in many beauty salons. The
inside of the dome becomes a 180-degree screen that displays images
or videos from a nearby projector that is connected to a computer
or television. The projector works like the rear-projection devices
within high-end television screens, which display an image on the
front and back of the screen at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers near the ears of the person in the Flostation _ Park
calls them ``nearphones'' _ provide sound, and shakers under the
chair provide low-frequency vibrations. A joystick or keyboard is
necessary to interact with the projected images. Park is working on
the chair's next component: an aromatherapy system that will emit
the perfume of herbal oils.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I focus on is comfort and relaxation for extended
immersion in a virtual space,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   He came up with the idea for the chair several years ago, when
he was a researcher for NASA, designing a training system for
astronauts. But now the technology exists to make the chairs a
viable commercial product, he said. He hopes to sell them to
airports, resorts and cruise ships. He also sees potential for the
chair as a high-end entertainment unit, for use in the home or in
virtual-reality playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Smartspace chair, on the other hand, may first show up in
office buildings. Scientists in British Telecomm's research
laboratory developed the Smartspace to get a glimpse of how
business people may be interacting with one another in the future.
``This is a concept of what your desk may look like in a few years'
time,'' said John V. Collins, a research scientist at British
Telecomm.
</P>
<P>
   This chair-desk hybrid does not include a keyboard, mouse or
typical computer monitor. Its main feature is a vertical wraparound
screen that is pulled around you after you have been seated; images
are projected from two cameras perched near the sitter's shoulders
onto the screen. The chair also includes a small horizontal screen
that floats above your lap once you have been latched in and uses
touch-screen technology instead of a keyboard. People have an
easier time focusing on their work when they are looking down on
it, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive work, like participating in teleconferences or
looking at large graphics, would be done using the wraparound
screen, which has a liquid-crystal display and can become opaque or
transparent at the touch of a button. A user could turn on the
screen to go into a teleconference or concentrate on an individual
project, then turn off the screen to see and interact with people
nearby. That flexibility became an important part of the design,
Collins said, after British Telecomm researchers realized that
people did not like the idea of putting on helmets to experience
immersive cyberspace, at least not at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a virtual-reality helmet, you are cut off,'' he said.
``They are uncomfortable. And you feel a bit like an idiot wearing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While both the Flostation and the Smartspace look quite
different from chairs we are used to, the sensing chair that Ms.
Tan is developing at Purdue may have a less futuristic appearance.
Its sensors are designed to be invisible to the user, embedded in
the seat cushions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tan declined to discuss the project at this early stage. But
Alex Pentland, the academic head of the MIT Media Lab and Ms. Tan's
adviser during her doctoral work, describes the sensors as air
pockets lined with something like aluminum foil. As the air pockets
are squeezed, pieces of the lining come closer together, and
electronic sensing is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the seat could react a little bit to you, it could say:
`Oh, he's been in one position for too long. Let's just change the
pressure system a little to get him to move,'' Pentland said. He
imagined the chair's being used in automobiles and airplanes. If
the chair was incorporated into automobiles, he added, it could
also include a subtle vibrating system that would send messages
from other sensors in and on the car. Bus drivers might feel a
slight tickle, for example, to warn them that another vehicle had
pulled up behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the chair of the future will combine elements of all three
new concepts: a relaxing, multimedia work space with a vibrating
message system. It would be missing only one thing: a cup holder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
