<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONG-DISTANCE-TRAINS-     05-05 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE-TRAINS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONLY WAY TO GO: LONG-DISTANCE TRAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    __________-FREE ART!__________-
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    _________________________-
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Their very names are evocative: ``The Empire Builder,'' ``The
Sunset Limited'' and ``The Coast Starlight.'' They are among the
last of the great trains that cross the United States, recalling a
time when rail travel was the only way to go. Even today, a
well-planned rail journey can recapture much of the old romance of
the rails. There are multi-day, cross-country routes in the United
States on Amtrak and in Canada on Via Rail, as well as two-day
daylight trips through the _ on the Rocky Mountaineer to choose
from.
 &HT;    Train travel is all about slowing down and making the journey a
part of the vacation. Fortunately, the comfort level has risen of
late. The much-beleaguered Amtrak has updated its cars and improved
levels of service and food in the past five years. While coach
travel remains an economical option, travel by sleeper car can
really transform a train journey.
 &HT;    Sleepers require first class fares on Amtrak and include all
meals. Standard bedrooms have two reclining seats that convert to a
bed. Deluxe bedrooms, which are about 30 percent more expensive and
come with a private bathroom, are designed for two passengers and
feature a sofa and armchair that convert to an upper and lower
berth.
 &HT;    Amtrak pricing is rather complicated and not unlike airline
pricing. There's a set charge for a sleeper compartment, and then
fare charges for each passenger which are based on a variety of
factors, including the season and the day of the week. Contact
Amtrak (60 Massachusetts Ave. N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002;
800-USA-RAIL/www.amtrak.com) for current pricing. Note that making
multiple stops is a popular option, as is the North America Rail
Pass, which provides 30 days of unlimited travel in both the U.S.
and Canada for a 90-day period.
 &HT;    What are the most exciting overnight routes in the United
States? Start with ``The Sunset Limited,'' which runs from Orlando
to Los Angeles by way of New Orleans and Houston, some 3,000 miles
across the county, an eight-state journey from Florida to
California. Then there's ``The Empire Builder,'' which leaves from
Chicago and goes to either Portland or Seattle. This train through
Big Sky country brings travelers face to face with the Bear Paw
Mountains, Glacier National Park, the Rockies and the Cascades.
 &HT;    The ``California Zephyr'' runs from Chicago through three
mountain ranges, two deserts and alongside the Colorado River for a
couple of hundred miles before arriving in greater San Francisco.
Many diehard train buffs as well as first-timers claim that this is
the most beautiful train ride in the United States. From the
breadbasket of America to the Rockies, from the Wasatch Mountains
and into Salt Lake City, the train continues to Reno, the mile-high
Donner Pass and then down to Sacramento and into Oakland.
 &HT;    ``The Coast Starlight'' runs from Los Angeles to Seattle. It's
Amtrak's most popular train and it literally hugs the Pacific
coast, from southern California all the way up to Santa Barbara,
and then to San Francisco, into Oregon and finally Washington. Only
``The Coast Starlight'' has the Pacific Parlour Car, a customized
lounge car for first class travelers.
 &HT;    ``The Cardinal'' links Washington D.C. with Chicago via the
riverfront city of Cincinnati, through the Blue Ridge Mountains of
Virginia and along the New River Gorge in West Virginia, with a
U.S. Forest Ranger providing commentary at apt moments.
 &HT;    On VIA Rail Canada's (P.O. Box 8116, Station A, Montreal,
Quebec, Canada H3C 3N3; 800-561-9181 www.viarail.ca) trains in the
East, Easterly Class offers private bedrooms with a bathroom and a
shared shower while semi-private seating converts to a curtained
berth by night. On VIA Rail trains in Western Canada, Silver &AMP; Blue
Class bedrooms sleep two with a private bathroom. Less expensive is
semi-private seating that converts to curtained berths at night,
with shared bathrooms.
 &HT;    In Canada, ``The Ocean'' is the train that runs between
Montreal, Quebec and Halifax, Nova Scotia. The scenic way to pass
from French-speaking Quebec into the Maritimes, this train speeds
along the southern shore of the St. Lawrence, past Riviere-du-Loup
through the Matapedia Valley to Baie des Chaleurs. From there, it
continues on to New Brunswick, through Moncton, into Amherst, Nova
Scotia and finally to Halifax.
 &HT;    ``The Canadian'' runs from Toronto, Ontario to Vancouver,
British Columbia. The most famous train ride in North America
crosses two-thirds of Canada, from the endless forest of Ontario to
the surreal plains of Manitoba and the wheat fields of Saskatchewan
before reaching the heart of the Rockies in Jasper, where elk
wander through the streets. Continuing through the Rockies, the
train cuts through the high desert of British Columbia before
reaching the coastal rain forest and Vancouver, a journey of 2,770
miles.
 &HT;    Finally, Rocky Mountaineer Railtours (1150 Station Street,
Vancouver, B.C. Canada V6A 2X7; 800-665-7245;
www.rockymountaineer.com) makes two-day daylight trips through the
Canadian Rockies on the Rocky Mountaineer, traveling from Vancouver
to either Jasper, Banff or Calgary, Alberta, with overnight hotel
stay in Kamloops, British Columbia. For Signature Service, prices
start at $362 per person and include the overnight stay and some
meals.
 (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 Everett Potter  
