<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKING-TUSCANY-ART-N     05-05 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKING-TUSCANY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER 
 WALKING THE HILLS OF TUSCANY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    If anyone tells you that mature travelers can't make a walking
tour of Tuscany, they're wrong. Bernie Lee (72-years-old) and his
wife, Helen, (62-years-old) are living proof: Last October they
hiked up to Cortona, Montepulciano, Pienza, Montalcino, Siena and
San Gimignano _ some of the most beautiful hill towns in Tuscany.
 &HT;    The Lees suggest that mature travelers get in shape before
undertaking a Tuscany walking trip. It's ill-advised to think you
can get up off the couch, go to Italy and start walking. Some
Tuscan hills rise 2,000 feet and more, and the most beautiful towns
are situated on top.
 &HT;    Both Lees are retired _ he from advertising, she from banking _
and live in Oregon in a house at 900-feet elevation. But since they
rarely walk to their home, they sought their doctors' OK to go
climbing in Tuscany which was also required by their tour company's
health questionnaire. The only extra shot their doctors recommended
was Hepatitis B.
 &HT;    Both exercise regularly. Helen does water aerobics three
mornings a week, and Bernie walks two miles and lifts weights. But
what saved the Lees in Tuscany was their homemade training program
of weekly 5-mile walk begun a month prior to departure.
 &HT;    According to the travel brochure from their tour company,
Ciclismo Classico, which books biking and walking tours from
offices at 13 Marathon St., Arlington, Mass. 02474 (call 800
866-7314), they would be walking four to six miles per day. But as
it turned out, some days they walked ten miles.
 &HT;    Lee especially remembers the sunny afternoon when they were on
their way from Montichiello to Pienza. After walking for about two
hours _ through farmers' fields and along a blacktop back-road _ he
looked across a broad valley where silver-green olive trees
shimmered in the heat. Beyond was their destination: A distant
pine-topped hill where the ancient wall of Pienza glowed in the
golden afternoon light.
 &HT;    He remembers sweating up the hill as the pines, but not Pienza,
got closer.
 &HT;    ``Forty minutes later,'' he recalls, ``I reached the trees and
saw that lying road make a right-angle turn, loop down the hill,
meander across another wide valley and then climb a longer, steeper
hill to Pienza's gate!''
 &HT;    Two hours later, he walked through the gate, tired and sweaty,
but grateful for their pre-trip exercise routine that had paid off
with extra stamina.
 DINING  
 &HT;    The Lees' hotel breakfast fare consisted of juice, coffee, tea,
great bread and croissants, cheese and/or thin slivers of
prosciutto. During eight days in Tuscany, they never saw an egg.
 &HT;    But the dinners! In Pienza at a restaurant located inside the
gate, the Lees say they ate one of life's memorable meals. They sat
down at 8 p.m. and the food kept coming for the next two hours:
appetizers, soup, pasta, vegetables, salad, two meat dishes
(including wild boar) and dessert.
 ARTICULATE AND ATTRACTIVE GUIDES  
 &HT;    Natives of Tuscany, the Lee's guides were proud of their land
and happy to share their knowledge of its history, art and culture.
Guido Giuntini, 34, is tall, athletic and a graduate in political
science, while 29-year old Angelica Turi is petite, fair, and works
in art restoration in Florence.
 &HT;    Near Cortona, Turi stood in a tiny cell in gray Etruscan tomb
and talked about the people who had built the structure in 900 B.C.
and the type of stone they used.
 &HT;    South of Siena, Giuntini led the group across a drawbridge and
into a beautiful Benedictine monastery founded in 1313, the remote
abbey of Mount Oliveto Maggiore. Inside the great cloister, whose
four walls seem alive with huge paintings depicting the life of St.
Benedict, Giuntini showed the group how to read the 36 frescoes by
artists Sodoma and Signorelli.
 &HT;    Occasionally the guides brought in other Tuscan experts _ an
archaeologist in Cortona, a historian in Siena and a wine maker in
Montalcino. Their tour also included side trips to a centuries-old
crystal workshop and to an olive oil factory.
 HITCHING A LIFT  
 &HT;    On some side trips the Lees' tour group rode in a van, which was
also available to walkers on long hikes who needed to hitch a ride.
The van was always ready in the event of an emergency and the
guides carried first-aid kits and cellular phones to contact the
van or the nearest hospital/helicopter service if needed.
 &HT;    Giuntini says most of the people on walking tours are over 50.
The Lees' group had a few 40-year-olds, but most travelers were in
their 50s, 60s or 70s.
 NO PROBLEM  
 &HT;    The Lees had no trouble with water in Italy. Or, with
communication. Italians are pros at reading gestures and
expressions, although they appreciate your efforts to speak their
language.
 &HT;    They recommend walkers take a small backpack or waistpack for
camera, binoculars, light rain jacket and water bottle.
Specifically, they suggest a pack with a handy bottle pocket.
 &HT;    Also recommended are comfortable, well-fitting walking shoes _
particularly high-tops _ to support ankles on rough trails and
cobblestone streets. To prevent blisters, the Lees suggest a thin
pair of socks over thicker walking socks.
 &HT;    Accommodations on the Tuscany walking tours were, according to
the Lees, on par with the not-bad hotels in Fresno or Keokuk.
However, the hotels are located atop hills and boast spectacular
views.
 &HT;    The Lees paid $2,250 for this eight-day tour, including hotels,
breakfasts, two picnics and six dinners.
 &HT;    ``A little spendy,'' according to Helen. Bernie agrees, ``Maybe
so. But we had a wonderful time in Tuscany.''
 &HT;    
 WALKS FOR SENIORS  
 &HT;    Hundreds of companies around the world package walking trips,
but some are ideal for mature travelers. Brochures rate them by
difficulty, van support and all meals. Walks can range up to ten
miles a day, but those designed for seniors are usually a bit
shorter.
 &HT;    Shott's Walks in the West offers an all-year series of
lodge-based walking trips limited to travelers 50 years and older
in Alaska, Colorado and other parts of the West and Northwest.
(719) 531-9577.
 &HT;    Walking the World packages hiking trips just for seniors that
include places ranging from Hawaii's volcanoes to New Zealand's
Milford Track. (800) 340-9255.
 &HT;    Walk Your Way. Rosemary O'Chris, who grew up in England, leads
low-key hikes through places like the Cotswolds, Dorset Villages
and the Lake District. Many are circular walks with light
day-packs, based in a single village. (970) 881-2709.
 &HT;    ElderTreks' demanding series of worldwide trips, limited to
active seniors, often includes back-packing and camping out in
places like the Australian Outback, Galapagos and Borneo. (416)
588-5000.
 &HT;    Mount Robson Adventure Holidays ``Fifty Plus Adventures''
include shorter scenic walks in the shadow of Canada's highest
peak, plus bird-watching, canoeing and rafting. (250) 566-4386.
 &HT;    Nifty Over Fifty tours are led by Jan Coyle in her native New
Zealand. Write Pacific Pathways, 1919 Chula Vista, Belmont, CA
94002; call (650) 595-2090.
 &HT;    Look Again Tours of Sacramento offers an annual walking trip to
the British Isles for those 50 years and older. Call (916)
448-7202.
 &HT;    Get information and book these direct or through your travel
agent.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     ( The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
