A5549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HASEK-BOS &LR;      05-05 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HASEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK: SABRES LONE MAGICIAN IN GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The Sabres encircled the angry buffalo logo at
center ice in Marine Midland Arena Wednesday as they awaited
instructions from their coaches at practice. All except one.
</P>
<P>
   Like an aloof diva, Dominik Hasek left the masses in his wake,
skating deliberately toward his net, deep in contemplation,
concocting who knows what diabolical and illogical schemes of
psychological torture. He did not hear as his boss indirectly
talked about him behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' said coach Lindy Ruff, ``let's do some
two-on-ones, score a few goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' chances of boosting their offensive confidence at
their goaltender's expense were about equal to those of the wispy,
5-foot-11-inch, 170-pound Hasek becoming Mr. Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, some 30 in all, a pair of Sabre forwards would
play keepaway from a lone defender and converge on Hasek _ the
classic goalie's nightmare, when the netminder is most vulnerable,
unsure which attacker will strike. At the end of the drill, after
Hasek had done his impressions of a starving seal flopping along
the ice begging for fish, exactly three pucks lay behind him in the
net.
</P>
<P>
   So rare was the occurrence that each time a Sabre converted,
observing teammates would form a chorus of cheers _ part
admiration, part disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I really notice about Dom,'' said veteran defenseman
Darryl Shannon, ``is the effort he puts out in practice. He tries
hard on every guy, gets pissed off when anyone scores, makes it
more of a challenge. It's contagious. Guys try harder. And when
they score, they celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   And these are his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what it must be like to confront Hasek in actual battle.
Sane opponents want no part of him _ perhaps because he has used
most of those parts, and some he seems to have invented, to deny
and demoralize them. Whether he's rolling on the ice as if he's
been shot, performing a scissor kick worthy of a synchronized
swimmer, thrusting out a skate as if he were discarding one of his
legs, or flicking his glove hand as if he were playing catch in the
backyard, Hasek stops the puck. True, it's in a manner that ranges
between unorthodox and unimaginable, but it works. Better than any
goalie in the National Hockey League, as a matter of fact. That's
why last season Hasek became the first at his position to win two
straight MVP awards _ which made suitable bookends for the 1998
Olympic gold medal he almost single-handedly seized for his native
Czech Republic _ and why he is being hailed as perhaps the greatest
ever to man a net.
</P>
<P>
   It is also why the Sabres strike fear into any potential playoff
opponent despite their lowly seventh-place ranking in the Eastern
Conference, which was largely due to the fact that Hasek was
sidelined for 13 games with back and groin injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Ottawa Senators, second overall in the conference and
champions of the Northeast Division, 12 points ahead of neighbor
Buffalo, were the first victims of the Curse of the Dominator this
spring. Ottawa was swept aside by the next-to-last playoff
qualifier mainly through the handiwork of Hasek, who set the tone
for the four-game ouster with a 2-1 victory in the opener, when
Buffalo was outshot, 41-15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the Bruins who have drawn the joker from the deck,
facing the Sabres in a best-of-seven second-round series that
starts Thursday night in Boston. The Bruins' alternative foe in the
Eastern semifinals would have been Toronto, a team of far more
balance than Buffalo and one that also boasts a goalie who is no
slacker, Curtis Joseph. Yet the prevailing notion is that the
Sabres loom as a tougher obstacle, for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Dom factor,'' said Ruff, whose team beat Boston in
four of five meetings during the regular season, three of the wins
with Hasek in goal. ``I don't think anyone wants to face him when
he's on his game. We're not kidding anybody _ Dom's the guy for us.
He's one of the elite players.''
</P>
<P>
   So elite that the company he keeps is historic. ``(Jaromir) Jagr
the way he's playing now,'' said Ruff. ``(Wayne) Gretzky in his
prime. Guys who could dominate, win a game, turn a series. That's
Dom. The first game against Ottawa was an example.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the playoffs, where goaltending is considered paramount,
Hasek's impact is even more fearsome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams come in,'' said Sabres captain Michael Peca, perhaps
hockey's finest defensive forward, ``and see he's the best goalie
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, whose excitement quotient is inversely proportionate to
his excellence, blandly dismisses the accolades, as he does most
things when he's in the public eye: ``I just go on playing hockey
and do the best I can on the ice. I don't care what other people
say about me. We are a very good all-around team.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, without Hasek, the Sabres are a very unimposing team.
They play bottleneck defense (175 goals against, second in the
league) thanks to him but have limited firepower (207 goals, 17th
among 27 NHL teams). And they won't be helped in that area by the
loss at least for the series opener of 40-goal scorer Miroslav
Satan, whose ankle, injured when struck by a shot from teammate
Alexei Zhitnik against Ottawa, hasn't responded during the nine-day
layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who that leaves the focus on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that Dominik Hasek basically makes that
team,'' said Boston's Byron Dafoe, one of the few goalies who
statistically approached Hasek this season _ and for whom Hasek
voted as a first-team All-Star. ``He can win games single-handedly,
and he has. He has such a presence about him that he can intimidate
a goal scorer. They almost do too much with the puck instead of
just putting a shot on net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about him,'' added Dafoe, who returned the favor by
putting Hasek on his All-Star ballot, ``is that he's a battler.
He'll stop the puck any way he can. It doesn't always look pretty,
but he doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, despite his own claims to the contrary, the maniacally
competitive and ferociously proud Hasek does care how he is
regarded. Universal acceptance has come relatively late in the
34-year-old's NHL career, which almost ended before it started.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A native of Pardubice, he learned about ice hockey on ponds and
goaltending by standing in a doorway at home while his father, Jan,
and an uncle barraged him with tennis balls; perhaps that's why it
often seems he treats the puck as one. To this day, his methods of
honing his game can be, shall we say, unique. During this extended
break between series, Hasek spent a couple of afternoons playing
street hockey with his son and the neighborhood kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's not where I get my style,'' he said with a laugh.
``It's something I like to do because it's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a nasty rumor circulating that Hasek had let a kid
score on him, but those who know him insist he would never permit
such perfidy.
</P>
<P>
   In more conventional circles, Hasek had a tougher time fitting
in. A star in the Czech League, he didn't give US hockey a try
until he was 25 _ and he tried to return to his homeland when he
found himself buried in the minors with the Blackhawks. Mike
Keenan, then the Chicago coach, wouldn't grant his release but did
shuffle him off to Buffalo, where, after his first full season, he
was left unprotected in the Anaheim-Florida expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some goalies longer to mature,'' said Peca. ``When
Dom started, no one knew he was going to be the best goalie in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't acknowledged even after Hasek began dominating in
the NHL. Despite winning three Vezina Trophies as the league's top
goalie in the next four years and becoming the first netminder
since Montreal's Jacques Plante in 1962 to capture the Hart Trophy
as MVP, Hasek was dogged by skepticism that he was merely a
statistical marvel, not a champion.
</P>
<P>
   That notion was reinforced during the 1997 playoffs, most of
which Hasek missed, claiming injury _ then assaulting a Buffalo
writer who suggested in print that the pain was all in his head, a
serious case of excessive pressure. Coupled with the fact that he
led the coup that got popular coach Ted Nolan fired, that caused
Hasek to become perhaps the first MVP ever to be the object of his
hometown fans' wrath when he took the ice at the start of the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   But the boos and the pejoratives vanished after that glorious
fortnight in Nagano, when Hasek led the long-shot Czechs past the
United States, Canada, and Russia in the Olympic medal round. It
was a performance punctuated by perhaps the most legendary shootout
since the O.K. Corral, when Hasek foiled Canada's five deadliest
snipers _ Theo Fleury, Ray Bourque, Joe Nieuwendyk, Eric Lindros,
and Brendan Shanahan _ to give the Czechs a semifinal win.
</P>
<P>
   Laconic as always, Hasek, who became an icon in his homeland,
insists that his exploits in Japan proved nothing to him. ``My
confidence has always been the same,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he does concede that it had a galvanizing effect on his
public image. ``All of a sudden,'' he said, ``I was the goalie who
won the gold medal for the Czech Republic in people's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca also believes that the Olympic impact was more one of
perception than self-discovery. ``I don't think he ever doubted in
his own mind how good he was,'' said Peca. ``I think what the
Olympics did for him was show he could perform against the best
players in the world, that he could beat them. In a lot of people's
eyes, it made him a winner in some sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In an NHL sense, Hasek still has not been the ultimate winner.
Despite another superb season _ a 30-18-4 record, a career-low 1.87
goals-against average, 9 shutouts (one behind league leader Dafoe),
and, for the sixth straight year, the league's highest save
percentage (.937) _ and his virtuoso first-round effort against
Ottawa, Hasek Wednesday faced questions about what his resume
lacks.
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded that for all his brilliance last season, popular
opinion was that he had been outdueled by Washington's Olaf Kolzig
in Buffalo's six-game Stanley Cup semifinal loss. ``It upsets me
any time I lose,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter who the other
goalie is.''
</P>
<P>
   He was advised that his next obstacle is Kolzig's best friend,
Dafoe. ``This is not a duel between the goalies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for all his inscrutability and quirks and
standoffishness, Hasek's self-demands may be helping his teammates
prepare for Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at practice as an opportunity to find ways to score
against the best goalie in the world,'' said Peca. ``If I can do
that, I figure I can score against the others.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Hasek. But don't dare do it against him,
whether you're ally or enemy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
