<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5550 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MOUNTAIN-CLIMBS-3     05-05 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MOUNTAIN-CLIMBS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, FIXING SLUGLINE)  
 MOUNTAIN CLIMBING AS A SPECTATOR SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Peter Dizikes is a freelance writer and recreational climber who
lives in New York.  
 By PETER DIZIKES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Armchair mountaineering is a time-honored tradition among those
seeking vicarious thrills from the comfort of their own homes. In
the last few years, however, it has been supplemented by a new
occupation: desktop mountaineering, the practice of following a
climbing expedition on the Web as its members try to reach the
summit of one of the world's greatest peaks. And May is the
beginning of peak climbing season.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Everest, for instance, has seen a huge increase in foot
traffic in the 1990s. But record numbers of people have also paid a
virtual visit to Everest, the world's highest mountain, in the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 expeditions (and at least 150 climbers) are trying
Everest this year, and more than a dozen have their own Web sites,
with journal-style dispatches, photos, route maps, audio and video
clips, and thumbnail Everest histories. Far from being a remote
adventure, high-altitude mountaineering is now a spectator sport.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way, of course. Sir Edmund Hillary, of New
Zealand, and Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa guide, were the first
climbers to reach Everest's summit, on May 29, 1953. The news of
the feat, by a British expedition, reached the public on June 2
(the day of Queen Elizabeth's inauguration, by happy coincidence) _
and the news moved that fast only because The London Times had sent
a correspondent, James Morris, to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed: James Morris now writes as Jan Morris, and
when Everest is climbed today, the public knows about it before the
climbers are off the mountain. Climbers radio from the top down to
base camp, where team members call home on satellite phones. Then
expedition Web sites quickly post updates that read like breaking
news, even if there is a little lag time.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Web, desktop mountaineers now get a taste of the
unfolding anxiety and uncertainty faced by real mountaineers. Take
Carolyn Hahn, a writer living in New York, who, along with other
family members, uses the Web to follow the feats of her brother
Dave, a professional climber who has reached the Everest summit and
sent witty Web dispatches back from the mountain in each of the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only know what's on the Web,'' she said. ``When two climbers
died on his route last year, we got an e-mail saying he was OK But
otherwise, I just read the same updates as everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web would be well suited to accounts of climbing feats even
without this immediacy. Good sites include abundant photographs
(most can be enlarged with a click) and other visual effects,
combining them with text in creative ways to give readers more of
that elusive you-are-there feeling than can be had while curled up
in an armchair with a book or magazine. With so many sites, though,
it may not be clear where to begin. Here are a few ways to make the
mountains come to you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Into Thin Air,'' a book by Jon Krakauer about the
1996 climbing disaster on Mount Everest, spent a long time atop the
best-seller list, and the Imax film ``Everest'' enjoyed a long run
in theaters. If you want to find out more about the disaster, in
which five people died, here are a few Web sites related to it and
to other climbs in 1996:(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A LOOK BACK AT EVEREST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.outsidemag.com:80/places/features/everest.html Updates from
Scott Fischer's expedition, Jon Krakauer's original magazine
article and more, from Outside Online. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE EVEREST ASSAULT STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   peacock.nbc.com/everest/main.html(NU)home Sandy Hill Pittman was
criticized for her role in the 1996 disaster, but her site is well
done. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST SUMMIT JOURNAL COMPENDIUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   members.xoom.com/Everest96/links.htm A thorough listing of
articles and interviews related to the 1996 climbing year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RISK ONLINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.risk.ru This English version of a Russian site contains the
best single-expedition Web site I've ever seen, in the
Mountaineering section under the heading Togliatti K2 1996. It is
the story of a Russian team that climbed K2 (the world's
second-highest mountain) in the summer of 1996, told from the
perspectives of two climbers. Lavishly illustrated with stunning
photos and video. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE MOUNTAIN ZONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.mountainzone.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A commercial site with plenty of high-end gadgetry at its
disposal, the Mountain Zone, based in Seattle, has done more than
any other site to move climbing into the virtual world. For
climbing fans, a significant part of the site's attraction is that
it follows the stars of American mountaineering, who are paid to
send in reports as correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain Zone is currently providing updates from three
Himalayan expeditions. One team is attempting the unprecedented
triple play of climbing the south side of Everest, then its two
adjoining neighbors, Lhotse (the world's fourth-highest peak) and
Nuptse.
</P>
<P>
   Another group is on the north side of Everest, searching for
evidence of the expedition of George Mallory and Andrew Irvine,
Everest pioneers who did not return from their 1924 climb. On
Sunday, these climbers announced that they had found Mallory's body
and would continue to search for more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Ed Viesturs, who is America's best-known climber
and is prominently featured in ``Everest,'' an Imax film, is
closing in on a highly coveted mountaineering prize: scaling all 14
of the world's peaks measuring 8,000 meters (more than 26,000 feet)
or more. With his climb of Dhaulagiri on Tuesday, Viesturs' tally
is at 12.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatches sent back to Seattle by climbers on all three
teams make up the heart of the coverage. These are either progress
reports or, on rest days, a chance for climbers to reflect on their
calling. Pete Athans, the south-side team leader, recently invoked
T.S. Eliot's poetry to describe his awe of Everest _ ``the object
of all our exploring is to arrive at the beginning and know the
place for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many dispatches are transcripts of satellite phone or radio
calls from base camp and above. I listen to these using the Windows
Media Player, although Real Playeralso works. Most have been casual
briefings from lower elevations on Everest, but when Viesturs
climbed Dhaulagiri Tuesday, he radioed down an hour later, in a
voice strained with fatigue. The recent dispatches about Mallory's
body are also available as audio clips.
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular parts of the Mountain Zone's Everest
coverage are its video clips and 360-degree photos. The former
(which require Real Player) include an airplane fly-by of Everest.
Even better are the photos posted by the south-siders. The images
automatically pan like video clips when loaded, but they can be
controlled by mouse, and it is possible to zoom in (although much
sharpness is lost).
</P>
<P>
   The 360-degree photo from Camp 1, with Everest, Lhotse and
Nuptse looming overhead, is by itself worth a trip to the site. My
favorite shows the Thyangboche monastery on the trek in: animals
graze serenely with Everest visible in the distance. To find the
images, go to the south-side dispatches, then click on the Features
and Multimedia links.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain Zone is, however, unabashedly commercial.
Advertisements line the site, and an Everest Store sells all manner
of memorabilia. So far I have resisted buying replica Sherpa prayer
flags for $29.95; my visits feel authentic enough already. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST NEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.everestnews.com  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a homespun feel and few visual offerings, Everest News is
the antithesis of the Mountain Zone. Nonetheless, it has also
become a virtual base camp for desktop mountaineers. The site
provides two attractive services: news updates from Everest and
other major peaks, posted a few times a day during the spring and
summer, and links to the Web sites of nearly every major
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Using an impressive network of climbers, Sherpas and base camp
managers as sources, the site aims for comprehensive coverage of
developments on Everest, including summit attempts, controversies
and, inevitably, deaths.
</P>
<P>
   It is unique among mountaineering sites in making an effort to
keep track of the Sherpas, who are among the strongest climbers
around. And in contrast with the Mountain Zone, the site emphasizes
climbers from outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   News items are gathered from contributors around the globe _
most of whom communicate with one another only through e-mail _ and
translated into English when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Partly for this reason, Everest News is in need of a more
consistent editorial tone, and the navigation is unwieldy. Getting
access to the site's other features _ a news archive, climber
interviews, book listings _ can be tedious. Still, if looking at
the Mountain Zone is akin to watching sports highlights on
television, reading Everest News is like a leisurely stroll through
the baseball box scores: it's a more complete way to keep track of
the game and sometimes more satisfying, as well. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOVA ONLINE: LOST ON EVEREST _ THE SEARCH FOR MALLORY AND
IRVINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/everest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay stood on top of
Mount Everest, the summit was reached by two other climbers: George
Mallory and Andrew Irvine. That, at least, is what some
mountaineering romantics claim. Mallory _ he's the one who said he
wanted to climb Everest ``because it is there'' _ and his partner
were last seen 1,000 feet from the top while making their 1924
summit bid.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Seventy-five years later, an American team _ the same
north-side team sending reports to the Mountain Zone _ is trying to
figure out what became of the climbers, and they are filming a
``Nova'' documentary in the process. On Sunday, they reported the
discovery of Mallory's body, and they are promising further
evidence of whether or not he reached the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the news of this discovery, the accompanying PBS
Web site is an excellent introduction to Everest. The team plans to
send a Quick Time movie back from each camp on the route. For those
unfamiliar with the topography of Everest, the Climb section
provides a good virtual tour of the mountain from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
