<HEADER>
A5559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-GUNS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS ACCUSE RENO OF NOT ENFORCING FEDERAL GUN LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the wake of the Littleton, Colo., high school
massacre, several Republican senators on Wednesday accused Attorney
General Janet Reno of failing to fully enforce federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal gun laws are not worth much unless the Justice
Department enforces them,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee, told Reno during an hearing on the
department's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that irritates us, to be honest, is that there are
all these calls for new gun laws by the president but very little
enforcement of the laws we have,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Another committee member, Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., called the
administration's prosecution record on gun laws a ``failure.''
Joining Hatch and Sessions in their criticism were Republican Sens.
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   According to Justice Department statistics, more than 6,000
students illegally brought guns to school last year, but only eight
were prosecuted under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, federal prosecutions of defendants who used a
firearm during a felony dropped nearly 47 percent, from 7,048 to
3,765, between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno defended her record, saying the bulk of the 6,000
students were prosecuted under state and local law, rather than
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do things based on numbers but on who can do the job
best,'' she told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a former district attorney for Dade County, Fla., said she
prefers to let state and local authorities handle cases unless they
ask for federal help. ``When I was (a prosecutor) down in Miami, I
often felt that the best way the federal attorneys could help was
in staying out of the way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said later that while federal
prosecutions of gun law violations dropped by about 27 percent from
1992 to 1997 _ from around 5,500 to 4,000 _ combined state and
federal prosecutions of those crimes jumped 33 percent in the same
period _ from about 30,000 to 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they said, the number of those convicted who went
to prison for state and federal weapons offenses rose nearly 21
percent between 1992 and 1997, from 20,681 to 25,186.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also refused to back a juvenile crime bill sponsored by
Hatch and Sessions. The bill would provide nearly $1 billion in
federal grants for youth detention centers, drug testing of minors
and improved record keeping of juvenile crime. The bill also would
make it illegal for a person who committed a violent felony as a
juvenile to ever own a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she supports parts of the bill but would like it to
focus more on the prevention of crime through after-school programs
and mentoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs a lot less to prevent a crime in the first place than
it does to lock somebody up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions agreed that preventive programs are needed to help
fight crime. But he said initiatives such as after-school programs
should be included in education bills, not crime legislation. ``We
can't put everything into a crime bill,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0506-C     05-05 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM RAMSTEIN: WAITING AND READY TO 'GET THE JOB DONE'
 &HT;    With Photo Mug.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany _ At a simple pine table in a cavernous army
barracks, the card game is spades and the mood is sheer boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Four camo-clad American soldiers deal a new hand. On the couches
nearby, others watch a movie on a wide-screen TV. Some stretch out,
trying to catch a nap on several of the 600 olive-green cots spread
across the vast room. Another crouches near his field pack,
applying some jet-black polish to the tips of his combat boots.
</P>
<P>
   They are support troops, firefighters, engineers and military
police. They have been waiting days now for their transport plane
to be loaded with cargo and whisk them to Tirana, Albania, a place
few of them had heard of a few years, or even months, ago.
</P>
<P>
   If war is hell, these servicemen are certain that this obscure
corner of America's massive military complex in southwestern
Germany is purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   There was no presidential appearance at this altogether
unphotogenic place, a waystation for American troops headed to the
Balkans with all the charm of a bus terminal.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton came to Germany on Wednesday to visit two U.S.
bases, boost troop morale and maintain public support for the war
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As he met at Ramstein Air Base with combat pilots and with the
three POWs released Sunday from Yugoslavia, the two dozen soldiers
here awaited their turn to join the growing NATO combat forces in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   They were preceded by some 4,200 American soldiers who before
flying to Albania spent a few hours or days at the Army's
warehouse-like deployment center at Kaiserslautern, a mammoth
complex of storage facilities, barracks and support facilities
adjacent to Ramstein Air Base.
</P>
<P>
   The young servicemen were oblivious to Clinton's attendance at
the airfield just a mile or so away. Some of them hadn't seen a
newspaper or TV since they left their base in the United States
last week and didn't even know the commander-in-chief was in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But speeches aren't necessary here among the twenty-somethings
with M-16s; a sense of mission is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready. We want to go. We want to do our job. We've been
waiting and it's like, when do we get our chance?'' said Army Spec.
Brandon Couch, 22, of Anderson, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The best morale-boost possible, they said, would be to achieve
the goal of curbing the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and allowing innocent refugees to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Air war alone? A ground invasion? Leave it to Clinton and the
commanders to worry over how, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any philosophizing here, it is: Let's get in there
and get the job done so we can get home,'' said Capt. Terry Jarvis,
an army chaplain from Atmore, Ala., who counsels the soldiers
passing through the deployment center.
</P>
<P>
   The foursome playing cards are firefighters who will spend their
little piece of the war protecting the Apache attack helicopters
and pilots who may need to make emergency landings at the Rinas Air
Field near Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   For all, it is their first duty in a potential combat zone.
Their casual chatter on Wednesday was of the assignment to come,
and the much-discussed ground war that could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants it to have to happen, but if it does we'll prove
we can do the job.'' said Spec. Brandon LaBonte, 22, of Olympia,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Their sergeant, a veteran of the Persian Gulf War, listened
appreciatively to the bravado of his young subordinates, but
suggested that today's boredom could end all too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of them expect the magnitude of this,'' said
Sgt. Michael Hudgins, 41, a native of Ringgold, Ga. ``I don't think
anybody was ready for how hot this is.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
