<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM RAMSTEIN: WAITING AND READY TO 'GET THE JOB DONE'
 &HT;    With Photo Mug.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany _ At a simple pine table in a cavernous army
barracks, the card game is spades and the mood is sheer boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Four camo-clad American soldiers deal a new hand. On the couches
nearby, others watch a movie on a wide-screen TV. Some stretch out,
trying to catch a nap on several of the 600 olive-green cots spread
across the vast room. Another crouches near his field pack,
applying some jet-black polish to the tips of his combat boots.
</P>
<P>
   They are support troops, firefighters, engineers and military
police. They have been waiting days now for their transport plane
to be loaded with cargo and whisk them to Tirana, Albania, a place
few of them had heard of a few years, or even months, ago.
</P>
<P>
   If war is hell, these servicemen are certain that this obscure
corner of America's massive military complex in southwestern
Germany is purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   There was no presidential appearance at this altogether
