against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As he met at Ramstein Air Base with combat pilots and with the
three POWs released Sunday from Yugoslavia, the two dozen soldiers
here awaited their turn to join the growing NATO combat forces in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   They were preceded by some 4,200 American soldiers who before
flying to Albania spent a few hours or days at the Army's
warehouse-like deployment center at Kaiserslautern, a mammoth
complex of storage facilities, barracks and support facilities
adjacent to Ramstein Air Base.
</P>
<P>
   The young servicemen were oblivious to Clinton's attendance at
the airfield just a mile or so away. Some of them hadn't seen a
newspaper or TV since they left their base in the United States
last week and didn't even know the commander-in-chief was in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But speeches aren't necessary here among the twenty-somethings
with M-16s; a sense of mission is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready. We want to go. We want to do our job. We've been
waiting and it's like, when do we get our chance?'' said Army Spec.
Brandon Couch, 22, of Anderson, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The best morale-boost possible, they said, would be to achieve
the goal of curbing the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and allowing innocent refugees to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Air war alone? A ground invasion? Leave it to Clinton and the
commanders to worry over how, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any philosophizing here, it is: Let's get in there
and get the job done so we can get home,'' said Capt. Terry Jarvis,
an army chaplain from Atmore, Ala., who counsels the soldiers
passing through the deployment center.
</P>
<P>
   The foursome playing cards are firefighters who will spend their
little piece of the war protecting the Apache attack helicopters
and pilots who may need to make emergency landings at the Rinas Air
Field near Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   For all, it is their first duty in a potential combat zone.
Their casual chatter on Wednesday was of the assignment to come,
and the much-discussed ground war that could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants it to have to happen, but if it does we'll prove
we can do the job.'' said Spec. Brandon LaBonte, 22, of Olympia,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Their sergeant, a veteran of the Persian Gulf War, listened
