<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV11-     05-05 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING AWAY FROM VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, May 11)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other night I got home in time for the last scene in ``Scent
of a Woman,'' where Al Pacino teaches a roomful of rich snots how
to be a hero, and I sat right down and cried. I've seen that movie
three times and it always gets to me, which I'm sure was Pacino's
intention as well as the filmmaker`s.
</P>
<P>
   Good films are supposed to do that. Same with great books,
paintings, certain songs, lines of poetry, TV specials, opera
arias, even newspaper stories. Anything with words and/or pictures
has the potential to play with your mind. Create incredible
longing, trigger a memory, make you laugh. Images can move you to
action, make you miss your father, inspire you to move to Maine and
to switch bathroom cleansers.
</P>
<P>
   We recognize the power of the media, by which I mean any high
and low art form of communication. As consumers we're easily
stimulated, motivated and, sure, often manipulated by what we see
and hear.
</P>
<P>
   So don't try to tell us it's different when it comes to brutal
and violent images.
</P>
<P>
   We may be suggestible but we're not stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of Hollywood carnage and makers of video games that
invite you to stalk and kill, blow up Chicago if you want, claim no
responsibility for what could have been in the heads of the
suspects in school massacres like the one in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Typical cowards, every time there's a horribly vicious crime and
talk turns to motivation, the blood and gore media run and hide
under a rock.
</P>
<P>
   We can't be responsible, they say, for who watches us.
</P>
<P>
   Come on. They have marketing experts and focus groups like
everyone else. They know exactly who's watching and they're a lot
of impressionable young kids mesmerized by killing games.
</P>
<P>
   You don't find personal training in how to be mean and nasty on
the side of cereal boxes. But there's at least a murder a night on
television. Leonardo DiCaprio, America's heartthrob, is in a movie
wearing a trench coat and shooting up a school. And video games
come complete with convincing screams and moans to make the
player's ``victims'' seem more real.
</P>
<P>
   And we, who say we are horrified, let it happen, acting almost
as detached as the media. A blood bath occurs and someone opines on
our ``culture of violence,'' and we agree as if there's nothing we
can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we have to be a culture of violence? It's our culture. We
can change it.
</P>
<P>
   If we wanted to we could become a culture of beauty. Or a
culture of wonder and reverence.
</P>
<P>
   We've got kids staring at video games with the same kind of
images they show U.S. Marines to get them desensitized to killing.
</P>
<P>
   Why are we desensitizing kids?
</P>
<P>
   One morning I drove by two little boys who were bent over,
peering into the grass. I suspect it was a caterpillar or a garter
snake. Kids are so easily fascinated with things that adults grow
up and get bored with. I thought about the first time I saw a
speeded-up photographic image of a caterpillar coming out of a
cocoon and turning into a butterfly. It was more convincing than
science class and it was on television.
</P>
<P>
   With all its talent and technology the media can contribute
intelligence, understanding and grace. The media taught us about
AIDS and compassion for people with the disease. Moviemaker Steven
Spielberg showed us the ludicrous waste of war. Poets point out our
daily miracles.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to put up with a culture of violence. We can
boycott slasher movies, turn the TV to the nature channel and start
monitoring computer games. We in the newspaper industry will have
to rethink front page violence. None of this will wreck anyone's
business. The media adapt almost instantly to popular taste.
</P>
<P>
   The media have to take responsibility for creating nightmares
along with dreams. Otherwise, another monster is set to pounce in
the form of censorship ``for the public good'' and that would be as
deadening a trend as school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
