<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CDSPINS-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      05-05 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF THE NEWEST MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 SPINS-MUSIC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Luxury'' &QL; 
Fantastic Plastic Machine &QL; 
(Emperor Norton) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of the vibe Fantastic Plastic Machine sets forth
on Luxury, just scan the song titles: ``Mr. Fantasy's Love,''
``Satellite Beats,'' ``He Became a Beatnik,'' `` Bossa for
Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the sound of yesterday's tomorrows, as enjoyably chichi as
the very 1970 orange and purple op art on the disc's cover.
</P>
<P>
   Along with such artists as Cornelius, Buffalo Daughter and
Pizzicato Five, Fantastic Plastic Machine (a k a Tokyo deejay
Tomoyuki Tanaka) is part of the Japanese club pop scene known as
Shibuya-ku. This party-ready sound combines elements of '60s easy
listening, '70s funk and soul, and '90s techno into a heady,
kitsch-filled blend.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Shibuya-ku is not recommended for those who
like their music tastefully subtle _ if anything, it's a genre that
is hyper-aware of its own in-your-face cuteness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tanaka has the talent to make ``Luxury'' light and
appealing, whether he's wigging out on the sexy robot fantasy
``Electric Lady Land'' (no relation to Jimi Hendrix) or retooling
the Eurythmics' ``There Must Be an Angel (Playing With My Heart)''
into a lush, nine-minute suite that's more Brazil '66 than London
'85.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers would dig it, baby. &QL; 
_ Matt Hinrichs &QL; 
 &QL; 
COUNTRY &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Ashes of Old Love'' &QL; 
Stacy Dean Campbell &QL; 
(Paladin Records) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The characters that populate the songs on Stacy Dean Campbell's
third album are desperate and haunted, full of insecurities and
fears that seem to literally jump out from the stereo speakers. The
vivid imagery and American gothic musical backdrop make for a
brooding, evocative piece of work that is quietly brilliant, a
journey through the stark back roads of society.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell recorded two fine-but-overlooked discs for Sony, which
marketed the New Mexico native as a twangy, hunky alternative to
Chris Isaak. After dropping out of the scene for a couple of years,
he resurfaces with a matured writing style and a lonesome, rootsy
sound that's as vast and breathtaking as an Oklahoma landscape.
</P>
<P>
   He has penned much of the material himself, revealing a
novelist's eye for detail. There's the pathetic loser threatened by
his woman's potential suitor in the unsettling ``One False Move.''
In ``Makin' Good Time,'' he's a weary road traveler, heading for an
unknown destination accompanied by his lady and a ``dashboard Jesus
chaperone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashes of Old Love'' has the richness and potency of a Lyle
Lovett disc, but without the biting irony. Campbell is not quite so
cool; instead, he's willing to wear his heart _ and his flaws _ on
his sleeve. And he's blessed with a voice as pure and vulnerable as
a teenage choirboy, which adds an extra layer of pathos and depth
to the proceedings. This is the kind of album that stays with a
listener long after it has left the CD player. &QL; 
- Randy Cordova &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JAZZ &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Duo'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Charlie Hunter &AMP; Leon Parker &QL; 
(Blue Note) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the title sounds a bit too minimalist for your taste, relax.
Charlie Hunter's custom eight-string serves as lead, bass and
rhythm guitar _ and, occasionally, electric organ. Add Leon
Parker's intricate percussion, and ``Duo'' has plenty of sound to
hold a jazz fan's attention.
</P>
<P>
   This is a relaxed set, not as funky-fiery as Hunter's past
efforts or as stylistically adventurous as Parker's ``Above &AMP;
Below.''
</P>
<P>
   Subtlety is the name of the game as Charlie delivers shimmering,
lyrical, sometimes bluesy guitar leads while his latest
collaborator proves that a master drummer needn't indulge in
bombastic displays of technical brilliance to prove his chops.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter takes on most of the composing duties here, from the
hypnotic ``Do That Then'' to the playfully bouncy ``Recess'' to the
up-tempo but still laid-back ``Calypso for Grampa.''
</P>
<P>
   He also continues his tradition of making other songwriters'
tunes his own without exorcising the spirit of the original _
witness his dark, vibrant take on the jazz standard ``You Don't
Know What Love Is'' or his echoing, sweetly sad rendition of the
Beach Boys' ``Don't Talk (Put Your Head on My Shoulder).'' Even
Parker's one contribution, ``Belief,'' still bears Charlie's
melodic stamp while showc asing the drummer's delightfully devious
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   It's all good stuff. Turn it down as a friendly mood-setter for
conversation or turn it up to immerse yourself in a mellow,
mind-pleasing groove. - Kerry S. Lengel &QL; 
 &QL; 
POP &QL; 
``By 7:30'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vonda Shepard &QL; 
(Jacket Records) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who's the most annoying character on the TV show ``Ally
McBeal''? Is it neurotic poster gal Ally? The Biscuit? The
not-very-sexy sexy secretary? How about the wattle guy? Nope, the
worst of the bunch is definitely Vonda Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Her musical patter is designed to help the viewer connect with
the show's emotional zing. If Ally is in a daze about some love
dilemma (gee, that just about describes every single episode), then
Shepard is trotted out to careen through a verse and a chorus of
some moldy hit. Too bad the singer makes every song sound the same.
She's a vocalist completely void of nuance and insight.
</P>
<P>
   And things don't improve on her latest album. ``By 7:30'' is a
collection of morose and charmless songs. Instead of butchering
Motown hits like she does on TV, Shepard's got her very own songs
to destroy. She dabbles in introspective ennui but doesn't have the
subtlety to carry it off. ``My words are like confetti,'' she sings
at one point. If only this were true. Most of her lyrics are as
broad and heavy-handed as her singing.
</P>
<P>
   The album isn't totally a bust, however. Two songs miraculously
survive the Shepard treatment. ``Baby, Don't You Break My Heart
Slow'' is saved by a guest appearance by the Indigo Girls' Emily
Saliers. And the best song,`` Newspaper Wife,'' sounds like the
music was transfered to disc completely backward. It may sound
kooky, but it works.
</P>
<P>
   Other than these two flukes, Vonda Shepard is as grating on CD
as she is on TV. And ``By 7:30'' is an album that never should have
made it onto prime time. &QL; 
- Eric Searleman &QL; 
BLUES &QL; 
``Houndog'' &QL; 
Houndog &QL; 
Columbia/Legacy) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sticker on the front calls ``Houndog'' ``a bluesy, trippy
amalgamation of riffs, rites and spirits.'' If the spirits are of
the alcoholic sort and the rites related to self-sacrifice, I'll
buy that line.
</P>
<P>
   Houndog is the duo of blues singer Mike Halby (John Mayall's
Bluesbreakers, Canned Heat) and Los Lobos multi-instrumentalist
David Hidalgo. The music isn't just ``bluesy'' _ it's a tour de
force of roots-blues revivalism. Trippy? Perhaps. Recorded in
Halby's home studio with Hidalgo as producer, the album has the
same spare quality and gritty lo-fi haze you hear from the Latin
Playboys (a Los Lobos side project), and Halby's voice is so low
and slow that you sometimes wonder if the entire recording has been
slowed down a notch or two. But trippy or not, the allure of
``Houndog'' is its good old-fashioned blues riffs, Hidalgo's smoky
guitar work and Halby's tragicomically houndlike vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, he's got the blues. ``I'll be the dog / That digs your
grave / . . .Romance me down, down, down / I'll die your slave,''
he sings on the opening track, ``No Chance.'' (According to a press
release, Bonnie Raitt's reaction to the disc was, ``This is great!
But is he gonna be all right?'') Yet it would be a mistake to
dismiss this album as parody. ``Somebody (Stop the Bleedin')'' has
concerns of greater import than just another broken heart, while
the dark but lilting music of ``I Brought the Rain'' brings the
melancholy lyrics to life, giving them emotional depth and reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houndog'' may never be a blockbuster, but it certainly is a
heartbreaker. &QL; 
- Kerry S. Lengel &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COUNTRY  &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Shane Minor'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shane Minor &QL; 
(Mercury/PolyGram) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shane Minor would be an interesting guy to sit around and shoot
the bull with. He worked as a uniformed police officer in the Watts
area of Los Angeles and even did stints as a rodeo bull rider.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who obviously has some rich life experiences to draw
from, he instead goes for the lowest common denominator on his
self-titled debut album, an unappetizing slab of commercial country
music at its most empty-headed.
</P>
<P>
   The up-tempo songs are nonsensical, butt-wiggling fare, the kind
of thing that Billy Ray Cyrus outgrew years ago. Minor doesn't have
better luck with the ballads, either. They are treacly moaners full
of greeting-card sentimentality. ``How Many Times'' is even written
by shlockmeister supreme Michael Bolton, not exactly a top
Nashville tunesmith.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing about the whole affair is Minor actually has an
agreeable singing voice. You get the feeling there's a real person
trying to get out from under all the leering whoops and hollers.
He's probably got a lot of great stories in him; instead, all we
can tell from this disc is that he's a vocal cipher who has a thing
for leather pants. _Randy Cordova &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      05-05 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: THIN SKINS AND THICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is improbable fantasy to suppose that authors and publishers
wouldn't do nearly anything to sell their books, so it's hardly
surprising that Frank McCourt took the opportunity to do a
television commercial for Barnes &AMP; Noble's online bookselling
operation and plug not only the chain but his best-selling
``Angela's Ashes'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   But to independent booksellers, it was as if the writer were
feeding bananas to an orangutan or trying to buy off the
neighborhood bully with candy. And although they certainly didn't
intend it, by the time the American Booksellers Association, their
trade organization, ended its convention in Tarrytown, N.Y., on
Sunday, most of the publicity it had generated was over its
melancholy fight with McCourt. Some of the independents felt he
betrayed them by making the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, making no apology, said: ``They should be dealing
with literacy, devoting themselves to nurturing future readers.
What good does it do to hound me? I'm not in the mood for my
crucifixion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCourt added that he was finished with the matter. Anyway, he
would have done a television commercial for the independent stores
had they suggested it, he said, explaining that he did the
commercial only because his publisher, Scribner, wanted him to.
``Last year I gave a reading at a bookstore in Tarrytown and
apparently insulted Barnes &AMP; Noble, and my publisher asked me to
write a letter of apology to the head,'' chief executive officer
Leonard Riggio, ``and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   McCourt said: ``I'm for the little guy. I buy at the local deli
and grocery store. I'm for the booksellers. I'm walking down
Broadway and they're selling David Halberstam's book for $10 on a
street stand. But I can't do that in good conscience, so I went
into a bookstore and bought it.'' The list price of ``Playing for
Keeps'' (Random House) is $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   McCourt was one of four writers to do the barnesandnoble.com (or
www.bn.com) commercial. The others were Stephen King, Tom Clancy
and Scott Adams, the cartoonist who created Dilbert. But only
McCourt caused a flap, because in 1997 he won the independents'
Abby Award, as the author they most liked to sell in their stores,
and at the time of the award he gave a great deal of credit to the
independents for the book's success. Resolutions to censure McCourt
failed by large margins at the convention, which the author
attended.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, McCourt sits at a desk trying to write his next book
while talking about ``Angela's Ashes,'' his memoir of growing up in
poverty, mostly in Limerick, Ireland. The book has already sold
more than 2 million copies in hardcover, a figure so large it meant
that the book sold well in every outlet, independent and chain,
although it did get its blastoff largely from word of mouth in the
independents. The paperback will be in the stores at the end of the
month, and the movie in theaters later in the year. The sequel,
``Tis,'' is scheduled for publication in September. The writer is
working on a novel about teaching and marriage, what he calls ``a
cross between `Goodbye, Chips' and `Who's Afraid of Virginia
Woolf?'''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath this wearisome book publishing melee lie some serious
concerns. Independent booksellers, with some justification,
consider themselves under siege by Barnes &AMP; Noble, Borders, the
Internet and Wal-Mart. In 1991 the association had 5,200 members
and now has 3,300, according to the association president, Richard
Howorth, who owns Square Books, a store in Oxford, Miss. ``This
year is the first time since 1991 that there was an increase in the
number of independent book stores, a slight one,'' he said, ``but
at least the decline stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, Andrew Ross, owner of Cody's Bookstore in
Berkeley, Calif., offered a resolution demanding that McCourt
return his Abby. ``It lost badly because booksellers are polite and
respectful of authors,'' Ross said. ``But I thought it was
provocative and it put out our thoughts and our principles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that many authors are ignoring the fact that
bookselling is becoming dominated by a few corporations which are
putting out the idea that our culture is homogeneous,'' he said.
``We were trying to make the point to Frank McCourt that we need
diversity, multiplicity, and that it was reasonable to help enforce
our independence and not be a pitch man for the chains.''
</P>
<P>
   Given McCourt's background, it would seem inappropriate to
lecture him on cultural diversity. And in fact, the association is
trying out more pertinent responses to its members being gobbled up
by chains. Many independents are sponsoring author breakfasts and
other events that bring authors and readers together. When an
author does a bookselling appearance at a store, it is supported by
cash from the publisher, and the bigger the store, the more money
it gets.
</P>
<P>
   The association is also starting what it calls its Book Sense
marketing program, and so far 900 members have signed contracts to
be part of it. The program will have its own bookselling Web site
to compete with Barnes &AMP; Noble's and Amazon. It will have a Book
Sense logo on all its member advertisements and promotional
material and its own slogan, ``Independent Bookstores for
Independent Minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Its first advertisement has been published in The New York Times
and elsewhere and is to be repeated. In the association's desire to
project the independent bookstore as the epitome of neighborliness
as well as a gathering place for unconstrained minds, the ad uses
an extraordinary metaphor, the pizzeria. It features the cover of a
take-home pizza box imprinted with the words: ``Original. Variety
of Taste. Just like your family-run pizzeria. Your Independent
Bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   One would think the association might be better off taking up
McCourt's offer to do a commercial for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
