<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOWN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-05 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOME TOWN': NO FRANK CAPRA HERE, OR JONATHAN EDWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first you think that Tracy Kidder's new book, ``Home Town,''
is going to present an idyllic profile of Northampton, Mass., one
consistent with the author's opening view of it from nearby Mount
Holyoke: ``From the summit, the cornfields are a dream of perfect
order, and the town seems entirely coherent, self-contained, a
place where a person might live a whole life and consider it
complete, a tiny civilization all its own. Forget the messiness of
years and days _ every work of human artifice has a proper viewing
distance. The town below fits in the palm of your hand. Shake it
and it snows.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moving closer, Kidder's focus tightens on the life of Tommy
O'Connor, whose happy childhood as a Northampton townie suggests
Frank Capra's film ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' without the hero's
frustration and sense of being stuck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tommy has grown up to fulfill his childhood dream of becoming a
policeman. (On the wall inside the closet of the room he grew up in
is written in crayon ``Tom O'Connor September 29, 1972 / I want to
be a policeman / I am in sixth grade.'') The town he works in is
not just the site of prestigious Smith College but also a
successful experiment in urban restoration whose heart is a mix of
Woodstock Nation and Main Street, where some 40 restaurants thrive
and kids feel free to display their hair dyed the more unlikely
colors of the rainbow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as Tommy drives his rounds you begin to sense an atmosphere
less like a Capra film and more like something by Stephen King.
Tommy knows that in the festive downtown crowds are dealers pushing
crack cocaine. Crises in which he frequently has to intervene
involve drunken or addicted former high school mates.
</P>
<P>
   Within three chapters, Tommy is approached by a somber Rick
Janacek, not only a fellow cop but also Tommy's childhood neighbor
and best friend. Rick confides that as well as having a severe
problem with alcohol he has been barred by his wife from contacting
her or their children. The restraining order has accused Rick of
sexually abusing one of his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way anything could have happened with me is if I was
in a blackout,'' Rick says, an admission that Tommy knows from
experience is usually a sign of guilt. Having heard Rick confess as
much, Tommy feels he will have to report the conversation to the
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Janacek is the first of four major close-ups of Northampton
citizens that Kidder presents against the background of the town's
daily life and history. The others are an odd assortment. There is
Alan Scheinman, an erstwhile real estate entrepreneur who suffers
so severely from obsessive-compulsive disorder that he has to keep
his hands wrapped in plastic and can't remove the garbage from his
apartment. There is Francisco (Frankie) Sandoval, alias Samson
Rodriguez, a crack cocaine addict and dealer who works as a snitch
for Tommy. Finally there is Laura Baumeister, a mother on welfare
who has won a scholarship to Smith but doubts that she can handle
the class work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Tommy turns out not to be so pleased with his life.
Although he loves his hometown and has won promotions and prizes
for his superlative police work, he is frustrated by the lack of a
child in his happy marriage and feels too often that his career has
come to ``a dead halt.'' What is Kidder trying to do with this
gallery of misfits? For the reader their histories are a mixed
experience. Sandoval's is edifying, telling you a lot about life in
the underclass. Baumeister's is inspiring; she masters her class
work and ends up in love with ``Paradise Lost.'' Scheinman's is
fascinating at first but gets to be a bit of a bore; he more or
less cures himself of his obsessive-compulsiveness but he spews a
fair amount of psychobabble in describing the process. As for
Tommy, although he is no misfit, his solution to his discontents is
cheering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what is Kidder's point in offering such a lopsided profile
of Northampton?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it is to illustrate how the tolerance and
cohesiveness of his town embraces all extremes. After all, he
reminds you in one excursion into the past, this is the town that
eventually threw out Jonathan Edwards, author of the sermon
``Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God'' and arbiter of
Northampton's morals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating the place's diversity, Kidder writes: ``The town has
American Legion baseball and contra dancing, a small Buddhist
church and a very active Elks club, homes that cost $400,000 and
many boardinghouses and halfway houses. Somehow it works.
Northampton is the kind of place where a professor, a potter,
unemployed musician, former mental patient, a woman with a handsome
alimony, can all be found on Sunday mornings sitting near one
another at sidewalk tables outside the coffee shops. Somehow _ is
it the sum of unconcerted efforts? _ a cohesive property seems to
bind the place, as if it were a liquid held by surface tension.''
In an interview describing his experience in getting to know
Northampton, Kidder has said: ``The picture that I'd held in my
mind began not to fall apart, but to fragment, the way a
pointillist painting turns into a bunch of small dots if you move
too close to it _ except that the dots in this case were in
themselves interesting, and sometimes appalling.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What his book succeeds in doing is bring the dots together
again. The picture they form is far from pretty, but it certainly
coheres. Shake it and it weeps.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOME TOWN'
</P>
<P>
   By Tracy Kidder
</P>
<P>
   349 pages. Random House. $25.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHEESES06-COX     05-05 2547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHEESES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expand your culinary borders with variety of Mexican cheeses
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The enchiladas at your favorite Tex-Mex spot are
blanketed in melted yellow cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The refried black beans at an interior Mexican restaurant are
sprinkled with crumbled white cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The two dishes are a border apart.
</P>
<P>
   Tex-Mex cooks tend to use a heavy hand with vivid Velveetas and
Cheddars. With a few regional exceptions, South-of-the-Border cooks
opt for a lighter touch, and the quesos, or cheeses, tend to be
white with flowing descriptive names:
</P>
<P>
   Queso fresco _ fresh cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Queso anejo _ aged cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Queso asadero _ roasted cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Flavorful and rich, these quesos are crumbled on top of beans
and appetizers; stuffed into tortillas, enchiladas, quesadillas;
melted with chiles for scooping.
</P>
<P>
   Cheeses are so integral to Mexican cooking that it is hard to
believe that they are not native to the New World, says Patricia
Quintana, author of ``The Taste of Mexico.'' But Mexicans learned
the art of cheesemaking from the Spaniards when the Europeans
introduced cattle in the early 16th century, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now more North Americans are discovering these quesos. As
Mexican food has caught on nationwide and as the Hispanic
population has moved northward, so has the interest in the quesos
of Mexico. Cacique, a popular brand of Mexican-style cheeses from
California, says sales have increased more than 20 percent
nationwide in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more to life than Monterey Jack,'' says longtime
Austin chef Miguel Ravago. Mexican quesos, with their increased
availability, are fun to explore, he adds. ``They have unique
flavors. They taste wonderful with corn tortillas. And crumbled
queso over tacos with two sauces is much better than with feta or
other cheese. ``
</P>
<P>
   Mexican cheeses are loosely categorized into three types: fresh,
aged and melting.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh quesos tend to be soft, crumbly and white, ideal for
sprinkling on tops of appetizers, beans, salads and other dishes.
Queso fresco or queso blanco is the generic label for these
cheeses, which are similar to mild feta or fresh goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The aged cheeses are harder, drier and saltier. Suitable for
grating, they might be compared to Parmesan cheese or pecorino
Romano.
</P>
<P>
   For stuffing peppers, enchiladas or quesadillas, Mexican cooks
opt for cheeses that melt easily: queso Chihuahua, queso asadero
and queso Oaxaca. The latter is known as Mexican string cheese, and
whether it is sold in a rope, balls of various sizes, or round
slices, the strands are visible.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's most famous melting cheese is Chihuahua, says Rick
Bayless, Chicago chef and author of ``Rick Bayless' Mexican
Kitchen.'' Some people also call it queso menonita because it was
introduced by Mennonites who emigrated to Mexico more than half a
century ago. This cheese is often melted for queso fundido or
enchiladas suizas. Move over, Monterey Jack.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis here is on ``Mexican-style.'' In Mexico, many
cheeses are made from unpasteurized milk. That's a no-no in the
United States, unless the cheeses have been aged 60 days. According
to the Food and Drug Administration, Mexican quesos or any cheeses
made in this country must begin with pasteurized milk if they are
to be sold fresh.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the cheeses are manufactured in a way
similar to the quesos that are so popular in Mexico. The emphasis
here is on ``similar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no standard of identity for the Mexican cheeses. Even
in Mexico, from town to town, similar cheeses have different
names,'' says Paula Lambert, owner and founder of the Mozzarella
Company in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Her 17-year-old company, which has won national awards for its
cheeses, makes Mexican-style queso fresco and queso blanco, as well
as a variety spiced with chiles and epazote. She also manufactures
queso Oaxaca, a string cheese stretched out to a long ribbon, then
wrapped into a half-pound yarnlike ball.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Santibanez, executive chef of Fonda San Miguel and
formerly of Mexico, laments that most Mexican-style cheeses north
of the border are not the same quality or flavor as those south.
The cheeses in Mexico often are not made from pasteurized milk,
which some believe kills the taste while eliminating the bacteria.
They are not chilled there, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our cheeses to get dry. We leave them outside. We
never put them in the refrigerator, `` he says, regretting that
here he can't get his favorite Cotija cheese, a goat cheese, here.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs often make substitutions when they can't find a cheese
like one they have used or eaten in Mexico. Santibanez has been
known to buy an Armenian string cheese here that is similar to a
Oaxacan queso. Bayless says if he can't find queso fresco, he
substitutes a pressed, salted farmer's cheese, fresh goat cheese
(even though it does not crumble as well), feta (soaked in cool
water to leach out some of the salt), or dry cottage cheese (with
salt added).
</P>
<P>
   There are many poor, rubbery copies of Mexican cheese made in
the states, says Diana Kennedy of Michoacan, author of ``The
Cuisines of Mexico.'' To test for quality, this Mexican-food purist
suggests melting the cheese over low heat. If it melts or softens
easily and looks shiny with fat, it is good. If it turns into
rubbery lumps, look for another brand, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Ravago says he definitely thinks you can find much, much
better Mexican cheeses here now. ``You are not going to get exactly
the same thing as Mexico, but close to it,'' says Ravago, co-author
of ``Cocina de la Familia.'' Ravago, whose family is from Mexico,
says the variety here is much better now, too. Twenty-five years
ago, you could buy one Mexican cheese. ``It was a melting cheese
for quesadillas. I think it was asadero or something like that. And
I found it at a specialty store.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the cheeses are everywhere. Everyday use is easy.
</P>
<P>
   So in his home refrigerator now, Ravago has queso blanco for
beans, tostadas and lasagne.
</P>
<P>
   Home cook Maria Fountaine would nod with approval. Queso fresco
is just a good all-purpose cheese, for quesadillas, enchiladas and
tacos, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Viva el queso. Queso Tip: Wrap cheese with fresh plastic
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't know this: Each time you remove cheese from
the refrigerator, tightly rewrap it in a new, fresh piece of
plastic wrap. This will reduce contamination by bacteria and mold.
(This hint is for all cheeses, not just Mexican quesos.) Tightly
wrapped, queso fresco or blanco will keep a month in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Lambert, owner and founder of the Mozzarella Company,
Dallas
</P>
<P>
   A PRIMER ON THE QUESOS
</P>
<P>
   Asadero (ah-sah-DEH-roh): Translates as ``broiler'' or
``roaster.'' This white cheese comes in balls, rounds and braids.
It melts easily when heated and strings nicely. Good in tortilla
soup. Substitute: Monterey Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Chihuahua (chi-WAH-wah): A mild, spongy, pale-yellow cheese
originally made in great wheels in the Mennonite farming
communities in the state of Chihuahua. Because of its high fat
content, it melts easily. Good in enchiladas suizas and
quesadillas. Substitute: Mild Cheddar or Monterey Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Panela (pah-NEH-lah): A semi-soft, smooth, white cheese, with a
woven imprint on the surface of the cheese from the draining
basket. Good as an appetizer, as garnish on cold dishes, or melted.
Substitute: Monterey Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Queso fresco (KEH-so FREH-sko): Translates as ``fresh cheese.''
The most common cheese in Mexico, it is crumbled and used as a
topping for appetizers, for stuffing chiles, for Mexican lasagne,
or sprinkling on beans. Substitute: feta.
</P>
<P>
   Queso blanco (KEH-so BLAHN-ko): A generic term that means
``white cheese.'' Interchangeable with queso fresco.
</P>
<P>
   Anejo (ah-NYAY-ho): Translates as ``old'' or ``aged.'' These
cheeses are harder, drier, saltier and suitable for grating. Good
on appetizers. Substitute: Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Queso enchilado (KEH-so en-chee-LAH-do): A queso anejo which has
been ribbed with powdered red chile. Good for enchiladas.
</P>
<P>
   Queso Oaxaca (KEH-so wah-HAH-cah): The specialty of the state of
Oaxaca. Known as Mexican string cheese, it is sold in a rope, balls
of various sizes, or round slices. A good melting cheese, it can be
used in quesadillas, or chile con queso. Substitute: mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   Queso caution
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. Department of Agriculture advises that soft cheeses _
whether they are Mexican-style quesos, feta, brie, blue cheeses or
others _ have the potential for listeria contamination, which can
cause serious illness to adults or even death to unborn babies.
Those particularly at risk include pregnant women, newborns, the
elderly, and people with compromised immune systems from AIDS,
chemotherapy or other medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Queso Derretido
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 white onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 large tomatoes, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 serrano chiles, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cilantro, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon oregano, dried and crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cheese:
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces Chihuahua or Muenster cheese
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces asadero or Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces Oaxaca or mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   Mix sauce ingredients in a glass bowl and let sit for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease 8 individual clay bowls or
ramekins (about 3/4-cup capacity).
</P>
<P>
   Grate Chihuahua, asadero and Oaxaca cheeses, and mix. Divide
cheese among the bowls. Bake until melted and bubbly. Serve
immediately with the sauce and warm corn or flour tortillas. Makes
8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Taste of Mexico''
</P>
<P>
   Frijoles Refritos
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons bacon grease, lard or oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 white onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups cooked beans with broth, any variety (canned beans
can be used)
</P>
<P>
   Salt if needed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red chile, optional
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces crumbled queso fresco, queso anejo or feta
</P>
<P>
   18 tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Melt the fat or heat the oil in a large, heavy skillet over
medium heat. Add the onion and fry about 5 minutes, until soft and
golden, stirring frequently. Add the garlic and cook several
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Raise the heat under the skillet and add the beans and broth, 1
cup at a time, smashing the beans down with a potato masher or the
back of a big wooden spoon. It should take about 10 minutes for the
beans to reach a smooth but still quite moist texture. Taste and
add salt or chile if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The beans can be served immediately with crumbled or grated
cheese sprinkled on top. The crisp tortilla pieces can be stuck
into the beans, both as a garnish and as a way to scoop them up._
``Cocina de la Familia'' by Marilyn Tausend and Miguel Ravago
</P>
<P>
   Elote con Crema
</P>
<P>
   (Fresh corn with cream, chiles and cheese)
</P>
<P>
   2-quart flameproof dish
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 chiles poblanos, roasted and peeled or 7 canned, peeled green
chilies
</P>
<P>
   About 4 cups corn (1 1/2 pounds frozen corn or kernels from 5
ears)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound Chihuahua cheese, in small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Thick sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter and cook the onion and garlic, without browning,
until they are soft.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chiles into rajas (strips), add them to the pan and cook
them, covered, 8 minutes for poblanos, 5 minutes for canned chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Add the corn, cheese and salt to the chili mixture. Cover
tightly with foil or a lid and let bake for 20 minutes for frozen
corn. If you use fresh corn, cook for 40 minutes, adding the cheese
after the first 20 minutes of cooking time. Serve hot with sour
cream. Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This is a very rich dish, and is very good served as a
separate course with hot tortillas. It is best eaten right after
it's cooked, as the cheese gets tough when reheated. For a change,
the chiles could be left whole, stuffed with corn and cheese, and
cooked in cream.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Cuisines of Mexico'' by Diana Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   Shortcut Quesadilla
</P>
<P>
   _ The simplest quesadilla is made from a fresh store-bought corn
or flour tortilla. A few slices of pickled jalapenos or chiles
strips will spice it up. Toast the tortilla on an open flame until
warmed through, sprinkle on the shredded Mexican Chihuahua cheese
or Monterey Jack, fold over and microwave on high on a plate for 10
to 20 seconds, just to melt cheese. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rick Bayless' Mexican Kitchen''
</P>
<P>
   Easy Queso (dip)
</P>
<P>
   Boil 2 tablespoons cream with 2 tablespoons salsa verde in a
small pot. Add 8 ounces shredded queso Oaxaca and stir until
melted. Add 1 roasted and peeled poblano pepper that has been cut
into strips. Serve with chips or spoon into tortillas to eat. If
desired, the queso can be garnished with diced tomato, fried
tortilla squares, chopped cilantro and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roberto Santibanez, executive chef, Fonda San Miguel
</P>
<P>
   Tacos a la Crema
</P>
<P>
   Tacos:
</P>
<P>
   24 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 large potatoes, peeled, cooked in salted water, drained,
and mashed
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 pounds Oaxaca, mozzarella, or Monterey Jack cheese, sliced
in thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 quart vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Green sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   14 tomatillos, husked
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, halved
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, whole
</P>
<P>
   4 chiles serranos
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 large California avocado
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Red Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   3 tomatoes (1 1/4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, whole
</P>
<P>
   2 chipotle, 4 serrano, or 2 jalapeno chiles
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups queso fresco or feta, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the tacos: Heat tortillas on a comal or griddle. Put
some mashed potato and cheese strips off-center on tortillas, roll,
and secure with a toothpick. (The tacos can be prepared ahead of
time to this point and stored in a plastic bag in the
refrigerator.)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the green sauce: Bring water to a boil in a saucepan.
Add tomatillos, 1/2 onion, 3 garlic cloves and chiles. Boil for 30
minutes. Remove from heat and cool. Drain and reserve cooking
water. Blend cooked ingredients with 1/2 onion, 2 garlic cloves,
cilantro and avocado in a blender or food processor. Salt. If sauce
becomes too thick, add a little cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the red sauce: Bring water to a boil in a saucepan. Add
tomatoes, half of the onion slices, 4 garlic cloves and chiles.
Boil for 25 minutes. Drain, and reserve cooking water. Blend cooked
ingredients with reserved onion slices and 2 garlic cloves in a
blender or food processor. Salt. Add a little cooking water to make
a slightly thick sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a frying pan to just under smoking point. Fry tacos
until crisp, turning. Remove and drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place 3 tacos on each of 8 plates. Pour green sauce on
one side and red sauce on the other. Mix creme fraiche, sour cream
and half-and-half, and pour over tacos. Sprinkle cheese on top.
Makes 24 tacos.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Taste of Mexico''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
