<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENTUCKY-ARTS-2TAKES-     05-05 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENTUCKY-ARTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COAL-MINING REGION'S RICH VEIN OF CELEBRITY MUSICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ohio, Okla., Tenn., Texas, W.Va.)  (rk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSELL, Ky. _ On this spring day, at least, last period
assembly at Russell High School was a special occasion with a
distinctly local flavor. Julie Reeves, a 24-year-old country singer
with a new recording contract, had returned from Nashville to her
alma mater in the Appalachian hills to belt out a few tunes in the
gym and give the seniors a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing her, Ann Mullins, the music teacher, reminded
everyone what a dedicated choir member her former student had been.
``You have just as much of a chance to make it big as Julie Reeves
has,'' she added. Then Ms. Reeves took the microphone, urging the
students to stay in school, have faith in God and consider the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to think, `What if my dream of being a star
doesn't come true?''' she said. ``Do you have a backup plan?''
</P>
<P>
   Then she launched into the rollicking ``Trouble Is a Woman,''
the lead song on her album ``It's About Time,'' which was being
released that day in April. Many students sang along, having
apparently learned the words from the video already being shown on
Country Music Television.
</P>
<P>
   When the song was over, the students' shouting and applause
resounded in the rafters, and though they were just teen-agers
thrilled by a brush with fame, they may well have been jubilant
that the harvest was in or that the king's line had been
perpetuated.
</P>
<P>
   Country singers are bred in this tri-state area of West
Virginia, Ohio and Kentucky, where the Ohio and Big Sandy Rivers
converge. An occasional record contact and music video for one of
the locals is seen as a birthright. Denizens try to explain the
wealth of talent with a shrug. Everyone grows up singing in church,
they say, and there's not much to do around here except make your
own entertainment. But they also like to say there's something in
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we were going to call our business,'' said Danny
Craig, a songwriter and advertising consultant who is the
co-founder, with Charlie Stewart, a Russell policeman, of a
fledgling music management firm that is scouting and developing
local singers. ```It's in the Water.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coal notwithstanding, country music singers might well be the
leading export of the region, which is centered on Ashland, Ky. (a
city of 27,000 with an oil refinery and two Wal-Marts), and extends
about 100 miles between, say, Portsmouth, Ohio, and Pikeville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   An otherwise unprepossessing strip of America, it has produced
an astonishing roster of stars: Patty Loveless, Ricky Skaggs,
Dwight Yoakam, the Judds, Keith Whitley, Crystal Gayle and Loretta
Lynn, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several areas in America that produce an
inordinately high number of artists _ Oklahoma, Texas, Louisiana _
but this may be the biggest,'' said Scott Hendricks, the president
of Virgin Records/Nashville, Ms. Reeves' label.
</P>
<P>
   The highway that cuts through the region's heart, U.S. 23, has
been memorialized as a coal-hauling route in a song by Yoakam
(``Readin', Rightin', Route 23''). Not quite two years ago it was
designated the Country Music Highway by the state of Kentucky, a
bit of legislation helped along by former state Rep. Ron Cyrus,
whose son, Billy Ray, made the music video for his hit ``Achy
Breaky Heart'' at the Paramount Theater on U.S. 23 in downtown
Ashland.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Reeves sang for the gym full of students the other day,
she was merely repeating Billy Ray's homecoming; he went to Russell
High, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make people forget the Hatfields and the McCoys,
who also lived in the neighborhood. But oddly enough, as a musical
trove it is a bit of a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people in Nashville have put it together that
Patty Loveless and Dwight Yoakam have come from the same place,''
said Mark Brown, the former vice president for Capitol
Records/Nashville, who is now dating Ms. Reeves. ``Until I met
Julie I didn't realize how much talent was here. We go out to a bar
and hear a local band and it's just awesome. There's got to be
something in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hendricks, speaking from Nashville, conceded, ``I don't
know if anyone in this town has gone in there to seek out new
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Bible-quoting, snuff-dipping, coal-mining territory,
culturally if not geographically remote, as ethnically homogeneous
as anywhere in the nation. It is a place where amiability is the
rule, where the accent, borrowing from the South and the mountains,
is thick and rolling and the idiom is full of ``yonders'' and
``you'uns'' and metaphors that couldn't grow anywhere but in a
country garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know beans from apple butter,'' said Craig, 46, the
songwriter and talent scout, recalling his early visits to
Nashville a decade ago, when he was part of a trio that included a
teen-age Ms. Reeves and her mother, Rosemary. ``This is Hicksville,
man. It's Mayberry. We're hillbillies.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the very things that may account for the new local
music and the obscurity of its origins. The area cannot really be
said to have a sound. The famous names who have come out of here
recently _ from the balladeering Judds with their heartbreaking
harmonies, to the more rock-oriented Ms. Loveless and Cyrus, to the
western-tinged Yoakam, to gospel star Michael W. Smith _ draw on a
variety of musical influences and predilections. Their work is a
good indication of how the Nashville sound has broadened, becoming
more commercial and more oriented toward rock and rhythm-and-blues
over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But musicians here say they can tell by a singer's locution if
he or she comes from the area. They have a hard time describing why
except that it all sounds so country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what you sing, it's got a twang in it,''
said Billy Joe Cantrell, 23, of Portsmouth, who plays guitar and
sings in the Midnight Thunder band behind Brandon Caserta, an
aspiring country crooner from Huntington, W. Va. ``Brandon used to
sing opera and he sounded like a country opera singer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock-and-roll intervened here for a couple of decades, usurping
the regional sounds; even Caserta, who is 21, said he grew up
listening to '70s rock. But now, inspired by a remarkable series of
local boys and girls made good (and a contemporary country idiom
that carries more pop and rock sounds than ever), the enthusiasm is
hearty and intense, particularly among the young. Among the singers
generating the best local buzz are Jessica Lynn Baldridge, 15, of
Flatwoods, Ky., and Kayla Hall, of Wurtland, Ky., who is 10. 10!
</P>
<P>
   ``What gets me is the younger people around here getting into
country music now,'' said Bob Shelpman, a 43-year-old guitarist
from Portsmouth who recently played behind Ms. Reeves and Caserta.
``When I was 20 or 21 and I was playing country, I kind of had to
hide it from my buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new music builds upon a tradition of lightning-quick banjo
players, energetic fiddlers and washtub-bass-and-moonshine-bottle
bands. And it is the traditional home of bluegrass; Bill Monroe was
a Kentuckian. It is a place where, as Jack Hicks, who played for
years with Conway Twitty and lives outside of Ashland, said,
``Everybody picks, everybody I know just picks.''
</P>
<P>
   The indigenous bluegrass sound lives on most notably in
Nashville in the music of Skaggs, who is often spoken of as the
finest, technically, of the local musicians. Dorothy Skaggs,
Ricky's mother, a former singer who still lives in Blaine, Ky., a
few miles off U.S. 23, remembers her husband, her three sons and
her daughter's entertaining 45 or 50 people in the living room. The
musicianship in her family goes back to the previous century.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather, Harmon Griffith, was an old-fashioned banjo
player,'' she said. ``When I was a girl I watched him make banjo
heads. He made them out of groundhog hides.''
</P>
<P>
   Another tradition, the heart-rending country crooner, was
personified locally by Whitley, who died of alcohol poisoning 10
years ago. Since then Whitley has attained the status of local
legend.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome man who was a boyhood friend of the portly Skaggs
(``Ricky used to tell us, `I like comin' over here to eat because
you'uns cook with lard,''' recalled Mary Whitley-Bailey, Whitley's
sister), his memory is kept alive by, among other things, an annual
motorcycle ride by his fans from the family home in Sandy Hook,
Ky., to his grave in Nashville, which usually picks up several
hundred bikers along the way.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that this combination of old-style
tradition and new-style celebrity has given rise to the idea that
there is something here to sell. Entrepreneurs are surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   Craig and Stewart (who is married to Ms. Reeves' mother) started
their company, Kentucky Blue, in the belief that there is more
golden talent in these hills than has already been dug up. They
represent Caserta and another singer, Carol Bryant, 27, the sales
manager at the Holiday Inn in Huntington, whom they are trying to
position for the contemporary gospel market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Judy Jennings, the general manager of WTCR, a country
radio station based in Huntington, has organized monthly concerts
at the Paramount in Ashland, each with local singers followed by a
headliner from Nashville. Called the Highway 23 Jamboree, the
nonprofit programs are modeled after the Grand Ole Opry, with a
house band and amiable masters of ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The last jamboree a couple of weeks ago featured half a dozen
local singers, including a vamping 9-year-old girl from Milton, W.
Va. (``I can love you better than that,'' she sang), a 15-year-old
boy from Coal Grove, Ohio, wearing a white cowboy hat and crooning
``I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry'' in a sweet adolescent alto, and
20-year-old Amy Chaney, an Ashland girl with a stately bearing, an
hourglass figure and a sequined orange stretch suit of her own
design who was being scouted by a road manager for Randy Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 800 people in the audience was Paula Rideout, who has
lived in the same house in Ashland for nearly 50 years, during
which time her daughter Naomi Judd and her granddaughter Wynonna
have come to some prominence. (So has Wynonna's sister, Ashley, the
actress.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it, why we have what we have,'' Ms. Rideout
said. ``It's just the mother lode here, and now we've tapped into
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
