<SLUG> BC-GUGGENHEIM-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$6 MILLION GOES TO 179 IN GUGGENHEIM AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (js) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among this year's 179 recipients of over $6 million in
Guggenheim Fellowships are the playwright Jon Robin Baitz, the
Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist Carol Shields, the biographer
Claudia Roth Pierpont, the writer Junot Diaz, the choreographer
Blondell Cummings and, by coincidence, two historians, Joseph H.
Lynch and Robert C. Davis, who have adjacent offices at Ohio State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The fellowships were awarded by the John Simon Guggenheim
Memorial Foundation to the artists, scholars and scientists who
emerged from its 75th annual competition. Of this year's $6.062
million, eight fiction and five nonfiction writers will share
$455,000.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Conarroe, the president of the foundation, said its
six-member committee of selection had made its choices from among
nearly 2,800 applicants. The recommendations were approved by the
foundation's trustees, who include three new members who are
themselves past Guggenheim Fellows: the writer Joyce Carol Oates,
the playwright Wendy Wasserstein and the composer Ellen Taaffe
Zwilich. The fellows were appointed on the basis of distinguished
achievement and exceptional promise for future accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're people who have already made significant contributions
to the field and are at a point where they are about to do
something very fine,'' Conarroe said. This year's winners range in
age from their late 20s to their late 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The grants average $34,000 and are not restricted in use, though
applicants must specify what goal in their field they would like to
pursue. ``The idea is to give fellows a period of creativity away
from other responsibilities, whether it's teaching, administering,
whatever,'' Conarroe said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, the foundation has awarded more than $185
million in fellowships to some 14,000 individuals. It was
established by Simon Guggenheim, an industrialist who was a senator
from Colorado from 1907 to 1913, and his wife, Olga, a
philanthropist and art patron, as a memorial to their son, John
Simon, who died on April 26, 1922. (The Guggenheim Museum was
founded by a brother, Solomon.)
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 fellows include writers, painters, sculptors,
photographers, filmmakers, choreographers, physical and biological
scientists, social scientists and scholars in the humanities. Some
work independently and others are from 92 American and Canadian
colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   A list of the 1999 fellows is available from the foundation at
90 Park Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10016, or on the foundation's Web
site: www.gf.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
