 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, May 6, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ATT-CABLELANDSCAPE _ The landscape of the cable industry changed
over night when AT&AMP;T emerged the victor in the fight for MediaOne.
Comcast, the loser and the no.4 cable operator, was able to wrest
some concessions from AT&AMP;T, what does this mean for the other cable
operators liked Cox Communications. Will there be a flurry of
consolidation among the remaining players? Will consumers get more
services at a cheaper rate? (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ATT-BELLSOUTH _ How will BellSouth and other telcos respond now
that AT&AMP;T has emerged triumphant in the battle for MediaOne making
it the nation's biggest cable company as well as phone company.
Will this spur BellSouth and other telephone companies to hurry
with their deployment of DSL, the telephone version of high speed
Internet access. How will consumer benefit. (Hzzzke, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ALALEGIS-HONDA _ The Alabama legislature considers a package of
economic incentives that might solidify Honda's decision to build
an auto assembly plant near Lincoln. We look at the package they
offered Mercedes and how Georgia did or did not compete. (Ritzler,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-BELLSOUTH _ MindSpring finally makes deal with
BellSouth to offer DSL service to MindSpring customers. This ends a
long period of antagonism between the ISP and BellSouth over access
and pricing for ``last mile'' access. (Hzzzke, Atlana
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ Mike Milken's name was once synbonymous with Wall
Street fraud and graft. connected especially with the insider
trading scandals of the 1980s. Many of his friends always contended
that he was a scapegoat for others who were the real culprits. At
any rate, Milkin served time in jail and has now started another
successful career. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
