A5589 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-05 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO THOSE NASTY OL' FREEDOMS NEED REVISING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's politicians have figured out the cause of all these
murderous rampages by school kids.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we should say that some of the politicians have it
figured out one way, and some have it figured out another way.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell: Conservatives believe that the violence is caused
by the First Amendment to the Constitution of the United States;
liberals believe that the culprit is the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   They don't say this in so many words, of course. They talk about
the lethal menace that is posed by the proliferation of violent TV
shows, or movies, or video games. They talk about the lethal menace
that is posed by the availability of guns.
</P>
<P>
   But cut through the partisan rhetoric and ideological claptrap,
and the message from these folks is clear. Each side is blaming the
recent killings in places such as Littleton, Colo., and Jonesboro,
Ark., on a precious freedom guaranteed by the Constitution: either
freedom of speech or the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a question: If politicians in Washington and around the
country are truly convinced that a constitutional provision written
more than 200 years ago is causing all this trouble, why don't they
step up to the plate and propose that the provision be repealed?
</P>
<P>
   It would make for a fascinating debate in Congress, that's for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   How interesting to hear Republicans argue for the elimination of
that pesky old First Amendment, the one that allows so many amazing
thoughts and words to find their way into our culture. How
intriguing to hear Democrats make the case for ridding the
Constitution of the Second Amendment, the one that allows
law-abiding citizens to take up arms against tyranny and injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Any fool can see that these freedoms have been abused _ that
Hollywood elitists have perverted the meaning of free speech, that
sociopathic misfits like those mass-murdering teen-agers in
Colorado have made a mockery of the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   When the nation's founders conjured up the First Amendment, they
couldn't have envisioned cable TV and the Internet. When they went
to bat for the right to bear arms, it couldn't have occurred to
them that one day schoolboys would amass arsenals of assault rifles
and semiautomatic pistols and use them to gun down classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Hasn't society become too sophisticated, too complex and too
dangerous to accommodate the sort of simple concepts that are
expressed in the First and Second Amendments? Isn't it time that we
did away with such naive, outmoded ideas and started dealing with
reality as it exists at the threshold of the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
   Please stop me if you think I'm going nuts here. Here I am,
pondering the practicality of repealing the first two amendments of
the greatest legal document ever devised, and a few of you are
sitting there saying: ``You know, he has a point. Maybe it's time
we changed some of this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   At least I'm hoping it's a few. If it's a lot, this country is
in bigger trouble than I thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   But this exercise in hyperbolic lunacy has a purpose. I am
trying to make the point that it isn't all that large a leap from
tinkering with constitutional rights to demolishing them.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal-leaning interviewers on the TV networks have done
everything but laugh in Charlton Heston's face _ or spit in it _
during the past few days, and yet the actor-turned-president of the
National Rifle Association is exactly right when he notes that one
of the first official acts of any newly installed tyrant is to
confiscate the guns of the citizenry. We tamper with the Second
Amendment at our peril.
</P>
<P>
   And the media might take note: Right after tyrants grab up the
people's guns, they usually shut down their newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural for society to yearn for answers in the
aftermath of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's also natural for politicians to exploit that
yearning by proposing unnecessary laws that promise easy solutions
but deliver no solutions at all.
</P>
<P>
   The people's job is to make sure they don't get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
