<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRING-AUCTIONS-ART-2     05-05 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-AUCTIONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITNEY ESTATE SWEETENS SPRING ART SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The round of important fine-art auctions that begins
at Sotheby's in Manhattan on Monday evening might be described as a
play in two acts. The first act could be called ``The Auctioneer's
Dream'': the collection of extraordinary Post-Impressionist
paintings from the estate of Betsey Cushing Roosevelt Whitney, a
New York socialite and philanthropist who died in March. The
Whitney collection, blockbuster material of pristine provenance,
should make for a near-perfect auction Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The second act, which includes two more sales at Sotheby's and
three at Christie's, could be labeled ``The Harsh Realities of the
Art Market.'' The offerings add up to a patchy selection of works
by major 19th- and 20th-century artists like Monet and Renoir,
Jasper Johns and Andy Warhol. These underscore the scarcity of
great art available. And that helps make the Whitney sale a major
event.
</P>
<P>
   During their 46-year marriage, Mrs. Whitney and her husband,
John Hay Whitney, a financier, publisher and former U.S. ambassador
to Britain who died in 1982, put together one of the most important
collections of modern masters in private hands. Mrs. Whitney left
works worth more than $300 million by van Gogh, Matisse, Picasso
and other masters to four major American museums. She left the
remaining paintings, drawings and sculptures to her two daughters,
Kate Whitney and Sara Wilford, who said they had decided to sell
many of them to help pay estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those rare moments in auction history,'' said
Charles Moffett, co-director of Sotheby's worldwide department of
Impressionist and modern art. ``No buyer could possibly make a
mistake.'' Others in the art world agree.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 50 works that will be sold Monday, two stand out:
Cezanne's ``Still Life With Curtain, Pitcher and Bowl of Fruit''
(1893-94), a first-rate example of one of his mature still lifes
that is estimated to sell for $25 million to $35 million, and
Seurat's ``Island of the Grande Jatte'' (1884), which carries the
same estimate. The Seurat is one of two large final preparatory
studies for his famous painting ``A Sunday on la Grande Jatte,''
which hangs in the Art Institute of Chicago. The other study, a
composition with figures, is in the Metropolitan Museum's
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``My old curator's eye could see the Seurat hanging in several
museums,'' said Moffett.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitneys also collected Picassos, and in 1968 they bought
two important works from the collection of Gertrude Stein that are
included in the sale. ``The Newspaper'' (1912) is a widely
exhibited painting from the artist's high period of Analytical
Cubism and carries an estimate of $4 million to $6 million. ``Still
Life With Glass, Bottle of Rum and Bowl of Fruit,'' painted two
years later, is estimated to sell for $5 million to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's and Christie's fight hard to win good estate property.
This season it was no surprise when Sotheby's announced itself the
winner of the Whitney estate, for the Whitneys had long been loyal
consignors to Sotheby's. In 1990 it sold one of the paintings from
their collection, Renoir's ``At the Moulin de la Galette,'' to
Japanese industrialist Ryoei Saito for $78.1 million. (In April,
Sotheby's sold the contents of Mrs. Whitney's five homes in a round
of sales that totaled $13.1 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Little other significant estate property has been available this
spring, leaving both Sotheby's and Christie's scrambling to find
top-quality art for sale while collectors are eager to buy and
money is plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem this season is that there isn't any sense
of urgency about having to sell,'' said Christopher Burge, chairman
of Christie's in America. ``People expect prices to go higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Both auction houses are selling a hefty number of paintings from
Japan, where banks that collected feverishly during the boom of the
1980s are now in financial trouble. Christie's has on offer works
owned by Lake Co., the Japanese consumer-loan concern that was
bought last year by GE Capital, the financial services arm of
General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Lake has sent Christie's about 500 works valued at $250 million
that the auction house plans to sell over a number of years. For
sale on May 19 and 20 are Pissarro's ``Road from Versailles to St.
Germain in the Snow'' (1872), estimated at $1.4 million to $1.8
million; Braque's ``Landscape at L'Estaque'' (1906), estimated at
$1.5 million to $2 million, and Monet's ``Garden of Vetheuil''
(1881), which sold at Christie's in 1990 for $4.9 million and now
carries an estimate of $2.5 million to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That work is just one of 13 Monets for sale this spring, with
Sotheby's offering five and Christie's eight. Asked why so many of
his works are now up for sale, Franck Giraud, head of Christie's
19th- and 20th-century art departments worldwide, said simply,
``It's a happy accident and highly unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Christie's offerings include many of Monet's familiar subjects,
including his garden in Giverny and Charing Cross Bridge. At
Sotheby's a Monet of a single haystack from 1891 was included in an
exhibition of 15 haystack paintings at the Durand-Ruel Gallery in
Paris the year it was painted. When it failed to sell at Christie's
in London in 1990, it was purchased by the members of the Nahmad
family, among the biggest auction buyers in the world, who are
selling it Tuesday at Sotheby's. It carries an $8 million to $12
million estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The Nahmads are also the sellers of another expensive painting
in Sotheby's Impressionist and modern art sale on Tuesday night,
Toulouse-Lautrec's 1889 ``Woman Seated in the Garden of Mr.
Forest,'' thought to fetch $6 million to $8 million. The painting
failed to sell at Christie's in 1991 and the Nahmads bought it
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Both auction houses are offering works with a lively sales
history. The star of Christie's sale of 19th-century and
Impressionist works Wednesday is van Gogh's ``Canal With
Washerwoman,'' a vividly colored landscape that captures the spot
where the women of Arles did their laundry. The painting was last
for sale at Sotheby's in 1984, when it sold for $1.7 million. Now
it is being offered with an estimate of about $20 million. ``It's
an event when van Gogh's like this come on the market,'' said
Giraud. ``They're simply not available any more, and collectors
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   One collection of 20th-century art that is generating a lot of
interest is being sold at Christie's next Thursday by a Chicago
couple, Maurice and Margo Cohen. A highlight of the collection is
Leger's ``Three Women with a Bouquet'' (1922), which combines an
elongated nude figure with two clothed women. It is similar to
``The Big Breakfast,'' a scene of three women painted a year
earlier that is in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art. The
work is expected to bring $5 million to $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's contemporary sale, which includes only art from the
last three decades, offers works by artists like Robert Gober,
Christopher Wool and Cindy Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to imagine the dream sale and made a list of artists,
even works I wanted to sell,'' said Philippe Segalot, who runs
Christie's contemporary art department in New York. One example is
Gober's ``Untitled (Leg With Candle),'' a sculpture of a human leg
fashioned from wax, human hair, leather, cotton and wood, with a
white candle sticking out of its shin; it is estimated to sell for
$300,000 to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's contemporary art sale May 18, which, unlike
Christie's, encompasses art from 1945 to the present, includes two
important Warhols, part of the group of contemporary works from the
estate of the German collector Helmut Kraetz.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Suicide,'' a 1964 monotype on paper from the artist's
much-sought-after disaster series. It is expected to sell for
$100,000 to $150,000. Another is ``Marlon,'' a 1966 silk-screen of
Marlon Brando that carries an estimate of $1.5 million to $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marlon'' is ``the picture of the week,'' said Tobias Meyer,
Sotheby's worldwide director of contemporary art. ``It was last on
the market in 1968.''
</P>
<P>
   Another highlight of the sale is a Calder sculpture,
``Constellation,'' commissioned in 1943 by Philip Johnson and his
sister, Theodate Severns, for Hidden House, their Manhattan home.
Made of painted wood and wire, it is estimated to bring $600,000 to
$800,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philip Johnson undoubtedly has the best eye in the second half
of the 20th century,'' Meyer said. ``This is the most sophisticated
of the artist's constellation series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough getting good property like the Calder,'' he
added. ``One of the biggest problems is that when something good
comes on the market, it is immediately sold because the demand for
top-quality art is so high and these days it is so rare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
