<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PAGERS-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW PAGERS RECEIVE MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the digital culture of the late '90s, being out of reach is
the ultimate faux pas; people have come to expect instant access
not only to information but also to one another.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, business cards are overflowing with addresses and
numbers for snail mail, telephones, cellular phones, Web sites,
e-mail and, of course, pagers. Approximately 155 million portable
electronic paging devices are keeping people connected worldwide.
Cellular phones seem not to have bitten into the growing use of
pagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over half our customers have cell phones, but they enjoy being
able to leave their cell phone off,'' said Scott Hamilton, vice
president for investor relations at Skytel, one of the more
extensive paging networks. ``With a pager, they can receive
notification and choose how or when to contact someone back.''
</P>
<P>
   If humans are to become cyborgs one day, then the ubiquity of
pagers represents some kind of evolutionary step. It's the next
best thing to having a tracking chip soldered into your skull.
Thanks to an elaborate network of transmitters, receivers and
satellites, you can almost always be found if you wear a pager.
</P>
<P>
   This technology has been decades in the making. When pagers
first appeared, in the early 1970s, they were designed for
receiving messages within a city. To reach someone, a caller had to
dial a number and tap in a numeric message. The person receiving
the message was notified by a beep and had to call in to get the
information. Not very efficient.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Mobile Communications Corp. of America
introduced alphanumeric paging. Problem was, it didn't represent a
direct channel of communication; an operator had to take the call,
type in the message and send it on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Today, such methods seem as antiquated as Morse code. Paging
culture is no longer limited to corporate executives with clunky
black boxes. Parents use pagers to keep in touch with baby sitters;
doctors use them to track patients; high school students use them
to make dates. (According to a recent poll by Motorola, one of the
largest manufacturers of paging devices, 15 percent of the nation's
teen-agers use pagers.)
</P>
<P>
   Pagers may have nearly as many uses as users. New systems allow
callers to send voice messages (which can be converted into text),
alphanumeric commands, faxes or e-mail. When someone calls a paging
number, that code tags the message for delivery, dictating its path
of satellite uplinks, downlinks, radio transmitters and receivers.
</P>
<P>
   But reliance upon wireless and satellite networks can lead to
vulnerability. In May 1998, the Galaxy 4 satellite temporarily lost
control and orientation. Fortunately, a redundant system rescued
most of the pagers' messages.
</P>
<P>
   Pager companies are continually adding new features, like
``reflex'' technology, which allows two-way communication. Instead
of just sending someone a message and hoping that it is received, a
sender can immediately get a response from the person with the
pager.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, at Skytel, said that compared with the previous year,
the number of subscribers with such advanced messaging had grown by
more than 170 percent in the past year while the number of one-way
subscribers had increased by only 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced messaging also allows customers to retrieve messages
and information on the Internet. Skytel reports that the number of
Internet messages has grown in the past two years to 5.2 million
from 500,000 per month. The Weather Channel, MSNBC and Golf
magazine are among the companies providing news and information for
paging units.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the data flow in only one direction _ you can
receive information from the Net but you cannot go online and surf
for it. Innovations like reflex technology are aimed at freeing up
cluttered gadget bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to look like something out of the Mexican
Revolution,'' said Jim Page, vice president of business development
for flex technologies at Motorola. ``Techno-weenies don't want to
carry that many products.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Page said that pagers were unlikely to morph into
all-in-one units to replace, say, laptops. They are more likely to
streamline the ways in which they communicate with other devices
instead.
</P>
<P>
   But all this networking comes with one unavoidable consequence:
the easier it becomes to get in touch, the harder it is to get
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
