<SLUG> BC-STAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HMM, THIS BOOK MIGHT MAKE A GOOD MOVIE' 
</HEADLINE>
 WARS-BOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
  
EDITOR'S NOTE: What if someone got lost in space 25 years ago and
had never heard of ``Star Wars?'' We asked reporter Scott Craven to
look at the novelized version of ``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace''
as though he'd never heard of the thing. Does it hold up as a book?
Would it make a decent movie? 
 
 ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' 
 Terry Brooks (Ballantine, $25) 
  
  
 By SCOTT CRAVEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is a bit presumptuous to write a book titled
``Episode I,'' assuming sales and popularity will dictate a
continuation of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Brooks, an accomplished writer in the genre, manages to
pull it off, making ``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' an engaging
read perfect for a summer afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The book does not hide the fact that it is based on a movie
script written by George Lucas, director of ``American Graffiti.''
Brooks' novel certainly lends itself to the screen, though likely
as an animated feature because of the complexity of the special
effects that would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' active writing style moves the action swiftly,
fast-forwarding the reader between rare lulls of character
interaction. The blast of lasers fill every page, and as soon as
someone settles in for some quiet insight, it's quickly broken up
by explosions and swordplay.
</P>
<P>
   And not just any kind of sword but one with a blade of energy so
powerful it can melt a steel door. You can guess what it can do to
organic matter (and does, as Brooks isn't afraid to shed any
literary blood).
</P>
<P>
   These so-called ``lightsabers'' are wielded by a quasi-religious
band of fanatics calling themselves the Jedi. Seems this ancient
sect, whose origins are conveniently lost in the mists of time,
have the power of ``the Force,'' which is in all living things
(even among those who do not carry a lightsaber).
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being mystical, the Force is biological. Bodies (and
perhaps trees, if the Force occupies everything organic) contain
midi-chlorians, microscopic symbionts that give those with high
concentrations the power, among other things, to run faster, jump
higher and move objects telekinetically, like an athletic Uri
Geller.
</P>
<P>
   Like the knights of Camelot, the Jedi are sworn to uphold the
laws of the Republic, sort of a U.N. for planets. The Republic is
threatened when the Trade Federation, a powerful association of
merchants, protests taxation by blockading Naboo, a peaceful planet
ruled by young Queen Amidala.
</P>
<P>
   A Jedi Master (Qui-Gon Jinn) and his apprentice (Obi-Wan Kenobi)
are dispatched to negotiate with the Federation, only to discover
that it is part of a larger plot to destroy the Republic.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are 250 pages of epic battles, intricate
hand-to-hand fights and narrow escapes, the perfect blueprint for
the kind of action-packed serial not seen since the 1950s. The tale
follows (``chases'' is a better term) the Jedis as they rescue the
queen from an army of murderous robots (battle and destroyer
``droids''). Their ship is crippled in a brief battle, and the crew
is forced to land on Tatooine, a barren planet home to all sorts of
nefarious creatures.
</P>
<P>
   There they meet Anakin Skywalker, a 9-year-old slave who has a
talent with all things mechanical. He also happens to be the only
human pod racer, a sport in which jet-powered vehicles race among
deserts and canyons in a way that is perfect fodder for a computer
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie,'' as he is called by his mom and friends, also happens
to have a lot of these midi-chlorians, which attracts the interest
of Jinn, who thinks the boy is destined for great things. Together,
they return to Naboo for the final showdown, not only to fight the
Federation, but an evil ``Sith Lord,'' whose midi-chlorians have
run afoul and thus practices a dark side of the Force and is intent
to destroy the heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks at times throws in characters, cities and planets with
little description or explanation, as if assuming the reader has a
prior knowledge of this universe.
</P>
<P>
   The ending leaves many unanswered questions and begs a sequel
(certainly to happen if the book is a success). This is an
established pattern for Brooks, who typically writes series (such
as the Shannara and Magic Kingdom of Landover books). The title
even suggests a follow-up, since one cannot expect an Episode I not
to be followed by and Episode II or even III.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks doesn't allow room for characters to grow beyond mere
extensions of their weapons. But clearly, that is his intent,
appealing to lovers of Westerns, swashbucklers and similar fare. No
doubt if the movie is made, it could well spawn a cross-marketing
treasure of toys and trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, though, is that ``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' has
been published with four dust jackets, each featuring a different
character. One book would suffice for most readers, though big
Brooks fans may want to collect them all should the book become as
popular as, say, anything written by John Grisham or Stephen King. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scott Craven can be reached at (602) 444-7983 or email him at
scott.craven(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
