<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday
May 6. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   TWIST _ Oklahoma City begins recovering from another disaster.
We touch on relief efforts, donations such as free funeral
services, response such as blood collecting in shopping centers.
There is a sense that past tragedy has prepared people and
institutions to react to this. Rick Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: Passage of a partial-birth abortion bill finally gives
the Missouri General Assembly something substantive to brag about
in an otherwise lackluster session. But not before several
filibusters, an MIA legislator and other legislative tactics nearly
threatened to derail proceedings. Although the governor is widely
expected to veto the bill, that doesn't mean Missouri won't end up
with a ban on ``infanticide,'' the term that would apply to
partial-birth abortions under the law. Last year, the legislature
came within one vote of overriding the veto. This year, with a more
lawsuit-proof bill, legislators could well overcome any opposition
from the governor. Will Sentell. 25.
</P>
<P>
   AWARD: The folks who give out the Harry Truman Good Neighbor
Award are being more inclusive this year. Not only is the award
going to John Hope Franklin, the first African-American to receive
it, but there are more people of color on the guest list at an
event that started out with a few white businessmen. Brian Burnes.
20.
</P>
<P>
   JANE (with AWARD): Actress Jane Alexander is the recipient of
another award to be given Friday during Truman week. And she's also
unusual _ she fought the Gingrich crowd that wanted to cut federal
funding for the National Endowment for the Arts. Mug. Brian Burnes.
12.
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA. Today's coverage out of Haysville &AMP; Wichita will focus
on how those who lost their homes can begin to rebuild their lives.
Jim Sullinger, Tom Perrin.
</P>
<P>
   SEITZ (biz) _ Sara Lee Corp. plans an $80 million expansion at
its St. Joseph Seitz facility, which makes hot dogs and other
processed meat products. The expansion will create 250-350 new
jobs. By Randolph Heaster
</P>
<P>
   STAFF (biz column) _ ``Hey, Bill, we've got a bomb threat. We're
evacuating, but we want you stay behind and search for anything
suspicious.'' Now that could ruin your day. There's a better way to
deal with emergencies. At Work column By Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEWORK (biz) _ Missouri Work at Home Day, proclaimed by the
self-interested Southwestern Bell, is today. Despite the fabricated
designation, there's reason to pay attention to home-based business
trends. By Diane Stafford
</P>
<P>
   CIGNA (biz) _ Cigna HealthCare is pulling out of the Medicare
HMO business in Kansas City and five other markets at the end of
this year. This will affect about 1,500 plan members in the Kansas
City area. Julius Karash.
</P>
</TEXT>
