<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-ELECT-425&AMP;AD     05-05 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-ELECT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL ELECTIONS MARK SHIFT TOWARD DECENTRALIZATION OF POWER IN
BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ The Scots will be voting for their first
Parliament since 1707. The Welsh will be electing the first one
they have ever had. And Prime Minister Tony Blair will be looking
for validation of his two-year-old government's transformation of
how the British run themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The elections of members of the two new legislatures and of 362
councils across Britain on Thursday are being called the most
important midterm balloting in the country's history. In addition
to providing the traditional barometer of a government, this year's
elections confirm Britain's move to decentralize political
authority.
</P>
<P>
   It is an undertaking central to Blair's program of what he calls
radical reform for Britain, and one that is being eyed with
interest elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put all this at risk,'' Blair said in outlining what he
said were his government's achievements and calling for a big
turnout in a televised campaign address on Tuesday night, an event
that is itself rare in British local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, election day has been called ``Super Thursday.''
More than 12,000 councillors, 129 members of the Scottish
Parliament and 60 members of the National Assembly of Wales are to
be elected.
</P>
<P>
   While Blair has been eager to portray the vote as a referendum
on national issues _ an arena where opinion polls show his party
with far greater voter appeal than his dispirited Conservative
opponents _ the races often turn on local concerns beyond the reach
of a popular national leader's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   And nowhere has that been truer than here, where the Scottish
Nationalist Party, which proposes full independence for Scotland,
turned long-held local resentment of rule from London into early
campaign success that provoked predictions of the imminent breakup
of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Labor appears to have recaptured the lead from the Scottish
Nationalists and will probably end up controlling the Parliament
either by itself or in coalition with the centrist Liberal
Democrats. If such an arrangement emerges, that would mark another
first in British politics arising out of this election.
</P>
<P>
   Also precedent-setting for Britain is the use of
Continental-style proportional representation. After they have
submitted their first ballot for a candidate from their own
district, voters will be asked to cast a second ballot for a
candidate from a party list.
</P>
<P>
   One early consequence will be a more complicated tabulation,
which will delay knowledge of the full results of the elections
until Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Running 15 points ahead of Labor in opinion polls during the
summer, the Scottish Nationalists stumbled badly over two gaffes by
their leader, Alex Salmond, a former bank oil analyst with a good
grasp of political economics, a wry sense of humor and a talent for
tweaking the English that was unfailing until this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His first mistake was to propose increasing taxes on Scots, a
move that overestimated the traditional Scottish faith in state
social services and willingness to ante up for them.
</P>
<P>
   The second was to assail the air raids on Yugoslavia as
``imponderable folly'' in the early days of NATO's attacks, a
statement that neglected local pride in the Scots' reputation for
being Britain's most courageous and accomplished fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Cook, the foreign secretary, who is also a Scot,
excoriated Salmond the next day as ``sure to be the toast of
Belgrade'' and questioned his credentials for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Blair came to Scotland to say that what the Nationalists were
talking about was not independence but separatism. He argued that
there were no grounds for Scotland to be seeking a divorce from the
rest of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The Salmond episodes left the impression that the Nationalists
were in over their depth in national and international politics,
and the poll numbers swung away from them in favor of Labor. Blair
exploited the lapses by putting the campaign here under the
direction of the most powerful member of his Cabinet and the most
formidable politician from Scotland, Chancellor of the Exchequer
Gordon Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists countered with an impassioned speech from Sean
Connery, the Scottish actor. But the effect of his visit was
diminished by press ridicule of him as a hypocrite for proclaiming
independence for a country that he himself will not live in.
Connery has homes in the Bahamas and Marbella on Spain's
Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devolution,'' the name by which the move to allocate more
power to the various parts of the United Kingdom goes, now appears
to be on course, with its backers expected to emerge in control of
the legislatures here and in Cardiff, Wales, where the nationalist
party, Plaid Cymru (pronounced plyde KUM-ry), is running behind
Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Devolution was a principal plank in Blair's campaign platform,
and he moved quickly once in office to hold referendums in Scotland
and Wales to gain local approval for setting up the two
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland, with its distinct sense of nationhood and separate
legal and educational systems, voted yes overwhelmingly. Wales,
where national identity is more elusive, passed the measure by only
a fraction of a percent. Unlike the Scottish Nationalists, Plaid
Cymru is not an independence party.
</P>
<P>
   The new regional governments will have authority over local
government, health, education, transportation, the environment and
culture. The Scottish Parliament will have tax-setting and
law-making powers, though the Welsh National Assembly will not. The
British Parliament will continue to control defense and foreign
policy, taxation and social security.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Blair program, London will get its first popularly
elected mayor and an assembly later this year, and regions of
England in the middle and north of the country will be encouraged
to think of future local governments for their areas.
</P>
<P>
   Keen interest in the outcome here has been expressed by
politicians in France, Germany, Belgium, Italy and Spain, all
countries testing their own formulas for granting restive parts of
their countries autonomous freedoms from traditional central
authority that stop short of full independence.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists in Britain have expressed fear over the
consequences of passing out power to the country's regions, but on
the eve of the balloting, more hopeful notes were sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If devolution works, it will suggest that Britain's
traditional gift for creating political stability through
moderation and pragmatism still exists,'' said an editorial in The
Economist's current issue. ``And if gloomy predictions of `the
breakup of Britain' prove to be ill-founded, the notion of
Britishness could well emerge strengthened by a proven ability to
accommodate diverse national cultures and new centers of power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-MARKETPLACE-NY     05-05 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LONG-TERM OUTLOOK FOR BRAZIL IS CALLED BRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may appear to many investors that the sharp rebound in
Brazilian stocks and bonds has passed them by. The stock market, in
local terms, is up 71 percent this year and is almost back to its
last peak in March 1998. Prices in the bond market have jumped, as
the yields, which move in the opposite direction, have plunged. The
yield on Brazil's benchmark long-term bond maturing in 2027 is down
to 12.6 percent, from 16.9 percent just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and money managers, though, say there is still much
more to make on a investment in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are betting on interest rates falling, the currency
stabilizing and inflation not being a threat,'' said Jay Pelosky,
the global emerging-markets strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, who recommended a move back into Brazil in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the bet will prove to be a smart one. He even thinks
the Brazilian economy will surprise this year by declining much
less than expected. In the last few weeks, Brazilian officials have
cut their forecasts of the decline to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pelosky thinks Brazil is a good bet in the longer-term,
he warns that the stock market is in a pause right now. All the
good news about Brazil's unexpected escape from disaster is, as
they say on Wall Street, in the market. Since reaching a high for
the year of 11,529.92 on April 7, the Bovespa index of 57 Brazilian
stocks has settled into a narrow trading range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you need new confirmation for Brazil to go appreciably
higher,'' Pelosky said. With good earnings news not expected for
some months and the economy still declining, that confirmation make
take some time.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is Brazil's congressional investigation
concerning the central bank's role in the bailout of two small
investment banks earlier this year. If it gets more serious, the
inquiry could distract the Brazilian Congress from completing
important structural changes that are aimed at ensuring Brazil's
long-term economic health.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosky also cautions American investors not to bet on a rebound
in the Brazilian currency, the real, to profit from an investment
there. Such a bet might look attractive. While the Bovespa has
surged, in dollar terms the index is still 57 percent below its
March 1998 highs.
</P>
<P>
   The real declined by as much as 44 percent in value after the
government abandoned foreign-exchange controls on the currency in
mid-January. But since early March it has rallied by 28 percent and
is now valued at 1.683 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosky does not think that it will rally much more in the near
term because several more months are needed for foreign investors
to be convinced that important benchmarks, like the size of the
government budget deficit, are moving in the right direction. Data
for April, which would give three full months of performance since
the devaluation, will not be available until June. Ernest Brown,
the chief Latin American economist at Morgan Stanley, forecasts
that the real will only strengthen another 3 percent by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Beneat, the portfolio manager of the new and tiny Dreyfus
Premier Emerging Markets Fund, cut his exposure to Brazil several
weeks ago because he thought that the good run since January was
going to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the summer we are going to have some pretty bad
numbers,'' he said, referring to data showing that the economy is
still in a decline. ``The environment will not be that positive.''
</P>
<P>
   While he cut back in Brazil, he increased his holdings in
Mexican stocks. ``The earnings are very good and the valuations are
very cheap there,'' he said. ``Mexico will outperform Brazil in the
coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the economy turns, he said, he will return to Brazil,
picking up more of the utility and telecommunications stocks he
already likes, including Tele Centro Sul Participacoes, the local
telecommunications company which has jumped 58 percent since the
devaluation, and Companhia Paranaense de Energia-Copel, a large
utility, which is up 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a view on Brazil,'' argued Arturo
Porzecanski, chief economist for the Americas at ING Barings. But
he thinks that the bond market, for now, may be a better bet. ``If
you are an equity investor you have to wait for earnings to come
back'' and that means waiting for the economy to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds, he said, are more a bet ``on a perception of risk.'' And
with a further decline in interest rates, that risk will be
lessening before the economy turns. Last week, the central bank
made its fourth interest rate cut in five weeks. The benchmark rate
was trimmed to 32 percent from 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said there is room for bond yields to fall
further, when compared to history and the yields in the rest of
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   According to a J.P. Morgan index that tracks the difference
between Latin American yields and comparable U.S. Treasury
securities, the spread for Brazilian debt is 8.82 percentage
points, 5.98 percentage points for Argentina and 5.48 percentage
points for Mexico. In addition, while the Brazilian spread has
fallen from a 1999 high of 17.79 percentage points Jan. 14, it is
still more than the 6.08 percent on July 31 last year, just before
Russia devalued its ruble and defaulted on its debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the opportunity to buy,'' said Porzecanski.
But he made sure to add the qualifier always invoked when
discussing emerging markets _ ``for the long-term investor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-05 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DROP IN SUPPORT, MORDECHAI VOWS TO STAY IN RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yitzhak Mordechai, the Center Party candidate for
prime minister, is facing increasing pressure from inside and
outside his party to drop out of the race and join forces with Ehud
Barak, the Labor Party leader and front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   But Mordechai, a candidate who was born by the polls, refuses to
die by them, even though they show his support plummeting; he is
now at less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Center Party is strong,'' Mordechai, the former defense
minister, said Wednesday as he emerged from an all-day huddle with
his running mates and advisers. ``I am continuing to run for prime
minister, and we will meet again on May 18,'' the day after ballots
are cast.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days before the election, the logic of Mordechai's
candidacy is fading. His slogan _ ``Only Mordechai can win big''
against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu _ does not stand up to
the evidence that his constituency is ebbing away. Former army
colleagues traveled to his home last weekend to beg him to step
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the man, he will never give up,'' Maozia Segal, a
close friend and a Center Party candidate for Parliament, said.
``He is going all the way. Take my word for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The party was created in the winter to break what its leaders
saw as a stalemate between the two main parties, Barak's Labor and
Netanyahu's Likud, which command tribal loyalties from their
partisans. Its four leaders were united chiefly by their desire to
oust Netanyahu. They said they did not think that Barak was able to
do that.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak, a highly decorated former general, has cobbled
together a coalition that incorporates moderate religious and
Sephardic leaders into his base at the Labor Party, which
represents the Ashkenazi elite. And he is running about 8
percentage points ahead of Netanyahu, although many voters say they
remain undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Center Party leaders, Mordechai, who is gruff,
straightforward and extremely well liked, was the most popular. He
was chosen to represent the party because he outscored Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, another former general and now second in the polls.
The party was mocked for its reliance on poll takers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the polls have turned against them, and Mordechai
has taken to discounting their reliability. The most recent show
him trailing Barak and Netanyahu in the first round of voting with
5 to 7 percent of the vote, down from 17 in March. In a runoff,
where polls had shown him trouncing Netanyahu in a one-on-one race,
some now find him barely ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a snowball effect at this point,'' a political scientist,
Yaron Ezrahi, said. ``Once he's headed downhill like this, he
cannot be rescued, especially since he has no secret supply of
charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Some polls, whose results were faxed to news organizations by
the Labor Party, found that if Mordechai were to quit the race,
Barak would win a significant victory over Netanyahu in the first
round of voting.
</P>
<P>
   It is a five-way race for prime minister, with Benny Begin, a
right-wing candidate, taking votes from Netanyahu and Azmi Bishara,
an Israeli Arab member of Parliament, taking part of the Arab vote
from Barak.
</P>
<P>
   If Mordechai were to drop out, Bishara said he might, too. That
could give Barak more than 50 percent of the vote, which a
candidate needs to win outright. Any percentage short of that would
push the top two vote-getters into a runoff on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   A top-ranking member of the Labor Party, Yossi Beilin, said
Mordechai was ``forcing a second round on the electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream has faded, and it should disappear before the
elections,'' Beilin wrote in an Op-Ed article in The Jerusalem
Post. ``It would be much more respectable for Mordechai to admit
this and join forces with the camp which will replace Netanyahu
than trying to prove to Netanyahu what a man he is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the one triumphant moment of his campaign, Mordechai, who is
not known for his way with words, out-talked Netanyahu, who is
considered a media wizard, in a televised debate a few weeks ago.
Although that tarnished Netanyahu's image as unflappable, the
debate did not improve Mordechai's standing in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   And in the debate, Netanyahu coaxed from him a promise _ not to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu sees an advantage in prolonging the race, apparently
believing that he will have an easier time having his voters to
show up at the polls twice.
</P>
<P>
   An Iraqi-born Kurdish Jew, Mordechai is the first Sephardic
candidate for prime minister, and many found his candidacy moving
because of the barrier it broke. When Mordechai campaigns, he
encounters many Israelis with deep feelings for him, and that has
led him to believe that the polls must not be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, though, he met with such hostility among religious
Sephardim that he had to leave an event at the suggestion of a
police commander. At Mount Meron in the Galilee, where religious
Jews were gathering at the grave of a rabbi, scores of
ultra-Orthodox men chanted Netanyahu's name and threw plastic bags
of water at Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   He was whisked away in the center of a circle of police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai has faulted the Labor Party for starting rumors that
he was contemplating withdrawal. The Israeli press is rife with
quotes from unidentified high-level associates of Mordechai saying
they cannot persuade him to throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mordechai is determined not to pull out,'' a senior political
correspondent for Israel Radio, Yaron Dekel, said Wednesday night.
``But to call that the opinion of all party members would be a
mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
