<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days According to Jesus''
</P>
<P>
   By R.C. Sproul
</P>
<P>
   Baker, $15.99
</P>
<P>
   ``End Times''
</P>
<P>
   By John F. Walvoord
</P>
<P>
   Word, $19.97
</P>
<P>
   Not with a whimper but a bang, to reverse T.S. Eliot's famous
phrase about how the world ends _ that much R.C. Sproul and John F.
Walvoord would probably agree on. But as for what happens before
God brings down the curtain on human history _ that is where these
two theologians would differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debates over eschatology'' _ the academic word for the study
of the last days _ ``will probably continue until the Lord
returns,'' Sproul observes. And ``The Last Days According to
Jesus'' is his contribution to the argument that much of
evangelicalism has misread the Scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   Sproul focuses on the Olivet Discourse, a lengthy prophecy in
the Gospels that deals with Jerusalem, the temple and Jesus' coming
in glory. The Reformed writer argues for ``preterism,'' which
teaches that many New Testament prophecies that are often thought
to deal with the world's end were actually fulfilled during the
first century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days'' does a series of quick dives into topics such
as the destruction of Jerusalem, the millennium and the Antichrist,
although the arguments that Sproul investigates may leave many at
least partially unswayed. The Florida scholar's book is written
more for the serious student than the casual reader, but it
provides an accessible glimpse into territory that is unfamiliar to
many.
</P>
<P>
   Walvoord's ``End Times'' stoutly defends ``dispensational
premillennialism,'' the idea that God has dealt in various ways
with humanity throughout history and that part of the program is a
1,000-year political kingdom to be inaugurated at the Second
Coming.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Theological Seminary chancellor presents a
wide-ranging study of a system of thought that has made the
Antichrist, the millennium and the pretribulational Rapture (the
``snatching up'' of Christians before the terrible judgments of the
Great Tribulation) familiar to millions. Walvoord spends little
time on alternate interpretive schemes, although amillennialism _
which argues that the millennium is symbolic rather than literal _
comes in for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``End Times'' is a thorough presentation of thinking that has
become orthodoxy in many conservative religious circles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
