<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5669 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOUSSEVITZKY-MUSIC-2T     05-05 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOUSSEVITZKY-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BATTLER FOR THE NEW IN AMERICAN MUSIC  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when the New York Philharmonic celebrates George
Gershwin one season and Aaron Copland the next, it is easy to
forget that the groundbreaking music of American composers once
went unheard in concert halls.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such scores were ultimately absorbed into the canon
largely through the efforts of one man, Serge Koussevitzky, the
first major maestro to make ``modern'' American music a priority.
</P>
<P>
   A double-bass virtuoso born in Russia, Koussevitzky led the
Boston Symphony Orchestra from 1924 to 1949 and blazed a trail for
innovative American music by not only performing new scores but
also commissioning more.
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitzky was practically hard-wired to champion new music.
First in Moscow, then in Paris, he gave premieres of works by
Scriabin, Ravel, Honegger and others, and was an intimate of
Stravinsky, Prokofiev and the great pedagogue Nadia Boulanger.
</P>
<P>
   So it was hardly surprising that when he arrived in Boston, he
brought along a dedication to the cutting edge. The Athens of New
England was not Paris, however, and Koussevitzky had to battle the
entrenched conservatism of his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   He nevertheless remained unshakable in his allegiance to
Copland, Samuel Barber, Howard Hanson, Roy Harris, William Schuman,
Walter Piston and Randall Thompson, as well as to many lesser-known
composers. And that commitment lies at the heart of two new CDs
from the Biddulph and Dutton labels.
</P>
<P>
   Devoted entirely to American works, these reissues are
inspiriting reminders of Koussevitzky's determination to lift
American music to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   The Biddulph disk (WHL 050) is a gathering of Americana:
Copland's ``Appalachian Spring'' Suite, ``Lincoln Portrait'' and
``Salon Mexico,'' Thompson's ``Testament of Freedom'' and two
marches by John Philip Sousa. The recordings, originally issued by
RCA Victor between 1938 and 1946, have been impressively
transferred to CD by Mark Obert-Thorn.
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitzky and the Boston Symphony did not give the premiere
of the ``Appalachian Spring'' Suite, in which Copland
reorchestrated a ballet written for Martha Graham in 1944, but they
were the first to record it. This 1945 effort remains unsurpassed
for its sense of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been more polished recordings of the work
(Copland's own with the London Symphony Orchestra, for example, or
Leonard Bernstein's with the New York Philharmonic), yet no one has
captured the music's wide-eyed innocence and irrepressible
exuberance quite the way Koussevitzky and the Bostonians do.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Revival Meeting'' section, they build energy
incrementally, and when they shift from a lope to a gallop, the
listener can't help bouncing along.
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitzky and the Boston Symphony were also the first to
record ``Lincoln Portrait.'' The performance dates from 1946 and
features the actor Melvyn Douglas as narrator. If ever there was an
effective exercise in American musical chauvinism, this work is it.
With its overtly sentimental melodies, deeply hewn phrases and
spoken excerpts from the 16th president's best-known speeches, it
swells the heart like a ticker tape parade.
</P>
<P>
   In the right hands and voice _ Copland's and Henry Fonda's, or
Eugene Ormandy's and Adlai Stevenson's, for instance _ the work
asserts undeniable power. But Douglas, in thrall to a melodramatic
esthetic, is too histrionic for modern tastes. He draws out the
tenderer passages and wildly declaims such famous phrases as
``shall not perish from the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitzky and the musicians fare better, investing Copland's
score with unaffected grandeur if not utter conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The 1938 premiere recording of ``El Salon Mexico'' finds them on
surer ground. The work, written by Copland after a visit to Mexico
City in 1932, vibrates with south-of-the-border pizazz, emanating
in large part from the native folk tunes the composer integrated
into his score.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is Copland's brilliance as an orchestrator that
Koussevitzky and the Boston Symphony emphasize in their reading.
Never has the E flat clarinet in this work sounded more out of
kilter, or the trumpet more defiant.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Lincoln Portrait,'' Thompson's ``Testament of Freedom''
incorporates the words of a great president, in this case Thomas
Jefferson. But rather than leave the ennobling lines to a single
speaker, Thompson scored his work for chorus, originally
accompanied by piano. He later enriched the piece with an
orchestration, and in 1945 Koussevitzky and the Boston Symphony
joined the Harvard Glee Club to record it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative in conception, Thompson's ``Testament'' recalls a
Victorian oratorio overflowing with persuasive gravity. Despite the
orchestra's fine contribution, the college glee club earns the
laurels here, its enunciation crisp, its ardor palpable.
</P>
<P>
   The disk concludes with Sousa's ``Semper Fidelis'' and ``Stars
and Stripes Forever.'' Some may think it odd that the Boston
Symphony's high-minded music director would tackle such light fare,
but Koussevitzky clearly relishes the energy of these marches,
savoring in particular the clipped rhythms of ``The Stars and
Stripes Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutton disk (CDEA 5021) also opens with the ``Appalachian
Spring'' Suite, and Michael Dutton's transfer achieves even greater
color and clarity than the Biddulph remastering. Unfortunately,
Dutton did not see fit to break the suite down into the seven
tracks Biddulph does, so zeroing in on a favorite theme is
something of a bother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lincoln Portrait'' also appears, though unadvertised on the
outside the package. And once again, Dutton surpasses the efforts
of Obert-Thorn, providing a transfer of uncommon vividness.
</P>
<P>
   But Koussevitzky's 1940 premiere recording of Hanson's sweeping,
moody Symphony No. 3 is the real prize here. Though less familiar,
perhaps, than Hanson's First (``Nordic'') or Second (``Romantic'')
Symphony, the untitled Third, like its predecessors, possesses
gripping immediacy. Its breathless rises and falls are reminiscent
of the symphonies of Carl Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   First performed by the Boston Symphony under Hanson's direction
in 1938, the work is dedicated to Koussevitzky, who had
commissioned and led the premiere of the composer's Second
Symphony, which Koussevitzky never committed to disk. (So
significant was Hanson's debt to the conductor over time that he
wrote an ``Elegy in Memory of Serge Koussevitzky'' for the Boston
Symphony's 75th anniversary in 1956.)
</P>
<P>
   Hanson found inspiration for the Third Symphony in America's
Scandinavian pioneers, and the piece appropriately melds high drama
with religious intensity. It is, in many ways, a perfect musical
match for the Boston Symphony and Koussevitzky, who zealously
explore its sonorities. Only Hanson's own outstanding recording of
the work on Mercury Living Presence (paired, incidentally, with the
``Koussevitzky Elegy'') can compete with this vividly textured,
colorful interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitzky was not alone in championing new American music
even at the time, but he was in an ideal position to affect its
fortunes. By placing such pieces next to established masterworks in
the concert hall and later recording them, he secured recognition
for many important scores.
</P>
<P>
   That devotion is worth remembering whenever one encounters these
works, and both Biddulph and Dutton have offered the pleasantest of
reminders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
