<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I THANK GOD FOR THE PRIVILEGE OF PRAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, I kept an unopened bottle of fertility pills in a
drawer in my guest bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of my trying to get pregnant, followed by a
series of embarrassing tests, my husband and my obstetrician
decided I needed help to conceive.
</P>
<P>
   I refused to open the bottle. I was convinced that God didn't
need help, that he would answer my prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Even after I miscarried a year later, I stubbornly held on to my
hope. After trying for two more years, I had Jamila. Asha came
along a year later. But I still held on to that bottle of pills.
</P>
<P>
   They were a reminder that I could depend on God alone, and that
he would reward my faith. I know that trusting him is a huge leap
for some people, but I can no more imagine my life without him than
I can fathom life without the privilege of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   That is, after all, how I was born into the family of Jesus
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   One summer night _ afraid of the evil within and the evil
without _ I was moved to pray the sinners' prayer and ask Jesus to
come into my heart. I was no more than 10 or 12, so I did not know
fully what I was reacting to; I did understand that the wages of
sin were death and that Jesus provided the way to eternal life.
</P>
<P>
   I think back now to that night, to Springhill Freewill Baptist
Church, the swirling white ceiling fans circulating in the thick
July heat, the prayers rising and falling from a row of big black
women in white dresses.
</P>
<P>
   At that revival meeting, I knew I wanted to live forever. And
so, when the preacher was done preaching and announced that ``Jesus
stands at the door knocking,'' I wanted to let him into my life, to
be saved from death.
</P>
<P>
   If I ever prayed before then, I don't remember it. I do remember
the church members singing, ``Somebody prayed for me, had me on
their minds, took the time and prayed for me.''
</P>
<P>
   I always believed those lyrics, always believed that was what I
was supposed to do for others. And for me.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible says, ``He that cometh to God must believe that he is
and that he is a rewarder of them that diligently seek him.''
</P>
<P>
   Implied in the Scripture is that faith is required for prayer.
It doesn't do me any good to talk to God if I don't believe he
exists and is trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   When my faith fails, one sure way to regain it is through
prayer. I find that whether I'm on my knees or driving into work,
talking to God causes doubt to dry like dew in the warmth of his
promises.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall a time when he didn't answer my prayers. There
have been times, though, when I've had to wait for an answer. Other
times he has answered in the midst of my prayers, as if he were a
parent rushing to dry his child's tears.
</P>
<P>
   When my family and I first moved to Fort Worth, we lived in a
hotel while we waited for our house in California to sell. After
two months, I grieved that we had not found a buyer. I was days
away from giving birth to Asha, and the Star-Telegram's obligation
to pay for our hotel stay had long passed. One afternoon, I kneeled
and began praying.
</P>
<P>
   The moment I finished my talk with God and uttered ``Amen,'' the
phone rang. It was my Sacramento real estate agent calling to say
he had an offer, a very good offer, on our home. Thirty days later,
the deal was closed and we moved into our new home.
</P>
<P>
   I realize this may seem coincidental to some, but I count it
among the many prayers God has answered in my life.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, I admit I sometimes am tempted to try to help
God out, to rush ahead of him to get results. But when I can't do
anything more, when all other sources of help are exhausted, when I
finally move out of the way, that's when God moves.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the circumstances, when I ask God to do something for
me, he usually does something in me. Not only does he change my
circumstances, he changes my character. In prayer, my faith is
increased, and my resolve to live my life in accordance with his
word is strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   So often, instead of asking God for something, I pause to thank
him for all the things he has done and is doing for me and in me.
</P>
<P>
   There have been times in my life when my problems seemed so big,
all I could do was sit still and tell God I was hurting. In those
times, I rely on Christ to intercede for me.
</P>
<P>
   I believe God knows and loves me just that much.
</P>
<P>
   Romans 8:15 says, ``We should not be like cringing, fearful
slaves, but we should behave like God's very own children, adopted
into the bosom of his family.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm an heir and co-heir with Christ. I'm special. More than the
lilies of the fields, more than the birds in the air. Whatever I
need, I can rest assured he will provide it.
</P>
<P>
   All I have to do is ask.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
