<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, May 6. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
VICKERS-EXECUTION (Florence, Ariz.) - Robert Wayne ``Bonzai Bob''
Vickers, Arizona's longest-serving death-row inmate, was executed
by injection Wednesday for killing a fellow prisoner in 1982. He
got his nickname after he killed another prisoner in 1979 and
misspelled the Japanese war cry when he carved ``Bonzai'' in the
corpse's back with a sharpened toothbrush. By MARK SHAFFER. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GARFUNKEL-MUSIC (Phoenix) - Speaking with Art Garfunkel, the
unspoken question hangs in the air, creating an odd bit of tension.
It's a bit like having a conversation with O.J. Simpson and dancing
around the subject of Ronald Goldman. Or speaking with Bill Clinton
but politely avoiding any references to a certain beret-wearing
brunette. With Garfunkel, possessor of one of the most virginal
voices in pop music, the million-dollar question has to be, Why the
heck is Paul Simon so amazingly famous and his former singing
partner is . . . well, not? By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
correspondent ANNE STEPHENSON, Special to the Republic. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - I need my space, and not in a
metaphorical sense. I want, at all times, to be able to thrust my
arms outward, twirl and not touch a single thing, because that's my
space and it belongs to ME. If people insist on breaching that
respect, I can't help it; I'll just want to fight them, most
preferably in a parking lot. One careless step from a stranger into
my twirling circle, and it's all fists and elbows. By LAURI NOTARO.
Story moved in the ``L`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-JACKSON (Phoenix) - The dilemma that the Rev. Jesse Jackson
now creates for President Clinton and his NATO allies is that his
mission will succeed entirely _ that it will help end the bombing
and bring parties to the negotiating table. If that occurs,
Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic wins, since bombs will have
ceased dropping on Serbia while hundreds of thousands of Kosovars
languish in the muck and mire as refugees. Who will go, then, to
rescue them? Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TUNDRA-AUTO (Wickenburg, Ariz.) - Leaning on a tailgate, the three
cowboys were talking pickup trucks. Full-size pickup trucks.
Uniquely American. Big as the land.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, they'd be discussing the merits of Chevys and Fords,
maybe a Dodge. But here they were checking out a newcomer,
something they'd never seen before. It was a full-size pickup
truck, all right, but it was built by Japanese automaker Toyota.
The cowboys seemed unsure how to judge the interloper, until one of
them, C.W. Williams, piped up. ``Let's give it the hat test,'' he
said. With PHOTO. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CD SPINS-MUSIC (Phoenix) - Reviews of the newest music by the
Arizona Republic staff. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
STAR WARS-BOOK (Phoenix) - What if someone got lost in space 25
years ago and had never heard of ``Star Wars?'' We asked reporter
Scott Craven to look at the novelized version of ``Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace'' as though he'd never heard of the thing. Does it
hold up as a book? Would it make a decent movie? By SCOTT CRAVEN.
Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
