<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELFLESS-MOM:MAXWELL-     05-05 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELFLESS-MOM:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN TERRIBLE ADVERSITY, MOTHER'S DEVOTION WAS CONSTANT
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By BILL MAXWELL 
 &HT;    (Bill Maxwell, African American, is an editorial writer and
columnist for the St. Petersburg Times in St. Petersburg, Fla. He
can be reached on the Internet at maxwell(at) sptimes.com) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When my father died a few days ago, my mother demonstrated why
so many people admire her and why a day is set aside to honor the
nation's mothers.
 &HT;    My parents separated when I was in elementary school. My father,
a hard-working, hard-drinking, womanizing farm laborer, routinely
beat my mother in front of my siblings and me. Each time, she would
pick herself up, mend her wounds and resume her duties as our
mother _ cooking, cleaning the house, seeing us off to school,
going to the fields where she labored all day in Florida's hot sun.
 &HT;    As far as I know, my father never paid child support. My mother
rarely complained and never went to the authorities. For her part,
in addition to picking vegetables, she worked as a maid in Fort
Lauderdale's hotels and motels. When money was really tight, which
was often the case, she and a group of friends would sell fried
fish and ribs in someone's front yard.
 &HT;    Even when we were young, my siblings and I marveled at how she
could make ends meet _ how she could take $20 and stretch it, feed
six hungry kids _ four of them strapping boys _ with a pound of
neckbones, a bag of rice and a pitcher of Kool Aid, get by without
ever learning to drive, find decent children's clothes in
second-hand stores.
 &HT;    Occasionally, my father would show up and my mother would take
him in. Each time, however, the abuse would start. Many of my
mother's friends urged her to call the police and have him
arrested. She never did.
 &HT;    One time, after my father went to work, my mother packed our
clothes and called a taxi that took us to the bus station. We left
Fort Lauderdale, traveling six hours to Groveland, near Orlando,
where my mother's parents lived.
 &HT;    We stayed there for three months, long enough for my father to
realize that we were not returning as long as he was in the house.
He came to Groveland to talk my mother into coming back to him, but
my grandparents chased him away, threatening to notify the police
if he came near us.
 &HT;    When we returned to Fort Lauderdale, my father did not show up
for about six months. This time, however, he was different somehow.
He did not have his usual anger and swagger. He was ill and my
mother sympathized with him. Again, she took him in and nursed him
back to health.
 &HT;    One morning I overheard them talking. He apologized for his
behavior and promised to be a different person. She kissed him and
told him that she forgave him. She said, though, that she no longer
loved him and did not want to live with him.
 &HT;    ``I have my children to think of,'' she said. ``I've got to take
care of them.''
 &HT;    I will never forget those words. For me, they made my mother
bigger than life, a selfless survivor who assumed her
responsbilities without complaints. Her strength of character
permanently changed my father. She would let him visit us as often
as he wished, and, although he did not pay child support, he began
to bring presents and food. Most important, he never hit my mother
again.
 &HT;    She never spoke negatively of him in our presence, except to say
that he had the world's worst toe jam. On his birthdays, she
encouraged us to send him a card. We never had enough money to buy
anything else.
 &HT;    ``No matter what your father did to me, he is still your
father,'' she would say, if one of us reminded her that he had
yelled at her and beat her.
 &HT;    I would look at her, admiring her clarity of purpose, her
generosity and her capacity to forgive.
 &HT;    When I telephoned and told her that my father had died, she
asked, ``Are you all right, boy? I know you loved him.''
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, she was comforting me.
 &HT;    ``I wish I could have been closer to him,'' I said. ``How do you
feel?''
 &HT;    She paused for a long time. Then, she said, ``He did some bad
things to us, but he asked me to forgive him a long time ago. And I
did. I don't have any hard feelings toward him. I'll see you at the
funeral, son.''
 &HT;    I understood at that moment that, although my mother is a simple
woman on one level, she possesses the inner complexity of one who
has led a moral life, one who has quietly contemplated her place in
the world and has accepted her fate and that of others.
 &HT;    I can think of no better reasons to love her and honor her on
Mother's Day.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Bill Maxwell 
