and yearning for her presence.
 &HT;    After making the 70-minute drive to the south Florida cemetery,
I sit by her graveside and talk to her as if she were right there.
I keep her apprised of what is happening in our world.
 &HT;    I tell her of the latest events concerning our family and
friends. I keep her up to date on international news, and because
she was a Weather Channel junkie I give her the day's weather
forecast and hurricane warnings for Florida where she and my dad
had lived for a dozen years.
 &HT;    I tell her about the mice in my kitchen walls and the garden
snake that occasionally visits my bathroom. I tell her I still
can't cook. I keep her up-to-date on my career _ one that she
encouraged since the day I left her womb.
 &HT;    Now, I will let her know that Dan Quayle from our hometown in
Indiana is back on the campaign trail.
 &HT;    But most important, I remind her that she was the most wonderful
person on earth, and how badly I miss her.
 &HT;    Mother's Day, for the eighth time, will be a sad one for me.
Doubly sad, because my father died last year _ on Mother's Day.
 &HT;    I still choke back tears when I visit her grave. These visits,
though, seem to help with my everlasting grief: feeling cleansed
and close to her, I hope she knows that she is not alone.
 &HT;    There are those who insist that time cures all pain of losing
loved ones. And that holidays like Mother's Day are easier to bear
as years go by. But Mother's Day just heightens my feeling of
emptiness and loss.
 &HT;    Why? Because I can't lionize and applaud my mother. I can't take
her out to dinner. I can't join in friends' conversations about
what to do or where to go on Mother's Day. Even worse, I have to
listen to those who complain that they are too busy to try and
``take mom out for a meal.''
 &HT;    But not everyone could have a mother like mine.
 &HT;    My parents put the wants and needs of their children above their
own in every way imaginable. They lived for each other and for
their children. Everything else was second place. And so, the
memories of my mother continue to be difficult for me on this
holiday.
 &HT;    With both of my parents buried together, the tableau has become
even more troubling. I begin wondering, too, why so many bad people
live long lives and good ones like my mom and dad were taken too
soon.
 &HT;    It's painful to read the advertisements for Mother's Day gifts,
Sunday brunches and loving greeting cards. It depresses me to watch
television commercials promoting everything special about Mom.
 &HT;    To know I can never again feel the excitement and elation over
sharing something good with her hurts as much today as it did when
she died eight years ago. I miss her flashes of wisdom as she
helped me solve life's ``insurmountable'' problems.
 &HT;    My beautiful mother knew many things. She was both an
intellectual and woman of common sense. She loved to read and
learn, sharing tales and quotes and missives with her family and
friends. And she was never too busy to answer our questions or help
us make decisions.
 &HT;    In all of my recollections of Mother, the most endearing quality
was her unselfishness. As an only child who was doted upon by her
parents, she could easily have grown up to be self-absorbed and
self-centered. But she didn't.
 &HT;    Instead, she was the most sensible, caring, funny, warm and
wonderful woman who is missed more than she could ever imagine. I
remember, wryly, how she used to tease us by saying, ``You'll all
forget me when I'm dead and gone.''
 &HT;    How wrong she was, I tell her repeatedly at her graveside.
 &HT;    On this Mother's Day, as every day, Gloria Bookstaff Marx
remains in my heart as the most important person in my life.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Linda Marx 
<TEXT>
