<HEADLINE>
SAN DIEGO MOTHERS GET TWO MOTHER'S DAYS!
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SAN DIEGO _ Mother's Day along the U.S.-Mexico border is an
adventure anytime.
 &HT;    For immigration from Mexico has brought us new trends, one of
which is Mexican Mother's Day, celebrated on May 10. As a result,
flower vendors have popped up all over neighborhoods in San Diego
that have large Mexican populations. And the two Mother's Days are
merging more and more.
 &HT;    In Mexico, when Mother's Day falls on a business day, offices
are empty of people spending time with their mothers, usually at
dinners. That doesn't happen here, of course, because it always
falls on a Sunday. So brunch is the order of the day in America.
 &HT;    This year, though, mothers here on the border can have brunch
this Sunday AND dinner on Monday. The flower sellers on the streets
will double their business. We sons and daughters can relieve our
mother-induced guilt trips (as only we Catholics and our Jewish
cousins have) by treating our mothers with love and respect on this
special day, the day to honor all mothers.
 &HT;    One time, years ago _ when I worked at the Tijuana racetrack in
Mexico _ to honor my mother I ordered the track florist to deliver
100-dozen red roses to my younger brother 7:00 a.m. at the border.
There was no duty to be paid as the roses were U.S. produced to
begin with, so Customs simply looked at the papers and wondered who
the lucky mother might be.
 &HT;    At home in San Diego, my other two brothers were busy preparing
for our mother a breakfast fit for a queen _ and making sure she
stayed in bed while the roses were dashing up the freeway.
 &HT;    When the roses arrived, the boys placed them in containers
throughout the house. I might tell you that 1,200 roses are a lot
of roses. Certainly, I heard about how many they were later.
 &HT;    Eventually, Mother arose, wondering why I hadn't called from the
track to wish her a happy Mother's Day. I was wondering why she
hadn't called me, but she hadn't seen the roses yet, for we
deliberately spread them around the living room, the dining room,
and the den and, of all places, the kitchen. The kitchen? Well, the
kitchen is a special place in Mexican homes.
 &HT;    The trans-border call eventually came to my phone at the track,
of course. Mother was happy, my brothers were happy and that all
made me happy. The track florist was pretty happy, too.
 &HT;    Not many honor their mothers with a thousand-plus roses and
breakfast in bed, but they do honor their mothers in many other
ways, in many places. However, no matter how they honor their
mothers, it never seems to be enough.
 &HT;    Surely, every day is Mother's Day. All you have to do is watch
some toddler holding on to its mother's hands in a store, or in the
park. Watch the child look at his mother when he asks her a
question. Watch the mother. I do, all the time, and marvel at the
interaction of mother and child. Did I, I wonder, hang on to my
mother's every word and her hand like I see other children do? Did
I cry for my mother when I was hurt? Of course. Didn't you?
 &HT;    We are lucky here this year to have Mother's Day on Sunday and
Mexican Mother's Day on Monday. But for some of us Mother is
honored every day.
 &HT;    She still deserves more.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
