discovered that an education ``could take you to places you had not
yet dreamed.''
 &HT;    She later attended high school in a nearby town. After her
junior year, her family sold the farm and moved to Madison, Wis.
She tried hard at her new school, earning the highest average in
the senior class.
 &HT;    She wasn't named valedictorian, as she'd been enrolled for only
a year. Still, she was allowed to give the ``senior farewell.''
 &HT;    Living at home during college, she typed graduate theses to pay
for tuition.
 &HT;    The dean of women called her in one day and gave her a knotted
handkerchief containing a mound of coins. A cleaning woman, saving
the money for her daughter's education, had turned it over to the
university after the girl died.
 &HT;    ``Give it to someone who needs it,'' the woman had said.
 &HT;    Nothing deterred Mother from her goal _ not even a proposal from
a doctor, eight years her senior, who wanted to ``take her away
from all this.''
 &HT;    ``I will marry you,'' she told him that September, ``but only
after I graduate in June.''
 &HT;    The day after she received her degree, the ``simple ceremony''
took place.
 &HT;    ``While in school,'' the newspaper said, ``the bride was a
member of the Wisconsin Players and took important roles in
university dramatic productions. She also is a member of National
Collegiate Players.''
 &HT;    After rearing four children and serving her community, Mom
taught drama for 15 years.
 &HT;    ``Since 1958,'' a former student, now a college professor,
recently wrote, ``you have guided my theater views from suggesting
plays to read, productions to work on, to the insight that theater
is constantly changing and should never be locked into one
stereotype. My (higher) education you gave me _ for so many other
students were less prepared and certainly less read than I _ was
all because of you.''
 &HT;    These days, at times, Mother cannot recall the beloved student's
name _ or even who I am.
 &HT;    Back home for her birthday, I took a walk with my brother and
sister.
 &HT;    ``There's Chris with two women,'' she told my husband, watching
out the window. ``I don't know who they are. And I don't ask.''
 &HT;    Alzheimer's disease takes her to places she never dreamed,
locking her into a new role. Each day resembles a ``farewell
speech'' as parts of her memory, parts of her life, fade forever.
 &HT;    Even we, her family, cannot say when or how the illness started.
 &HT;    We had signs, to be sure: her increasingly repeating ``I don't
know; I can't remember; I forget'' said as one sentence _ or her
driving a well-known route and suddenly becoming disoriented and
lost.
 &HT;    Did six years spent caring for a stroke victim defeat her? Or
the stress of her cancer? Or the fire that swept through the house?
What sweeps through Mom destroys her connections. Her diploma can
be reordered, but not her mind.
 &HT;    When memory goes, do we become a stranger not only to other
people but also to ourselves?
 &HT;    ``Get all the education you can,'' Mother (like her father
before her) always said. ``It's the one thing people can't take
away from you.''
 &HT;    Yet Alzheimer's can.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Kirsten Chapman 
<TEXT>
