<HEADER>
A5706 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OTHER-MOTHERS:MONIFA-     05-05 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTHER-MOTHERS:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN A BIOLOGICAL MOTHER
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer living
in Oakland, Calif., and a contributor to the forthcoming book
``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories and Practices.''
(1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mother. What is she? Who is she?
 &HT;    The flower industry sells more flowers on Mother's Day than on
any other single day or holiday. And an estimated 65 percent of
Americans will purchase a present for their mothers to celebrate
the occasion.
 &HT;    The card and flower industries have helped us see that mothers
are also grandmothers, mothers-in-law, mother figures, play
mothers, adoptive mothers, and may not even be limited to the
female gender.
 &HT;    Sports figures and anyone else who find themselves on television
invariably utter a ``Hi, Mom.'' People thank their mothers
publically more frequently than their fathers when receiving
awards. Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers talks to his mother
on the telephone prior to every game. It's definitely a
superstition with him.
 &HT;    Mother's Day became an official celebration in the United States
in 1914 while Father's Day wasn't recognized as a national holiday
until 1972. Then there is Mother Earth, Mother Nature, lots of
mothers.
 &HT;    Of course there are mother issues in general and there is still
controversy about who is a mother. Like, is the adoptive mother
your mother or is that reserved for your birth mother? What about
mother figures or ``play mothers.'' Surrogate mothers? What of
women who donate their eggs to other women who have fertility
problems? And what of the women who give birth using donor eggs not
their own?
 &HT;    Do you assume that a single woman with a child is the child's
mother? And what do you think when there are two women with a
child? Is it obvious that they are a couple, co-parents,
co-mothers? A stranger stops the couple and comments on how cute
the child is and inquires who the mother is. ``We both are'' is the
reply. ``No, who is the real mother?'' comes the next question.
 &HT;    Is motherhood really only linked to DNA, genes, conception,
fertility and birth? Or is it nurturing, parenting, caring, and
rearing a child?
 &HT;    I have not spoken with my biological mother in nearly a decade.
But there is a woman with whom I am not biologically linked who I
have known for 13 years. I call her Mom, and she refers to me
either as ``luvey'' or ``my darling daughter.'' At a time when I
was searching for a mother to fill an emotional need, this woman
was real, and we developed a healthy mother-daughter relationship.
I feel love and connection to her and believe she possesses more
maternal instincts than any woman I have encountered.
 &HT;    So on this Mother's Day maybe we can all reflect on what it is
to be a mother, who owns that label in your life and what that
person means to you on the other 364 days of the year beyond
Mother's Day.
 &HT;    The times they are a-changing and mothering and being a mother
ain't what it used to be.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
