<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-MOTHERS-DAY-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBORAH WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVEN IN TERRIBLE ADVERSITY, MOTHER'S DEVOTION WAS CONSTANT. One
morning, columnist Bill Maxwell overheard his parents talking. His
father, a violent and abusive man, was apologizing for his behavior
and promising to be a different person. His mother said that she
forgave him but that she could no longer live with him, adding: ``I
have my children to think of. I've got to take care of them,''
recalls Maxwell. ``I will never forget those words,'' he writes.
``For me, they made my mother bigger than life, a selfless survivor
who assumed her responsbilities without complaints. I can think of
no better reasons to love her and honor her on Mother's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SELFLESS-MOM:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   ALZHEIMER'S: THE THIEF OF LOVE. Columnist Kirsten Chapman's
mother battles Alzheimer's disease, and now, at times, does not
always recognize her daughters. ``Each day resembles a `farewell
speech,' as parts of her memory, parts of her life, fade forever,''
Chapman writes. Her mother used to tell her: ``Get all the
education you can. It's the one thing people can't take away from
you.'' But sadly, for her mother, Alzheimer's is doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SLOWLY-LOSING-MOM:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO MOTHERS GET TWO MOTHER'S DAYS! Immigration from Mexico
has brought new trends, such as Mexican Mother's Day on May 10. So,
flower vendors now have popped up all over Mexican neighborhoods in
San Diego. And the two Mother's Days are merging more and more,
observes columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. In Mexico, when Mother's
Day falls on a business day, offices are empty of people spending
time with their mothers over lunch or dinner, he notes. ``That
doesn't happen here, of course, because it always falls on a
Sunday. So brunch is the order of the day in America,'' he writes.
But this year, mothers on the the border can have brunch this
Sunday AND dinner on Monday, he reports happily.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-MEXICAN-MOTHER'S-DAY:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBERING AND MISSING MOM. This Mother's Day columnist Linda
Marx will celebrate as she has done for the last eight years:
visiting her mother's grave. ``I sit by her graveside and talk to
her as if she were right there,'' she confesses. She keeps her mom
apprised of what is happening in the world and of the latest events
concerning family and friends. She keeps her up to date on
international news, and because she was a Weather Channel junkie
she gives her the day's weather forecast and hurricane warnings for
Florida where she and her father had lived for a dozen years. ``But
most important,'' Marx writes, ``I remind her that she was the most
wonderful person on earth, and how badly I miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-MISSING-MOM:MARX-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN A BIOLOGICAL MOTHER. The flower industry sells more
