A5721 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NUDITY AND ENERGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One hundred fifty peaceful exhibitionists assembled
at 6 a.m. in Manhattan's Times Square recently, stripped off all
their clothes and together posed in the altogether for the
photographer Spencer Tunick.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could get the shot of massed nudes, the lubricious
lensman was arrested for ``tumultuous and violent conduct.'' The
D.A. has charged Tunick with ``promoting the exposure of a
person.'' (What kind of crime is that? I try to do that in this
space twice a week.) We libertarians view this bluenosed
 &QC; suppression of artistic expression as a foolish waste of the
police's time.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, at almost the same moment, a crowd of more
than 15,000 middle-aged Chinese of the Fulan Gong sect assembled in
front of the compound housing China's leadership. Fully clothed,
they sat silently on the sidewalk in yoga's lotus position for 13
hours, in deep concentration.
</P>
<P>
   They thereby threw a scare into the Chinese Communist government
the likes of which has not been felt since the demonstration at
Tiananmen Square 10 years ago on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's demonstration was not political. No signs were
raised, no slogans shouted, no replicas of the Statue of Liberty
held aloft that triggered a massacre. These are practitioners of
qigong (pronounced chee-goong), both a martial art and a method of
breathing and meditation that directs energy to improve health and
spiritual awareness. Though an offshoot of Buddhism and denounced
by the government-run qi establishment, it avoids condemnation as a
cult by claiming not to be a religion.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji rolled out no tanks. He
listened to a delegation's complaint about harassment by
officialdom, and offered them bus rides home. The crowd dispersed,
having made its point. The official newspapers are now warning the
Fulan Gong not to try that surprising stunt again.
</P>
<P>
   This can be dismissed as a cult promoted by Li Hongzhi, a
Chinese forced out of China and now in New York. Reported to
believe in alien beings and levitation _ and selling TV cassettes
of his outlook on his Web site _ Li's 5,000-year-old symbol of
yin-yang means ``all is well'' but looks a lot like a swastika.
Tibetan and Chinese friends tell me that by a Buddhist, he's no
Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he's selling scary superstition or uplifting
spirituality _ or the brain-body interaction that Western
scientists no longer pooh-pooh _ between 40 and 70 million people
are buying. The movement has about as many members in China as the
Communist Party and is growing much faster. Beijing has not cracked
down because it fears turning the energy of qi on itself by making
martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu has reason to worry. Communism is producing political
suppression while its capitalist road requires economic
belt-tightening and its social policy limits families to one child.
With 200 million unemployed or underemployed making up 25 percent
of the work force, China may be yearning for a movement offering a
happier, healthier, freer life.
</P>
<P>
   That's what troubles the Forbidden City. ``They remember the
Boxer Rebellion,'' says Columbia University Prof. Robert Thurman,
``a popular movement to purify the corruption of the Manchus. Any
nationwide reawakening of spirituality is seen as a threat to
central control. They feel threatened by any organized movement,
but how do you handle a nonviolent, transcendental ideology that
seems so innocuous?''
</P>
<P>
   In good times, Communism and Confucianism, with their common
respect for authority, can easily co-exist. But when a sense of
impermanence takes hold, and the mandate of Heaven comes into
doubt, all in authority sense the danger of spiritual revival. Most
sects die aborning, but a few, strengthened by repression, mushroom
into a major challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Advice to Zhu: Ease up. Don't turn a shrewd salesman into a
mythic hero. Neither your stolen nuclear secrets nor your boughten
supercomputers can smother an internal brush fire begun in
spirituality and selflessness and ignited by outrage.
</P>
<P>
   On a different order of magnitude, advice to the NYPD and the
Manhattan DA: Lighten up. If they're not blocking traffic and do
nothing more violent than smiling at a camera, let the nudies shape
themselves into a message and pose. Good for tourism, better for
art, best for liberty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APACHE-PROBLEMS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHE-PROBLEMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNERS FOR THE APACHE HELICOPTERS SAYS KOSOVO ISN'T IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the Army's Apache
helicopters were technological stars that used a potent arsenal of
missiles, rockets and cannons to destroy hundreds of Iraqi tanks
with speed and precision.
</P>
<P>
   But the gunships have gotten off to an inauspicious start in the
Kosovo conflict. Two of the attack helicopters have crashed and two
crew members have been killed since 24 of the choppers arrived at a
base in Albania near the Kosovo border. None of the sleek craft has
been sent into action and both crashes involved training missions.
</P>
<P>
   NATO commanders had to wait more than three weeks for the
Apaches _ designed to fight in bad weather and at night _ to arrive
from bases in Germany. The delay was partially attributed to the
Army's insistence that it have a force of 5,000 support troops to
protect and maintain the helicopters at the base.
</P>
<P>
   Though the war against Yugoslavia is well into its second month
and the ethnic cleansing of Kosovar Albanians continues apace, the
Apache gunships haven't been sent into action yet.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the high-tech helicopters were used in the Gulf War
on the first night of Operation Desert Storm to destroy Iraqi air
defenses. The Pentagon credited the Apaches ``with destroying
numerous tanks, trucks and armored vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials and military experts say there are several
reasons why the aircraft have been on the sidelines thus far in the
Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   First, the mountainous Balkan terrain is far more dangerous for
Apache pilots than the deserts of Iraq, a fact brought home by the
first of the training accidents in which the low-flying aircraft
may have crashed after hitting a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Desert Storm. We are talking a different terrain.
We are talking a different situation,'' German Maj. Gen. Walter
Jertz, a senior NATO official, said Wednesday. Jertz added that the
Apache crews needed to become more familiar with the region's
topography before going on combat missions.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz said NATO's maps for the area were poor, a potential
danger for Apaches that can fly just a few feet off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. Edward Atkeson, a senior fellow at the
Institute of Land Warfare in Arlington, Va., a think-tank
specializing in Army issues, said Iraq ``is flat like a billiard
table. It's the simplest flying you could have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is one of the most difficult terrains you could fly
over. It has woods. It has mountains jutting up. It's dangerous,''
Atkeson said.
</P>
<P>
   The dangers of the terrain are prompting the Army to rigorously
train the Apache crews sent to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's crash came during night training in rugged
northeastern Albania. Initial reports indicated that the aircraft
may have struck power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger much greater in the skies over Kosovo than over
Iraq is the threat from shoulder-fired missiles. The Pentagon
estimated that Yugoslav forces have hundreds of these hard-to-find
weapons, while Iraq had few.
</P>
<P>
   Because they fly low to the ground, the Apaches are more
vulnerable to these weapons than are high-flying jets.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Armitage, a former assistant secretary of defense, said
the shoulder missiles are giving NATO commanders considerable
pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the Apaches increase the probability of killing enemy
tanks and troops, they also increase the likelihood that we will
sustain combat casualties because they fly low and slow,'' Armitage
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another major difference is that U.S. combat troops were never
far away in the Gulf War from an Apache and could be called on to
track down or suppress enemy forces. Over Kosovo, the Apaches would
be on their own, with some help from NATO artillery.
</P>
<P>
   That worries Army planners, according to a military aviation
expert who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take attack helicopters into a place where you don't
have some control of the ground,'' the officer said. ``When you
don't have control, you invite the kind of failure that the Soviets
had in Afghanistan with massive losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a defense analyst at the Brookings
Institution, a non-partisan think tank, echoed those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in Iraq was use the Apaches in many instances to
attack targets whose locations we knew in advance. In Kosovo, we
are asking the Apaches to go out and find a lot of the targets.
That's a lot more dangerous where there's little or no ground
support providing protection,'' O'Hanlon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
