<HEADLINE>
UGLY WINS FOR BRUINS AGAINST SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Bruins are out to prove that very ugly really is
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   For example, back on Feb. 4, 1998, at Marine Midland Arena in
Buffalo, N.Y., it was 15 minutes 51 seconds into the third period
when Dmitri Khristich blasted a shot from the left circle that
deflected into the air, caromed off the head of goalie Dominik
Hasek, and went into the net.
</P>
<P>
   It was strange and it was certainly ugly. But most important, it
counted. That goal, which gave the Bruins a 2-1 lead in a game that
ended in a 2-2 tie, is exactly the type of unorthodox offense the
team is going to have to generate if it is going to beat the
Buffalo Sabres and Hasek when the Eastern Conference semifinal
series opens Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Steve Heinze led the Bruins in scoring against the
Sabres this season with three points (two goals) in five games.
Only one goal came against Hasek. He said the key to beating Hasek
sounds simple enough. It's just not that easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, shoot, and shoot again,'' said Heinze. ``You have to
crash the net. You know he's going to save most first shots. If he
sees it, he's going to save it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no textbook way to beat Hasek. He's not a standup
goalie, a butterfly goalie, or any other version of a style that's
remotely describable. If you ask players how to beat him, the
question is met with shrugs, puzzled looks, and furrowed brows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew,'' said Heinze. ``I don't think anybody really
knows. He is unconventional. You can't really figure him. He just
gets the job done and that's why it's so hard to beat him because
he's doing different things. He's saving it with all different
parts of his body. Sometimes he leaves his stick behind and he's
diving at things. But he saves them and that's why it's so tough to
figure him.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other Bruin with two goals against the Sabres this
season, both against Hasek, is defenseman Hal Gill. Gill, who had
three goals all year, laughed at the notion that he might have the
secret as to how Hasek can be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals are just proof that fluke goals go in on him,'' said
Gill. ``One goal I had came when I turned in and took a quick shot.
It kind of squeaked through his legs. That overtime goal (April 17
in a 2-1 victory) was a shot that knuckled and went through a crowd
and went in. I don't think you're going to get good goals on him. I
remember Dmitri's goal last year, the one that went off the back of
Hasek's head. That's the way you have to score.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Hasek's key assets is his ability to psych out his
opponents, to make shooters so nervous about his impenetrability
that they fire the puck over the net, wide of the net, or worse,
pass up the shot altogether in search of a better play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys and teams get so uptight and worried about how they have
to beat him that they think too much,'' said defenseman Dave
Ellett. ``When we get good shots, we've got to take them. He has a
little bit of an edge because he's played so good. Guys, when they
get good chances, instead of maybe doing what they would do
naturally right away, they outthink themselves and change their
minds and that gives the goaltender an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to make a move, make a move. Don't change your
mind three different ways. He's got no rhyme or reason to his
style, it's so unique. A lot of times, that's in the back of guys'
heads. They think they have to make a perfect shot or a perfect
play to beat him. It's tough to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true. Perfectly ugly is just as acceptable and possibly
even preferable in a series like this. It's also important to not
be insecure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be confident that you can score goals,'' said
Heinze. ``The equation here has always been to get the puck to the
net and crash the net. That's what we're going to have to do with
him or any goalie in the playoffs. If you look around the league at
the goals that are being scored, there are a few tic-tac-toe goals
like with Pittsburgh but the rest of them are throw them at the
net, get guys there, get guys crashing and in the crease, all that
stuff. That's how you're going to beat anybody, especially Dominik
Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were 1-4-0 against the Sabres this season but coach
Pat Burns said, in essence, ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at that now,'' said Burns. ``That has no
bearing on it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Bruins go into the game with respect for the Sabres and
respect for Hasek. But they also enter the series with a lot of
self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasek's a good goalie but people have scored on him,'' said
Gill. ``I've scored on him. That pretty much says it. He's a clutch
goalie but we've got Byron Dafoe in net and he can come up just as
big. So we're even.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
