<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DRAW A LINE ON THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Let's see, we've got the battle of the goalies, the
pox that is Michael Peca (all scourges should be so productive),
and, sure, the eternal postseason question: who will win the battle
of the special teams?
</P>
<P>
   All that aside, let's get to the true crux of it: the
Bruins-Sabres Eastern Conference semifinal series, to open
Thursday, will turn on what kind of performance the Bruins get out
of their No. 1 trio of Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov, and Dmitri
Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   As great as Dominik Hasek is, Byron Dafoe can match him nearly
save for save. Peca can't check two lines at the same time (keep
repeating that until you believe it). And don't expect either squad
to make much of a statement with the power play, which will have a
lot to do with Hasek and Dafoe and the general defensive makeup of
both sides. Both sides will grind this series into grist with the
penalty killing.
</P>
<P>
   So, are the Bruins about to advance to the Stanley Cup
semifinals for the first time since 1992? To do so, they'll need
far more out of the Allison-Samsonov-Khristich line than they got
in their first-round triumph over the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Most critical of all, Khristich has to show up with jump in his
legs and muscle in his shot. He totaled only one shot in the first
three games against Carolina, his game completely out of synch,
especially in Game 1 when he had fill-in Randy Robitaille as his
center. Rather than bench him after three games, coach Pat Burns
kept Khristich in the game, reuniting him with Allison and
Samsonov. Khristich improved, which is to say he wasn't invisible.
He was better, but he wasn't close to being an impact player.
Khristich and Cameron Mann were the last to leave the ice here
Wednesday, both taking extra time to tune up their shots.
</P>
<P>
   Against Carolina, Samsonov scored a pair of goals, and one of
those came off an easy pot at the end of a dazzling rush by Landon
Wilson in Game 2. The second-year Russian winger is an electrifying
skater and stickhandler, but he still has a lot to learn when it
comes to using his linemates. A little more give-and-go in his game
would confuse defenses and open up some room for his one-on-one
dances. Right now he is flashy, but predictable, and predictable
leads to some maddening turnovers and not much else. No one wants
him to be a north-south winger, but he must find more options when
he has the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, hurting with a sore wrist, might have potted a handful
of goals with a little more touch around the net. He finished with
none. He did, however, total six assists and tied Ray Bourque
(1-5_6) for most points in the series. He remains a force when he
isn't putting the puck in the net, and his reward for that,
undoubtedly, will be a constant barrage of Peca's stinging hits.
The Bruins can't afford to see Allison shut out again in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   When the three are at their most effective, they force the puck
deep in the offensive end and keep possession. Either Allison or
Khristich can use their size and strength in the corners. Samsonov,
though lacking in size, is strong enough to work the puck deep,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all three of us, wanting to do it,'' said Allison. ``It's
the three of us having the will to do it. That can break down,
though, if, say, I stay out too long, or Deemer (Khristich) tries
to make a pass that isn't there, or if Sammy loses control of the
puck. But I think all three of us can do a good job in there. I
mean, you give Sammy time and he's tough to check _ he's strong and
he's moving in five different directions at 100 miles an hour. He's
stronger than you think down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Without that kind of containment, without that determination to
keep cycling the puck, the No. 1 Boston line essentially rubs
itself off the scoresheet. In fact, the scoring then is left to the
1A line of Joe Thornton between Steve Heinze and Anson Carter. If
Thornton's line can maintain its momentum out of the Carolina
series, then Peca might be switched away from the Allison trio,
opening up more room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a good dilemma for us,'' said Heinze. ``Usually
you see the checking line up against your finesse line, facing the
great one-on-one players like (Wayne) Gretzky and (Mario) Lemieux.
Peca can get under your skin a bit, and the history between these
two clubs has been that he's usually on our finesse guys _ Ally,
Deemer, and Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   Home ice will help, or should help. Burns has the home-ice edge
in Games 1 and 2 to buy the Allison line some room. He gets the
last match. Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff undoubtedly will counter with
some quick line changes, forcing Peca onto Allison. The two benches
could look like stretch jack-in-the-boxes for the first couple of
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not discouraged, by any means,'' said Allison, reflecting
on the fact that he didn't score in the opening series. ``If you
aren't getting any chances, then you worry. But, I hit a post . . .
a couple of others, the puck wouldn't get down for me. I was making
the right decisions. I was placing the puck, or trying to put it
where I thought was a good spot, it just wasn't going there. Sure,
it would have been nice to score a goal, but I got an assist per
game. I'd call that a good slump, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The days ahead are sure to bring a lot more talk, from both
sides, about oportunities lost and shots to open holes that were
quickly closed. When Hasek and Dafoe are at their best, we may need
a U.N. interpreter to translate the one-way mutterings among the
forwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins showed in Round 1 that they can win with something
less than their best. This time around, they won't have that
opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1910EDT &QL; 
