<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TOURS BASES IN MORALE-BUILDING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany _ Trying to boost morale in the wake of the
first NATO casualties in its six-week bombing campaign, President
Clinton barnstormed Belgium and Germany Wednesday, urging American
soldiers to stay the course and vowing to intensify the attacks on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deaths of two American pilots in the second crash of
a US Army Apache helicopter in as many weeks, Clinton, General
Wesley K. Clark, and Defense Secretary William S. Cohen gave an
upbeat assessment of the air campaign against the forces of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the NATO commander, said there were no plans to send in
ground troops, and denied reports that a plan that called for
60,000 such troops had been drawn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I sound upbeat, it's because I am upbeat,'' said Clark.
``And the reason I'm upbeat is because we're winning. The air
campaign is working and it is working well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark made that point to Clinton during the president's first
stop Wednesday, at NATO headquarters in Brussels. He also warned
that NATO casualties like the ones that occurred early Wednesday
were inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But the second crash of an Apache in nine days, even before the
helicopters have come under hostile fire, underscored the costs of
escalating the war over Kosovo and raised concern among military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred to the crash only briefly, paying tribute to
the dead pilots as ``two brave Americans'' while addressing Air
Force personnel and their families at Spangdahlem Air Base in
Germany. Many of those at the air base learned of the fatal crash
only a few hours before Clinton spoke to them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent most of his time praising and meeting soldiers and
their families, and assuring them that the American people support
what they are doing. Clinton told them their mission was noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission in Kosovo has nothing to do with trying to acquire
territory or dominate others,'' Clinton said. ``It is about
something far more important _ creating the kind of world where an
innocent people are not singled out for repression, for expulsion,
for destruction just because of their religious and ethnic
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contrasted the ``ethnic cleansing'' _ a term coined by
Serbs to refer to the forced removal of a different ethnic group _
with the multiracial, multiethnic group of some 2,000 US military
people who crowded into a hangar to hear him speak. He said the
number of people expelled from Kosovo in the last two months is
equal to the population of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is an affront to everything we stand for,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Ramstein Air Base in Germany, the president met with
the three US servicemen who had been captured by Serb forces and
released by Milosevic to the Rev. Jesse Jackson last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a leather bomber jacket, Clinton stood with the smiling
former prisoners, Staff Sergeants Christopher Stone and Andrew
Ramirez and Specialist Steven Gonzales, who were dressed in their
army fatigues. Clinton praised the soldiers and their families, who
accompanied them, saying he was ``very moved by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Cohen said he was likely to recommend the release of
two captured Serb soldiers being held by American forces, but
insisted it was not a reciprocal gesture for Milosevic's releasing
the three US servicemen. Cohen and Clinton both stressed that the
US servicemen were in Macedonia, not Serbia, when they were
captured and should never have been taken in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The crash of the Apache helicopter, occurred while Air Force One
was en route to Brussels, during a nighttime training mission about
45 miles northeast of the military airport at Rinas, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time that one of the vaunted attack
helicopters crashed while American pilots prepare to deploy them in
Kosovo. The two crew members in the April 26 crash escaped with
only minor injuries, but Wednesday's victims were not as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Army investigators were still trying to determine why
the helicopter crashed, but said there was no indication it had
faced hostile fire.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are designed to fly low and attack the tanks and
mobile units that Serb forces have used to destroy villages and
expel ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, the Apaches are an important
military and psychological weapon against the Milosevic regime.
They were expected to be deployed within days, but the two crashes
raise questions about their reliability and what will happen when
they come under hostile fire.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing reporters at Spangdahlem, Clark said the crash was an
inevitable risk of training for combat. Cohen noted that seven
soldiers were killed in a helicopter training accident at Fort
Campbell in Kentucky last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a risk-free campaign,'' said Cohen. ``We are
likely to suffer casualties. Any campaign has inherent dangers
involved to the people who are carrying out and prosecuting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clark insisted that six weeks of bombing, which has
intensified since skies cleared a week ago, has taken a toll on
Yugoslav forces. He said NATO is beginning to inflict heavy damage
on the tank and mobile artillery units that are destroying villages
in Kosovo and creating the flood of refugees that threatens to
destabilize surrounding countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 48 hours, we've hit 10 armor concentrations, 11
artillery positions, three command posts, fuel dumps, radio relay
links, ammo dumps, barracks, bridges, railways, border posts,''
said Clark. ``We're hitting them hard, right where it hurts, on the
ground in Kosovo. Thousands of these forces are now in hiding,
which at least stops them from doing what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We're going to go on looking for them. This is a
relatively small area. It's about the size of the state of
Connecticut, and there are not that many places for them to hide.
We're going to pin them down, close them out, and take them out.
And we'll keep on hitting them until Milosevic faces up to the
demands of the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that NATO pilots are flying lower to
minimize the risk of mistakenly attacking civilians, and to get a
better look at Serb forces on the ground, Clark said the pilots are
safer now that they had been because the Yugoslav air defense
system has been diminished by bombing. Besides two NATO planes
being shot down, only two others have suffered what he called
battle damage. Both of the pilots in the downed planes were
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've flown over 15,000 sorties, of which 5,000 have been
strike missions. We now have more than 700 aircraft, over 30 ships,
almost double the forces we had some five weeks ago, with more on
the way,'' said Clark. ``The target sets have been deepened and
broadened, and measures are underway to further tighten the
strategic noose around Serbia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
