<HEADLINE>
A TRUNKLOAD OF TRIVIA IN HONOR OF ELEPHANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elephants are big.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Bonnie is the reigning star at the Fort Worth Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The 700-pound baby, born Dec. 16, is the first elephant born at
the zoo in its 90-year history. Her name, short for Bluebonnet, was
selected from suggestions made by schoolchildren and first
trumpeted in a naming ceremony this month.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fort Worth Museum of Science and History, the Omni
Theater opened its own trunk show this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa's Elephant Kingdom'' is the story of an elephant family
that makes a perilous trip across Kenyan plains to escape a
terrible drought. The 40-minute film pairs the massive mammals with
the massive IMAX format for a show that makes a big impression.
</P>
<P>
   But this spotlight on pachyderms is hardly unique. Throughout
history, elephants have had a big impact on popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have loomed large in literature: Babar, the King of
the Elephants, is regal but still playful, as well as a natty
dresser, in a book series by Jean De Brunhof.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have figured in military history: Hannibal crossed the
Alps with elephants on his way to fight the Roman army.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have been befriended by royalty: Queen Victoria
protested when the London Zoological Gardens decided to sell Jumbo,
an elephant beloved by Londoners, to P.T. Barnum. It didn't help;
Jumbo was sold anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have found fame and fortune in Hollywood: ``Dumbo,'' a
Disney story about a little elephant with big ears, is a favorite
of moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have secured a place in the annals of comedy: Q:
What's red and white and gray? A: Campbell's cream of elephant
soup.
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANT FACTOIDS:
</P>
<P>
   Elephants are of two types, African and Asian. African elephants
are larger and have much bigger ears.
</P>
<P>
   The largest elephants grow to be about 12 feet tall and weigh
about 9 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant tusks grow throughout an elephant's life and can weigh
more than 200 pounds. Among Asian elephants, only the males have
tusks. Both sexes of African elephants have tusks.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants have ``fingers'' at the end of their trunks to help
them grab things. Asian elephants have one trunk finger, and
African elephants have two.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants live 50 to 60 years on average.
</P>
<P>
   The gestation period for elephants is 22 months, and newborns
weigh between 250 and 300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants perform greeting ceremonies a member of the group
returns after a long time away. The welcoming animals spin around,
flap their ears and trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants eat about 350 pounds of grass, leaves, bark and other
vegetation every day.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants are on the endangered species list. About 600,000
African elephants and 50,000 Asian elephants are left in the world.
About 20 percent are in captivity. Sources: The People's Almanac;
Africa's Elephant Kingdom fact sheet; www.elephants.se/faq.htm.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``AFRICA'S ELEPHANT KINGDOM''
</P>
<P>
   Through Nov. 4 at the Omni Theater, Fort Worth Museum of Science
and History, 1501 Montgomery St.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $6 for adults, $4 for seniors 60 and over, $4 for
children 3 to 12
</P>
<P>
   Information: For show times, call 255-9300 or (888) 255-9300, or
visit the Web site at www.fwmuseum.org.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
