<HEADLINE>
COHEN SAYS TWO   SERB SOLDIERS MAY BE FREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPANGDAHLEM, Germany _ Defense Secretary William S. Cohen
Wednesday said he was likely to recommend the release of two Serb
soldiers being held prisoner by the US Army.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he had asked Cohen and his National
Security Council staff to consider the possible release of the
Yugoslav POWs _ now held in Germany _ and to make a recommendation
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to get it in a couple of days,'' said Clinton,
standing for photographers with the three US servicemen turned over
to the Rev. Jesse Jackson by Yugoslav authorities last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect within a relatively short period of time that
we could see their release,'' Cohen said of the POWs, adding it
could take place ``within days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen emphasized that releasing the Yugoslavs would not be
the reciprocal good will gesture that Jackson had urged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good will overture to Mr. Milosevic,'' said
Cohen. ``I don't believe Mr. Milosevic has made any good will
overture to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen maintains that Serb forces had no right to take the three
Americans prisoner as they patrolled near the Macedonia-Serbia
border March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the release of the Serb prisoners could give new momentum
to the diplomatic efforts being led by Russia to find a negotiated
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, Clinton insisted there would be no
negotiation on NATO's five core demands: that the killing end; that
Serb forces withdraw from Kosovo; that refugees be allowed to
return; that an international force ``with NATO at its core'' be
allowed into Kosovo to protect the refugees; and that Kosovo be
given back the autonomy Milosevic stripped it of in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The two Serb soldiers whose release Cohen said was impending
were captured separately last month by rebels from the separatist
Kosovo Liberation Army. The KLA turned them over to Albanian
government officials, who handed them to American forces.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the attention paid to the three captured
Americans, there has been little said about the Serb prisoners.
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said the administration had
purposely not used them as a bargaining chip or a propaganda tool.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said one of the Serb prisoners was still being examined by
the International Red Cross. Some sources suggested that prisoner
may be reluctant to return to Serbia because his KLA captors had
videotaped him making statements that his comrades in the Yugoslav
armed forces had engaged in summary executions and systematic rape
of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Cohen Wednesday, Bacon said he did not know if the
prisoner being examined by the Red Cross is the one in the
propaganda film.
</P>
<P>
   If released, the Serb prisoners would most likely be turned over
to the Red Cross or to Swedish diplomats, who represent US
interests in Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
