   EDUC-HOSPITALS (Boston) _ Normally, the great teaching hospitals
of this medical Mecca carry an air of white-coated,
best-in-the-world arrogance. But lately, their chief executives
carry an air of pleading and alarm. They tend to cross the edges of
their palms in an X that symbolizes the crossing of rising costs
and dropping payments, especially Medicare payments. The special
missions of the teaching hospitals give them no immunity to the
great changes sweeping American healthcare. By Carey Goldberg. With
photos. 1,900 words.
</P>
