<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN LEADER FREED FROM HOUSE ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ After weeks of enforced isolation, a key leader of ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo arrived in Rome on Wednesday from Serbia as a
guest of the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Rugova, 54, a moderate intellectual who had long
embraced a policy of nonviolent resistance to the Serbian
authorities in Kosovo, was until now reported to be under house
arrest, according to NATO and a German journalist who stayed in
Rugova's house for the first weeks of the allied bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He shocked many of his followers when he criticized the NATO
bombing campaign on Serbian television on April 2nd. Western
leaders said that his statements had been doctored and that he was
forced to comply with Serbian authorities. Serbian officials have
denied that, pointing to Rugova's reported meetings with Serbian
leaders and even to an agreement Serbian media said Rugova signed
with Serbian President Milan Milutinovic late last month.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Kosovo Liberation Army in Tirana have said
that if Rugova's statements were not coerced, then he was a traitor
to the ethnic Albanian cause. Wednesday, they said that while they
welcomed Rugova's release, he was not the legitimate leader of the
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the exact circumstances of his stay in Serbian
territory, Rugova's sudden arrival in the West suggested that
Belgrade is seeking to gather momentum and public support for a
mediated settlement to the conflict. Previous requests by Western
intermediaries for Rugova's release had been turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be eager to have an opportunity to talk to him and
hear his perspective on what's been happening to his people in
Kosovo,'' said James Foley, a State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova, who stepped off a chartered plane Wednesday with his
wife and children, wearing a smile and a trademark silk scarf
around his neck, did not speak to reporters and gave no public
indication of what his circumstances had been. Instead, he met with
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema and Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini. In a statement, the Italian government said they had
``examined the possibility of a political-diplomatic solution to
the conflict, to which Rugova can contribute as a free man.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, a government official who was familiar with the
discussion said that Rugova did not offer a new plan for an end to
the conflict, but reiterated his longstanding views that a
political solution is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``His position, and the moderate orientation he had at
Rambouillet, hasn't changed,'' the official noted. ``The main
difference is that he is now free to say whatever he wants,
wherever he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rugova spoke with Italian officials, his wife and children
were moved to the small town of Artena, outside Rome, where other
Rugova family members have been living for close to a month.
Italian officials said that all of Rugova's relatives were now out
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it has not been clear whether Rugova was able to
express himself freely, but it was evident that his freedom of
movement was sharply curtailed. Last month, a reporter for the
German newsmagazine Der Spiegel wrote an account detailing how she
was at Rugova's home in Pristina, when Serbian forces put him under
house arrest and witnessed how he was pressured into signing
statements by Serbian authorities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On April 28, Serbian television announced an agreement between
Rugova and Milutinovic to work on a political settlement for
Kosovo. In that program, Rugova addressed the camera from Pristina,
the capital of Kosovo, and speaking in Serbian, said, ``the most
important thing is this mutual trust that we have built and that
the world will salute.'' He told the cameras that he had
``successfully cooperated'' with Serbian officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Rugova and Milutinovic, agreed to form a
new, temporary government for the province, resume negotiations on
a form of self-rule for Kosovo, and invite some foreigners as
``guests'' to attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement did not address NATO demands that an
international military force, with NATO at its core, secure the
return of Kosovo refugees. Nor did it meet the expectations of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, which with its militant tactics and
determination to fight for Kosovo's independence, has sought to
supplant Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   On April 6, a delegation from Sant' Egidio, a Catholic religious
organization based in Rome that is active in relief work and
conflict mediation, went to Belgrade to seek a peaceful conclusion
to the war. The group is known to both Serbian officials and Rugova
and earlier this decade helped negotiate an unsuccessful agreement
for Serb and Albanian children to be educated in the same schools
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Marazziti, a spokesman for Sant'Egidio, said that the
delegation which went in April spoke over the telephone with
Rugova, but said members received the call on condition that they
not discuss the logistics of the conversation with Rugova. ``He
gave us the impression that he was free to express his thoughts,''
Marazziti said. ``But that he was not free to move around as he
pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation pressed Milutinovic and other Serbian officials
to allow Rugova to travel to the West. At the time, Marazziti said,
officials rejected the proposal, saying they were concerned about
protecting Rugova's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arrival here re-establishes his legitimacy as a leader,''
Marazziti said. ``He will be able to express himself without
restrictions, and he is still a significant player in the search
for a peaceful outcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
