<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIANS-ECON-ART     05-05 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-ECON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PALESTINIAN HOLDING COMPANY DOMINATES DEVELOPMENT IN WEST BANK,
GAZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABLUS, West Bank _ From his hillside offices, Munib Masri can
look down on the neighborhood where his grandfather's family
founded the city's first university and survey the old town center
where uncles and cousins served as mayors.
</P>
<P>
   But Masri, a dapper, Texas-educated billionaire, keeps his eye
on new features of the Nablus landscape, all of which he had a hand
in building: a Palestinian stock exchange, a modern television
assembly plant, the headquarters of Paltel, the Mideast's first
privately owned phone company.
</P>
<P>
   These are cornerstones of an emerging Palestinian economy, being
built with offshore Palestinian money in expectation of statehood.
And all are offshoots of the Palestinian Development and Investment
Co., or Padico, a Nablus-based holding company run by the
iron-willed Masri. In five years, Padico has become the biggest and
most influential company in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, with
interests ranging from manufacturing and real estate to finance and
power generating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything we can to put Palestine on the economic
map of the world,'' said Masri, who made his fortune in Europe and
the Persian Gulf during the quarter-century that Nablus was under
Israeli administration.
</P>
<P>
   In government circles, Padico is applauded for bringing urgently
needed Palestinian capital and business skills back home. Local
critics, though, contend that it rests on a foundation of cronyism,
nepotism and protectionism, with troubling implications for a
Palestine of the future. Some see Padico's close ties to Yasser
Arafat's Palestinian Authority as a framework for further
concentration of wealth in a society already riven by deep
inequities.
</P>
<P>
   In project after project, Padico has recruited top Palestinian
managerial and engineering talent, most with advanced degrees from
abroad, and assembled financial backing for critical new
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to promote private investment here, one of the
engines is Padico,'' said Mohsen Khalil, Middle East director for
the International Finance Corp., the World Bank's private
investment arm. ``They bring in a lot of competence, a lot of
expertise and a lot of resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Local business rivals, however, portray Padico as an enemy of
the free market and a beneficiary of political concessions. And
Padico's founding investors are resented by others here for their
affluence, their long absence and their Westernized ways. (Masri's
wife and six adult children are U.S. citizens, and most senior
Padico employees speak fluent English.)
</P>
<P>
   ``During all our struggles here, during the intifada, all these
millionaires were living abroad,'' said Hatem Abdul-Qader, a member
of the Palestinian legislative council, referring to the uprising
against Israeli military administration that erupted in 1987.
``Then these people came to harvest the fruits of our struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition legislators hint darkly that they have proof of
payoff schemes and secret deals to restrict competition. But they
have yet to produce any evidence of corruption involving Padico.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Nashabishi, the Palestinian Authority's finance chief,
dismisses the attacks. ``They are pioneers,'' he said. ``Let those
who criticize them come and compete with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the authority gave Padico a head start. Its subsidiaries are
already busy crisscrossing Palestinian territory with fiber-optic
cables, erecting beachfront condominiums beside Gaza refugee camps,
and spawning an array of start-up companies from plastics makers to
poultry farms.
</P>
<P>
   Among Padico's most prominent projects is the Palestinian
Authority's showcase tourism enterprise, a $48 million Bethlehem
luxury hotel being rushed through construction in hopes of
receiving Pope John Paul II and others for millennial celebrations.
The authority's biggest manufacturing venture, a Gaza industrial
park with its own Israeli customs post, is another subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   And Padico is the only private local shareholder in a new
Palestinian home mortgage corporation, a $22 million partnership
including the authority and a German development bank. All three
projects are being developed with loans and equity from the
International Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they first received these contracts,'' said
Husan Khader, a Nablus legislator. ``But once they have the job,
they do it professionally,'' adding that if they were responsible
for all the Palestinians' economic affairs, ``they would be a
civilizing influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Masri is happy to acknowledge that he is an Arafat confidante.
Now a member of the Palestinian central council, he was a Jordanian
Cabinet minister when the Palestine Liberation Organization rose
against King Hussein in 1970. Dispatched to the PLO leader's desert
hideout by Hussein, Masri forged an enduring bond with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I am so close to Arafat, some people think that Padico
is part of the government,'' Masri said. ``But it is not. It is
completely private and independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Padico is seen here as an extension of the Masri
clan, West Bank patricians who made fortunes abroad but always
considered Nablus their home. The family traces its lineage back
more than three centuries in this old Jordan Valley city _ which,
with Padico's help, aspires to become the business capital of a
future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Munib Masri's second cousin, Sabih Nasri, another recently
returned billionaire, runs Paltel. Almost every other Padico
subsidiary has a Masri or two on its board. The Palestinian
Authority's trade and industry chief is another Nablus cousin,
Maher Masri.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in the family, there is dissent. ``What they are really
doing,'' said Muawia al-Masri, a distant relative who represents
Nablus on the legislative council, ``is imposing monopolies on
services, which is hurting the Palestinian people.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Masri bridles at such comments. ``We don't want to monopolize
anything,'' he said. ``There is plenty of work to do here. We need
10 Padicos to repair the damage that the Israelis have done to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no better indicator of Padico's influence, and the
ingrown nature of its business ties, than its role in the nascent
stock market. Started by Padico in 1997 with a charter from Arafat,
the Nablus exchange is managed by a small Padico subsidiary.
Suleiman Abbadi, the recently hired director, reports to the
exchange chairman, Sabih Masri, who is also chairman of Paltel, the
largest company traded on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Paltel, Padico and a Padico real estate subsidiary together
account for two-thirds of the market capitalization of the 28
listed companies.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Padico's dual role as market player and manager, and lax
local rules on financial disclosure and insider trading, some
Palestinian businesses refuse to be listed on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I trust it?'' asked Mazen Sinokrot, a candy maker in
Ramallah, whose family business has diversified into animal feed
and real estate. ``You are my competitor, and you also control the
stock market? You have information about my company, but I don't
have information about yours?''
</P>
<P>
   What most irks Sinokrot is that he and other local entrepreneurs
did not have a place at the table when Arafat and Padico's founders
devised their projects, like the plan for a telecommunications
monopoly. ``We were never given the same opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paltel president Hatem al-Halawani, who earlier served five
years as Padico's chief executive, argues that by limiting itself
to a minority holding in Paltel and selling shares to the public _
a Palestinian first _ Padico provided ample openings for local
investors. ``We could have taken 50 or 60 percent if we wanted
to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Padico's original mandate, notes Amin Haddad, until recently
Padico's vice president and spokesman, was to create investment
opportunities for expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, with local political control about to pass to
the Palestinian Authority, Masri returned here from London at
Arafat's invitation, joining his first cabinet and helping to
assemble Padico. With the Israeli-Palestinian peace accord just
months old, it was a time of heady optimism, but also of few local
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept was to build the Palestinian economy,'' Masri
said, ``and to make a decent profit, but not an exorbitant profit.
And what we did was clean; it was over the table.''
</P>
<P>
   With Arafat's endorsement, Masri and other expatriates courted
Palestinian investors from Europe, the Americas and throughout the
Middle East. A key recruit was the Amman-based but
Palestinian-owned Arab Bank, the Arab world's fourth largest.
Others followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to convince people to put 3 or 4 percent of
their wealth into a country where they will be able to raise their
children,'' Masri said.
</P>
<P>
   The group raised about $150 million initially and backed the new
company with $1 billion. Each founding investor was limited to a 2
percent share. Last year, Padico directors made what they said was
a one-time exception, accepting $10 million from Prince Walid bin
Talal, the Saudi billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Padico is a holding company of fairly standard design,
modest dimensions and meager profits. The core company and its
majority-owned subsidiaries have about 100 professional employees
scattered across the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. On the
Palestinian exchange, Padico's market capitalization hovers around
$190 million, not all that much more than its reported $84 million
in paid-in capital. Until a recent 1,000-for-one split, Padico
shares sold for $1,000 each, discouraging most local interest.
</P>
<P>
   Padico's 1998 report, released at its annual meeting in April,
includes a summarized audit by Arthur Andersen showing net assets
of just $122 million and an after-tax profit last year of $2.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some unhappy investors,'' Haddad acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But such figures belie Padico's true importance here. The
company says it manages some $500 million in additional assets for
its partners, including the Palestinian Authority. And the personal
wealth of its board members is ``about $20 billion,'' Haddad
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Even allowing for exaggeration, the assets of Padico's
expatriate founders loom extraordinarily large in a $3 billion
economy. And some holdings give Padico significant profit
potential, analysts say, pointing to its 10 percent share of a new
Gaza electric company and 23 percent of Paltel.
</P>
<P>
   Few foreign investors are ready to wade into the shallow and
murky waters of Palestinian finance, but Padico and Paltel are
considered the most viable eventual candidates for international
stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at emerging markets, it is almost always the case
at the beginning that a few companies will account for most of the
capitalization,'' said Angus Blair, head of equity research for the
Middle East at ABN Amro in London. ``Invariably, telecoms and
holding companies are going to be very important.''
</P>
<P>
   The London-based emerging markets department of Nomura, the
giant Japanese brokerage house, is now preparing what Padico says
will be the first thorough independent assessment of the company,
in conjunction with a Jordanian investment banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   But prospective investors may receive the report somewhat
skeptically. The owner and managing director of Nomura's Jordanian
partner, Atlas Investment Group, is Omar Masri, Munib Masri's son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
