<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LAWYER QUESTIONS AOL EXECUTIVE ON ACQUISITION OF NETSCAPE
BROWSER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Microsoft lawyer tried to make the case Wednesday
that America Online plans to use ``all of its marketing muscle'' to
promote its newly acquired product, the Netscape Navigator Web
browser. But an America Online executive disputed that, saying the
company thinks ``the browser business is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The back and forth came this morning as Microsoft took the
deposition of Barry Schuler, the president for interactive services
at America Online, in preparation for the resumption of the
antitrust trial late this month.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft plans to make the case in court that America Online's
purchase of the Netscape Communications Corp. for $10 million this
year seriously undermines the government's argument that Microsoft
is a monopolist with no serious competition. If America Online
stepped up Netscape's competition with Microsoft's browser, that
could seem to support this assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from company documents obtained by subpoena, a Microsoft
lawyer, Steven Holley, noted that one America Online executive had
proposed in December to increase marketing of Netscape's browser _
perhaps, Holley said, even using direct mail to send out millions
of copes of the software, as America Online has done with its own
software.
</P>
<P>
   Schuler called the executive's suggestion ``just his opinion,''
not company policy, adding that America Online ``is not actually
considering'' direct-mail marketing of Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases it was hard to know which of Holley's assertions
came from America Online documents that Microsoft had obtained and
which might have been his own suggestions because America Online
tried to insist that every document be marked as confidential _
even newspaper clippings and news releases. Holley managed to
persuade the America Online lawyer to take the confidential
markings off the newspaper clippings.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Schuler insisted that America Online had little
interest in Netscape's browser. The company was much more
interested in Netscape's Internet portal business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The broswer business had been decimated, he said, by Microsoft's
decision to bundle a competing browser with the Windows operating
system that is installed on more than 90 percent of the world's
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Holley spent most of the morning questioning Schuler about the
timing of America Online's decisions in the purchase of Netscape.
He tried to force Schuler to acknowledge that an America Online
lawyer had informed David Boies, the lead Justice Department
lawyer, about the company's proposed acquisition of Netscape in
early October, before the antitrust trial began, but then kept it
secret from the government and the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman, said, ``If that was the
case, it would cast the testimony of Netscape and AOL witnesses in
a very different light.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft plans to call David Colburn, a senior America Online
executive, as a hostile witness and question him about his earler
testimony in the trial and how it related to the acquisition plans.
</P>
<P>
   But Schuler said George Vradenburg, a senior company lawyer, had
simply told Boies on Oct. 3 that America Online and Netscape were
involved in ``a very preliminary conversation of a sensitive nature
about a potential commercial relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Vradenburg and Boies are former law partners, and Boies was
preparing to take a deposition from Colburn that day. America
Online says Vradenburg wanted to make sure Boies did not stumble
into that confidential area.
</P>
<P>
   This Oct. 3 discussion is a central piece of evidence behind
Microsoft's assertion that America Online, Netscape and the
government plotted, in essence, to keep the proposed deal from
Microsoft and the judge until the other companies' witnesses
completed their trial testimony.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Justice Department official said Boies and government
lawyers had taken Vradenburg's imprecise remark on Oct. 3 to mean
that America Online was considering using Netscape in its online
service, adding, ``for the life of me I don't quite understand the
relevance of this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray added, ``These issues will be a significant part of
our rebuttal case.''
</P>
<P>
   When a government lawyer, Philip R. Malone, got his turn to
question Schuler, he asked whether America Online and Netscape had
``delayed or postponed'' their acquisition agreement ``because of
any concern about the impact it might have on the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we did not,'' Schuler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
