<HEADER>
A5758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIND-GAMES-TEX     05-05 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIND-GAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE IMAGINARY VIDEO GAMES REALLY ROCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bands and video games have always, for some reason, made for
frequent _ albeit very strange _ bedfellows. Remember that Journey
game for the Atari 2600, ``Journey Escape?'' Band members fled a
rock concert, with ``Don't Stop Believin''' playing in the
background, and you had to help them avoid crazed groupies and
scummy agents. You do know what we're talking about, right? Anyone?
</P>
<P>
   More recent attempts at turning rock stars into Marios have been
just as disastrous: That Spice Girls game for the Sony PlayStation
was more hideous than humorous. And the recent announcement of an
in-time-for-Christmas Wu-Tang Clan fighting game for PlayStation _
an as-yet unnamed game in which the rap group fights its way from
ancient China to Staten Island in New York City _ looks like
another Mortal Kombat clone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if we had our way we'd come out with some really cool,
``Behind the Music''-style video games featuring rock stars. Such
as:
</P>
<P>
   Game title: ODB Breakout
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Always-in-hot-water rapper Ol' Dirty B------.
</P>
<P>
   Game description: In this spinoff from the Wu-Tang Clan game,
you help WTC member ODB break out of jail in time to make his
CD-release party. This is a two-player game: One controls ODB, the
other ODB's girlfriend, YCM (Young Coochie Mama). To escape, they
must blackmail, dodge or beat up jail guards with plastic spoons
from the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: You'll need a cell phone to complete the mission (try the
warden's office). How else are ya gonna reach your limo driver to
come pick ya up?
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Age 17 and up for violence, as well as language, which
mostly comes from the background music.
</P>
<P>
   Game title: Find Your Way Back
</P>
<P>
   Starring: '60s acid-rock band Jefferson Airplane
</P>
<P>
   Game description: A flight simulator in which players must try
to control a plane that is as disoriented and high as the band was
in 1969. The longer the plane flies, the more wavy-gravy it
becomes. Especially difficult is the hallucination level, in which
players must evade such ``whoa, dude'' obstacles as flying cows and
an airborne Titanic while the Airplane morphs into a Starship.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: One pill makes you larger, the other makes you smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Age 13 and up. Feel-good '90s message stamped on each
game: Talk to your kids about drugs before they talk to you about
them.
</P>
<P>
   Game title: Doomed
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Cutie-pie pop pinups Backstreet Boys, Five, 'N Sync,
98 Degrees
</P>
<P>
   Game description: You're walking around an arena, zapping
members of pop acts Backstreet Boys and 98 Degrees _ as well as
their crazed fans _ minutes before they're to perform. If you don't
tag every member, they'll go on to the next town to play, and we
don't want that, do we?
</P>
<P>
   Tips: Enlist the help of Donnie Wahlberg, former New Kid on the
Block. He's got plenty of time on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Age 17 and up for graphic _ but pretty funny _ violence.
</P>
<P>
   Game title: Stoned Temple Pilot
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Admitted former drug addict and lead singer Scott
Weiland
</P>
<P>
   Game description: After several years, STP singer Scott Weiland
is finally clean. For one night, you are his manager, and you must
keep him in sight so he can perform a concert without passing out.
This, of course, is not easy. While you're on the phone trying to
persuade club owners to book him and journalists to interview him,
Weiland tries to sneak off to neighborhood crack houses and liquor
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: On the hidden bonus level, try to find and flush as much
of Weiland's smack as you can. For each bag, you'll gain tools to
help keep Scott in check, such as handcuffs and long-sleeved
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: All ages. Minimal violence, but graphic scenes of Scott
going through unsightly withdrawal symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Game title: The Marilyn Manson Makeover
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Ghoulish schlock-rocker Marilyn Manson
</P>
<P>
   Game description: In the vein of Barbie's dress-me-up CD-ROMS
comes this fun little title in which players help Mr. Manson with
his new makeover. Select clothes, makeup and hairstyles for a brand
new look, such as the earnest, coffeehouse folkie or Vegas-bound,
suit-and-tie wash-up.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: Injections and implants can be used to adjust the size of
his head, feet and, if you so desire, breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Age 13 and up only. They don't want anyone suing because
their kids had nightmares about this guy.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: WE MADE UP ALL THESE GAMES. You can't buy them
anywhere. Don't call us asking where to find them.
</P>
