<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WEB-KAN &LR;      05-05 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WEB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB AIDS HUNT FOR RELATIVES IN BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tears well up in Fatmira Beka's eyes as the
computer images slowly download. Scenes of children wandering in
rubble. Distraught, dirty faces. Sorrow and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   For Beka, a 20-year-old Kosovar Albanian, each photo, image or
TV broadcast is another opportunity to learn a shred of news about
the whereabouts of her grandfather, uncles and cousins she and her
family left behind in Kosovo. The Bekas moved to Kansas City a year
ago, after fleeing to Germany six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not heard from them in two months,'' she said. ``We
have heard bad things they do to men. I want every day to know how
my family is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross might be able to help.
</P>
<P>
   Through Web site technology the organization is trying to help
Beka and others find loved ones in Kosovo with a few keystrokes
online.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, the Red Cross posted an interactive Web site called
the Displaced Persons Linking Center. The site is at (BEGIN
BOLDFACE)www.redcross.org(END BOLDFACE).
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials hope the site will produce connections soon.
Gathering information from refugees is a massive undertaking
because they rarely have identification and frequently are on the
move.
</P>
<P>
   The site has two screens of questions. Some of the personal
questions, such as birth dates of relatives, Beka couldn't answer.
But there are boxes available for guessing, too.
</P>
<P>
   The search data requires many questions because English
spellings for names can vary greatly from Slavic ones. Although
users can scan in photos of family members, Beka has no photos _
her family took few personal items when they left Kosovo in the
dead of night after her father had been beaten by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The information that Red Cross volunteers enter about refugees
from the Yugoslavian border camps will be cross-referenced with
data entered on the Web site to look for matches.
</P>
<P>
   Matches will be reported to the local Red Cross agency of the
family or friend searching for that refugee, said Richard Liles,
family services manager at the Greater Kansas City Red Cross
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a match, we will get in touch with the people
looking, either by calling them or maybe telling them in person,''
he said. ``There haven't been any matches yet, but we're expecting
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross also is prepared to pass messages back and forth
from the refugee camps to the families, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's letting the family know everyone's all right or
setting in motion the process of moving them to the United States,
the Red Cross will provide that line of communication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One concern for refugees considering revealing private
information on themselves is who will see the data, said Doug
Rekenthaler, a spokesman at the Red Cross national headquarters in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very mindful of security,'' he said. ``Even the local
Red Cross chapters don't have access to it. This is not information
that anyone can tap into. It's like a giant census project forced
by unfortunate circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating lines of communication between families in times of
disasters or war has been a goal of the Red Cross since the 1870s.
Internet technology offers a way to expedite that process and maybe
alleviate some of the suffering of displaced families, Rekenthaler
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get this up and running now,'' he said. ``Not
only will this technology help the refugees, it has applications
down the road for other disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rekenthaler was frustrated that the technology wasn't working
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have really helped if we had this for the Hurricane
Mitch disaster in Honduras,'' he said. ``Right now, we have 10,000
dead and 5,000 still missing. We might have had more answers for
families with this service.''
</P>
<P>
   For Beka and her family, this service offers hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can really understand how it is to think that someone
from your blood is hungry or cold or hurting,'' she said. ``Thank
you America and the Red Cross for helping us. I hope, I hope, I
hope America helps us until this is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
