<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5767 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PROFILE-TWOTAKES     05-05 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EX-PRESIDENT'S SON, NAME'S BIG PART OF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With big leads in the polls and big bucks in the bank, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush is, by any measure, the front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But one question won't go away: What if he wasn't the son of the
former president?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'd still be hot stuff. And maybe he wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his name was Governor Smith, he might not be so popular,''
said Bruce Buchanan, a political scientist at the University of
Texas. ``A lot of this is name recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll in New Hampshire showed exactly that. Described
generically to voters without using his name, Bush saw his lead
fall by 14 points, twice as much as any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that Bush lacks distinction. Last November, he became
the first Lone Star State governor to be re-elected in 24 years,
and he did it in a landslide, winning 69 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And, in an unusual twist, Texas Democrats praise him. Bush, 52,
has won national notice for his ability to win votes from groups,
such as Hispanics, that traditionally have been in the Democratic
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, he's the best governor I ever worked with,''
said former Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a brusque political
veteran from central Texas. ``I admire him, and I respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's popularity has spread beyond Texas, Bush himself
has stayed put, keeping a low profile while reaping endorsements
and contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is gearing up to launch his national campaign in Iowa and
New Hampshire next month. Few observers expect him to waltz to the
nomination as easily as he shot to the head of the Republican pack
in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an optimistic person about his candidacy,'' said Bob
Stein, a Rice University political scientist in Houston who has
watched Bush closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think there's lots and lots of unresolved questions
here,'' said Charles Cook, a Washington political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   One is Bush's relative inexperience in public service. The
governorship is, after all, his first public office.
</P>
<P>
   Another is his ability to straddle both wings of his party. Bush
is anti-abortion, for instance, but anti-abortion leaders are
skeptical of his commitment to their cause. His ``compassionate
conservative'' themes could prove mushy in a GOP that has tilted
hard right in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One more question mark hangs over past behavior:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the first to admit that I did irresponsible things when
I was young and irresponsible,'' the governor has said on more than
one occasion _ always declining to explain exactly what.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters expect Bush to remain more cautious than some of
his rivals. No need to go out on a limb when you're cruising in the
polls, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Every move Bush makes comes under scrutiny. The governor
endorsed a contentious gun-control measure in the Texas
Legislature, but did so only after the Littleton, Colo., shootings.
Now, Democrats criticize him for so quickly dropping it.
</P>
<P>
   In April, The Wall Street Journal called Bush's statement on
Kosovo ``a model of obfuscation'' and derided his halting
performance in answering questions. The Journal concluded that Bush
may not be ready for the big time.
</P>
<P>
   During the Clinton impeachment crisis, Bush took the small step
of saying he felt embarrassed for the country. But even those words
got slapped back in his face. Lanny Davis, a Clinton adviser who
attended Yale with Bush, said on national television that Bush
``shouldn't throw stones.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5769 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-     05-05 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EX-PRESIDENT'S SON, NAME'S BIG PART OF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... ``shouldn't throw stones.''
</P>
<P>
   That Bush is drawing so much attention reflects his unquestioned
status as the GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   He's garnered more endorsements from elected GOP officials than
any other candidate. Already 15 governors, including Kansas' Bill
Graves, have announced their backing along with eight senators,
dozens of House members and hundreds of state lawmakers, including
a majority of GOPers in the Missouri General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   He's also collected the most money in a crowed GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised $7.6 million through March 31, and took in $3.5
million more in April alone. At that pace, he could reach the $20
million threshold by July.
</P>
<P>
   Such success is fueling speculation that he will forgo federal
matching funds, a move that will free him to spend as much as he
wants in any state. The tactic would help him compete with
billionaire publisher Steve Forbes, a GOP presidential rival, who
in 1996 became the only major contender in recent years to refuse
federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   History, however, is littered with early leaders who fell short
because they became everyone's prime target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for hot front-runners to get into
troubleespecially for one as untested as Bush,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the doubts, the governor will be a formidable
candidate. A man of nervous intensity, Bush defeated a popular
Democrat, incumbent Ann Richards, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It was Richards who once described the elder Bush as born ``with
a silver foot in his mouth.'' The feisty Democrat didn't hold back
against the younger Bush, either, calling him ``Shrub,'' ``that
young Bush boy'' and ``some jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing a seasoned maturity, Bush laughed off the lines and
stuck like glue to a four-point platform: more control for local
school districts, welfare reform, tougher juvenile-justice laws and
tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican landslides of '94 helped Bush turn a tight race
into a surprisingly easy win. He beat Richards 53 to 46 percent and
immediately went to work turning his campaign promises into law. He
succeeded in passing legislation that addressed all four of his
chief planks during his first session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets results,'' said state Sen. Buster Brown, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   His successes were generally described as equivalent to hitting
a series of singles. Bush went for the long ball in 1997 when he
proposed an ambitious $3-billion-a-year cut in local property
taxes, partly offset by new taxes to finance the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats liked the plan; many Republicans hated it. In the end,
the proposal was whittled back to a $1 billion property-tax cut,
hardly a massive cut in a state the size of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties describe Bush as difficult to dislike.
He is respectful. He listens. And he is ingratiating, often
greeting lawmakers with a self-styled nickname. Sen. Teel Bivins is
``Bivy.'' Sen. Florence Shapiro is ``Flo-Jo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does have a way of expressing himself when he does not
agree with you,'' Brown said. ``He's very honest. He doesn't hide
his position from you. You understand him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat ironic that the GOP could find itself turning to
a man named Bush to reclaim the presidency. After all, the elder
Bush lost the White House to Clinton at a time when the GOP had
made winning the White House an almost routine event.
</P>
<P>
   But those who know them say the younger Bush is a different man
than his father. George W., who spent years struggling to get out
of his father's shadow, has a harder edge and may be more
conservative. And, some say, the governor learned from his father's
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Stein at Rice University says Bush's assets and liabilities
stand out clearly. While he admires Bush's centrist politics and
the courage of his more inclusive policies, he notes the lack of
experience and depth of knowledge on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a big question mark,'' Stein said. ``If he became
president, I'd be nervous. I'd pay a whole lot of attention to who
he picks for his Cabinet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
