<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIPPER-CASE-TWOTAKES-     05-05 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIPPER-CASE-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE PLACED PREDATOR IN CRYSTAL KIPPER'S PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 OSCAR AVILA AND BENITA Y. WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Both Crystal Kipper and John E. Williams had
made the late-night run down Interstate 29 many times.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper, enjoying her first days as an adult, would coax her 1989
Ford Probe toward her Gladstone, Mo., apartment after a night out.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, filled with sexual frustration, would slink home from
Leavenworth, Kan., after another unsuccessful tryst with his
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper and Williams shared the highway on Feb. 24, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Williams told authorities he accidentally hit Kipper with his
car as she stood on the shoulder. Police say he killed her and
disposed of her body.
</P>
<P>
   What if Kipper had listened to her friends and filled her gas
tank before driving to St. Joseph, Mo., to take a friend home? What
if Williams had been fiddling with the radio and not noticed her on
the roadside?
</P>
<P>
   What if?
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star has obtained more than 2,500 pages of
investigative files that showed how fate brought Williams and
Kipper together.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews, letters, calls to the TIPS hot line and other clues
in the files shed light on the lives of Williams and Kipper, as
well as how authorities were shaping the case in her disappearance
and the lengths Kipper's mother went to in trying to find her
missing daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But after Williams hanged himself in the Jackson County Jail
nine days ago, many questions still remain.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before that Feb. 24, Kipper and Williams were
trying to find their places in the world and deal with change.
</P>
<P>
   Loved ones say Kipper, 18, had overcome early rebellion and had
rediscovered her faith.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Kipper always seemed to need money: for traffic
tickets, for clothes and, down the road, for college.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why she had answered an ad for dancers shortly
after her 18th birthday. She danced at Ziegfield's for about two
months in the summer of 1996. Kipper quit when her mother asked her
to leave the downtown adult entertainment club.
</P>
<P>
   She then made some changes in her life.
</P>
<P>
   She attended church with a rededication to her faith and began
working double shifts at the Tippin's restaurant on North Oak
Street. At the time she disappeared, she was two days away from
taking jazz and tango dance lessons.
</P>
<P>
   She had planned a trip to Springfield, Mo., to visit a young man
she recently met at a gospel service.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, on the other hand, was continuing patterns that he had
established early in life.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 16, he had abducted a Leavenworth boy, killed
him and buried him by railroad tracks. When he was released from
juvenile custody, he sodomized another boy.
</P>
<P>
   The move to a downtown Kansas City high-rise didn't provide the
change in life that Williams had been looking for. He found a job
at a North Kansas City printer but he was virtually without
friends, and his nights were lonely.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter to a friend, he wrote: ``I am getting tired of
coming home to nothing each and every night. It is not like I am
not trying to make any friends. It seems like that everyone is
always in a hurry and if they are not in a hurry, they look at you
like they think you are the Boston Strangler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to the conclusion that Kansas City is a very
depressing town,'' Williams wrote in another letter.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Williams started dating a Leavenworth woman. She
said he was a tender and gentle man. But Williams could not perform
sexually and he would often leave her home about 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't remember whether he was with her on Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   That February night, Kipper drove to St. Joseph to pick up a
friend, Jay Sampson. They picked up two other friends in Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   The four trekked to Crown Center about 11 p.m. Sampson had never
seen the waterfall or traversed the skywalk the shopping and office
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The four stayed until midnight, then headed to Kansas City,
North, where Kipper drove to a gas station at 58th Street and North
Oak Trafficway. She pointed out a cute guy, but was afraid her
friends would tease her if she stopped.
</P>
<P>
   She drove away without buying gas.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Schmitt, one of the friends in the car that night, said
Kipper didn't mind driving Sampson back to St. Joseph at 1 a.m.
Kipper dropped Schmitt and Schmitt's boyfriend off in Riverside,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The low-fuel warning on Kipper's maroon Ford Probe lit up on the
way to St. Joseph, but Kipper said she got good mileage on her car
and refused Sampson's offer to buy gas. She had miscalculated
before. Her AAA service had brought gas to her three times in the
previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had constantly told her to stop running around with her fuel
running low,'' said Kipper's mother, Anna Kipper. ``In some ways, I
think she was pushing the envelope there and thought she was
invincible by thinking she could make it on so little gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Kipper and Sampson made it to St. Joseph, 50 miles north.
Sampson told Kipper that if she didn't call him by 3 a.m., he would
call and make sure she made it home.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 a.m. when Kipper left St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper never called.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the last person to see Kipper before she met her killer
was an Associated Foods truck driver who saw a car with its
flashers on sitting on the southbound shoulder of Interstate 29
after 2:34 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Another car was backing up the on ramp toward the stranded car.
</P>
<P>
   As the truck driver passed the cars, he saw a dark-haired white
female flagging traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Her face was stressed and concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper's mother found the abandoned car the next morning, its
battery dying and hazard lights blinking.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Williams went to a Gladstone shop to have his
windshield fixed.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, authorities who had been contacted about Kipper's
disappearance had no reason to even know who John E. Williams was.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Platte County Sheriff's Capt. Bill Taylor
interviewed six persons. Kipper's Sunday school teacher took her
picture to businesses near the area where the Probe had been found.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
