<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-05 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE BIGGEST PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I believe the voucher system in New York City would be very,
very troublesome,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in a speech to the
Wharton Club of New York in August 1995. ``Our system is so large
that making that kind of transition would pose tremendous
difficulties. Not to mention the constitutional and legal
difficulties that would be entailed in providing tax relief and tax
dollars for religious education.''
</P>
<P>
   Vouchers would ``weaken, if not create the collapse of the New
York City public school system,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now, as he tries to impress fellow Republicans
and win a U.S. Senate seat, he's in favor of vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was once a champion of Rudy Crew, the schools
chancellor, and claimed to be a close friend. But that was then.
Now he publicly treats Crew like yesterday's garbage and says the
school system should be blown up.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor before Crew was a decent and popular and
competent man named Ramon Cortines. Giuliani publicly humiliated
him and ran him out of town.
</P>
<P>
   The school system in New York has an insurmountable problem, and
his name is Rudolph Giuliani. There will be no substantial
improvement in the schools until he leaves City Hall and takes his
crazy-making behavior elsewhere. By that time the shell-shocked
Crew will most likely be gone, too. Few tears will be shed. There
are worse things than a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the schools are being treated cruelly. The latest
mantra is higher standards. The people chanting the loudest (
Giuliani foremost among them) must get a perverse kick out of
conning the city's 1.1 million students, because anybody with a
brain would know that we don't provide the system with anywhere
near the resources necessary to meet existing standards.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three years in office Giuliani drained more than $2
billion out of the system. He didn't start replacing that money
until he had to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Messinger, who ran against Giuliani for mayor, complained
in her campaign about overcrowding so severe that children were
being taught in lavatories. Randi Weingarten, the president of the
United Federation of Teachers, said this week: ``I remember when I
was still teaching in 1995 and 1996, there were times when I had to
go scavenging for chalk. I would go from room to room, and nobody
had any chalk.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are not as extreme now, but the schools are still
hurting badly. New York City spends about $8,000 annually per pupil
compared with the $12,000 spent by the average downstate suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have small enough class sizes, we don't pay our
teachers enough, and on and on,'' said Carol Gresser, a former
Board of Education president who was also publicly ridiculed by
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The first step toward a quality education is a well-prepared
teacher. The city has more than 10,000 uncertified teachers in its
schools, well over 10 percent of the total. Ms. Weingarten helped
put that in perspective when she noted that there were probably
only 500 uncertified teachers on the job throughout the rest of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Crew is moving to end social promotions, which could lead in the
short term to 300,000 students being left back. And the state is
imposing tough new Regents requirements that, by 2003, will require
all graduating high school students to pass stringent Regents
examinations. Just one of every five New York City students is
passing the current exams and graduating with a Regents diploma.
</P>
<P>
   As the Community Service Society noted: ``School districts
unable to prepare the majority of students to demonstrate mastery
of rudimentary skills are now asked to prepare students to
demonstrate a far more complex set of skills _ in English, global
studies, U.S. history, math and biology _ in just five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The tough work of preparing children to meet higher academic
standards requires a huge long-term commitment and lots and lots of
money. Neither Giuliani nor anyone else will say how that
commitment is to be carried out and from where that money will
come.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is that Giuliani is trying to get to Washington,
and he's ready to walk all over the public school students of New
York to get there.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
