<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIPPER-CASE-2NDTAKE-K     05-05 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIPPER-CASE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE PLACED PREDATOR IN CRYSTAL KIPPER'S PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 OSCAR AVILA AND BENITA Y. WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... where the Probe had been found.
</P>
<P>
   No one, it seemed, had seen Crystal Kipper.
</P>
<P>
   The police searched the area on foot and by helicopter. They
brought in dogs and searched the nearby Platte River.
</P>
<P>
   They found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began to focus on those who were among the
last to see Kipper _ her friends.
</P>
<P>
   All three were given voice stress tests. All three passed.
</P>
<P>
   Early leads went nowhere. Detectives reached a quick standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, meanwhile, continued life as usual.
</P>
<P>
   He sparred with his boss. He wrote letters containing reviews of
computer programs and tirades against black people.
</P>
<P>
   Inside his apartment, Williams was amassing a stash of
pornography, including pictures of children. Into some of the
pornographic videotapes he had spliced television news reports of
Kipper's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, police knew nothing of Williams and his activities. He
had not come to their attention, and might never have surfaced had
he not kidnapped Angela Amos on July 5 and tortured her and raped
her over a 10-day period before she escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe authorities would have found Williams anyway. Maybe he
would have slipped up. Or maybe the clues to Kipper's disappearance
would have remained Williams' secret forever.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't, because Amos was able to escape on July 14. She
told police about a man who bound her head with a bicycle lock,
smothered her until she passed out and threatened to inject her
with battery acid.
</P>
<P>
   Amos said he told her that he knew how to dispose of a body.
</P>
<P>
   With Amos' escape, Williams' problems intensified. That night,
he arrived at his ex-girlfriend's house shaking, sweating and sick.
</P>
<P>
   She said he was ``acting really weird _ more than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   He told her: ``The only way out of this for me is''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed his index finger to his head and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, police entered Williams' apartment with a passkey
and woke him. They were looking for padlocks, duct tape, wires and
weapons to implicate Williams in Amos' kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   They found a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Police discovered Crystal Kipper's ID cards, a paycheck stub,
jewelry, her car keys, a mock turtleneck and a pair of ``Lucky U''
brand jeans. They found a missing-person flier of Kipper, in
addition to computer files.
</P>
<P>
   But no blood. No body.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had little hard evidence against Williams.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams in jail on the kidnapping charges, police got to
work.
</P>
<P>
   DNA tests confirmed that the clothes belonged to Kipper, but
showed no evidence of blood or semen.
</P>
<P>
   Police did have Williams' story about what happened that night.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was driving along I-29 when something struck his
windshield. When he returned, he found the ``remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he panicked because he was a convicted sex
offender. He said he put the body in his car, backed up and drove
``forever, to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he disposed of the body. When asked where, Williams
replied cryptically that it didn't matter because the remains were
not on Earth and she was now ``part of the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Williams led detectives to the Platte City area.
They drove around for two hours. Williams claimed he didn't
remember where he dumped the body. He acknowledged that his actions
caused Kipper's death.
</P>
<P>
   When police asked Williams about the windshield he fixed the
next day, Williams responded with an expletive and dropped his jaw.
His arms fell to the table. He denied that the windshield had been
broken by someone kicking it during a struggle. Authorities think
he was lying.
</P>
<P>
   An expert told police that damage to Kipper's clothes was
``consistent with a homicide,'' not someone having been struck by a
car.
</P>
<P>
   Police added the information to hundreds of tips they had
received that year. Some implicated other suspects. One man drew
authorities a map, saying he had a dream about Kipper's
whereabouts. A woman said she was a psychic who felt an urge to
find Kipper in some woods near Platte County.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Kipper did her part. Once, authorities met her along the
highway after her foraging discovered a piece of used duct tape.
Was it a clue?
</P>
<P>
   Other callers kept coming back to the fields of southern Platte
County.
</P>
<P>
   A man called the TIPS hot line and said he was driving on
Highway FF in the spring of 1997 when he saw Williams standing
outside a vehicle. He said Williams stared at him and made a
barking sound.
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City man said he saw a ``very ugly'' man leaving the
woods that March along Missouri 45. He said the man tried to hide
his face by turning it toward his shoulder. The witness was one of
several who described a putrid odor from that area, smelling like a
dead, decaying body.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a bait shop said she often sold equipment to
Williams, who fished on the Platte River. She thought Williams
fished at the bridge on Missouri 45.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives, meanwhile, were hearing from Williams' cellmates.
</P>
<P>
   One inmate said Williams had bragged about killing Kipper and
burying her near Worlds of Fun. Williams told him that he killed
her near where her body was buried. And Williams said he could not
be convicted in Missouri because police did not have a body.
</P>
<P>
   Another inmate said he had overheard Williams tell someone that
he killed Kipper. Again, Williams expressed confidence that no one
would find the body.
</P>
<P>
   But there were holes in the inmates' stories.
</P>
<P>
   One inmate said Williams told him about a lot of blood in the
vehicle. Police found none.
</P>
<P>
   In March of this year, authorities gave the evidence to
prosecutors, who said they planned to file formal charges this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams intervened. On April 24, he hanged himself in jail,
even though he was on suicide watch. He left no suicide note, but
authorities think he knew he was about to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were waiting for Kipper's mother to return from a
trip. She was on a cruise in the Pacific, trying to find peace.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' death means she might never find it. Authorities have
closed the case and Platte County Sheriff Dick Anderson said ``it
would probably be a coincidence if Kipper's body was located.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Anna Kipper's only memorial to her daughter is a white
cross along I-29, behind a hill that blocks out the lights of
Platte City.
</P>
<P>
   Fate brought Crystal Kipper and John Williams together. Chance
led her avengers to Williams' door.
</P>
<P>
   And now Anna Kipper thinks there is only one way her daughter
will ever be found so her family and friends can mourn her
properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take divine intervention at this point,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
