A5777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JESSE06-COX     05-05 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JESSE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson tells of `journey of faith'
 &HT;    By Gayle White and Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At a news conference and luncheon speech that took on
the tones of a Sunday morning church service, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson told Atlantans on Wednesday that his recent trip to Kosovo
was ``a journey of faith rooted in prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clergy and church leaders at Atlanta's Antioch Baptist Church
North responded loudly with ``amen'' and ``yes, sir,'' as Jackson
compared his meeting with Serbian President Slobodon Milosevic to
Moses's demand to pharoah in the Hebrew Bible's story of Exodus to
``let my people go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went as a preacher of the gospel and the word had a
liberating power,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson headed a group of clergy who went to Yugoslavia last
week and emerged on Sunday with three American soldiers formerly
held captive by the Serbs. U.S. officials warned the ministers that
NATO bombing of Serbia would not cease while they were there,
Jackson said, ``but our group had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been criticized in some quarters for meeting with
Milosevic. In answer to accusations that he had been ``used'' by
the Serbian leader, Jackson said, ``We meant to be used and, if
necessary, sacrificed. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Jackson told the CNN World Report Conference,
an annual gathering of international journalists, ``We must break
the cycle of fear and give peace a chance. . . We must search for
an all-winners solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson cited several past peace initiatives, from Nixon's
ping-pong diplomacy to Carter's Camp David accord between Isreal
and Egypt. He said the current conflict needs ``just a little talk,
just a little daylight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking past each other,'' Jackson said of President
Bill Clinton and Milosevic. ``That's the gulf. That's why they need
the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson emphasized he had visited Belgrade not as an emissary of
the United States government. ``I was a religious envoy, a moral
envoy. I was not there as a negotiator. I offered a possibility of
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he hoped his successful release of the prisoners
had not embarrassed Clinton. ``He is my president. He is my friend.
His options are different from mine.''
</P>
<P>
   At the church, Jackson emphasized that after ``forty days and
forty nights'' of NATO bombs falling on Serbia, NATO leaders should
re-evaluate their position. ``We're now at the crossroads in this
struggle . . . Bombs keep falling and the exodus continues. We
bomb, they purge. There's no talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from the Gospel of John, Jackson said, ``In the
beginning was the Word. The word speaks worlds into existence. With
no talk there is no change. With no talk, there is no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson condemned the persecution of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
that provoked the NATO bombing of Serbia. ``What Milosovic is doing
is unconscionable,'' he said. And, he characterized as ``morally
sound'' the U.S. demands that Milosevic stop the violence against
the Kosovars, repatriate those who have been exiled and accept an
international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, rather than escalating the military effort to
involve ground troops, NATO leaders should step back and attempt a
diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a former presidential candidate, said he has decided to
keep his emphasis on his own role as a minister and not to run for
president. ``Politics by its nature drives you toward consensus and
conformity,'' he said. ``Religion drives you toward conscience and
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   To be faithful means to take chances, he said. ``The gospel is
more difficult to live than to preach, but more rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
