<SLUG> BC-HENDRICKS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS NO ORDINARY GARDEN SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MIKE HENDRICKS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lady of the house demanded the big geraniums.
</P>
<P>
   Not those puny ones you find at the stores this time of year.
But big, honking geraniums in the three-gallon pots, and to heck
with the cost. The yard simply had to look like the Fourth of July,
even if it was barely May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the party they're planning, it has to be an instant
garden,'' Kathi Krouch, a gardener with Uncommon Grounds Inc.,
explained as we stood in the driveway of the house on Mission
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations are very high here.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course. Expectations are always high in Mission Hills,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Lovely Mission Hills, the garden spot of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Early this century, J.C. Nichols designed his premier
subdivision not just as a haven for the rich. Not just as a place
of narrow lanes lined with Mediterranean-style villas and castles
of ivy-covered brick.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Hills was to be more than that.
</P>
<P>
   It was to be a community within a garden. Around each curve, a
pleasant vista.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Hills remains true to Nichols' vision. It's a suburban
Eden encompassing 1,343 acres abutting State Line Road.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of town, you're lucky the neighbors clip the weeds
before they go to seed.
</P>
<P>
   In Mission Hills, it's assumed the flower beds will be lush and
colorful, the grass as thick as a Persian rug, the trees pruned to
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real particular,'' Don Birks of Kansas City said as he
dumped a bag of grass clippings into the back of his pickup. ``It's
good money around here. They don't care what it costs, just make it
look pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Cedar Creek may be pleasant. Hallbrook, oh so nice. But the
Mission Hills accounts are the ones the landscaping crews prefer
for the same reason the city's fortunate few choose to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Money and beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Monday through Friday, so many lawn and garden crews from around
the region park their rigs there that it's hard to squeeze through
the narrow lanes. On every block, you hear the sounds of leaf
blowers, mowers and weed whackers.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Chris Jackson of Rosehill Gardens proudly
displayed muddy hands fresh from the flower beds of Don and Adele
Hall, the Halls of Hallmark fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have gorgeous yards to work in, gorgeous flowers,'' she
says. ``There's no limit to what it takes to make it look
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's a pleasant place to spend a day digging the bulbs
and trimming trees. But more than a few landscape workers wonder
whether their clients have as much time to enjoy the surroundings
as they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people we work for are rarely at home,'' says Ron
Chiswell of Belton, who's been mowing lawns in Mission Hills for 25
years. ``You wonder why they have a yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's true of some, but not all are too busy to enjoy the
fruits of their fortunes. Many Mission Hills residents work closely
with the tree men and the spray crews and the sprinkler system
repair specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on the day we met, Jackson was tending the vinca, per
the personal instructions of her company's high-profile client.
Jackson's understanding was that the yard was being primped for an
upcoming social affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Mrs. Hall picky about the weeds?'' I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, she doesn't care about the weeds,'' Jackson said, smiling,
``as long as she can't see them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
