<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS REPUBLICAN BOLTS PARTY ON HATE CRIMES BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Republican member of the Texas House accused
his own party Wednesday of pressuring state senators to prevent a
hate crimes proposal from reaching Gov. George W. Bush's desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very emotional issue for the Republican Party,''
said Rep. Tommy Merritt of Longview.
</P>
<P>
   The James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act, named in memory the black
man who was dragged to death behind a truck last year in Jasper,
would toughen certain penalties for crimes that target people
because of their race, gender, sexual preference or religion. A
white man was convicted of murdering Byrd and two other men are
awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was approved by the state House last week on a
83-61 vote. The House is controlled by Democrats while the Senate
has a Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Criminal Justice Committee is expected to consider
the measure at a hearing Thursday, but its prospects before the
committee, as well as in the full Senate, are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, said only one Republican senator
has even hinted he might vote for the measure if it makes it to the
full Senate. None of the four Republicans on the seven-member
Criminal Justice Committee has said he or she would support it,
Ellis added.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Merritt joined a group of
Democrats from the House and Senate to support the measure. He also
said he believes Republican senators are being pushed to vote
against the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there has been pressure applied by the Republican
Party to prevent people from voting their districts, from voting
their convictions,'' Merritt said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, suggested that presidential
politics was playing a role in the matter because of provisions in
the legislation covering crimes committed against people based on
their sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe obviously there are political considerations,''
Whitmire said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is leaning toward running for the Republican presidential
nomination next year, and could face attacks from social
conservatives in his party if he were to sign into law legislation
with a sexual preference provision.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wouldn't say Wednesday if he would sign such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will look at the bill when it comes off the floor of the
Senate to see if I can live with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past, he has expressed some resistance to the
legislation, saying, ``All crime is hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claims by Merritt, Texas GOP spokesman Robert Black
said he doesn't know of any effort by party officials to influence
GOP senators on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no pressure being exerted on anyone by the party,''
Black said. ``However, we've been very clear that the Republican
Party thinks the legislation is a very dangerous bill that would
create a justice system where one life is more important than
another. We don't think that's good public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Wentworth, R-San Antonio, said he has not been lobbied
by fellow Republicans on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has told me how to vote on this issue,'' said
Wentworth, who plans to vote against the bill if it goes before the
full Senate. ``I am going to vote my conscience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1948EDT &QL; 
