A5781 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINCER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      05-05 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINCER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVER YOUR OWN BEST ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pamela Gilberd learned from experience that getting fired isn't
always bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose your job, I congratulate you,'' she said. ``Now
you have a choice to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   After a varied career in teaching, modeling and the airlines,
Gilberd worked for 10 years in marketing and sales for an umbrella
company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her success, she was fired because of downsizing. Losing
her job was traumatic initially, but it forced her to re-evaluate
her life and make choices she wouldn't otherwise have made.
</P>
<P>
   It also motivated her to learn more about successful women and
to write about these individuals. She received 24 rejections and
wrote three book proposals before getting ``The Eleven Commandments
of Wildly Successful Women'' published.
</P>
<P>
   As Gilberd traveled the country lecturing and talking about the
book, she often encountered women with what she calls the ``woulda,
coulda, shoulda syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though these women were supportive and decisive with
friends and family, they suffered from chronic indecision,
self-criticism and self-doubt when it came to their own lives and
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The women already knew the answers to their questions, Gilberd
said. But they asked questions because they wanted someone to
validate their choices. They wanted someone to give them permission
to act on their intuition.
</P>
<P>
   Gilberd's newest book, ``The Twelfth Commandment of Wildly
Successful Women,'' is designed to help people make these tough
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 12th commandment is to discover your own best answer,''
said Gilberd, who spoke recently at a local American Business
Women's Association Express Network meeting. ``They need to know
there are choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is divided into sections in which a composite character
must make a decision about work, family or other issues. Each
chapter includes four possible consequences that depend on the
decision someone makes.
</P>
<P>
   Gilberd hopes this will help readers make choices, since they
can see different consequences of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   She has several suggestions to help people make decisions. For
starters, release yourself from the coulda, woulda, shoulda
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Recognize you have choices, and consider more than one option
before making up your mind.
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial to do your homework, she said. So arm yourself with
lots of information.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gilberd recommends that you write a ``screenplay''
about your dilemma with several outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important of all, we need to trust ourselves.
Sometimes that's difficult. Sometimes people don't agree with our
decisions. But the worst possible choice we can make is not acting
at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      05-05 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH BIGGER KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING FORCE WILL BE NEEDED, OFFICIALS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(bl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY with ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO allies now believe they will need
nearly twice the 28,000 peacekeeping troops they originally planned
to station in Kosovo in a negotiated settlement, allied and U.S.
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and other NATO officials said the alliance would need
perhaps as many as 50,000 soldiers to enforce any Kosovo
settlement, even if NATO bombing eventually forced Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept allied demands to stop
attacking ethnic Albanian civilians in the province, withdraw
Serbian forces and let the refugees and peacekeepers enter
unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   Under NATO's original plan, the United States would have
contributed 4,000 soldiers to a peacekeeping force, but that number
is likely to grow substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Allied planners in Brussels and in Washington said more troops
would be necessary to quell scattered resistance from Serbian
paramilitary groups and to detect and destroy hundreds, if not
thousands, of land mines laid by Yugoslav forces. They would also
be needed to help begin rebuilding devastated villages in Kosovo, a
necessary step before hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanian
refugees can return.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have said the force could include soldiers from
Russia and other countries outside NATO if they wanted to take
part. NATO has taken to describing it as ``an international
presence with NATO at its core,'' under a United Nations Security
Council mandate, like the 20,000-member force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian has already rejected one plan that was proposed early
and is still being mentioned by military planners, officials said.
Under this scenario, the international peacekeeping forces would
divide Kosovo into four sectors of responsibility. A northern
sector, adjacent to Serbia, would be monitored by Russia. The two
southern sectors, along the Albania and Macedonia borders, would be
overseen by NATO countries. The final sector, in between, would be
monitored by some neutral country.
</P>
<P>
   But a State Department official said Russia had rejected that
option during early discussions about the composition of a
peacekeeping force, arguing that the notion of sectors harkened
back to the Cold War and to a divided Germany.
</P>
<P>
   However it is organized, the force in Kosovo would have to be
far larger than 28,000, officials said Wednesday. ``A lot of
difficult tasks will be more onerous,'' a senior U.S. official
said. ``The force will likely have to be at least somewhat
larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials would not be specific about how large. But NATO
commanders denied Wednesday that there was any plan under active
consideration to send troops into Kosovo as long as Serbian forces
were still there and able to resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all a what-happens-if-we-win plan,'' a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied spokesmen said NATO's two top military officers, Gen.
Wesley Clark of the United States and Gen. Klaus Naumann of
Germany, told President Clinton during his short visit to the
alliance's headquarters Wednesday that there was no reason to
abandon the allied strategy of bombing Serbian military forces and
installations until Milosevic gives in and lets more than a million
ethnic Albanian refugees go back to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy was chosen late last year after allied military
leaders worked out contingency plans to deal with the emerging
crisis. There are now more than a dozen such plans, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Among the options not chosen but kept on the shelf and
occasionally dusted off, allied officers say, is one that would
have required 200,000 soldiers before the bombing started to invade
Kosovo and drive out the 40,000 Serbian military and police forces
that have since expelled most of the province's ethnic Albanian
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, subsequently ruled out, would have gone even
further with an allied invasion of Belgrade to force Milosevic to
capitulate, according to a senior allied official.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the 28,000 peacekeepers, including 4,000
Americans, who were to have gone into Kosovo if last winter's peace
negotiations at Rambouillet Castle in France had succeeded, and the
much larger force that would have been needed to fight the Serbs
out of Kosovo, is another option that allied commanders insist they
do not have under active consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That option would be to send in a few tens of thousands of
allied ground troops after more weeks of bombing had so demoralized
Milosevic's forces in Kosovo that they could not fight back
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   But officials say those troops would have to start going in by
midsummer to have any chance of letting more than 400,000 refugees
in Albania and nearly 140,000 in Macedonia, plus 650,000 people who
took to the hills in Kosovo, find permanent shelter in the province
before freezing weather sets in during the fall.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair tried to persuade Clinton and
the other allies in Washington last month to put such an option
back on the front burner, allied officials said, but ran up against
resistance from U.S. commanders who insisted that it was not
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are winning,'' Clark told Clinton in Brussels on Wednesday.
``The leadership, its military and security forces and its support
infrastructure are vulnerable to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, with Clinton in Spangdahlem Air Base in Germany, Clark
said there was not ``a bit of truth'' in a published report that
said NATO was preparing a plan to send 60,000 troops into Kosovo by
late July to take over the province and chase out the remaining
Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said just before the start
of the NATO summit in Washington in April that the alliance would
review and refresh all the various contingency plans for ground
troops. Solana and other officials in Brussels gave Clinton a
general progress report Wednesday on those updates, a senior U.S.
official said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime Clark, using the NATO acronym for a Kosovo
peacekeeping force, said later Wednesday: ``There are a number of
reviews under way, and I suspect that one will be made available in
NATO in the near future to do with how the KFOR mission should be
further enhanced and modified, as we look at the changing situation
on the ground in Kosovo. That's the review that's hot on our plate
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the need for more than 28,000 peacekeepers in Kosovo
even if Milosevic finally accepts allied demands, a senior U.S.
official said, ``The force will now have the Herculean task of
returning one million refugees to their homes, and this will place
more demands on it than were originally planned for.''
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers would also now have to remove thousands of land
mines planted by Serbian forces all over Kosovo and oversee the
rebuilding of civilian houses that Serbian paramilitaries and
soldiers have partly destroyed or burned to discourage the ethnic
Albanians from trying to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crops have not been planted, so the food supply's not there,''
Clark said. ``Homes have been destroyed, roofs ripped off, houses,
apartments blown up, and whole villages apparently just
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So even when they're allowed to go home, life won't be normal
for a while,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of refugees from Kosovo would be a task that
occupied the allies and international civilian aid agencies for
many months, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that, yes, we have to look very much ahead, past the
summer, into the autumn, the winter and even the next spring,''
Clark said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
