<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS SHOW MANDELA'S PARTY CLOSE TO ELECTION GOAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A flurry of recent polls show that
President Nelson Mandela's ruling African National Congress is
edging closer to the two-thirds majority it is seeking in South
Africa's second post-apartheid election scheduled for June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, polls showed that support for the party had dipped to
as low as 51 percent in the face of the country's growing
unemployment and rising crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   But with only four weeks to go before the elections, several
polls show that the African National Congress _ which has been
energetically campaigning for the 66 percent majority that would
give it the power to make changes to the constitution _ may well
reach its goal.
</P>
<P>
   One poll, released Wednesday by the Institute for Democracy,
said the party had the support of 59 percent of the electorate. But
if voting turn out was low, researchers for the Institute, said
that the ANC's overall share of the vote could be as high as 67
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by another non-profit research group, the Human
Sciences Research Council, showed that support for the party had
risen in March to 62 percent, up from 57 in December. Again,
researchers said a low turn out would help them over the line.
</P>
<P>
   The South African election season has been slow to take hold in
part because there has been little question about who the winner
will be. The ANC has tried to make its goal of a two-thirds
majority a rallying cry for its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a goal that has raised concerns among its critics,
many of whom are wary of what will happen to this fledgling
democracy if one party should have such power.
</P>
<P>
   The African National Congress, which won 63 percent of the vote
in 1994, has fueled this concern by being vague about what it wants
to do with a two-thirds majority. Some officials have seemed to
suggest that they would remove or reconstruct some of the watchdog
agencies that are for the time being very independent of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   There also has been talk that the African National Congress
wants to have more power over the country's 11 provincial
governments, which have had trouble delivering services and running
efficient administrations.
</P>
<P>
   But even Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, who is expected to become
the country's next president, seems unwilling to explain why the
African National Congress chose to focus on this goal. During a
television interview on April 18, he brushed aside the question,
saying that all political parties sought ``overwhelming''
majorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, South Africa seems to be involved in two
secondary political contests: Whether the ANC can get its
overwhelming majority and which party will emerge as the leader
among the pack of opposition parties fighting over the crumbs. The
new surveys seemed to show the crumbs are getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The New National Party, which used to run the country under
apartheid appears to still have the edge in the opposition race,
with about 8 percent of the vote according to the IDASA poll.
However, that is a long way from the 20 percent it got in 1994. The
liberal Democratic Party, which never supported apartheid, is close
at 6 percent, up from 2 percent in the last elections. The
Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party looks to have 4 percent of the
vote, down from 8.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed United Democratic Party, which is trying to
offer itself as a multiracial alternative and appeared to surge in
popularity earlier this year, only has about 2 percent of the vote
at the moment, according to IDASA.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that the African National Congress' recent gains
come largely from the voters who used to say that they were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that as of mid-march 1999, South Africa's
opposition parties have failed to take advantage of the weaknesses
in ANC support and the large number of undecided voters that our
first survey uncovered,'' the researchers said in their analysis.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, still a large number of undecideds _ 17
percent, according to the IDASA poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
