<SLUG> BC-KC-BLOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER KILLER STORM, SURPRISE FOR MANY IN TOWN IS THAT THEY
SURVIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Scores of families used to live here, in brick
houses and duplexes under shade trees, with pictures on the walls
and food in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains of Shirley Phillips' home is the frame of the
bedroom closet that shielded her family from the twister. The wide,
black funnel plowed across Interstate 35 on Monday and ate
everything up and down Phillips' block in about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   They lived here, more than 300 strong, in a subdivision called
Moore Highland, a few miles south of Oklahoma City. Many of them
wondered aloud how they escaped dying here.
</P>
<P>
   At the police barricade on Northeast 27th Street and Highland
Avenue, families embraced and pleaded with authorities to let them
through so they might retrieve some photos or prescription medicine
or a pet. One teen-age boy who was allowed in came back two hours
later bouncing a basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I could find from our house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips lived around the corner from that boy. How she managed
to stay alive Monday night, along with her 6-year-old daughter, a
3-year-old grand-daughter and a sister-in-law _ all huddled in that
closet behind the bifold doors _ she could not explain. In fact,
only three bodies had been pulled from the devastation in Moore
Highland as of late Tuesday, a police official said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hundreds who stumbled out of the debris Monday,
caked in the dust of fiberglass insulation, credited their closets
or their bathtubs; this was a modest 1960s-style development where
basements were rare.
</P>
<P>
   About 7 p.m. Monday, as civil defense sirens wailed and TVs
flashed warnings of what was bearing down on Moore, a city of
40,000, the Phillips family sat down in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have sung `Precious Memories' to my babies four or five
times to keep them calm,'' Shirley Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right before it hit, everything got real quiet and dark, and
then came this huge roar and the bedroom windows shattered and I
looked up and saw this swirling in the bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   The roof had been ripped off, and there in the swirling was all
that Phillips owned _ bedding, clothing, groceries and a painting
that hung in the dining room. Only her pool table stayed put, and
the purse she left on top of it didn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   A block away, Trina Shannon trembled in a bathtub beneath a
mattress with her infant daughter. As the tornado passed, it wanted
to yank the whole bathroom floor skyward. Shannon felt the tub
rattle and the wall behind her head bulge.
</P>
<P>
   The bathroom stood. The rest of her duplex crumbled. ``I had
seen that tornado jump across I-35 so big, so black, so wide,''
Shannon said. Authorities think it was a half-mile wide at its
base, large enough to swallow the subdivision in one gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's husband, Lincoln, was racing home from work on the
interstate when it happened. By the time he reached the exit ramp
leading to the neighborhood, police had blocked it off. All he
could see from his driver's side window was the First Baptist
Church, the Texaco station on the corner and acres of rubble where
the homes stood.
</P>
<P>
   He drove a mile past other parked cars and emergency vehicles
before finding a place to pull over. He ran at top speed to reach
Moore Highland, and he found his wife standing in the ruin amid a
web of power lines strewn like cobwebs. She was clutching their
baby daughter. Both were OK.
</P>
<P>
   The Shannons returned Tuesday and found their baby stroller, a
pair of sneakers and a few sweaters in the remains of their home.
Pushing the stroller back to their car, Trina Shannon said, ``Well,
we've got to start over.'' She said they were not insured.
</P>
<P>
   They're spending the week at a hotel. Dozens of their neighbors
have found shelter in the First Baptist Church, where the Red Cross
tacked up computer printouts listing more than 200 ``found people''
and a few ``lost people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming in and saying they can't find a mother,
can't find a grandmother, but so far we've been able to help locate
many more people than not,'' said volunteer Carla Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Angie Thompson, a youth worker for an ecumenical group called
Faith Believers, spent Monday night and most of Tuesday with
families now homeless in Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little blond boy told me he knew God was with him because he
was praying to God when the storm hit,'' Thompson said. ``As for
the doubters, I tell them I don't have any answers.''
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, First Baptist was taking in truckloads of
items donated from across Oklahoma: boxes of canned peaches and
peanut butter, toys, paper towels, lawn furniture, diapers, soda
pop and saltines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have enough? We can't have enough for this disaster,'' a
Cleveland County relief worker said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church, a chunk of wood the size of a baseball bat
had somehow lodged into the concrete cross that towers above 27th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Vans and mattresses were tossed 200 feet over chain-link fences
and into the interstate overpass. Utility poles were shaved off at
their bases. At a restaurant and bar up the street, adults throwing
a birthday party Monday night could only crouch and stare out the
window as the twister rolled in from the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drink up. The liquor's free,'' a bartender nervously joked as
the funnel passed a mile to the south, barely missing the Moore
water tower.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south and west, at West Moore High School, the tornado
had thrown 150 cars in the parking lot and at least one horse out
of the way. Some 300 students and their parents were attending an
awards ceremony inside the auditorium when the warning sirens
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   They took cover in the hallways, and though the storm heavily
damaged the school, nobody inside died and only a few suffered
``superficial injuries,'' said City Councilman Jerry Foshee. ``Just
the corridors kept them out of harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaylon Core of West Moore jumped into his pickup with his son,
daughter and dog as the twister neared. ``We just boogied out of
there as fast as we could,'' he said, but the tornado seemed intent
on trailing them.
</P>
<P>
   As Core sped east on 27th Street, he glanced out his
passenger-side window and saw the funnel passing him. By the time
he reached his girlfriend's home in Del City about 10 miles away,
the tornado had already damaged 600 homes there, leveling many.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to get out of the path of disaster, you
realize that your kids, your dog and your truck is about all in
life that you need,'' Core said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the Moore Highland subdivision realized Tuesday that
for all they had lost, they somehow hung onto their lives. They
thanked the early warnings, which gave them a good hour to prepare,
and they praised their little closets, corridors and bathtubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at all that mess, I feel very lucky,'' said Shirley
Phillips as she clutched the hand of her daughter, Tori. ``How
about you, Tori? Do you feel lucky, honey?''
</P>
<P>
   The little girl just gazed at the vista of ruin where she and
her friends used to skip rope. She had nothing to say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
