<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S OPPOSITION PARTY TONES DOWN CALL FOR INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Reaching for the political center as it prepares for a
presidential election, Taiwan's main opposition party is softening
its call for formal independence from China, once its defining
trait.
</P>
<P>
   The popular former mayor of Taipei, Chen Shui-bian, is the
party's likely candidate in the election next March, which will be
only the second direct election for president here. But to have any
chance of winning, his Democratic Progressive Party needs to
reassure voters that it will not provoke a dangerous confrontation
with China, which considers Taiwan an errant province.
</P>
<P>
   At a party congress this weekend, a new statement will be added
to the party's charter. It is intended to signal that, if elected
to national power, the Democratic Progressives would not take
precipitous action _ like calling a plebiscite on the island's
status or officially adopting ``Republic of Taiwan'' as a national
name _ that could shake the prosperity and de facto independence
which Taiwan now enjoys. A draft of the new statement was adopted
by a committee Wednesday for final approval on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that independence sentiment remains deep among
many core supporters, the charter will not be overhauled as
sweepingly as Chen and others had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The draft statement says the status quo is acceptable only
because Taiwan is in effect already sovereign, and it pointedly
rejects the concept of ``one China'' so cherished by the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should give Chen Shui-bian what he needs to show that the
party is not to be feared,'' said Fu-Hsiung Shen, a legislator and
a close ally of Chen, in a telephone interview. ``But any deeper
change would create another hazard: people would say the party sold
its soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking overt independence was the founding goal of the
Democratic Progressive Party when it emerged in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Nationalist Party _ founded by Chiang Kai-shek,
who was driven from the mainland in 1949 by the Communists _ has
consistently maintained in principle that it seeks reunification
with China, though in practice, Taiwan has aggressively sought an
independent identity.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, Chen and other Democratic Progressive leaders have
begun to backtrack on the independence issue, and the positions of
the two major parties have been converging. But largely because of
personal rivalries, it now appears that the election could be a
melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwanese politics in coming years may be in for an
upheaval,'' said Chu Yun-han, a political scientist at National
Taiwan University.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, after losing his mayor's seat in a suspenseful election in
December, remains popular around the island and is seen as a
domestic reformer. But his party may be weakened by the defection
of its former chairman, Hsu Hsin-liang, who has long had his heart
set on running for president. Hsu has said he intends to run on his
own ticket.
</P>
<P>
   With Popular Nationalist President Lee Teng-hui, who must step
down next year after his four-year term, the Nationalist Party
still has the broadest public support and the strongest
organization, but it may suffer a more catastrophic split. The
likely candidate for president will be Vice President Lien Chan,
but another Nationalist powerhouse and a rival of Lee, James Soong,
has indicated that he may bolt and run on his own, too. And in
opinion polls, Soong has greater support than either Chen or Lian.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Nationalist Party is united, then I think it can crush
Chen Shui-bian,'' said Chu, the political scientist. ``But if James
Soong enters and there is a three-way race, then Chen Shui-bian
will have a fighting chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
