u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-PAY-ART-NYT &LR;      05-05 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-PAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED MILITARY PAY HIKE POPULAR, BUT WILL IT RETAIN KEY
PERSONNEL? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few issues have generated more bipartisan support
this year or moved faster down the legislative track than the drive
to increase pay and pensions for the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed a plan in January with a
price tag of $36 billion over the next decade. The Senate passed a
10-year, $62 billion package by a vote of 91 to 8 in February. On
Thursday, the House will take up a measure to provide $1.8 billion
for the first year _ all of it on an emergency basis, which would
allow the appropriation to dodge the tight limits that budget rules
impose on most spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is strong, overwhelming bipartisan support in the
Congress this year to make some changes in pay, in retirement, in
enlistment and re-enlistment bonuses,'' President Clinton told
troops on his visit to Ramstein Air Base in Germany on Wednesday.
``And those things, plus some other things we're going to do, I
hope will help to keep more of you in the service and I hope will
help to get more young people coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the political appeal _ especially in the midst of a
military conflict _ of giving a raise to the men and women who put
their lives on the line for the country, a wide array of government
and private analysts question whether the billions of dollars will
solve the main problem the money is intended to address: the exodus
of skilled personnel in midcareer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruitment and retention is a real problem that needs to be
addressed,'' said Steven Kosiak, an analyst at the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, a research group. ``But it's a
classic situation where you shouldn't just throw money at a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the costliest measures being considered by Congress
this year, a raise could also test the commitment of both parties
to keep spending in check.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal watchdog groups are particularly concerned about plans to
reverse a military pension cut imposed in 1986, a provision of both
the administration and Senate measures. Such a turnabout, they say,
would not only be extremely expensive for decades to come but also
send the wrong signal as Congress struggles to address the looming
insolvency of the Social Security and Medicare systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when our nation is preparing for the fiscal
challenges of an aging population by debating the tough choices
involved in Social Security and Medicare reform, we can ill afford
to undo one of the few tough choices about long-term spending that
already have been made,'' said Robert Bixby, policy director of the
Concord Coalition, an organization that promotes budget discipline.
</P>
<P>
   A few members of Congress have questioned any need to rush
through a bill, saying the issue of keeping highly trained
personnel like pilots in the armed services is complicated and
involves factors other than pay and pensions, among them lengthy
deployments away from families and the quality of health care and
housing.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals ``are not silver bullets that will solve the
retention problem,'' said Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., chairman of the
House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel. ``There is
a risk that once we spend the money to implement all those
proposals, we will still likely be confronted with lagging
retention that continues to degrade readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, Pentagon officials have encountered
nothing but support from the administration and Congress for their
case that better pay and retirement plans are a crucial component
of their efforts to reverse a slide in recruiting and stem the
departure of the people the military most needs to keep.
</P>
<P>
   The latest backing came last week from the House Appropriations
Committee, which added $1.8 billion for military pay next year to
the bill for emergency spending on the conflict in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   As with the rest of the bill, which seeks a total of $12.9
billion in emergency spending for the Kosovo operation and a
variety of other military needs, the $1.8 billion for military pay
would fall outside the limits imposed by the government's usual
spending caps, but only if President Clinton certified that dealing
with the issue qualified as a national emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Senate, which has authorized a pay raise but not yet
appropriated money for it, will adopt a similar emergency approach
is unclear. In any case, Clinton has not said whether he would
designate military raises an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal calls for a 4.4 percent military
pay increase next year, followed by raises in subsequent years
matching civilian compensation growth. It would provide bonuses of
up to 9.9 percent for selected midcareer personnel and improve the
pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version would add to the raise, increasing pay by 4.8
percent next year and setting subsequent raises half a percentage
point above civilian wage growth. It would increased the size of
the midcareer bonuses to 10.3 percent, and further sweeten the
pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   As for the House, although it is about to vote on financing the
first year of a pay increase, it has yet to take up legislation
detailing how the money would be spent.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties have largely swept aside warnings from the
Congressional Budget Office and the General Accounting Office that
the pay gap between the civilian work force and the military may be
exaggerated and that increased retirement benefits are unlikely to
stem skilled personnel's departure from the service.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the budget office found that the 1986 pension
cut _ to 40 percent of base pay after 20 years of service, from 50
percent _ had had no significant impact on early retirement
decisions. Reversing that cut, a move that would cost $14.3 billion
over the next decade, would therefore probably do little to help
retain midcareer personnel, the CBO concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
