<SLUG> BC-SENATE-CRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRA ALLOWS BANKS TO BE BLACKMAILED, GRAMM CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A 1994 agreement between a Boston banking activist
and Fleet Financial Group Inc. was highlighted on the Senate floor
Wednesday as a prominent lawmaker argued for changes to a federal
law that requires banks to loan money to low-income homebuyers and
inner-city businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying large posters with language from the 1994 deal,
Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas, argued that a federal law
called the Community Reinvestment Act had given a Boston organizer
undue clout in persuading Fleet to commit money to his group.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the deal had not previously been made public,
and Gramm did not mention the activist, Bruce Marks, or Fleet by
name. But Marks Wednesday said that the contract Gramm displayed
was from his deal with Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   That deal has been the subject of wide attention in Boston. It
was signed after Marks and his Neighborhood Assistance Corp. of
America highlighted predatory lending practices by banks in several
Boston neighborhoods in which homeowners were persuaded to sign
second mortgages at very high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   By drawing attention to lending activities by a former Fleet
subsidiary, Marks was able to win a commitment from Fleet to make
$140 million available for loans to low-income and minority
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm Wednesday said that federal law had given community
groups the clout to ``blackmail'' banks by threatening to lodge
complaints with regulators unless they win loan commitments and
cash payments.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm is proposing changes to the Community Reinvestment Act
that he says would limit the power of community groups seeking
commitments from banks. Others say Gramm's changes would prompt
banks to reduce their lending in low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   One of several contracts displayed by Gramm Wednesday showed
that an unnamed bank agreed to pay a community group 2.75 percent
of the value of loans made under a $140 million loan program. The
contract also showed that the bank would pay the group $200,000 to
cover start-up costs for administering the loan program.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the community group agreed to ``withdraw all
pending protests'' before regulators against the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm had removed the name of the bank and the community group,
but Marks said they were Fleet and the Neighborhood Assistance
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Marks said that payments by Fleet to his group cover the cost of
services provided to low-income borrowers. Marks's group finds
potential borrowers, offers credit counseling, and guides them
through the mortgage process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take people two, three years to get ready to be able to
purchase a home,'' Marks said. ``Look at all the services we do,
then at the fees we get, and you'll see we don't get enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
