A5792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCORCHER06-COX     05-05 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCORCHER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters survive Six Flags' Scorcher
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A sudden blur of purple-and-gold twisted steel
accompanied by the suppressed cries of fellow riders. The sensation
of being pulled apart while airborne.
</P>
<P>
   This is amusement.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Scorcher, Six Flags Over Georgia's first stand-up
roller coaster, was christened Wednesday with more than 100
firefighters on the inaugural ride. Firefighters from 16
departments showed up for a free ride in full gear, jogging from
their trucks to the coaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Scorcher provides adrenaline junkies with a healthy dose of
fear and excitement. Riders straddle a bicyclelike seat while
standing with their knees slightly bent. A U-shaped harness bar
keeps riders from falling out. There is no enclosure, so those
brave souls in the outside seats have nothing between them and the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Riders climb more than 10 stories before the first downhill run.
The top speed is 54 miles per hour. The cars fly up and over six
times on high-speed loops, spirals, a camel back, corkscrew and a
figure-eight. G-forces pull the tears out of your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smooth, 2 1/2-minute ride without the jerking and pulling
of some coasters. ``It's real exciting _ better than fighting
fires,'' Fulton County firefighter Antonio Hines said while trying
to catch his breath. ``The standing makes the difference, and
there's more turns and curves.''
</P>
<P>
   Marietta firefighter Dean Wilkinson said the ride was too short,
but compared it favorably with other coasters. ``It felt like I
lost my stomach more. You tense up a little more,'' he said as he
headed up the ramp a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Those were amateur opinions. Gary Slade, publisher of trade
magazine Amusement Today, gave a professional's description. ``It
has a lot of elements _ thrills, speed and action all packed into a
tight ground space. Because of that, the ride does not slow down or
lag. There's no time to catch your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're standing up through the first vertical loop, it's
the first time you feel the G-forces coming down into your legs,''
Slade said. The track also is heavily banked sideways, which allows
riders to be parallel to the ground. ``There's the sensation that
you might teeter out or fall out. You don't get that kind of
sensation in a coaster car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Designed and engineered by Bollinger &AMP; Mabillard of Switzerland,
the new $10 million coaster is the park's eighth. The park has
removed the Raging Rivers water ride, the least popular of the
water rides. ``People love to be thrilled and coasters are the No.
1 attraction at most theme parks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The park opened the ride last weekend without fanfare, but the
official opening will be Saturday, said Six Flags spokeswoman
Terrie Ward. The park will open daily beginning Memorial Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And about those firefighters: The thrill ride was followed by a
real training exercise, coordinated by the Georgia Mutual Aid
group.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
