<SLUG> BC-SEITZ-PLANT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARA LEE TO BUILD SEITZ MEAT PROCESSING PLANT IN ST. JOSEPH, MO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Sara Lee Corp. said Wednesday that it would build an
$80 million Seitz meat processing plant in St. Joseph, Mo., adding
250 to 350 jobs to its operation there.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee, which currently employs 155 persons at its Seitz plant
in St. Joseph, expects the new facility to be completed by the
first quarter of 2000. The company hasn't decided what to do with
the existing Seitz facility.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the 250,000-square-foot building will begin
immediately on 40 acres north of Mitchell Woods Business Park.
Financing for the new plant came through a combination of private-
and public-sector funding, said Patt Lilly, president and chief
executive officer of the St. Joseph Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $80 million initial investment, Sara Lee
plans to spend $45 million over a six-year period to expand the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Once completed, the new Seitz plant will have between 405 and
505 employees, with wages averaging $11 to $12 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new jobs, additional payroll, millions of dollars in new
construction and new tax revenue will have a positive effect on the
St. Joseph economy for many years to come,'' Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Seitz plant will process meats such as Hillshire Farm
Deli Select, Hillshire Farm smoked sausage, Seitz hot dogs and
luncheon meats, and Ball Park franks.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber officials said information regarding employment at Seitz
had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee follows two companies that began expanding in St.
Joseph earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Aegis Communications Group Inc. of Dallas plans to open a
customer service center in St. Joseph, employing 300 persons.
Phoenix Scientific Inc. also is expanding its St. Joseph facility
and could add 200 jobs over the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-0506-C     05-05 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAGIC APACHE CRASH SPOTLIGHTS DEMANDING COMMANDER OF TASK FORCE
HAWK
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR BASE, Albania _ When Army Lt. Gen. John W. Hendrix got
a phone call on March 26, he knew he was getting a rough
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his bosses in the military chain of command were on the
secure line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want you to put together a force that is built around some
Apaches,'' as Hendrix recalls it. ``And take it over (to the
Balkans).''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix, who has kept a very low profile in media coverage of
the U.S. military build-up in Albania, told this story to visiting
U.S. congressman last week. A partial transcript of his briefing
was released on Wednesday, hours after one of the Apache attack
helicopters under his command here in ``Task Force Hawk'' crashed
in a training exercise over Albania killing both men on board.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most challenging days in the fast-track
military career of the 57-year-old general from Statesville, Ga. A
tank commander, he was the demanding boss of the 3rd Infantry
Division (Mechanized) at Fort Stewart, Ga. from 1996 to 1997,
following a stint as a commander at Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of a century earlier, when he was a green
officer not long out of Atlanta's Georgia Tech, he fought in the
Vietnam War with the Screaming Eagles of the 101st Airborne
Division.
</P>
<P>
   So Hendrix didn't get three big black stars on his helmet by
saying no to challenges.
</P>
<P>
   But until Wednesday at 1:30 a.m. (local time), he didn't know
how rough and heart-wrenching his new job would turn out to be.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Hendrix got word that the second of his 24 Apache
helicopters had crashed within 10 days on a midnight training
mission near the border with Kosovo. A third Apache was knocked out
of commission, at least temporarily, by a hard landing in northern
Italy even before the first of the helicopters arrived at this
likely staging area for a NATO strike force against Serb forces in
Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of Lt. Gen. Hendrix and the soldiers of Task Force
Hawk, I would like to express our deepest sympathy and sincerest
condolences to the families and loved ones of the pilots,''
Hendrix's spokesman told journalists waiting at the gate to the
airfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches were supposed to be ``the tip of the spear in the
entire United States military.'' That is the memorable phrase of
Hendrix's young Apache pilots, Capt. Mark Arden, 29, of Washington,
D.C., said when the first Apaches arrived on April 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks to the Serbian Forces I would say are great,'' Arden
said. ``They have been successful so far against women and children
that are unarmed . . . the table is about to turn when we enter the
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Apaches will finally go into combat is now unclear. On
Wednesday, Hendrix's spokesman insisted that the second Apache
crash would not delay the ``timeline'' for the first mission. But
then there came word from the Pentagon that there really isn't much
need right away to send in the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton will have to dispatch his ``execute''
order to the NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark. And then
Clark will tell Hendrix to launch the first Apache mission when he
is ready.
</P>
<P>
   Although Apaches were designed to team up with advancing tank
columns, going in low and hard to sweep away enemy armored units to
allow ground troops to surge forward behind them, military
officials never indicated any plans to put them in Kosovo with any
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy, in line with the repeated U.S. policy of not
using ground troops in Kosovo, suggests that the remaining 22
Apaches would be used to blast Serb forces with the most lethal
anti-armored weapon in the American arsenal without risking the
inevitable casualties of ground warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular mission is interesting and difficult,''
Hendrix said to the congressman last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix's first Apache crashed on April 26, reportedly when it
hit an air pocket descending over a ridge, forcing the chopper to
clip its rotor blade on an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   That first crash, the pilots got lucky and so did Hendrix,
saying that ``aggressive'' night training missions with live
ordinance on board were necessary to make his Apache crews ready
for war.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by Wednesday, Task Force Hawk had shaken off the
embarrassment. Enough so, that the rigorous training was back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   In the dead of the night, over rugged mountainous terrain of
northern Albania, Hendrix's Apaches were on a low-flying rehearsal
mission. It may well have been their last rehearsal before striking
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Lt. Col. Garrie Dornan said the second crashed
Apache was carrying a full combat load of munitions -- eight
Hellfire laser-guided anti-tank missiles and 38 rockets hanging
under the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   These pilots weren't lucky -- nor was their commander.
</P>
<P>
   Other troops taking part in the exercise saw the second Apache
fireball in 10 days. And now some hotshot young Apache pilot and
his weapons officer lay either dead or dying in a maelstrom of
flames and bursting ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache's Hellfire missiles and its rockets are built with
``insensitive'' high explosives that aren't supposed to detonate by
accident. But this time they did.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Medivac copter got here fast, in only 15 minutes from
this air field 45 miles to the southwest of the crash scene. But
because of flames and exploding ordinance, the Medivac crew
couldn't rush in and pull out the bodies. For at least two hours,
according to the Army's sketchy statements, the risk of blowing up
a team of combat medics was judged to be over the limits for
safety.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix, who has the reputation as an extremely demanding boss,
believes that wars are won by training.
</P>
<P>
   He inherited the Apaches of the 11th Aviation Regiment last year
when he was handed one of the Army's prime assignments: commanding
the Army's V Corps in Germany, which includes two divisions of
heavy M1A1 battle tanks. The Apaches were one of the units that
came with his headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months, while he commanded V Corps, Hendrix has
pushed his Apache pilots through six major Combined Air Operations
exercises and one battle command exercise called a BCTP, or battle
command training program. Then when he got the assignment to bring
his Apaches to the Balkans, he immediately ordered them back to a
firing range for more gunnery training.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix also found Brig. Gen. Richard Cody, the Army's top
expert on Apache tactics, at an assignment in the United States.
Cody was flown into Hendrix's headquarters at V Corps and became
his right-hand man for the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
