<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN INVESTORS HOPE TO RECOUP LOSSES FROM RUSSIA'S DEBT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Russia defaulted on $40 billion in debt last
August, most foreigners who had once been lured by the high
interest rates on Russian government bonds figured they would be
lucky to get anything out of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   By late last week, nearly all of them had agreed to the
stringent terms of the Russian government's debt restructuring
plan. The trouble is, no one really knows what they have exactly
agreed to and how much, if anything, the government's plan will
give them in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners agreed without truly knowing the reality of what
they were entering into, what it's going to bring them,'' said
Sergei Prudnik, an economist with Troika Dialog, a Moscow brokerage
firm. ``Their feeling was that it's better to get something than
nothing at all. And the government's idea was, `Let's do something
now and work out the details later.'''
</P>
<P>
   The broad terms of the restructuring plan are clear. In return
for the nearly $17 billion in ruble-denominated Treasury securities
they held at the time of the default, foreigners will get about 10
percent of their investments in what the Russians are calling
``cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the only cash investors might receive would come from
using some ruble proceeds from the Treasury bills to buy a limited
amount of dollars at special currency auctions. After that,
foreigners can transfer these dollars abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty percent of the restructuring package comes in the form of
tax write-offs, which most foreigners do not need but can sell to
Russian investors. But the bulk of their investments will be
swapped for new government securities that mature over four to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   All proceeds from trading in these new securities will be in
rubles, and foreigners will not be able to convert those rubles to
dollars and repatriate them for an unspecified period.
</P>
<P>
   After much pressure from foreign investors, the government
agreed to let nonresidents use those rubles to buy stocks and bonds
at leading Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after the default and a week after the restructuring
offer deadline passed, the government has yet to disclose an
official, complete list of the Russian companies involved and the
mechanism by which foreigners may invest in them. Some information
has come out, however haphazardly, and investors and their brokers
are now trying to decide, based on an incomplete picture, where to
put all the rubles they are expecting to get.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions vary wildly about which investments would be the safest
and most fruitful, primarily because of Russia's own inherent
instability. The annualized interest rates paid by the new Russian
government securities exceed 100 percent, but that may not be
enough to offset a steep devaluation of the ruble or rise in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was so scared last fall about hyperinflation that
there's still this hangover fear,'' said Peter Boone, head of
research at Moscow's Brunswick Warburg investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate bonds that foreigners can purchase under the debt
restructuring would offer far lower interest rates, starting at
about 6 percent. But they would be redeemed, in part or in full, in
dollars. So far, Gazprom, &UR;  &LR; Russia's gas monopoly, and Lukoil, &UR;  &LR; the
country's largest oil company, have submitted prospectuses for bond
issues. Both earn much of their revenue in hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   For the Russian companies, the bond issues would be a way of
essentially getting enormous loans on which they would pay
relatively low interest. But here, too, there's risk involved for
investors: the companies could default if their revenue fell
sharply or if the government confiscated their hard-currency
earnings, as it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Russian equities would be a good investment. The
government has said that foreign investors in the debt
restructuring plan can use their rubles to buy shares of Russian
blue-chip companies like Lukoil, metals giant Norilsk Nickel,
long-distance provider Rostelekom and utilities Unified Energy
Systems, Mosenergo and Irkutskenergo. The list is expected to be
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation that foreign investors would be putting more money
into the Russian stock market was one reason why it surged 12.1
percent Wednesday to its highest level since the August default.
Optimism generated by the International Monetary Fund's
announcement last week that it would restructure $4.5 billion in
Russian debt also contributed to the rally.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Russian shares, which are priced in dollars, are
still undervalued, analysts say. The hope is that by buying them
now, investors can reap a windfall when the share prices rise. That
is assuming, of course, that Russia pulls out of its latest
economic mire. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
