<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-STRENGTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMANS HAVE BEEN THERE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ First there was the tornado of '58, which blew
past Yvonne Rose's house in Shawnee and set it ablaze. Then there
was the twister of '59, which ripped apart her roof, followed by
the one in '75 that yanked her fences out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But this was different. It wasn't just the force of the tornado
that leveled the Rose family house Monday night, destroying decades
of memories. It was the timing: On the heels of so many disasters
around the world _ especially the Oklahoma City bombing _ the
devastation of her 600-home neighborhood seemed to Rose, 63, to
mean something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the end is a lot closer than people think,'' she said,
sitting in a living room chair on her front lawn to survey a sea of
splintered wood that stretched as far as the horizon. ``You can see
it every day. People just aren't putting it in context.''
</P>
<P>
   Her interpretation was among the most dire in Del Aire Addition,
a close-knit suburban enclave that suffered almost complete
destruction and at least two deaths Monday night. And yet everyone
spoke in extremes. At the very least, they all said, the tornado
ruined a hard-built way of life in this community of military
servicemen and government workers, nearly all of whom had lived
here more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahomans have grown accustomed to cataclysmic events in recent
times, and have even developed a certain pride at their ability to
rally together when disaster hits. Red Cross workers know how to
mobilize, as they did after the 1995 bombing of the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building in downtown Oklahoma City. Church groups
are in close contact across the state, ready to ship food at the
first sign of natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Even residents know the drill. ``I think Oklahomans are very
resilient folks,'' said Kari Ferguson, executive director of the
Oklahoma City National Memorial, soon to be unveiled at the site of
the bombing. ``I heard one survivor of the bombing say that people
don't see beauty in the state, but the beauty is in the people. And
I think that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an Oklahoman is about hanging in there and doing what
you have to do for each other,'' agreed Lynda Mobley, 41, a
resident of Del Aire Addition. ``We've got it in our blood.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was clear Wednesday in Mobley's neighborhood, where
hundreds of residents and their relatives picked through rubble,
pausing often to shake hands with friends and take strolls along
the winding lanes to see if others needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Most had come to the neighborhood in the 1960s to escape urban
crime and to be close to Tinker Air Force Base next door, risking
the annual tornado season in Oklahoma for a quiet suburban way of
life. It was, at the time, ``where everyone wanted to live,'' said
Linda Haynes, 58, a resident of 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, families raised children in the development's
cul-de-sacs, built a swimming pool, and formed one of the strongest
neighborhood associations in Oklahoma. Few ever moved out.
</P>
<P>
   But now, for the first time, many are wondering whether that
will change. Of the 600 homes, some 450 are all but gone. Those
that still have their foundations intact are heavily damaged. What
was once a cookie-cutter layout of backyards and driveways has been
transformed into a giant junkyard, with cars lying in twisted piles
of metal and housing insulation scattered everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the front yard of one resident lay a perfectly preserved
white ceramic bathtub, directly in front of a house that was
otherwise demolished. The resident, Don Northern, took refuge in
the tub during the storm. When the tornado blew through his house,
the tub was catapulted outside, knocking the elderly man
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, neighbors played off the humor of stray
objects with a dark joke, planting a sign _ ``Garage Sale'' _ in
front of 3388 Del Aire Place, a residence that was virtually gone.
In front of another pile of rubble, resident Tex Irwin, 69, placed
a ``For Sale'' sign pointing in the direction of what was once his
home of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we might as well,'' Irwin said with a grim smile.
``It's not like we can live here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many of the thousands left homeless by Monday's
storms will be able to return home. Eleven counties in Oklahoma and
Kansas had been declared disaster areas the day before, qualifying
them for immediate emergency aid. But the long process of securing
insurance funds was only beginning Wednesday, two days after the
deadliest tornado storm to hit Oklahoma in 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the medical costs of the 700 or so in the state
who were injured, the property damage from the storm could cost as
much as $250 million in Oklahoma alone, where more than 1,500 homes
were hit, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the costs of rebuilding were not yet clear, the emotional
toll was becoming so by late Wednesday, especially as residents
stopped to consider what this latest wave of devastation meant for
Oklahoma City as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Some shrugged off the connection between the bombing and the
tornado, chalking it up to an odd string of bad luck that must now,
for sure, be at an end. Others said they were considering moving
elsewhere, though they had nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   At least one resident, Danny Speaks, laughed about the string of
horrifying events as part of Oklahoma City's charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pretty place to live, isn't it?'' said Speaks, 41.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Rose, for her part, is leaving town. She raised five
children and four grandchildren in that house. She had seen one too
many tornadoes, and heard repercussions from the Oklahoma City
bombing from her own backyard. The time had come to move to
Tennessee or North Carolina, somewhere with relatives, even though
she said she believed the worldwide apocalypse was on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Allen, a minister of the Christ Life Church of God,
expressed a similar view as he brought food and water to the
neighborhood. The tornadoes were a ``sign of the times,'' as the
Earth ``belched with problems'' and headed into its final years, he
said, citing both the Murrah building bombing and the shooting last
month at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., as examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma, for whatever reason, has been plagued recently,''
Allen, 34, said. ``I'm not going to blame it on evil spirits or
anything. I think it's just the way the world is turning now. But
fortunately, here in Oklahoma, we're in the Bible Belt. We know how
to help each other out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
