<SLUG> BC-HOME-WORKERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME-BASED WORKERS NOW HAVE A DAY OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Today is the first Missouri Work at Home Day. You
probably haven't heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Southwestern Bell _ which not so coincidentally
sells telephone services that home-based offices might use _ just
created the day, getting the blessings of state, city, chamber and
economic development officials.
</P>
<P>
   Contrived or not, there's justification for recognizing the
growing force of at-home workers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent numbers available from the U.S.
Bureau of Labor Statistics, 1.79 million of the 129.6 million
members of the American work force spend 35 or more hours a week
working at home, making home-based work their principal job and
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like a minuscule market, but it's only part of
the at-home picture. According to the same 1997 numbers, there are
4.125 million home-based businesses in the United States. For about
2.3 million of them, the home business is a second job.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers get much bigger when you count all the Americans who
conduct some kind of income-related work in their homes. The bureau
counts more than 21 million workers in that category.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of those working at home report that they're
``traditional'' employees, drawing a wage or salary from an
employer. More than half of them, though, say they're not expressly
paid for their work done at home.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there are lots of teachers, sales agents,
lawyers _ anyone, really _ who take work home at night.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one in five of the work-at-home crew actually gets
paid for work at home.
</P>
<P>
   However the numbers are analyzed, though, it's apparent that
Southwestern Bell knows its market potential. The company has
created a Work at Home Resources staff to provide
telecommunications support for home offices.
</P>
<P>
   Homebuilders; furniture manufacturers; security system
providers; computer companies; software designers; purveyors of
telephones, answering machines, fax machines and all manner of
office equipment; and service providers are responding to home
office needs.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Internal Revenue Service got into the act, making it
easier this year for home-based workers to qualify for the income
tax deduction for business use of the home.
</P>
<P>
   The new tax rule still requires the ``exclusive'' and
``regular'' use test: You must use your home office only for
business, not for any personal reasons (such as letting the kids
play games on the computer), and the home office must be used on a
continuing basis, not occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   But the new rule makes it a bit easier for some home-based
workers to meet the qualification. If the home office is used
exclusively and regularly for the administration and management of
the business _ and there is no other fixed location where the
taxpayer conducts those activities _ then the home office may meet
the deduction.
</P>
<P>
   That allows for, possibly, a home repair contractor, who has no
other office location but does all his scheduling and other
business management activities out of a home office, to qualify if
he meets all other conditions. In the past, because most of the
contractor's time was spent outside his home office _ in the homes
he was repairing _ he could not have qualified for the deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Home-based business operators say their growing numbers may be
what it takes to eliminate other impediments to their operations.
That means getting more than just high-speed access lines for their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Local zoning laws often prohibit home-based businesses.
Temporary staffing agencies sometimes refuse to send workers to
home-based operations. Some package-delivery services charge more
for pickups and deliveries at homes than at office sites.
</P>
<P>
   Home-based workers interested in keeping up with trends and
issues may want to check out www.gohome.com, a Web page created by
Business &LR; Home, which publishes a national magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
