<SLUG> BC-RIGHTS-ARABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE REFLECTS WOES OF ARAB NATIONS' HUMAN RIGHTS ADVOCATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASABLANCA, Morocco _ When human rights activists from 15 Arab
nations met here recently for the first conference of its kind in
the Arab world, organizers were reminded of the suspicion with
which many Arab governments view efforts to widen individual
liberties.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-day meeting, an intruder was discovered
searching through wastepaper baskets, recovering handwritten notes
discarded by delegates. Several attempts were made to gain passes
to the conference by men posing as reporters or students, but who
turned out to be neither. In the photocopying room, another
intruder fled when he was discovered copying conference documents.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion reached by the Egyptian activist who was the
conference's principal convener, Bahey El-Din Hassan, was that the
intruders were agents sent from outside Morocco by some of the Arab
world's most repressive governments. Hassan, director of the Cairo
Institute for Human Rights Studies, a private group that has
frequently clashed with Egyptian authorities, had worked for
several years to prepare for the conference, and knew the meeting
would be seen as a threat by many Arab governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some delegates who canceled in the last month because
of concerns for their safety,'' Hassan said in late April. ``It is
understandable, but it is a shame, because the purpose of our
meeting here was to foster a sense of solidarity among human rights
defenders throughout the Arab world, who face the same pattern of
repression, the same official discourse against human rights and
democracy, and the same pattern of abuse of human rights
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   According to conference officials, more than 50 Arab human
rights groups are active in Arab nations, many of them established
in the last decade. Organizers said that represented a change from
the 1980s, when rights activities in Arab countries were mostly
undertaken by non-Arab, Western-based organizations like Amnesty
International and the U.S.-based Human Rights Watch. A conference
document said that that had led to Arab governments dismissing
human rights pressures as ``an American plot to dominate the Arab
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arab groups have faced an uphill struggle. Activists in some
countries have been killed, have disappeared or have been held for
long periods in jail. Others, including some from Iraq, Libya,
Algeria and Tunisia, among other countries, have been forced to
operate from bases in Europe or the United States. Finding an Arab
country prepared to act as host for the meeting _ the first time a
broad array of Arab rights groups have met in a conference setting
_ was another problem. After Egypt refused, Morocco stepped
forward, the only country to offer itself as a location.
</P>
<P>
   The conference offered a showcase for Morocco, where King Hassan
II has taken steps recently to improve a rights record that had
attracted harsh criticism by political opponents and Western rights
groups at earlier periods of his 37-year reign. In the last year,
the 69-year-old king, promising to ``close the dossier'' on rights
cases, has freed more than two dozen political prisoners, promised
compensation to the families of others who disappeared while in
custody, and appointed as prime minister a former political exile,
Abderrahman Youssoufi, who formally opened the rights meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 delegates to the conference held their sessions behind
closed doors, another reflection of the ``fear'' Hassan, the
Egyptian rights activist, said was inescapable for Arab rights
activists. The meeting concluded without establishing an umbrella
organization, and without any firm plan to hold another conference.
That was partly because of the practical difficulties of finding
another Arab site, and partly, Hassan said, because participants
concluded that the ``most effective work to be done at present'' is
at the level of individual Arab nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANDERSON     05-05 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL FOR JAMAL ANDERSON NOT `VIABLE,' PATRIOTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was an exciting story for a little while,
but it doesn't appear there is a future for Atlanta running back
Jamal Anderson in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Both Patriots executive Andy Wasynczuk and coach Pete Carroll
confirmed the Falcons called the Patriots on draft day about a
trade for Anderson, but the deal couldn't be worked out because of
salary cap problems, which prompted the Falcons to make Anderson
available in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a viable option for us right now,'' said Wasynczuk.
``We may still address the running spot in the next few months, but
we have to concentrate now on being able to sign our own draft
picks and getting them under our cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk said the draft day deal, which would have included New
England's two first-round picks, was not offered until the Patriots
``were on the clock,'' so they had little time to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said one of Atlanta coach Dan Reeves's assistants
called, but the Patriots never considered the offer. ``He has a bad
contract,'' Carroll said of Anderson. ``He only has a year left, so
you risk losing him after a year. Don't get me wrong, I love the
player, but we don't anticipate being able to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who gained 1,440 yards last season as the Falcons went
14-2, is in the final season of a four-year deal. He will make $1.6
million this year and can become an unrestricted free agent next
season. But the Falcons have serious salary cap concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's agent, James Sims Jr., said he and his client are
seeking a six- or seven-year deal that includes a signing bonus
near $10 million and an average salary of $6 million-$7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would put Anderson in the Terrell Davis-Barry
Sanders range.
</P>
<P>
   Sims currently is negotiating with the Falcons, but isn't
getting very far. Upon hearing that the Patriots refused to
consider a deal for Anderson because they didn't think they could
afford to sign him long term, Sims called Patriots vice president
of player personnel Bobby Grier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically told Bobby to stay tuned,'' said Sims. ``If things
didn't work out, who knows? The Patriots have a first-round pick
next year and the Falcons don't. I think Coach Reeves initiated the
talks, figuring he could get two No. 1 picks for Jamal and knowing
he had a lot of guys whose contracts were up. He knew the Patriots
needed a running back and the Patriots had discussed Jamal with
them last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims said if Anderson becomes a free agent, New England would be
one of his top choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal is only 26,'' said Sims. ``He wants to go someplace
where he can win and where the team is committed to winning. New
England is definitely that place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited. If this were the Cincinnati Bengals we were
talking about I wouldn't be this excited. But the first thing Jamal
said to me was, `Imagine being in the same backfield with Drew
Bledsoe?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on America On-Line, Anderson said,
``Apparently, the deal would have been for a couple of first-round
draft picks plus some additional picks. I know the Patriots have
had some recent problems at running back with Robert Edwards going
down with a knee injury, and I guess I'm flattered that they hold
me in such high regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, on the other side of the coin, I've always been very
happy in Atlanta and truly have high hopes about continuing the
success we've had as a team and that I've had personally. What this
does is make me realize that, after all, this is a business. The
bottom line is, I'm shocked by the whole thing and although I'm
sure everything will work out whether I get traded or not, it's
still pretty unsettling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
