<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS THREATEN TO LAUNCH AN ASSAULT ON ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two influential senators threatened Tuesday to
launch an assault on the entertainment industry, hoping to
``shame'' its leaders into changing the culture of violent movies,
music and video games aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, Democrat Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and
Republican Orrin Hatch of Utah, said that First Amendment concerns
probably would override any legislative attempts to coerce the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   But they suggested waging a campaign much like that against the
tobacco industry, which faced a growing wave of anti-smoking public
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us wants to resort to regulation,'' Lieberman said,
``but if the entertainment industry...continues to market death and
degradation to our children and continues to pay no heed to the
genuine bloodshed staining our communities, then one way or the
other, the government will act.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Hatch said they might call for an investigation by
either the Federal Trade Commission or the Justice Department to
see if the entertainment industry was violating laws against unfair
trade practices or false advertising related to the marketing of
violent entertainment to children.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators and witnesses said parental warnings and
ratings on movies, games and other merchandise often failed to
deter either the seller or the children that they were designed to
protect.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee, which
held the hearing, had invited entertainment executives from several
companies, including Time-Warner, Nintendo, Sega and Sony, to
attend. But none showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president and chief executive officer of the
Motion Picture Association of America, agreed that the film
industry had an obligation to examine its work for ``gratuitous
violence, language or sensuality.'' But he testified that whatever
changes might be made should come from Hollywood, and not ``without
nagging or commands from anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the hearing seemed keyed to the school shootings, Sen.
Sam Brownback had scheduled it almost two months before Littleton,
Colo., was on anyone's political radar. The Kansas Republican has
been speaking out about violence in rock lyrics for several years.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the line to get into what otherwise would have been
a pretty standard congressional hearing snaked down the hallway and
two stairwells a half-hour before it began. Inside, cameras clicked
away and television lights reflected off polished marble walls.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the trappings of authority, most senators and
witnesses betrayed a sense of frustration and inability to come to
grips with the kind of cultural forces that many said they believe
played a part in the bloody rampage in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an endless debate about First and Second Amendment
rights,'' Brownback said of the constitutional freedoms of
expression and the right to bear arms, ``while our children are
being traumatized.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, they displayed advertisements for video games
marketed to children where carnage appeared to be the only point,
such as ``Die by the Sword,'' that attracted customers with this
teaser: ``Lop off heads, sever limbs and bring your enemy to his
knees (literally).''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as former Education Secretary William Bennett did, showed
snippets from popular violent movies. The first was ``The
Basketball Diaries,'' where a disaffected teen-ager in a long black
leather coat and brandishing an automatic weapon has a dream
sequence where he walks into a classroom and mows down the
students. The other was the gory, top-grossing film ``Scream,''
where one by one, teen-agers are stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   At that, some in the hearing room audience turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had enough?'' said Bennett after the second clip.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent speaker and writer on values and popular culture,
Bennett said: ``I applaud Jack Valenti's courage in coming here. He
should go back (to Hollywood) and tell it collectively that
Americans have had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles J. Chaput, the archbishop of Denver, who buried
some of the dead of Littleton last week, told the hearing: ``Common
sense tells us that violence of our music, our video games, our
films, and our television has to go somewhere _ and it goes
straight into the hearts of our children, to bear fruit in ways we
can't imagine. Until something like Littleton happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
