<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-ART-2     05-05 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MASSACRE, KOSOVO ALBANIANS SEE ENEMIES WHERE THEY ONCE SAW
NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-PRISTINA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Betrayal is the theme of the story of
Slovinje. Of the village's 600 homes, 40 belonged to Serbs and the
rest to ethnic Albanians. The two communities lived on opposite
sides of the river but got along without major problems. They
shopped at each other's stores. Their kids competed at soccer. They
knew each other's names.
</P>
<P>
   When the violence began in Kosovo, the Serbs of Slovinje told
their ethnic Albanian neighbors they had nothing to fear from the
army or paramilitary, several refugees woefully recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ```We will protect you,' they promised, and then when the army
came, our own Serbs put on masks and joined in the butchery,'' said
Magribe Neziri. ``They knew who to single out. They knew who had
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, two mass graves were dug up in Slovinje, and 16
muddy corpses were laid out in a classroom of a village school,
said three men who were there. The bodies were covered with black
plastic but the heads were left exposed for purposes of
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing who was who was hard. The Serbs had rampaged through
Slovinje on April 15 and 16, according to more than a dozen
witnesses, killing more than 40 people. The dead had been in the
ground for two weeks, and decomposition had begun its work of
returning dust to dust.
</P>
<P>
   Ferat Gashi, 62, almost buried another young man in the grave
set aside for his young nephew, Enver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found Enver's driver's license in his pants or a horrible
mistake would have been made,'' said Gashi, his face a portrait of
sorrow. ``But then who is to say what is truly horrible anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   While 16 Albanians in Slovinje now have some privacy beneath the
soil, many others are assumed by relatives and friends to be lying
dead elsewhere, rotting in the debris of burned homes or washed up
on the rocky banks of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Gashi said that when he and others re-buried their kin,
authorities threatened them with death if they chanted any funeral
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps our silence helps them to deal with their shame,''
said a retired miner who was also present at the pantomime of a
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Slovinje, a village 10 miles south of Pristina,
Kosovo's capital, is an incomplete one without independent
confirmation. In separate interviews, 17 ethnic Albanians who had
been in Slovinje on April 15 and 16 told their stories to The New
York Times during the last week. Five of these refugees said they
had witnessed killings. A local teacher who has added up the
killings from witnesses' accounts puts the total at 44. A lawyer,
Naser Gashi, has compiled a list of the dead with 41 names.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers for Human Rights Watch have also spoken with a half
dozen Slovinje refugees. They were told of many of the same
killings. A spare, but consistent account of the deaths has
appeared in at least one Albanian-language daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something terrible happened there, that's for sure,'' said
Benjamin Ward, a Human Rights Watch researcher. ``There was a great
deal of familiarity between the persecutors and the persecuted. One
is struck by the degree of trauma and the residual fear. Many of
these people still have family members there.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are usually at least two sides to any
story, and Serbian testimonies have yet to be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   After Serbian forces began emptying cities and villages and NATO
bombing began, some of Slovinje's Albanians considered escaping to
Macedonia over the frigid mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Their Serbian acquaintances counseled against flight, several
Albanians say. On the night of April 14, some leaders of the
Serbian community called upon some of their Albanian counterparts.
``They told us the army was coming in, but we shouldn't be
afraid,'' said the teacher, who withheld his name in fear of harm
to his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we could meet with the army at the school at 7 a.m.
the next day, but at 5 the army was already blocking a main road
with tanks. Some Serbian paramilitary had been hiding in the
village overnight, hiding in the house of someone who had told us
to stay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians were petrified. In a few hours, they saw smoke coming
from Okllap, a nearby Albanian village. There was little to do but
cower.
</P>
<P>
   In the early afternoon, Serbian forces entered the village and
began shooting into homes, witnesses said. A teen-age girl,
Fathushe Dubov, is believed by some to have been the first to die.
Sniper fire then cut down Rifat and Milaim Gashi. The paramilitary
began going house to house.
</P>
<P>
   People were beaten, report both those who saw it and those who
suffered it. Money was stolen and extorted. People were ordered to
flee.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shehide Sopjani, 85, felt she was too old for such a sudden
departure, said her son, a retired miner who asked that his name
not be used. He said that she sat fearfully with another son,
Mehmet, who was nearly blind, and his frail wife, Qamile. The
rat-tat-tat of machine guns seemed to be everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they have to come with me or we'd all be
massacred,'' said the miner, who recalled that his mother then
invoked an old Albanian expression: ``As the one who fed you from
the breast, I tell you to run from this house so that I can at
least know one of us will remain alive.''
</P>
<P>
   From the foothills, he looked back but could not see much. He
would only learn of his mother's fate when he took part in last
Friday's burials, he said. He was able to identify the body of his
mother by her earrings. His dead brother was recognizable by the
gaps in his teeth, his sister-in-law by a deformed leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things will haunt me forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With tanks blocking the main way out, the only open road passed
through the Serbian part of town. As Albanians tried to drive off,
they met a roadblock. ``Whoever the local Serbs didn't like, they
told the soldiers to order them out of the car,'' said the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Gafurr Hyseni, an activist in the Mother Teresa Society, was
taken into a house and beaten, witnesses said. The house was set
ablaze. Hyseni never came out.
</P>
<P>
   At least three other men were pulled from their cars and killed,
said one witness. One man was Jakup Kryeziv. Another was Adem
Bytyqi, who was shot dead while trying to run. Faik Krasniqi was
executed and his nose and mouth were cut off, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Five men, including Omer and Enver Gashi, were ordered into a
yard along with their wives and children. ``Three men in ski masks
told everyone but the men to run away,'' said Omer's wife,
Nebahate, 31. ``Then we heard shooting and no one ever saw my
husband again until the mass graves were opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians fled to Smallusha, a nearby village. But Serbian
forces chased them from there as well. By the next morning,
hundreds of people from both Smallusha and Slovinje found
themselves in a fearsome limbo, gathered in a field in the
foothills and unsure if the killing had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Another day of mayhem was ahead. Accounts differ as to who died
first in a burst of random shooting. Feroleze Bytyqi, who was
there, believes it was her brother, Hasan Bytyqi, 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hit in the stomach'' with gun shots, said Bytyqi, 27, a
pregnant woman now living in a refugee camp. ``My father asked for
someone to help his boy, but the answer he got was a beating.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her father lifted his wounded son onto the seat of a tractor,
Bytiqi said: ``The Serbs told my brother to put his hands up and
then they shot him 10 times. I saw this. I saw my brother die.''
</P>
<P>
   Men were separated from women and children, three eyewitnesses
said. Everyone was commanded to empty their pockets. Valuables were
stolen. Identification papers were put in a pile and set afire.
</P>
<P>
   Several men were then singled out for beatings, including Remzi
Limani, 30, Bytiqi's husband, who said he was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs taunted their captives. ``You wanted NATO, so let NATO
come and save you now,'' two Albanians recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The women and children were ordered to leave. ``Go into the
woods and die of hunger,'' Bytiqi said they were told. The group
wandered toward the mountains, looking over their shoulders to see
the fate of the men.
</P>
<P>
   The beatings were continuing, witnesses said. One particular
target was a well-built young man, Habib Dubova. When Dubova and a
few others successfully made a run for it, their captors were
furious, witnesses said. Other Serbs were called over and then they
huddled. Suddenly, they told the Albanians to run for their lives.
Three were quickly shot as they hurried up an incline toward the
woods, witnesses said. One of those shot was Fatmir Bytyqi, 30,
another of Feroleze Bytiqi's brothers. He lay wounded until a
Serbian soldier fired several bullets into his head, two witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 16 people died trying to sprint for safety, the
Albanians agree. Avni Sopiani, a mentally handicapped young man,
was said to be among those killed. A 34-year-old barber was
wounded, but his brother and a cousin helped him stumble along, he
said. He recently arrived in Macedonia and on Wednesday was lying
in a clinic at a refugee camp, awaiting surgery to have a bullet
removed from his buttock.
</P>
<P>
   Most men who escaped found their families in the hills around
other Albanian villages, several witnesses said. During nights,
some men would return to Slovinje to feed their farm animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were still soldiers around, but the local Serbs told us
to come back,'' recalled the teacher. ``They said, `Some innocent
Albanians were killed who weren't supposed to be.' They said they
were sorry and that we could all return now as long as we didn't
bring along any troublemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, many Albanians did come back, some to search for
loved ones. This bitter homecoming lasted but a few hours before
the police began shooting in the air, the teacher said. The
Albanians again fled into the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Many chanced a second return a week later. And it was then that
the Serbian police agreed to unearth the dead. The Albanians were
given barely an hour to identify the dead and bury them. `'We were
not permitted to say even a word or look into each other's eyes,''
said Ferat Gashi.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he and dozens of others decided to leave for good.
They made their way to the border and now either live with
relatives or in hastily built tent cities.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of the Albanians have chosen to stay in Slovinje
and to see what happens next, according to the recent refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The local Serbs, they said, have told them everything is going
to be all right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
