<SLUG> BC-KC-TORNADO-EXPLAIN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BLAME SEVERE WEATHER ON CLIMATE CHANGE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be quick to chalk up this week's killer tornadoes to
global climate change.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have speculated that extreme storms, such as the
series of tornadoes that struck Kansas and Oklahoma on Monday, may
become more frequent with global warming.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, there's little evidence that links tornadoes and
hurricanes to climate change.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong indicators that the globe's climate is
changing. Temperatures have definitely increased the last dozen
years, and precipitation also may be up.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence of an increase in the frequency of tornadoes and
hurricanes just isn't there, say some scientists who are
researching the effects of global climate change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen an increase as yet,'' said Eugene Takle, a
professor of atmospheric science at Iowa State University. ``But
there's definitely a lot more property damage'' because of the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Those damages are due primarily to a failure to take the proper
preventive steps. Such efforts include building better structures;
locating structures out of areas prone to disaster; and acting on
improved storm warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the deadliest tornado years on record occurred in the
1950s and 1960s. In 1953, for example, 150 persons died in Texas in
May; on May 25, 1955, 81 died in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Federal maps and data of the areas of the United States most
prone to devastating tornadoes lead you straight to Kansas,
Oklahoma and Texas, the three most tornado-prone states.
</P>
<P>
   May is also the heaviest tornado month. Of the 787 tornadoes
that annually occur in the United States, on average, 171 occur in
May, according to federal climate data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
