<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-HAYSVILLE-KAN &LR;      05-05 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-HAYSVILLE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Haysville, a town familiar with calamity, suffers another dose  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER and TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ The people of Haysville, just south of Wichita,
say they've had their fill of disasters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a tornado sliced through the west side of town on a
rampage that killed 19 persons in Sedgwick and Butler counties.
Then last year, the DeBruce Grain elevator exploded, killing seven
workers and again putting Haysville on the national news map.
</P>
<P>
   But the death and damage from the tornado that smashed into the
center of Haysville about 8:30 p.m. Monday represented by far the
worst calamity that anyone in this town of 9,500 could remember.
</P>
<P>
   After ravaging Haysville's business district and damaging homes,
the twister moved into south Wichita. In its wake, it left five
people dead and scores injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this was devastating to our downtown core area and
residential area,'' said Haysville Mayor Tim Norton. ``It's just
desolate. We're going to have a lot of rebuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornado first struck just south of Haysville, ripping out
trees, destroying a home and damaging several others. It then
traveled north along railroad tracks that run through the center of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Officials there estimated that about 150 homes were either
damaged or destroyed, along with 27 businesses, three churches and
four historic buildings in the ``old part'' of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said several buildings in that area were being restored
with the hope that one day, the area could become an attraction
with brick streets and gaslights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's out the window now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the damage occurred just east of the railroad tracks
along a two-mile stretch. Hit especially hard was the business
district in the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said the administrative offices of the town's largest
private employer, Norland Plastics, were turned into rubble by the
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Graves stood near the intersection and surveyed the
destruction. All around him, heavy equipment was removing debris,
and electrical workers were repairing power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so resilient,'' Graves said. ``Folks are already
over there cleaning up their lots. Even though there's not a house
standing there, they're already trying to figure out how to rebuild
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves said both the state and federal governments had issued
emergency disaster declarations for Sedgwick County.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of the storm were allowed to return to their homes about
noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Rhonda Sherwood looked through their heavily damaged
home for items to take with them. The Sherwoods fled to the
basement Monday night and emerged to find a new ``skylight'' where
the roof had been.
</P>
<P>
   While many of their neighbors were evacuated to a nearby church,
the Sherwoods spent the night in their relatively undamaged
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to stay at home and protect your stuff,'' she
said, adding that authorities had asked them to leave several
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A block away on Main Street, Deanna Turpin, her 27-year-old son,
Paul, and 17-year-old daughter, Jessica, were staring at what was
left of their home.
</P>
<P>
   Turpin said she was prepared to ride out the storm, but fled to
the basement at her son's insistence. His determination probably
saved them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About that time all the windows blew out and our ears started
popping,'' she said. ``Thanks to him, we're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   A ladder sitting just outside the house came through the kitchen
window, and part of Turpin's roof collapsed. Trees around her yard
were stripped bare of their limbs or were bent completely over. A
blue mattress hung about 20 feet up in a tree behind her house.
</P>
<P>
   Haysville officials said full electrical power won't be restored
until the end of the week. It will take a lot longer, Norton said,
to restore the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're still in shock,'' he said. ``I'm sure we'll
begin the grieving process when that wears off.''
</P>
<P>
   In south Wichita, two adjoining mobile home parks were
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief Terri Moses of the Wichita Police Department said
the tornado destroyed 100 mobile homes in the Lakeshore and
Pacesetter mobile home parks.
</P>
<P>
   At the Machinists Hall in south Wichita on Tuesday, a steady
flow of people visited a Red Cross Center set up for those seeking
news about loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all looking for someone,'' said Darla Ward, shelter
manager for the Red Cross. She said volunteers were taking
information and then calling people later after relatives and
friends were located.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas of the adjoining mobile home parks escaped major
damage, while other parts were totally destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Some mobile homes were tossed into a nearby lake.
</P>
<P>
   Overturned cars and twisted sheet metal lay about the park.
Personal belongings were scattered everywhere: toys, playing cards,
televisions, furniture.
</P>
<P>
   City workers cleared a pathway on main roads through the mobile
home parks so residents could reach their homes.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 p.m. Tuesday, residents who didn't remain in their homes
overnight were allowed back in, along with family members. What
they returned to, in many cases, was difficult to take.
</P>
<P>
   Some people lost everything _ family possessions, pictures,
furniture and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   What had been the home of David and Misty Seeber was a 10-foot
pile of ruin Tuesday afternoon. Like others at the Lakeshore Mobile
Home Park, the young couple spent the day trying to salvage
whatever memories they could uncover.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, a neighbor found their two cockatiel birds
alive and handed them to a police officer, who returned them. The
Seebers also found a photo album from their wedding two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God for saving both of our lives,'' David Seeber said.
</P>
<P>
   Shena Miloni and her three children were even luckier. Their
mobile home sustained only a couple of small holes and a lost
carport and a broken television antenna. A 40-foot elm tree fell
parallel to their house, barely missing it.
</P>
<P>
   During the storm, they huddled in the bathroom and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid of dying and wishing it could get over with,''
Miloni said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
