<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLA-SEARCH-ART-2TAKE     05-05 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-SEARCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRUESOME SEARCH FOR STORM'S VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OKLA-STORM, OKLA-POLICE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY, Okla. _ For the fifth time in three days, Capt.
James Smith and a band of other National Guardsmen waded into a
thorny thicket Wednesday morning to search a muddy creek bed near
here for the bodies, or parts of bodies, of those who remain
missing after Monday's tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   And for the fifth time, after tromping for nearly two hours
through virtually impenetrable brush in the Bridge Creek community,
the soldiers came up empty. Smith, an eighth-grade history teacher
from Rowlett, Texas, and the father of eight-week-old twins, said
he had mixed feelings about whether he wants the search to be more
fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hoping and praying that the person's alive, but if
they're out there you want to find them,'' he said. ``Because for
every minute that person's dead you know that family is suffering,
and you're thinking, `What if it was my family?'''
</P>
<P>
   As this area recovers from this week's devastating storm, which
has accounted for 38 deaths in the Oklahoma City area and 5 in a
community south of Wichita, Kan., no task has been more gruesome
than the search for the missing. It has been complicated by
significant confusion, with the authorities apparently uncertain
about how many people really have yet to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Blakeney, director of operations for the Oklahoma State
Medical Examiner, said at a news conference Wednesday afternoon
that about 100 people may still be missing. But some of those
people, Blakeney said, may have been counted twice. Others may be
among the 15 dead who have yet to be identified. And still others
may be among those who are unconscious and unidentified at area
hospitals. Blakeney said that his office hopes to come up with a
computerized index of the missing on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The chaos was illustrated Wednesday by the disclosure by Stan
Florence, the sheriff of Grady County, that he had inaccurately
announced on Tuesday that a missing woman had been found alive
under debris in Bridge Creek. Florence said he had received
incorrect information.
</P>
<P>
   Because the tornadoes struck such a broad area, because they
were powerful enough to fling objects dozens of miles away, and
because communication is hampered by downed telephone and power
lines, the search for bodies has been painstaking.
</P>
<P>
   At midday in Bridge Creek, where 11 bodies were found shortly
after the tornado, members of a search and rescue team found an
unattached leg and foot under debris near what had been a homesite.
They covered the body parts with a cardboard box, marked it with an
orange flag, and then began to thoroughly search the area for other
remains. ``We'll see if it's from one of the bodies already
recovered,'' said Gene Christian, the district attorney for the
area. ``It's not unusual for bodies in these situations to have an
amputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Search and rescue officials throughout the area said that the
widespread havoc spread by Monday's tornadoes created special
problems even for agencies accustomed to such missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to look for someone in a house, but the house is
gone,'' said Jack Briggs, an assistant fire chief in Moore, an
Oklahoma City suburb that was heavily damaged by the storm. ``You
go to look for the street, but the whole street is gone. In the
situation we've got here, sometimes you go to look and the whole
neighborhood is gone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
