</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYATLANTA-RECORDS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dispute over releasing Olympic records heads to court
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The state attorney general demanded Wednesday that
Billy Payne's private foundation open Atlanta's Olympic bid records
to the public. The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation responded
by taking the dispute to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect for the almost herculean effort required
by those who organized the bid to bring the Olympic Games to
Georgia,'' Attorney General Thurbert Baker wrote to Payne's
attorney, ``they were not the GAAF Olympics. They were the Atlanta
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the attorney general's letter early Wednesday,
the GAAF later in the day announced it had filed suit seeking a
court's opinion that the records are private and not subject to
state Open Records laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to litigate this in court, we'll litigate this in
court,'' Baker said after learning of the foundation's action late
in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, GAAF chairman, and his attorneys say that the Olympic bid
campaign was a private effort organized by private individuals.
Baker, Gov. Roy Barnes and lawyers representing The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution argued the bid effort and the Olympics were
public events and the complete historical record of those events
should be made public.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Payne's attorney, which was copied to Barnes,
Baker cited the ``overwhelmingly public nature of the 1996
Olympics,'' as well as the ``inextricable link between private
interests and governmental entities'' in the bid campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have acknowledged reaching an impasse. Under threat
of the attorney general taking legal action, the GAAF filed a
lawsuit in Fulton County Superior Court seeking a declaration that
the Games were private.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks to preserve ``the established rights to privacy
of the foundation's donors, volunteers and staff,'' according to
spokesman Lee Echols of the GAAF, which Payne created in 1987 to
bid for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of negotiations with the attorney general's office
and the newspaper's attorneys, Payne's foundation on Friday opened
to public view nine of the 1,400 boxes containing Olympic documents
stored at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   However, entire file folders of materials, primarily dealing
with financial matters, had been removed before the material was
made public.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said any documents purged from the records that the GAAF
believes fall under the law's ``privacy'' exception must be
reviewed by his office, as well as by the newspaper's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general cautioned that the privacy exception would
not cover materials that could be considered ``embarrassing.'' Only
a document that would amount to a ``tortious invasion of privacy''
could be withheld from disclosure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The purged files have not been identified or presented for
review, as earlier agreed, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   GAAF attorney Joseph Bankoff disputed Baker's account. He said
the foundation had not agreed to show the removed files to
newspaper lawyers, but it was willing to give them to Baker for
review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process you insist upon would simply leave us in the
position of allowing counsel for the paper to fish through all GAAF
records to see what is of interest,'' Bankoff wrote in a response
to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Baker referred to the ``cloud of scandal'' over Salt Lake City's
bid for the 2002 Winter Games that has ``cast a shadow'' over other
cities' efforts to lobby the International Olympic Committee
delegates. Payne has said that no such corruption marred the bid to
bring the Games to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker said Payne's ``steadfast refusal to make the documents
available to the public, however, lends credence to the belief that
GAAF has something to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said that ``allowing public access to these documents on
an expeditious basis would certainly do much to bolster GAAF's
assurances that this is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankoff responded that there is no shadow over the Games ``other
than the one manufactured by'' the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general is plainly right that the law requires _
and the current cloud of scandal demands _ immediate disclosure of
the records by GAAF and the Atlanta History Center,'' said Peter
Canfield, a lawyer representing the newspaper in its effort to
obtain access to the bid records. ``In bringing the Olympics to
Atlanta, GAAF did not act privately. It acted in the official name
of the city and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope that what's most embarrassing about the records is
that they've been kept secret,'' Canfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
