<HEADER>
A5819 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLA-SEARCGH-ART-2NDT     05-05 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-SEARCGH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 OKLAHOMA CITY, Okla.: is gone.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the hours since the storms struck, Red Cross volunteers have
been compiling lists of both missing and located persons on a
computer in the city's makeshift emergency center and delivering
copies of those lists to Briggs. Often, the lists contain only a
name and little else, but Briggs said each report is pursued as
thoroughly as possible. His department supervised 18 dog-assisted
searches Wednesday morning in addition to visiting every known
address where a person's location has been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these reports are people calling in from out of
town,'' he said, ``and saying they just haven't heard from
so-and-so in a while. That's a lot different than a neighbor
telling us that someone never came out of their house after the
storm.'' He added: ``Sometimes we'll be out talking to someone in
their yard when a radio call comes in that they're missing. That's
just what happens when you've got no phones, no electricity, and
this kind of devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hill, a rescue worker from Abilene, Tex., said that the
search in Moore had been complicated because all the search dogs
had to go on was the general scent of humans. ``Often, the dogs
will bark or sit down or give whatever their indication is but
there's no one there,'' he said. ``Mostly it's just blood on the
boards or dirty diapers or the clothing people were wearing before
they changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bridge Creek, where Sheriff Florence believes that four or
five people remain missing, the Army National Guard has been
assisting law enforcement agencies in repetitive searches. The
sheriff said that scuba divers may soon search muddy ponds.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith and his men searched the creek bed this morning,
looking for a 26-year-old mother in an area where other bodies have
been found, they walked through layers of debris that had been
flung into the woods from nearby mobile homes. As they walked in
camouflage through the remains of a family's life _ a red-suited
teddy bear, inspirational books, a roll of Christmas wrapping paper
_ they also came across a cotton-mouth snake disturbed by the
intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take your time guys,'' Smith instructed his crew of Guardsmen,
which included a nursing student, a law student, a car mechanic and
a construction worker. ``Look under things and don't just look
down. Look up in the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   One soldier found a framed collage of photographs of smiling
young women, and said it would be passed along to the medical
examiner to help with possible identifications. In past searches,
one soldier found and collected a grainy sonogram image. ``He just
couldn't leave it out there,'' said Capt. Barry J. Guidry.
</P>
</TEXT>
