<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY CHEFS WIN PRESTIGIOUS JAMES BEARD AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who dine at the American Restaurant in Kansas City are
familiar with the artistry of a squash stuffed with peekytoe crab
or mustard-braised short ribs on a bed of wide noodles.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the rest of the country applauded fine dining
in Kansas City as Michael Smith and Debbie Gold, co-executive chefs
at the American since 1994, were honored with a James Beard Award
for Best Chef of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The husband-and-wife duo received the award during a black-tie
dinner at the Marriott Marquis in New York. It was Smith and Gold's
third consecutive nomination, and the first win for a chef from
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were created almost a decade ago to honor the late
culinarian James Beard, considered the father of American
gastronomy. Highly coveted, the awards are widely regarded as the
culinary equivalent of an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The honor comes as the American marks its 25th anniversary. Gold
and Smith were in elementary school when James Beard served as a
consultant for the restaurant in the mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good night for Kansas City, proving the city is
becoming more than a blip on the country's food radar screen. Also
a winner was Lidia Bastianich, chef//owner of Felidia's in New York
and Lidia's in Kansas City. She was named Best Chef of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all just one more piece of evidence...that we're
really coming of age as a restaurant town,'' says Art Siemering, a
trend-tracker for the food industry based in Kansas City and a
judge for the Beard Awards for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Siemering says other local chefs' names have appeared
on the preliminary nominee list recently, for the past decade
Midwest honors have been dominated by Chicago chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good,'' Michael Smith said of the award. ``But I
always look forward to the chase....You're walking around after and
you don't really know what to say to (the other chefs). Before,
we've always said, `We'll do it next year!' ''
</P>
<P>
   News of the award was greeted with enthusiasm by Patrick Weber,
chef at the up-and-coming Stolen Grill in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows about our barbecue and Stroud's (fried
chicken). And we're proud about those, but we're also coming of age
in fine dining. We're getting more respect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their serving top-of-the-line cuisine, Weber
credits Smith and Gold with having trained many of the city's best
cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 38, and Gold, 35, came to Kansas City from Chicago in
March 1994. They met at the famed Charlie Trotter's there. They
share responsibilities at the American, a co-executive chef
position that makes them one of a handful of high-profile
husband-and-wife chef teams in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of sharing their workday, they have also learned
to juggle their schedules to care for their toddler daughter,
Misha, a frequent visitor to the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   With their newfound recognition, they will also learn to balance
work with a higher level of fame. They can expect to be more in
demand for public appearances ranging from profiles in national
publications, guest appearances on TV and possibly even cookbook or
gourmet food tie-ins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
