<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR PLANS TO EXIT THE CHIP BUSINESS   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Calif.)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Less than two years after paying $550 million
for Cyrix Corp. to enter the personal computer microprocessor
business, National Semiconductor Corp. said Wednesday that it was
exiting that market.
</P>
<P>
   National said it would seek a buyer for the business as well as
for its related chip plant in South Portland, Maine, and that it
would cut 550 jobs, or 4.8 percent of its workforce, and take a
related charge of $250 million to $300 million in the fourth
quarter ending May 30.
</P>
<P>
   National executives said that the PC processor business was
unprofitable as a result of the price wars between Intel Corp. and
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. Sustained losses from the processor
division dragged down the entire company, National said,
attributing its losses for the past year to it, even though other
parts of the company's business were relatively healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Without the PC chip losses, National said, it expects to return
to profitability in its second fiscal quarter, which ends in
November. However, the sale of the plant, and the write-off of the
Cyrix business, should no buyer materialize, could lead to further
charges.
</P>
<P>
   National shares rose more than 20 percent to close at $17.6875,
up $3.0625, on the New York Stock Exchange. The stock had
previously gained on rumors that National was selling the Cyrix
business to International Business Machines &UR;  &LR; Corp. National did not
name a buyer, but said it was holding discussions with several
potential suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Peck, an analyst with S.G. Cowen, said that while the chip
factory would be an easy sale, the Cyrix business ``wasn't all that
appealing back in the heyday of the microprocessor business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's hard to imagine how you would profit from that
product,'' he said. ``National couldn't do it; AMD can't do it, and
Intel probably couldn't do it at the low end. It was an enormous
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyrix and Advanced Micro had an early lead in microprocessors
for the sub-$1,000 PC market, which Intel initially ignored. But
Intel caught up rapidly, and by aggressively lowering prices and
improving the performance of its low-end product line, dubbed
Celeron, eroded all profitability for its rivals. Further, Advanced
Micro and National both had manufacturing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not believing Intel would come after us in the low-end space
was a mistake,'' said Brian L. Halla, National's chairman,
president and chief executive. ``It doesn't make sense for us to go
slug it out with Intel,'' he said. ``We know, and the world knows,
that we don't have the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   National will pursue the market for so-called information
appliances, small communications and consumer electronics devices,
using the computer-on-a-chip technology developed by Cyrix.
National will also try to gain ground in the market for analog
chips, used to process audio and video signals, Halla said, with a
goal of being the No. 1 analog chip company. He argued the
microprocessor business could be attractive to the right buyer,
perhaps without the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious buyer would be IBM, but I have to assume they were
in discussions and that fell through,'' said Michael Slater, editor
of the Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter. Other
potential buyers would include ST Micro electronics, &UR;  &LR; the European
chip company, although it has, like National indicated it will
pursue the information appliance market, and perhaps Texas
Instruments Inc., he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said other makers of so called X86 Intel-compatible
chips, like Integrated Device Technology Inc., are also feeling
pressured. ``I think this is not the end of the turmoil,'' he said.
``AMD clearly needs to start executing better, and may need a
partner,'' he said, adding that an IBM partnership with AMD might
make more sense than acquiring Cyrix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the last X86 business that will be put
up for sale,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
