<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-LOTTO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S LOTTERY WINNINGS IS TWICE AS NICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Who says it's nearly impossible to win at
Powerball?
</P>
<P>
   It's happened twice in the Dreiling family.
</P>
<P>
   Grandview resident Regina Dreiling was introduced Tuesday as the
winner of last weekend's $47 million Powerball jackpot. Four years
ago, her husband's distant cousin won $31.2 million in a Kansas
Powerball drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The cousin will get around $1 million a year until 2015. Regina
Dreiling chose to take her money in one lump sum of $25.6 million
rather than the $47 million paid out over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dreiling, 37, was the only player to match all six numbers in
Saturday's drawing. She still has not decided what to do with the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem like a dream. It still seems like a dream,''
Dreiling said.
</P>
<P>
   She bought the lucky ticket at a 7-Eleven Food Store in
Grandview, on her way home from work last week. She had done the
same thing every Friday night for at least three years. Once
before, she won $100.
</P>
<P>
   She usually calls to get the winning numbers on Saturday night,
but this time she fell asleep and didn't call until Sunday morning
around 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it, I just hung up and kept calling back,''
she said. ``Then I had my husband call and he couldn't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Regina Dreiling, who have been married for seven years,
slept very little Sunday night. They kept the ticket hidden until
they redeemed it at the lottery office Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-Eleven store got $50,000 for selling the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Branch, a field consultant trainee at the 7-Eleven, said
this is the first time that store has sold a winning ticket. He
said the money will go into a corporate fund to benefit
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Uncle Sam will get his cut. Dreiling will pay a
little more than $1 million in state taxes and about $7.2 million
in federal taxes, lottery officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreilings have no children. They invited relatives to their
home so they could share the good news. Some thought they were
joking.
</P>
<P>
   The millionaire cousin's advice: Change your phone number and
get a tax lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreilings say it's too early to tell if they will need that
advice. For now, they're just trying to cope with what's happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much walked around in a daze for a whole day,'' Mark
Dreiling said. He said they're not sure what they want to do first.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Dreiling, who drives an '82 Oldsmobile Cutlass, would
like a new car. Mark Dreiling, 38, says he's always wanted to go to
Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Dreiling said she plans to quit her job as a secretary
for a security company after 14 years there.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dreiling, who for 15 years has been part owner of
Dreiling's Ornamental Iron Inc. with his father, said he won't quit
immediately. However, he said he will ``sure find other things to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is a word that I want to take out of my vocabulary,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple plan to stay in the area, but they want to move into
a new home. Regina Dreiling will continue buying lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreilings and their family members say it still doesn't seem
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``(When they told me,) I just walked back out; I couldn't
believe it,'' Mark Dreiling's father, Ed Dreiling, said. ``I
grabbed her and congratulated her.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the elder Dreiling said, he will have to persuade his other
son to take over the business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
