   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APACHE-PROBLEMS (Washington) _ During the 1991 Gulf War, the
Army's Apache helicopter was a technological star, destroying Iraqi
tanks with precision and speed. But now, during the Kosovo crisis,
the gunships have gotten off to an inauspicious start _ two crashes
and the deaths of two crew members in training missions. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUNDING (Washington) _ Republican leaders in Congress
press U.S. defense contractors to lobby hard for the GOP plan to
add $6 billion to the emergency funding bill for U.S. operations in
the NATO-led attack on Yugoslavia, a measure that would be a boon
to defense industry. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-GUNS (Washington) _ In the wake of the Littleton, Colo.,
high school massacre, senators accuse Attorney General Janet Reno
of failing to fully enforce federal gun laws. But Reno defends her
record, saying that many of the estimated 6,000 students who
illegally bought guns last year were prosecuted under state and
local law. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Ramstein Air Base, Germany) _ President Clinton
meets with the three GIs freed by Yugoslavia as Defense Secretary
William Cohen says the United States may release two Yugoslav POWs.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Austin, Texas) _ A Republican member of the Texas
House accuses his own party of pressuring state senators to prevent
a hate crimes proposal from reaching Gov. George W. Bush's desk.
``This is a very emotional issue for the Republican Party,'' says
Rep. Tommy Merritt of Longview. By LAURA TOLLEY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Texarkana, Texas) _ Attorney General John Cornyn
accuses his predecessor, Dan Morales, of fraud in his dealings with
Houston lawyer and friend Marc Murr. In a court motion, Cornyn says
Morales didn't have a contract with Murr and that it was all part
of a scheme to help Murr cash in on the billions in fees stemming
from the state's legal action against cigarette makers. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DAMAGE (Oklahoma City) _ Officials assess damage and
displaced residents pick through rubble as Oklahoma City begins to
recover from the devastating storms that hit the region Monday. By
ALLAN TURNER and DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-BRIDGE-CREEK (Bridge Creek, Okla.) _ Eight people are
still missing in the flattened community of Bridge Creek. Search
dogs used in the Alfred P. Murrah federal building bombing four
years ago are being brought in to sniff for bodies. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Denver) _ With a home-court advantage in the first
round hanging in the balance, the Houston Rockets play their final
regular-season game of the year Wednesday night against the Denver
Nuggets. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (New York) _ The Houston Astros try to finish what
has been a successful East Coast road trip on a high note as they
wrap up a three-game series against the New York Mets. By JOSEPH
DUARTE.
</P>
