<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SUSPENDS SALES OF HANDGUNS TO VENEZUELA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has suspended sales of
handguns to Venezuelan companies, one of the largest foreign
markets for American gun sellers, because of concern that many of
the guns were ending up in the hands of narcotics gangs and
guerrilla groups in neighboring Colombia, American officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to a State Department report on arms sales, which has
not been made public, licenses were issued for the sale of more
than 80,000 handguns from the United States to dealers in Venezuela
last year, a volume three times that of 1997 and seven times that
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That ``dramatic increase'' caused the Clinton administration to
undertake an investigation and stop accepting new license
applications pending the outcome, an official said. A brief
investigation last year, by both the Customs Agency and the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, concluded that there was a ``good
likelihood'' that handguns licensed for sale in Venezuela were
being diverted to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The sales suspension is unusual, only the third or fourth time
that the United States has blocked sales of handguns to a foreign
country, an administration official said. Three years ago, the
administration suspended sales of handguns to dealers in Paraguay
after Brazilian officials complained that thousands were pouring
across the border; that ban remains in place.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Clinton administration stopped issuing licenses
for handgun sales in Britain, after it decided that the guns going
there were often sold to terrorists, organized criminal gangs and
to warring parties in the Balkans and Africa. That suspension has
since been lifted, but handgun sales in Britain have fallen off
sharply, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been working with Latin American
countries to tighten the controls on weapons sales. The
Organization of American States has adopted a treaty on arms sales,
which is awaiting ratification in the Senate. By executive order
last July, President Clinton instituted regulations, meant to be a
model for other countries, that are intended to regulate the import
and export of handguns and rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan ambassador to the United States, Alfredo
Toro-Hardy, said that he was not aware of the State Department's
action, which was taken early last month, but that he knew the flow
of guns from the United States to his country had widened
significantly through improper permits and other illegal channels.
He added that the current government, which took office in
February, was taking ``strict measures to restrict the issuance of
licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   A private arms control organization, the Council for a Livable
World Education Fund, commended the suspension, but also raised
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shutting down the gun spigot to Venezuela was a prudent
move,'' said Thomas Cardamone Jr., director of the arms control
project at the fund. ``But why wasn't the suspension of new
licenses imposed earlier?'' Cardamone called for a congressional
investigation ``to insure that a similar situation does not occur
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Cardamone called for a closer look at handgun
sales in the Philippines and South Africa. In 1997, American
companies were licensed to sell 35,000 handguns in the Philippines
and 29,000 in South Africa, a country plagued by a proliferation of
weapons and rising crime.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said one reason the United
States had not acted earlier against Venezuela was that ``we have
American firms in the gun-selling business.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest seller of handguns in Venezuela last year was Valor
Corp., in Cape Coral, Fla., according to American licensing
applications. Valor received 95 of the approximately 240 licenses
approved. (A license can apply to more than a single gun; in one
instance in Venezuela, for example, one license was for 1,200
handguns.)
</P>
<P>
   An employee at Valor, who declined to identify herself, said the
only person who could answer questions was the owner, who would not
be available until the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   The second largest seller was Baxter South, according to
American licensing documents. The company declined to answer any
questions. ``We do not give any information to the press,'' said a
woman who answered the telephone at the company's headquarters in
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
