<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business Week looks at Milken's attempt to rebuild his
reputation
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Milken's name will be linked forever with Wall
Street scandal, especially the insider trading fiasco of the 1980s
that sent dozens of people _ including Milken _ to jail.
</P>
<P>
   With that behind him, the man who invented the junk bond market
has for the last six years ``used every waking moment to rebuild
his life and reputation,'' Business Week (May 10) reports in its
cover story.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he has outlived doctors' predictions that he
would die of cancer, which is why he is pouring copious amounts of
time and money into finding a cure for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he has launched a new business, Knowledge
Enterprises, which offers educational services to corporations.
</P>
<P>
   CEOs at warp speed
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (May 24) attempts to answer the question, ``What kind of
person thrives as CEO of an e-corporation?''
</P>
<P>
   They are the heads of companies such as Dell Computer,
Amazon.com, Cisco Systems and Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new breed of CEO ... operates at warp speed and suffers
from ... `bandwidth-separation anxiety' _ they get crazy when
deprived of high-speed connection to the rest of the planet via
cell phone, two-way pager, or e-mail. E-business is business in
real time, where nothing can wait until tomorrow or even after
lunch,'' Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that, since the Internet lowers barriers to
entry, ``it amplifies weaknesses,'' Fortune adds.
</P>
<P>
   Strength is weakness
</P>
<P>
   Fast Company (May) warns fast-trackers to be careful: ``It's not
your weaknesses that can trip you up on your way to the top _ it's
your strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing research by the Center for Creative Leadership in
Greensboro, N.C., the magazine says talented people fail to reach
the top for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   They resist change and won't adapt during transitions; they are
difficult to work with, and often seem to be insensitive,
manipulative and overly critical; and fail to lead in a
``team-centered way.'' Since work is a social activity, Fast
Company offers advice to talented people. Among the gems of wisdom:
Drop into someone's office for a 10-minute talk at least once a
day; when people talk to you, listen; when you need help, ask for
it; start conversations with small talk; do favors for others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
