<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH FREED U.S. SOLIDERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany _ As President Clinton met Wednesday with
three American POWs recently released by the Serbs, Defense
Secretary William Cohen said he was inclined to recommend the
release of two Yugoslav soldiers now held by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen, who accompanied Clinton on a whirlwind trip to two
U.S. air bases in Germany and to NATO headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium, said any such release would not be in response to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's decision to free the U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a goodwill overture to Mr. Milosevic,'' Cohen
said. ``I don't believe Mr. Milosevic has made any goodwill
overture toward us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the soldiers would be released ``consistent with
traditional standards'' _ but he did not spell out what those
standards are.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav soldiers were captured in separate incidents last
month by the Kosovo Liberation Army and turned over to the Albanian
government. The Albanians turned the prisoners over to U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   Both soldiers are being held in Germany, Pentagon spokesman Ken
Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said NATO intends to step up its bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia regardless of whether the Serb soldiers are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue,'' he said. ``It will not impede our
intensification of the air campaign. We're going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president also was faced with vivid reminders of the
risks of prolonged military involvement. An Apache helicopter on a
training mission in Albania crashed, killing its two pilots. It was
the second of these low-flying combat helicopters to crash before
they have engaged in military action.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred to the pilots, the first U.S. fatalities in the
Kosovo conflict, in an address to soldiers and their families at
Spangdahlem Air Base in southwestern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I have tried to make sure the American people
understand in the years I have been president is that your jobs
have inherent dangers, even when not directly engaged in
conflict,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another reminder of the hazards of war, Clinton met with the
three former American prisoners of war and separately with each of
their families. The soldiers are being housed at Ramstein Air Base
while they undergo evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who had donned an airplane bomber jacket for the
Ramstein visit, posed for pictures with three soldiers and their
families at the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of them,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The three men _ Spc. Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas;
Staff. Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles and Staff. Sgt.
Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich. _ were captured March
31 while on a routine reconnaissance mission near the Macedonian
border with Kosovo. The Rev. Jesse Jackson negotiated their release
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stone did most of the talking in the presidential meeting, White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just glad to be free,'' Stone told the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's trip was clearly intended to boost the morale of
U.S. soldiers stationed at bases here that supply personnel and
equipment for the military engagement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to soldiers at Spangdahlem in a hangar surrounded by
F-16 aircraft, Clinton stressed that the Americans were fighting
Milosevic now to avoid another protracted European conflict in this
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This base was built in the aftermath of the Second World War
at the dawn of the Cold War,'' Clinton said to an enthusiastic,
flag-waving welcome. ``Because of allied vigilance, the war we then
feared would occur never happened. Now planes are actually flying
into combat from this base for the very first time, to protect the
future your forebearers worked so hard to build.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
