<SLUG> BC-MATH-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 STATES PLAN NEW MATH CURRICULUM AND EXAMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis., Ill., Ind., Md., Mass., Mich., N.H., N.C.,
Vt. , Wash. ,  N.Y., N.J., Va.)   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motivated by the mediocre performance of American eighth-graders
on an international math test, the governors of 10 states said
Wednesday that they would help develop a new curriculum and
rigorous exam designed to raise students' performance to the level
of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Mathematics Achievement Partnership, which experts called an
unusual collaboration among states, comes at a time when most
states are working on or have adopted new academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   The new curriculum and test will focus on the highest levels of
eighth-grade math, like algebra and geometry, the bane of many a
student but a bellwether of future achievement in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kids, no matter if they are headed for higher education or
work, ought to head into high school prepared for what the rest of
the world regards as a high school sequence of mathematics,'' said
Robert B. Schwartz, president of Achieve, a not-for-profit
organization developing the instructional materials and test.
</P>
<P>
   Achieve, based in Cambridge, Mass., was formed at the 1996
National Education Summit of governors, educators and business
leaders and is co-chaired by Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin and
Louis V. Gerstner Jr., chairman and chief executive of IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Wisconsin, the other participants in the math project
are Illinois, Indiana, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New
Hampshire, North Carolina, Vermont and Washington. The states,
working with their legislatures, state boards of education or other
channels, would seek to incorporate the Achieve test into their
regular battery of tests in spring 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Achieve officials said they hope to attract more states as they
draft the curriculum and test, guided by an analysis of current
practices in 20 states they consider reform-minded and six
top-performing nations on the Third International Mathematics and
Science Study, known as TIMSS. That is the exam on which American
eighth-graders showed lackluster performance, placing 27th out of
40 nations in the 1995 round.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said Achieve had asked the 20 states it studied,
including New York and New Jersey, to join the program but only 10
have confirmed. Officials in New Jersey and New York said they
declined because they are introducing new eighth-grade tests this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts reacted favorably to the test. ``We have learned a
lot from TIMSS, in particular what students in American schools
don't seem to be doing,'' said Albert E. Beaton, a Boston College
testing expert who has worked on TIMSS.
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Gerald Bracey, an education policy analyst and
former director of testing for Virginia, were more cautious,
asserting that the program seemed redundant with several states'
efforts to improve their teaching and assessments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those state assessments, 36 states participate in
the federal government's National Assessment of Education Progress
exam, which covers eigth-grade math and other subjects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
