A5846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIGHTS-RAPPORTEURS-NY     05-05 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGHTS-RAPPORTEURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE A-TEAM FOR REPORTING HUMAN-RIGHTS ABUSES AROUND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Their job is to document many of the most gruesome and
persistent abuses of societies around the world, including torture,
disappearances and summary executions. They collect information,
interview victims and weave those accounts into a pattern, usually
one that tells of flagrant deprivations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   They are called ``special rapporteurs'' in the lexicon of the
United Nations, which offers administrative support and pays the
expenses, but not the salaries, of 36 such independent
investigators. Their primary employment is as little-known lawyers,
judges or human rights advocates, though some have served the
United Nations for years.
</P>
<P>
   The rapporteurs' names come to light about once a year, when the
U.N. Human Rights Commission, which appoints them, meets for its
six-week conference. The investigators have to report their
findings and usually, but not always, see their work validated when
the 53-nation body approves resolutions that rebuke countries for
their failures.
</P>
<P>
   Rights inspectors are specifically assigned to more than 12
nations to examine and monitor their performance. Some are
countries that have undergone cataclysms like Cambodia and Rwanda.
Others have long-term troubles like Afghanistan, Iran and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The situations vary, but many face considerable obstacles. Iraq
has banned its rapporteur, former Dutch Foreign Minister Max van
der Stoel, since his first report, in 1992. After his latest
report, which described the government as having one of the
bleakest rights records of any leadership since World War II, Iraqi
officials dismissed van der Stoel as ``reckless and incapable'' and
accused him of ``inventing lies.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fighting in Kosovo unfolded during the commission's last
session, which recently ended, Jiri Dienstbier, the investigator
for the Balkans and a former foreign minister of Czechoslovakia,
was shut out of the Serb province. His teams were stranded, he
said, and he is now gathering firsthand reports of refugees who
have fled.
</P>
<P>
   Asma Jahangir, a Pakistani lawyer who is the investigator for
extrajudicial and summary executions, has faced death threats and
has been under police protection for years.
</P>
<P>
   Rapporteurs examine not only government conduct, but also
broader wrongdoing. In addition to torture, that includes religious
intolerance, child prostitution, the effects of armed conflict on
children, the sale of children, violence against women and extreme
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the special rapporteurs dates from 1978, when it was
decided that a single person should replace the traditional working
groups, usually consisting of several people from various regions,
to examine strife-ridden countries.
</P>
<P>
   The idea spread, according to John Pace, an official with the
U.N. Human Rights Office in Geneva. In the '80s fact-finders were
named for Argentina, Bolivia and Guatemala, among others, along
with rapporteurs to investigate abuses across national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Under U.N. rules, the work depends on the cooperation of
countries, which have to invite them to visit and which often
stonewall. For years, China ignored British law professor Nigel
Rodley's request to visit. This year, Rodley finally received an
invitation and plans a trip early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal of a country to cooperate creates what some see as a
weakness in the reporting system. Rapporteurs who are locked out of
a country are forced to depend largely, if not exclusively, on
information from nongovernmental organizations, which can be
unreliable or biased, rather than on firsthand interviews and
information gathering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
