<SLUG> BC-ATT-CABLELANDSCAPE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable operators face few disadvantages after AT&AMP;T's buy
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T's purchase of MediaOne leaves surprisingly smooth
waters for Cox Communications and other cable TV operators to
navigate.
</P>
<P>
   True, for the first time, MediaOne, the largest owner of cable
TV systems, will no longer be a cable TV operator. Long distance
carrier AT&AMP;T will now hold that distinction, controlling systems
that pass 60 million homes nationwide. Its systems will include the
one in the city of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's tentative purchase also pushes Atlanta-based Cox
Communications further down in the rankings of largest cable TV
operators. Cox Communications is between fifth and seventh,
depending on how the ranking is calculated.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's No. 1 status, for the most part, is not expected to
accelerate the deployment of digital television in Atlanta or
nationwide. Nor will it hail the broad introduction of interactive
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T's purchase means nothing in terms of new services and
pricing to consumers,'' says Abhi Shaki, a director of media
consultant Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is because AT&AMP;T is not a television company and
doesn't care much about it. Its interest is in using cable networks
to provide new services such as high-speed access to the Internet
and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Those interests dovetail with those of MediaOne, which has one
of the most advanced cable TV systems, but used it to provide local
telephone service and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``MediaOne has not been aggressive in rolling out digital
television or interactive services,'' says Bruce Leichtman, a cable
analyst with media consultant the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T does care about Internet access, which it has offered as a
service for years. Some industry observers now believe that the
company will put its immense marketing muscle behind establishing
cable TV's new cable modem technology as the standard Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   These modems, using new digital networks of some cable systems,
provide Internet connections up to 100 times faster than
traditional telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if AT&AMP;T pumps $300 million into marketing cable modems
under its brand name,'' says Shaki. ``That would help all of cable
TV to make these modems mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers wonder whether Cox Communications and
other independent operators can make it alone any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago we said that you needed at least 1 million
subscribers to be a player,'' said Spencer Grimes, a media analyst
with Solomon Smith Barney. ``Now that number has moved to 5
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications, with 4 million subscribers, falls just under
that threshold. ``I think the company can go it alone, but it will
be at a disadvantage,'' says Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, counters Leichtman. He says size is not as important as
concentration. A cable operator can do well if it dominates a large
and lucrative market, like Cox Communications does in San Diego,
Phoenix and Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a misconception that you have to be huge to survive or
prosper,'' says Leichtman. ``Cox Communications can survive very
well in the markets it now dominates.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Cox Communications, the company recently told analysts
that it has no intention of selling. It is a buyer. And, as if to
make the point, the company recently announced a $1.4 billion
purchase of cable systems from Media General in Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get bigger,'' says Cox Communications President Jim
Robbins, ``and we are continually chipping away at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
