<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LIKELY TO PASS KOSOVO FUNDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House is expected to approve a $12.9 billion
emergency funding bill Thursday that would finance the U.S. portion
of the NATO operation against Yugoslavia through Sept. 30, but also
would add billions more in questionable Pentagon spending.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is likely to draw overwhelming, if somewhat reluctant,
support from a majority of Democrats and Republicans. It is
designed to meet the president's request for $6.05 billion in
supplemental military spending for this year to help replenish bomb
and cruise-missile inventories depleted by the allied campaign, and
to help ease the refugee crisis in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But an attempt by the Republican leadership to add on another
$6.85 billion in spending for some favored programs has angered
members of both parties who believe that unrelated Pentagon
spending issues should be sorted out later, when Congress debates
the 2000 defense appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the GOP leadership is pushing ahead with the added
funding, despite objections from the Clinton administration that it
goes well beyond the cost of continuing the Kosovo engagement
through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the congressional opposition, House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, enlisted some defense contractors and lobbyists
last week to remind lawmakers that their own districts could
benefit from the extra spending.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ``sweeteners,'' as one Republican aide called it,
include a pay increase of $1.8 billion for military personnel,
$1.07 billion in construction funds, $70 million for diplomatic and
consular programs, $1.34 billion for spare parts, and nearly $1
billion for depot maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the administration nor the Pentagon listed as high
priorities many of the items, such as a firing range worth $3
million to be built at the Aviano Air Base in Italy and $48 million
for a complex for bachelor enlisted personnel in Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   But they are priorities for Republican lawmakers who, because of
budget constraints set by law, have been unable to get all of what
they want attached to previous defense spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would also like to see many of the add-ons to the
Kosovo measure approved, especially the military pay raise. But
they want those issues addressed in the regular appropriations
process.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, conceded last week that much of the extra
spending proposals are ``worthy.'' But he stood by his charge that
Republicans are trying to turn the emergency Kosovo measure into a
``pork barrel'' spending bill of sorts to assure passage of
spending measures that could get left out of the Pentagon's 2000
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The added spending also troubles some conservative Republicans
who are vigorous Pentagon advocates. One of them, Rep. Sam Johnson
of Plano, Texas, is having a tough time reconciling the need to
replenish ammunition and weapons supplies with his opposition to
U.S. involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a former prisoner of war in Vietnam, was still
undecided Wednesday about how he will vote on the emergency
measure. He would prefer not to support it, one aide acknowledged,
because of his opposition to the NATO campaign and because the bill
includes additional spending that he believes should be addressed
in the regular appropriations process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that he is frustrated at this
point,'' the aide said. ``He does not want to forward-fund the war,
and he thinks that this is the wrong vehicle for adding on all this
other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Johnson, like many other members of Congress, may vote
for it to show support for U.S. personnel and to ensure their
safety as the NATO operations proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is planning to vote on the Kosovo funding bill soon
but is unlikely to include additional spending much beyond the
president's $6 billion request. The two versions then would be
reconciled in a conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leadership, meanwhile, is advising members
to vote for the Kosovo measure regardless of how they feel about
Republican efforts to beef it up and the vote by most GOP members
last week against continuing the allied air campaign. House
Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri said last week that the
GOP vote was ``inconsistent'' with Republicans' attempts to
``double-fund'' the president's Kosovo spending request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general sense (among Democratic leaders) is they
(Republicans) are trying to have it both ways. They've been very
reckless and very irresponsible in how they've voted on the war so
far, but they're trying to use the war as political cover to fix
some of the spending problems they've had because of the (budget)
caps,'' said one Democratic leadership aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is ... the Republicans have done enough damage and
we don't want to compound that by voting against this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, writing in USA Today on Wednesday, said it was perfectly
legitimate for Republicans to ``cast a vote of no confidence
against the president and vote for funding troops in the field at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, we must not sacrifice the safety of our troops at
the expense of a deeply flawed policy,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
