<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' EX-ATTORNEY GENERAL ACCUSED OF FRAUD IN TOBACCO SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas attorney general on Wednesday filed court papers
accusing his predecessor of giving a fraudulent contract to a
lawyer friend who was awarded $260 million in legal fees from the
state's settlement with the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   In those papers, filed in U.S. District Court Court in
Texarkana, Texas, Attorney General John Cornyn said that former
Attorney General Dan Morales created phony contracts for Marc Murr,
a Houston lawyer, which Murr would get as much as 3 percent of the
$17.3 billion settlement that Texas reached in its lawsuit against
the nation's cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   In September, an arbitration panel in Texas awarded Murr $260
million. But three months later, after other lawyers in the case
told a national arbitration panel they were not even aware that
Murr had been involved in the lawsuit, Murr's fees were reduced to
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Murr is still seeking hundreds of millions of dollars from the
state for his role in the lawsuit, while Cornyn has opposed the fee
request.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Morales, a Democrat who did not seek re-election
last year, called the accusations false and ``bizarre'' and said
that Cornyn, a Republican who took office in January, was smearing
Morales to hurt his future political hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Murr could not be reached for comment, and his lawyer, Roy
Minton of Austin, did not return a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge who oversaw the Texas tobacco case, David
Folsom, has scheduled a hearing Thursday in Texarkana for Murr to
show why the state panel's $260 million award should not be thrown
out. Cornyn had sought to compel Morales to testify at the hearing,
but Folsom ruled late Wednesday against requiring his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has also been investigating the matter, according to
people who have been contacted by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Murr and Morales worked together as associates at a Houston law
firm in the early 1980s, and have been friends ever since. Murr
also helped raise money for Morales' political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ended its lawsuit against the tobacco industry in January
1998, becoming the third state, after Mississippi and Florida, to
win a large settlement for lawsuits that sought to recoup the costs
of treating smoking-related illnesses of Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   Part of those settlements required the tobacco industry to pay
the fees for lawyers who handled the states' cases. In December,
before the three-member panel that convened in New York to
determine those amounts, Morales said that Murr played an important
role in the Texas case. But other lawyers sharply criticized Murr's
fee request, saying they believed he actually played little, if
any, role in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Murr and Morales had appeared before the separate
state arbitration panel in Texas that determined Murr was entitled
to $260 million, a claim now pending before the federal court in
Texarkana. Murr had also sought to use the $260 million state award
to convince the national panel to award him a high fee.
</P>
<P>
   But that state award was ``procured by fraud,'' according to
Cornyn's filing, which alleges that Murr and Morales presented the
state panel with a fake contract _ created a few weeks before the
panel met but dated Oct. 17, 1996 _ that said Murr was entitled to
a fee of 3 percent of the Texas settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn also alleges that a separate contract with Murr, dated
Jan. 31, 1997, is also fake. He said that contract was created
after that date when the signatures of Murr, Morales and another
state official were ``switched'' from a separate ``secret''
contract after another lawyer who had signed on to the case, Will
Pryor, decided that he did not want to be involved in the lawsuit.
Pryor could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' lawyer, Sam Millsap of San Antonio, said the
accusations were political. ``This is the first shot from the
Republican Party for what they expect to be the governor's race in
2002,'' Millsap said. They're trying to take Dan out as a potential
candidate for governor in 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Millsap said the contracts were not doctored, and he accused
Cornyn of trying to turn Thursday's court hearing in Texarkana into
a ``star chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn was traveling to Texarkana on Wednesday and was not
available for comment. A spokesman, Ted Delisi, declined to say
what evidence the attorney general has that the contracts are
phony, and he said Cornyn only made the allegations after Morales
sought to avoid being called as a witness at Thursday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Delisi also denied that politics played any role in the attorney
general's investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
