<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS WITH U.S. TROOPS IN MORALE-BOOSTING TRIP TO EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, Germany _ Donning a brown bomber jacket in
solidarity with the NATO forces in Yugoslavia, President Clinton
began a two-day morale-boosting trip to Europe on Wednesday that
included a brief visit with the three American soldiers who were
recently released from Serbian captivity.
</P>
<P>
   His trip here was the closest Clinton has come to the Yugoslav
theater of war since NATO began bombing Serbia on March 24. Despite
a packed schedule that took him from Brussels to two air bases in
Germany, the visit, in a gray drizzly chill, was a subdued one for
the weary-looking president, for whom the war presents an array of
nettlesome complications.
</P>
<P>
   Because of diplomatic moves between the United States and Russia
over how to end the Balkan conflict and a meeting of the Group
Seven countries plus Russia in Bonn on Thursday, Clinton's schedule
was expanded from a 24-hour visit with troops to include talks with
NATO commanders in Brussels on Wednesday morning and a visit with
Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The visit also included plans to meet with relief agencies
handling the refugee crisis and to boost the spirits of the
thousands of military personnel providing support for the NATO
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed the troops at the American air base in
Spangdahlem and then here, where he locked into an earnest
discussion with nine men during supper in a hangar under the
propeller of a hulking C-30 transport plane.
</P>
<P>
   He said later that they talked about the war as well as the
military's recruitment problems and low pay and that he assured
them of bipartisan support in Congress for a pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States military, because of people like you, can do
things for a troubled world that no one else can do,'' the
president told the troops after supper. ``And I'm profoundly
grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in Brussels on Wednesday morning after an overnight
flight from Washington to the news that the two pilots of an Apache
helicopter had been killed, apparently in a training accident. They
are the first American casualties of the Kosovar conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that the immediate fall-out of the war _ the
overwhelming difficulty of helping perhaps as many as 1.5 million
refugees _ weighed heavily on Clinton, even as the United States
accepted its first planeload of 453 refugees on Wednesday at Fort
Dix, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Atwood, head of the Agency for International Development,
who traveled here with Clinton, said that the quandary of the
refugees dominated the president's private talks on Wednesday.
``The international community is going to, at times in the next few
weeks, appear to be very disorganized,'' Atwood said, contemplating
the scale of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the president's public appearances on Wednesday were
fairly low-key. His speech at the American air base in Spangdahlem
was just 17 minutes, and he seemed to hasten through his stack of
events, putting himself uncharacteristically ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his day at NATO headquarters in Brussels by
meeting with Secretary General Javier Solana. He was then briefed
by Gen. Wesley K. Clark, the supreme allied commander. He later
flew here and met privately with the three former captives and
their families for about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thought Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president,
had let them go, Clinton declined to speculate. ``The important
thing is he did let them go,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
