<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-MULHALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``WE HAD A PRETTY NICE TOWN AND THEN AN HOUR LATER IT WAS JUST
GONE''
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MULHALL, Okla. _ Standing on the sidewalk outside Mulhall's
elementary school, kindergarten teacher Judy Knight was beginning
to grasp the wallop that Monday's tornado had unleashed on this
tiny farming community.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old grandmother, who has lived in Mulhall all her
life, watched teachers and their spouses sift through the remains
of desks, books and lockers in search of anything that could be
salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to her left, Knight could see her place of worship, the
Mulhall Christian Church, where the front portion of the chapel was
crumpled onto the front lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's starting to sink in just how bad this storm
was,'' Knight said. ``It didn't really leave any of the town
untouched.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that descended upon this town of 250 wasn't as
destructive as the massive twister that hit several hours earlier
50 miles to the south in the Oklahoma City area. But it struck a
near-fatal blow to the community's core.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of the town's 110 homes was damaged. Fifty are
considered uninhabitable, 50 have major damage, and 10 have minor
damage, according to a survey by the Oklahoma Fire Marshal's
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the damage, there were no serious injuries in Mulhall.
</P>
<P>
   Besides hitting the elementary school _ which might be a total
loss _ the tornado hammered the post office, a fire station and all
three of the town's churches. It also toppled the town's
75-foot-water tower, and the water washed a nearby frame house off
its foundation. Two 50,000-bushel grain storage bins also were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``wE HAD A PRETTY NICE TOWN AND THEN AN HOUR LATER IT WAS JUST
GONE,'' SAID Willis Doggett, chief of Mulhall's volunteer fire
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wiped out our infrastructure,'' he said. ``We have no
water, no sewer and no electricity _ and that's just the tip of the
iceberg. That doesn't even address how we build this town back to
what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials estimate that a limited supply of water will be
restored by this weekend, but it could be two weeks before the town
gets electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the obstacles, Mayor John Pangburn was optimistic
that the tornado, which tore the roof off his house, would wake
Mulhall from its doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   The town, which was formed in 1889, was named for Wild West
promoter Zack Mulhall, whose daughter Lucille was dubbed ``The
World's First Cowgirl,'' according to a historic marker.
</P>
<P>
   Pangburn, who retired to Mulhall eight years ago from San Diego,
said that heritage and Mulhall's compact size give residents a
chance to improve the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this happened, there was a tendency for people here to
be apathetic,'' Pangburn said. ``Now we've got a chance to get rid
of some derelict homes that had become fire traps because of
neglect. I'm a positive thinker, so I'm convinced we'll make it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   One business owner, Jackie Pfeiffer, was an overnight convert to
the mayor's philosophy. Pfeiffer, who owns the only convenience
store in town, went to bed Tuesday night questioning whether she
should rebuild after the storm tore away her store's roof but left
shelves and refrigerated units standing.
</P>
<P>
   Her small store was the only place in town for residents to buy
food, and also served as the community's only restaurant with a
small grill and fryer behind the counter. In effect, it was
Mulhall's unofficial gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked so depressing around here the morning after, I had
to ask myself whether I wanted to start over from scratch,''
Pfeiffer said. ``I put a lot of time into this place and I was
telling myself I was ready to move on. But after 150 people stop
by, begging you to rebuild, what choice do you have? You've got to
rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
