<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-DEAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST MEMORIES ARE BITTERSWEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD and REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Sondra Doty clings to the memory of her
husband's goodbye kiss and the sound of his voice on the telephone
after she called him at his job Monday to warn him of the
approaching tornado.
</P>
<P>
   She would not see him again until the next day, after a
supervisor at an Oklahoma hospital asked her to come to the
facility and identify his body.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that swept through the Oklahoma City area Monday
night passed behind Spencer's Super Thrift, the Newcastle store
where Bill Doty worked as assistant manager. The 54-year-old man
suffered a heart attack during the ordeal, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   She rushed to Southwestern Medical Center to be by his side at 8
p.m., but chaos during the tornado's aftermath apparently left some
hospital employees unaware that Bill Doty was there, Sondra Doty
said. It would be six hours before the matter would be cleared up
and Doty would learn that her husband had died within minutes of
arriving at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a nightmare,'' Sondra Doty said. ``It was like a bad
movie, but it was happening to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For dozens of families, the details are different, but the
horror is the same. Just as with Sondra Doty, the deaths of their
loved ones has left them embracing bittersweet memories.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Melissa Battaglia is facing motherhood for
the second time, she struggles with being a widow. Her husband,
37-year-old Anthony Battaglia, was killed Monday by flying debris
as he crouched beside a loading dock, using his body to shield
other employees from the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real excited about having a little girl,'' recalled
Battaglia's mother-in-law, Marilyn Smith. The couple had picked out
the baby's name: Natalie. ``She's got a hard time ahead. She has a
very large extended family, so hopefully that will help her get
through it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said her son-in-law was very outgoing and never met a
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we appreciate was his sense of humor and his outgoing
personality and his love for his family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Killed along with Battaglia was co-worker Jerry Webb of Enid,
Okla. He also perished trying to shield others from the deadly
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both really respected and loved around there,'' said
Terry Stambaugh, executive vice president of human resources for
their employer, American Freightways. ``They'll be greatly
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Webb said his brother was a typical ``redneck cowboy'' who
cared greatly for others and had a large family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a good cowboy and he was always ready to help
somebody else,'' Ray Webb said. ``I never heard him complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Webb lived on a farm in Enid and had about 20 head of
cattle, his brother said. There, he enjoyed fishing and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Webb said his brother's third wife, Becky, is taking his
death hard, as are his nine children. Jerry Webb was one of 10
children. His mother, 91-year-old Delma Ruth Webb, had been living
with him, but is now staying with sister Marilyn.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, workers searching the debris of the destroyed
building found the trademark black cowboy hat that Webb wore, and
which co-workers described as his ``pride and joy.'' Employees plan
to give the hat to Webb's widow, Stambaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Sondra Doty said that in her husband's last moments, he also
focused on others.
</P>
<P>
   In a rushed telephone conversation, Bill Doty told his wife that
he and fellow employees were heading to the store's cooler, and he
urged his wife to take their 8-year-old son Dakota and seek
shelter. She told him they would hide in the closet, and the couple
hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was worried about us, Dakota and I,'' Sondra Doty said.
``He was worried about us and his employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Doty described her husband as upbeat and a hard worker who
always put her and their two children first. Bill Doty was a native
of Marlow. It was there, at a dance held at a roller skating rink,
that the couple met. Two months later they married, Sondra Doty
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, family and everyone told us it wouldn't last six
months,'' she said with a laugh. They were to celebrate their 30th
anniversary in September.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
