<HEADLINE>
FBI JOINS SEARCH FOR MISSING IN BRIDGE CREEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ The FBI has joined in the effort to help
account for Bridge Creek residents who remained missing two days
after a monster tornado scarred the landscape and decimated homes
in this semi-rural community, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Five people remained unaccounted for late Wednesday, Grady
County Sheriff Stan Florence said. The list stood at eight early in
the day, but FBI agents whittled the number by three, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Information was unavailable as to where the three were located.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven are confirmed dead from the twister that struck Monday
evening. Their names had not been released late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because phone lines are still out and residents may have gone
elsewhere before or after the storm, the number of missing can
change by the hour, Florence said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the missing might be in hospitals scattered around the
Oklahoma City area, unconscious and unable to identify themselves,
Florence said.
</P>
<P>
   Some bodies may not have been found, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All resources are being directed toward accounting for all of
the area's residents, Florence said. Authorities used search dogs
all day to look for victims, but none had been were found by the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our big issue now,'' he said. ``Matching up names with
bodies _ missing and dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridgecrest Baptist Church, which was a mass of mangled metal
after the tornado struck, had a service in an amphitheater next to
the 20-year-old church.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Tom Duckett wanted his church members ``to see each
other, love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And pray for people we don't see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State Sen. Carol Martin was at Snow Hill Baptist
Church, one of two locations in the Bridge Creek area where food,
clothing and other necessities were being collected for those in
need.
</P>
<P>
   Her district covers Bridge Creek, Moore and South Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers are the backbone of the area pulling together, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are coming out of the woodwork,'' she said. ``We're doing
the best we can. How can you make a sane situation out of chaotic
one?''
</P>
<P>
   In Newcastle, a bedroom community of about 3,800 residents east
of Bridge Creek, about 500 homes were damaged or destroyed,
Newcastle Police Chief John Quinton said yesterday. Fortunately,
the storm hit the north side of the city where there are fewer
homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were minor injuries but no deaths from the storm in
Newcastle, Quinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Livestock, however, is a different matter. No one really knows
how many animals were lost because fences went down and animals are
roaming freely, Quinton said. Many likely were killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people with dead animals on their property who
don't own livestock,'' Quinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
