<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND RUSSIA TO ISSUE JOINT STATEMENT ON A KOSOVO FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(bl) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Western allies and Russia have narrowed
their differences over a future international force in Kosovo to
the point where they will be able to issue a joint statement
Thursday on ending the conflict in the Serbian province, U.S. and
NATO officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior German official said an outline accord had been reached
with Russia on the need for ``an international civil and security
presence'' that would enter Kosovo under a United Nations mandate
after an eventual withdrawal of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   But officials stressed that gaining Russia's agreement to a
joint statement was still a long way from winning the agreement of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But subtle changes in official announcements and news in
Yugoslavia have led journalists and analysts to suspect that
Milosevic may be preparing Serbian public opinion for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The joint statement, to be issued after a meeting in Bonn of
foreign ministers from the Group of Seven most industrialized
nations plus Russia, is intended rather to increase the isolation
of Milosevic, who has looked to Moscow for support, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The partial reconciliation with Russia, after ties were strained
to breaking point at the start of NATO's bombing campaign,
represented a boost to President Clinton as he arrived in Germany
on Wednesday. His two-day visit is intended to cement allied unity
over the Kosovo campaign and bolster a German government under
increasing pressure from critics of the air war.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Germany, Clinton said that he believed it was
important ``that the Russians, perhaps the Ukrainians, perhaps
others who come from the Orthodox tradition, who have close ties to
the Serbs, be a part of such a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said Wednesday that the
meeting of foreign ministers from the so-called G8 countries
``should enable the West and Russia to set out the principles of a
solution in Kosovo.'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is
traveling with the president, will attend.
</P>
<P>
   To get the Russians on board, the officials said, the statement
was likely not to name NATO, nor to spell out an explicit role for
the alliance in the proposed force. Milosevic and the Russians have
strongly opposed any NATO force in Kosovo, leading allied officials
in recent statements to speak of an international force with NATO
``at its core.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet another Russian desire, the statement is also expected
to refer to the need for a mandate from the United Nations for the
Kosovo force.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the omission of specific reference to NATO in the
statement should not be interpreted as a change of policy.
``There's a gray area here,'' one official said. ``Given our desire
to have the Russians, no one is going to be insistent on ramming
down the throat of the Russians every element of NATO's five
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said many differences with Russia remained, but enough
progress had been made for a statement that would call for the
return of all refugees and the deployment of an international force
to protect them _ both central demands of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The exact composition, mandate and weaponry of the international
force, the degree of Serbian military withdrawal from Kosovo, how
any such withdrawal would be linked to an end to the NATO bombing
campaign, and whether a solution can be imposed rather than
negotiated, remain contentious questions with Russia, they said.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joshcka Fishcer wants to use the accord
with Russia as the basis for a U.N. Security Council resolution
agreed upon under Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter, which, unlike
Chapter 6, does not require the consent of the parties to any
dispute for the authorization of military operations.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said no diplomatic breakthrough was expected
during Clinton's stay and made clear that the bombing was expected
to continue at least into next week, despite the president's first
allusion Monday to the possibility of a pause.
</P>
<P>
   The longer NATO's campaign goes on, the more frayed the
``Red-Green'' coalition of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder may
become. Already, Schroeder is facing some vociferous calls for an
end to the war from within his own Social Democratic Party and from
the once pacifist Greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing of Serbia cannot be justified from any possible
standpoint,'' Oskar Lafontaine, a prominent Social Democrat and
former finance minister, said last weekend. ``It is wrong to label
whole groups of people good or evil. It is senseless to bomb
bridges and then turn around and plan how to rebuild them.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was Lafontaine's first since he quit the
government in March. It reflected growing uneasiness on the left of
the Social Democratic Party, although up to now such anti-war
feeling has been fairly muted.
</P>
<P>
   The growing criticism has involved allegations that the bombing
violates international law, outrage over civilian deaths, and
uneasiness at the high cost of the war. Schroeder told his party
executive Monday that the United States was paying 90 percent of
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, minority partners in the government, are to hold a
party congress next week that is certain to reflect sharp divisions
over the war. If a motion for an immediate stop to the bombing was
passed, the coalition could be endangered. But Fischer will strive
to avert such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not Great Britain,'' said one official close to
Schroeder. ``This war is not an easy sell to a people whose
pacifist feelings are still strong. That is one reason why the
picture of Clinton and Schroeder standing together is so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be particularly important because German uneasiness is
such that any suggestion of the use of ground troops could lead to
the fall of the government. And without ground forces, or even the
threat of their use, NATO's air campaign could be extremely long.
</P>
<P>
   However, senior German officials with normally reliable
intelligence reports believe Milosevic's support may be
increasingly tenuous. ``Those who back Milosevic because they
depend on him see that he cannot protect them any longer,'' one
official said. ``Internal opposition is growing, and that could
become clear next week.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say what might happen next week, or where the
focus of resistance might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether allied countries are working on a covert
plan for Milosevic's overthrow _ something they publicly deny _ and
whether the official was indulging in propaganda or wishful
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The core of Milosevic's backing has traditionally been a small
coterie of ministers and political allies who have been granted
lucrative control of various import-export businesses, from the
well-paid architects of the government's propaganda, and from a
cosseted core of military police officers. The army has been more
ambivalent, at least until the NATO campaign began.
</P>
</TEXT>
