<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-FEMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISASTER BRINGS NEW WORKLOAD FOR FEMA OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ANDREW BACKOVER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Mary Ann Carlisle drove into what used to be the
thriving suburban neighborhood of Frolich Meadows in southeast
Oklahoma City on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a tornado ripped through the area Monday night, smashing
dozens of homes into rubble and splinters, the most visible signs
of the neighborhood were neighbors salvaging lost memories.
</P>
<P>
   It's Carlisle's job to help them rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Total devastation,'' said Carlisle, a reservist for the
Federal Emergency Management Agency who lives in Waco, Texas.
``Total devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, teams from FEMA and the state of Oklahoma began the
seemingly endless task of contacting residents and city officials _
and explaining how to apply for federal grants and loans available
after President Clinton declared 11 counties in Oklahoma a disaster
area.
</P>
<P>
   The process will take many days, Carlisle said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle and Lynn Roberts, who is from Northern California,
started the outreach program in Del City, asking city officials to
point out the hardest-hit areas. Then they went to nearby
neighborhoods to hand out fliers detailing the
application-by-telephone process. They were chauffeured by Tommy
Kirkpatrick, a retired IRS agent from Oklahoma City whose sole
mission is to take the FEMA representatives anywhere they need to
go.
</P>
<P>
   For residents, some of whom rolled up the yellow fliers in their
tired, mud-caked hands, the information was much appreciated. But
many had more immediate concerns on their minds. Just two days
after the deadly storm, they were just beginning to pick up the
pieces of shattered lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't worried about that right now,'' said Tony Helms, 46, a
Frolich Hills homeowner, referring to the federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Helms survived the tornado in a bathtub with his wife and
mother-in-law. The bathroom walls are gone, as is most of the
house, and his white Ford Escort sits upside down in what used to
be a den. They survived unhurt, but took with them only some
clothes and a drawer full of compact discs and cassette tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ought to be dead,'' said Helms, who plans to contact FEMA as
he works out details with his insurance company. ``This whole
neighborhood ought to be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bush, who survived the tornado alone in a closet with
pillows over his head, was not sure he would even try to rebuild
the 1,900-square-foot house he moved into March 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, that's up in the air,'' said Bush, 48, a team
leader at a nearby General Motors plant. ``We really don't know
about that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still holding the flier, Bush said he didn't even know if he was
eligible for FEMA's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have insurance, and FEMA could probably help people worse
off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Carlisle stressed throughout the afternoon, renters,
homeowners or business owners with even minimal damage could be
eligible for aid, including Small Business Administration loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are your tax dollars at work,'' she told residents and
local officials.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA officials, who only Wednesday began sending teams to
neighborhoods, would not estimate the amount of aid tornado victims
might receive. Up to 300 military reservists will be on hand to
help assess damage and deal with recovery, said Billy Penn, a
spokesman for FEMA's Region VI headquarters in Denton, Texas, who
arrived in Oklahoma City by daylight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA and its state counterpart also coordinate the deployment of
``assets'' such as water tanks, flashlights, hard hats and
generators.
</P>
<P>
   But, to the people picking the rubble of their homes, FEMA's
true contribution will come in the form of financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll contact FEMA and see what my options are,'' said Leroy
Nitzel, 64, a retired truck driver whose Frolich Hills home was
largely spared. His neighbors' homes across the street were razed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, FEMA has countless residents to contact. In Del
City, a town of about 24,000, nearly 560 homes were destroyed, said
Judy Gordon, Del City's assistant to the city manager. Inspectors
are still trying to assess the damage there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hardly any houses in those areas,'' she said, pointing
to a map. ``They are all leveled.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
