<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALALEGIS-HONDA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama proposal attracts Honda
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alabama is likely to use part of its $3.2 billion
tobacco settlement to help attract a Honda Motor Co. auto plant to
a site about 100 miles west of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The incentives Alabama will offer have not been finalized, The
Associated Press reported, but they are expected to include bonds
for the project, with the interest to be paid with $16 million a
year in tobacco money. Local governments are also expected to kick
in $15 million in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Months of secret negotiations with state officials likely will
culminate today in Birmingham, Ala., with an announcement that
Honda will build a new sport-utility vehicle in Alabama.
Officially, the company maintained Wednesday that no decision has
been made, but Gov. Don Siegelman called a news conference to
announce ``a major economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature debated details of the Alabama incentive
package Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was under consideration for the plant _ along with
Illinois and Virginia _ but the talks did not progress beyond
discussions with a consultant for an unnamed client, said Randy
Cardoza, commissioner of the Georgia Department of Industry, Trade
&AMP; Tourism. The state was touting an 800-to-2,000-acre site in
Jackson County that has been mentioned as a possible location for
other manufacturing operations. The talks were never called off,
but they aren't active, Cardoza said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman told the Birmingham News the project will cost more
than the $300 million Mercedes-Benz sport-utility plant that began
production in Vance, near Tuscaloosa, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda site is near Lincoln, on Interstate 20 about 50 miles
east of Birmingham in Talladega County and about 50 miles from the
Georgia line, close enough for Georgia to feel some of the economic
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plant couldn't go to a better place, other than inside
Georgia,'' Cardoza said.
</P>
<P>
   It's close enough to attract suppliers who could locate in
Georgia as well as provide high-paying manufacturing jobs for
Georgians. Lincoln is not too far to commute from west Georgia,
Cardoza added.
</P>
<P>
   While some suppliers will need to be on or near the site for
just-in-time deliveries, others might want a more central location
so they can serve other Southeastern auto plants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the assembly jobs probably will be filled locally,
although managers and certain skilled workers are likely to be
drawn from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Besides jobs at the auto plant, Cardoza said each job there
generates 1.8-to-3 related jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
