<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-BELLSOUTH06-COX     05-05 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-BELLSOUTH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth prepares to face competition
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Local phone companies can now see the main rival they
will battle for the huge consumer market and it turns out to be _
their estranged mother.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as Ma Bell, AT&AMP;T Corp. was forced out of local
service and compelled to divest itself of BellSouth and six other
regional phone companies in 1984. However, with Wednesday's
announced deal to buy MediaOne, AT&AMP;T now envisions a return to
local markets with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   It is a battle for which BellSouth has been preparing _ will it
be ready?
</P>
<P>
   By using upgraded cable lines, AT&AMP;T hopes to offer tens of
millions of cable customers a package that will include phone,
high-speed Internet access and television. And while improvements
to MediaOne wires are incomplete, the upgrades are far ahead of the
former Tele-Communications Inc. franchises that AT&AMP;T bought last
year. With MediaOne, AT&AMP;T will have access to more than half the
homes in the United States. Moreover, in bowing out of the bidding
for MediaOne, Comcast added to AT&AMP;T's local clout by agreeing to
let AT&AMP;T serve its customers too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chore is to upgrade our own plant, services and
capabilities so we can be an efficient competitor,'' said C. Sidney
Boren, executive staff officer for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The chore could be a matter of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Cavallari, executive vice president of Boston-based
consulting company Renaissance Worldwide, said an alternate wire to
millions of homes via cable can be worse than just a damper to
phone company growth. Much of BellSouth's expansion in its
nine-state region has come from consumers adding extra lines for
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the cable company can give you high-speed Internet access,
you are going to cancel that phone line,'' Cavallari said. ``It's
not just competition for growth _ it's knocking out the second
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike MediaOne, AT&AMP;T has a nationally recognized and trusted
brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is thinking, 'we've got 80 million long-distance
customers and we need to touch them with a wire,''' Mines said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has for years trumpeted a three-legged strategy:
dominance in the Southeast, combined with lucrative businesses in
Latin American and wireless service. That approach has kept
BellSouth on the sidelines watching other companies merge in a
series of huge deals.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deal sets the stage for confrontation with AT&AMP;T, but
Boren said the biggest surprise is that AT&AMP;T would choose to spend
more than $100 billion to own cable companies, rather than forge
alliances. BellSouth for about six years has been expecting rivalry
from that second wire to the home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is betting that digital subscriber line (DSL)
technology can compete with high-speed cable. DSL has a headstart,
since it can work on existing copper lines _ sometimes.
Unfortunately, many lines cannot handle DSL for a range of
technical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   That means that BellSouth too must spend many millions of
dollars more to install revamped lines or add fiber optics,
Cavallari said. ``AT&AMP;T has a steeper hill to climb but they are
resolved they are going to do it. This is the time bomb that
BellSouth and the other regional phone companies are looking at.
You must roll out DSL, and you must roll it out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth last year started offering DSL in metro Atlanta, but
the rollout has been slow. Perhaps not coincidentally, MindSpring
Enterprises said Wednesday it would finally start offering
BellSouth's DSL service to its customers in the fall. The company
had complained for months that BellSouth had not been cooperative
in setting marketable prices for DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other regional phone companies, BellSouth has held a
virtual monopoly in local service, with challenges mostly limited
to some larger business customers. In Atlanta, BellSouth has only
two competitors for residential service: MGC Communications and
MediaOne, whose upgrade is still unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts expect AT&AMP;T's deep pockets to ensure a relatively
quick completion of the new, high-speed systems, and if the Bells
do not respond, they will be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Although overall totals are small, cable modems now outnumber
high-speed phone lines by a 10-1 margin, according to Forrester
Research. As both markets grow, that margin is projected to fall to
3-1, with about 15 million customers for cable modems in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth does have some time: Forrester predicts that it
will be 2001 or 2002 before cable phone service nationally has more
than 1 million subscribers. BellSouth has more than 20 million
phone customers in its region.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bells face a dilemma, said Chris Mines, analyst with
Forrester: If they don't pour money into boosting their own
systems, customers in search of new services will abandon them. But
if they do invest what is needed, that could drain short-term
profits _ something that is awfully hard to explain on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an announcement earlier this year about a net income
shortfall helped dampen BellSouth stock for months. To suffer less
from that kind of announcement, BellSouth could reshape its
corporate image among investors from one of a stodgy monopoly with
solid and predictable growth to a company spending aggressively to
compete in a shifting industry.
</P>
<P>
   Until AT&AMP;T entered the fray, the Bells had no incentive to move
fast, Mines said. ``Their core business is not under attack. There
are only a few thousand cable phone subscribers. But at the risk of
earnings growth and margin expansion, they have to invest now to
protect their core business that will be in danger five years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth recently announced a 10 percent investment in Qwest
Communications, a move that will give BellSouth a long-distance
company, once it is permitted into that market. Qwest also has
high-speed data services and a presence in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But is that enough? ``Not even close,'' Mines said. ``That helps
them with their plans to offer long-distance. This is a whole other
level of strategic challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boren rejected the notion that BellSouth is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The company can spend millions improving its networks without
hurting earnings, because customers want the new services, he said.
``The deployment of broadband has accelerated beyond what any of us
anticipated 12 or 24 months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren declined comment on reports that BellSouth might invest in
the merger of Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia. But he said the
alliance with Qwest gives BellSouth the reach it needs to serve
customers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you see BellSouth do is an attempt to come to your
home and sell you what you need to make your life easier and
better. The price goes to the company that is big enough to do
that, but small enough to provide individual good service.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth expects to be in long-distance within the year, a
change that would permit ``bundled'' offerings with the range of
services that customers want. And while $23 billion-a-year
BellSouth will be dwarfed by AT&AMP;T, Bell Atlantic, SBC and MCI
WorldCom, Boren brushed aside the idea that bigger is always
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be big enough _ but not any bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
