<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-BELLSOUTH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring links with BellSouth to provide ADSL
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises said Wednesday it has entered
into an agreement with BellSouth that will allow it to provide
high-speed ADSL service to MindSpring subscribers in the nine-state
BellSouth service area.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based MindSpring is one of the largest Internet service
providers in the country, with 1.2 million subscribers. A
significant portion of those subscribers are in Atlanta and the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Anderson, MindSpring director of product management for fast
access, says the Internet provider will begin offering the service
in the early fall to MindSpring subscribers in the metro Atlanta
area. Other cities will follow. MindSpring will manage installation
and service to Atlanta households that are ADSL-ready.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said MindSpring isn't ready to announce pricing plans
for the high-speed service but promises competitive pricing.
BellSouth.net currently charges a monthly fee of $59.95 for its
high-speed service. BellSouth customers pay $49.95 monthly.
BellSouth.net charges a one-time installation fee of $199.95 to
configure computer and phone lines for ADSL service, and a one-time
service activation fee of $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   The ADSL service will be up to 200 times faster than a 28.8k bps
dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson cautions MindSpring subscribers that the company is at
the beginning of the ADSL process. ``Even then not every customer
will be eligible,'' he says. ``We are sensitive to the frustration
customers feel and we are going to do everything to move that
along,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth deal is a giant step in MindSpring's battle for
access to so-called ``last mile'' phone and cable access from local
utilities to users' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, MindSpring Chairman Charles Brewer openly expressed
his annoyance with BellSouth and other phone companies for offering
DSL at prices he considered outrageous and unreasonable. However,
since then, consumer demand for high-speed service has grown while
MindSpring has nearly doubled in size to become one of BellSouth's
biggest and best customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our size and the potential size of the service has led us to
really become a top tier customer of BellSouth for this service,''
says Michael McQuary, MindSpring president and chief operating
officer. ``We've always been one of their top customers, but with
some of the evolution in the last year, it has made us one of the
top providers of Internet service, and it's given us a better forum
to discuss what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary also says the aggressive moves by cable operators such
as AT&AMP;T and Time Warner to roll out cable modem service have forced
phone companies to rethink DSL deployment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cable companies have really invested a lot of time and
money into showing that high-speed broadband Internet access over
the cable system is a reality. It's coming and it's made the
regional Bells take notice and gear up their own plans for
broadband.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary says once the phone companies recognized the possibility
of cable owning the so-called ``last mile'' from the local provider
to users' homes, they worked to make sure their hardware is ready
and their service is offered at a consumer-acceptable price point
to make it a viable alternative to the cable offering.
</P>
<P>
   According to Herb Cash, vice president of marketing for
BellSouth business, the price for BellSouth's ADSL service hasn't
changed, but other things have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is really ready for these kinds of service
offerings,'' he says. ``If anything has changed it's that we are
going aggressively toward the ISP customers.'' He also said that as
more people begin to use the Net, they'll want to upgrade their
service to the best of what's available. ``It's like anything else
_ you want to improve on it from a speed standpoint and from an
'always on' standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analyst Abhi Chaki says it's neither fear
of cable modems nor lower prices that's made BellSouth more willing
to do business with MindSpring and other ISPs. ``It's the law,'' he
says. ``They are required by law to open up their high-speed
services to ISPs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they wanted to make as much money up front as they
could,'' Chaki says. ``They were making it too expensive for people
to resell the services. Now with its investment in DSL and its
efforts to ramp it up, BellSouth sees the advantage of wholesaling
ADSL to companies like MindSpring. The break-even mentality the
telecos typically operate on is a very anachronistic now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
