<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATSEMI-SFCHRON &LR;      05-05 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATSEMI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Nat Semi Exiting Microchip Business
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Succumbing to pressure from Intel Corp., National Semiconductor
Corp. is getting out of the microchip business and laying off 550
people, including 180 at its Santa Clara headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The move will cost the company as much as $300 million and
represents a black eye for National chief executive Brian Halla,
who bought Texas chipmaker Cyrix Corp. in 1997 for $540 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Cyrix chips helped pioneer the sale of cheap computers, Halla
crowed that he had found a niche in the market that could be safe
from Intel.
</P>
<P>
   But after some initial stumbles, Intel revved up its engine for
making low-cost chips and quickly attacked National and Advanced
Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking that Intel wouldn't have the stomach for
those kinds of prices,'' Halla said in an interview yesterday.
``Not only did they go aggressively after the market, but they
quickly took away the market share we had taken from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Halla, who once worked for Intel, hadn't counted on Intel's
strategy of ``market segmentation,'' in which the company's
tremendous profits in selling expensive chips for corporate servers
and workstations help subsidize sales of its low-end Celeron chips.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Dave Tremblay of InfoBeads, a Ziff-Davis market research
firm, said Halla shouldn't have been surprised. ``Intel had to get
aggressive at the low end,'' he said. ``They couldn't let AMD or
Cyrix go unchallenged there.''
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessors _ often called the brains of personal computers
_ account for only 10 percent of National's sales. The company
makes most of its money _ about 70 percent _ from selling products
such as amplifiers based on its analog technology and the rest of
its money comes from chips sold for cellular phones, networking
devices and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Without microprocessors, Halla said, he's still pinning his
hopes on ``information appliances'' such as television set-top
boxes and stand-alone computers that connect to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While that vision may yet come to pass, Halla has paid a price
for his early investments in such products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part of being a visionary is not just seeing the
future, but knowing when it's going to happen,'' said Linley
Gwennap, editor of the Microprocessor Report, an industry
newsletter. ``It's surprising to me that the board (of directors)
is still standing behind him, given how much his strategy is
unraveling.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, National posted a net loss of $98 million on sales of
$2.5 billion. The company said unloading its microprocessors will
lead to returned profitability by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered the news, sending National's stock up $3.06
to close at $17.69, its biggest one-day gain since November 1990.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear who would end up with Cyrix or how
much they would pay. Rumors had been rife within the industry that
International Business Machines was interested, although some
analysts questioned why IBM would want to compete directly with
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, National's challenge in selling the microprocessor
business is to find anyone willing to compete with Intel, the
world's largest maker of computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just aren't a lot of companies that want to go and
charge the Intel hill,'' Gwennap said. He cited one possibility:
the German firm SGS Thompson, which makes similar microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Dan Briody, an editor at InfoWorld, ``A lot of
people wonder why someone would buy a dying company.''
</P>
<P>
   Halla said prospective buyers are now kicking the tires, but he
wouldn't name names. Gwennap said a large Japanese or Korean
company would ordinarily make a strong suitor, but those firms
aren't capable of a large acquisition because of the economic
situation in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   National isn't putting all of Cyrix on the market, only the
microprocessor part of the business, which is based in Richardson,
Texas. Halla said National also plans to keep a minority interest
in the chip fabrication plant that it built in South Portland,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The move caps a rough year at National, one of the oldest
semiconductor companies in Silicon Valley. In July, it asked its
13,000 employees to take off 10 days, either as vacation or without
pay. That belt-tightening came on the heels of the layoff of 1,400
workers, including 560 in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 550 job cuts announced yesterday, 180 will be at the
company's development factory in Santa Clara, leaving about 120
people working in that facility. Another 165 workers in Singapore
will be laid off, with the other cuts spread to other National
sites.
</P>
<P>
   National's retreat from the business comes just two months after
Intel settled government charges that it violates antitrust laws.
Although National's exit leaves only AMD as a significant
competitor, analysts didn't see enough of a marketplace change to
warrant government scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it hard to compete with Intel? Yes. But does that make them
anticompetitive? That would be very hard to prove,'' said analyst
Drew Peck at SG Cowen &AMP; Co. ``Nothing has changed except National
has decided to cut bait.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwennap noted that National controlled only about 3 percent of
the worldwide chip market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
