<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Devices Put the World in Your Palm
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The next time you're on vacation and trying to find the way to your
hotel, you may pull out your cell phone or electronic organizer
instead of a map.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of companies are developing services that provide
directions, emergency help, maps _ even the location of the closest
Starbuck's _ for mobile phones and personal digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next year, customers will be able to buy phones and
PDAs (personal digital assistants, such as a PalmPilot or a Windows
CE-based Palm-size PC) that can pinpoint a caller's exact location.
By using satellites or cellular signals, the devices will be able
to ``know'' where they are.
</P>
<P>
   When a phone or PDA is turned on, software inside the device and
at a central network can sense where the phone is located. Some
phones and PDAs may display a map showing where you are, others
will have an operator or voice system that can relay your exact
position.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that information, cellular carriers and other
companies want to offer consumers a way to find their favorite
haunts while on the road. With a single phone call or click of a
button, business travelers and vacationers will soon be able to
find the nearest ATM, taco joint or Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   That information could be relayed on the screen of the cell
phone or on the PDA. It could also be given to the caller by an
operator or a voice-activated system.
</P>
<P>
   Most cellular carriers plan to offer these wireless location
services over the next few years, and some organizers, such as the
PalmPilot, already have some of the capability.
</P>
<P>
   The Strategis Group, a research firm in Washington, D.C.,
projects that cell phone companies will spend more than $2 billion
on location technologies over the next five years. Most of that
money is being spent to meet federal requirements, which mandate
that wireless carriers be able to tell the location of a 911 call
by October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 69 million people already carrying a mobile phone
and several million more with PDAs, the market has a lot of
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people become increasingly untethered, they want
information about &LR;   &LR; the area they are in at the moment they are in
it,'' said Ellen Kirk, vice president of SnapTrack, a San Jose
company that help wireless carriers pinpoint a caller's location.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody needs a tow truck, they want to be able to get one
for the area they are calling from. If they need flowers, they want
to find a flower shop a few streets away.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk's San Jose company has developed software that can help
achieve that. SnapTrack's software locates where a call is being
made by using technology based on Global Positioning Satellites or
GPS. When a caller turns on his or her cell phone, SnapTrack's
software pinpoints the location of the caller.
</P>
<P>
   SnapTrack has agreements with several wireless manufacturers,
including Motorola, which plans to embed SnapTrack's technology
into its wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as Palo Alto's Vicinity Corp. and
Boulder's SignalSoft, are creating databases of shops, banks,
hotels and other businesses that road warriors may want to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in New Orleans, for example, and want to find the
nearest Cajun restaurant, you just push a button on your phone and
we provide that information,'' said David Hose, president of
SignalSoft.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still negotiating agreements with various
wireless carriers, but expects that several companies will soon
offer the ability to access SignalSoft's database from a cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Sprint PCS say they plan to offer location
services as early as this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The company believes that customers would like ``to have a
certain amount of information at their fingertips tailored to their
specific needs,'' said Tom Murphy, a spokesman for Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   He said customers can already get some localized information by
dialing 411 on their Sprint PCS phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in Knoxville and want to know what's showing at the
movie theater today, you can dial 411 and we'll get you that
information,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   But the new suite of services will go a step further by giving
directions to the theater and possibly even ordering tickets for
the customer in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as 3Com's PalmPilot division, are
providing the information via electronic organizers.
</P>
<P>
   At least one third-party vendor already provides a GPS system
for the PalmPilot. DeLorme offers a product called the Earthmate
GPS Receiver, which allows Palm users to download maps and routing
directions. Palm users can track their location on the device as
they move about a city.
</P>
<P>
   When the Palm VII is rolled out nationwide this fall, it will
include Web-browsing capabilities that will let users access
MapQuest to find directions, and Visa and MasterCard's Web sites to
find the nearest ATMs. However, the Palm VII won't have a built-in
locator system. Users will have to add a GPS product or punch in a
ZIP code to find location-specific information.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the cell phone and PDA companies are branching into
the wireless location market is the amount of money to be made, say
industry experts. The costs of the service has not been determined,
but most industry watchers predict carriers will charge between $5
and $10 per month for location-specific information.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the largest markets to serve is the business traveler
or the vacation traveler,'' said Albert Lin, who follows the
wireless industry for the Abernathy Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But the cell phone carriers are actually being forced by federal
regulators to provide the location-specific information.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission requires that by October
2001, cell phone carriers be able to identify a caller's location
when they dial 911. Cell phone companies will need to pinpoint
within 125 meters where a 911 call was made in order to route
callers to the closest emergency 911 center and locate the caller
if they've been in an accident or need immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are doing this by using GPS, technology such as
SnapTrack's or by gauging where a person's call is coming from
based on which cellular towers are picking up the call.
</P>
<P>
   Installing the technology is an expensive process that the
carriers originally balked at, but they've come to realize that
location-based information can be used to their advantage, Lin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC goes as far as saying they recognize this is a huge
commercial opportunity for the carriers,'' Lin said. ``This is a
billion-dollar opportunity for companies. Being able to know the
location of a person is great for advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, companies like SignalSoft and Vicinity have already
lined up a slew of companies to participate in their shared
database. Their listings may include some of the biggest
corporations, such as Hilton Hotels, Federal Express and Pizza Hut.
Eventually, customers who want to find an ATM or hotel will be able
to punch ATM or HOTEL on their phone and get a listing of the
closest ones.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of providing travel directions and information is not
new. General Motors has been giving driving instructions and
roadside assistance through its OnStar system, which is installed
in 31 brands of GM cars.
</P>
<P>
   OnStar uses a GPS system to track the vehicle and has a call
center where customers can get driving instructions, a listing of
the closest restaurants and other information. The company has
about 60,000 customers and charges about $25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But while OnStar is helpful within a car, the selling point of
the new products is that they are mobile, said Andrew Cole, a
principal with Renaissance Worldwide in Boston. However, these
locator services won't sell a phone or PDA, Cole said. They are
more of an add-on feature, like voice mail or call waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a bundle of services, this will be attractive,'' Cole
said. ``Concierge services are the icing on the cake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
