<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HQ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 H&AMP;Q Chief Says IPO Fees Are Likely to Fall
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist chief executive Daniel Case, whose San Francisco
firm is one of more than a dozen investment banks hit by a federal
probe of possible fee-fixing for initial public stock offerings,
said those costs are likely to fall as competition among
underwriters heats up.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Case declined to comment on a Justice
Department antitrust investigation of whether securities firms
fixed fees for taking companies public.
</P>
<P>
   Justice last week said it was looking into whether investment
banks engage in ``anticompetitive practices'' in deciding how much
to charge companies for selling newly issued stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, Case said stiffer competition will
force down fees as new players such as banks and Internet
underwriters enter the IPO arena. He compared the situation to
retail stock brokerage, where the growth of discount firms pushed
commissions down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all transactions in financial services, there
is downward pricing pressure,'' Case said. ``IPO fees are no
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Case was one of the first securities industry CEOs to comment on
IPO fees since the Justice probe came to light.
</P>
<P>
   Companies paid underwriters a fee of exactly 7 percent in more
than 90 percent of midsize IPOs in recent years, according to a
study by Jay Ritter, a University of Florida finance professor, and
a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   At H&AMP;Q, that charge was virtually set in stone. In all but two
of the 56 IPOs the firm led or co-managed in 1998 and 1999, issuers
paid a 7 percent fee, according to CommScan, a New York firm that
tracks securities offerings.
</P>
<P>
   While the 7 percent level may look solid, some investment banks
are undercutting the standard by picking up costs traditionally
borne by the issuer, Case said. For example, some underwriters are
now willing to pay for travel by company officials to meet with
potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q's chief said a trend is also emerging to give issuers a menu
of options with different fees.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional, full-service IPOs will carry a full fee, while
bare-bones offerings with fewer underwriters may cost less, Case
said. The cheapest alternative may be IPOs transacted entirely over
the Internet and managed by a new breed of all-electronic
underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fees collected by individual underwriters have
been falling ``for a long time,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the 7 percent IPO fee must be divided among more
investment banks as the average number of IPO co-managers has been
edging up in recent years. Stock issuers are demanding more
co-managers to ensure that their shares are sold as widely as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   University of California at Los Angeles finance professor Ivo
Welch, a specialist in IPOs, countered that the amount individual
firms get is irrelevant to the fee-fixing question.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the perspective of an antitrust investigator, I would not
be concerned about how much each underwriter gets, but at how much
underwriters get in total,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Case said he expected H&AMP;Q's profits to hold up even as
underwriting fees shrink because the firm will increase the number
of IPOs it manages, though he noted the IPO market experiences
sharp swings in volume.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter that ended March 31, H&AMP;Q reported earnings of
$25.8 million, up 62 percent from the first quarter of 1998, as the
number of IPOs it led or co-managed jumped 50 percent. ``Volume has
been exploding while unit-pricing has been going down,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   Case and Welch agreed that issuers worry less about the fees
they pay for IPOs than creating a buzz in the marketplace and
getting strong demand for their stock from investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like paying for your daughter's wedding,'' said Case.
``You don't want to be cheated, but you don't focus primarily on
what it costs. You just want everything to go well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
