<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Tech Journalists Scramble to Get on
Magazine's  Most-Powerful List 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
This month, Jeff O'Brien is the hottest lunch date in town.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien edits the San Francisco magazine Marketing Computers,
and the next issue will feature the sixth annual ``Influencers
List,'' ranking the most powerful technology journalists.
</P>
<P>
   He probably should put himself on the list. Editors, reporters,
columnists, chief executives and their flacks are all calling,
e-mailing, wining and dining the 29-year-old career-maker to get on
the list, which quickly has taken on power beyond its origins.
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists have told O'Brien that their raises and bonuses
depend, at least in part, on their ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of lunches I have with high-powered editors ramps
straight up in the months before I publish this list,'' O'Brien
says. ``My floor is covered with reams of articles they've
written.''
</P>
<P>
   I met O'Brien at a schmooze-fest sponsored by the editors of PC
Week magazine at the swanky restaurant Shanghai 1930 in the
Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing a table with reporters from the New York Times, the Wall
Street Journal, USA Today, Bloomberg News and Reuters, we munched
on crispy Peking duck wrapped in steamed buns, and O'Brien told how
the list originated as a service to his core readers, the high-tech
public relations industry.
</P>
<P>
   Those people still tape it to their cubicle walls, but ``it's
taken on a life of its own,'' O'Brien says. ``It garners as much
attention from the media as it does from the PR people.''
</P>
<P>
   By its nature, the list wounds some egos, and many people find
fault with O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was outrightly accused of sexism and of ignoring
whole publishing companies because of some vendetta against them,''
O'Brien says. ``I get calls asking me for career advice: `Am I at
the wrong publication? How can I get on the list?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of attention for a magazine that's only six years
old, with a free circulation of about 25,000. Marketing Computers
is a division of New York's Adweek magazine, which is part of BPI
Communications (publishers of Billboard magazine), which itself is
owned by the Dutch publishing conglomerate VNU.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien compiles the list through as many objective criteria as
he can find _ circulation of a publication, number of speaking
engagements of a journalist, how often they're quoted in other
media. But there also are intangible factors, such as if the
journalist in question was among an elite handful invited to Bill
Gates' house.
</P>
<P>
   One name has topped the list every year since its inception:
Walter Mossberg, the personal technology columnist for the Wall
Street Journal. O'Brien won't tell who's on this year's list, but
he tells how last year Mossberg nearly didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a heart attack and was not writing for three or four
months,'' O'Brien recalls. ``There was a lot of speculation that I
was going to bump him down. I thought long and hard about it. As
powerful as the people below him (on the list) are, given his
circulation and the power he wields, it's very difficult to knock
him out of the top spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The list will be out in the June issue, in mailboxes around May
24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the bane of my existence, and at the same time, it's a
high-profile, fun and interesting thing that draws attention to the
magazine,'' O'Brien says. ``It's a bittersweet experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SILENT SALON: &LR;  Nothing like kicking someone when they can't defend
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Salon.com, muzzled by a federally mandated
``quiet period'' while it plans its public stock offering, is under
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Byron, whose piece for the New York Observer was
reprinted in Sunday's San Francisco Examiner, praised Salon for its
fine writing and reportage but slammed the online magazine's
pending initial public offering as a dubious investment.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Byron routinely turns his acerbic tongue toward
Internet IPOs. But the barb that must really sting came from
Michael Kinsley, editor of Microsoft's media foray Slate, Salon's
direct competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley deftly lifted passages from Salon's filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission and compared them with public
statements during the past few years from Salon's founder, Chairman
and Editor-in-Chief David Talbot.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot didn't fare well in the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley cited a Newsweek story published in September.
Newsweek's Steven Levy wrote: ``Talbot says that though revenues
are up ($6 million for this year), profits won't come until 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotcha. Kinsley points to the prospectus to show that Salon
couldn't possibly have brought in even $3 million in 1998, and that
instead of profitability in 1999, losses will continue ``for the
foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece _ posted as one of Kinsley's regular Read Me columns
at  &LR; www.slate.com &LR;  _ continues in that vein, pointing out
conflicting statements on the number of advertisers and of paid
subscribers, and on what Salon charges for ads.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley's caustic conclusion: ``The only logical explanation is
typographical errors in the prospectus.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon declined to comment on the Kinsley report. My efforts to
cajole technology editor and Vice President Scott Rosenberg into a
reaction were fruitless. ``We can't say anything about it,''
Rosenberg said. ``I cannot say a word.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the SEC frowns on public comments about pending
stock offerings
</P>
<P>
   So I can only guess what Salon thinks. And here's a guess: It's
Kinsley's revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Salon hasn't been kind to Kinsley over the years, most savagely
last July. That's when a Kinsley memo leaked out in which he
described how S.I. Newhouse offered him the editor's job at the New
Yorker and then withdrew the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Salon not only questioned Kinsley's account, calling his tale
``a weirdly convoluted and self-lacerating hoax,'' but it also
published a parody by Daniel Radosh of Kinsley's memo. The parody
referred to Kinsley's columns as ``stunned mumbling'' and indicated
that his memo killed any hope Kinsley ``still had left of ever
getting a job at a real magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted by telephone, Kinsley said he did not recall reading
Salon's skewering of him _ though he said, ``I'm sure I read it'' _
and that he wasn't writing out of bitterness. He also wasn't trying
to poke Salon just because of the SEC gag. ``When else would I do
it?'' he asked. ``I couldn't do it before the IPO'' was announced.
</P>
<P>
   If Salon's IPO reaches the financial stratosphere of other Net
stocks, should we look for a Slate IPO soon thereafter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not,'' Kinsley said. ``I like staying close to mom and
dad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SPEAKING OF REAL MAGAZINES: &LR;  In a news story last month on Salon's
IPO, I unfairly tweaked the Atlantic Monthly for not having ``a
significant online presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Shame on me. Just because it's 141 years old doesn't mean it
can't be a feisty Web zine.
</P>
<P>
   Wen Stephenson, editorial director for New Media for the
Atlantic Monthly, set me straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what Mr. Fost considers a `significant' online
presence, but perhaps he is not aware that the Atlantic's Web site,
Atlantic Unbound ( &LR; www.theatlantic.com &LR; ) _ which was launched in
October 1995 (one month before Salon and eight months before Slate)
_ has been nominated twice for the National Magazine Award for
General Excellence in New Media, has been named by both PC Magazine
and P.O.V. magazine as one of the Top 100 sites on the Web (one of
the few print-magazine sites to gain that distinction) and is
widely considered one of the Internet's premier literary and
political sites. Furthermore, 50 percent of the editorial content
of Atlantic Unbound is exclusive to the Web, making it a competitor
to online magazines such as Slate and Salon.''
</P>
<P>
   He's absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
