<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLA-STORM-ART-NYT &LR;      05-05 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-STORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMANS CREDIT LOCAL METEOROLOGISTS WITH KEEPING DEATH TOLL
DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OKLA-SEARCH, OKLA-POLICE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Tom Chase had been following the tornado for
about 90 minutes on television, watching the little map in the
bottom corner of the screen as it traced the twister's chewing path
across central Oklahoma to the edge of his middle-class
neighborhood a few miles south of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we had plenty of warning, plenty,'' said the 77-year-old
retired fighter pilot. ``We were able to follow the whole thing on
television. Finally, we could hear it outside. I walked out on the
front porch and there it was, black and twirling, all this debris
spinning up in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase and his wife, Mary, scurried down into the underground
shelter that her father had built in the 1960s to protect them from
nuclear bombs. Soon, they were joined by their next door neighbor,
the people across the street, 11 souls in all, huddled in a
10-by-10 foot room that, as the tornado passed almost directly
overhead, began to throb and pulse like a heart in palpitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one big crack and the house was gone above us,'' he
said. ``We heard it coming apart. Just crack, and it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   All up and down Chase's block in the Highland Park section of
Moore, which took some of the hardest wallops from Monday's
tornado, and in similarly hit areas across the southern and eastern
edges of Oklahoma City, almost everyone seemed to have been
watching the storm on television.
</P>
<P>
   Pansy Harjo, who lived on a house around the corner from the
Chases, said they broke into the movie she was watching on a
pay-cable channel. ``That's when I knew it was a serious
situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City on Wednesday, as more and more residents were
allowed to venture back into their neighborhoods to salvage what
they could from the surreal debris, it became jarringly clear to
everyone that many, many more people could easily have died in
Monday's killer storm. Instead, the death toll Wednesday held
steady from the day before _ 38 killed in central Oklahoma, five in
a community south of Wichita, Kan. _ and rescuers were beginning to
offer the tentative hope that there may actually, unbelievably, be
no more bodies left to find.
</P>
<P>
   And the reason for that seemed to be that here in the southern
Great Plains, where a tornado is not exactly rare, people have
learned since elementary school what they must do when one strikes,
and the lesson has been re-hammered into their heads with each new
storm.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Oklahoma apart, its residents say, is that over
decades, through the schools, public seminars and repeated
television and radio programs, the state has built a population
that understands hostile storms and knows what to do when
confronted with one.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, recent improvements in the technology of
tracking storms and broadcasting the information have made it
possible for these tornado-savvy people to follow a storm as easily
as they follow a football game, down to knowing street-by-street as
the twister approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were watching it on TV and they said, OK, the twister's now
passing Penn Avenue, which is a little ways away from here, so I
could go outside and look up and see it coming,'' said David
Lawrence, whose home, six houses south of the Chases, had suffered
relatively little damage. ``We knew it was time to get inside and
underneath a mattress, just like we've been told to do over and
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   As residents returned to their shattered neighborhoods
Wednesday, the streets filled with pickup trucks loaded with
salvaged goods. Officials said that it was still too early to put a
figure on the extent of the storm damage. One state official said
he expected it to top $1 billion. ``I don't know what the final
total will be, but it will be a big number,'' said Oklahoma City
Mayor Kirk Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials were able, however, to begin to put a firmer
figure on the number of buildings demolished, at least in the
Oklahoma City metropolitan area, where most of the damage occurred.
The mayor said that 609 homes, 16 businesses, 19 apartments and one
church were totally destroyed by Monday's storm in the metropolitan
area, while another 367 residences and nine businesses suffered at
least ``half-destruction,'' which he said meant the roof was gone
but the walls were still standing. Some lesser damage was suffered
by 878 homes, 24 apartments and six businesses.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Wednesday, there was a certain level of pride
in the way the city handled this, its latest emergency, numerous
residents and local officials said. Shelters in the hardest hit
areas had filled up with so much food by late afternoon that the
mayor of Moore pleaded with people to bring no more. Relief
drop-sites all over the city were brimming with canned goods and
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Many people credited the city's response to the 1995 terrorist
bombing of the Alfred Murrah Federal Building that left 168 dead
with instilling this self-image among many Oklahoma City residents
that theirs is a town that knows how to handle civic emergencies
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' said Gary England, a meteorologist for
KWTV-Channel 9, the city's CBS affiliate, who was credited by
dozens of storm survivors Wednesday with having steered them
through Monday's disaster. ``We take it on the chin but we don't
give in.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   England has been forecasting the weather in Oklahoma for more
than a quarter century and said that when he began, the only way he
would have been able to warn people about a twister was if it
``blew down your friend's house up the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, England said, researchers began to develop new Doppler
radar equipment that revolutionized the way weather systems can be
tracked and, in 1981, the first commercial system along those lines
went on line in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history has been of good advances in Oklahoma, but this
has come out of necessity,'' England said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, with improved computer models and new
generations of radar, it has become possible to institute the kind
of storm-tracking that was so crucial on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end result was that on Monday night, for the first time in
my 27 years, I was able to look at that storm, tell people exactly
where it was and where it was going and, when I could see it was at
least an F4 tornado, in terms of intensity, I could say to people
that they were going to have to be below ground level to survive,''
England said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that no matter what I said, somebody was going to
die,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds, perhaps thousands, who knew they could not get
underground, fled the threatened areas, many who had underground
areas went into them while the rest tried their luck under
mattresses and blankets in interior hallways, closets and
bathrooms. The result was hundreds of shattered buildings but less
than four dozen fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   William Brodie tried to ride out the storm with his wife, two
sons, dog, three cats and a pet iguana in an underground shelter
that he'd built in 1972 and was using for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie, a lightning protection consultant for the FAA, said he
believes his family owes their lives to England and other local
meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gary England said `Jiminy Cricket!' and something about
how humongous it was, I just shut everything off and ran for the
shelter,'' Brodie said.
</P>
<P>
   When they came up from the shelter, iguana and all, the house
above them was gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
