<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR, ATTORNEY GENERAL ANNOUNCE BOXING REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki and the New York attorney general,
Eliot L. Spitzer, went Wednesday to Madison Square Garden, the
scene of the controversial March 13 heavyweight unification bout
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis, to announce a set of
reforms to better screen and select boxing judges and to place
greater controls on promoters and sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Their announcement coincided with the news that the proposed
Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act, which aims to reform the business
side of the sport, had been approved Wednesday by the U.S. Senate's
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee, and will come to a
vote of the full Senate perhaps as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the reforms that Pataki and Spitzer, who heads the
National Attorneys General Boxing Task Force, unveiled Wednesday
are included in the Ali Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfield-Lewis fight ended in a draw, although many people
who watched the fight believe that Lewis should have won. The
decision prompted a criminal investigation by the Manhattan
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms involving judges, which will be implemented and
enforced by the New York State Athletic Commission, call for full
financial disclosure by boxing judges, including consenting to a
credit check, revealing any pending litigation, like bankruptcy
proceedings, and any financial relationships with those involved in
a boxing match, like the promoter, the boxers, the managers and the
broadcast outlets.
</P>
<P>
   It was revealed after the Holyfield-Lewis bout that Eugenia
Williams, the only judge to score the Lewis-Holyfield bout for
Holyfield, had filed for bankruptcy two months before the match.
She was not required to disclose that information to anyone with
the athletic commission.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective judges would also have to pass a written exam before
they received a license to judge fights.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reforms calls for promoters to file their contracts
with boxers with the commission. Each contract must be for no
longer than three years, with an option for only two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctioning bodies will have to file copies of their
constitutions and ratings criteria with the commission, and they
cannot exclude any boxer who is not associated with their
organization from their ratings. Also, the sanctioning
organizations have to disclose to the commission the fees they
charge the boxers, and the payments, fees and services received
from promoters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pataki and Spitzer have recommended that the
Association of Boxing Commissioners adopt requirements that the
referee keep a scorecard to be submitted in case of a draw; adopt
round-by-round consensus scoring, which throws out the score of a
judge who disagrees with the other two judges, and institute an
independent boxing poll voted on by writers and broadcasters to
better rank boxers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
