<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-ATLANTA06-CO     05-05 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-ATLANTA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agencies looking for ways to ease Kosovars' plight
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although the first refugees from Kosovo aren't due
here until next week, local relief agencies are already feverishly
working to line up housing, furniture and volunteers to help them
resettle.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early refugees do not have family members in the
United States and have few belongings, relief officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of 400 arrived yesterday at Fort Dix, N.J. About
the same number are to arrive today, according to Peter Herbert,
regional director of the International Rescue Committee.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of 20,000 Kosovo Albanians who will be brought to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come in with refugee status, which means they can
remain here permanently. However, there is emphasis on letting them
know they can return if they choose. It's up to them,'' Herbert
said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Refugee Act of 1980 established refugee resettlement
programs in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia refugee coordinator Barbara Burnham said refugees are
eligible to receive cash and medical assistance and social services
under a federally funded Refugee Resettlement Program. Social
services are provided through local offices of the Department of
Family &AMP; Children Services, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Voluntary agencies contract with the U.S. Department of State to
help refugees through the first 90 days of their resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, more than 15,000 refugees have settled
in Georgia. Most have come from Vietnam (6,473) and Bosnia (3,677),
according to state figures.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, six agencies are helping to find homes for the
Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   They are: Christian Council of Metropolitan Atlanta, Jewish
Family and Career Services, International Rescue Committee,
Lutheran Ministries of Georgia, Catholic Social Services and World
Relief Refugee Services.
</P>
<P>
   These agencies work with area churches and volunteers to find
homes and support for the new residents.
</P>
<P>
   World Relief spokesman Brian Burt said his agency has already
gotten offers of help from about 20 volunteers and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Morgan Wallace of Peace Presbyterian Church in
Lawrenceville said his church will sponsor a family, working
through World Relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already started collecting household items and furniture,
beddings, linen _ all things it would take to begin a new life,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The church also provides transportation and other necessities
and has English-language instruction for the refugees, said
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee Partners, a Christian commune in Comer, Ga., will take
25 individuals in cooperation with International Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, located on a 260-acre farm in Madison County,
operates a refugee orientation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main things we do is give them a peaceful place to
come to while they adjust to different culture. And, to be friends
and help them learn the English language,'' Jubilee staff member
Carolyn Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said many refugees feel a sense of frustration and
loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sadness of having left their families and
difficulty learning a new language,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially important that these refugees have a period of
quiet before trying to find work and begin their new lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be working with people just weeks out of the
war zone. They'll need weeks to collect themselves before they can
get out on their own,'' Herbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
