<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CASCADES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NORTH CASCADES CREST' CAPTURES THE VISUAL POETRY OF `AMERICA'S
ALPS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fierce and fiercely beautiful terrain of Washington's North
Cascades has inspired poets, but curiously resisted accurate
depiction in photography and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting into the core of the range is so difficult that the
telephoto lens is often used to simulate views available to those
who use their legs. Mount Shuksan is carefully framed in tarns a
few feet from the Mount Baker Highway. Mount Baker is made to grow
out of the roofs of Skagit Valley farmhouses.
</P>
<P>
   In James Martin, however, the mountains have found an author
with music in his soul and a photographer steeped in swirling
clouds and distinctive North Cascades light. He is also a climber
who gets to places where he does not need to play telephoto tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Cascades Crest: Notes and Images from America's Alps,''
is a celebration of the wildest spots in the range, mile-high walls
in the Northern Pickets and the infrequently visited swath of
icefields between the North Cascades Highway and the remote Park
Creek Pass. Non-climbers can enjoy a few of these places, such as
Trapper Peak and Sourdough Mountain, accessible by
</P>
<P>
   steep trails out of the Skagit.
</P>
<P>
   As a young hiker, Martin ran into poet Gary Snyder in the Sierra
Nevadas who told Martin of his summers as a fire lookout atop
Sourdough. He writes movingly of days when poets manned lookouts
high above the Skagit. A funny interval is his account of Allen
Ginsburg running into a fisherman on the trail and telling him:
``We are forest beatniks.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing episode is that of Jack Kerouac, who spent a
summer of solitude atop Desolation Peak east of Ross Lake,
entranced by the black towers of Hozomeen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years of life on the road had ground him down,'' writes
Martin. ``Drugs, booze, false friends, hostile cops, and other
tortures left him exhausted and despairing despite his huge
appetite for life. Desolation Peak cleared his perception. He had
the time to wrestle his demons to a draw, at least temporarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid his outstanding photographs, Martin has time to muse. He is
fascinated that peaks bear such names as Terror, Fury, Triumph,
Despair, Inspiration and Forbidden. He traces the path of a young
Seattle teenager named Fred Beckey, who made his initial first
ascent in 1939 (Mount Despair) and a year later took major summits
of the Pickets by storm. It was the kickoff of a 60-year career of
scaling walls from the Bugaboos of British Columbia to the
Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
   Using his camera, Martin shows off the Cascades at sunset, with
sunlight turning clouds into ``a tapestry of reds, yellows and
oranges.'' In words, he details less uplifting Cascade experiences
_ retreating from the Ptarmigan Traverse in a downpour, sweating
through brush of Downey Creek, and trying to find a route across
brushy, rain-slick hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of places, he does let the telephoto run wild.
``Dome Peak dominates the skyline from Sahale Peak,'' reads one
caption. It doesn't. Dome is quite some distance from Sahale, and
appears as but one of numerous summits visible in this finest of
all views down the spine of the range.
</P>
<P>
   Other shots legitimately take the breath away, such as the
northeast buttress of Mount Slesse, just over the border in British
Columbia. Slesse is a Salish word meaning ``fang.'' Never was a
mountain better named.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line conservation groups have a curious attitude toward the
North Cascades. When public support was needed for preservation,
the Sierra Club and the Seattle-based Mountaineers group published
picture and guidebooks to encourage attention. After the creation
of parks and wilderness areas, they have seemed intent on limiting
access.
</P>
<P>
   Martin parrots the party line: Not enough land is protected. A
proliferation of backpackers threatens to spoil everything. ``We
foul the water and spook the wildlife,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast! Thanks to hikers, the North Cascades are the most
protected mountains of the ``lower 48'' states. The area Martin is
writing about contains a national park, three national recreation
areas, and four wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ignores the real tale of degradation, though he doubtless
witnessed it when hiking to remote Mount Redoubt via Depot Creek, a
valley that crosses the U.S.-Canadian border near Chilliwack Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The British Columbia Forest Service allowed Depot Creek to be
logged almost to the border. Similar vast clearcuts reach nearly to
timberline, and right up to the boundary, in several areas that are
protected on the U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians love to preach at international environmental
conferences. In the North Cascades, however, it is the Yanks who
walked their talk. And, for the most part, so has James Martin in
this splendid celebration of a unique and dramatic corner of
America.
</P>
<P>
   North Cascades Crest: Notes and Images From America's Alps
</P>
<P>
   By James Martin (Sasquatch Books, 128 pages, $19.95)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
