<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' bats break down Cards 12-3
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves spent Wednesday afternoon making Tuesday's
loss to the St. Louis Cardinals a distant memory. An estimated
1,250 feet worth.
</P>
<P>
   That's how far three home runs traveled off the bats of Bret
Boone, Ryan Klesko and Brian Jordan to help run the Cardinals out
of town with a 12-3 pounding by the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The only bench clearing Wednesday by the Braves came by virtue
of an nine-run lead, as they bullied with their bats, beating Cards
pitchers for 16 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko ended a 15-game homerless drought with a two-run home
run, Boone hit a home run and a double and drove in three runs, and
Brian Jordan came alive from his 1-for-10 slide against his former
team with a two-run home run in the sixth inning. Andruw Jones
chipped in by going 3-for-5 with a double, a triple, two runs
scored and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while we get kicked around, but we stay
positive,'' said Klesko, one of five Braves with two or more RBIs a
day after the Cardinals won 9-1. ``We owed them one back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Bottenfield was second in the National League with a 1.53
ERA before the Braves got to him Wednesday for 10 hits, five for
extra bases, and five earned runs. Bottenfield had given up five
runs in his first five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth and fifth runs came with two outs on Klesko's home
run in the third, which put the Braves up for good. It was his
second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to drive in some runs,'' Klesko said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had taken a 3-2 lead on a bases-loaded single by Mark
McGwire and an error in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the grand slam he got Tuesday, but he got two runs on
his single and the third on Andruw Jones' error on McGwire's hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had an answer this time, and a quick one. Two home
runs in the next half-inning _ Boone's game-tying and Klesko's
go-ahead _ gave John Smoltz his lead back at 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz didn't budge after that, setting down the next 11 men he
faced. In seven innings, he allowed five hits and three runs, two
earned, and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say, `Enough is enough,' at some point,'' said
Smoltz, who is 5-0 and hitting .375 after going 2-for-2 with a
double and a sacrifice on Wednesday. ``After that, I just beared
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who have won 10 of their past 12 and finished the
homestand at 7-2, are 6-0 with Smoltz on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be his worst game of the year,'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ``But if it is, we'll take that for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
