<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES BILL TO RESTRICT DEBT-FORGIVENESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Americans filing a record 1.4 million personal
bankruptcies in the last year, the House of Representatives
Wednesday night overwhelmingly approved sweeping legislation
proposed by the nation's largest banks, but opposed by consumer and
civil rights groups, that would make it harder for many people to
erase their debts.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 313-108 to impose new income requirements on
those in bankruptcy who wish to get a fresh start by making use of
the debt-forgiveness provisions of the law. The bill generally says
that anyone with the ability to make at least $6,000 in payments
over five years would not be able to have their debts forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   It provides an exception, allowing some debt to be forgiven, for
people who make less than the median income in their region.
</P>
<P>
   With similar legislation moving quickly through the Senate, the
White House announced Wednesday that President Clinton's advisers
had recommended that he veto the measure. A similar veto threat
last year helped kill bankruptcy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the House floor reflected the recurring question
of whether it is the banks or their customers who are responsible
for the proliferation of bankruptcy filings. As household debt has
risen sharply, the number of personal bankruptcy filings has risen
by 400 percent since 1980, growing by 300,000 in the last year
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But even some conservative Republicans complained that the
legislation was too harsh and would give bankruptcy judges little
authority to offer assistance and protection to those in financial
straits.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking ranks with most of his fellow Republicans, Rep. Henry
Hyde of Illinois, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee,
pleaded to change the legislation so that it would give judges
discretion in deciding the reasonable living expenses for debtors
in bankruptcy. The bill relies on a rigid formula based on expense
allowances of the Internal Revenue Service. The formula takes no
account of a number of significant expenses, like health care and
assistance to elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For goodness sakes, let us give some flexibility to the
debtor,'' said Hyde, clearly frustrated with his colleagues. ``I'm
as capitalist as anybody and I'm as conservative as anybody. But it
doesn't seem to me that giving some flexibility to someone in
bankruptcy is a renunciation of one's conservative standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me also pay my respects to the creditor lobby,'' he added
sarcastically. ``They are awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader, rose to
criticize the amendment written by Hyde and the ranking Democrat on
the Judiciary Committee, John Conyers Jr. of Michigan, it was
soundly defeated by a vote of 238 to 184. Armey urged the members
to impose ``legislative discipline'' by giving judges no leeway in
interpreting the bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde-Conyers amendment received the support of only 26
Republicans, a clear signal of Hyde's diminishing authority in the
aftermath of his handling of the impeachment of President Clinton.
(Hyde ultimately voted for final passage of the legislation.)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans supporting the legislation said it would impose
sanctions for the failure of consumers to assume personal
responsibility for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we're able to recoup some debt from high-income
people, the less burden we will put on everyone else,'' said Rep.
George Gekas, Pa., who sponsored the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats portrayed the legislation as a sop to the banks and
credit card companies and spoke of Dickensian hardships it would
create, particularly for single parents and children. Under the
legislation, credit card companies would be able to receive
repayment of debt at the same rate as debts like child support.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the record number of personal bankruptcies was as
much a result of the easy extension of credit. Last year, for
instance, credit card companies sent out some four billion
unsolicited letters offering consumers new credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``A more balanced bill would require responsible behavior not
only of debtors, but of credit card companies as well that have
done so much to drive consumers into bankruptcy,'' said Rep. Bill
Delahunt, D-Mass. ``This bill, in effect, would turn a taxpayer
funded system, the bankruptcy court, into a new collection
instrument for credit card companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation gives many benefits to the credit card
companies. It permits them to challenge bankruptcy filings. It
restricts class-action lawsuits that in the past have been brought
accusing banks of harsh repayment agreements. And it gives the
companies an equal priority with claimants of child support.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its opposition to the legislation, the
administration said it unfairly tilted against consumers,
particularly the less affluent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the bill's provisions are unfair to middle- and
low-income debtors,'' the administration said in a statement issued
about the legislation. ``At the same time, the bill fails to close
loopholes in current law that protect the wealthiest debtors.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, both the House and Senate adopted competing
legislation overhauling the bankruptcy system. After those bills
were reconciled in conference, the Senate failed to adopt the
legislation in the face of a presidential veto and it died in the
final days of the congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Senate Judiciary Committee approved a similar
measure by a vote of 14-4. Senate leaders have said they expect to
introduce it on the floor as early as this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
