<SLUG> BC-OKLA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS AND POLICE OFFICERS LOST HOMES, BUT KEPT ANSWERING
TORNADO CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OKLA-STORM, OKLA-SEARCH) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Assistant Fire Chief John Hansen was on his
first call after the tornadoes hit on Monday night, helping
hundreds of dazed and injured students out of their ruined high
school, when his eyes turned homeward.
</P>
<P>
   His two-story townhouse was on the other side of a small creek
to the east of the school, Westmoore High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked over and the trees were gone,'' Hansen recalled
Wednesday. ``The area was pretty well devastated. I knew then it
was a good possibility that my house was going to be one of those
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he stayed on the job.
</P>
<P>
   He learned later that his family, and his father who lived
around the corner, had safely evacuated their homes, but that the
tornado had blown away a wall of his townhouse, burst all the
windows, flooded the rooms and broke much of the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   He was among dozens of rescue workers here who lost their homes
but continued working to help others even though they could use a
little rescuing themselves. By his own count, 19 members of the
Oklahoma City Fire Department and 23 members of the Oklahoma City
Police Department returned from work to find their houses
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, a suburb just southwest of here, the rescue workers
fared little better. Police Sgt. Jeff Owens lived in the Highland
Park neighborhood, where whole blocks were razed. His house was
among them, and his patrol car was smashed to pieces. After working
with search and rescue teams for two days, he finally returned home
Wednesday to begin picking up the pieces of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a trooper,'' said Glenn Lewis, the mayor of Moore. ``He
was out here working to help others, in his sneakers, because his
shoes blew away.''
</P>
<P>
   The deputy fire chief of Moore, Jerry Dosher, lost his house as
well. His wife had to be dug out of the rubble. ``But he went right
back to work,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the rescue workers who lost their homes, Hansen among
them, ignited a brief controversy here when they were allowed back
to check their homes in neighborhoods where the authorities had
barred other homeowners from entering. The flap, which lived mainly
on talk radio, ended when the authorities began to let civilians
back into the neighborhoods in question.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who became a nationally recognizable figure four years
ago when he served as a department spokesman and a calming voice
after the federal building here was bombed, has spent most of the
last few days helping others. While he worried about his house, his
family, and his father, he said, he just kept taking calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firefighter in you and the parent or spouse are closely
connected,'' he said. ``The firefighter in you says, there are
people right here who need my help. And there are my colleagues,
who will go help my loved ones just as I'm helping someone else's
loved ones. That's the discipline you have. `'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
