<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT-ART-     05-05 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct slug)  
 AT&AMP;T's CABLE AND MICROSOFT DEALS STIR CONCERNS FROM REGULATORS AND(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having cleared the way to become the nation's biggest cable
television company by acquiring Mediaone Group Inc., AT&AMP;T Corp. on
Wednesday moved closer to a partnership with Microsoft Corp., the
software giant. The whirlwind of deals surrounding AT&AMP;T raised
concerns in Washington and in many high-technology quarters about
the prospects for competition in the fast-growing communications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   With its cable and Microsoft deals, AT&AMP;T, which two years ago
appeared as a crippled giant, is poised to once again stand astride
the communications world. For Microsoft, a strong relationship with
AT&AMP;T could become the company's most important vehicle for
expanding from the arena of desktop computers and into a new world
in which millions of consumers use seamless bundles of telephone,
television and high-speed Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   But for regulators and competitors in industries ranging from
computers to telephones to Internet access, a partnership between
AT&AMP;T and Microsoft, which is still being negotiated, could appear
as frightening as it is formidable. AT&AMP;T's expansion into cable
television so quickly and broadly _ starting with its deal last
year to acquire Tele-Communications Inc., then the No. 2 cable
company _ raised concerns on its own.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, AT&AMP;T opened a path to acquire Mediaone, the No. 4
cable company, for $58 billion. To set up that deal, AT&AMP;T agreed to
sell up to 2 million of its existing cable subscribers to Comcast
Corp., which had made an earlier agreement to acquire Mediaone. In
exchange, Comcast agreed to withdraw its Mediaone bid and to offer
local telephone service over its cable lines in league with AT&AMP;T,
the nation's biggest telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had earlier considered backing Comcast in a fight
against AT&AMP;T, but decided instead to try to form a partnership with
AT&AMP;T to use Microsoft's Windows operating system as part of AT&AMP;T's
cable-based communications system.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate antitrust subcommittee said Wednesday that it would
hold hearings into the competitive impact of AT&AMP;T's looming
acquisition of Mediaone. AT&AMP;T wants to use cable systems to offer
integrated bundles of telephone, television and high-speed Internet
service to millions of consumers. The subcommittee's leadership
said that AT&AMP;T's expansion into the cable business could speed the
advent of local telephone competition, but added that AT&AMP;T's
dealmaking might slow competition in video services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal will likely increase AT&AMP;T's ability to provide
competitive local phone service to residential customers, which we
certainly support,'' Sen. Michael DeWine, R-Ohio, the
subcommittee's chairman, and Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., the ranking
minority member, said in a statement. ``But the jury is still out
on how it will affect the cable/video market and we need to closely
examine all of the competitive aspects of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts decried AT&AMP;T's flurry of deals as good for all of
the companies involved, and the market supported that notion.
AT&AMP;T's shares rose, $5.375 on Wednesday, to $56.9375, while
Comcast's shares gained $9.1875, to $73.3125. Microsoft's shares
rose $1.0625, to $79.125. Mediaone's shares fell by 75 cents, to
$76.875, perhaps on disappointment that an extended bidding war for
the company appears highly unlikely. What clearly emerges from the
whirlwind of billion-dollar dealing is a sense that AT&AMP;T is putting
the pieces together to achieve a level of importance in the
communications landscape unmatched by any company since the old
American Telephone and Telegraph broke up under government pressure
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the resurgent AT&AMP;T could become a major force in
promoting competition. That is because AT&AMP;T, with its cable lines
into millions of homes, has now become the biggest threat to the
Baby Bells' functional monopoly in offering local phone service to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   None of the other long-distance giants has announced a
full-fledged plan to offer local phone service to residential
consumers, but AT&AMP;T has made offering local service in competition
with the Bells a cornerstone of its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But because AT&AMP;T is moving so fast to gain links to U.S. homes,
and because of its legacy as the nation's telephone monopoly, any
strategic relationship it forges with Microsoft is bound to raise
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is putting together a cable monopoly that is beyond the
wildest dreams of John Malone,'' said Gregory C. Simon, co-director
of Open Net Coalition, a group that includes many of AT&AMP;T's
competitors _ including America Online and Mindspring in Internet
service and MCI Worldcom in long distance _ and a former domestic
policy adviser to Vice President Al Gore. ``And now that they have
cornered the network, they are putting the network under lock and
key by putting Microsoft technology inside the set-top box.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft dominates the market for personal computer software.
But its main objective in dealing with AT&AMP;T was to obtain assured
access for its software and Internet commerce businesses _ and
preferred access, if possible _ to the fast-growing high-speed data
network that AT&AMP;T is assembling.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal being negotiated between AT&AMP;T and
Microsoft, Microsoft will invest about $5 billion in AT&AMP;T, perhaps
in exchange for some sort of preferred stock in AT&AMP;T. AT&AMP;T would
also agree to use Microsoft's software in its integrated packages
of voice, video and data service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is adamant that Microsoft will not get an exclusive
arrangement to supply its Windows CE software on the set-top boxes
of AT&AMP;T's expanded network. But Microsoft is negotiating hard to
get AT&AMP;T to agree to allow its Windows CE software to be rolled out
in at least one large cable market run by AT&AMP;T, as an early proving
ground for Microsoft's set-top box technology, according to people
close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, a $5 billion investment is a fairly conservative
hedge against the uncertain future represented by so-called
broadband networks, in which households are continuously connected
to high-speed data lines.
</P>
<P>
   These broadband networks _ whether built by cable companies,
regional phone companies or wireless operators _ are expected to
stream video, audio and text into people's homes, everything from
movies-on-demand to e-mail. And users will tap into this rich flow
of information and entertainment using various equipment, from
Internet-enabled televisions to handheld devices. It is seen as a
world of diverse information appliances, and all of them will need
software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wants to compete in that market against traditional
makers of cable television equipment, including General Instrument
Corp. and Scientific-Atlanta Inc. Before being acquired by AT&AMP;T,
TCI had agreed to use Java software from Sun Microsystems Inc. in
its advanced set-top boxes. Executives close to the negotiations
said that agreement would not be affected by AT&AMP;T's looming deal
with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   To bring the United States to this broadband future, the cable
industry, including AT&AMP;T, is locked in a battle against the Baby
Bells, GTE and the rest of the local phone industry. As that
inter-industry fight intensifies, and as AT&AMP;T becomes a unifying
force in the cable business, some of the rivalries that had
traditionally divided cable operators may soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Mediaone, AT&AMP;T will also get a 25 percent stake in
some of Time Warner's cable systems, its HBO cable network and its
Warner Brothers movie studio.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which has bickered incessantly with Mediaone on a
number of issues, sat on the sidelines as Comcast and AT&AMP;T jockeyed
for Mediaone, rooting simply for one of the deals to occur. Even
though AT&AMP;T's victory creates a bigger rival for its cable systems,
Time Warner benefits by eliminating Mediaone's influence over its
cable and movie units.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased with the outcome and pleased with the role Brian
Roberts played in bringing the companies together with a solution
that benefits the cable industry,'' Gerald Levin, Time Warner's
chairman, said in a prepared statement, referring to Comcast's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner is likely to try to create accords with AT&AMP;T on a
number of fronts, according to media executives. It hopes to find a
way to buy control back of HBO and Warner Brothers. In return, it
will likely look for ways for Road Runner, the high-speed Internet
service in which it is a shareholder, to cooperate with At Home, a
comparable service in which AT&AMP;T is the leading shareholder. The
services could be merged out right, or they could be linked more
closely using compatible technology. As part of this, Time Warner
is likely to complete its planed venture to offer local telephone
service through its cable systems in cooperation with AT&AMP;T. The
deal, announced in February, was being delayed by Mediaone,
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the cable industry rallies around AT&AMP;T and At Home,
the biggest player in the Internet market today _ America Online _
is notably excluded from the party.
</P>
<P>
   For now, America Online plans to offer high speed services using
a technology that uses telephone lines rather than cable wires. It
already has agreements with Bell Atlantic and SBC communications
and is courting the other local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is also eager to have access to cable systems as
well and considered backing Comcast in an effort to outbid AT&AMP;T for
Mediaone, but ultimately decided the deal was an expensive way to
get into a business that is growing much slower than its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we are a pure Internet Company, said
Robert Pittman, America Online's president. ``We used to be in the
data transport business and we got out of it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
