<HEADLINE>
APACHE HELICOPTER MAY HAVE HIT POWER LINE OR TREE, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ The Apache helicopter crash that killed two
American pilots early on today in rugged mountains about 45 miles
from here may have been caused by a rotor clipping a power line or
a tree, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash killed Chief Warrant Officer, Third Class, David A.
Gibbs, 38, of Ohio and Chief Warrant Officer, Second Class, Kevin
L. Reichert, 28, of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter, heavy with fuel and weapons, crashed while
carrying out a mock attack and exploded on impact just after 1:30
a.m. on Wednesday, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Garrie Dornan, an army spokesman here, said the
helicopter was flying under ``total blackout conditions.'' The
Apaches fly at night with no lights on to avoid being shot down by
shoulder-fired missiles or low-altitude anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter exploded on impact, he said, sending a fireball
into the night sky that was spotted by fellow Apache pilots flying
nearby. Both crew members appeared to have been killed instantly,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter was carrying live weapons, even though it was not
on a combat mission, because of threats from terrorists or even
Yugoslav forces across the border in Kosovo, an Army official said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the second in nine days. Last week, another Apache
helicopter went down during a nighttime training mission, but its
crew escaped with only cuts and bruises.A team of investigators
from Fort Rucker, Ala., sent to investigate the first Apache crash,
will stay to investigate the second.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots killed in the crash were members of C Troop, 6th
Squadron, 6th Cavalry Regiment, part of the Army's 11th Aviation
Regiment, based in Illesheim, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO officials summoned the attack helicopters as an
answer to the failure of heavy high-altitude bombing to stop the
Serbian push against ethnic Albanians, it has been a mission
plagued by logistical problems and lengthy delays.
</P>
<P>
   American aviators piloting the Apaches face a nightmarish array
of natural and man-made obstacles as they fly at night, at high
speed and low altitude through northern Albania into Kosovo,
according to military and civilian helicopter pilots here. The
two-person crews, they said, are trying to navigate a maze of
ravines of ridges with poorly marked maps that do not clearly list
all of the manmade obstacles, such as power lines, a helicopter can
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches could still prove to be a powerful weapon, but for
now critics are citing them as an example of a lack of planning by
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan vowed that the training mission accidents would not delay
the long-awaited launch of combat missions. He and NATO officials
cautioned that the flights were inherently dangerous and that more
casualties are likely.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Walter Jertz, a NATO spokesman, said on Wednesday in
Brussels, This is not Desert Storm,'' referring to the desert
terrain of the Gulf War. ``We are talking about a different
terrain. We are talking about a different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apache, a helicopter originally designed to attack thousands
of Warsaw Pact tanks advancing across the plains of Northern
Europe, performed brilliantly in the Gulf war, wiping out hundreds
of Iraqi tanks and vehicles, according to Pentagon officials. But
the effort to deploy them in mountainous Balkan terrain against
dug-in opponents may show their shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks and two crashes after the Apaches arrived, they have
yet to fly a combat mission.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, other helicopter pilots said, may be a blessing for
Apache crews. Knowledge of the jagged terrain in northern Albania,
particularly for pilots flying at night, is crucial. The area is an
aeronautical minefield, they said, where 3,000-foot mountains
abruptly rise from valley floors and power lines haphazardly dot
the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Carrier, a Canadian pilot who has been flying in Albania
for four years, said that like much else in Albania, Europe's
poorest country, power lines were built in a haphazard fashion and
are poorly marked. While in other countries power line towers are
usually same height and placed roughly 1,000 feet apart, in
northern Albania the towers vary in height and can be as far as
1,500 to 2,000 yards apart.
</P>
<P>
   A European military pilot who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that NATO maps show the power lines, but not in
great detail. He said the towers do not have orange markers placed
on top of power line towers in Western Europe and many of them are
rusted.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache is equipped with a ``pilot night sensor'' which
allows it to ``navigate and attack'' at night, according to
military officials. But how well the Apaches, which must fly low to
avoid enemy radar, can maneuver at night is clearly being tested in
the mountains here.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan called the mood among the U.S. soldiers here ``mournful
but resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a hazardous and risky business, flying at night with
heavy loads and full ordinance,'' he said. ``We're flying in
difficult terrain. We're flying under difficult conditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
