<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-COMMISSIONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. COMMISSIONER DENOUNCES SERB EFFORT TO EXPEL REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said
Wednesday that Kosovo was being ``brutally and methodically''
emptied by an ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign and that the 700,000
refugees from Kosovo would return home only if Serbian forces
withdrew and an ``armed international force'' assured their safety.
</P>
<P>
   In her first formal statement on the crisis to the 15-member
Security Council since NATO air strikes began, and in an interview
later Wednesday, the commissioner, Sadako Okata, attributed the
refugee crisis not to NATO's air strikes, but to what she called
``the systematic and intolerable violence'' being waged by Serb
forces against the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of NATO bombing may have been a factor in the flight of
20,000 Muslims from part of Yugoslavia into Bosnia, she said. But
most of the Kosovo Albanians interviewed by her agency in camps in
Albania, Macedonia, and Montenegro said they had either been
expelled from their homes or terrorized into fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Mrs. Ogata refused to call the campaign
``genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ogata's agency provided specific estimates of the growth of
the refugee population since NATO began its air strikes. Before
March 23, when her agency ``reluctantly'' left Kosovo, she said,
the agency was helping 400,000 displaced people inside Kosovo and
Montenegro, and 89,500 refugees outside of Kosovo. As of Wednesday,
Mrs. Okata said, the number of refugees outside Kosovo stood at
700,000 _ including 404,000 in Albania, 211,000 Montenegro, and
62,000 displaced people in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' plight, she continued, is ``increasingly
desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has proposed a
``humanitarian'' mission to Kosovo to begin exploring, among other
things, whether rape is being used systematically by the Serbs as a
weapon of war. But Belgrade still has not responded to Annan's
request, diplomats said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After having publicly objected to such a mission on Tuesday, a
spokesman for Sergey Lavrov, the Russian representative to the
United Nations, said that Moscow did not oppose the mission,
provided it assessed not only the refugee crisis but also the
damage to Yugoslavia's infrastructure caused by the NATO bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
