<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SENIOR06-COX     05-05 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Flash' remembers life with less cash
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Through three wins as a rookie on the Senior PGA Tour,
Bruce Fleisher's bank account has reached a different level. The
same for his answering machine, which after a victory in the
season-opening event at Key Biscayne, Fla., was stuffed with 463
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to remember,'' said Fleisher, a Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., resident, ``these are the people you've touched for
30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher's perspective remains unchanged. No matter how many
Ritz-Carltons might enter Fleisher's life, when a $2 million season
actually is possible, he will not forget the Red Roof Inns and
Monday qualifiers of the PGA Tour. After Fleisher won his first two
events on the Senior Tour in February, establishing a record that
not even Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer or Lee Trevino could match,
Fleisher fought off any evidence of ego inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hell of a note,'' he said then, ``me replacing some
of the greatest golfers in the world. They can make that my
epitaph.''
</P>
<P>
   When they paired Fleisher, 50, at the PGA Seniors Championship
with Palmer and Trevino, the man they call ``Flash'' said, ``Who
cares if Bruce Fleisher wins? These guys are legends. I'm not a
legend.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, quite a story. As the Nationwide Championship
unfolds Friday at the Golf Club of Georgia, Fleisher, who arrived
through qualifying school, already has to modify his rookie goals.
One was to make the top 31 and retain fully exempt status for 2000.
The other was to move up on the career money list, and with
$842,220, he's already up to 69th.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much more Fleisher could be doing. Had he not gotten
sick after the record start, he might have won five times by now.
David Duval has nothing on Fleisher's statistical domination.
Playing just eight events, he leads in scoring average (69.29),
putting (1.744 per green), birdies (4.04 per round), sand saves
percentage (70.4) and all-around ranking, 50 points ahead of
second-place Vicente Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce and I were talking (at Charlotte) about playing the last
two rounds together at tour school,'' Allen Doyle said. ``It
wouldn't have surprised me that the two of us would be playing in
the last group of this event, but walking off the first tee winning
close to half the events that have been played and being 1-2 on the
money list, that's a little more than we might have expected to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher's trademark now is a pair of wrap-around sunglasses.
When he won the U.S. Amateur as a 19-year-old, he wore tattersall
pants with frayed cuffs. His nickname then was ``Teen Angel.'' He
made 280 cuts on the PGA Tour, but only won once, at the 1991 New
England Classic at age 42, and accurately describes himself as ``a
journeyman, a grinder.'' Even today with the rest of the Senior
Tour chasing him, Fleisher admits to his faults, even if they
haven't been noticeable lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to screw up,'' he said. ``I'm going to choke and
gag.''
</P>
<P>
   He marvels at what television exposure has done to his
recognition factor. Last week at the Bruno's Memorial Classic in
Birmingham, Ala., he was eating breakfast in a country eatery when
a lady said, ``Oh, yeah, I saw you on television. You're the one
who wears stockings.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to last month's snow-stormed Tradition in
Scottsdale, Ariz., where Fleisher borrowed a page from Joe Namath's
old playbook and wore a pair of panty hose from his wife, Wendy, to
keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Life's contrasts? In 1980, Wendy almost died while giving birth
to their only child, Jessica. Wanting to stay closer to her after
the crisis, Bruce became a club pro in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to the PGA Tour in his 40s, Fleisher had to
grind his way through tour school to keep his card. When he earned
a Senior Tour card last December, Fleisher felt like he had won a
major.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either make that school or go find yourself a job,'' he
said. ``At 50 years old, you don't want to be playing Nike Tour
events. There was a lot of pressure there that I wouldn't wish on
my worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
