</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scottish refs stand their ground
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is not a good time to be a Scottish referee _ on
either side of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The referee who was hit in the head with a pound coin and later
had bricks thrown through his windows after Rangers clinched the
Scottish Premier League title is unfazed about calling the May 29
rematch with Celtic in the Scottish Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Dallas ejected three players and soon after being struck
with the projectile awarded a penalty kick to Rangers. That
prompted four Celtic hooligans to rush onto the Celtic Park pitch
and assault him. A steward also was injured and 113 people were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to ruin my day that day,'' Dallas told the
British Press Association, in reference to the Scottish Cup final
assignment. ``You can't be hounded out because of a mindless thug
who wants to have a pop at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer officials are defending a Scottish referee
participating in a league exchange program who whipped out cards at
a record pace. Stuard Dougal handed out an MLS record 11 yellow and
three red cards in Sunday's 3-2 victory by Chicago against D.C.
United. He broke his mark on cautions from the week before, when he
booked 10 players in San Jose's shootout victory against Los
Angeles. In his three MLS matches, Dougal issued 26 yellows and
three reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need to go 4,000 miles to get a referee that
poor,'' said D.C. United president and general manager Kevin Payne,
enraged when United's Brian Kamler was issued a red card for a
minor elbowing incident. Two of his teammates also got tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the fine I get will pay for (Dougal's) ticket home,''
Payne said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MLS officials denied that international referees were thumbing
their noses at the quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not the Bundesliga; we are not Serie A,'' said U.S.
Soccer Federation referee supervisor Esse Baharmast. ``But the
people coming here do have respect for the level of play.''
</P>
<P>
   In Glasgow, a TV-dictated 6 p.m. Sunday start gave fans of the
normally acrimonious Rangers and Celtic all day to imbibe. But most
of the arrests came during post-match rowdiness in a part of town
known for its pub crawls. SFA officials plan to tighten security
before the Scottish Cup grudge match.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, by the way, was fined $15,000, the second-highest fine in
MLS history. That kind of cash should just about get Dougal on the
Concorde, and none too soon, as far as Payne is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA finalists stumble in
</P>
<P>
   Olympique Marseille appears to have risen from the humiliation
of a match-fixing scandal disclosed the day after winning the 1993
European Cup. Parma is aiming for only its second European trophy.
But neither team is in the best of moods heading into Wednesday's
UEFA Cup finals in Moscow (2:30 p.m., Fox Sports World Espanol).
</P>
<P>
   Marseille gave up two goals in the final seven minutes to Paris
Saint-Germain in a 2-1 loss Tuesday that puts it a point behind
Girondins Bordeaux in the French first-division title race. And
despite a recent $60 million spending spree, Parma is left to vie
for only the continent's second-best club championship and probably
will miss the Champions' League next year.
</P>
<P>
   Marseille, 0-2-2 in its past four French league outings, will be
without strikers Fabrizio Ravanelli and Christophe Dugarry. Both
are suspended because of a raucous post-match brawl after its
semifinal victory against Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Parma should be in better spirits after beating Fiorentina in
the Coppa Italia finals on Wednesday. The teams tied 3-3 on
aggregate, but Paolo Vanoli's header in the 71st minute gave Parma
the edge on away goals.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: 'Hot Chocolate' served
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ``El Superclasico'' duel pitting Buenos Aires rivals
Boca Juniors and River Plate (4 p.m., Fox Sports World Espanol) has
major Clausura season implications on the line. Host Boca, which
plays at the formidable home ground called La Bombonera (``The
Chocolate Box''), leads by 26 points, while River is tied with San
Lorenzo for second with 21 apiece. River must find a way to shut
down Boca striker Martin Palermo, who has nine goals in his last 11
matches. England: Arsenal widens lead
</P>
<P>
   If Arsenal does win its second Premier League title in a row, it
might have Liverpool to thank. As the Gunners were putting the
finishing touches on a 3-1 victory against Tottenham Hotspur on
Wednesday, Liverpool's Paul Ince scored a dramatic 88th minute
equalizer against his old club for a 2-2 draw with Manchester
United. And Chelsea's 1-0 victory against Leeds has the top three
spots still up for grabs. Arsenal has 75 points to 72 for United,
while Chelsea is at 71.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
