<SLUG> BC-NET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Justice Resurrects Antitrust Probe of Network Solutions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Federal antitrust officials have reopened a 1997 probe of Network
Solutions Inc., the U.S. government-sanctioned company in charge of
registering the most popular Web addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the Justice Department objects to NSI's insistence
on controlling a database of more than 4 million registrations it
has compiled since 1993, when it won the exclusive contract to
assign top-level domain names from the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Privately, NSI officials are perplexed by the action. They
question why the Justice Department is reviving a nearly 2-year-old
probe at a time when other companies now are authorized to register
addresses with top-level Web suffixes such as .com and .org.
</P>
<P>
   But evidently, the Justice Department thinks that NSI is
clinging to control by not sharing key information in the database
with its new competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are reviewing whether NSI's claim of exclusive
rights to the database violates antitrust law, according to those
familiar with the probe.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's antitrust division is ``looking at the
possibility of anticompetitive practices in the Internet address
registration industry,'' a department spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've revived communications with the Department of Justice
and their request for additional information about NSI's business
practices,'' NSI spokesman Christopher Clough said. He added that
NSI is cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Justice Department suspended its investigation of
possible anticompetitive practices by the Herndon, Va., company
after the Clinton administration formed an international nonprofit,
Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers, to end NSI's
monopoly on the most popular online addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's move is designed to give consumers the
benefits of a competitive market for online addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The popular domain names are considered prime real estate
destinations for selling goods and conducting business on the
Internet, and they are a major reason behind NSI's market valuation
of $2.25 billion. NSI has registered three-fourths of the world's
5.5 million online addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, America Online, France Telecom and three other
high-tech companies were the first selected to compete against NSI
under a two-month test program. A second group of 29 companies led
by AT&AMP;T Corp. is expected to follow them and dole out popular Web
addresses as early as this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiations between NSI and the government apparently hit a
snag over how NSI will share information from its database with new
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   NSI will continue to maintain a master database of addresses.
The company will receive at least $9 for each domain name its
competitors register and will charge test registrars a one-time
licensing fee of $10,000 for software. Test registrars also will
pay a $5,000 annual accreditation fee to ICANN for administrative
costs.
</P>
<P>
   NSI charges consumers $70 for registering a Web address for the
first two years, and $35 for each additional 12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
