<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USATODAY-ADVERTISING-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA TODAY TO RUN ADS ON FRONT PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, Fla., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   USA Today, the newspaper whose bright colors and strong graphics
became a catalyst for the remaking of the industry's front pages a
decade ago, Wednesday announced plans to sell color advertising at
the bottom of its front page.
</P>
<P>
   The decision sets the flagship publication of Gannett Inc.'s
newspaper chain apart from virtually every major competitor; the
vast majority of publishers save their newspapers' display space
for news and features.
</P>
<P>
   ``With circulation as large as ours, to run a whole color page
without any advertising it is prohibitively expensive,'' Thomas
Curley, the president and publisher of the newspaper, said in an
interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He and the paper's editor, Karen Jurgensen, both noted that the
inch-high color strip that runs under the front-page news columns
has for years been used to promote the newspaper or its web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jurgensen pointed out that ``It's always been promotional
space from the beginning. So in that sense it's really not
different.'' She added, ``We have run ads on the other section
fronts for years now. There has been no ill effect. In doing this,
we are not taking anything away from readers.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Readers can tell the difference'' between
advertisements and news.
</P>
<P>
   European papers, including the staid Financial Times, the
British paper with growing American circulation, have long run
advertisements alongside page-one news. But newspapers in the
United States have shied away from this practice, although The New
York Times has long run a one-column, two- or three-line personal
classified advertisement on its front page.
</P>
<P>
   The official rate card of USA Today indicates that advertisers
can buy the one-inch color strip for a single day of the week, like
Mondays, for a year at a time. A year's worth of ads on Mondays,
Tuesday, Wednesdays or Thursdays would cost $1 million. Fridays
would cost $1.2 million, according to USA Today spokesman Steven H.
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said that AT&AMP;T, Northwest Airlines and the Marriott
Corp. had signed up for a year's worth of ads in that space. The
advertising will begin Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   P. Anthony Ridder, the chairman and chief executive of Knight
Ridder, said in an interview Wednesday that he knew of no plan for
front-page advertising material in any of Knight Ridder's 31
newspapers, which include big-city dailies like The San Jose
Mercury News, The Miami Herald and The Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I would encourage them to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I see USA Today as _ it is a five-day a week
newspaper and it is really different from our newspapers or the
other Gannett newspapers, it's a national newspaper. Their model is
different. Their advertising is more a magazine's kind of
advertising than the typical newspaper advertising.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Orville Schell, the dean of the graduate school of journalism at
the University of California at Berkeley, said he did not find the
innovation an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the ads The Times runs at the very bottom of the
front page, no large paper has done this, within my memory,'' he
said. ``What is frightening for me about such changes is not the
specific change, but the direction they suggest.'' He added, ``My
view is that big serious newspapers of record _ or even not of
record _ are something like schools, churches, national parks. They
should not be completely enslaved to the imperatives of larger and
larger profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Curley said Wednesday that some American newspapers printed
page-one advertisements nearly until the outbreak of World War II.
He said he first had the idea of using the color strip on USA
Today's front page for advertising in 1994, when the newspaper
turned the space over to the Atlanta civic committee for free
promotions of the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Curley said that the newspaper will add 1/8 of an inch of white
space between the color bar and the editorial material. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
