<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEY'S-CEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN QUESTROM TAKES THE TOP JOB AT BARNEY'S  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Calif., Ill.)   By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Barney's Inc., the luxury retailer known for basic
black everything, named a new chief executive Wednesday whose most
recent experience was running stores known more for affordable
sweaters and blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   But the appointment of Allen Questrom as chairman and chief
executive of Barney's is not entirely surprising. The retailer,
whose Barneys New York stores are known for their snobbish sales
staffs and endless racks of size 2 dresses, has been expanding its
appeal beyond model types and the yuppie chic.
</P>
<P>
   Questrom is a former chairman and president of Federated
Department Stores, which owns Bloomingdale's but is mostly known
for mid-priced stores like Stern's that cater to everyone from men
shopping for sportswear to teen-agers in search of cheap khakis.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that Barney's will toss out the Gucci bags
and start selling faux leather purses to appeal to the masses.
Barney's majority owners said that the company remained foremost a
luxury retailer despite its history of financial troubles and
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   While the company says it will continue to cater to the high-end
shopper, Questrom, who joined the company's board in January, is
expected to teach the sales help to smile and to tweak the
merchandising mix, changes his predecessor initiated to lure new
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen has a background that would fit that strategy,'' said
Jeffrey Stein, a retail analyst with McDonald Investments. ``His
background is in moderate department store chains.''
</P>
<P>
   Questrom, 59, replaces Thomas Shull, who became president and
chief executive in May 1998 and led the company through its
emergence from bankruptcy in January. In February, Barney's said
Shull was departing and that the chain needed ``a growth chief
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   In what the company says is evidence of his confidence in the
chain, Questrom has signed a contract through January 2003 that
pays him no salary but gives him an ownership stake in the company.
No specific terms were disclosed. ``He is betting on the future of
Barney's,'' said David A. Strumwasser, a principal of Whippoorwill
Associates Inc., one of the company's majority owners.
</P>
<P>
   Retail industry experts and analysts who know Questrom from his
Federated days said he was well regarded for his merchandising and
service focus but that at Barney's the challenge would be to use
those skills to attract a wider range of shoppers without turning
off the stores' core customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is not to dilute the appeal,'' said Kurt
Barnard, publisher of Barnard's Retail Trend Report. Questrom, he
said, must use his strengths as ``a merchandiser and marketer who
never takes his eye off the store, the customer or the investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Questrom was chairman and chief executive of Federated
Department Stores from 1990 until 1997. He later sued the company,
saying he was owed $47 million in additional compensation. During
his tenure at Federated, he brought the company out of bankruptcy
and led its acquisition of R.H. Macy &AMP; Co.. He also was president
and chief executive of Neiman Marcus from 1988 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Barney's said they would rely on his ``track
record in finance, operations and day-to-day management'' to move
the company forward. Since he joined the board, ``we have
increasingly turned to him for advice and counsel on issues ranging
from emerging designers to retail operations,'' said a joint
statement issued by Strumwasser and Douglas P. Teitelbaum, managing
partner of Bay Harbour Management, which along with Whippoorwill
Associates is the chain's majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor has made huge progress in turning around the
troubled merchant, having closed unprofitable shops, cut debt and
taken advantage of the company's credit-card list for marketing
purposes. Sales, as a result, improved, increasing 10 percent last
year. Sustaining even half that growth will be difficult unless
Questrom can swiftly intensify a focus on service and new
merchandising, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``he's got very strong credentials,'' said Jeffrey
Feiner, a retail analyst with Lehman Brothers, ``and I really view
it as a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Questrom, who declined comment through the company's owners,
said in the statement that his priority would be to ``unlock
Barney's full potential.'' The company operates seven Barneys New
York stores, including its landmark New York, Beverly Hills and
Chicago shops, and 13 off-price outlets. It employs 1,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
