A5936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-CAPSULES06-CO     05-05 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-CAPSULES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL playoff capsules
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO VS. BOSTON
</P>
<P>
   First round: Sabres swept Ottawa 4-0; Bruins defeated Carolina
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Buffalo won 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 1.88 _ Dominik Hasek's goals-against average the
past three playoff years.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: The Bruins won the last meeting between the teams in
overtime 2-1 after Buffalo had won four in a row. This figures to
be the lowest scoring series of the playoffs, as Hasek (.937 saves
percentage) and Boston's Byron Dafoe (.926) were two of the
dominant goalies down the stretch. The Bruins, who had 11 different
goal scorers in the Carolina series, have more depth and talent up
front than the Sabres and have been given a lift by 19-year-old
forward Joe Thornton. But Boston scored just seven goals in five
meetings with the Sabres (Hasek started four, Dwayne Roloson the
other). The Bruins were blessed with a home series when the Eastern
Conference's top three seeds _ New Jersey, Ottawa, Carolina _ were
eliminated, but home ice has meant little in the playoffs. The
Bruins haven't advanced past the second round since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Quoteworthy: ``A lot of teams have one superstar they're going
to rely on. Our star is our goaltender. He's the reason we win
hockey games.'' _ Buffalo's Michael Peca.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Buffalo in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH VS. TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   First round: Penguins defeated New Jersey 4-3; Maple Leafs
defeated Philadelphia 4-2
</P>
<P>
   Season series: They split four games, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 1 _ the number of Canadian teams remaining in
the playoffs after first-round losses by Ottawa and Edmonton.
Montreal, Calgary and Vancouver did not make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Penguins coach Kevin Constantine deserves some kudos
for keeping his players focused amid the franchise's financial
problems. The Pens rallied to eliminate the Devils and played four
games in the series without Jaromir Jagr. But Jagr was the
difference in the end, scoring two goals in Game 6 and setting up
two in Game 7. He needs to be the equalizer against the Leafs, who
have an edge in goaltending (Curtis Joseph over Tom Barrasso) and
defense and have more depth up front. Toronto was the league's
highest-scoring team during the regular season but managed just
seven goals in its four victories against Philadelphia. But Joseph
allowed only three goals in those wins. The Penguins aren't nearly
as physical as the Flyers, so the Leafs should have more room to
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Quoteworthy: ``I'm looking forward to the Toronto Maple Leafs
winning the Stanley Cup.'' _ Canadian actor/comedian Mike Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Toronto in six games.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT VS. COLORADO
</P>
<P>
   First round: Red Wings swept Anaheim 4-0; Avalanche defeated San
Jose 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: They split four games, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 58-25 _ Detroit's playoff record since a
first-round elimination in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: This series might be the best of the entire
playoffs. The only problem is that possibly the league's two best
teams are meeting in the second round. Both improved their depth
before the trading deadline: Colorado obtained Theo Fleury and Dale
Hunter; Detroit added four players, including Chris Chelios and
Wendel Clark. And the teams are evenly matched, as evidenced by the
season series. But give the Avs the edge in goal, with Patrick Roy
over Chris Osgood, who has a sore knee. Detroit's attack, dormant
much of the season, overpowered Anaheim for 17 goals in four games,
including five by Steve Yzerman and three by Brendan Shanahan. Avs'
Joe Sakic (three goals, nine assists, 12 points) and Fleury
(3-8-11) are the playoffs' two leading scorers. Colorado will be
minus top checker Stephane Yelle (knee).
</P>
<P>
   Quoteworthy: ``We can't give up two games at home like we did
against San Jose. If we do that against Detroit, we're in big
trouble.'' _ Colorado's Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Colorado in seven.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS VS. DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   First round: Blues defeated Phoenix 4-3; Stars swept Edmonton
4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Dallas won 2-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: 0 _ Brett Hull's playoff goal total, with one
assist, in the Edmonton series.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: If goalie Grant Fuhr plays as he did in Game 7
against Phoenix (35 saves in an overtime shutout), the Blues have a
shot to pull an upset. Games between these teams have been tight
the past two years, with St. Louis holding a 5-4-1 edge. The Blues
also have excellent speed. What they don't have is anything close
to Dallas' depth of scoring talent. Hull tipped that scale when he
left St. Louis and signed with Dallas as a free agent before the
season, setting up a nice subplot for this series. St. Louis twice
needed overtime to defeat the undermanned Coyotes. The Blues will
be facing a rested Dallas team and goalie Ed Belfour, who has
allowed two goals or fewer in 19 of his past 21 playoff starts. The
Blues' best chance to win in Dallas could be Game 1, with Stars
defenseman/captain Derian Hatcher still sitting out a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Quoteworthy: ``We have to jump hard and now and often and quick.
We have to take advantage of what we've gained in winning four
straight.'' _ Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock on the Stars, who have
been off for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Dallas in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
