A5938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-ADVANCE0     05-05 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-ADVANCE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wings, Avalanche in early showdown
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not unusual for the raised elbows and sticks to
increase during an NHL playoff series, but the progression of
60-minute boil-overs by Detroit and Colorado in recent years has
created some uncommon occurrences.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman yelled obscenities out of a bus
window at Colorado's Claude Lemieux and his family in the arena
parking lot after Lemieux had sucker-punched one of his players.
</P>
<P>
   _ Then-Avs coach Marc Crawford said about his counterpart,
``Scotty is a great thinker, but he thinks so much that the plate
in his head causes interference in our headsets during the game.''
Bowman's follow-up slam: ``I knew your father before you did, and
he wouldn't be very proud of you right now.''
</P>
<P>
   _ And how about this: a six-on-six brawl, with goalies Patrick
Roy and Chris Osgood as the main event at center ice.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit-Colorado series is the centerpiece of the playoffs
again, only this time it arrives early. Unlike their meetings in
the conference finals in 1996 and 1997, the owners of the last
three Cups meet in the second round, beginning Friday in Denver.
Other matchups find Dallas and Brett Hull going against his old
team, St. Louis; bankrupt Pittsburgh, coming off an upset of No. 1
Eastern Conference seed New Jersey, meeting Toronto; and Boston
facing Buffalo and goalie Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   But all take a back seat to the Wings and Avs, whose rivalry was
born in Colorado's Cup season of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the underdogs and they were the favorites, trying to
win their first Cup in 40 or 50 years,'' Colorado general manager
Pierre Lacroix said. ``We've both changed a few players but
basically we expect to see the same thing _ great hockey, great
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps also a collision or two. In '96, Lemieux punched
Detroit's Slava Kozlov from behind in Game 3 after Kozlov had
opened a 20-stitch cut on Adam Foote's forehead. In Game 6, Lemieux
earned a two-game suspension for a blindside check that broke Kris
Draper's jaw. The Wings screamed after the game, but Lemieux mused:
``Is that why they lost the game? Is anybody going to ask them why
they lost the game?''
</P>
<P>
   In '97, Colorado's Mike Keane, now with Dallas, called the Wings
``heartless'' and ``gutless'' and the feud between Bowman and
Crawford, now in Vancouver, escalated, with Crawford even scaling
the glass between the player benches to yell at Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Uwe Krupp left Detroit to sign with Colorado
as a free agent, although he missed most of the season with a back
injury. The teams split four meetings this year. There were no
fights but several stick penalties. Bowman and Bob Hartley,
Crawford's replacement, have been civil toward each other.
Colorado, which added Theo Fleury, and Detroit, which added four
players, including Chris Chelios, also drew the most attention
before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hatred's going to be a motivating factor for some,'' Red Wings
forward Brendan Shanahan said. ``You've got the two teams who
really improved themselves the most at the trading deadline. And it
excites some people that one of those teams is going to get knocked
out in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
