<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MAY 6
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-EVEREST-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 4,
about an attempt to climb Mount Everest in 1924 misstated the month
that Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay reached the summit. It was
May 1953, not June.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the age of Andrew Irvine, a
participant in the 1924 attempt. He was 22, not 28.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misspelled the surname of a film maker and
author who has climbed to the summit four times. He is David
Breashears, not Brashears.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS-NYT (moved on Monday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 3,
about troubled adolescents referred incorrectly to some research in
the field. Information about which children are likely to ``break''
in stark ways comes from a growing number of ``psychological
autopsy'' studies of youthful suicides and from less formal studies
of adolescents who have committed murders, not ``less from studies
of adolescents who have commited murders.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 4,
about the Coca-Cola Company's bottling network, misstated the year
in which Coca-Cola Enterprises was spun off. It was 1986, not 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
