r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-RECONSTRUCTIO     05-05 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-RECONSTRUCTION-2200(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH AND DESTRUCTION ROAR THROUGH OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY: noise was gone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he came out, the house was demolished and his two cars had
vanished. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Chris Malone was huddled with dozens of
others at the First Baptist Church of Moore. He had taken his
family to the church because it had an underground area that he
thought would provide a haven. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the twisters were approaching, Malone heard people banging on
the outside doors. He let them in, and they huddled together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the storm bore down on the area, they tried to reassure their
children by singing, ``Jesus Loves The Little Children.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When they stepped outside a few minutes later, they saw that the
tornadoes had demolished hundreds of homes next to the church and
had driven 2-by-4s into the cross on the side of their building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the storm passed, people began to arrive at the church,
looking for shelter and help in finding their relatives. The church
would soon become a central meeting station for victims, relief
agencies, government officials and the news media. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell Monday night, the storms moved to the north,
causing more destruction in Stroud, Okla., and later in Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard and other officials quickly moved into the
damaged areas near Oklahoma City, fearful of looting or gas leaks
that could lead to fires and explosions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Malone, a business manager at the church, began working on ways
to accommodate the relief effort. Miller returned to her home and
found that the twisters had missed it entirely. She put on her work
uniform and made it on time for her 3 a.m. shift at the local
convenience store. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and his family went to a Marriott Hotel, which
provided free lodging for a few days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Lindsey went to her sister's house, which was
undamaged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People also started gathering at the First Baptist Church of Del
City, near another hard-hit area, about 4 a.m. Some tried to sleep
on baby mattresses that were moved from nursery cribs, but most sat
in stunned silence, neither crying nor showing much emotion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By dawn Tuesday, the National Guard had cordoned off most of the
badly hit areas. Residents were required to show identification,
and some were allowed to sift through their homes _ or what
remained of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-lane roads soon were clogged with traffic backups that
stretched for miles. There was gridlock during the morning commute,
as drivers slowed to take in the carnage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Lindsey reached her home Tuesday morning, her husband
immediately found the all-terrain vehicle that had been swirling in
the air; he put it in his pickup bed. She located her washing
machine, broken up and thrown far from the house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She reached into the machine's tub and pulled out a load of
clothes, figuring she would need them later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What struck many victims and observers was the capricious nature
of the tornadoes. On Lindsey's street, next to a mobile home that
was stripped of its aluminum, was a blooming honeysuckle bush,
apparently untouched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearby a tree was pulled completely out of the ground, with its
roots pointing to the sky. Next to it was an untouched mimosa tree,
lucky enough to be just beyond the tornadoes' path. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By early Tuesday, people from the community and local companies
were delivering loads of diapers, clothing, food, even cash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist church in Moore became a command center for the Red
Cross, federal relief agencies and dozens of news media outlets. A
slew of insurance company adjusters began to arrive and survey the
damage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late morning, anxiety stirred again when the skies darkened
and heavy rains fell. But by early afternoon Tuesday, the sun was
shining brightly, and the search-and-rescue efforts were gaining
momentum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A woman was found alive near Lindsey's neighborhood, pulled from
debris near her house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at the Midwest Regional Medical Center in Midwest City,
medical workers and victims began to show the strain of the
tragedy. One nurse, who was busy tending to the injured, didn't
realize for hours that a relative was among the dead brought to the
hospital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One man walked into the hospital gift shop at 2 p.m., saying
that his wife was in surgery and that he needed chewing gum. When
he realized that he didn't have his wallet, he lost his composure,
a hospital employee said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my god, I have nothing,'' the man reportedly said. ``I
don't even have a comb for my hair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He walked out before the clerk could give him the gum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Wednesday that at least 100 people remain
unaccounted for, and they asked the public to provide information
on the whereabouts of missing individuals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds remain homeless, and many have few belongings. Some
children rang around area shelters Wednesday in their stocking
feet; their mothers wore house slippers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, who saved his family and parakeet by rushing them
into the storm cellar Monday night, was walking through Moore with
a shopping cart Wednesday. He went to the makeshift store at the
Baptist church and picked up bags of cereal, canned goods, dog food
and a few stuffed animals for his children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' he said, adding that he
was looking for a place to keep his family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many volunteers continue to make food, hand out donations and
provide encouragement to twister victims. But after two days of
often keeping their emotions in check, people are losing some
control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diana Beal, a Moore resident who was helping at the Baptist
church, broke into tears Wednesday afternoon. She said she was
overcome by losing her home and by the outpouring of community
support. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe the number of people who are coming to help,''
she said, sobbing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Star-Telegram writers Jennifer Autrey, Deanna Boyd, Yvette
Craig, Jack Douglas Jr., Bill Hanna, Miles Moffeit and Rebeca
Rodriguez contributed to this report from Oklahoma. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
