<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-RECONSTRUCTIO     05-05 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-RECONSTRUCTION-2200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH AND DESTRUCTION ROAR THROUGH OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ On Monday afternoon, before the tornadoes hit,
Johnnie Lindsey was enjoying her 31st birthday. It is a milestone
she will never forget. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was at work, and she was casually cleaning the
shelves in their mobile home and playing with their four young
children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She had no reason to notice that dangerous storms were building
a few hours away in southwestern Oklahoma, where cool air from the
Pacific Ocean was colliding with a warm front from the Gulf of
Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey also had no reason to suspect that, within a few hours,
she would be at ground zero, clinging to her children and her
life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 4:15 p.m., the National Weather Service issued its first
thunderstorm warning for Oklahoma's Comanche County. Half an hour
later, it broadcast the first tornado warning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, like many involved in the disaster, learned about the
twisters from television. She was preparing a birthday dinner when
she heard the news bulletins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 6:19, a twister touched down north of nearby Chickasha, and
Lindsey went outside to have a look. She was quickly gripped by
fear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it come from my front door,'' she would say later
about the huge tornado, which appeared to be at least a half-mile
wide as it barreled toward her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her pickup didn't work, so she never considered making a run for
it. She put her children in a closet and covered everyone with sofa
cushions, pillows and comforters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the monster tornado was upon them, and the roof
and walls were gone. Huddled with her screaming children, she
glanced from beneath the bedding and saw the family's miniature
all-terrain vehicle swirling in the air amid flying debris. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, the night was still and she heard her
husband's truck pulling up. He was yelling her name and screaming
for their children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got them with me,'' she yelled back, and they ran toward
each other. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The storm system that would eventually spawn more than 70
tornadoes and kill at least 40 people had just struck a deadly blow
at Bridge Creek, Okla. Eleven fatalities have been confirmed there,
and a community has been destroyed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But nature's mayhem was far from done. Within a few hours,
thousands of lives would be changed forever. And for many, the
fallout would not be clear for a couple of days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weather officials say that what appeared to be one huge tornado
was probably four or five twisters in a single mass. The tornadoes'
size and wind speed, estimated at more than 200 mph, were a deadly
combination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what made the storms exceptional, officials said, was how
long the tornadoes clung to the ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most twisters touch down for fewer than five minutes, but this
one kept rolling for more than an hour, cutting a path of
destruction for 60 miles, officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The storm system triggered 174 tornado warnings, caused dozens
of deaths and hundreds of injuries and destroyed thousands of
homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Lindsey, Anne Miller began noticing the tornadoes when the
twister touched down in Chickasha and the swirling storm became a
fixture on TV. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller lives in a trailer park in the northern part of Moore, a
suburb of Oklahoma City that would be among the hardest hit. As the
tornadoes continued to move northeast, directly toward her, she and
her husband jumped in their truck and tried to outrun them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they sped away, she stared at the storm through the rear
window and offered a running commentary on the action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my god,'' she said to her husband. ``It got another tree.
Another power pole. Another car.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Miller fled, Richard Hutchison held his ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tracking the tornadoes on TV, he stepped outside his Moore home
on 22nd Street at a few minutes after 7 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wall of darkness,'' he said about the approaching
storm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the twisters cut through power lines, ``the sky just lit up
like an explosion,'' he added. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison ran to his wife and two children, and rushed them to a
storm cellar in the middle of their frame home. He had time to grab
his dog and pet parakeet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For about a minute and a half, he said, the twisters howled and
debris pounded the cellar door. Then the noise was gone. &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
