<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-MIDWESTCITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``BABY J.R. WENT FLYING ... AND THE HOUSE DISAPPEARED''
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ The neighborhood wouldn't know how the
Yonnes baby died if his 3-year-old sister hadn't been able to tell
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandfather, John Richmond, said little Josephine Yonnes
riveted nurses and doctors at the hospital Monday night as she told
how she climbed into a bathtub with her mother, father, twin
brother and four-month-old baby brother as a tornado roared toward
their house on Will Rogers Road.
</P>
<P>
   ```The big storm came and the house came open. Baby J.R. went
flying and Momma went flying and the house disappeared,' ''
Richmond said Josephine told him.
</P>
<P>
   A baby was found dead in the adjacent yard. The medical
examiner's confirmation hadn't come in Wednesday, but Richmond said
he knows it will be his grandson, Jeffery ``J.R.'' Yonnes Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's mother, LaManda Kelly, 24, is in critical condition
at Presbyterian Hospital and hasn't been told about her baby's
fate. His father, Jeff Yonnes, remembers nothing of the storm. And
3-year-old twin Jeremy hasn't spoken, Richland said.
</P>
<P>
   So it was Josephine, through her grandfather, who helped the
Will Rogers Road residents piece together what happened to each of
them after their 5700 block suffered some of the worst damage from
Monday night's storms.
</P>
<P>
   Including the baby, all four confirmed fatalities in Midwest
City were found on their street. The bodies were so badly mangled
that for a while authorities mistakenly counted one woman's body as
two, said Lt. Gerald Beabout, Midwest City Police Department public
information officer. The victims' names hadn't been released late
Wednesday because next of kin hadn't been contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Will Rogers Road is bordered by busy Sooner Road to the west and
a small through-street, Center Drive, on the east. It is just south
of 15th Street, where dozens of businesses were obliterated. The
200-member Sooner Baptist Church on the northeast corner of the
block and the Peter Pan Small World day care across from it were
the only buildings left standing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the first day that most residents were able to
return, looking for mementos among the rubble and discussing the
week's events with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the one-story wood houses were rental properties and the
neighbors knew each other more by sight than by name. But they were
concerned about their neighbors. Rumors were rife. Many mistakenly
thought Kelly had been killed along with all the children in the
neighboring York house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yorks are OK?'' said Dewey Young, 54, who lives down the
street. ``No way. We thought they were all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Young drove his pickup 80 mph to a friend's storm cellar as the
tornado chased him and his wife, Leona, up Sooner Road. They
returned Wednesday to find only the four bathroom walls and a
kitchen counter with two unbruised bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The York family lived beside the church, where the children
loved to play even if they attended irregularly. Sooner Baptist
youth minister Deric Brock had been checking on the family. He was
able to tell neighbors yesterday that Tierra York, 8, was expected
to have permanent vision loss. Doctors had removed the two-by-four
embedded in the back of Justin York, 5, to leave no spinal damage.
Jacob York, 18 months, would also live.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said the Yorks' father, David Sean, 30, covered his
children as they lay in the bathtub. The next thing he remembers,
he was lying on concrete, the bathtub was gone, and the children
were scattered across fields of debris, Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor from across the street, Dave Dimick, 37, said he took
the York children to a hospital. Minutes later, Susan York came
home to find her family gone. Fearing the worst, she screamed their
names in despair, Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Dimick had escaped uninjured. He had watched television until
the tornado was at Interstate 240 and Sooner Road. Knowing his home
was just north of Interstate 40 and Sooner, Dimick grabbed a
Hershey's with almonds, a Walkman radio and a metal chair and
opened a manhole in front a neighbor's house.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed in, stood on the chair in the nine-foot-deep manhole
and held the lid until it blew away. Then he crouched in the chair
until the storm blew by.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, Evelyn Blanton, 82, rode the tornado like a
bucking bronco as it picked her up in her Ford LTD, spun her and
her puppies three times, then set the car down in a ditch. Blanton
was unscathed but her house was gone, said her niece, Gina Hulsey.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Hawkins bore the brunt of the storm outside. He had a
storm cellar but waited until he heard the tornado coming before
trying to take the padlock off. His wife had died in an accident in
the cellar last year, and his son, Tim Hawkins of suburban Dallas,
suspected that his father was reluctant to go in.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could open the door, Cecil was blown to the ground
between a tree and his house. He watched a 150-pound tank land
beside his head. His house blew away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the roof, then the walls, then the floor and then the
joists,'' said Hawkins, 74. ``I was the only thing that didn't
move.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
