<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Location is everything
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He had done a good job of hiding it until Tuesday
night, but Greg Maddux hasn't pitched like himself this season.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is 4-1, but he has given up a league-high 55 hits,
allowed opponents to hit .333 against him and watched his ERA take
off from 2.73 to 4.34 after he allowed eight runs to the Cardinals
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been locating well,'' Maddux said Wednesday morning.
Why? ``I don't know. I'm still looking. . . . I've always started
off slow with location. Sometimes I go out there and don't pitch
very well and the other team doesn't hit very well either. Last
night I thought they hit very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said it was all the two-strike hits that ate at him the
most. The home run to Mark McGwire? Not that bad a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody else hit that ball, the right fielder probably catches
it,'' Maddux said. ``I made some mistakes, but my good pitches
didn't get hit. Last night they took them or fouled them off, that
was a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said his movement on his pitches was finally where he
wanted it and that's what he chooses to focus on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the good out of the game and move on from there
instead of thinking about how bad it was,'' said Maddux, whose next
start is Sunday against Sterling Hitchcock and the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty blues
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones opened this season on a right-handed tear and has
struggled from the left side, his dominant side. A switch-hitter,
he came into Wednesday's game hitting .448 (13-for-29) from the
right and only .206 (14-for-68) from the left before showing some
left-handed signs of life, going 2-for-3 with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very inconsistent right now,'' Jones said. ``I've gotten
into some bad habits. I'm very disappointed with my contact through
the first month.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones stayed after the game on Tuesday night for extra batting
practice, using the time to concentrate on not pulling pitches.
None of his seven home runs have gone to the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get some muscle memory working, hoping one day
it'll carry over into the game,'' Jones said. ``I haven't been
hitting very many balls in the gap in left center, or right center.
I'm in front of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's grand slam on Tuesday night may have played
second-fiddle to a homer he hit in batting practice earlier in the
afternoon. He launched a 500-plus foot home run off the scoreboard
above the 755 Club, denting one of the panels.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
