A5947 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-NUKE-2TAKES-     05-05 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-NUKE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY LEAKS STILL POSSIBLE AT WEAPONS LABS, SCIENTISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scientists at the government's weapons laboratories
can still download nuclear secrets onto computer disks and walk out
without being checked, the directors of three of the labs told
Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   New security measures put into effect in response to evidence
that a scientist suspected of spying for China transferred huge
amounts of secret data from a classified computer system into an
unclassified one at Los Alamos National Laboratory will not prevent
simple file transfers by scientists with security clearances, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Their statements came in response to questioning from Senate
Energy Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, who waved a
computer disk and expressed shock that the lab officials have still
failed to address a security problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a monitor of individuals walking in and out that
would pick up if somebody had this in his pocket?'' Murkowski asked
the directors, as he held a disk in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``No there is not,'' conceded John Browne, director of Los
Alamos. ``And the problem is that any floppy disk like you're
carrying, you can't tell unless you read all the contents whether
it's classified or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski expressed outrage at the way the Los Alamos case has
been handled by lab officials, by the Energy Department and the
FBI. Lawmakers said they were particularly angered that
investigators did not examine the office computer of the scientist,
Wen Ho Lee, until March, nearly three years after he first became a
suspect in the theft of nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said Lee's computer was not examined earlier even though
a 1995 policy statement by Los Alamos notified employees that the
lab or federal government could audit or access office computers of
any employee without notice. Lee, along with other employees,
signed such a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI and Justice Department had decided that the policy
statement would not allow them to use evidence from a computer
search in court, Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials have previously stated that in 1997, they asked
the Justice Department to seek court authorization to monitor Lee's
computer, but Justice officials rejected the bureau's request.
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI did check his computer, it found that he had
transferred huge files containing millions of lines of computer
code from a classified system at Los Alamos into an unclassified
network. The codes that he moved contained the distillation of more
than a half century of American research on how to perfect nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Lee transferred files repeatedly from 1983 through 1995, and
there is evidence that someone accessed the files once they were in
the unclassified system, according to officials. There is no
evidence that the computer codes were handed over to China, but
officials say Lee jeopardized the security of virtually the entire
nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has not been charged with any crime. His lawyer has not
returned phone calls seeking comment. Top officials in China have
denied any involvement in stealing nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Floppy disk drives on computers on the unclassified system have
been disabled or sealed in recent weeks, but not on the classified
computers, officials said. Energy Department officials said they
are now working on ways to eliminate the use of floppy disks on the
classified network.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Energy Committee is one of several congressional
panels investigating how the spy case was handled, and some new
information was revealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was hired at Los Alamos in 1978, came under suspicion
in 1982, when he made a telephone call to a scientist from Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory in California, who had been fired as
a result of an investigation into evidence that a spy had passed
neutron bomb secrets to China. The FBI investigated Lee and gave
him a polygraph test in early 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Lee gave deceptive answers to seven questions, Sen. Pete
Dominici, R-N.M., said. The FBI gave Lee an opportunity to explain
his answers and retake the test, and he passed the second
polygraph. The FBI then determined that he had cleared the
polygraph.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also cooperated with the FBI in its case against the
Lawrence Livermore scientist, officials said Wednesday, by
telephoning the scientist again at the FBI's request.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI polygraph report was included in a counter-intelligence
case file on Lee that was lost by the Energy Department's
Albuquerque office for several years, officials said. The
Albuquerque office had to hire an outside contractor to reconstruct
the lost file in 1992. Lee did not become the prime suspect in an
FBI criminal investigation until 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
