<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEN-HUMMER-FENCING06-     05-05 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEN-HUMMER-FENCING06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cast those romantic notions aside; fencing is hard work.
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stance is slightly balletic, front foot pointed
straight forward, back foot turned at a right angle. I assume it
without requiring an orthopedic device, a fine start.
</P>
<P>
   The dress is straight from the Hannibal Lecter collection _ a
white coat that is just two straps away from being a straitjacket
and a bird cage that fits snugly over the head. I might borrow the
outfit the next time the dental hygienist tries to get at me.
</P>
<P>
   The language is like something stolen from a good wine list. En
garde. Epee. Maitre d'Armes. The list of French fighting words
can't be very long, but they're all here.
</P>
<P>
   The instructor, well, he has just raised his blunted foil to me
and said something along the lines of, ``You have sullied my sister
and for this you must die!'' Gene Gettler was only kidding. At
least he seemed to be. If he wasn't, I think I might well have
sullied my shorts.
</P>
<P>
   This is my introduction to fencing. It's not just for European
fops anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Many are called by the lure of swordplay, even those whose swash
may have buckled some with the passing of time. It's there from the
moment you duel a playmate with birch branches. It's reinforced
every time Luke Skywalker fires up his light saber. Gettler, the
master of arms at the Atlanta Fencers' Club, realizes this and is
not afraid to use it. Whatever works. Even if competitive fencing
is to big-screen dueling what a Roger Clemens fastball is to
anything thrown Kevin Costner's way in any of his baseball movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something there that appeals to people, the
whole romantic notion of dueling for honor,'' Gettler said. He will
notice little spikes in membership whenever the occasional Zorro
movie is released or a Summer Olympics comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I am the missing Musketeer. Call me Pathos, the sorry
one.
</P>
<P>
   I met with Gettler one afternoon in his small, sparse clubhouse,
located in the heart of downtown. This would be a beginner's
run-through, and believe me, I was frequently run through.
</P>
<P>
   Fencing is not merely a matter of taking up a weapon and
flailing away like you have to dispatch the entire king's guard in
three minutes. That technique stuff, which always gets in the way
of a good time, is thick in this sport. There is a proper way to
move, a proper way to turn your body in order to offer less of a
target, a proper way to hold the foil, and a whole menu of various
attacks and defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The movements are not automatic or natural. Like trying to pat
your belly and carve out another man's liver at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't tell anyone that fencing is easy to learn,''
Gettler said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you are not inclined to take this to a highly
competitive level or go on any quests in the foreseeable future,
fencing has its upside. ``It gives some people a chance to do some
exercise if you're not inclined to run or go to the gym. It's a
physical workout. Fencing is very aerobic,'' Gettler said. And I
have the sweat stains to prove it. Spend a few minutes thrusting
and parrying and scampering around as if your life depended upon
it, you'll froth up nicely. Even if you never swing from a single
chandelier or slide down one ship's rigging.
</P>
<P>
   Having been shown all the little things that I do wrong, I
returned the next evening during regular club hours for a little
mock battle. Here, I was introduced to young Will Tauxe, a lanky
teen who has been about a year fencing. He was only too happy to
cross swords.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon of choice was the foil, the light weapon often handed
the beginner. It also is the most specific of fencing's arsenal,
with points awarded only for strikes to the torso. Unfortunately,
some of us have more torso than others.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to come clean: I fought like a scared rodent. Upon
further review, I believe I was more concerned with fending off
Tauxe's attacks than going on the offensive myself. I had a fairly
substantial height advantage, and that was good enough to score a
couple of accidental points. But Tauxe had mastered this one move
in which he flicked me on the shoulder with his foil, scoring a
series of nonfatal, annoying, mosquito-bite-like points.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue also became an immediate factor. I don't remember Errol
Flynn calling too many 20-second timeouts, but I needed one in the
midst of our little first-to-five-points match. By the close of my
5-2 loss, I was drenched.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to beat Tauxe, there was only one other possible course
of action. I dueled his 14-year-old little sister, Genevieve. Now,
the height thing would be almost insurmountable. I claimed a 5-4
victory, although she would have won anything that went a minute
longer or would have required me to take one more breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're good,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're tall,'' she answered. My first fencing compliment,
backhanded as it might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes five to seven years to become a national-caliber
fencer,'' Gettler said. ``That's a minimum of three (training
sessions) a week, two hours each. Maybe some fitness training,
along with a running program, some weight training and something to
work on your explosiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too late for any of that. This Musketeer retires, glad for
the experience and grateful for a 1-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
