<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-COMCAST-NYT &LR;      05-05 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-COMCAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGING A FRIENDLY DEAL: HOW AT&AMP;T AND COMCAST CAME TO TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT) 
(bl) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Sunday afternoon, Comcast president Brian
Roberts was resting at his home near Philadelphia after an
exhausting week of negotiations. He had reason to be tired. After
making a costly $53 billion stock bid for MediaOne, the nation's
fourth largest cable operator, a month earlier, Comcast found
itself trumped by AT&AMP;T, which had muscled in with a $58 billion
stock and cash offer of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast sought help from Microsoft the previous week, hoping the
software giant would dig into its $22 billion cash coffer to aid
the company in its bid. But even as Microsoft chief financial
officer Gregory Maffei met that week with Comcast at the offices of
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell, Microsoft's law firm, the Comcast team knew
that Microsoft representatives were simultaneously meeting with
rival AT&AMP;T, indicating that Microsoft might only be using the talks
with Comcast as leverage in the AT&AMP;T negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Without support from Microsoft or America Online, another
potential ally, Comcast had little chance of winning. But AT&AMP;T
executives also knew it was wiser to strike a friendly deal with
the cable operator with which it hoped to do business with in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking set the stage for what was to be a conciliatory
call from an AT&AMP;T executive to Roberts that ultimately led to
Tuesday's settlement _ widely hailed as a savvy resolution for both
parties. AT&AMP;T, which already owns Tele-Communications Inc., the
nation's second largest cable company, gets MediaOne. But Comcast
too walks away with a prize: it acquires 2 million cable
subscribers outright and gets to manage franchises serving more
than 2 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Why was AT&AMP;T, eager to be the industry's goliath, willing to
give up control of more than 4 million subscribers? Company
executives did not talk publicly Wednesday, but one person involved
in the talks noted that it would behoove AT&AMP;T _ which is trying to
offer local telephone service through alliances with cable
companies _ not to alienate Comcast. ``Having Comcast, which
controls 6 million homes, or 10 percent of the cable industry, as
an avowed enemy for life was not smart,'' said the participant, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there was still the potential for Comcast to drum up
support from other quarters and escalate the bidding war. But the
recent settlement puts an end to the specter of another round of
bids.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to offer local telephone service on its wholly owned
Tele-Communications' cable lines and is working on a deal with Time
Warner. Adding Comcast's subscribers to that overarching plan would
be another coup. And indeed an agreement to offer Comcast
subscribers telephone service was part of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the role played by AT&AMP;T chairman Michael Armstrong,
an investment banker involved in the negotiations who requested
anonymity said: ``Mike was smart enough to rise above the occasion
and get the deal done in a way that everybody could go home with
dignity. In a fast changing industry, he managed to keep
relationships with Comcast that insured they would work together in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not always the case. Viacom Inc.'s chairman Sumner
Redstone and QVC's then-chairman Barry Diller battled for months in
1993 over Paramount Communications. Each side continued to raise
its price far beyond what then appeared economically feasible,
forcing the ultimate winner, Viacom, to pay far more than Redstone
had initially intended. Moreover, Redstone and Diller remained
bitter to one another for at least a year after the battle ended.
</P>
<P>
   And after British Telecom lost the battle for MCI to Worldcom,
British Telecom immediately entered into a relationship with AT&AMP;T
that some observers said was aimed at damaging MCI/Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   One reason AT&AMP;T and Comcast may have avoided friction is that
much of the negotiating was done directly between top level
corporate executives who are seasoned dealmakers in their own
right.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Roberts got a call from Leo Hindery, the president
and chief executive of AT&AMP;T Broadband and Internet Services, who
had been a chief dealmaker for the cable operator
Tele-Communications Inc. before it was acquired by AT&AMP;T last year.
``The question he raised was how to make it a `win-win' for both
sides,'' one person involved in the negotiations recalled. The pair
talked in earnest about a plan that had actually been kicking
around for awhile that would let Comcast buy or gain control of
more AT&AMP;T cable subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   That concept had been around for weeks and last Friday, as it
became clear that MediaOne was poised to accept the AT&AMP;T bid,
preliminary discussions began, according to two people involved in
the talks. Comcast and AT&AMP;T executives had been leery of talking
directly because AT&AMP;T's offer for MediaOne dictated that neither
could have discussions with any other potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   But by Friday night, according to one participant in the
negotiations, a decision had been made that because MediaOne had
already singed confidentiality agreements with America Online and
Microsoft, the standstill provision was no longer in effect, and
preliminary talks between AT&AMP;T and Comcast had started. (An AT&AMP;T
spokesperson denied that there were any settlement talks before
Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   In deals, politics count. And no one wants to be rebuffed. So
before Hindery actually picked up the phone to call Roberts,
representatives from AT&AMP;T's investment bank, Goldman Sachs, called
one of Comcast's investment banks, Lazard Freres. (Comcast is also
represented by Salomon Smith Barney.) Lazard, in turn, called
Roberts to say that Hindery would be phoning, said people close to
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And so the talks began. By 8 a.m. Monday both Hindery and
Roberts and their teams were at the New York offices of AT&AMP;T's law
firm, Wachtell Lipton Rosen &AMP; Katz, hammering out what was to
become the final settlement between the warring sides. Comcast
would get 2 million more subscribers for $9 billion, and management
over 2 million more cable homes, helping it accomplish its initial
goal of getting bigger. AT&AMP;T would acquire MediaOne, and the two
sides also agreed to a crucial goal of AT&AMP;T's: to offer telephone
service over Comcast's cable wires.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Comcast was finishing up the terms of its deal with
AT&AMP;T, reports that MCI Worldcom was interested in joining the
battle for MediaOne began making their way on Wall Street. The news
did little to sway the parties, but indeed quickened the pace of
the discussions, said one person.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T chief financial officer Daniel Somers, in particular, did
not take the MCI threat seriously but still wanted a quick end.
``Dan wanted to get the deal done, but they were testing'' Comcast,
said one person involved in the talks. ``Time was ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, once the agreement was signed, Comcast
executives and their advisers went to the Waldorf Astoria, drank
champagne and celebrated their victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
