<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-HOSPITAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS SEE THE PHYSICAL SUFFERING OF THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ They began pouring in late on Monday, wearing
expressions of shock and pain, as nurses and doctors scrambled to
help them survive the injuries inflicted by tornadoes that had
trampled their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were covered in mud _ and blood,'' said Dale Askins,
chief trauma physician for Hillcrest Health Center, where about 150
storm victims were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them were stunned and dazed by the suddenness of it
all,'' Askins said Wednesday from the hospital, one of several
where nearly 100 survivors remained under treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Medical personnel at Hillcrest, including one who arrived after
digging out of the ruins of his own home, saved most of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   But four people died in the Hillcrest emergency room, including
a 4-year-old girl whose body was crushed by the fierceness of the
storms.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Downs, lead emergency room nurse at the hospital, said
many patients were surprised that even after being warned and
taking shelter, they were still swept away.
</P>
<P>
   One patient, Downs said, repeatedly cried: ``I got sucked out of
my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Another victim was asked what her address was. ``Well, I don't
have one anymore,'' Downs quoted the woman as saying. ``Then she
started crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the lucky ones were Allen Dunn, 78, and his 77-year-old
wife Dorothy. Wednesday, they were recovering in adjacent hospital
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   His broken right arm in a sling, Allen Dunn recounted the events
of Monday night, which he said began simply enough with a TV
weather alert.
</P>
<P>
   After the warnings grew more serious, Dunn said, he and his wife
went to their bedroom and sat on stools between their bed and a
wall, their heads covered by heavy blankets.
</P>
<P>
   They waited.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he heard a roar. ``It sounded like a dozen freight
trains. It was loud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the glass in our bathroom blew in. About that time, it
kind of went dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said that when he awoke, he and his wife were on the floor
under debris, holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't see any walls. All we saw was sky,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he and his wife made it out of what was left of their
home of 10 years. They were immediately met by their frantic
grandson, who drove them to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his broken arm and his wife's cuts and bruises, Dunn
said, he and his wife were extremely lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were spared for some reason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't decided whether they will rebuild in ``Tornado
Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they have recovered, Dunn said: ``We'll go out and rent an
apartment and rent a car. And start from there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
