</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEIGHBORHOOD PARK DRAWS LITTLETON PILGRIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The television trucks and trailers streamed
out of town at the first report of tornadoes in Oklahoma. But even
without the encouragement of television coverage, people keep
coming in a steady stream to visit the vast impromptu memorial
created for the victims of the Columbine High School shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Lund was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Although she did not know anyone hurt or killed in the mayhem at
Columbine two weeks ago, she felt compelled to join the quiet
pilgrimage on Wednesday, her 4-year-old son, Daniel, in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so sad _ everywhere you turn, you think of the kids,''
Ms. Lund said after walking pensively among the flowers, the
placards and the teddy bears. ``Suburban America is so
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is nestled in Clement Park _ on Rebel Hill, so
called because of the nickname of Columbine High, which it
overlooks. Constantly replenished by new bouquets, the shrines have
withstood two blizzards and torrential downpours. This was the
wettest April in Denver since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, even as the visitors continued to arrive, park
administrators began removing mementos and uprooting 13 crosses _
one for each of the victims of the two young Columbine gunmen _ in
a campaign to reclaim Rebel Hill, which had begun turning into a
muddy mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people slipping and falling in the mud, and one lady
with heart problems had a medical emergency while trying to climb
the hill,'' Bob Easton, executive director of the local parks
agency, said as he watched more mourners walking in twos and threes
to a consolidated memorial site, on a nearby lawn within Clement
Park. ``We anticipate this will last all summer long.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers, hoping that all mourning at the park can gradually
be channeled into one tent by the start of summer, have begun to
thin the wave upon wave of offerings: Wilted flowers will be used
in compost, and fresh flowers will be made into bags of potpourri.
Initially the bags will be given to family members of the victims.
Later they will be sold to raise money for a permanent park
memorial to the 12 students and one teacher shot to death on April
20 by Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold; the two gunmen then killed
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers organized by the Colorado Historical Society have
started collecting and cataloguing truckloads of mementos at the
park: homemade art work, handwritten poems wrapped in plastic,
teddy bears, team shirts, votive candles and wind chimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody _ businessmen, schoolchildren, families _ people
from all walks of life have been moved to come here and leave
something,'' said Duncan McCollum, the Jefferson County Archivist,
who placed two of the offerings _ a pair of athletic shoes and a
pink terra cotta angel _ in a cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since this neighborhood park became a national focal point, it
has received visits from Vice President Al Gore, the duchess of
York and Martin Luther King III. President Clinton is expected to
see the park when he arrives here later this month.
</P>
<P>
   But it also a place where emotions, already raw in the wake of
the shooting, can spill over, as Greg Zanis, a carpenter from
Illinois, has discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Zanis, a rough-hewn man who runs a private charity,
Crosses for Losses, erected 15 handmade crosses on Rebel Hill. ``I
got calls about people spitting on the bad guys' crosses,'' he said
Wednesday, referring to the two inscribed with the names of Harris
and Klebold. ``A girl called me and said a person pushed her in the
mud because she left flowers at their crosses.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of the week, a father whose child was slain
simply removed the Harris and Klebold crosses. With anger growing,
Zanis tried to defuse matters by then removing the 13 others. In
response to public appeals, though, he erected 13 new ones
Wednesday, at a site approved by park officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid controversy, he said, ``I'm just not going to
put up crosses for murderers anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the park's southern border stands Columbine High, a vast
crime scene that police investigators expect to return to the
school district by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   School Superintendent Jane Hammond has estimated that it will
cost the district, the largest in the state, $50 million to repair
the school, including $8 million for victim assistance counseling
for staff and students.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear where the money will come from. The state
Legislature adjourned for the year Wednesday night without setting
aside extra money for the district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
