u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANICSIN-TEXTBOOKS     05-05 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICSIN-TEXTBOOKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic feats lifted from footnotes
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sure, you've heard of J. Robert
Oppenheimer, the man who ran Los Alamos National Laboratory and
told the government it should drop the first atomic bomb on
Hiroshima. But have you heard of Luis Alvarez?
</P>
<P>
   Neither have most Palm Beach County students. But Alvarez worked
with the Manhattan Project and, in 1945, sat in a plane 30,000 feet
above Japan and watched his work devastate that city. In 1968, he
won a Nobel Prize in physics for his discovery of numerous atomic
particles.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of many Hispanic names from Florida's textbooks was
noted last year by state legislators who required school districts
to teach the contributions Hispanics made to the United States.
Four years earlier, they ordered districts to teach about
African-American contributions and the Holocaust. In response, Palm
Beach County educators went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here technically because of the law, but that's not our
mission,'' said Lhisa Almashy, a resource teacher in Hispanic/Latin
American studies. ``It's so our children, as they grow up, can have
an identity. . . . It's not just to recognize the contributions,
but to celebrate and validate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when local middle-school science teachers get to
their lessons on atomic energy, they'll be encouraged to mention
both Alvarez and Oppenheimer. And when their social studies peers
teach lessons on American currency, they can mention its roots in
the Spanish peso. And right about this time next year, they can
talk knowledgeably about Cinco de Mayo (the anniversary of Mexico's
May 5, 1862, victory against French invaders).
</P>
<P>
   The new curriculum doesn't replace anything. Nor does it require
spending days on Hispanic lessons only, said Carlos Diaz, a Florida
Atlantic University professor who developed some of the lessons for
Palm Beach County. Instead, it allows the teacher to mention
Hispanic people at natural times, during regular lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic students make up about 18 percent of all students in
Palm Beach County, and that number is expected to grow. A
population study conducted by Florida International University and
commissioned by The Palm Beach Post found that by 2025, Hispanics
will have become the county's largest ethnic group, 44.9 percent of
the population. The number probably will be larger in the school
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not have a curriculum that includes Hispanic-Americans is
incomprehensible to me,'' Diaz said. ``Inclusion in the curriculum
implies legitimacy. It is an affirmation that you exist. . . . Some
people argue that this is tokenism. Let me suggest that telling the
truth, the whole truth, is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
