<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADILLAC-LINCOLN-NYT &LR;      05-05 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADILLAC-LINCOLN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A RECOUNT, LINCOLN PASSES CADILLAC AS NATION'S BEST-SELLING
LUXURY CAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Here in the Motor City, automakers take their annual
battles for sales titles pretty seriously. Perhaps the most
fiercely fought feud has been between Cadillac and Lincoln, as
Cadillac struggled to keep its 57-year winning streak as the
nation's best-selling luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cadillac acknowledged pulling out all the stops to
hold on to the title. After reporting almost unbelievable sales
results in December, Cadillac eked out a come-from-behind victory
by just 222 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the numbers were pulled from thin air. On Wednesday,
General Motors Corp. said that its Cadillac division sold 4,773
fewer cars in December than it had reported at the time,
acknowledging four months late that Lincoln was the nation's
best-selling luxury car for the first time since 1939. The December
sales results were ``overstated due to an improper reporting
process,'' GM said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Cadillac of overstatements.
</P>
<P>
   GM said it had found the truth after an internal audit, and that
it had taken disciplinary action. The company did not say what that
action was or how many people were involved. GM said the sales
overstatement had not affected the company's financial reporting,
and that revenue, income and production figures were correctly
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning in the marketplace obviously is very important to us,
but nothing is more important than our integrity,'' said Roy S.
Roberts, GM's vice president and group executive for North American
vehicle sales, service and marketing. ``General Motors will assure
the process for reporting dealer sales will be accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition for the auto sales titles is fierce because the
winners often widely advertise their victories. Jim Farmer, a GM
spokesman, said the company had not said in advertisements this
year that Cadillac was last year's best-selling luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   But after journalists had predicted that Lincoln was about to
dethrone Cadillac, GM early this year distributed a promotional
mailer, with a picture of President Harry S. Truman holding a mock
version of the The Chicago Daily Tribune with the headline,
``LINCOLN DEFEATS CADILLAC!'' Inside it said, ``History has a
strange way of repeating itself.'' (The reference, of course, was
to the that newspaper's erroneous headline _ ``Dewey Defeats
Truman'' _ in its early edition on the day after the 1948
Presidential election.)
</P>
<P>
   Back in November, it looked as if Cadillac was out of the sales
race. Lincoln, which had last beat Cadillac in 1939, had sold
nearly 7,000 more cars and trucks than GM's luxury division as of
December 1. So Cadillac slapped on rebates and other sales
incentives, mailed out promotions to current Cadillac owners
encouraging them to trade in their old models, gave discounts to
employees and retired employees, and gave sales people a bonus for
each new Cadillac they sold.
</P>
<P>
   The result, GM claimed at the time: Cadillac 187,343, Lincoln
187,121. Cadillac won by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Auto journalists immediately raised red flags. They were even
more skeptical when GM said that Cadillac sales plunged 38 percent
the next month. They assumed GM had counted sales that took place
in early January as December sales. GM's internal auditors then
began digging, according to Farmer, the GM spokesman, and the
problem turned out to be bigger than that. ``It is a combination of
an internal control breakdown and some overzealous people,'' said
Farmer, who refused to provide further details.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln said its dealers were disappointed not to be able to
claim the title but praised GM for its candor. ``Our dealers would
have loved to have had the opportunity'' to call Lincoln the luxury
sales leader, said spokesman Jim Trainor. ``They were really
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lincoln released a statement praising GM for
setting the record straight. ``This action by Cadillac exemplifies
the integrity we've always said is the basis for a luxury brand. It
is another example of what makes this rivalry so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the announcement shocked the auto industry. In Detroit,
it was as if the class president had been caught cheating on a
final exam. Auto industry observers said the embarrassing
disclosure showed how troubled the Cadillac division is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadillac has a tremendous number of problems today and this is
just a manifestation,'' said Keith Crain, publisher of Automotive
News, a leading trade journal. ``They are not the standard of the
world and they haven't been for a long time,'' he said, invoking
Cadillac's famous pre-war advertising slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's sales have been sliding for years, and until
Wednesday they seemed to continue their swoon: GM said Cadillac
sales were down 14.9 percent so far this year, to 41,503. That left
Cadillac behind Lincoln's 48,896. On Wednesday, GM restated
Cadillac sales for the last five months to account for the audit's
results, and voila, Cadillac sales for the year had climbed 6.4
percent, to 51,914, edging ahead of Lincoln once again.
</P>
<P>
   But Mercedes and Lexus have outsold them both, with sales of
56,716 and 56,678 respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
