A5968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIJUANA-SLAY-NYT &LR;      05-05 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIJUANA-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BUSINESSMAN KILLED IN TIJUANA CARJACKING  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (rk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Japanese businessman who, like thousands of
executives, commuted from the United States each day to work at a
factory on the Mexican side of the border, has been shot to death
in Tijuana in an attempted carjacking, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Jiro Sayama, 50 years old, was slain on Tuesday afternoon as he
scuffled with two assailants who forced him from his car in an
industrial section of Tijuana, which faces San Diego, said Marcia
Coronado, a spokeswoman for the Baja California state attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Two youths, Hugo Buenrostro Ramirez, 15, and Jorge Roman
Frausto, 21, have been arrested and charged with the murder, police
officials said Wednesday. The two young men were identified by
several eyewitnesses to the killing, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Organized crime including carjackings and kidnappings has surged
in recent years across Mexico. Only a handful of foreigners,
however, have been victimized.
</P>
<P>
   In Tijuana in 1996, Mamoru Konno, the president of Sanyo Video
Components, a San Diego company, was seized and held for nine days.
He was released after his company paid a ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The Baja California police were anxious to dispel reports that
Sayama's death had occurred during an attempt at another
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Sayama was one of the Japanese managers who ran an assembly
plant in Tijuana employing 300 workers. The plant is owned by
Mogami America of National City, Calif., a subsidiary of Pioneer
Speakers, said Kim Minakoshi, an accountant at Mogami's Tijuana
plant. The plant produces parts for stereo speakers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sayama, who lived in the United States for 20 years, was on his
way back from the Tijuana plant in his 1993 Honda Accord at about
3:30 p.m. on Tuesday, Ms. Minakoshi said. He was wearing a Mogami
company uniform and traveling with his windows down, she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Mexican police, the two youths confessed that
they had met in a Tijuana shopping center and laid plans to steal a
car. When one armed youth approached Sayama at a stoplight, he got
out of his car and fought with the attacker. Roman fired the two
shots that hit Sayama, the police charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
