with campaign-finance petitions. Speaker Dennis Hastert met
Wednesday with more than two dozen House Republicans who were
pushing for an early vote on overhauling the nation's campaign
finance laws, but he refused to commit to act earlier than the end
of September. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- May 5, 1999 --
PALESTINIANS-ECON, 5-05 -- Munib Masri on the phone before signing
a loan agreement. Masri, a Texas-educated billionaire, has invested
in building a Palestinian stock exchange, a modern television
assembly plant, the headquarters of PalTel, the Mideast's first
privately owned phone company. The investments can be considered
cornerstones of an emerging Palestinian economy, which is being
built with offshore Palestinian money in anticipation of statehood.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- May 5, 1999 -- SOUTHERN-FOOD-2-COX, 5-05
-- Herbert T. Kaplan, Operations Manager of Vidalia, a restaurant
in Washington, holds a plate with their signature appetizer, a
baked Vidalia onion, left, and a lobster salad on a bed of mushroom
fennel and Peruvian potatoes. Some purists chafe at the versions of
down-home food served at upscale eateries like Vidalia. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- May 5, 1999 -- SOUTHERN-FOOD-1-COX, 5-05
-- For more than half a century, the Florida Avenue Grill has been
the epicurean epicenter for authentic Southern cooking in
Washington. The walls are covered with pictures of celebrities who
have eaten the cornbread and fried chicken over the years. There
are testimonials from Strom Thurmond, Denzel Washington, the Four
Tops, Clarence Thomas, Janet Reno, Lena Horne, a dozen or so
Washington Redskins and scores of other distinguished diners. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
