children. But, like conventional suburbs, they overlook the
inevitability of teen-agers in their design. (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) TIVOLI, N.Y. -- May 5, 1999 -- CALLENDAR-HOUSE-2, 5-05 --
McKim, Mead &AMP; White reconfigured the Callendar House in 1910,
adding the south-facing salon and porch. The house was built by
Henry Gilbert Livingston and promptly sold off to a relative who,
in the 1830s, added the house's most memorable feature, the Greek
Revival colonnade across the back, overlooking the river to the
west and, to the south, the river's North Bay. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TIVOLI, N.Y. -- May 5, 1999 -- CALLENDAR-HOUSE-1, 5-05 --
A family cemetery, with room for pets, near the Callendar House,
one of the few great Hudson River mansions still in private hands.
Although the late-18th-century house is indubitably American, a
combination of Mount Vernon and Gracie Mansion, most of the
furnishings are French. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
