Boston Bruins have made it through the first round of the NHL
playoffs, so the thick blanket that covers Ray Bourque's face must
be his playoff beard. ``I'm always thinking, 'OK, do I shave it
after every series? What should I do here, trim it, carve it,
what?' `` says Bourque, 38. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) SOMERVILLE, Mass. -- May 5, 1999 -- FOOD-PIZZELLE-BOS,
5-05 -- Giovanna ``Jennie'' Loverro Ferri, age 99, with her
homemade pizelle, (peat-ZEL-le), a crisp Italian pastry. Mrs. Ferri
will turn 100 on June 24, and since her retirement in the late '60s
from her job as a raincoat stitcher for Byron Clothing in Davis
Square, she has baked almost every single day. ``If the eggs are
too small, you put in a little more flour,'' she says. (Barry
Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- May 5, 1999 -- AUTHOR-KIDDER-BOS,
5-05 -- Tracy Kidder, author of ``Home Town,'' his sixth book and
something of a departure. Instead of the tightly defined narratives
that made him famous, Kidder, 53, presents a broad cross section of
life as found in this small Western Massachusetts city. ``Sociology
is not what I'm out to write,'' he says. ``I wanted to write
interesting stories.'' (John Bohn/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
