<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mayor Glenn Lewis of Moore said people have been so generous
that there is enough food in the First Baptist Church ``to feed
Oklahoma City.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor asked for donations of tools, packing boxes and
medical supplies, such as Band Aids.
</P>
<P>
   In most Moore neighborhoods, yesterday was the first day that
people were allowed back in. Some suffered minor cuts and puncture
wounds stepping on broken glass and nails as they sifted through
the debris for personal belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need gloves, shovels and boxes people use for moving,''
Lewis said.
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mealman lives in Wayne, Okla., and drove to the disaster
area to volunteer his services.
</P>
<P>
   Mealman works in construction and drove his 16-foot trailer to
the area to help people salvage what they can from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can help cover the roof and do some other things to protect
what's left,'' he said. ``I've got this ability and I'm going to
spend four or five days helping. And I don't charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I donated blood yesterday,'' Mealman said. ``This is total
devastation, worse than anything I've ever seen. This is the least
I can do.''
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Don Dorough's parents home was leveled by Monday's tornado as it
swept through Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Dorough said his parents were not injured and were more
fortunate than their next-door neighbor. The neighbor was huddled
in a bedroom closet shielding her two young boys when the roof blew
off her home and she was pelted with debris.
</P>
<P>
   She suffered two fractured wrists, as well as the indignity of
being hit in the face by a flying skunk.
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, a police spokesman said the state's chief medical
officer had confirmed two deaths and expected to attribute four
more deaths to the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Police said there were no reports of new casualties, nor were
there any additional survivors found. A 7:30 p.m. curfew will
remain in effect for the rest of the week.
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Some people are keeping a sense of humor in the face of the
devastation. One home, reduced to a couple of brick walls, had this
advertisement scrawled across it: ``4 Sale, Fixer Upper.''
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Like most tornado victims, D.L. Frizell and his wife, Betty,
lost a number of personal belongings such as family photo albums. A
photo of Frizell's granddaughter, with her name written on the
back, was found several miles from his home and given to a local TV
station. The station showed the photo during the newscast and
several of Frizell's friends identified it.
</P>
<P>
   The photo is being returned to Frizell, who said, ``I haven't
been able to watch TV the past few days so I didn't know anything
about this.''
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service engineering teams are only beginning to
inspect the tracks of 76 tornadoes that tore through five states.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that advanced through southern Oklahoma City and
Moore cut a 40-mile swath across the middle of the state, leaving
concrete slabs where homes had been.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the tornado reached F5 status, described as
``incredible'' on the Fujita scale, and which means its winds
topped 260 mph. It dropped back to an F4 as it continued on a
northeast track, weather service reports said.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburb of Moore, the tornado expanded to three-quarters
of a mile wide. Officials suspect that it again reached F5 status
in portions of the city, but indications are only preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday storms will go down as one of the top 10 outbreaks of
tornadoes in one day in the nation, said Kevin Kelleher, a
spokesman for the National Severe Storms Laboratory in Norman,
Okla. It is the sixth worst in Oklahoma based on deaths.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
