<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;      05-05 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: A WRONG MOVE ON SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big plans to overhaul Social Security may or may not be dead in
Congress this year. But regardless of what happens, Washington will
eventually have to come up with a way to keep the system from
running out of money when the baby boomers retire in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   What each of the plans now on the table has in common, including
the bipartisan House bill proposed Wednesday, is that they all
promise financial salvation through the creation of private
accounts. These accounts would provide some of the retirement
benefits that now come entirely from a common trust fund. Private
accounts have a simple allure. Workers can expect to earn only
about a 1 or 2 percent a year above inflation on the money they pay
in payroll taxes to the trust fund. But they could expect to earn
at least 4 percent on money they put into private accounts and
invest in stocks and bonds. The difference is enough to raise
retirement benefits by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem obvious, then, that private accounts are
stunningly better. Not so, economists say. Private accounts provide
no financial benefit. Indeed, they are financial losers. There is a
defense of privatization. But that defense is political.
</P>
<P>
   A careful analysis by John Geanakoplos of Yale, Olivia Mitchell
of the University of Pennsylvania and Stephen Zeldes of Columbia
University shows that private accounts accomplish nothing on
average that the trust fund couldn't accomplish more cheaply. It
should be noted that Professor Mitchell comes to this result
despite her outspoken advocacy of private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Under current law, most of the money that comes into
the trust fund through payroll taxes goes right back out to support
current retirees. The obligation to pay current retirees continues
whether or not the system is privatized. If reform did nothing more
than replace a common trust fund with private accounts, there would
be little financial benefit, because there would be little to
invest in stocks, bonds or anything else. Without new money, few
dollars would ever go to the new private accounts because they
would be committed to current retirees.
</P>
<P>
   To make private accounts work, privatization advocates propose
tapping expected federal surpluses to pump extra money into the
system. They envision 150 million workers investing the extra money
in stocks and bonds yielding more than 5 percent above inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the extra money could instead be invested in the existing
trust fund. Under current law, the money can only be used to buy
special government bonds that pay interest of only about 3 percent
above inflation. The financial advantage of private accounts over
the trust fund in the congressional plans, then, follows from a
quirk of current law, a law that could be changed to permit the
trust fund to invest in a diversified portfolio of stocks and
bonds. Invested similarly, private accounts are not better than the
trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they are worse. A single trust fund keeps administrative
expense at a minimum. But setting up and maintaining 150 million
private accounts would rack up substantial fees and commissions for
Wall Street. Professor Peter Diamond of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology estimates that the administrative costs would reduce
retirement payments by at least 25 percent by the time of
retirement and would cost another 5 to 10 percent to convert, as
most plans require, the savings into a monthly annuity.
</P>
<P>
   So if private accounts cost more to administer than does a trust
fund and produce no better investment returns, why bother setting
them up? The answer, proponents say, is that government cannot be
trusted to purchase shares in American companies. It would be
tempted to meddle _ for instance, by interfering with the
management of tobacco companies or selling shares of companies that
offer violent computer games to children. The way around that, say
those who favor trust fund investments, is to legislatively put
stock-picking decisions in the hands of private managers and forbid
the government to exercise voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   So the debate over private accounts rests almost entirely on a
political call. To supporters, they create private property that
Congress could never reclaim. To opponents they represent
needlessly costly and potentially pernicious reform that would
undermine the current system's transfers to low-wage workers and
scrape away the insulation a single investment pool provides
individuals against the risk that their own stock and bond
purchases go awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a terrific economic argument for pumping more money
into Social Security in order to raise national saving and
investment,'' said Laurence S. Seidman, an economist at the
University of Delaware and author of a new book on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a terrific economic argument for investing at least
some Social Security money in stocks because that would allow
low-wage workers to reap the benefit of high-yield stocks without
exposing themselves to much risk. But there is no purely economic
reason why either of these reforms need to be done through private
accounts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
