<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- May 5, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 5-05 -- A
house roof has joints between roof sections and around vents,
skylights and chimneys. These joints are vulnerable to leaking
because they usually connect different materials that expand and
contract at dissimilar rates. Builders protect these joints by
covering them with flashing, a flexible material like aluminum,
copper, galvanized steel or neoprene, to repel rain and snow.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KENTLANDS, Md. -- May 5, 1999 -- SUBURBS-PSYCHE, 5-05 --
In downtown Kentlands, Jessica and Brenna Dorney see some friends.
Towns like this often foster nostalgic views of families with young
children. But, like conventional suburbs, they overlook the
inevitability of teen-agers in their design. (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) TIVOLI, N.Y. -- May 5, 1999 -- CALLENDAR-HOUSE-2, 5-05 --
McKim, Mead &AMP; White reconfigured the Callendar House in 1910,
adding the south-facing salon and porch. The house was built by
Henry Gilbert Livingston and promptly sold off to a relative who,
in the 1830s, added the house's most memorable feature, the Greek
Revival colonnade across the back, overlooking the river to the
west and, to the south, the river's North Bay. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TIVOLI, N.Y. -- May 5, 1999 -- CALLENDAR-HOUSE-1, 5-05 --
A family cemetery, with room for pets, near the Callendar House,
one of the few great Hudson River mansions still in private hands.
Although the late-18th-century house is indubitably American, a
combination of Mount Vernon and Gracie Mansion, most of the
furnishings are French. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) OKLAHOMA City -- May 5, 1999 -- OKLA-STORM-2, 5-05 --
Volunteers sort clothing Wednesday at the Oakcrest Church of Christ
in Oklahoma City. The items had been donated for victims of
Monday's tornadoes, which destroyed housands of homes here and
killed at least 43 people in Oklahoma and Kansas. More twisters
swarmed across parts of Texas and Arkansas on Tuesday, killing one
more person. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OKLAHOMA City -- May 5, 1999 -- OKLA-STORM-1, 5-05 --
Sofas are used as beds by people who evacuated their homes or were
left homeless by tornadoes at the Oakcrest Church of Christ on
Wednesday. People who fled neighborhoods that suffered the worst
damage in Oklahoma's deadliest tornadoes in five decades started
returning on Wednesday, many of them finding only rubble where
their homes had stood. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 5, 1999 -- CIR-MUSEUM-GUIDES, 5-05 --
Maxwell Anderson, director of the Whitney Museum, demonstrates a
tablet computer in front of Grant Wood's ``American Gothic.''
Visitors to the Whitney's current exhibit ``American Century'' can
use the Pad PC and, with the touch of a finger or stylus, have
access to audio, text and high- resolution color video and film
programmed to accompany specific pieces of art. (Barbara Alper/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WALNUT CREEK, Calif. -- May 5, 1999 -- CIR-DEBT-TECH.,
5-05 -- Debt collectors at Exterra celebrate with noisemakers the
resolution of an outstanding account by a colleague's work.
Computers are assisting debt collection companies in tracking down
people who change their identities in order to obtain new credit.
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 5, 1999 -- CIR-GYM-COMPUTER, 5-05 --
Jo-Jo Tyler works out using a Netpulse computer at Crunch Fitness.
The computer acts as a personal trainer monitoring the workout
while counting every pound lifted and offering advice like ``go
slower.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
