A5979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-STEELE-BOS &LR;      05-05 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-STEELE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE AGAINST STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton is not the accused in the federal trial that
started this week in Alexandria, Va., but he was mentioned 37 times
in the 30-minute opening statement by the prosecutor working for
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to a growing list of bizarre prosecutions, Starr is
seeking an obstruction-of-justice conviction of a woman
tangentially connected with an unproven allegation of an unwanted
sexual advance from Clinton in 1993. Each day's testimony has
raised more doubts about Starr's conduct than that of anyone in the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The central charge by former White House volunteer Kathleen
Willey _ repeated on the stand Wednesday _ is that Clinton groped
her crudely in 1993. Clinton has denied the story. Some friends of
Willey support her version; others say she was seeking an amorous
encounter with Clinton. One account says she attempted to sell her
story. Starr believes Willey but lacked the evidence to include the
incident in his impeachment referral. This did not stop him,
however, from harassing and then indicting Julie Hiatt Steele, a
former friend of Willey who at first backed her up but now says she
was lying because Willey asked her to.
</P>
<P>
   One witness is a third woman, Mary Highsmith, who claims that
her former friend Steele is now lying. But Highsmith has produced
three versions of when she first heard of the incident from Steele.
</P>
<P>
   The case is labyrinthine, to put it politely. It seems to hang
on the ability of Starr's prosecutors to show that Highsmith's
revised memory is credible, thereby proving that Steele's revised
memory is not credible.
</P>
<P>
   A more basic question is what relevance any of this has. Perhaps
the issue all along was timing. Starr indicted Steele on Jan. 7 _
the day Clinton's impeachment trial began in the Senate. The move
was derided then for its cynicism; now Starr has to make the case.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is not the accused in Alexandria, but Starr
has put himself on trial. If the jury fails to convict Steele, it
will by inference convict Starr of misconduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
