<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-EMAIL-BOS &LR;      05-05 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EMAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOO PERSONAL COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-mail can be a seductive and evil genie. Summoned to serve man,
it can incriminate him, or her, as the temptation to tell all _ or
at least the juicy parts _ overwhelms caution at the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The genie tripped up Bill Gates, who saw a series of blunt
exchanges between his executives become what the government called
``the smoking gun'' in its antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The genie trapped chatty presidential paramour Monica Lewinsky,
whose e-mail and that of confidante Linda Tripp and others was
confiscated by independent counsel Kenneth Starr and read all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post recently reported that a husband whose
steamy e-mail is being used against him in a Virginia custody case
signed off one message with the obviously unheeded warning ``You
must not print this, and delete all files!!'' In what may explain
the compulsion to type one's most private thoughts on this most
public medium, he added: ``It's good to talk it out, but
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, ``talk'' is often electronic, sent in
stream-of-consciousness bursts that seem to move with the speed of
a tennis match. The fingers fly, the thoughts whiz back and forth,
creating a sense of intimacy despite distances, or maybe because of
them, since the solitary person sitting at a screen may find it
easy to shed inhibitions and speak from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   People may be lulled into a false sense of security by the hum
of the machine or the friendly ``desktop'' icons _ particularly the
one labeled ``My Computer,'' or America Online's folksy country
mailbox with the flag, accompanied by the nice voice that says
``You've got mail!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being told that the mail is about as private as a
postcard, that the boss could be monitoring it, and that gossipy
messages frequently go astray _ sometimes to the very person being
gossiped about _ we cannot resist firing off a hot one.
</P>
<P>
   So the red face joins repetitive stress injury in the
``downside'' file of this indispensible innovation. It might have
been more aptly named the impersonal computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
