<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JANE-AWARD-KAN &LR;      05-05 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANE-AWARD-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Actress Jane Alexander `deeply honored' to receive KC award  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Awards are nothing new to actress Jane
Alexander, who has earned a Tony, an Emmy and four Academy Award
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Harry S. Truman Public Service Award, which she will
accept Friday night in Independence, Mo., has her delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``To receive an award for distinguished public service,'' she
said this week, ``named after one of the best presidents we have
had and that is given in his home city, I am deeply honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceremonies, free to the public, begin at 7 p.m. at the Truman
Library. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Truman Public Service Awards, which are given by the
city of Independence, have gone to politicians. Past recipients
include former U.S. Sens. Sam Nunn and Bill Bradley, and former
Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Until six years ago, Alexander was but an actress, known for her
presence in about 100 plays and about 40 films, including ``The
Great White Hope'' and ``All the President's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1993 President Clinton nominated her to head the
National Endowment for the Arts, an agency that conservative House
Republicans had vowed to abolish.
</P>
<P>
   In her tenure, Alexander pared the organization's staff from 275
to 150. Grants to arts organizations also were reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alexander won the larger battle. In October 1997, Congress
approved a $98 million budget for the agency, overcoming a previous
House vote to eliminate all funds. Alexander left soon after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held the course,'' Alexander said. ``I kept the agency
alive. There were some hard-liners, very formidable foes...but
their voices have been quieted, and I think that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits arts leaders in the country, as well as members of
both parties, for the agency's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Mayor Ron Stewart said Alexander represented
Truman's qualities in contemporary times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love of country and a dedication to cause,'' Stewart said.
``She had both of those. And when you start going through her
background, you find her support of causes like civil rights,
causes that Mr. Truman also supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is confident that Truman, a lover of classical piano
and a friend of painter Thomas Hart Benton's, would have supported
the arts agency.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Truman, however, Alexander could not have made politics
her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to love the game, the fight,'' she said. ``I didn't
love it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AWARD-TRUMAN-KAN &LR;      05-05 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWARD-TRUMAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUMAN GOOD NEIGHBOR AWARD TO GO TO AFRICAN-AMERICAN FOR FIRST
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City institution that for years
didn't include many African-Americans, either in the crowd or in
the seat of honor, will have both Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Historian John Hope Franklin will become the first
African-American to receive the Harry S. Truman Good Neighbor
Award, given every year since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   And of the 478 guests expected at the noon luncheon in downtown
Kansas City, about 80 are black, said Margaret MacDonald, the award
foundation's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   That's a significant increase from the minority representation
at previous lunches, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just decided to go into the next century as an organization
that ignores nobody,'' MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon is a Kansas City tradition that began in 1953 with
a small group of men. Yet as the lunch developed into a more formal
affair that brought distinguished guests from politics, journalism
and other fields, it didn't become as inclusive as some thought it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. District Judge Scott O. Wright criticized the
foundation for never having honored a black person. Since 1973, 28
men and two women have received Truman Good Neighbor awards.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he was pleased with this year's changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a positive commitment, and I applaud them for
that,'' said Wright, who plans to attend Friday's lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, professor emeritus at Duke University, said he was
unaware of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know much about what went on between then and
now with respect to the Good Neighbor Award,'' Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that he was flattered to receive the award.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon began in 1953 when 21 of Truman's friends held a
birthday celebration at a downtown restaurant. The event grew,
relocating to the nearby Muehlebach Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from surviving photographs and programs, much of the
ritual was of the affable, service club variety.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1957 lunch, as Margaret Truman was pregnant with the
former president's first grandchild, guests wore oversized infant's
bibs bearing the message ``Hi! Grandpa Truman. We hope it's
twins.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman attended the lunch every year until shortly before he
died in 1972. The group, by then called the Eddie Jacobson
Foundation in honor of Truman's former haberdashery partner, soon
adopted its current name, the Harry S. Truman Good Neighbor Award
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Of about 300 names of guests found on invitation lists from 1961
and 1964, there were no women. Henry J. Talge, the Kansas City
businessman who founded the Rival Co. and who organized the event,
preferred the company of men at the lunch, MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   But Talge's regard for Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.S. ambassador
to the United Nations, was such that she became the foundation's
first woman honoree in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   When MacDonald arrived at the foundation in the mid-1980s, she
began inviting women to the lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Talge, who died in 1990, was responsible for inviting
African-Americans to the event for the first time. In 1969, current
City Council member Alvin Brooks came to his first Truman lunch at
Talge's invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Brooks was one of several African-Americans to
suggest possible minority invitees to this year's lunch. At
MacDonald's request, Brooks faxed the names of about 75 black and
Hispanic men and women to the foundation office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read what Judge Wright had said and was ready to call
Margaret when she called me,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, without success, foundation members invited former
Gen. Colin Powell to receive the award. In 1994, the group gave a
special award to Call publisher Lucile H. Bluford. And the lunch
for years has featured a multicultural flavor, given the groups of
international students recognized annually.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said this week that he was curious whether the foundation
board would become more inclusive. Eighteen white men and
MacDonald, the only female member, make up the board.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Pistilli, foundation president, said that issue would be
discussed at the next board meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
