<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-600&AMP;A     05-05 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC MAY BE READYING HIS PEOPLE FOR A DEAL TO RESOLVE THE
CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Analysts and local journalists say they
detect small signs that President Slobodan Milosevic is preparing
public opinion for an end to the war over Kosovo and for a deal
with the West.
</P>
<P>
   In Milosevic's Yugoslavia, the process by which decisions are
made is opaque and divorced from public input or debate. Political
analysts are reduced to watching and interpreting the minutiae of
state news broadcasts and official announcements _ even more so
during the wartime censorship that now prevails.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a senior Yugoslav official on Wednesday reiterated
his government's opposition to foreign troops in Kosovo as part of
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts accustomed to watching the more subtle signs point
to the recent change in emphasis of the national television news,
which now leads each day with stories on the diplomatic efforts of
the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson, who persuaded Milosevic to release three
U.S. soldiers last weekend, and the Russian envoy Victor S.
Chernomyrdin, and features correspondents' reports from Western
capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on the results of NATO bombing around the country, which
used to receive the most prominent news coverage, are now relegated
to the second half of the news, 15 or 20 minutes into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``People smell something is in the air,'' said Ognjen
Pribicevic, a senior research fellow at the Institute of Social
Sciences in Belgrade. ``I do believe there might be a break.''
</P>
<P>
   The first item on Tuesday's news was Milosevic's meeting with
two top military and police commanders in Kosovo reporting the
completion of their tasks, namely defending the country, claiming
destruction of the Kosovo Liberation Army and keeping NATO at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the army and police, at great sacrifice and loss of
life, were able to prevent the greatest aggressor in the world
occupying the country and at the same time defended our border from
bands of terrorists,'' a Belgrade daily, Blic, wrote the following
day.
</P>
<P>
   The two generals' report to the president that their task was
accomplished looked very like a final report, local journalists
suggested. ``They are definitely preparing the public for a deal,''
said one journalist, who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many local analysts in Belgrade feel that Milosevic will
accept a solution for Kosovo which will include NATO troops this
week,'' wrote Bratislav Grubacic, editor in chief of the VIP news
service.
</P>
<P>
   Pribicevic, who recently joined up with Vuk Draskovic, the
maverick politician dismissed as deputy prime minister last week,
predicted that: ``There will be some international mission, with
Russians, Ukrainians and members from the northern European
countries. NATO is insisting it will be an armed mission. We are
saying it will not be. A compromise will be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Draskovic broke ranks last week, calling for an end to the
war and acceptance of an international force in Kosovo, the subject
has been openly debated in the press. Local media, heavily
controlled and cowed into silence on many topics in the first weeks
of the war by fear of government reprisals, have begun to discuss
the chances of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians, who became quiet amid the intense
patriotism the NATO air strikes evoked, have begun to voice
opinions on the possibility of foreign troops arriving in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Obradovic, leader of the small political party Social
Democracy, said in an interview that ``if that is the condition for
us to go back on to the road to peace and stop the killing and
destruction of the country, then let them come in.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-known former general, Obradovic said the Yugoslav
military and Serb police could find an understanding with a foreign
force. Yet after the NATO attacks, he said, ``We think it is in the
common interest of all, NATO as well, to put the whole thing in
U.N. hands and those forces should be under the U.N. flag.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He and other politicians also say that it is important that the
international force have a clear mandate, a limited time frame for
their mission in Kosovo and be restricted to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians voiced similar views. Vojislav Kostunica,
leader of the Democratic Party of Serbia, was quoted in Blic as
saying that Milosevic was pondering the way in which the
peacekeepers could be armed. Last week, Milosevic said in an
interview with a Western journalist that foreign soldiers could
bear arms for self-defense only.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops should not be in the forefront of the force,
Kostunica suggested, but added: ``There is little likelihood of it
being only a civilian force.''
</P>
<P>
   Goran Svilanovic, the new leader of the opposition group Civic
Alliance of Serbia, was quoted by Blic: ``It is in the interests of
Serbia, not the U.S.A., to stop the war, because our citizens are
getting killed and our towns are being destroyed. That is why we
have to do more than others to stop the war.''
</P>
<P>
   While none of these politicians has any influence with the
leadership, and all admit that Milosevic will keep them guessing
whether he will make a deal until the last moment, they all seem to
sense a change in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Grubacic, editor of the VIP news service, suggested Milosevic
needed two more weeks to prepare the Yugoslav people and military.
``He needs to tire the people a bit more, so they are ready to
accept anything,'' he said. ``So the question now is how he sneaks
out of the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
