<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      05-05 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOL BOARD BACKS MAYOR TO REJECT CHANCELLOR'S 5-YEAR PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew moved to a new front Wednesday, as a
four-member majority of the Board of Education backed by the mayor
rejected the chancellor's five-year school construction proposal
and agreed on its own version.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement _ by the two appointees of the mayor and the
appointees of the Queens and Staten Island borough presidents _ set
the stage for the first defeat by Crew by the board since it hired
him as chief executive in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The substitute plan was devised in recent days at City Hall at
the insistence of Queens officials, who felt shortchanged by the
chancellor's proposal. But the new majority could not have been
forged without the support of the mayor's two appointees, an
indication of the mayor's sway over the board and city education
policy.
</P>
<P>
   In coming together, the majority brought the feud between
Giuliani and Crew out of the theoretical realm, over such questions
as whether there should be taxpayer-financed vouchers or an
education commissioner who reports to the mayor, and into the
practical.
</P>
<P>
   The board had already scheduled a vote on the chancellor's
proposal for noon on Thursday, and that vote is still expected to
take place. The four members said in a written statement Wednesday
that they would vote no and then approve an outline of their plan,
ordering the chancellor and his aides to write a proposal that
meets their specifications by ``the close of business Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Though stopping short of a formal vote of no confidence in Crew,
the board majority made clear that it could curtail the
chancellor's power in a crucial area: setting the construction
priorities for a system of 1.1 million students and 1,100 schools.
</P>
<P>
   The four who wrote the alternative proposal did so with all the
secrecy of a palace coup, conferring without involving the members
from the Bronx and Manhattan, as well as the Brooklyn member, board
president William Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Under the revised plan, the overall number of new classroom
seats would be reduced, as a result of a more conservative estimate
of financing, as would money for repairs and high school computers.
But the share of new seats for Queens and Staten Island would rise,
at the expense of the other three boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   The four-member majority announced its plans, in a signed formal
board resolution released late Wednesday morning, at a time the
chancellor was in Washington state, tending to a son recovering
from an emergency appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said he was flying back late on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though the board's headquarters at 110 Livingston St. in
Brooklyn was rife with whispered questions about how Crew could
remain as chancellor if he lost such a crucial vote, his aides said
emphatically that he had no intention of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever the board goes, so goes the chancellor,'' said Chiara
Coletti, the chancellor's spokeswoman. ``The chancellor thinks that
the capital plan he presented is a far better one for the children.
However, the mayor got the votes for the plan he wants. The
chancellor reports to the board and will follow the will of the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't believe it's a divided board,'' she added. ``The
board divided on this one issue. The mayor worked hard to get those
votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor's latest capital proposal, released last weekend,
called for $11.2 billion to be spent on school construction from
this July through 2004, though his aides felt assured of only $8.1
billion of that money, which is drawn from federal and state as
well as city sources. The substitute plan would reduce the
chancellor's plan further still, to $7 billion, because, the
members in the majority argued, Crew's plan was based on overly
optimistic projections of financing from the state and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But though the total number of classroom seats would go down,
the substitute proposal would substantially reconfigure how those
seats were distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Queens, whose officials had complained the loudest about
inequities in the initial plan, would increase its share of all new
school construction to 65.4 percent from 61.9 percent, and Staten
Island's would rise to 4 percent from 1.6 percent. The share of new
construction in Brooklyn would fall to 12.3 percent from 16
percent, in the Bronx to 13.2 percent from 14.8 percent, and in
Manhattan to 5.1 percent from 5.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
