<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FHS-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FHS REPORTS 7% INCREASE IN EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Managed care specialist Foundation Health Systems
Inc. reported a 7 percent gain in first quarter earnings Wednesday
thanks in part to the sale of some money-losing operations.
</P>
<P>
   The health insurer said profits rose to $46.3 million, or 23
cents a diluted share, on revenues of $2.28 billion, compared to
$43.3 million, or 22 cents, one year ago. The results, which
exclude several one-time gains and charges, met a consensus
estimate of 22 cents per share from analysts surveyed by First Call
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the company's net income was a $53.5 million pretax gain
from the sale of Foundation's pharmacy benefit operations to
Advance Paradigm Inc. in March. Foundation took a restructuring
charge of $21 million from the pending closure of its service
center in Pueblo, Colo., and was hit by a $5.4 million charge from
new U.S. accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodland Hills, Calif., company previously sold its
money-losing workers compensation unit, further easing the drain on
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Though year-on-year there wasn't much of a gain, Wednesday's
results are a clear improvement over Foundation's recent
performance. The company lost $104 million in the last quarter of
1998, for an annual loss of $164 million. Much of that stemmed from
the poor performance of the company's Medicare contracts in the
northeast United States. In several counties, Foundation
subsidiaries spent more providing care to elderly members than they
were paid by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a turnaround in the Northeast, a lot of other
issues become secondary or tertiary,'' said analyst Robert Hoehn at
ING Baring Furman Selzs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts noted that while encouraging, Foundation's
results do not guarantee the firm is past its financial woes. The
first quarter is typically the most profitable among health
insurers and medical costs often rise as the year progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent Foundation shares down 31.25 cents, or 2.05
percent, to $14.9375. The company had closed at a 1999 high of
$15.25 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
