<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAFFITI-ARTISTS-ART-     05-05 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAFFITI-ARTISTS-ART-900&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAFFITI ESTHETIC, ONCE REVILED, FLOURISHES IN THE MAINSTREAM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day after the Dow Jones industrial average hit
10,000 this spring, a special report explaining the record-breaking
news appeared on the Wall Street Journal's Web site: The headline
was a panel of bold, 3-D letters layered one upon another, and a
dollar-green bull leapt off the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The image bore a striking resemblance to the script that once
covered the city's public transportation system. And that was no
coincidence. The man The Journal had tapped to design its site _
Kel First Rodriguez _ was once a graffiti writer, slipping out of
his South Bronx home under cover of night to emblazon his moniker
on New York City subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of that graffiti feeling, that energy, sort of crept in
there,'' Rodriguez, now 35, said of his work for The Journal,
adding this caveat: ``I knew how far to go in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kel First's rise from the underground, so to speak, mirrors the
radical transformation of graffiti in the 20 years since its peak.
Once reviled by some as a visual scourge of the city, graffiti
today _ or at least the astonishing esthetic it invented _ is
everywhere. Only now, it is paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Its influence is indelible: It can be seen on billboards
plugging $100 sneakers and in advertisements for soda. And, even as
city subways are touted as graffiti-free, ads promoting everything
from radio stations to the Metrocard now cover some buses top to
bottom, just as graffiti did back in the days when taggers dangled
from the tops of subway cars, risking fines and jail time to turn
the trains into their personal moving billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graffiti was able to come along on the coattails of hip-hop
and people are appreciating it for its style, which they couldn't
back then, because they couldn't get beyond the vandalism thing,''
said Martha Cooper, a photographer who, with Henry Chalfant, wrote
the authoritative history of the movement, ``Subway Art'' in 1984.
``It's been altered and embraced by the corporate world.''
</P>
<P>
   The graffiti trio TATS Cru has covered entire walls with ads for
Coca-Cola, for instance, while Lady Pink, one of the rare women to
paint trains in the late 1970s, now paints murals on commission.
Cey Adams designs album covers and Futura and Stash produce a
graffiti-inspired clothing line.
</P>
<P>
   Full-time artists like Lee Quinones and Blade, contemporaries of
graffiti-inspired artists like Keith Haring, whose work brought him
fame and fortune nearly two decades ago, now sell their canvasses
on the other side of the Atlantic, where graffiti and other
accouterments of hip-hop culture are enjoying an exploding market.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, young Europeans make the journey here _ some to paint a
bona fide New York subway car _ though today it is less for the
sake of seeing their work on a running train than it is for a
snapshot to take home. A few writers still toss up a piece on a
blank wall, as others throw them up in cyberspace; several sites,
including Blade's, (bladekingofgraf.com) are devoted entirely to
graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, something commemorates the world that was. The
most recent event was a show at Exhibit A Gallery in Harlem
memorializing one of the old kings of the genre: Dondi, who died
last fall at 38. The show was organized by James T.O.P., a fellow
graffiti writer, as a tribute to his childhood friend. On the
walls, he hung a couple of Dondi's own works as well as photos of
the old painted subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   Lance and Vance Paul wandered into that gallery on 147th Street
one Saturday afternoon recently, and it was like wandering into
their childhood, they said. The 36-year-old twins, who grew up in
Harlem watching trains, peered closely at the photos, reminiscing
aloud. They rattled off the names of their favorite writers. They
debated whether Zephyr did the No.1 train or the No. 3. (Zephyr, in
fact, covered the No. 1 out of Riverdale while it rested in a yard
near his private school.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Long time,'' mused Lance Paul, shaking his head at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the big years for graffiti,'' added Vance.
</P>
<P>
   Those big years were chronicled in the 1982 cult movie ``Wild
Style.'' In the film, made just as graffiti was being embraced by
the art world, Quinones, then a rising star in the city's graffiti
movement, summed up its audacious, rebellious spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a graffiti writer is about taking the chances,'' he
said. ``You got to go out and paint and be called an outlaw at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   At 38, Quinones is no longer called an outlaw. In fact, just the
other day he was calling from Paris, where he was hanging his
canvasses at a gallery in the Bastille district and painting two
pieces commissioned by a deejay.
</P>
<P>
   Although many New Yorkers regarded graffiti as one of the most
conspicuous signs of urban decay, to its perpetrators it was both
game and vocation _ and, most of all, an expression of identity.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, in the early 1980s, the Manhattan art world embraced
the movement. Uptown suddenly met downtown. Agents picked up
taggers, and their words appeared on SoHo walls.
</P>
<P>
   It was mostly a short-lived affair. These days, with the
exception of venues like the Martinez Gallery in Chelsea, which is
devoted to the genre, graffiti finds a home mostly in European
galleries and museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to support an artist as he develops,'' Quinones said
of his patrons in Europe, where a modest-sized canvas of his now
fetches up to $10,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His resume today includes exhibitions from Nagoya, Japan, to
Barcelona, Spain, to the Whitney Museum of American Art in New
York, where his work was shown in the '80s. ``What I'm doing on
canvas, I used to do on trains,'' he said. ``I want people to study
my work and not just be astonished when a train comes out of a
tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, veteran graffiti writers like Quinones, Lady Pink and
Blade are invited to demonstrate their skills at annual graffiti
jams from Milan to Stockholm. Outlaws who once took great pains to
conceal their identities are now asked to paint before crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Back when half the skill lay in eluding the authorities, Lady
Pink was muscling her way into the boys' club that was graffiti. By
age 15, she was crawling out the windows of her parents' home in
Astoria, proving that she, too, could perch on the edge of a train,
paint for hours straight and sprint at the sight of cops.
</P>
<P>
   At first, when her parents discovered what she was doing, they
were appalled. But they came around when she sold her first canvas
in 1981 _ for what seemed then like a whopping $500. ``My dad built
shelves for all that spray paint I had stolen,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with her husband, a fellow graffiti writer who calls
himself Smith, she runs a painting company that has put fantastical
scenes in murals inside posh restaurants on Long Island. Even the
old neighborhood school in Astoria, which she tagged mercilessly as
a teen-ager, employed her to do a mural.
</P>
<P>
   While some former graffiti writers have become full-time
artists, others have bypassed the art world for greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Cey Adams hooked up with the rapper Russell Simmons in the
mid-1980s, just as the gallery scene began losing interest in
graffiti and hip-hop was becoming more commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, Adams is the creative director of Simmons' Def Jam label.
His work can be seen on billboards advertising radio station Hot
97, WQHT (97.1), whose fat, bold logo he designed, and on the album
covers of countless rappers, from L.L. Cool J. to E.p.m.D.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, he said, few teen-agers today seem to have the same
urge to grab a marker and tag the subways _ and those who do do not
impress him. ``If you tag on the back of my seat and I got on a
$1,000 jacket,'' he said, ``I'm not going to be smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, some young people _ and some not so young _ still burn
with the desire to ``bomb'' a train or a wall. Now the windows of
subways are scratched with monikers, and every now and then,
someone paints an elaborate piece on a building. Although graffiti
is still very much illegal, punishable by fines and criminal
prosecution, the train tunnels still lure the occasional writer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 25 years ago, Futura got caught in one of those tunnels
when a fire caught him and a friend unawares while they were
painting a train. The friend suffered massive burns and spoke out
passionately against graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken, Futura joined the Navy. But when he returned home, art
summoned him back. He began painting walls legally and flirted
briefly with the art world. By 1990, he and a fellow writer, Stash,
had begun churning out T-shirts splashed with brand name logos.
</P>
<P>
   Today they produce several lines of ``urban wear,'' including
one made for Japan. At their Eldridge Street boutique, a sweat
shirt sells for up to $70.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story of survival,'' said Futura, who is also known as
Leonard McGurr, 43 and the father of two children, 14 and 8.
``There's a way to profit from the work without defacing public
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Kel First figured that out as well. He gave up his post at The
Wall Street Journal last month and is devoting himself to his own
Web site, where he is building an online shopping mall for urban
gear: labodega.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
