</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CAMPAIGN FOR PHIL JACKSON IN FULL SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When Phil Jackson was a player with the New York
Knicks in the early 1970s, he would hear coach Red Holzman and
trainer Danny Whelan inform starting small forward Bill Bradley
that when Bradley became president of the United States, they
wanted the jobs of checking the height of the water levels of the
Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. Holzman would sit at one coast for six
months and Whelan at the other, and then they would switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't approached Bill for that job yet,'' Jackson said
Wednesday, ``although he tells people that if elected I'd be his
secretary of dee-fense. Which is different from secretary of
de-fense.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has been unemployed since last June, has been an
unpaid campaigner for Bradley, who, some 25 years after the end of
his playing career, has announced that he is seeking residence in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Jackson, at age 53 and looking fit and rested
and shorn of his gray beard, was honored at halftime of the
Bulls-Orlando Magic game at the United Center for his masterful
contributions as coach of Bulls teams that won six National
Basketball Association championships in the previous eight seasons.
Among those in attendance was former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   For a combination of reasons _ the retirement of Michael Jordan
to a personality conflict with general manager Jerry Krause, to a
need to simply clear his basketball sinuses _ Jackson quit the
Bulls and took a sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   In that time he has built a house in Woodstock, N.Y., and has
been giving speeches to the tune of $45,000 a talk (outside of
politicking), doing some writing. He is, after all, the author of
the best seller ``Sacred Hoops.'' And he is still ``looking over my
shoulder at the world of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more than that surely. While Wednesday night was the
first time this season that he has entered an NBA arena, Jackson
said he has checked out some games on television. But he has also
been Penelope to NBA suitors. He has sat and woven his thoughts
quietly while his representative, the Chicago lawyer Todd
Musburger, has been fielding love notes from teams desirous of
Jackson's hand as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four offers on the table,'' Musburger said, ``and at
the end of the season we're expecting at least two or three more.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``I'd be interested only if the intrigue is
there.'' And while Jackson has sometimes spoken in cryptic terms,
it was clear what ``intrigue'' meant: money, team, control, city,
and not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that conceivably have been in touch with Musburger are
the Lakers, the Nets and maybe Washington, Denver, Charlotte and
Vancouver _ and the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Jackson said he would have to look at is the contracts
of current players and where the team is in the salary cap and how
flexible they would be in dumping aging veterans and getting
players who appeal to him. Which conceivably would eliminate the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And everyone would like to go to a warm-weather city,''
Jackson said, ``but that's not a determining factor.'' That might
have significance for Los Angeles or Charlotte, where Jordan may
become a part owner. But Jackson says Paul Silas has done a good
job as coach of the Hornets and he would imagine that Jordan would
be very hands-on as an owner.
</P>
<P>
   Which would not be too attractive for Jackson, who would like
the kind of control over decisions on players that Pat Riley and
Rick Pitino have with Miami and Boston. ``I want to decide the
players for my coaching style.''
</P>
<P>
   One such player is Shaquille O'Neal, who traveled to South
America with Jackson three years ago to conduct basketball clinics.
Jackson, Musburger said, liked O'Neal and believes he would be
great for the triangle offense that Jackson employed with the
Bulls. Then there is the cash. Jackson made $6 million in his last
year as the Bulls' coach. He would want more. Chuck Daly is
currently the highest-paid pure coach at $5 million. Riley and
Pitino have upper-management deals in which they earn $10 million
or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you know Phil,'' said Musburger, alluding to Jackson's
flower-child early years and his Zen-blend later days, ``you know
that it's not just money that motivates him.''
</P>
<P>
   One other factor: how Bradley is progressing as the one, as
Jackson said, ``to lead us into the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone who doesn't know Jackson asks what he does for a
living, what does he say? ``I say I'm a magician,'' he said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   A magician now, he was asked, or then? ``Both,'' he said,
inscrutably. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
