<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEINZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-05 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEINZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZ AIMS FOR MORE GOLD OUT OF ITS RED CONDIMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the chief executive of H.J. Heinz spoke before a group of
Wall Street analysts in Florida in February, promoting his
company's fresh take on its business, the souvenir handed out to
everyone to remind them of the big changes at Heinz was . . . a
bottle of ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Using its flagship condiment as a battering ram, Heinz is in the
middle of a major campaign to revamp itself as a zippy, modern
corporate behemoth, not the slow, barely growing behemoth it has
long been. For the first time in five years, Heinz is spending
large sums _ an estimated $50 million _ on an advertising campaign.
The campaign, designed by the Leo Burnett Co., centers on ketchup
and is intended to put forth a more contemporary image for the
whole company. The new ads portray ketchup as a way to make your
food ``taste however you want it to taste,'' among other things.
But the question remains: What kind of future is there in ketchup?
</P>
<P>
   At the company's headquarters in Pittsburgh, people are wildly
enthusiastic about the red stuff. Last fall, the test kitchens came
up with recipes for a ketchup vinaigrette and for peanut butter
cookies, slightly darker than usual, made from dough with a
quarter-cup of ketchup in it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the supposed role of ketchup in human psychology,
a theory that probably gets more attention at Heinz than it does in
any formal academic quarters. ``We're letting people, particularly
kids, personalize their food,'' said Kenneth C. Keller Jr., the
marketing manager for ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the chief executive's view on the subject.
``Ketchup is the barometer for how Heinz does,'' said William R.
Johnson, who made his name in pet food at the company but has
clearly shifted his allegiance. After several years of inertia,
worldwide ketchup sales rose 8 percent in the last fiscal year,
which ended in April.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ketchup can truly be turned around will be a serious
test for Johnson, who took over the company's top job last year
from the colorful, debonair Anthony J.F. O'Reilly. While the latter
remains chairman of Heinz and is the ninth-largest stockholder,
with 6.2 million shares, Johnson has made it plain, without naming
names, that he inherited several problems across the company's
divisions, which include canned tuna, pickles, baby food and Weight
Watchers products and classes. In February, he announced the latest
Heinz reorganization, in which products are grouped globally to
capitalize on what is working well, and said he would sell the
Weight Watchers classroom business.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Heinz executives are expected to paint a bright
picture of the company's future, particularly as it pertains to
ketchup, at a food-industry conference organized by Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co. Thursday. But with the stock near its 52-week low, analysts
are taking a wait-and-see position as to whether Heinz's strategy _
which includes cutting some prices, distributing recipes in the
manner of condensed-soup companies during the 1950s and trying to
spin the image of ketchup to appeal to a wider audience _ will pay
off. After all, this is the twilight of the 20th century, during
which Americans became acquainted with cosmopolitan alternatives
like salsa, Dijon mustard and tamarind glaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in my industry is that there is a battle for the
stomach,'' said Nomi Ghez, a food analyst for Goldman, Sachs. ``And
all of the companies are saying they are going to get per-capita
consumption up. Well, the stomach is a limited space. They are not
going to be able to increase per-capita consumption of all their
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Ketchup is seen mainly as an accompaniment to something else,
such as hot dogs and french fries. But Keller is sure it can be
more.
</P>
<P>
   For example, recipes that use a lot of ketchup should drive
sales, he said. ``The bottom line is, if we can get people to use
these recipes, they are going to use between 4 and 10 ounces of
ketchup at a shot, versus a typical serving of 1 to 2 ounces,'' he
said. ``That's gold for us, and gold for the category.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinz had been a little arrogant about its brand strength,
managers acknowledge. The price had risen to about 65 percent more
than store-brand ketchup but has been rolled back to 40 percent
more. Changes in the way tomatoes are processed for ketchup helped
bring about savings worldwide that are covering the price drop,
said Joseph Jimenez, the president and chief executive of Heinz
North America.
</P>
<P>
   The company also stopped advertising ketchup, again thinking it
had momentum to spare. Market share fell steadily, although Heinz
kept its spot as the leading brand. A brief campaign last year, on
the theme of 25 tomatoes in every bottle, failed to connect with
most consumers. ``What happened was, the mentality was not as
focused on marketing and growing the top line as it is now,''
Jimenez, a recent hire from Conagra Inc., said.
</P>
<P>
   But in October, it selected Burnett to handle the worldwide
brand duties for Heinz ketchup and other condiments.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign, which includes print and television ads, is
intended to graft a personality onto ketchup that will appeal to
teen-agers and young adults _ the people who have grown up without
associating ketchup with a Carly Simon song or a cowboy theme. The
TV ads feature a voice-over seemingly narrated by a teen-ager (the
voice actually belongs to a member of the Burnett team) and an
ironic take on the condiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the Heinz tomato ketchup never comes out,'' the voice
intones, while the camera zeroes in on an almost-empty bottle. ``It
just stays stuck in there and we can only look at it. This part of
the ketchup will never be completely understood. This part of the
ketchup has issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spot refers to Heinz as ``the rude ketchup'' because it
keeps people waiting. Another discusses how Heinz ketchup ``allows
you to make food taste however you want it to taste,'' and goes on,
``Two popular options are ketchuppy, and even more ketchuppy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads are being broadcast in Canada, Albany and Kansas City,
Mo., and may be expanded to the rest of the country, Keller said.
``We're not going national with this until we measure the impact of
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is for the ads to be shown worldwide as well, where
Heinz hopes to get everyone to spend at least half as much on
ketchup as Americans do, which is now about $2 a person each year.
Sales in Thailand are almost at the goal, and Heinz recently
completed a deal with ABC Foods in Indonesia that Jimenez predicted
would bolster its sales in Asia. ``It gives us a springboard to
launch into the region in a very big way,'' he said. ``Ketchup is a
pretty universal taste.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
