</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT HAS NOT BEEN EASY BEING A KNICKS FAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is this the Knicks' year?
</P>
<P>
   Nola Whiteman considered the question for a split second then
laughed. ``The year that they're going to win?'' she asked. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a mean-spirited no or a condescending no. This was
the incredulous no of a veteran Knicks fan who has cared so much,
for so long, that she refuses to let on that she cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody says this is a new season, but it can't be a
new season,'' she said. ``Your history and your experience play a
part in whatever you are on a given day. The Knicks' history and
experience do not lead me to believe with any degree of faith that
we're going to be champions this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nola Whiteman, 60, is not just any spectator. She is the
quintessential Knicks fan: cynical, brutally frank, yet loyal and
forgiving to a fault. Her loyalty has been tested over the years by
a succession of coaches in the post-Red Holzman era: Willis Reed,
Hubie Brown, Bob Hill, Rick Pitino, Stu Jackson, John MacLeod, Pat
Riley, Don Nelson and now Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman and her husband, Herbert, watched the Knicks during
their dark seasons _ 1984-87, when they failed to reach the
playoffs. The couple suffered through four more seasons when the
team did not get past the second round. Then there was the 1993-94
season, when the Knicks lost to Houston in the NBA finals, 4 games
to 3. Since then, the Knicks have gone no further than the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks never make it easy, and they've been like that for
a long time,'' Nola Whiteman said Wednesday afternoon. ``In the
Holzman days you had a greater sense of comfort _ you knew you had
a winning team. Riley almost brought that back, but I don't think
he ever quite accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Herb, a graduate of Columbia's school of engineering,
came home and announced that the family had their first Knicks
season tickets. The team was coming off its first NBA championship.
Patrick Ewing and Jeff Van Gundy were 8 years old. The Whiteman's
daughter, Cheryl, was 7. ``Cheryl used to go down and talk to John
Condon, the longtime Knicks announcer, and speak to the players,''
Whiteman said. ``Walt Frazier was her hero.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next 27 seasons, the Knicks became part of the Whiteman
family tradition: On most Tuesdays and Saturdays, the three would
go to the Garden and cheer for their Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970-71, they sat in the green seats and watched the Knicks
as they were eliminated by the Baltimore Bullets in the Eastern
Conference finals. The Knicks reached the NBA finals the next
season, but lost to the Lakers, 4 games to 1. The next season was
the last great season: the Knicks defeated Los Angeles, 4 games to
1.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman tracks the ebb and flow of the family by their
progression of season tickets. Seven years after he bought the
first set, Herb Whiteman became a vice president of the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York _ the first black vice president at the
Fed.
</P>
<P>
   As the family became more prosperous, they moved closer to the
floor. When Cheryl went off to MIT, they moved behind the basket,
to the red seats _ now purple _ and downsized to two seats.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's season finale against Miami marked the end of
a triumphant return season for Nola Whiteman. Her husband died in
October 1997 at age 61 after a long, heart-related illness. She
often didn't go to the Garden after he died, though when she did
go, the miniature families that sections of fans can become served
as a support network.
</P>
<P>
   Two season-ticket holders made contributions to one of
Whiteman's favorite charities. By coincidence, a mural-sized photo
of her husband cheering with other fans is on the wall of a
corridor in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basketball games have been a source of comfort,'' she
said. ``What the Knicks did for us as a family was give us a common
interest; something you could talk about as a family, something you
could participate in as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she comes to the games with an assortment of close friends.
Her daughter has her own pair of season tickets, and brings her
5-year old daughter to the games. She reacts to the players, the
crowd and the drama like her mother had nearly 30 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   All that is missing are the championships. On Monday, Nola
Whiteman sat and watched the Knicks struggle into the playoffs with
a Ewing-inspired victory over Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the year the Knicks make a championship run? Whiteman
softens her stance ever so slightly and allows for the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think they can manage Miami,'' she said. ``I don't get
as excited as I used to. I wait until the game is over. At one
point there was a greater level of comfort with the Knicks. Now
you're in turmoil with them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
