u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-540&AMP;A     05-05 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUTALITY TRIAL TOLD OF OFFICER'S CONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prosecution witnesses at the trial of four police
officers charged with brutalizing a Haitian immigrant testified
Wednesday that one of the officers had been acting aggressively
during a melee outside a Brooklyn nightclub shortly before the
alleged attack occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony in federal court in Brooklyn appeared intended to
portray the officer, Justin A. Volpe, as a provocative, strutting
figure shortly before prosecutors say that the immigrant, Abner
Louima, was beaten in a police car near the nightclub and then
tortured in a restroom of the 70th Precinct station house in
Flatbush.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that Volpe and the three other officers on trial
beat Louima in the car because they mistakenly believed he had
punched Volpe during the melee. The prosecution has also charged
that Volpe and one of the other three officers later tortured
Louima in the restroom by shoving part of a broken broomstick into
his rectum and then into his mouth, severely injuring him.
</P>
<P>
   Other prosecution witnesses testified that when they saw Louima
in the nightclub in the hours before he was arrested, he did not
appear to be injured or in pain and he did not complain of any
injuries or pain. Those witnesses appeared to be intended to
counter the suggestion by Volpe's lawyer in his opening statement
on Tuesday that Louima had received his internal juries not from an
assault by police officers, but in an act of consensual sex with
another man before he had come into contact with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, the subject of one of the most explosive and racially
sensitive cases of purported police brutality in New York City in
recent years _ he is black and the accused officers are white _ is
expected to testify Thursday, although legal wrangling could delay
his appearance on the stand. On Wednesday, one of his lawyers
served papers on the lawyers representing the police officers,
seeking to circumscribe their questioning of Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The papers were served under seal, making them confidential, and
neither the lawyers for the officers nor Louima's lawyer, Sanford
A. Rubenstein, would discuss them. For the restrictions to be
enforced, the judge at the trial, Eugene H. Nickerson, would have
to rule that Louima enjoys a legal privilege that permits
questioning of him to be restricted as requested.
</P>
<P>
   The officers' lawyers have indicated interest in questioning
Louima about what they claim is his lawyers' involvement in
preparing him for his testimony, and it is possible that his
lawyers are seeking to preclude questions on that topic on the
ground of lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, 32, was working as a security guard at a sewage
treatment plant at the time of his arrest in the street brawl in
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers are all charged with violating his civil
rights by beating him in the police car after his arrest. In
addition to Volpe, they are Officers Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder
and Thomas Wiese.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Volpe is charged with using the stick on Louima in
the station house restroom and Schwarz is charged with holding him
down. A sergeant, Michael Bellomo, is charged with trying to cover
up the alleged beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   All five deny the charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Wednesday's testimony, one of the witnesses, Ian Russell, who
in 1997 was a member of Phantoms, a Haitian band that was playing
at the nightclub near where the melee took place, said he saw Volpe
push a man to the ground from behind as a large group of club
patrons were on the sidewalk outside.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said that one man ``seemed to be gesticulating to the
officers'' but ``didn't seem to be making any sort of threatening
gestures.'' Russell said Volpe then shoved the man to the ground,
``puffed out his chest, brushed back his hair and walked back to
the other officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, sought to undermine
Russell's credibility by citing contradictions between his
testimony Wednesday and what he had told investigators in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like police officers, do you?'' the lawyer asked
after Russell had admitted he had cursed the officers after he saw
the man pushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true at all,'' Russell replied.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, John Rejouis, a New York City correction
officer, testified that Volpe had pushed him to the ground after
Rejouis had tried to get to his car, and then had made motions as
if he daring Rejouis to fight him.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg got Rejouis to admit he had had five or six drinks of
``straight rum'' in the hours before this happened, and suggested
he had been too drunk to know what had happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
