<SLUG> BC-NY-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER OFFICERS' INDICTMENT IN DIALLO CASE, ARRESTS DROP IN NEW YORK
CITY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arrests have fallen sharply in New York City in the
month since four officers were indicted in the fatal shooting of
Amadou Diallo, prompting concern among some officials about a
possible work slowdown by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics released Wednesday by the Police
Department, the number of people arrested in April fell to 30,134,
from 35,813 in March, a 14 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials attributed the decline in arrests to fewer
crimes being reported. They noted that complaints of crime were
down 12 percent in the first four months of this year compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fewer customers,'' said John Haviken, who heads the
department's Criminal Justice Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But April's drop-off was considerably more pronounced than in
previous months, and crime rates have been falling for years even
as the number of arrests has risen. That has some law enforcement
officials searching for other explanations for April's decline,
including the possibility of fallout from the death of Diallo, an
unarmed African immigrant who died three months ago in a hail of
police bullets.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, four officers were indicted on second-degree murder
charges in Diallo's death, prompting an angry response from
hundreds of police officers. Two weeks later, James Savage, the
president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, the city's
largest police union, urged officers to use ``maximum discretion''
when citing people for minor offenses.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city's crackdown on minor violations like drinking
alcohol in public had harmed relations between the police and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it could be a slowdown,'' said one law
enforcement official.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Savage said he knew of no organized
effort to cut back on arrests, but he suggested that the decrease
might be related to low morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a morale problem out there in the precincts,'' Savage
said. ``I feel their anger, their mistrust of the city
administration. With morale down, it might affect productivity in a
negative way. Maybe they're not as anxious to go out there after
the petty offenders just for the sake of numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Reppetto, head of the Citizen's Crime Commission, said he
doubted that low morale or instructions from union leaders would
drive arrest rates in New York City. ``I think most police follow
the law and the directives of the department regardless of how they
feel,'' he said, ``and I don't know how much effect a union head
can have.''
</P>
<P>
   William J. Bratton, a former police commissioner under Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, said that if the decline in arrests was the
result of a slowdown by disgruntled officers, the numbers should
bounce back as tempers ease.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Bratton said, last month's falloff in arrests could
be an early indication of a broader trend toward fewer arrests. He
said he had long predicted that arrests would inevitably fall as
the city became a more orderly place. He calls it the ``peacetime
dividend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I go around the city, I just don't see the kind of activity
that would draw a police officer's attention,'' Bratton said. ``At
some point in time, arrests are going to come down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
