<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEFEATS CLINTON PROPOSALS TO OVERHAUL BANKS   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation to overhaul the nation's banking system
was significantly set back Wednesday after the Senate defeated two
measures endorsed by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Democrats predicted the votes would make it far more
difficult to enact a law to eliminate the Depression-era laws that
have made it difficult for banks, securities firms and insurance
companies to compete against one another. Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
who is the chief sponsor of the bill, threatened to pull his
measure from the floor if the Senate adopted an amendment sponsored
by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., that would restore the Treasury
Department's authority to regulate banks. Republicans want the
Federal Reserve to have that regulatory authority.
</P>
<P>
   On a straight party vote of 54-to-43, the Republicans defeated a
substitute bill sponsored by the minority leader, Tom Daschle of
South Dakota, and Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, the ranking
Democrat on the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also defeated an amendment that would have eliminated
from the Republican legislation some of the provisions most
objectionable to the White House and Senate Democrats. Those
provisions would sharply limit the Community Reinvestment Act, a
1977 law that encourages lending to minorities, farmers and others
who have historically had little access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights groups criticized the votes as significant
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extreme measure of gutting the Community Reinvestment Act
accentuates the unfortunate partisan nature of this Congress,''
said Wade Henderson, executive director of the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle and Sarbanes' alternative bill closely resembled one
jointly sponsored by Democrats and Republicans that failed last
year after running into opposition from Gramm, who is now the
chairman of the banking committee.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative measure, like the one sponsored by Gramm, would
remove barriers put in place by the Depression-era Glass-Steagle
Act to separate banks, insurance companies and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   But there are several big differences between the bills that
have divided the lawmakers largely along partisan lines. The
Democratic measure would have retained a significant role for the
Treasury Department in regulating the growing number of financial
conglomerates, while the Republican version would give a leading
role largely to the Federal Reserve. The Democratic measure would
also have restricted the ability of commercial conglomerates from
entering into the banking business.
</P>
<P>
   The Gramm measure would make it more difficult for challenges to
the lending records of banks to be raised under the Community
Reinvestment Act. It would also exempt some 4,000 smaller
institutions from the Act's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted in 1977 to combat the banking practice of
``red-lining,'' or discriminating against poorer and minority
neighborhoods, the Community Reinvestment Act has become a central
battle ground in the new legislation. Many lobbyists say that if an
agreement can be reached on the Community Reinvestment Act, then
Congress will be able to complete landmark legislation on the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders in the Senate contend that the Republican
legislation will be doomed unless Gramm eliminates the Community
Reinvestment Act provisions from the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure to proceed on a bipartisan track has placed this
bill in unnecessary risk,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic amendment to strip the provisions and expand the
application of the act to some financial conglomerates failed on a
vote of 52 to 45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
