A6028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-CARTER-NYT &LR;      05-05 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAE BERTHA CARTER, MOTHER WHO DEFIED SEGREGATION LAW, DIES AT 76  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mae Bertha Carter, who defied gunfire and the loss of employment
to send her children to previously all-white public schools in
Mississippi, eventually winning a legal battle that confirmed their
right to be there, died on April 28 at her home in Drew, Miss. She
was 76.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said Francine E. Cheeks, a spokeswoman for
the American Friends Service Committee in Philadelphia, a Quaker
organization that supported Ms. Carter and many other black
families in the civil rights struggle of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter was born on Jan. 13, 1923, in Sunflower County, Miss.
She married Matthew Carter in 1939, and the couple became
sharecroppers, raising 25 acres of cotton and sharing the income
with the landowners, on Pemble Plantation, near Drew.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1965, just after the Carters had enrolled 7 of
their 13 children in local white schools, the owner of the
plantation told them to withdraw the children, saying they would
receive a better education in a black school.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carter's response was to take an old phonograph onto the
porch and play a recording of a speech by President John F. Kennedy
on civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I birthed those children and bore the pain,'' she later told
her husband. Referring to the plantation owner, she said, ``He
cannot tell me what to do about my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Public schools throughout Mississippi were desegregated by the
Civil Rights Act of 1964, but the state enacted what it called a
freedom-of-choice law and used it to intimidate blacks into
remaining at inferior black schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Carters, however, resolutely kept their children in the
once-segregated white schools, even though their house was once
riddled with bullets in the middle of the night and they were
eventually evicted, losing their income and their house.
</P>
<P>
   From 1965 to 1968, the Carters were the only black family to
keep their children in the county's schools.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 the Carters and Marian Wright Edelman, a lawyer with the
NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund Inc., sued the Drew school
district, challenging the state freedom-of-choice law. They won the
suit in 1969, removing the last legal hurdle to the desegregation
of Mississippi's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, eight of the Carter's children graduated from what
had been all-white schools in Sunflower County; five older children
graduated from local black schools. Eleven also graduated from
college _ seven from the once-segregated University of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Carter family's battle was recounted in a book,
``Silver Rights'' (Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill, 1995) by
Constance Curry, a field worker with the American Friends Service
Committee in 1966, who worked closely with the family. The title is
an old rural-black colloquial abridgment, noted by the novelist
Alice Walker, of the phrase ``civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter's husband, Matthew, died in 1988. She is survived by
five sons, Carl, of Columbus, Miss., Stanley, of Tulsa, Okla.,
Larry, of Hampton, Va., John, of Lake Charles, La., and Matthew
Jr., of Conway, Ark.; eight daughters, Beverly Carter of Drew,
Naomi Granberry of Cleveland, Miss., Pearl Owen and Deborah Smith,
both of Oxford, Miss., Gloria Dickenson of Battle Creek, Mich.,
Ruth Whittle and Bertha Huckleby, both of Toledo, Ohio, and Edna
Threats of Kansas City, Kan., 35 grandchildren and 36
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACYS-SPINOFF-LADN     05-05 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACYS-SPINOFF-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACY'S SPINOFF SOUSON AIMS AT IMPULSE MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Tapping into one of the hottest areas in
retailing today, Macy's department store is spinning off a new
chain of stores specializing in beauty products, candles and other
``impulse'' merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern California testing ground for the new concept --
called Souson: A Little Something Extra from Macy's -- is the
Westfield Shoppingtown Topanga Plaza in Canoga Park in the city's
suburban San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The local store, expected to open in early June, will be Macy's
second Souson. The first opened April 30 in San Jose, said Betty
Krogh, a spokeswoman for Macy's West in San Francisco. Others could
follow, depending on how well the originals perform.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's doesn't have a department store in Topanga Plaza, but it
does have one in the nearby Westfield Shoppingtown Promenade in
Woodland Hills. Both malls are owned by Los Angeles-based real
estate investment trust Westfield America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Topanga Plaza) has a great reputation in the Valley and
we don't have representation there,'' Krogh said. ``I'm a Valley
Girl and used to go to that mall on the bus all the time. It's a
great mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Souson should ``seduce'' mall customers in the same way that
they're lured by impulse items such as cosmetics and fragrances as
they make their way through Macy's aisles, Krogh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impulsive,'' Krogh said. ``You're walking and you have an
opportunity to pass the shop and you say: This is a great new shop,
I'm going to walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the San Jose store, the local 4,500-square-foot Souson will
carry a broad line of makeup and fragrances, as well as related
products such as cosmetics bags, brushes, applicators, potpourri
and candles, according to officials with Cincinnati-based Federated
Department Stores, which owns Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetics will include Shiseido, Elizabeth Arden, Christian Dior
and Benefit. Souson will also carry British hairstylist Charles
Worthington's line of hair-care products.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Souson merchandise isn't sold in Macy's. This
includes the Worthington line -- for the time being, at least,
Krogh said -- some decorative items, candles, hair ornaments and
brushes.
</P>
<P>
   The market for decorative items, candles and the like has heated
up of late, and stores specializing in this merchandise are
springing up everywhere, said Jackie Fernandez, director of the
retail services group for accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Candle retailers such as Illuminations and the Yankee Candle
Co., for example, have opened or plan to open outlets in the
Topanga Plaza and Northridge Fashion Center, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Given enough product differentiation, Macy's doesn't run the
risk of competing against itself, Fernandez said. And if the price
point is low enough, Souson should compete well against similar
stores such as Bath &AMP; Body Works.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Macy's name recognition is sure to help, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good move (and) I think they've got the
know-how to make this concept work well,'' Fernandez said. ``It's
an area of the retail industry that's hot. People are interested in
candles and home decoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good area to hop into,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
