<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-RELIEF     05-05 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-RELIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL:THE POLITICS OF HURRICANE RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, May 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victims of Hurricane Mitch, which ravaged Central America
six months ago, are still waiting for $600 million in promised
humanitarian aid from the United States. Congress seems willing to
make them wait forever. The money is stalled in a partisan fight
that has nothing to do with the merits of helping Honduras,
Nicaragua and other countries hit by the storm and other natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle in Congress is over compensating budget cuts, or
``offsets'' in Washington jargon. The aid bill passed both the
House and Senate accompanied by cuts in valuable programs _ to help
dispose of uranium and plutonium in Russia, to protect embassies
from terrorism and provide relief for domestic disasters, for
example. The administration has reasonably said it will veto a bill
containing these measures, and argues _ correctly _ that the budget
rules do not require balancing cuts in emergency aid such as this.
</P>
<P>
   Congress exposed the hollowness of its call for fiscal
responsibility by tacking projects onto the bill such as aid to
steel and oil companies. By contrast, an emergency spending bill to
pay for humanitarian relief and military expenses in Kosovo that
will be voted on Thursday in the House will contain no compensating
cuts. Indeed, it will include $7 billion in extra defense spending
that the Pentagon did not request.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane aid package contains money to reimburse the
Pentagon for its role in relief efforts after the hurricane, and
some to the Immigration Service for detention of illegal aliens.
But $600 million would go to Central America, with additional money
to the Caribbean nations struck by Hurricane Georges, and to
Colombia for earthquake relief. In Central America a new planting
season is arriving, and money is needed for seeds and agricultural
credits. Holding these funds hostage to a political squabble is
shameful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506-C     05-05 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON RALLIES U.S. TROOPS, KEEPS DIPLOMACY IRON IN FIRE IN
WAKE OF APACHE CRASH
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-APACHES-0506; KOSOVO-TROOPS-0506.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, Germany _ President Clinton rallied U.S.
forces participating in NATO's air war against Yugoslavia on
Wednesday, but the day was marred by a helicopter crash that killed
two American pilots, the first allied fatalities associated with
the six-week-old campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with NATO commanders, U.S. troops and three
American soldiers released Sunday from Yugoslav captivity, Clinton
was scheduled to visit Thursday with ethnic Albanian refugees and
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, part of the national
security entourage accompanying Clinton, was to peel off Thursday
to meet in Bonn with her Russian and European counterparts in what
could be a pivotal moment in the effort to broker peace in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting will group foreign ministers from the
so-called Group of Eight, or G-8. Those countries are the United
States, Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is insisting that Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president
of Yugoslavia, agree to a number of conditions, including the
admission of a heavily-armed NATO-led peacekeeping force into
Kosovo, before any halt in bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has so far publicly rejected that demand, saying that
he would accept only a lightly-armed civilian monitoring regime
under the auspices of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that Russia -- which has close
historical and diplomatic ties to Yugoslavia -- might be near
enough to accepting the NATO position to agree to a joint statement
to that affect on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Such a declaration would mark a major -- and perhaps decisive --
move forward in the search for a diplomatic solution to the
conflict. It would not necessarily end it right away, however,
because it is Milosevic, not Moscow, that ultimately must agree.
</P>
<P>
   In a move likely to be interpreted in Belgrade as a goodwill
gesture, Defense Secretary William Cohen said he was poised to
recommend that Clinton order the release -- perhaps in the coming
days -- of two Yugoslav soldiers held in U.S. custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``At an appropriate time, I would recommend that,'' Cohen told
reporters. ``I would expect within a relatively short period of
time that we could see their release.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Yugoslav soldiers -- each a private in his early 20s --
were captured by guerilla fighters belonging to the Kosovo
Liberation Army, or KLA, an ethnic Albanian rebel group that
supports independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA troops turned the captives over to the government of
Albania, which then placed them in the custody of U.S. military
personnel there.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said it was possible that
the Yugoslav captives could be turned over to a third country -- he
mentioned Sweden as a possibility -- for processing back to
Yugoslavia. The United States and Yugoslavia broke off formal
diplomatic relations after the NATO air strikes commenced March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure of their status and make sure that the
International Committee of the Red Cross has an opportunity to see
them, interview them and then complete some administrative work.''
</P>
<P>
   That process, Cohen said, could take several days.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen denied any link between the Yugoslav prisoners and the
Americans released in Belgrade last weekend. Both moves come,
however, amid mounting indications that both NATO and Milosevic are
searching for a diplomatic way out of a conflict that entered its
seventh inconclusive week with attacks across Yugoslavia early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied military officials told Clinton that NATO air
strikes are hitting hard at Yugoslav forces across the embattled
province of Kosovo, where alliance warplanes are having increasing
success hunting down individual tanks, artillery batteries and
fielded forces and destroying them on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite deteriorating weather, alliance pilots destroyed 40 such
targets in strikes late Tuesday and early Wednesday, NATO officials
said, promising that the pressure on Yugoslav forces in the field
would mount further in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they move, when they're in the open, they're seen. And
when they're seen, they're hit. And when they're hit, they're
killed,'' said NATO's supreme commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley
Clark. ``We're going to pin them down, close them out and take them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough rhetoric, Clark conceded that, after 15,000
sorties, nearly one-third of which were strike missions, NATO has
yet to halt the military onslaught that has driven an estimated 1.5
million ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands, still, paramilitary thugs committing
murder and mayhem on the ground in Kosovo,'' Clark told reporters
at a press conference at Spangdahlem Air Base. U.S. pilots have
been flying F-16 fighter-bomber and F-117 stealth bomber missions
into the skies over the Yugoslav state of Serbia, of which Kosovo
is a part, from the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask so much of you, and you never let us down,'' Clinton
said to a crowd of perhaps 2,500 Air Force personnel and their
families who gathered beneath a cavernous hanger. Behind the dais
where Clinton spoke stood a steely grey F-16 and an American flag
two stories high. ``Night after night, to Serbia, punching through
enemy defenses, putting ordinance on target, returning home to
debrief, rest and then do it all over again. That takes courage and
skill and a lot of support that we must never take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit gave troops a boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President coming to see us, means that what we're doing
here is really important,'' said Air Force Staff Sgt. Thomas Abram,
32, of Milwaukee, a crew chief in charge of keeping F-16s
flightworthy. ``It keeps moral up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was haunted by a grim reminder of the dangers
pilots face.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, near the Kosovo border, two American pilots were
killed when the Apache attack helicopter they were flying crashed
during night training exercises in support of Operation Allied
Force.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, which occurred when the pilots were practicing
tree-top level attack maneuvers over tricky terrain, was the second
such crash since the Apaches deployed to Albania in mid-April. The
crew of the two-seat Apache that crashed last week survived with
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon identified the pilots killed early Wednesday as
Chief Warrant Officer David A. Gibbs, 38, from Massillon, Ohio, and
Chief Warrant Officer Kevin Reichert, 28, of Chetek, Wis. They were
members of the Germany-based 6th Cavalry Regiment, which arrived
last month.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash was under investigation. The training,
however, involved obvious hazards: streaking just above the
treetops through the blackness of night over hilly terrain at
speeds that can top 180 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost two brave Americans,'' Clinton said of the pilots.
``And today we grieve with their families and pray for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At this sprawling base of U.S. Air Force cargo aircraft, which
have been flying humanitarian aid missions to provide assistance to
refugees in camps along Kosovo's border, Clinton shared a happier
moment with three U.S. soldiers who were released last Sunday from
a month of captivity in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke privately and separately with each of the three --
Spec. Steven M. Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas., Staff Sgt.
Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt. Christopher
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich. -- and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of them,'' Clinton told reporters during a photo op
with the freed troops. ``I'm just glad to have these people home --
halfway home anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air campaign entered its seventh week, Clark said he
expects to add some 250 U.S. warplanes to the operation in the
coming weeks. That would raise to nearly 1,000 the number of attack
and support aircraft in the NATO armada.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has asked for the additional strike craft, refueling
tankers and reconnaissance planes as part of a larger request for
about 300 planes. About 40 have been provided and Clark has been
working with the governments of Hungary, Bulgaria and other Balkan
nations to secure bases for the additional aircraft or permission
to overfly those countries' air space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the president that everything is on track,'' Clark
said. ``We expect the full flow of assets within the next 30
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has agreed to allow some NATO aircraft to fly missions
from its bases. On Tuesday Bulgaria's parliament voted to allow
NATO planes to fly in its air space. Those developments would give
U.S. and allied pilots new routes of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0517 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506-C     05-05 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
