</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air campaign entered its seventh week, Clark said he
expects to add some 250 U.S. warplanes to the operation in the
coming weeks. That would raise to nearly 1,000 the number of attack
and support aircraft in the NATO armada.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has asked for the additional strike craft, refueling
tankers and reconnaissance planes as part of a larger request for
about 300 planes. About 40 have been provided and Clark has been
working with the governments of Hungary, Bulgaria and other Balkan
nations to secure bases for the additional aircraft or permission
to overfly those countries' air space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the president that everything is on track,'' Clark
said. ``We expect the full flow of assets within the next 30
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has agreed to allow some NATO aircraft to fly missions
from its bases. On Tuesday Bulgaria's parliament voted to allow
NATO planes to fly in its air space. Those developments would give
U.S. and allied pilots new routes of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
