A6035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BOXING-NYT &LR;      05-05 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIXING THE FIGHT GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, May 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outrageous judges' decision in March's heavyweight title
fight between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis embarrassed New
York's politicians. They had hoped for a fight that would establish
an undisputed heavyweight champion and lead to a rebirth of
big-time boxing in the state. What they got was a verdict that
turned a clear victory for Lewis into a draw. Wednesday two of
these officials, Gov. George Pataki and Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer, answered with modest reforms and suggestions for bigger
changes that could weaken the grip of boxing's monopolists.
</P>
<P>
   One change will give the state athletic commission final say
over the selection of the judges in all title bouts. Under current
procedures, judges are in effect chosen by boxing's three ratings
organizations. Another reform will require judges to disclose
personal financial information to the commission before a fight.
Both reforms flow directly from questions raised about the only
judge who actually scored the fight for Holyfield, Eugenia
Williams. Mrs. Williams was chosen by the International Boxing
Federation, whose champion happens to be Holyfield. The IBF also
has close ties to Don King, who owns Holyfield's contract and
naturally stood to benefit by a decision that allowed Holyfield to
preserve his share of the championship. A few days after the fight
it was disclosed that Mrs. Williams had declared personal
bankruptcy before the bout. Mrs. Williams has denied that she was
offered financial help to influence her verdict. Even so, the steps
announced Wednesday will help insure that judges are not
compromised in future bouts.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials also pledged to fight for other reforms. One
intriguing idea would establish an independent boxing poll similar
to the college football polls. Boxers are now ranked by the three
ratings organizations, which routinely manipulate the rankings to
generate legitimacy for fights that should never occur, just to
guarantee a fat payday for favored promoters.
</P>
<P>
   What boxing really needs is some sort of national regulation, so
that shady promoters cannot simply shift their fights to states
with more lenient rules. A bill sponsored by Sen. John McCain would
help meet that need. But for now, it is gratifying to see New York
taking tangible steps to clean up a dishonest sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
