<HEADLINE>
CLAIRVOYANT BUFFY HOLDS HER FIRE  
 ANCHOR AWAY: DOWNS SIGNS OFF 
EX-PRESIDENT DOLE KEEPS A PROMISE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Kan., Ohio)  (rk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with YASMIN NAMINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Will WB, Time Warner's youth-oriented network, which
postponed last week's episode of ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer''
because it seemed to be setting the stage for a high school rampage
so soon after the one in Littleton, Colo., think twice about the
season finale?
</P>
<P>
   The episode not shown last week featured the clairvoyant title
character, played by Sarah Michelle Gellar, reading her high school
classmates' minds. She realized that someone was thinking about
killing everyone in school _ everyone, that is, except the
vampires. (Remember, guns don't kill vampires, vampire slayers do,
but only with weapons like crossbows that do not discharge
bullets.)
</P>
<P>
   In the two-part finale, scheduled to be broadcast in a couple of
weeks at the height of the May ratings sweeps, a cataclysmic
``ascension'' takes place on graduation day, said someone who saw
the outline for the episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the high school students arm themselves in
anticipation of the `ascension,''' he said. ``It's 100 percent in
the realm of fantasy, but it's still high school students with
weapons. Of course, there's a huge distinction between this and the
catastrophe at Columbine. I don't recall anything in the outline
that mentioned semiautomatics or pipe bombs, but attendant to the
ascension there is a lot of carnage.''
</P>
<P>
   No decision about the episode has been made, a WB spokesman
said. ``It's something that we're looking at,'' he said. ``Last
week, it was just too close, and we're too cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Away: Downs Signs Off &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years ago, the year that Hollywood released ``The Wizard
of Oz,'' `` Smith Goes to Washington'' and ``Gone With the Wind,''
18-year-old Hugh Downs signed on as a staff announcer at WLOK-AM in
Lima, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he switched to a medium in which he was seen as well
as heard. He was Jack Paar's announcer on ``Tonight'' from 1957 to
1962, the host of the game show ``Concentration'' and a host of
``Today'' from 1962 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, ABC News said that Downs, 78, was leaving
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for me to move on,'' he said, adding that he was
planning something ``in the context of new media.'' He did not say
what. Leaving ABC News, he said, would let him do things that ``I
cannot do under a network news policy, a policy with which I
agree.'' Meaning, make commercials? ``Yes, that kind of thing,'' he
said, ``and making speeches and going on other venues like cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs, who has been an anchor on the ABC News magazine ``20/20''
for 21 years, told network officials some time ago that he was not
interested in negotiating a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous about that,'' he said. ``I didn't want
them to go through some embarrassing thing of offering more money,
because it wasn't about money, and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   His current contract expires in October. He will continue to
appear on ``20/20'' until then.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-President Dole Keeps a Promise &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is not in Kansas anymore. Wednesday, Mrs. Dole,
the former president of the American Red Cross who wants to be
president of a somewhat larger outfit, was in Manhattan, where she
was the guest of honor at a lunch sponsored by The Ladies' Home
Journal. She was far from her home state, where tornadoes left a
trail of devastation earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your life goes on,'' she said in the receiving line. ``I have
a commitment to be here and I couldn't cancel this commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, she reached across Libby Pataki, wife of New
York Gov. George Pataki, and added, ``If I didn't have this
commitment, of course I'd be in Kansas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
