u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-401K-SWITCH-SUIT-NYT &LR;      05-05 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-401K-SWITCH-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  
 FIRST UNION CORP. IS SUED OVER 401(k) SWITCH  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John T.H. Carpenter, a loan officer with Signet Bank in Virginia
Beach, Va., put his 401(k) savings into three investments that
turned in sizzling performances in recent years. So when he quit in
November 1997, a week before First Union Corp. took over Signet, he
left those investments in place.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Carpenter found that First Union had replaced
his investments with First Union brand mutual funds, which would be
much less profitable. And, he learned, First Union charges full
fees to its own employees' accounts, though it often waives
administrative fees for large 401(k) plans it administers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have made $50,000 in those few months from just one of
my investments,'' he said, referring to Capital One Financial, the
credit card company spun off from Signet. Instead, he earned about
5 percent annually because those proceeds were invested in the
First Union Stable Value fund, one of nine funds offered to
employees for 401(k)'s.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter and eight other participants in the Signet plan
Wednesday sued First Union, the nation's sixth-largest bank, saying
5,000 former Signet workers would have $150 million more today if
First Union had not moved $100 million to its own mutual funds,
none of which have performed nearly as well as the three
investments they were forced to leave: the Vanguard Index 500 fund,
the American Century Ultra fund and shares of Capital One.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Richmond, contends
that First Union violated the terms of the Signet plan, did not
notify people like Carpenter that they could withdraw their money
and breached its duty of loyalty to those workers so that it could
collect more fee income.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for First Union, Ken Darby, said it had no comment
on the litigation. The company has told complaining workers,
however, that it sent them notification letters before the change.
</P>
<P>
   More than 32 million workers now save through 401(k)-type plans,
investing about $2 billion a week. The case raises issues that
could affect anyone whose employer merges with another company that
has different 401(k) investment options.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement law experts said Wednesday that the case could become
one of the most significant brought in the 25 years since Congress
enacted the Employee Retirement Income Security Act, or Erisa.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cummings, a Washington lawyer who represents companies,
said there would be no case had First Union replaced the Signet
investments with funds it does not own. And he said a bank could
invest 401(k) money in its own mutual funds under some
circumstances. ``This case is going to depend on whether there are
smoking pistols that show that these First Union guys had some
ulterior motive'' like collecting fees by moving the investment to
the bank's own mutual funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gordon, a Washington retirement lawyer who represents
workers, said that ``switching employees of an acquired company
whole hog into proprietary funds is extremely troublesome and,
regardless of the technicalities under Erisa, is an obnoxious
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lieder and Eli Gootesdiener, the Washington lawyers who
filed the case, said they would show that First Union's motive in
changing the investments was increasing its fee income.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said he complained in May 1998 that he was never told
that his investments would be sold. He said First Union then sent
him a copy of the notice it said it had mailed him and the address
to which it had been mailed. ``The address First Union listed was a
house that when they say the notice was sent had not been built
yet,'' he said of the house, where he now lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
