<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-DEJA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING MEMORIES SHAPE RESPONSE TO NEW TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 VU-WRITETHRU-TEX 
EDS: Changes date of Oklahoma City bombing to 1995 sted 1994. (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The question nagged at rescue workers and
government officials as they spent the first grueling hours
throwing blankets over victims and maneuvering around crackling
power lines to survey the tornado's massive damage.
</P>
<P>
   How could such destruction visit Oklahoma City again?
</P>
<P>
   Barely four years after a bomb devastated downtown Oklahoma City
in the country's deadliest terrorist attack, many people have found
themselves facing the same shocking realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few towns have seen anything as horrific as this,'' Gov. Frank
Keating said Wednesday, his shoes caked with mud as he talked with
dozens of the newly homeless at the First Baptist Church of Moore.
``But we've done it before and will do it again. We'll dig
ourselves out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City addressed the bombing tragedy in several ways that
could ultimately speed emotional and financial recovery from the
tornadoes that left thousands homeless, more than 500 injured and
at least 38 dead this week, community leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is difficult to measure, many city leaders say a
powerful community spirit bred partly from the April 19, 1995,
bombing of the Murrah Building is carrying Oklahoma City through
its latest nightmare. That's evident in the mobilization of
thousands of volunteers and the spontaneous acts of giving this
week, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Alliances that grew out of the bombing's aftermath are also at
work. The state of Oklahoma and nonprofit groups created the
Resource Committee, to steers donations to families affected by the
bombing who can't afford to put their children through college.
That group plans to help the tornado victims as well, Keating said.
</P>
<P>
   And new disaster relief strategies, such as the American Red
Cross' methods of dispatching numerous counseling teams to ease the
mental anguish of victims and rescue workers, were on display in
Moore, one of the hardest-hit suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, at least 20 counselors were trudging through ruined
neighborhoods in Moore and creating ``private spaces'' at shelters
for immediate therapy. More counselors are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger counselor volunteer base we're using today came out
of the bombing,'' said Timothy Sartorius, chief executive officer
of the Central Oklahoma Chapter of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Said John Clizbe, vice president of the National Red Cross, who
helped respond to the bombing: ``That event took the stigma out of
counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Federal Emergency Management Agency said
Wednesday that they have expanded use of search and rescue teams,
which primarily use dogs to sniff out victims, because they were so
effective after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bombing exacted a huge toll on human lives, many
people were talking Wednesday about something powerful that endured
from that disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Keating calls it ``extreme outpourings of goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred businesses have pledged money or support.
Reports are rampant about residents catching sight of area relief
workers in public and hastily writing checks to help the effort.
People have jammed the highways to approach churches and nonprofit
groups with donations.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous hotels, such as the Marriott Hotel Corp., are donating
temporary shelter space and free phone lines for long-distance
calls to relatives. Universities are donating dormitory rooms. The
stories go on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the bombing tragedy, people are grouping fast,''
said the Rev. Ronnie Harrison of the Heartland Harvest Church in
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, as he was after the bombing, has been a continuous
fixture at disaster relief scenes this week, reaching out to the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, families at a Red Cross station held plastic bags
full of diapers and food as they crowded around the governor to
tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   One family said their home had been replaced by a 30-foot-high
stack of debris. They said they don't know how the pile can ever be
removed. Another family recalled watching as its cars blew into the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Keating said that insurance companies and federal aid will help
with some of the problems. He said he will organize a meeting of
area mayors to gauge progress in the rescue effort and to determine
``where to go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These things help bring us together. People coming together
have helped stitch this city together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Parrish, missions minister with the First Baptist Church of
Moore, said Oklahoma City residents are obviously dealing with many
of the same horrors that they faced after the bombing. They will
need to express their pain in different ways, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the community can persevere by putting its trust in a
higher power, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an act of faith,'' he said. ``We let people get angry and
you take the anger and find trust in God.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
