<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ARTIST-NIGHTSHIFT-     05-05 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTIST-NIGHTSHIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPHIC VISION: ART FOR PEOPLE, NOT ARTISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are a million stories in the naked city, but if
they involve the night workers who clean the toilets and make the
subways run on time, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The little drama of the aspiring comic book artist who works as
a topless dancer and loses her wallet with the rent money: so what?
</P>
<P>
   The subway worker who works the graveyard shift and finds solace
in the company of rats: who wants to read about him?
</P>
<P>
   But no! In a project called ``The Invisible City,'' the stories
of some of the night shift workers who make the city run, told in
comic book panels, will be on placards throughout the subways until
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Using their own computer program _ ZAP! or perhaps we should
say, CLICK! _ which transforms photos to comic illustrations, two
artists, Christopher J. Sperandio, who lives in Manhattan, and
Simon Grennan, who lives in England, have made the workers comic
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   How did the artists get the idea?
</P>
<P>
   Frame One: Sperandio, 35, sitting in the Manhattan office of the
Public Art Fund, because he's self-conscious about the studio
apartment he shares with his wife. Black T-shirt, black shirt,
black sports jacket, buttoned up. (GADZOOKS! The sign of a fellow
self-conscious about his weight? Hair a downtown mix of peroxide
blond and brown. Box of Pepperidge Farm cookies, plateless,
unadorned, real, furnished by artist, on the table. Artist will eat
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been working as a graphic artist at one of those desks
in a cubicle farm in a corporate office. I don't want to name them
because I don't want to plug them.''
</P>
<P>
   Frame Two, noir office, the artist as drone:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working from noon to 8, kind of a bridge person between
the day people and the night people, and I realized that they were
completely oblivious of one another, though they shared the same
space. So in the morning, it would be: `Why is the mouse pad over
here?' The day person would be right-handed but the night person
left-handed, and they would not know.''
</P>
<P>
   Frame Three, top of the artist's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hair? I had always wanted to dye it and now I've started
losing it, so I've dyed it all these different colors in the last
few months. I've been red, black, blond, now crazy, for a while
Chromatique _ that's this bright, bright red.''
</P>
<P>
   There are artists who feel they must be true to their vision,
the public be dashed. This has never been the case of Sperandio,
raised in the town of Kingwood, W.Va., whose father worked as a
lineman for the power company and whose mother worked in the
unemployment office.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sperandio, who put himself through college with scholarships
and construction work, and met Grennan while they were doing
graduate work at the University of Illinois in Chicago, felt art
should be relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon and I were very dissatisfied with the role of the
artist,'' says Sperandio, who, while his heart is with the workers,
talks about art theory till you turn bright, bright blue. ``I had
trouble reconciling my working-class background with the nature of
contemporary art. Essentially, they're class issues, issues about
the social role of the artist. Like, remember Tilted Arc, the Serra
sculpture at Federal Plaza?''
</P>
<P>
   (Comic book cue, Frame One: A 120-foot long, 12-foot high slab
of curved steel, in lower Manhattan. Next Frame: Federal Plaza
without the steel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of controversy,'' Sperandio continues, ``and
eventually it was removed. We found it to be a failure of the
artist rather than the public. There was a gulf of understanding
between what he was doing and the people who were trying to enjoy
their lunch hour. It happened in '81, and had a big influence on
Simon and me. It showed us how not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   A little smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teachers felt we were very reactionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The projects of Sperandio and Grennan have included
collaborating with chocolate workers on the design of a chocolate
bar wrapping (``We're kind of known in the art world for that''),
as well as a number of comic books, including ``Life in Prison,''
for which Sperandio interviewed his brother after his brother had
become ``drunk as a skunk'' &UR;  &LR; and landed in the county jail. There
are also a limited number of ``Invisible City'' comic books
available, free, from the Public Art Fund, which paid for the
project. The artists each got $2,000, which Sperandio estimates
comes to about 25 cents an hour, though he professes not to care.
</P>
<P>
   The people's art thing, again:
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics are good because so many people can get to the work.''
Final frames: The light is fading in the offices of the Public Art
Fund. Sperandio, after saying that he keeps his distance from the
New York art scene because it is ``a perilous place,'' is
explaining why it is so important to him to do good work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father died the middle of my sophomore year in school. Lung
cancer. He smoked all his life. I had the opportunity to visit him
at the end, but I was getting my final portfolio together at
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Next frame:
</P>
<P>
   ``I put off seeing him till Friday. He didn't make it to Friday.
That's really the motivating factor for me. I owe it to him to work
hard with my art work and make it mean something, because I
sacrificed seeing him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last frame:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
