<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T AND MICROSOFT POISED TO TOWER OVER TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Having cleared the way to become the nation's biggest cable
television company by acquiring Mediaone Group, AT&AMP;T moved closer
to a partnership with Microsoft. The whirlwind of deals surrounding
AT&AMP;T raised concerns in Washington and in many high-technology
quarters about the prospects for competition in the fast-growing
communications industry.
</P>
<P>
   With its cable and Microsoft deals, AT&AMP;T is poised to once again
stand astride the communications world. For Microsoft, a strong
relationship with AT&AMP;T could become the company's most important
vehicle for expanding from desktop computers into a new world in
which millions of consumers use seamless bundles of telephone,
television and high-speed Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR TO SELL UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years after paying $550 million for Cyrix to enter
the personal computer microprocessor business, National
Semiconductor is exiting that market. National Semiconductor said
it would seek a buyer for the business as well as for its related
chip plant in South Portland, Me., and that it would cut 550 jobs,
or 4.8 percent of its work force, and take a charge of $250 million
to $300 million in the fourth quarter. Shares of National
Semiconductor rose $3.0625, to $17.6875.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST UNION SUED OVER 401(k) PLAN
</P>
<P>
   First Union, operator of the nation's sixth-largest bank, is
being sued by a group of former employees of Signet Bank, which
First Union acquired. They contend that First Union cost workers
millions of dollars by moving their 401(k) investments to First
Union mutual funds, none of which performed as well as the
investments they were removed from.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AMERICA ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   While taking a deposition in preparation for the next stage of
Microsoft's antitrust trial, a lawyer for the company tried to make
the case that America Online planned to use ``all of its marketing
muscle'' to promote its newly acquired product, the Netscape
Navigator Web browser. But an America Online executive disputed
that, saying the company thought ``the browser business is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS RISE AS BLUE CHIPS RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rebounded as investors showed renewed affection for the
blue-chip growth stocks they had shunned lately. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 69.30 points, or 0.64 percent, to
10,955.41. The Nasdaq composite index did even better, surging 1.98
percent, or 49.28 points, to 2.534.45. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 15.31 points, or 1.15 percent, to 1,347.31.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE TELEKOM MAKES ITS CASE
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia began a series of investor
briefings to rally support for their $82 billion merger as new
signs of concern emerged. Deutsche Telekom's chief executive, Ron
Sommer, said he remained confident that financial institutions
would soon agree the deal made sense but that the two companies
would have to show they could improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   A YEAR 2000 PROGRESS REPORT
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing optimism that year 2000 computer problems will
not seriously affect American business is premature, according to
two new studies of corporate spending to solve the problems. The
figures suggest that many large companies have left themselves just
one year to complete more than half their work.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE APPROVES BANKRUPTCY BILL
</P>
<P>
   With a record 1.4 million personal bankruptcies filed in the
last year, the House of Representatives overwhelmingly approved
sweeping legislation proposed by the nation's largest banks, but
opposed by consumer and civil rights groups, that would make it
harder for many Americans to erase their debts.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE REJECTS BANKING MEASURES
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to overhaul the nation's banking system was
significantly set back after the Senate defeated two measures
endorsed by the Clinton administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
