<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6041 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEREAL-SFCHRON &LR;      05-05 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEREAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cereal Prices Creeping Back To Old Highs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Snap, crackle, pop.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sound of the cereal business changing direction. This
time, it's coming amid cereal industry acceptance that it failed to
win back consumers by slashing prices as much as $1 a box from 1996
to 1997. All it got out of that ballyhooed price war was soggy
sales and bland profits.
</P>
<P>
   Now the industry is raising prices slightly _ Quaker Oats Co.
being the latest with a 2.5 percent price increase announced this
week after a 3 percent increase last month by General Mills _ and
is funneling the extra money into product development.
</P>
<P>
   The big push comes at a time when chains such as Safeway that
once were cereal industry partners now are competitors with
proprietary brands that are taking away market share. In addition,
consumers are gravitating toward other breakfast foods, like bagels
and muffins that they can eat on the run.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the new focus is evident in the grocery cereal
aisle. Prices are creeping back up, although not to the level at
the peak four years ago, when many cereals approached $5 a box.
There is also an increase in coupon promotions, television
advertising and product innovation symbolized by the faster pace of
cereal rollouts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, rather than simply adding on to an existing brand
like Raisin Bran with Raisin Brand Crunch, Kellogg is expanding its
whole product line with completely new cereals.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg has come out with Smart Start and Honey Crunch Flakes,
Post with Oreo O's and Waffle Crisp, and General Mills with
Sunrise. All were rolled out within the past year and are designed
to stave off imitators like Malt-O-Meal and Safeway, which have
positioned low-cost knockoff cereals to lure customers away from
the biggest brands.
</P>
<P>
   What the industry has learned, not surprisingly, is that the
best defense is a strong offense, food industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only flank your major cereals with line extension so
many times before it begins to look tired,'' says food analyst
Lowell Singer at BancBoston Robertson Stephens in San Francisco.
``The strategy of extending lines and cutting prices clearly didn't
work because sales weren't growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quaker Oats spokeswoman Karen Savinski agreed: ``We know that to
grow, we have to bring innovative new products to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1998, for example, grocery sales of cold cereal
fell from $8 billion to $6.9 billion and the number of boxes and
bags sold declined by roughly 200 million. Although some of that
business went to nongrocery competitors like Wal-Mart, industrywide
profits still were down.
</P>
<P>
   During that same period, Kellogg cut domestic cereal advertising
by an estimated 40 percent, noted food analyst John McMillin at
Prudential Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Kellogg installed a new management team led by
Carlos Gutierrez. &LR;   &LR; The 45-year-old Cuban native says it is
imperative that Kellogg come up with innovative cereals that are
harder to copy and have the potential to build brand loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's leading a renaissance in product development,'' says
BancBoston's Singer. ``Part One is committing to new products. Part
Two is making sure they have the right products. That's what we're
watching for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fruitful Squares, a heartier breakfast bar from Kellogg, is one
attempt to woo back younger consumers who grab food to eat on the
run. NutriGrain bars, another Kellogg product, didn't make it with
breakfasters because they weren't filling enough, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Amid criticism that many cereals have too many calories for the
nutritional benefit, the new cereals tout natural ingredients as
well as vitamin and mineral fortification. General Mills' Sunrise,
for example, says it is the first mass-marketed cereal made from
organically grown grains.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kellogg is spending an estimated $20 million to
promote its ``K-sentials'' initiative to fortify some children's
cereals like Froot Loops and Apple Jacks with calcium and B
vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   And its advertising campaign for the newly introduced Raisin
Bran Crunch _ ``breakfast is back'' _ is designed for people who
don't think they have time for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   In coming months, analysts expect Kellogg to roll out a new line
of Country Inn Specialty Cereals, intended to lure upscale shoppers
who think nothing of spending $5 for a Starbuck's latte and pastry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the cereal industry, you want people trading up to
higher-priced cereals instead of down to private labels,'' says
Prudential's McMillin in New York. ``That's what they're trying to
provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg intends to roll out its Country Inn cereals nationwide
this year. They're expected to sell for $4.49 a bag and are modeled
on cereals served at regional inns, including the Inn at Ormsby
Hill in Manchester, Vt.; Greyfield Inn at Cumberland Island, Ga.;
and the Green Gables Inn in Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the industry is trying to evoke the spirit of its
19th century founders, primarily dietary reformers like Charles W.
Post, John H. Kellogg and Sylvester Graham, who preached the health
benefits of whole grain cereals and graham crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Will this new campaign work? The industry is hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of 1999, Kellogg reported sales up from
$1.64 billion to $1.75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're been encouraged by what we've been seeing when we try to
broaden the cereal category,'' says Kellogg spokeswoman Chris Irvin
in Battle Creek, Mich. ``We're definitely reaching out more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
