<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN AIDES IN PIQUE AT FIRST LADY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aides to Gov. Christie Whitman accused Hillary Rodham Clinton of
trying to avoid sharing the media limelight Wednesday during
ceremonies to greet Kosovar refugees as they arrived in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Peter McDonough, a spokesman for the governor, said that Whitman
had wanted to shake hands with the refugees as they got off a
chartered plane at McGuire Air Force Base. But McDonough said that
the first lady's office vetoed the idea, contending that it would
not be safe for Whitman to be so close to the refugees because many
of them were thought to be carrying tuberculosis or other
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough scoffed at that explanation, asserting that Mrs.
Clinton simply did not want to allow Whitman to be first in line
greeting the refugees at an event that was getting intense media
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how stupid they think we are to fall for such a
flimsy excuse,'' McDonough said. ``It's an extraordinarily
transparent bit of political jockeying by an apparent Senate
candidate in the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is said to be thinking of running as a Democrat for
the U.S. Senate in New York next year. Whitman, a Republican, has
already said she plans to run for the Senate in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mason, a spokeswoman for Mrs. Clinton, said, ``The first
lady was not involved in establishing how the refugees were greeted
when they arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman eventually did get to shake hands with many of the
refugees as they disembarked from buses that had brought them from
the Air Force base to nearby Fort Dix, where they will be housed.
Mrs. Clinton also waited until the refugees got to Fort Dix to
greet them. She addressed the refugees inside a gymnasium, where
she was joined by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Mrs. Clinton and Whitman exchanged niceties.
``She thanked the governor for being so helpful in setting up the
event,'' said Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman for Whitman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
