<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWIST-OKLAHOMA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPECIAL BRAND OF RESILIENCE ON DISPLAY IN OKLAHOMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ A sunburned, crew-cut bulldog of a man clutches
a crate full of plastic bottles with attached nipples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby stuff!'' he shouts above the commotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby stuff goes here,'' answers Elida Lopez, folding infant
sleepers under the noontime sun. She tapes a cardboard box closed
and says, ``I'm a housewife who just kind of showed up yesterday.
Today I'm heading up the baby department.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday across Oklahoma City _ a place seasoned by two very
different disasters within four years _ thousands of volunteers
such as Lopez were stacking, lifting, hauling, piling everything
imaginable into tractor-trailers destined for those who lost
everything imaginable in Monday's tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Entire city blocks and parking lots were transformed into
charitable drop sites crammed elbow-to-elbow with folks who took
the day off work to help, then worked even harder than usual. Some
directed lines of traffic. Some wrenched their backs hoisting boxes
onto loading docks.
</P>
<P>
   Countless others simply donated what they had, like the
9-year-old girl who handed over $300 in cash that she'd been saving
to buy a bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking straws! Got a load of drinking straws and cups!''
</P>
<P>
   At the Feed the Children drop site off Meridian Avenue, Shara
Hendrick, 21, had her own reasons for being here. She had been
enjoying an aerobics workout at a gym Monday night as the tornado
lurched toward the suburb of Moore; the aerobics instructor got
everybody into a vault that was once a restaurant cooler. Hendrick
thought she might die as the twister pounded over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped out of that place and saw the whole area
devastated,'' she said Wednesday, loading bibs into a box. ``I just
feel so lucky. The windshield of my car (was) blown out, but that's
nothing when you think about all those who had everything they
owned turned to twigs.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hendrick and her mother skipped a day's pay from their jobs
at the state tourism department to help Wednesday in the relief
trenches.
</P>
<P>
   At Quail Springs Mall on the north side of Oklahoma City, dozens
waited in line to donate blood. At Crossroads Mall on the south
side, two trailers were packed with non-perishables. One woman
showed up Wednesday with a $100 bill she said she had found in a
gutter; she was certain it belonged to someone whose home was
destroyed miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Another person turned over a family album filled with pictures
of unknown people. She said she found it in her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma College of Dentistry hauled in more than 1,000
toothbrushes and 1,000 rolls of floss. And at Pratt Discount Foods
on Northwest 39th Street, some shoppers paid for $150 worth of
groceries and then stacked every last sack into a giant donation
crate normally used for holding watermelons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filled that crate in two hours,'' said check-out man David
Kimberlin.
</P>
<P>
   This response to a nationally publicized tragedy reminded
Oklahoma Citians of a similar blitz four years ago. The April 19,
1995, bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building killed 168
persons, leaving many parents childless and some children
parentless.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the relief agencies here learned from the bombing how
to coordinate things quickly,'' said Aaron Blaser, assignment
editor for a local CBS television affiliate, which sponsored a
drop-off site. ``During the bad weather Monday night, everyone was
just instinctively asking, `What do we need to do off the bat?' ''
</P>
<P>
   By dawn the next day, when the doors of a blood collection
agency opened in nearby Norman, a score of donors waited in parked
cars.
</P>
<P>
   And by Wednesday, volunteers by the thousands toted
walkie-talkies and fielded instructions at the Feed the Children
site, where forklifts criss-crossed semi-trailers criss-crossing
armored trucks bearing parcels of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we call very organized chaos,'' said Duane Hunt,
a director of the local ministry that sponsors Feed the Children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Need some muscle power here! Got a forklift waiting!''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Price, a local youth pastor, said this disaster would take
longer to overcome than the 1995 bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you had more lives lost, but people still had their homes
and belongings. Now we've got _ what, 1,500 homes to rebuild?
That'll take a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's something about Oklahoma _ you still have this
remnant of the pioneer spirit,'' Price said. ``We've only been a
state since 1907. Some of the original homesteaders are still
alive. I think that helps cement this necessity of community.
Oklahoma City is probably the biggest small town in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He taped another box down and a stranger carried it away to a
van.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say character is revealed in times of challenge, and
Oklahoma City has had its share,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bleach! Got a box of bleach!''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Gates was willing to take whatever she could get.
</P>
<P>
   She was shopping for her cousins _ Paul Olga and the Brinlee
brothers _ who were left homeless in Moore after the storm. She was
at the First Baptist Church, a command center for emergency crews
and a shelter and food kitchen for the estimated 300 families in
Moore whose homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Long tables sat in every hallway of the church to hold items
hauled in from the drop-off sites. Gates grabbed a tube of
deodorant, some shampoo and soap before moving to the tables of
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cousins, all they've got are the clothes on their backs,''
she says. ``They're out there right now going through the wreckage
wearing the same things they had on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the receiving end, you can't imagine how
important this is. And you really appreciate the work that went
into delivering this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   She reached into her shopping bag and pulled out a disposable
Bic razor, which retails for less than $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even this,'' Gates said with a smile. ``Those boys have to
shave, you know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
