<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AT&AMP;T-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AT&AMP;T GROWS LARGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, May 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades after AT&AMP;T was forced by antitrust laws to
give up its most vital asset _ ownership of a wire into most
American homes _ the company is trying to regain that access by a
different means. Now it hopes to use the cable television wire into
your home to get your telephone business.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deals negotiated by AT&AMP;T, including the purchase of
Mediaone, a cable company, and a series of transactions involving
Comcast, a cable company that had wanted to buy Mediaone, mean that
AT&AMP;T will be in a position to offer local phone service to most
American homes.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, who has been running AT&AMP;T for 18 months,
has now committed to spend $112 billion to buy cable systems that
are positioned to connect to about a quarter of the homes in
America. In addition the company has tentative agreements with
other cable operators, including Comcast and Time Warner, to offer
AT&AMP;T-branded local phone service through cable systems to another
quarter of America. At the moment no homes get such cable-phone
service from AT&AMP;T, although AT&AMP;T says it will begin offering the
service in several communities around the country later this year,
with a broader availability next year.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether AT&AMP;T's huge investment in the area
will prove to be a brilliant business move or as disastrous as its
ill-fated effort in the 1980s to become a computer company after it
was forced by an antitrust settlement to spin off its local
telephone operations. But the venture is to be welcomed because it
holds out the possibility of real competition for local phone
service for millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Microsoft in the cable deals may need further study.
Microsoft owns a substantial stake in Comcast _ bought about three
years ago when cable stock prices were depressed _ and had talked
to Comcast about helping to finance its bid for Mediaone. Now it is
reported to be considering making an investment in AT&AMP;T in return
for an agreement that a version of Microsoft's Windows operating
system will be used in the cable boxes that will be providing a
growing range of services.
</P>
<P>
   Any such arrangement should be scrutinized to make sure that it
does not provide a new monopoly area for Microsoft in one of the
businesses _ Internet access via cable television _ where
competitive positions have yet to be sorted out. There is nothing
wrong with Microsoft's gaining a dominant position because it
offers a superior product, but such dominance should not result
from the financial clout that the company now has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
