<SLUG> BC-POT-PUNISHMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY PUNISHED FOR REPORTING DRUGS TO PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICIA FARRELL AIDEM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAUGUS, Calif. -- Tyler Hagen tried to do the right thing when a
friend asked him to get rid of a small bag of marijuana he had
bought just to be ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-grader turned it over to his parents, who did the
right thing by calling the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the doing the right thing went wrong when school authorities
were informed. The 13-year-old was suspended under the school
district's ``zero-tolerance'' policy -- leaving the boy upset, his
parents furious and the Sheriff's Department flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose the real right thing would have been to take it to
the school office, but they're kids and they won't do that,''
Sheriff's Sgt. Lee White said Wednesday. ``So he took it to his
parents. He did the other right thing. That should count.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the 13-year-old's parents -- with White's support -- are
fighting for their son's return to Arroyo Seco Junior High School
in the Santa Clarita Valley north of metropolitan Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should he have lied?'' said Tyler's mother, Linda Hagen.
``Here we are, trying to tell our kids to come forward and talk to
us, but what happens? He gets in trouble. He gets the same
punishment as the kids who are pushing drugs at school.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials with the William S. Hart Union High School
District said the 13-year-old was punished for taking possession of
the marijuana on campus and bringing it home to his parents rather
than turning it over to the principal.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo Seco Principal Jackie Snyder did not return telephone
calls. And Michael Almandinger, assistant superintendent of student
services for the Hart District, would not comment on the specifics
of Tyler's case, but cited district policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If kids are in possession of drugs at school, our board has
taken a `zero-tolerance' stand,'' Almandinger said. ``The
principals are directed to bring forth a student for expulsion
unless they find circumstances that make them think expulsion is
not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's options now are to enter a special class at Arroyo Seco
for kids in trouble -- which his parents refuse to allow -- or to
enroll in another local junior high.
</P>
<P>
   According to White, a friend of Tyler's was taunted April 29 by
peers at Santa Clarita's Skate Park, until he finally agreed to buy
a ``dime bag'' of marijuana at school the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid felt he was pressured,'' said White, the chief
juvenile crime investigator in Santa Clarita. ``He bought it to be
cool, but then he didn't know how to get rid of it. He gave it to a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler was talking over the situation with his friends --
unidentified because they are juveniles -- as they waited by Arroyo
Seco's flag pole for their ride home, Linda Hagen said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler wanted to help, so he took the plastic bag of marijuana
with him. He then confided in his parents, and gave them the bag
containing a half-teaspoon of marijuana, Hagen said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, Chris Hagen, called the sheriff's station and
their son and the other boys were interviewed by school officials
Monday, the day that Tyler's suspension took effect.
</P>
<P>
   White supports the district's get-tough policy, but said Tyler
Hagen seems to be an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there should be some consideration if he went to his
parents,'' White said. ``That's what we try to teach these kids: Go
to your parents. Talk to them. Talk to someone. We want kids to
report these things.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
