<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSE PUTS ON STRONG CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Back when spring was winter, before balls
fluttered around Spaulding Field, UCLA defensive lineman Pete
Holland set his goals for spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   A history major who quotes Thurgood Marshall, Holland kept it
simple: The defense needed to regain the respect of UCLA's
offensive players and the coaching staff. Yielding 87 points in the
two most important games of the season (Miami, Wisconsin) has a way
of causing concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were divided,'' said Holland, who was chosen
defensive captain for the 1999 season. ``It was no secret the
defense was the weak point. We needed to win the offense's respect
back during the spring. That was vital to the team's morale, and I
think we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense left no doubt Saturday, holding the offense to two
touchdowns and a field goal in a 70-play scrimmage. Granted, Cade
McNown wasn't directing the attack, and the best receivers were on
the sideline. But for the first time since the USC game, the
defense had a presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``They got a lot of
pressure, and obviously they covered pretty good.... We had better
pad level. Better gap control. We covered better. We tackled
better.''
</P>
<P>
   All true. But three months before training camp, plenty of
questions remain _ on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: After four weeks and no answers, the question is
not only who, but when. Will Toledo wait until the Sept. 4 opener
(Boise State) to name a starter? Will the Bruins rotate
quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   That junior Drew Bennett didn't win the job in April indicates
he may never win it. After all, his massive edge in experience will
diminish over time.
</P>
<P>
   In several scrimmages, the Bruins responded best to freshman
Cory Paus, who vaulted to second string on the depth chart. Both
Scott McEwan (early) and Ryan McCann (late) had their moments, but
neither matched Bennett or Paus for playmaking.
</P>
<P>
   As for rookie J.P. Losman, two things are evident: He has the
best arm, and he has much to learn. Perhaps the spring experience
will catapult Losman to a terrific training camp. More likely,
though, he'll spend 1999 as a redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: The Bruins are loaded in the backfield. DeShaun
Foster, bigger and faster, is the best third-string tailback in the
nation. Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown were solid as well, and
watch for a big season from fullback Durell Price. His role will
expand in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver: Another loaded position, although injuries (Freddie
Mitchell, Brian Poli-Dixon) and a volleyball commitment (Danny
Farmer) limited this unit.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Crecion made good use of his redshirt season. He looked
stronger and more confident and should be the starting tight end
when training camp opens. Randy Hakes, Bryan Fletcher and incoming
freshman Mike Seidman make tight end one of UCLA's deepest
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line: What's left of it is young but talented. Since
last season, the Bruins have lost seven players to attrition,
injury or position change.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of the spring were freshmen Mike Saffer (right
guard) and Blake Worley (left tackle), who won starting jobs in the
spots previously occupied by Andy Meyers and Kris Farris,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Reserves Josh (shoulder) and Micah (knee) Webb missed spring
practice but are expected back for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line: First-year assistant coaches Jethro Franklin
(tackles) and John Pearce (ends) were relentless. At Toledo's
request, they turned spring practice into boot camp, toughening the
young linemen, forcing them to disregard fatigue and play through
minor aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches really tightened the screws on the front line,''
Holland said. ``It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mover and sacker was freshman Rusty Williams, the
high-energy weakside end from San Diego. He vaulted into the
starting spot vacated by Santi Hall, who was suspended for
violating team rules and might not return.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Sean Phillips moved from tackle to strongside end
behind Kenyon Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kocher, Anthony Fletcher, converted offensive lineman Steve
Morgan and Holland will rotate at tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker: The injury-induced retirements of Mike Wiley and
Ramogi Huma have left UCLA so thin at linebacker that incoming
freshman Marcus Reese could play immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Ryan Nece (weak side) and Tony White (middle) adjusted
quickly to the new 4-3 alignment, but the Robert Thomas situation
was not resolved. (He's listed as the No.2 middle linebacker.) One
option is to move Thomas or White outside, to Brendon Ayanbadejo's
former position.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary: Long a problem position, cornerback is now the
strength of the defensive backfield. Jason Bell (heel) did not
practice but is slotted to start. Marques Anderson played with a
passion he usually reserves for USC, and freshman Joe Hunter was
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ryan Roques has moved from cornerback to free safety,
since neither Eric Whitfield nor Audie Attar played well. Jason
Stephens is No.1 at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams: With Foster, Lewis, Mitchell and Roques, the
Bruins have their most talented group of returners in years.
Although walk-on Chris Griffith kicked well, both the punting and
kicking positions are wide open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
