<SLUG> BC-TWISTER-WICHITA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AFTERMATH OF WICHITA TORNADO, MAMMOTH RECOVERY EFFORT UNFOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN, JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ Truckload by truckload Wednesday, residents of
Sedgwick County continued the tedious job of digging out and
clearing away the tons of debris left in the wake of Monday night's
twister, which ripped through the center of suburban Haysville,
then shredded two mobile home parks in south Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Residents began to reckon with the emotional costs of burying
five of their dead, along with the physical toll imposed on more
than 150 persons who needed medical treatment for injuries, and
property damage already estimated at near $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   All over Wichita, equipment rental outlets reported a run on
generators, chain saws, tractors and boom lifts. And along a broad
front, relief was pouring into the area:
</P>
<P>
   - Federal and state officials, including Gov. Bill Graves and
James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, were in the area to review the damage and vow support.
Other cities in Kansas, including Lenexa, Lawrence and Overland
Park, either had public works crews on the scene or on the way to
Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   - An army of insurance agents swept into the area to begin
processing thousands of claims that will be filed. Initial
estimates of damage in Sedgwick County were approaching $150
million. Preliminary counts indicated that 8,480 homes and
businesses had been damaged; 1,129 of those were destroyed. Major
damage was inflicted on 2,245 buildings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   - Mental-health counselors and religious ministers were meeting
with residents devastated by the storm, offering emotional support,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the missing has ended, and everyone had been
accounted for within 48 hours of the storm, said Ken Cox, Sedgwick
County battalion fire chief. He credited Haysville's tornado
sirens, in particular, with giving residents time to seek shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had it not been for the early warning we would have had a lot
more loss of life,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was expected to arrive today to tour the
region, which President Clinton has already declared a federal
disaster area. Graves and the federal agency's Witt pledged
financial support to those who lost homes and businesses, and to
make the cleanup process as smooth and swift as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is keep the anger and frustration level
down, because they (victims) have been through enough,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the governmental response, insurance claims
adjusters fanned out over the area to view damage and write checks.
Allstate Insurance brought in adjusters from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Farm Bureau Insurance has a satellite office in south Wichita
about a mile from the tornado-ravaged area. A steady stream of
people called or came in to that office, which has become a center
for the company's claims activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a total loss and they need money for clothing or even
a toothbrush, they can come here and we'll cut them a check,'' said
Terrie Enslinger, an insurance underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people coming in with just the clothes on their back,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Enslinger said many people just coped with the shock Tuesday and
waited until Wednesday to contact their insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm Insurance Cos., the largest insurer of homes and
autos in Kansas, estimated that at least 3,500 homeowners suffered
$14 million in losses and that 300 vehicle owners suffered $450,000
in damages in the Haysville and Wichita areas.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm has set up a claim contact center in the area and
established a toll-free hot line at (800) SF-CLAIM for policy
holders who cannot reach agents directly, said Doug Eaton, the
company's Oklahoma-Kansas regional vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers Insurance Group, another large insurer, estimated it
would receive at least 4,000 claims from homeowners and 2,400 from
vehicle owners in Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas, which also was hit.
More than half are expected to come from Oklahoma; about 900 Kansas
property damage claims and 250 Kansas auto claims are included in
the total.
</P>
<P>
   Damage was not confined to the tornado's path. Fallen tree limbs
littered yards in many neighborhoods in south Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   The tree limb problem was so extensive, Wichita public works
officials still hadn't been able to come up with a strategy
Wednesday to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Peck, a spokeswoman for the city of Wichita, said it
will take the area a long time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take months to just get things cleaned up,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Haysville said hundreds of volunteers were coming
to the community activity center near the Kansas Turnpike entrance
to help in the massive cleanup. They were advising everyone to
bring heavy gloves. Crews were still trying to restore power there.
</P>
<P>
   Among the volunteers were city crews from Lenexa and Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   The Lenexa Public Works Department dispatched a crew of 12 to
Wichita on Tuesday to assist with the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the city business, everybody tries to help everybody if we
can,'' said Dennis Banka, Lenexa's public works manager. ``It can
happen to us just as easily as it happened to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park has a team of six vehicles and seven employees
they will send as soon as Wichita makes the request, said Bob
Lowry, the city's public works director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
