A6214 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWISTER-AGONY-KAN &LR;      05-05 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWISTER-AGONY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS COPE WITH AFTERMATH OF WICHITA AREA TORNADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN, JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ Amid the prayers of thanks for keepsakes
recovered and the muffled curses over personal losses, the
collective shock that many in the Wichita area felt the morning
after Monday night's tornado was giving way Wednesday to a more
ominous feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of people supporting us,'' said Tim Norton, the
mayor of Haysville, a city of 9,500 that abuts Wichita's southern
border. ``We're being ministered to, but three months from now _
when we wake up and our whole town is still gutted and there aren't
a lot of people supporting us and helping us clean up _ we're going
to go through a grieving process and have to come to terms with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there was plenty of immediate grief to go around.
But devastation notwithstanding, there were lighter moments, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Leanora Smith wasn't able to salvage much more than a few
clothes and toys from the wreckage of her mobile home, but there
was a bright spot Wednesday for her boyfriend, Matt Lathrom.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the rubble at Lakeshore Mobile Home Park was Lathrom's
prized 1975 Harley-Davidson motorcycle. It took three hours and a
gasoline-powered saw to cut through the debris, but Lathrom and a
couple of friends were able to extract the motorcycle he finished
restoring a year ago, at a cost of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a Harley rider, that's about as important as life,''
Lathrom said. ``I was just glad I found it.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances may have tempered his joy. But it was a moment
of something other than the scenes of grief, desperation and
helplessness that were playing for block after block in south
Wichita and nearby Haysville as the cleanup continued.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, knee-deep in rubble, had their minds occupied with
competing concerns: retreiving what they could from their previous
homes; wondering where they would make their next ones.
</P>
<P>
   Lavenia Martin, though, set about the task with greater focus.
As family members helped salvage belongings from what was left of
her mobile home Wednesday morning, she was looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Even though her home at the Lakeshore park was destroyed,
Martin, 71, remained set in her ways. Once the insurance comes
through, she and her husband, Harold, 75, plan to buy another
mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did make the remark that it seems tornadoes target mobile
home parks, but it never occurred to me not to get another one,''
said Lavenia Martin, who had lived in the mobile home since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Others were having a harder time figuring out where to turn.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Meredith, a chaplain and crisis counselor at Wesley
Medical Center in Wichita, talked with victims at one of the
trailer parks.
</P>
<P>
   She said they felt powerless and helpless, looking through the
wreckage of for pictures _ ``visual clues to their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   A few took photographs or videos of their damaged property.
</P>
<P>
   Still dazed, others were not sure what to do next. Meredith said
even a little direction from someone was enough to jump-start
thoughts about the future.
</P>
<P>
   She said many victims, especially children, will feel a
heightened sense of anxiety and loss of security as the days and
weeks go by.
</P>
<P>
   Many will depend on charity, she added, and that could be hard
for some.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said people who were trapped in the rubble and waited
in the dark for rescue will have nightmares and flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult adjustment,'' she said. ``Kids who are going
to school will get a lot of support. That will help.''
</P>
<P>
   In future storms, they will exhibit a heightened state of alarm,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Haysville, Linda and Shawn Langhover estimate they've had
help from 30 friends and family members in cleaning up the remains
of their home. The bright spots Wednesday were the recovery of
Linda Langhover's wedding ring and her husband's Masonic ring.
</P>
<P>
   However, they were able to recover only half of their
13-year-old son's 100 wrestling medals.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks away, Michelle and Edward Coldiron had the
opportunity to speak with federal and state officials who brought
promises of aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps reassure us that some action will be taken, that it
won't just be overlooked,'' Michelle Coldiron said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other victims, the Coldirons coped by keeping their sense
of humor. Using white spray paint, Edward Coldiron sprayed ``For
Sale'' signs on the remains of their house.
</P>
<P>
   Among those sifting debris, searching for the proper perspective
on the death and destruction, was Calvin Waters, a sheet metal
worker whose home was damaged by the tornado. He spent a second day
trying to clear the wreckage, patch holes in the roof and mop up
water damage.
</P>
<P>
   He called himself fortunate, saying such things can be replaced.
But he was especially shaken by the deaths of a woman and
1-month-old baby near his home, even though he did not know them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think a child should get a chance to grow up,'' he
said. ``If you have to take two people, don't take a baby child.
Take me: I'm 44 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
