r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABSENT-STUDENTS-LADN     05-05 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABSENT-STUDENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMORS OF VIOLENCE PROMPT WAVE OF STUDENT ABSENCES AROUND L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN AND GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Rumors of racially motivated violence at suburban
San Fernando Valley schools led thousands of students to stay home
Wednesday, as police beefed up patrols and campuses braced for more
absences today.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to schools districtwide today, Los Angeles Unified
School District Superintendent Ruben Zacarias urged parents to
return their children to school and alert authorities with concrete
information about threats or impending violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He encouraged parents and community members to contact their
local schools or police departments if they have specific concerns
about safety issues, rather than allowing youngsters to use
generalized and unverified threats or rumors as a reason to stay
out of school,'' said LAUSD spokesman Brad Sales.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest hit campuses was Chatsworth High School, about
35 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles, where more than half
the 3,200 students stayed home. Several principals planned parent
meetings and assemblies, while stepping up checks of students with
metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they are continuing additional patrols until rumors
subside, and they are working to track down the sources of the
false reports.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police detectives questioned several North Hollywood
students including one who acknowledged he had joked about wanting
to bomb a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told them that perhaps they're sorry, but if it happens
again they can be arrested and prosecuted,'' said Detective George
Armenta of the North Hollywood Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also notifying principals that they should advise their
students that pranks can't be taken lightly,'' Armenta said.
</P>
<P>
   Today at a meeting of the school safety committee, school board
member Julie Korenstein plans to introduce a resolution to bring
criminal and civil charges against students caught making terrorist
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students should realize that if they do this they will be
arrested by the LAPD and expelled from L.A. Unified,'' Korenstein
said. ``These threats have been very contagious. They really think
that it's funny and it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Unified School District officials said the rumors
and fear were sparked largely by the school shootings in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tensions in the community and in the whole country
because of the Littleton incidents. To think that schools are
immune from that tension is Pollyanish,'' said Shel Erlich, a
district spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Several San Fernando Valley schools reported drastically low
attendance figures, including at Chatsworth High School, where
1,883 of the 3,200 students were absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen this large number of students out of school,''
said Vice Principal Greg Lee. ``It's just the anxiety that the
students and the parents have.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Anthony Muzichenko, 18, said he didn't believe the
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just childish,'' he said, adding that he understood why
his classmates stayed home. ``Nobody wants to take chances after
the Colorado shootings.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lawrence Middle School in Chatsworth, 28 percent of the
student body was absent.
</P>
<P>
   At North Hollywood High School, a bomb threat on Wednesday
proved false. ``We've been receiving an increased number of bomb
threats that are made. I'm sure it has to do with the incidents in
Colorado,'' said LAUSD Assistant Police Chief Richard Page.
</P>
<P>
   At Monroe High School in suburban North Hills in the San
Fernando Valley, counselors, deans and teachers increased their
routine metal detecting and backpack searches on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The disruptions Wednesday follow a series of rumors that began
after the Colorado shootings April 20.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest round, students and teachers at Valley schools
told police and school officials they heard about plans by Latino
youths to shoot white students.
</P>
<P>
   Students reported that the rumor appeared on the Internet, but
police could not confirm that report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where that came from, but I know lots of people
are nervous, and there's a heightened awareness to possible
threats,'' said Gerald Kleinman, principal at Birmingham High
School in Van Nuys, where student attendance also was slightly
down.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa Miranda, a mother of a Chatsworth High School sophomore,
was not about to take chances with her son, Andy. She drove him to
school but only to attend the lunchtime Cinco de Mayo festivities
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that there were going to be a lot of things
happening. I didn't want him to come to school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Wednesday, a 15-year-old student was arrested
Wednesday at Narbonne High School in Harbor City after allegedly
planting a fake bomb outside the cafeteria, said LAPD Lt. Anthony
Alba. He was arrested on suspicion of having a fake bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, a 15-year-old boy at the same school was
questioned for allegedly making a false bomb threat and telling
several students that ``he could blow up the school by using his
personal computer,'' Alba said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
