<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEX-WRITETHEU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO SURVIVORS SORT THROUGH BITS AND PIECES LEFT OF THEIR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: CORRECTS to clarify that Chickasha is southwest of Oklahoma
City sted southeast. (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS Jr. and BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ They survived that wicked brute of a tornado and
finally got to go home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But many found no home, just bits and pieces of brick, wood and
insulation, crumpled automobiles and everything they owned gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back and seeing it all destroyed is kind of hard,''
said Chris Pillifant, who rode out Monday's tornado huddling in a
shower stall with his wife and 3-year-old golden retriever. ``This
just looks like 'Nam,'' he said referring to the war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The casualty list resembled a war's toll: at least 38 dead,
hundreds injured, thousands homeless, dozens missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have over 100 missing persons reports ... at the present
time,'' said Ray Blakeney, director of operations for the state
medical examiner's office. He issued a public plea for help in
finding the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Although early damage estimates hovered around $225 million,
officials Wednesday called that figure low _ ``like really low,''
said Rick Buchanan, press spokesman for Gov. Frank Keating. The
latest estimates put loss at upwards of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't surprise me a bit,'' Brad Craine, a spokesman
for the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the death count remained at 38, although
authorities said a man identified as John Green, believed to be
from Moore, died shortly before noon Wednesday. His name had not
been added to the official fatality list by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scores of people remained in area hospitals, many
suffering serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A 39-day-old baby clung to life at one hospital, his skull
shattered by flying debris; a 13-year-old girl was in serious
condition at another hospital with a broken neck; and a 33-year-old
woman was being treated for injuries suffered when a board or fence
post entered one side of her face and exited the other.
</P>
<P>
   Between 2,000 and 3,000 homes were destroyed or heavily damaged
in the Oklahoma City area, said David Van Nostrand, director of
Emergency Management Services for Oklahoma County.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of homes remain without electricity or gas, and 70
utility crews from Texas were expected to arrive in Oklahoma on
Thursday to help restore power.
</P>
<P>
   Residents allowed back into their neighborhoods for the first
time since Monday said they were among the lucky _ they had somehow
survived tornadoes packing winds approaching 260 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said our Hail Marys and kept yelling,'' said Pillifant, who
was buried in the rubble of the 2,000-square-foot house that
collapsed around him, his wife and dog.
</P>
<P>
   Cars by the hundreds lined up bumper to bumper at police
checkpoints where people had to show identification and proof they
lived in a certain neighborhood before they could enter.
</P>
<P>
   When John and Sheryl Molsbee drove onto their street, they found
their brick-and-frame home standing, but minus its roof. Still on
the stove was Monday's macaroni dinner in a pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse than I thought,'' said John Molsbee, who wasn't
home when the giant twisters leveled neighborhoods in Oklahoma City
and surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, residents searched for irreplaceable
possessions: photographs, keepsakes and mementos collected before
the tornadoes shattered their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some scoured their shredded and ravaged apartments and found
undamaged CDs, home videos and high school and college diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost me $30,000,'' said Aaron Penix, 22, referring to his
sheepskin. ``I'm actually really surprised. It was merciful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Chong Wren sat at an apartment complex with her back to
a fallen tree, its bark stripped away by tornadic winds. She had
survived by hiding in one of her unit's two bathrooms. The one she
chose remained untouched; the other disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had stayed there, I would have died,'' Wren said. ``I
don't know why I picked that one. It was Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   At Westmoore High School, the parking lot was littered with
scores of damaged vehicles, many of them turned upside down. Wood
from nearby houses speared the windshields of some. A dead horse
lay against the front bumper of a green pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to the Pillifants, members of the Westmoore football
team helped their coach, Chris Stiles, sort through the rubble of
his family's home. They found eight albums with photos of Stiles'
two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm looking for,'' said Stiles, 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is the kids don't have a scratch. By the grace
of God, we're here and we'll rebuild better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents face the task of rebuilding from what the
National Weather Service officially upgraded from F4 to F5 the
tornadoes that tore through Oklahoma City and Moore. An F5 tornado
is the most severe with winds exceeding 260 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Service engineering teams tracing the tornadoes' paths
said one was 3/4 mile wide as it sliced a 40-mile swath rumbling
through Moore and Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   In one Oklahoma City neighborhood, police found part of an
airplane wing thought to have come from Chickasha, about 30 miles
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials, meanwhile, were making arrangements
to find housing for the displaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking tent cities,'' said Ben Frizzell of the
state Office of Civil Emergency Management. ``There is a disaster
housing program through FEMA that will provide rental assistance
for up to 18 months if needed. Some people may even use this to
rent travel trailers to put on their property.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross also passed out vouchers for people to
temporarily stay in motels.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Andrew Backover and Anita Baker contributed to
this story. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
