<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BILL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GOVERNOR SAYS HE WILL VETO ABORTION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Gov. Mel Carnahan said Wednesday he will
veto an abortion bill that seems certain to win legislative
approval, but backers of the measure are optimistic they can
override any veto.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear win for abortion foes, Missouri senators ended a
marathon debate and filibuster at 12:10 a.m. Wednesday by approving
a bill that backers said would ban a certain late-term abortion
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said it would prohibit what they call
``partial-birth'' abortions by essentially labeling the procedure
infanticide. The procedure would be a felony unless it was done to
preserve the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which was approved 27-6, now returns to the House,
where backers predict it will win easy approval, probably next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, asked if he could sustain a veto, said: ``I am not
sure. We will make the fight. You never feel secure about
sustaining a veto, but we will work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said lack of a provision to permit such an abortion to
protect the mother's health, not just her life, was one of his key
objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that is both bad policy and also clearly
unconstitutional,'' said the governor, who favors abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill, who contend the measure can withstand any
court challenge, said there is a good chance the House and Senate
can muster the two-thirds majorities needed for the law to take
effect despite Carnahan's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan vetoed a similar bill two years ago. The Senate
sustained it by one vote. Any override attempt this year probably
would take place in September.
</P>
<P>
   An override would require 23 votes in the Senate and 109 in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the votes are more solid than they were two years
ago,'' said Sen. Ted House, a St. Charles Democrat and sponsor of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Luetkenhaus, a Josephville Democrat and House sponsor,
noted that the House has already approved a similar bill with 129
votes, much more than the two-thirds needed for an override.
</P>
<P>
   However, one factor in Carnahan's favor is that political
dynamics change when the governor's prestige is on the line. Some
fellow Democrats do not want to embarrass him, even on an emotional
issue such as abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's veto promise did not go unnoticed by the office of
U.S. Sen. John Ashcroft, the Republican whose post Carnahan is
seeking next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel Carnahan is trying once again to impose his extreme
abortion views on Missouri, extending even to the horrible practice
of partial-birth abortion,'' said Steve Hilton, Ashcroft's press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, who opposes abortion, is co-sponsor of a Senate bill
to ban the practice. Two previous such bans passed by Congress were
vetoed by President Clinton. Similar bans are in effect in seven
states; they have been tied up in court or struck down in 19 other
states, according to the National Right to Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate debate and filibuster consumed six days and more than
38 hours, delaying action on virtually every other issue.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, action on the bill halted for 90 minutes when Sen.
Jet Banks, a St. Louis Democrat, disappeared after offering an
amendment. He returned Wednesday. Critics said Banks, who
criticized the bill, was trying to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a diabetic,'' Banks said of his absence. ``My blood sugar
was going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the abortion bill cleared the way for final approval
of the state's $16 billion operating budget, which has to be done
by 6 p.m. Friday, and debates about tax cuts, crime, drunken
driving and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri said
that the bill was deceptive and would threaten women who seek
abortions already protected by the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   House disputed that argument. He noted the bill says the measure
does not apply to legal abortions if they are done before the child
is ``partially born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not make it any clearer,'' House said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure under fire involves the partial, feet-first
extraction of the fetus. The barely visible skull is then punctured
with scissors and its contents are drained before the skull is
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill makes physicians subject to charges of infanticide. The
mother would not be liable unless suspected of taking a
``substantial step'' that results in the infant's death.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill said charges against the mother would be
unlikely, but critics disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan also denounced that provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very idea we would be finding women culpable and charging
them with murder, putting them in jail, for making a health
decision is very disturbing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only Kansas City area ``no'' votes on the bill were Sens.
Mary Groves Bland and Ed Quick, both Democrats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0543 </DOCNO>
