<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBURY SCORES 41 AS THE NETS WIN FINALE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This was supposed to be the beginning,
not the end. Wednesday night's regular-season finale against the
Milwaukee Bucks was supposed to mark the start of the most
successful post-season run in the Nets' 22-year history in the
National Basketball Association. The young and talented team from
New Jersey was a second-round lock, a potential Eastern Conference
finalist and, with a little luck, maybe more than that.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, those preseason predictions will not come to
pass. After John Calipari, at one time the team's upstart coach,
was dismissed, after six of the team's top nine players were
sidelined with season-ending injuries, and after two players
originally signed to 10-day contracts became starters by default,
the Nets will disperse summer vacations this weekend as arguably
the most disappointing team in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why? Why, after making the playoffs last season
with a 43-39 record, overcoming numerous injuries along the way,
did the Nets degenerate into a team with a 16-34 record that lost
in routs to the woeful Los Angeles Clippers, Denver Nuggets and
Chicago Bulls?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is multifaceted, but clear, and much of it is rooted
in two men who have since been removed, Calipari and point guard
Sam Cassell, who was traded to Milwaukee on March 11 in the deal
that brought Stephon Marbury, who scored a career-high 41 points
Wednesday night in a 115-107 victory over Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But there were other factors _ like the lack of a low-post
scorer, the various foot injuries to Rony Seikaly, and the subpar
play of Kerry Kittles _ but the Nets' 3-17 start fell largely onto
the shoulders of Calipari and Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   The season-ending injuries to Jayson Williams (broken leg),
Keith Van Horn (broken thumb), Jim McIlvaine (left shoulder) and
Scott Burrell (knee) had little to do with the Nets'
underachievement because all occurred after Calipari was fired and
the team had essentially been eliminated from the post-season race.
Despite those injuries, the Nets finished the season winning 13 of
30 games under the team's interim coach, Don Casey, adding more
evidence to the fact that Calipari had lost his players.
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, even on the heels of last year's
surprising success, the players' lack of respect, trust and belief
in Calipari was a dynamite stick waiting to be lighted. Many of the
players grew weary of Calipari's excessive ego and verbal assaults
last season, but because they were winning, it did not become a
major issue.
</P>
<P>
   But when the losses began stacking up, the little confidence the
players had in Calipari's coaching ability vanished altogether, and
some, including Kendall Gill, a co-captain, went to the Nets'
ownership with complaints. One Nets official who spoke on condition
of anonymity said that after Marbury's first two games with New
Jersey, he was amazed by the players' lack of respect for Calipari.
``I'd say John lost the players around the 10th game of the
season,'' another Nets executive said. ``And once that happened,
the season was basically over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell was a huge factor in this because if he did not sprain
his right ankle in the season opener and subsequently miss 15 of
the next 18 games, the Nets almost certainly would not have had
such a poor record, and the players would have pushed forward
despite their dislike for Calipari. Cassell admitted as much before
Wednesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was healthy, the New Jersey Nets would be in the
playoffs,'' Cassell said. ``I know that for a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell went on to say that Calipari would still be the Nets'
coach if he had not been hurt. ``Cal made the game fun for me,'' he
said. ``A lot of guys didn't like his style and his charisma, but I
never had a problem with Cal. I think they made a drastic mistake
by giving up a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell was perhaps the only player in the Nets' locker room who
enjoyed playing for Calipari, and many of his teammates resented
the special privileges Calipari seemed to afford him, such as
loafing in practice, yelling at Calipari during games and even
refusing to re-enter games.
</P>
<P>
   When Cassell was injured, the situation became exacerbated
because some players felt that Cassell was faking and that Calipari
should have pushed him to play. Calipari lost credibility when he
refused to adjust his game plan to fit the team's personnel without
Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Murdock, Cassell's backup, could not play the uptempo,
helter-skelter game that Calipari favored, but the coach would not
implement a slower, more deliberate offense in which he could
thrive. Nor would he play a bigger lineup that featured McIlvaine
(and Seikaly, when healthy) at center alongside Williams and Van
Horn.
</P>
<P>
   The players, nearly all of whom want Casey to return as the head
coach next season, set a goal of winning 50 percent of their games
under the new coaching staff. If they had had Williams, Van Horn,
McIlvaine, Seikaly, Burrell and Murdock, they probably would have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
