<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA PLUCKS HOPE FROM RUBBLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
and DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ After days of disaster and mourning, Oklahoma
struggled to its feet Wednesday and made plans to rebuild in the
wake of the state's worst tornadoes in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahomans are incredible,'' said Oklahoma City Mayor Kirk
Humphrey. ``They are in incredibly good spirits. They are digging
through rubble, reclaiming all kinds of things to rebuild their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours after dawn Wednesday, garbage men armed with brooms and
carts, heavy machinery and dump trucks filtered into the city's
stricken neighborhoods to begin cleaning the streets and city
easements of debris.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of sunny, windy weather, thousands of residents
climbed through the wreckage of their neighborhoods to salvage
fragments of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the mood among the ruins seemed upbeat. Many declared
their intention to clear their property and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere the devastation was apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's tornadoes _ at least three dozen swept through the
center of the state _ were the deadliest Oklahoma has suffered in
more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Examiner Dr. Ray Blakeney on Wednesday reported that the
confirmed death toll in Oklahoma remained at 38. But as many as 100
people have been reported missing, and efforts to locate them among
the more than 600 Oklahomans treated for storm injuries proved
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four of the victims, Blakeney said, have been identified.
The bodies of 18 or 19 have been released to their families.
</P>
<P>
   Six additional people died in neighboring Kansas when the storms
hit the Wichita area.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1,854 homes in Oklahoma City were damaged or destroyed
by the twisters, said Public Works Director Paul Brum, and the
number statewide was thought to have exceeded 5,000. Federal
Emergency Management Administration official Lacy Suiter said
property damage in Kansas likely matched or topped that in
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Brum placed damage in the state capital at approximately $250
million, but other officials suggested damage in the greater
Oklahoma City area might reach $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm Insurance spokeswoman Beth Hamilton said her company
is expecting as many as 26,000 damaged-home claims, totaling $100
million. In addition, it expects 12,000 auto claims, totaling
approximately $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said she was unable to compare the storm claims to
those from comparable natural disasters. ``We've just never seen
anything like this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In heavily hit suburban Moore, school officials said two
schools, an elementary and a high school, may have been destroyed.
Initial estimates placed damage at $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, they said, the district's students will return to
class in an improvised off-campus site May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City Police Chief M.T. Berry on Wednesday lifted a
curfew for neighborhoods that were only slightly damaged, but
warned that some areas remain dangerous. ``There are boards with
nails, glass _ and when it gets dark, you won't be able to see,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, thousands of current and former residents took to
the street to examine their storm-damaged property. A six-mile-long
traffic jam formed as motorists tried to enter the devastated
suburb of Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Haggard was among Moore residents grimly surveying the
damage Wednesday. Haggard said he and his family first had sought
shelter in a hallway, but abandoned the house when they heard the
tornado's fearsome roar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing it, you could tell it wasn't just another storm,'' he
said. ``We went to get in the van, and it was huge. Stuff was
flying by, being sucked into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Haggard was wryly able to see a bright side.
</P>
<P>
   Haggard was a volunteer worker during the May 1997 Jarrell
tornado that killed 27 people. In Moore, he noted, the tornado left
shattered wood and other debris. In Texas, the storm had left
wreckage the consistency of papier mache.
</P>
<P>
   Moore residents Marilyn and Rusty Yeakley also were on the
street Wednesday, searching the rubble of their home for their
wedding photograph.
</P>
<P>
   They, too, had planned to ride out the storm, they said. ``But I
thought `somebody upstairs' was trying to tell us something,'' said
Yeakley, an architect. ``We grabbed Felix the cat and got out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, the house collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   About all that was left Wednesday was the residence's house
number. The Yeakleys vowed to rebuild at the same site.
</P>
<P>
   A curious aspect of the tornadoes, Police Chief Berry noted, was
the degree to which paper items, including bank and insurance
documents, were spread around the devastated neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The chief warned homeowners that such papers might be scavenged
and used by the unscrupulous to perpetrate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said that officers also have recovered more than 40
firearms that apparently were scattered by the tornadoes. They have
been tagged and will be returned to those who can prove ownership,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said no looting has been reported in the city. Armed
officers have been stationed at virtually every intersection in the
damaged areas.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen from local utility companies said electricity has been
restored to all but 26,000 of the 121,000 area customers who lost
power during the storm. Most service should be restored within a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the American Red Cross, which opened 10 emergency
shelters to house about 1,600 storm refugees, Wednesday announced
that three shelters would be closed for lack of need.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Humphrey noted that many people driven out of their homes
have found shelter with friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Red Cross' Oklahoma City headquarters was
jammed with volunteers. Seventy signed up in an hour, said
volunteer Lana Hale. One man from Tulsa, she said, offered to
donate hundreds of sleeping bags.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, just 24 hours after President Clinton declared 11
counties in Oklahoma and Kansas eligible for federal disaster
assistance, more than 1,000 people had requested the aid.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA's Suiter reported that those eligible may receive grants
for temporary housing, minimal emergency home repairs and medical
or funeral expenses. Low-interest loans for uninsured residential
losses also are available, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
