<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEKALB BATTERED AND SHAKEN BUT SURVIVING IN AFTERMATH OF TORNADO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DeKALB, Texas _ Wet and wild, the winds came up from the
Southwest on Tuesday afternoon and, somewhere beyond the athletic
fields, spun a funnel that filled the afternoon air with a
thunderous roar.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb, population not quite 2,000, was in for a taste of nature
at its ugliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal was on the porch watching,'' said Jeannie
Foster, the elementary school counselor. ``He came back inside, and
the kids put their heads down. We had gone through our safety
drills that morning. They knew what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As they ducked in the hallway, the raging winds slammed into the
school, cutting off the electricity, ripping off a portion of the
roof and buckling the walls. The clocks on the walls stopped at
3:02 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the suction,'' Foster said. ``The roof was
gone, and the rain was coming in. We smelled the gas and evacuated
the kids onto the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few seconds, the fury had passed, moved on to the high
school, shattering glass, felling beams and hurling debris. Several
teachers and students were injured, including Troy Bullard, a coach
who was trapped under a mound of rubble with a collapsed lung.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the tornado, grinding a path two blocks wide,
battered a row of modest frame houses on both sides of Broadway on
its way to the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Boyce Rhea was outside talking on the phone to his son in
Texarkana when he realized what was coming. As he ran back inside,
shingles began to fly off the roof. He dropped to the floor just as
the wind hit, flinging him and his sofa across the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it was gone,'' he said, watching backhoes and chain saws
clearing rubble from his and his neighbors' yards. Eleven stitches
sealed a long gash down the front of his head. ``It probably lasted
five to eight seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossing Texas 82, moving, some residents were told, at 65 mph,
the twister disemboweled the Austin Hotel and the dentist and
insurance offices that occupy the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   It flattened a convenience store, damaged a Bowie County
Sheriff's Department substation, tore metal walls and doors from
the fire station, bent columns and took sections of roof from the
First Baptist Church and took out a dozen homes as it headed out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   N.T. Howell and his wife, who gets around with the aid of a
walker, had been hearing the storm-warning sirens for 20 minutes
when the television suddenly went blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife got up and started toward a closet, but I took her
into the bathroom,'' he said Wednesday, sitting beside what was
left of his house. ``It happened so fast. There was just this loud
roar, and then it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the bathroom, he found his house in ruins.
Outside, stunned neighbors already were gathering on the street and
in yards to count their losses. Trees and electrical poles were
scattered randomly in the wake of the tornado, and a web of
telephone and power lines covered everything. The odor of natural
gas blew across the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing that all were saved,'' Jeannie Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   Some were luckier than others. A spokeswoman for the county's
ambulance service said 12 residents were transported to hospitals
in Texarkana, and three of them suffered serious injuries,
apparently from falling ceilings and wind-borne debris.
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Peek, the city administrator, said 90 percent of the
downtown structures were damaged and half of those ``are gone.''
The elementary school and the high school, including the gymnasium,
were destroyed, she said. At least 50 to 60 houses were damaged, a
dozen of them destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday morning, tiny DeKalb had the look of a
battleground. Military-style tents were erected on a grassy expanse
in front of City Hall, where Salvation Army, Red Cross and county
emergency vehicles lined the street. Police cars cruised the
torn-up areas, and state troopers stopped traffic coming into town.
</P>
<P>
   After a tour of the area, Gov. George W. Bush said he had
declared a state of emergency so state teams can assess the damage
Thursday to determine whether the state can apply for federal
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said officials also are talking to state Education
Commissioner Mike Moses about how DeKalb's students can finish the
school year without a school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
