<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-BRIDGE-CREEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOUSE IS GONE, BUT `AT LEAST WE'RE STILL ALIVE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ Volunteer Fire Chief Steve Emery was
assisting at a wreck scene on Interstate 44 about 6:30 p.m. Monday
when he saw the massive, black funnel cloud approaching his
community.
</P>
<P>
   Two miles away, in the heart of this once bucolic little
subdivision, Bob and Jeannie Spear were looking out the sliding
glass doors of their second-story living room. Their view was of a
normally glassy pond in the southwest quadrant of this
five-square-mile community. At that moment it was ominously black
on the horizon, however, and the Spears were preparing to take
shelter in the laundry room below.
</P>
<P>
   A stone's throw from the Spears, Jay Lovett, was already hiding
in a storm cellar with his wife and son, two nephews and his
sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The next few moments would impress themselves on all of them.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Emery, Lovett and the Spears looked over the
devastated remains of their neighborhood, one of the hardest hit by
storms and one where more than a dozen died. As they did, their
memories all returned to that same interval in time on Monday, and
to the same terrifying 30 seconds in which they were all frozen by
the high-pitched whine of a monstrous tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked at least a mile wide,'' said Emery, ``and it just
whipped toward Bridge Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw it and heard it I knew how bad it was and I
left the wreck and headed back for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spears were not so immediately concerned. They'd seen storms
before, and the retired Baptist missionary and his wife grabbed a
couple of crossword puzzles and went to their downstairs laundry
room to wait out the worst.
</P>
<P>
   They sat quietly for a few minutes, until the lights dimmed and
they heard a tremendous roar and a popping sound they thought was
hail. The crosswords had given way to prayers when, suddenly, a
small hole appeared in the plaster of the outside wall. Jeannie
Spear eyed it calmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to fix that, Bob,'' she said, just before
her ears began to close from a sudden increase in barometric
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the storm shelter, Lovett was trying to calm his
9-year-old nephew. He heard the high-pitched squeal of wind and
watched as the vent pipe was ripped away above him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never heard a sound like that,'' he said. ``It didn't last
but 30 seconds, but I knew it was a huge tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. The F-5 tornado, the most destructive possible, cut a
capricious swathe of destruction through this unincorporated, rural
community. In a matter of minutes it killed at least 13 people and
injured dozens more, destroyed 235 homes and left a barren, denuded
wake through the middle of Bridge Creek. Eight residents remain
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after it had passed, as Emery was pulling into town, Bob
Spear opened the laundry room door, looked out and turned to his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about the hole in the wall, Jeannie,'' he said. ``The
house is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovett was prying open the cellar door, blocked by a fallen
tree. He looked toward his sister-in-law's home and turned back to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you before you see it,'' he said. ``There's
nothing left of your house.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing left of many others.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado flattened much of Bridge Creek, a working-class
haven about 20 miles southwest of Oklahoma City, and left at least
500 of its 7,500 residents homeless. By Tuesday morning its
elementary school had become a temporary triage unit for the
wounded, its middle-school gymnasium a morgue for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   At least 400 of its residents were sleeping in Red Cross
shelters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no electric power to Bridge Creek, no water and no
phones.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Emery was directing fire units as they combed the area
looking for leaking propane tanks while workers with a backhoe were
burying dead livestock.
</P>
<P>
   There were scores of volunteers and an abundance of donated food
and clothing. A Red Cross shelter at the edge of the community was
overflowing with donations and friends were helping the Spears sort
through the tangled mess of what had been their vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're only things,'' said Jeannie Spear, as she looked at
the scattered remnants of a Bible-study book she had been
assembling. ``At least we're still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Lovett was helping a neighbor gather strewn clothing.
Lovett's home had been spared except for roof damage and he was
preparing to move back in as soon as electricity was available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky,'' he said. ``None of my family were hurt. We'll
move back in and I'll have a storm cellar dug by next year and
we'll weather more storms in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, I don't think I'll ever forget that sound.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
