A6258 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:CD:JOEY-McINTYRE     05-05 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:CD:JOEY-McINTYRE-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 
 CD REVIEW: JOEY McINTYRE, STAY THE SAME  World rights. 
 By ANGELICA LARA 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If an old member of New Kids on the Block releases a new solo
CD, does anyone care? Unless you are a die-hard fan of the early
'90s pop group, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   The songs on McIntyre's debut CD are mostly pop ballads and
dance music. If you're into 'N Sync or Backstreet Boys, you might
like it. While I am a fan of both groups, I didn't really like this
CD. It either put me to sleep or got on my nerves because the
choruses were too repetitive. It's the type of CD you could listen
to for about two or three days, and then have all the songs
memorized.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, I liked the romantic lyrics of a few songs,
but then I couldn't remember if I was listening to 'N Sync, the
Backstreet Boys or Joey McIntyre.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to hate the CD, because Joey McIntrye has made a
strong effort to return to the music world, and you can't help but
admire the guy for trying. Plus those great baby-blue eyes of his
on the CD cover tend to make you like him even more. Who knows _
maybe some poor fan who's been waiting for the return of New Kids
on the Block can finally breathe a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
