<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSA     05-05 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT DRUGS, CORPORAL PUNISHMENT 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: A friend of mine has become addicted to
morphine. He worried me and my other friends so much that we got
him into rehab. After about two weeks he came out and really seemed
changed. Then he started using again. Now he is worse than before.
He shoots up every day and steals money to support his habit. His
parents couldn't take it anymore, so they threw him out. We don't
hang out anymore, but I still want to help him. What can I do?
Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Drugs: Your friend is in serious danger. Two weeks in rehab
usually isn't enough time to cure a person of drug use. It sounds
like your friend has good parents who tried and don't know where to
turn next. They were forced to throw their son out of the house for
the family to survive. Families can't let one member destroy the
rest of the family. They tried when they sent him to rehab. Often
drug addicts will steal from their families or become violent to
support their habits.
</P>
<P>
   You could talk to your friend's family and let them know you are
concerned and would like to recommend that the family and friends
join an organization such as Tough Love at (972) 558-1762. This
group meets in local neighborhoods and consists of parents and
friends of troubled youth; its purpose is to support families and
help them deal with violence, drug abuse and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Bridge/STAR Program at (817) 332-3317 has some
excellent programs and will house and counsel troubled youth. There
are other drug-abuse hot lines and organizations that can help your
friend. The key is whether your friend wants help. You and your
friends can help best by talking to his parents and encouraging
your friend to get help. Drug habits are hard to break.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: When my brother was sent to the office, our
principal threatened him with a belt. My brother got scared and
told him to call our parents. He didn't. I think he has been
hurting other children. Punished.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Punished: This sounds like abuse of power by a person who
holds power over another. There are discipline methods other than
corporal punishment available to your principal. You should talk to
your parents about what happened and have them talk to your
brother, then contact the school to talk to the principal. Your
parents need to make an appointment with the principal about your
brother's behavior and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts Teenstalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: Teenstalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
