<SLUG> BC-ROCKETTE-SEARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETTE HOPEFULS AUDITION   AT L.A. STUDIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- Rolling on the balls of their feet,
thrusting arms high with wrists bent, all the while keeping backs
straight and heads sharp, dozens of young women seek Linda
Haberman's eye.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer is quick with corrections, demonstrating the
jazz combination and issuing a clear reminder: ``OK, I really want
it that clean, ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichole Martinez's dream of becoming one of the world-famous
Rockettes was still alive after that first elimination Wednesday as
she and about 30 other versatile dancers moved on to the tap
combination, while more than 60 less-fortunate dancers were walking
out of the North Hollywood dance studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be a Rockette. They just look like
sophisticated women and it looks just like a classy show,'' said
the statuesque 24-year-old Valley Village resident.
</P>
<P>
   Then came tapping and turning to the tune ``Here Comes Santa
Claus.'' The sounds of steel heels and toes clattering on the
hardwood floor was deafening, but apparently not distracting as the
dancers learned the combination of steps.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 dancers were sharp enough to make today's callback and
a shot at one of the seven casts of The Radio City Christmas
Spectacular -- which bills itself as the No. 1 live show in
America, based on attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The admittedly nervous Martinez will have to try again next
year, after improving her tap steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can do it. I definitely will try again,'' she said.
``If you want it bad enough, you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, hundreds of dancers turn out in hopes of joining the
show that premiered at Radio City Music Hall in New York City in
1933 and remains a Christmas holiday favorite.
</P>
<P>
   There have been more slots to fill since the show began
expanding in 1994. Seven shows will play simultaneously in seven
cities during December -- Universal Amphitheatre and Las Vegas are
the venues out west -- and more than 2 million fans will see more
than 550 performances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the competition is no easier. Even those from previous casts
must audition each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the best,'' Haberman said.
</P>
<P>
   A Broadway musical veteran who has been the Rockettes' director
and choreographer the past eight years, Haberman needs about two
hours of increasingly difficult dance combinations to weed out the
best. Dancers need talent, but they also must be able to understand
and follow specific corrections because the Rockettes are a unit,
not a corps of soloists.
</P>
<P>
   ``On an emotional level it never gets easy to do. I know what it
feels to be on that end,'' she explained during a break. ``But part
of being in this field is having to deal with rejection.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a competitive atmosphere, the dancers' camaraderie
includes applauding for each other and exchanging smiles and hushed
comments on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity because when you become a Rockette,
you become a part of history,'' said Kelli Coleman, a Studio City
resident in her late 20s.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining a spot in the Branson, Mo., show following her
first audition in 1994, Coleman has made the show every year since,
including the inaugural Los Angeles cast last year.
</P>
<P>
   Having to audition each year keeps the veterans on their toes.
They do have the advantage of knowing what Haberman wants. But
they, too, must wait until June when the final cast is called.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0557 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKETTE-SEARCH-LADN     05-05 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
