<DOCNO> NYT19990505.0558 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-05 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6267 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-05 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ATTORNEY GENERAL ACCUSES PREDECESSOR OF FRAUD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXARKANA, Texas _ Attorney General John Cornyn accused his
predecessor, Dan Morales, Wednesday of using fraud to try to win a
quarter of a billion dollars in legal fees for a friend in the
state's tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, in a document &UR;  &LR; filed in federal court here, said two
contracts that Morales claimed to have with Houston attorney Marc
Murr were ``fake'' or ``bogus'' and did not exist on the dates they
were purportedly signed.
</P>
<P>
   But Morales' lawyer said the accusation by a Republican attorney
general is part of an effort to discredit Morales, a Democrat, so
he will not run for governor in 2002. Morales ended his second term
as attorney general Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, a former state Supreme Court justice, says he has
evidence that a state arbitration panel's award of $260 million to
Murr was ``procured by fraud.'' He claims &UR;  &LR; Morales created one of
the contracts by replacing the signature of one of his assistants
with Murr's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ploy would make it appear that Murr was actually working
with Morales on the tobacco suit months before he ever made an
appearance in the case. Specifically, Cornyn claims that a 1996
contract Morales signed with Murr was not actually created until
1998, a move that Cornyn said would mislead a federal judge
deciding on fees in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murr nor his attorney, Roy Minton, returned phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' lawyer, Sam Millsap of San Antonio, called the
accusations politically motivated, ``bizarre'' and ``false.'' He
said Republicans like Cornyn know that Morales would be a strong
contender if he decides to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are scared to death that Dan Morales is going
to run for governor in 2002,'' said Millsap. ``What they are doing
is everything they can to take Dan out. It is the worst imaginable
slime job.''
</P>
<P>
   Millsap said Morales will answer the specifics of the
allegations at the ``appropriate'' time.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Morales had post-dated any contracts with
Murr, Millsap replied: ``The allegation is that fraud was
committed. That is untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's court filing was made on the eve of Thursday's hearing
at which Murr is supposed to show why the $260 million fee awarded
by a state arbitration panel shouldn't be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The state arbitrators were all chosen by Morales and Murr, and
Cornyn has asked U.S. District Judge David Folsom to dismiss their
award and instead abide by a national arbitration panel's figure of
$1 million for Murr. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The document Cornyn filed Wednesday was in response to dueling
motions between him and Morales over the possibility of getting
Morales to testify in today's court hearing. Late Wednesday, Folsom
quashed Cornyn's subpoena for possible Morales testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' claim that Murr deserved a big share of the attorneys'
fees from the $17.3 billion tobacco settlement has been under
attack since Murr first made an appearance at the national
arbitration panel last December. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The other attorneys in the case said they had never seen Murr
at any of the negotiations with the cigarette manufacturers and
believed he did little, if any, work on the case. His name does not
appear on any of the hundreds of legal documents in 1996-97 leading
up to the tobacco settlement. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Morales, who worked with Murr at Bracewell &AMP; Patterson in
Houston in the early '80s, has said that he consulted his friend
early on in the tobacco case and had signed separate contracts with
him for his services. He said Murr's advice was ``critical'' to the
state and that Murr wanted his work to be discreet and
behind-the-scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But the mystery surrounding Murr and controversy over the huge
fees going to tobacco attorneys in general _ $3.3 billion to the
five leading attorneys who won the Texas case _ prompted Cornyn to
investigate. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Two separate contracts between Morales and Murr have been
previously reported. The first, which promised Murr 3 percent of
whatever damages the state eventually recovered, was reportedly
signed in October 1996, although Morales has said Murr worked on
the case for months before that.
</P>
<P>
   That contract was replaced by a Jan. 31, 1997, agreement that
simply provided that Murr would be paid a ``reasonable fee.'' After
the tobacco settlement was reached, Murr agreed to submit his fees
to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   In his response to Morales' motion to quash his subpoena, Cornyn
said Morales created the Jan. 31, 1997, contract by switching the
signatures of Morales, Murr and then-assistant Jorge Vega from an
earlier proposed contract.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier contract from which the signatures were switched,
Cornyn said, had proposed a 6 percent contingency contract for Murr
and Will Pryor, a former high-level Morales staffer who is now a
mediator in Dallas. Cornyn said Pryor ``decided not to go forward
with the 6 percent agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The purported Jan. 31, 1997, `contract' providing Murr the
right to recover a `reasonable fee' is a fake _ it did not exist on
Jan. 31, 1997,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's court filing, which was signed by
Cornyn's first assistant, Andy Taylor, accused Murr and Morales of
attempting to mislead Folsom, the state arbitration panel and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In a secret meeting with the state arbitrators last fall, Cornyn
alleged, Morales submitted a 3 percent contingency contract for
Murr in an effort to win the Houston lawyer as much as $520 million
in fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state will prove that the 3 percent contract which was
submitted to the state arbitration panel, which purports to have
been created on Oct. 17, 1996, was not in fact created until
1998,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the alleged ``conspiracy'' began to unravel before
the national arbitration panel last December, when attorneys for
the tobacco industry suspected that the 3 percent contract was
``bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the attorney general continued, Morales refused the
industry's request for a copy of the contract in advance and
refused tobacco lawyers' demands that he testify under oath about
the contract before the national arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Cornyn has said Murr's role in the tobacco suit also
is being investigated by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Saturday that the FBI has been
comparing computer hard-drive data to a paper analysis to try to
determine whether certain contracts and letters were backdated to
make it appear that Murr was involved in the tobacco case earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
